		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> ADVISOR BRIEFS  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald and Maxwell G. Dale  <p> Nuking Card Fraud <p>Been scammed on your plastic lately? Take heart the Department of Defense is on the case. To fight the $486 million it loses annually to credit card fraud, MasterCard has hooked up with Los Alamos National Laboratory, a government-owned research center in New Mexico, known for its top-secret nuclear-weapons research. The result? A neural-net computer program designed to learn a cardholder's spending pattern through genetic algorithms. The computer determines how cardholders typically spend their money and in what amounts. Any anomalous charges, and the program will alert bank officials to possible fraud. "The computer actually tells the bank in real time when there is a discrepancy," says MasterCard spokeswoman Nancy Elder. "It's a major advancement in fraud detection."  <p> Student-loan Lifeline?  <p>Over the last five years, college tuition costs have risen 7 percent annually, with no signs of abating. Many students cannot qualify for loans, leaving cash-strapped parents with little recourse. To assist these families, the National Collegiate Trust, a New York City nonprofit made up of private colleges and universities, recently introduced the Guaranteed Access to Education, or GATE, loan. The loan has no cap and carries an average fixed rate of 8 percent. The downside: It's a balloon loan. Students make interest-only payments for the first five years of payback, thereby lengthening the loan's term and fattening costs. So far, 23 schools have signed on, with another 14 scheduled to join by the end of this year. Currently, the trust has pulled together $50 million in available funds backed by privately placed bonds rated AA by Moody's Investor Service. Last year, the GATE program granted $7 million in loans to 3,000 students. For information, call 800-895-4283.  <p> Pricing Cheap Insurance <p>Pricing insurance isn't every family's idea of fun. With that in mind, Quotesmith Corp., an insurance-information company based in Darien, Illinois, recently introduced a hot line that offers consumers free price comparisons for more than 2,000 policy variations, based on Quotesmith's database of more than 400 insurers. A typical report will show the insurer's latest claims-paying-ability rating, the policy's guaranteed initial rates, and premiums ranked by price. Quotesmith offers information on six different types of insurance, including long-term care, but not on auto or homeowner policies. "The time is right for this kind of information service," says Quotesmith president Robert Bland. "Consumers need to be as informed as possible." Interested? Call 800-431-1147.   <p> Buddy Up <p>If you're thinking of entering a partnership, here's a big carrot: Auditing business partnerships has proved a no-win job for the Internal Revenue Service. According to a recent General Accounting Office report, the IRS audits relatively few partnership returns. When it does, odds are one in three that no taxes, penalties, and interest will be assessed. Moreover, change is not in the offing. "The IRS would have to begin now if it decides to have a partnership document-matching program in place by 2001," the report says.   <p> Capital gainers <p>Might it be that, contrary to common wisdom, the middle class would benefit most from a capital-gains cut? A recent study by the conservative Manhattan Institute for Policy Research says wealthy investors can "for the most part avoid the tax through well-known and commonly used techniques." For one, wealthy individuals typically have large and diversified investment portfolios, in which losers offset winners, thereby shrinking capital-gains taxes. The affluent also typically hold on to their assets, bequeathing them to heirs without incurring any capital-gains tax. Middle-class families, in contrast, often must sell an investment to pay for a large expense, such as a home or a college education. Having realized the gains, these folks are then hit by the taxes.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance, Taxation, Banking Industry, Small Business Ownership

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
