	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Reading Your Way to Riches</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Reading Your Way to Riches</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Reading Your Way to Riches</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>READING YOUR WAY TO RICHES
Whether you invest according to lunar cycles or modern portfolio theory, there's a newsletter out there that will sell you advice.<p>By Nick Ravo<p>Surely, somebody out there subscribes to the Hanover Intermediate Term Trader, Whitfield's Utility Letter, the F.X.C. Newsletter, or Bob Carver's Market Clues. And doubtless scores of investors won't make a move without the latest issue of Russ Kaplan's Heartland Adviser, which offers "in-depth Omaha-style analysis as popularized by Warren Buffet [sic],'' according to the promotional literature.
"Omaha-style analysis"?<p>Ah, the tip sheets (also known as newsletters, or market letters, if you want to get formal). Whimsical, occasionally wise, and often amazingly wrong, market newsletters number in the hundreds--500 is a common estimate. <p>Even the august Wall Street Journal began, in 1883, as the Customers' Afternoon News Letter. But the golden age for these publications dawned in the 1970s, when deregulation of the brokerage business prompted people to make more of their own financial decisions. Today, there's something out there for almost everyone. The choices range from The Moneypaper's general economic prognostication, personal-finance advice, and model stock portfolios to The Option Advisor, which deals exclusively with options strategies, to the Dick Davis Digest, a newsletter that samples other newsletters.<p>Newsletters appear weekly or monthly, run between 8 and 16 pages, and cost a lot--$69 to $250 per year is typical, and much higher fees are not unusual (though free or cheap trial subscriptions are quite common). The big ones, like the Value Line Investment Survey and the Standard & Poor's Outlook, have tens of thousands of subscribers. Others, like Harmonic Research, which uses solar and lunar eclipse cycles to "confirm its technical analysis," have perhaps a few hundred.<p>But are they worthwhile investments? After all, anyone with some newsletter-publishing software, a roll of stamps, and a hunch about the market can put one out. <p>"The proportion of newsletters that beat the market over the long haul is about the same--between 20 and 25 percent--as it is for mutual funds and professional money managers,'' says Mark Hulbert, publisher of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a newsletter based in Alexandria, Virginia, that ranks the performance of financial newsletters.<p>Newsletters are often a valuable source of information, according to Hulbert, whose digest, published since 1980, has become the Consumer Reports of comparative newsletter performance. Newsletters cover sectors often avoided by mutual funds and money managers, like micro-cap stocks, special situations (usually mergers and acquisitions), and medical technology. And unlike brokerage houses and sell-side research analysts, says Hulbert, newsletters have little or no vested interest in the stocks they recommend. They can be very useful, too, for investors who have a strategy and simply need the discipline of a model portfolio to follow it.<p>"That may be the major benefit,'' Hulbert says, "helping investors focus on a single strategy through thick and thin.''<p>Hulbert derives his rankings from model portfolios created from the advice offered by the newsletters. While he cautions that investment records sustained for less than five years are not a predictor of future results, long-term performance, particularly ten-year returns, appears to be more predictive, as the luck factor evens out over time.<p>He also cautions against combining the strategies of various newsletters. "I am less inclined to think that mixing and matching makes much sense even though you would think, in theory, that it would,'' Hulbert says.<p>The best-performing market letter by Hulbert's ten-year return criteria--by a wide margin--is Louis Navellier's MPT Review, up almost 1,000 percent in a decade. Navellier, a quantitative analyst, uses modern portfolio theory and computer programs to bet on inefficiently priced "high-alpha" stocks (stocks rising faster than the market). He also offers an unusually high number of stock recommendations.<p>Navellier, 37, became enamored with modern portfolio theory while studying for his M.B.A. at California State University at Hayward. The theory, based on research by Nobel Prize winners William F. Sharpe and Harry Markowitz, holds that it is possible to maximize return while minimizing risk, based on a belief that the market is efficient and that index funds are the best way to invest. Navellier, however, uses the theory to show that the market is only about 84 percent efficient. He looks for stocks in the other 16 percent by screening about 21,000 stocks each week before whittling the buy list down to about 400.<p>Besides his 14-year-old newsletter--which costs $225 annually and has 7,000 subscribers, about half of them brokers or institutional investors--Navellier also runs a money-management business with more than $1 billion in assets.<p>"My motive was different from a lot of people who put out newsletters,'' Navellier says. "I was an academic, and I just wanted to establish my theory.''<p>The worst ten-year performer according to Hulbert, also by a wide margin, is the Granville Market Letter, which lost 96.7 percent in the decade ended April 30, 1995. Joseph Granville, who charges customers $250 a year for his weekly newsletter, which has been around since 1963, has long been a critic of Hulbert's ranking technique, especially the averaging of various model portfolios to create one total return for a newsletter.<p>Granville is best known for having divined that the market was about to plummet and advising his readers on January 6, 1981, just as the Dow Jones Industrial Average broke 1000 for the first time in years, to "Sell everything!'' Thousands did, and the resulting flood of orders was widely credited with causing the Dow to fall 24 points. Unfortunately, those investors who stuck with the bearish Granville in the following years missed out on the historic bull market of the 1980s.<p>Interestingly, there appears to be no correlation between investment strategy and success or failure. "Almost any method, in the right hands, can work,'' Hulbert says. "And, in the wrong hands, almost any method can't work.'' In other words, a precious-metals newsletter is as likely to perform well or poorly as one devoted to value investing or penny stocks.<p>But one detailed study did demonstrate that market-timing newsletters were about as accurate as flipping a coin. Campbell Harvey of Duke University's Fuqua School of Business and John Graham of the University of Utah's Eccles School of Business studied the recommendations made according to 237 market-timing strategies in 100 letters between 1980 and 1992. <p>The study, released last May, found that the market rises only 48 percent of the time after market-timing letters recommend increasing equities and decreasing cash in asset allocations. The market falls only 51 percent of the time following a call by market-timing letters to reallocate portfolios with more cash and less stock.<p>"If the choice is between a buy-and-hold strategy and listening to asset-allocation recommendations in these newsletters, you are better off with buying and holding,'' Harvey says.<p>Not only was the overall performance of market-timing letters poor, but just eight newsletters in the study, which was published by the National Bureau of Economic Research, had substantial positive performance. "That number is, statistically, what one would expect if the strategies [employed by the letters] were randomly selected,'' Harvey says.<p>The winning market-timing newsletters were The Chartist's Actual Cash Account; Investors Intelligence's Switch Fund; Overpriced Stock Service; Switch Funding Timing's Conservative Strategy; No Load Select's Timing Strategy; Closed-End Funds IV; National Trendlines' Stock Timing Strategy; and Bob Nurock's Advisory, which had two successful strategies, TMI: Shorting and TMI: No Shorting.<p>At the bottom of the survey was, once again, The Granville Market Letter (Traders), which lost an average of 0.4 percent annually over the 12-year period.<p>"This is, in my opinion, remarkably hard to do,'' Harvey says, referring to Granville's performance. "Just putting your money in a savings account would beat that, and it compares quite unfavorably to the annual return for someone who bought and held the Standard and Poor's 500 over that period.''<p>In any case, market-timing letters are not the current rage in the notoriously faddish newsletter universe--mutual fund letters are. Some of them cover a single fund family, such as Fidelity Insight, Fidelity Monitor, and similar publications focusing on the Vanguard and T. Rowe Price funds. "When I started, only 2 of the 36 letters I followed were about mutual funds,'' says Hulbert, whose own monthly newsletter has 15,000 subscribers and costs $135 a year, with a five-month trial subscription available for $37.50. "Now half of the about 170 I follow do.''<p>There are also letters devoted to esoterica like sector rotation, Elliott wave theory, New Zealand stocks, even astrology. "J.P. Morgan used to keep an astrologer on staff,'' says Arch Crawford, a former<a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> analyst, now a "financial astrologer" and publisher of the 18-year-old Crawford Perspectives, which has about 1,000 subscribers who pay $250 a year to read about how the stars and the moon (along with a little technical analysis) may affect Wall Street. "[Morgan] also said that millionaires don't use astrologers but billionaires do,'' Crawford says.<p>The Granville-induced nosedive of 1981 is almost unthinkable today, in part because of the surfeit of market information now available at low cost on cable television, online, and in personal-finance magazines. However, newsletters--which have been reducing subscription prices since the crash of 1987 because of slow or no circulation growth--can still have quite an impact on individual stocks and mutual funds.<p>In January, for example, Wall Street Strategies, with a circulation of about 5,000, said that The <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab Corp.</b></a> was about to be bought by Goldman Sachs. The deal never materialized, but Schwab shares rose 5 percent on January 16 following the newsletter's prediction. The next month, shares of <a name="NASD:ERTS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14059"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Electronic Arts</b></a> soared 10 percent over two days because of a Wall Street Strategies tip--once again wrong--that the software company was about to be taken over by DreamWorks SKG, the motion picture studio formed by Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg, and David Geffen.<p>"Even though the takeovers didn't happen, both of those stocks exploded anyway,'' boasts Charles V. Payne, the owner and chief editor of the four-year-old Wall Street Strategies. Schwab's stock went up 86 percent between January and early July, while Electronic Arts rose 45 percent between the rumor of its takeover and early July. "Ninety-nine percent of the rumors don't work out, but that doesn't mean you can't make money in rumors. If you can get something before Business Week or Dan Dorfman, you are going to make money.''<p>Sometimes, however, the rumor mill is correct. For example, Payne's letter reported in its April and May issues that Lotus Development Corp. was a takeover candidate. This was before <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>'s hostile offer for the company at the beginning of June. <p>Payne, a former broker and analyst, charges $2,250 a year for a subscription that includes a monthly newsletter and updates faxed four times daily. Roughly 90 percent of the subscribers are brokers, which Payne calls "a huge testimonial since their firms already provide them with millions of dollars of information for free.''<p>Wall Street Strategies also watches for technical bounces and undervalued stocks, but, says Payne, "It's the takeovers where we are making a reputation.'' He adds that about 70 percent of the newsletter's calls this year have been correct.<p>Such self-promotion is mild compared with some of the advertisements seen every day in Investors Business Daily, Barron's, The Wall Street Journal, and elsewhere. Claims of quadruple-digit returns and No. 1 rankings from obscure publications are not uncommon, especially for commodities, futures, and options newsletters. <p>The Journal didn't accept newsletter ads until the late eighties, in part because their claims were--and are--often difficult to prove. In May, for example, the Securities and Exchange Commission charged Stephen Leeb, a fund manager and investment advisor based in New York, and KCI Communications, an Alexandria, Virginiabased publisher of several newsletters, with using Leeb's letter, The Big Picture, to promote a fraudulent investment strategy as part of a coordinated marketing effort to solicit investments in Leeb's fund.<p>In ads for The Big Picture, according to the SEC, Leeb said an investor using his market-timing program, Master Key, could have turned $10,000 into more than $39 million from 1980 to 1992. But the SEC claims the results could have been obtained only by retroactively applying a constantly updated version of the program. According to the SEC, many strategies included in the constantly updated program were not developed until after 1980. Thus, no one could have realized the advertised gain--even hypothetically.<p>Performance puffery, though, is common in the market-letter business, so caveat subscriber--this is a largely unsupervised market. In June, the Commodities Futures Trading Commission requested that commodity and financial-futures letter writers register as commodity trading advisors, even though the Supreme Court has ruled that market letters are bona fide publications, which suggests that such licensing or registration would constitute an unconstitutional infringement on free speech. Only if the publishers are also investment advisors, as defined by the SEC, must they register as such with the commission.<p>Still, Peter Brimelow, a senior editor at Forbes and author of The Wall Street Gurus: How You Can Profit From Investment Newsletters (Minerva, 1986), says that most newsletter publishers "are not getting any commission, and they only succeed if they make money for the subscriber.'' <p>He's right, at least insofar as his description holds. But some publishers try to have it both ways. George Chelekis's Hot Stocks Review, one of the few financial newsletters available on the Internet (<a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b>'s popular Motley Fool stock forum is also available online), focuses on small Canadian stocks and derives some of its income from research fees paid by some of the companies he writes about, often glowingly. By law, such interests generally must be disclosed, which Chelekis does. Nonetheless, in the eyes of some, this would make him a stock promoter rather than a newsletter publisher. <p>In the end, says Mark Hulbert, "People should subscribe--but they should be skeptical.'' <p>Nick Ravo is a reporter for The New York Times. He can be reached by E-mail at nravo@aol.com.<p>
NEWSLETTER: GOOD, BAD, AND UGLY
