	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The New Book on Book Value</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-New Book on Book Value</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> THE NEW BOOK ON BOOK VALUE  <p> By Jonathan Butler  <p> When Benjamin Graham and David Dodd published their landmark investment book Security Analysis in 1934, they laid the foundation of what has become known as value investing. Over the past six decades, value investors like Warren Buffett have consistently earned strong returns picking stocks based on three criteria: low price-to-earnings ratios (the price of a stock divided by the current year's earnings per share), high dividend yields, and low price-to-book ratios a measure based on book value. Ofthe three, the price-to-book ratio has become the most vexing to use in valuing a stock.   <p> Book value (also referred to as common shareholders equity or net asset value) is simply a company's total assets minus liabilities. It provides "a snapshot of the worth of the company at any given time if you were going to close the doors and cash in everything that the company had," says John Cleland, chief investment strategist at Security Benefit in Topeka, Kansas.  <p> Investors usually look at either book value per share (book value divided by the number of shares outstanding) or price-to-book ratio (share price divided by book value per share). If a company's current price-to-book ratio is below its own historic level or below the current levels in its industry group, it can be a sign that the stock is cheap.  <p> Using book value to pick stocks is a proven formula for success, says Christopher Browne, a general partner at Tweedy, Browne in New York City. Browne cites a study by the Yale School of Management that divided companies on the New York Stock Exchange into ten groups, from highest to lowest price-to-book. The cheapest decile returned 14.4 percent per year between 1967 and 1984, while the most expensive decile returned only 6 percent per year. "Buying assets at a discount generally leads to superior returns, "Browne says. "If you cover the downside, the upside will take care of itself."  <p> The problem is that this historical evidence may not be valid for the future. Book value, says Cleland, was created at a time when manufacturing companies that had invested heavily in plants and equipment both easy to value were dominant. But the U.S. economy has shifted toward technology and service companies whose book value does not accurately reflect their breakup value the cash a company could raise after all of its assets were sold and its debt repaid.   <p> Compare software giant <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> with <a name="NYSE:IP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10800"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>International Paper</b></a>. Microsoft's current market value of about $50 billion is five times that of IP, but Microsoft's book value is roughly one third smaller.Why? Because the market value of Microsoft's stock reflects a larger portion of intangible assets a highly educated workforce, programming expertise, and market dominance. These intangible assets aren't counted toward book value. This helps explain why the U.S. equities market now trades at 3.5 times price-to-book, about double its historical average. "Book value meant liquidation value, and it just doesn't anymore," says Chris Davis, comanager of the <a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a> and the <a name="FUND:SLASX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SLASX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Selected American Fund</b></a>. <p> The lofty market valuations of growth stocks like Microsoft or semiconductor maker <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a> also reflect expectations of earnings growth. "Using book value to look at something like a semiconductor company is meaningless," says Jeremy Biggs, chief investment officer at Fiduciary Trust Company in New York. The same holds true for other burgeoning industry sectors such as biotechnology and entertainment.  <p> Book value also can be misleading because of the way companies value assets on their balance sheet normally based on acquisition cost minus depreciation. Accounting rules do not permit companies to appreciate the value of most assets. Thus, during times of inflation, the assets on a company's balance sheet may sharply understate their true value.   <p> Rising commodity prices can have a similar effect. If, for instance, the price of oil doubled overnight, <a name="NYSE:XON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10537"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Exxon</b></a>'s stock would skyrocket. And so would the value of all of its assets. But its book value would be unchanged, so the stock would suddenly appear much more expensive on a price-to-book basis, despite a share price rise based on a real increase in the value of the company.  <p> Although corporate management cannot raise the price of an asset on the balance sheet, it can decrease it. The restructuring of corporate America over the past ten years has resulted in many such write-downs. This has also decreased the utility of book value.   <p> In 1992, <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> took a $1.2 billion restructuring charge and a $33.1 billion charge to cover retirement benefits. As a result, the book value per share fell from $43 in January to almost $8 by the end of the year. Was GM really worth a fraction of its former value? Not at all. Over the same period, the stock price rose modestly from $29 to $32, not an uncommon reaction to such fiscal house cleaning. "By removing the uncertainty surrounding a festering situation, a write-off can be good news for a stock," says Brian Berris, a partner at Brown Brothers Harriman in New York.  <p> Book value can be especially useful in analyzing finance companies, public utilities, and many foreign firms. The holdings of securities firms, investment banks, and brokerage firms consist mostly of marketable securities, the one asset type whose value can be marked up on a balance sheet. In the case of public utilities, their rates, set by regulatory agencies, are usually based on the original value of their underlying assets, generally equal to book value. So a utility's book value helps estimate future rate increases and hence, earnings increases.  <p> Outside the U.S., says Jeremy Biggs of Fiduciary Trust, book value remains "very relevant." The reason is that many countries require that hard-asset values be written up to reflect inflation. In Latin America, this accounting difference has kept price-to-book ratios in line with historic levels, even with recent declines in stock prices.  <p> The elegant simplicity of book value will not be replaced easily. In a recent letter to the shareholders of ,<a name="NYSE:BRK.A"></a><b> Berkshire Hathaway</b>, the investment company he runs, Warren Buffett suggested using "intrinsic value" as a measure of a company's true worth. Intrinsic value the discounted value of the cash that can be taken out of a company during its lifetime is in essence the price a reasonable person would pay to acquire it. Because it takes into consideration earnings, dividends, future prospects, and quality of management in addition to assets, intrinsic value "is the only logical way to evaluate the relative attractiveness of investments and businesses," Buffett says. Unfortunately, it is also "impossible to pinpoint."  <p> Another measure of a company's underlying worth is replacement book value. To calculate this, analysts estimate a current market, or replacement, value for all its tangible assets. According to Goldman Sachs, the S&P 400 now sells at 1.03 times replacement book. This number peaked at 1.9 in the mid-1960s and sank below 0.5 in the early 1980s, foreshadowing the flood of corporate stock repurchases, mergers, and acquisitions that followed.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

