	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Stock Tip:  E Pluribus Unum</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Stock Tip:  E Pluribus Unum</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Stock Tip:  E Pluribus Unum</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> STOCK TIP:  E PLURIBUS UNUM  <p> By Jonathan Butler  <p> Pity the investor trying to do his due diligence. Well over150,000 U.S. stock recommendations are made by equity analysts each year; some stocks are followed by 40 or 50 investment firms at a time. Even the most omnivorous reader can't stay abreast of it all.  <p> To help investors get an overview of how a company is regarded by Wall Street, Standard & Poor's now produces an average qualitative opinion rating, part of its new Analysts' Consensus Estimates database. The AQO calculates the consensus recommendations of more than 2,200 market analysts from 210 firms covering 5,400 stocks. In addition to "evening out the static from corporate-finance relationships, trading, and market-making relationships," says Tom Elliott of Research On Line in San Francisco, one of the developers of the AQO, "the rating lets you see what the whole forest looks like instead of just a few trees."  <p> To compute the AQO, S&P assigns a numerical weighting to every outstanding market analyst recommendation according to the following scale: Buy is assigned a 2; buy/hold, 1; hold, 0.5; no opinion, 0; hold/sell, -1; sell, -2. These scores, tallied and averaged, yield the AQO. Greater than 1 is a buy, less than 0 a sell. For example, Pepsico, at 1.17, is a buy, while Salomon, at -0.57, is a sell.  <p> While the idea of looking at a consensus opinion is fairly new, the long-running debate over the effect of equity analyst recommendations on stock prices provides a useful backdrop for evaluating the AQO. The most recent voice in this debate is that of Kent Womack, a professor of finance at the Amos Tuck School of Business at Dartmouth College. In his 1995 study of more than 1,500 recommendations made from 1989 to 1991, Womack found that strong buy recommendations led to an average 5 percent rise over the market in just a one-month period. Strong sells have a longer effect on stocks and cause bigger moves in prices: Stocks getting sell recommendations underperformed the market by 14 percent over six months.  <p> Womack's work contradicts other research, such as a 1994 study by University of Chicago professors Jennifer Francis and Leonard Soffer suggesting the effect of buy recommendations is at best negligible and at worst negative. But most academics agree that sell recommendations have greater predictive power than buys. One reason? Analysts are under pressure not to jeopardize investment-banking relationships by giving a damaging review of a client company hence brokerage-house buys outnumber sells by as high as 10 to 1, and the AQO on the S&P 500 is 0.88, much closer to 1, a buy, than 0, a sell. Considering their relative rarity and the collateral risks an equity analyst takes with negative opinions, sells have more credibility in the marketplace.  <p> Unlike an individual recommendation, which is an absolute and time-bound judgment, the AQO is most useful for evaluating a company relative to its own record. "The changes in rating over time are what really have power," says Andy Ratoff of Zack's Investment Research in Chicago, which offers a similar product called Analyst Watch. The lesson for investors using the AQO, says Womack, is to watch for stocks with extreme ratings that are shifting greatly. "If you start to see a change in a very positive or very negative consensus view, it's very likely there's some money to be made," he says. Or saved.  <p> This strategy would have worked well this past year for investors in Players International, a California-based gaming company. Stockholders keeping an eye on Players' AQO last September could have avoided the 28 percent drop in stock price that occurred before the end of the year. Throughout the summer of 1994, the company's AQO remained at a lofty 1.85 while its stock price climbed from 15 to 23. By the end of September, the stock wasat 24.25, but the AQO had changed direction, dropping to 1.57 still a buy but reflecting a 15 percent move in the wrong direction. Over the next three months the AQO slid to 1.35 in November whilethe stock hit a low of 17.50 in December. At the end of January, with the stock at 20.50, the AQO turned back up, strengthening the buy signal. By mid-March the stock was back above 26.  <p> The AQO is also a good way to see how a company stacks up against its industry competition, which Michael Dougherty, an independent broker at Linsco/Private Ledger in Denver, says often leads him to revise his investments. "If I like a company that doesn't have such a high AQO rating, I'll go look at other ones in its industry with higher ratings to see if I'm missing something and perhaps find a better candidate," he says.  <p> Where there is a consensus, there is also a contrarian view. The contrarian reasoning goes like this: If every market analyst out there is saying sell, then all the smart money will already be out of the stock and the only way for the stock to go will be up. These folks look to buy stocks with negative AQOs for several months running, long enough for all the pessimism to be reflected in the price.  <p> This can be a lucrative strategy, says Christopher Ma, a vice president at Investment Research Co. in Chicago and a former professor of finance at Texas Tech University. After studying more than 4,000 consensus opinions since 1989, Ma concluded recently that while the strong buy stocks outperformed the market by 3.1 percentage points over a 12-month period, the strong sell stocks did even better, beating the market by almost 4 percentage points."If the market becomes one-sided, it can be wrong," he says."In this case, when the consensus tells you to sell, it looks like you should buy." Or as James Mallett, an associate professor of finance at Stetson University in DeLand, Florida, puts it, "Once all the good news is out and the rating is as high as possible, where else can the demand come from?"  <p> The AQO is available to anyone with access to S&P Research Reports. Individuals who don't want to subscribe directly to the $425-a-year online database (800-438-1032) can get individual reports mailed to them for $10 apiece by calling 800-642-2858. They can also try requesting company reports from their broker. Useful as it is, Elliott cautions that the AQO should not be the only analytical tool investors rely on. "Sticking rigorously to this system without engaging your judgment hurts performance," he says. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investment Strategies, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
