<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Keep Your Options Covered</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Keep Your Options Covered</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Keep Your Options Covered</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor   <p> KEEP YOUR OPTIONS COVERED <p>Stock options aren't alchemy. Properly understood, they're a safe, sane way to make money or guard against risk. <p>  <p>By Nick Ravo  <p> It's easy to see why derivatives frighten most investors. After all, a cardinal rule of investing is never buy something you don't understand. And how many investors can define a recon, a tranche, or a strip?  <p> There is, however, one derivative that investors can master with a little effort: stock options. And there is, as well, a conservative way to invest in them.  <p> Buying stock options confers the right but not the obligation to buy or to sell stock at a set price (the strike price) by a set date (the expiration). The buy option is a "call," the sell optionis a "put," and both can be purchased or sold through a broker. It's an investment arena that has experienced explosive growth since 1990, with the number of equities traded in the U.S. that could be optioned rising from 800 to more than 1,550 in 1994. Many more trade on foreign exchanges.  <p> "People shouldn't be afraid of options,'' says Bernard Schaeffer, senior editor of The Option Advisor, a newsletter based in Cincinnati. "They can be useful for insuring a portfolio, or for speculation, or for adding income.''  <p> The idea of trading commodity options insuring a supply of, say, wheat at a given price has been around for centuries. Similarly, as long as there have been stockbrokers, they have been selling de facto options as well as the stocks themselves. In the United States, options are as old as Wall Street. Until 1973, however, they were private transactions between "put and call'' brokers who concocted their own prices and wrote the options and investors.That year, options were listed for the first time, just like stocks, which allowed investors to sell puts and calls as easily as they could buy them.  <p> Selling options, particularly call options on stocks one already owns (a practice known as writing covered calls), is the conservative way to play the options market. But most investors prefer to buy options and risk the loss of their entire investment. Why? Potentially phenomenal returns.  <p> Options provide investors with an opportunity to leverage their capital to participate in the price movement of a large amount of stock for a relatively small amount of money. For illustration, let's say that instead of buying 100 common shares of XYZ Corp. for $10,000 (at $100 a share), you purchase one 30-day call contract for XYZ common with a strike price of $105 a share. You pay "1,"or $100, for this contract, the right to buy or sell 100 shares. Contract prices vary widely but can cost far less than a single share of stock. As a general rule, call premiums are more expensive in relation to the stock price when the market is rising and put premiums are more expensive when the market is falling. <p> Now let's suppose that sometime during the next 30 days, the price of XYZ springs from $100 a share up to $110 a share. XYZ's common shareholders have just cleared a paper profit of $10 a share, or $1,000 on 100 shares a very nice 10 percent gain in less than a month.  <p> But now let's look at how well you would have done with your XYZ options contract. Because of the movement in the price of XYZ's stock, your option entitles you to buy 100 shares of a $110 stock for only $105 each. Essentially, it's become a ticket to cash in on a $1,000 move, and it's worth much more than the $100 you paid for it.  <p> Alternatively, you could sell the option anytime before it expires to someone who wants to buy XYZ stock or to another option buyer. The option that you paid 1 for would be worth at least 5, or $500. Or, upon its expiration, you could exercise the option and keep or sell the shares yourself.  <p> Your final profit, either way, will be slightly less than $500 though, because of commissions and the price of the option. Still, you could end up clearing about $365 on the transaction a return of about 250 percent on your initial risk money.  <p> The catch, as we mentioned, is that you could and probably will lose your entire upfront investment. Call options become worthless if the stock closes under the strike price on the expiration date (less than $105 a share in the XYZ example). In fact, according to most studies, stock options expire worthless to the buyer 70 to 80 percent of the time.  <p> The reasons for this have to do with how options premiums are structured, a subject we will deal with shortly. Even when you win, however, the likelihood of making a killing is small, as stocks seldom appreciate 10 percent in a single month, as XYZ did.  <p> If option contracts expire seven or eight times out of ten, then somebody must be raking in all those bets, which are called premiums. The folks who do are the option sellers, usually referred to as writers. Instead of trying to break the bank, these more conservative investors prefer collecting premiums of 1 and 2 percent of the money they are risking (sometimes more) everyone or two months. That's where selling covered calls comes in. <p> Writing covered calls is the easiest and most cautious way to sell options. "Covered'' means that stocks you own back the options, like collateral.  <p> It works like this: Let's say you bought 300 shares of <a name="NYSE:TWX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11482"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TimeWarner</b></a> on April 7 for $38.38. That same day, you could have also sold three covered-call contracts (remember that one contract equals 100 shares). Depending on the strike price and the expiration date you chose, you could have collected a premium ranging from4 1/8 (for a call option expiring in June with a strike price of 35) to 1 1/8 (for a call option expiring in June with a strike price of 40) to 1/8 (for a call option expiring in May with a strike price of 45).  <p> Now let's say you sold the middle option. You would collect $337.50 in premiums, about $300 after the broker's commission. If the price of Time Warner hasn't exceeded 40 by the third Friday in June, you keep your stock and the premium.  <p> If the stock "strikes'' 40, you retain the premium but are obligated to sell the shares at that price, which still leaves you with a gain of 1 5/8 points, or $487.50. If the stock goes to 42, however, or shoots up to 60, you still must sell at 40.  <p> The premium may sound measly, but $300 is 2.6 percent of the $11,512.50 that 300 shares of Time Warner cost you. Since the option was about two months long, multiply that return by six and that's the equivalent of an annual return of 15.6 percent. And that's just the premium. The stock itself may increase in price.  <p> Writing covered calls isn't a great all-weather strategy, though it worked very well in 1994, when many stocks traded in a narrow range. In a flat market, the risk of having your stock called away is lower, but so are the premiums.  <p> There are two major risks with this options play. First, should your stock shoot up past the strike price say, because the company is a takeover target you will not share in the run-up. Second, the stock could decline by an amount larger than the premium you collected.  <p> "It works great in nonvolatile markets," says Lawrence G. McMillan, president of McMillan Analysis Corp., an options consultant and publisher in Morristown, New Jersey. "But you are giving away upside potential and still have downside risk."  <p> But assuming you invest only in stocks you believe in and wish to hold, you would have experienced this loss anyway, and the options premium you collected at least cushioned the blow. (You can also buy back the option and then sell your stock if you are worried about the share price falling even further.) "With writing covered calls, investors should expect to enhance their performance in an up market and cushion their losses in a down market," says Richard Schmidt, president of Stellar Management, a money-management firm in Naples, Florida. "But it's not a foolproof strategy. It won't make you money in a down market unless you are a great stock picker."  <p> Generally, the longer to expiration, the bigger the premium you can collect (and the greater the risk the stock will move above the strike price or lose more than you earn on the premiums). An option that has 90 days until its expiration might have a premium of two points, but two days before expiration the premiummay have declined to an eighth of a point.  <p> In addition to its so-called time value, a premium's size depends on its intrinsic or cash value, as well as the perception of investors on how likely the contract is to finish in the money. The key terms used to describe this cash value are in the money, at the money, and out of the money.  <p> For a call option, if the stock is selling at a higher price than its strike price, it is in the money. That's because the option could be instantly exercised.  <p> That doesn't mean the buyer will make a profit. Premiums for in-the-money options are generally slightly greater than the spread between the stock price and the strike price. For example, if CBS were selling at 63 and the strike price is 60, somebody could simply buy the stock at 60 with an option and then sell it at 63. But the cost of this option would probably be at least 3 1/8 points even more if there is a long time until expiration or if the stock is unusually volatile.  <p> Sellers of covered calls face an analogous dilemma: The premiums can be quite large with in-the-money options, but unless the stock was purchased at a price below the strike price, much of the profit will evaporate if the option is exercised. And within-the-money options, the odds are very good that it will be. Of course, the CBS stock could fall below 60. Then it would be out of the money, enabling the option seller to keep the premium and the stock.  <p> An option is at the money when the strike price and sale price are identical. If it expires at the money, you keep the premium and could be called to relinquish the stock at the strike price, though that is unlikely, since the option holder could get the same price in the equity market.  <p> Most professional investors advise amateur covered-call writers to stick with options that are slightly out of the money and expire in one or two months, at least in the beginning. That's because these options are the least likely to be called away. <p> Most investors use covered calls to pick up a little extra income on stocks that have already appreciated somewhat but may be stagnant. Developing an entire portfolio around covered-call writing requires a lot more technical knowledge, training, monitoring, and trading skills.  <p> Puts, too, can be covered. Their sale can be offset by "shorting" the same stock selling borrowed shares in the expectation that the price will fall, allowing you to buy the shares back at a lower price and pocket the difference. Or you could simultaneously buy and sell a put on the same stock.  <p> If a put is exercised, or "put" to you, it is a cash transaction. You buy stock at the strike price instead of handing over stock you own.  <p> As an example of this, imagine you own 300 shares of <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b> and you sold three puts for a premium of one with a strike price of 70. If the stock should happen to fall to 40, you lose. The person who bought the put option makes you buy 300 shares of America Online at 70. You are out $30 a share, or $9,000,with only the negligible solace of keeping the modest premium. <p> If you do want to write puts, your broker will scrutinize your trading history and financial wherewithal before allowing you to do so. (All option traders, even those writing covered calls, have to sign an options agreement with their broker stating that they understand the risks.)  <p> Stories are legion about investors who were wiped out in October1987 after writing puts. They had been collecting fat premiums, betting that the strong market would run forever. When the market crashed, however, the puts were exercised, and the buyers forced the sellers to buy stock at precrash prices.  <p> These investors, however, were selling on margin, also known as writing "naked" puts. They didn't have the cash to buy stock put to them. The same thing can also happen with calls that aren't covered. For example, you sell a call option on a stock you don't own, and that stock shoots to the moon. If the option is exercised, you'll have to buy it at the new stratospheric market price so it can be called away from you at the much lower strike price. <p> The clear lesson here is that naked writing leaves a naked investor. Keep your puts and calls covered.  <p> For those who wish to learn more about options and there is a lot more to learn, there are many places to turn. In addition to newsletters like The Option Advisor, the Value Line Options Survey (800-535-9643) is a weekly service offered by Value Line describing various options strategies, for beginners in the option market as well as advanced investors, and providing specific recommendations for covered-call writing. The Options Institute (800-OPTIONS), the educational arm of the Chicago Board Options Exchange, has lots of how-to information for investors. An easy-to-follow introductory book on options is How the Options Markets Work (New York Institute of Finance Press), by Joseph A. Walker. <p>- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - -  <p>Nick Ravo is a reporter for The New York Times. He can be reached by E-mail at nravo@aol.com. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
