	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Don't Take Hold of ARM Funds</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Don't Take Hold of ARM Funds</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Andrew Gluck  <p> Adjustable-rate mortgage funds, among the hottest mutual fund products of the early 1990s, may be about to join the ranks of other fad funds. ARM fund assets, which peaked at $22.2 billion in September 1993, plunged to $9.9 billion by the end of1994. <p> This phenomenon is not without precedent in the mutual fund industry. In the early 1980s, "government plus" bond funds raised yields by writing options on their portfolios. Gone. In the late1980s it was option income funds, now extinct. Short-term world multimarket funds enlivened the early 1990s, mixing foreign government bonds with cross-hedged currencies. The strategy foundered when international-currency relationships broke down in 1992, and the funds that remain have returned 1 percent annually over the last three years.  <p> ARM funds may be next on the list of casualties. On March 31,         T. Rowe Price, the no-load fund family that manages $60 billion, turned its ARM fund into a plain short-term bond fund. "We found that the ARM concept just didn't work," says Steven Norwitz, a company vice president. And Geoff Bobroff, president of Bobroff Consulting, an East Greenwich, Rhode Island, mutual fundconsulting firm, says, "There probably will be no ARM funds five years from now."  <p> ARM funds promised money marketlike safety with about two percentage points higher yield. In fact, they've returned 2.01 percent annually over the last three years, compared with 3.31 percent for money market funds. Of course, any fund category can go through a slump, but ARM funds don't make sense for the average income investor. When asked whether there is such a thing as a good ARM fund, newsletter publisher William E. Donoghue says, "That's like asking which foot I'd like to have stepped on. ARM funds are not worthy of consideration."  <p> ARM funds sound great. They invest at least 65 percent of their assets in adjustable-rate mortgages. Unlike conventional bonds, ARM yields typically reset, or adjust, at least annually. Payments also eventually rise, providing an inflation hedge that is unique for a fixed-income investment. And because ARMs eventually reset their rates to the current yield, a long-term investor should ultimately get back all principal.  <p> Franklin Advisers, the San Franciscobased load-fund giant, rolled out its first ARM fund in October 1987. By mid-1991, yields on safe money market funds and CDs were at lows not seen in ageneration. Yield-hungry investors poured $100 million a week into the Franklin fund, pushing assets to $1.5 billion. Other firms scrambled to offer their own ARM funds, which numbered 75 by the end of 1993.   <p> The seeds of the ARM funds' demise were sown just as their appeal peaked. Fixed-rate mortgage rates fell in 1991 and 1992, hitting 30-year lows in 1993, and homeowners refinanced out of adjustable-rate mortgages in unprecedented numbers. When a homeowner prepays an adjustable-rate mortgage, the fund that owns the mortgage gets its money back sooner than expected and reinvests at lower interest rates.   <p> In 1994, mortgage rates jumped 2.5 percentage points, ARM coupons couldn't reset upward fast enough to maintain their price, and the average fund lost 2.2 percent. But even if the market gyrations of recent years do not repeat themselves, the case for investing in an ARM fund remains weak.   <p> Newlin Rankin, portfolio manager of the <a name="FUND:BARGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BARGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Benham Adjustable Rate Government Securities Fund</b></a>, rated above average by Morningstar and a rare no-load in the category, argues that his fund is a good choice for anyone who is parking cash for three years and wants a higher return than a money market but less risk thana short-term bond fund. Rankin projects that an investor could earn an annualized total return of 6.90 percent over three years. "Now, you have to ask yourself, Is it worth it?" he says.  <p> The answer is no. If an investor put half his cash in a money market fund at 6 percent and the other half in a three-year Treasury note at 6.8 percent, he or she would get a blended return of 6.4 percent just 53 basis points less than the ARM fund but with virtually no risk and lots of liquidity.  <p> Any investor who does want to invest in an ARM fund should find out whether it holds derivatives or illiquid mortgages, both of which have caused big losses for these funds. The ARM-fund investor should also determine how often a fund's mortgages reset and what type of index most of its portfolio is pegged against.  <p> Finally, all but 25 of the 85 ARM funds carry sales loads or12b-1 fees, according to Lipper Analytical Services. They range from a 5 percent front-end load to 12b-1 fees below 1 percent and will lower any return.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
