	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Dear Computer, I need a Job</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Dear Computer, I need a Job</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Dear Computer, I need a Job</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> DEAR COMPUTER, I NEED A JOB  <p>Why a machine might read your next resume  <p> By Kathleen Pender  <p> Job hunting--already impersonal and dehumanizing--is getting more so. The latest development: Companies are using computers to screen resumes for key skills, degrees, credentials, and experience. <p> Last year, when UPS Airlines said it would add 145 jobs, the largest private employer in Kentucky got 2,910 resumes in ten days. "We put them all into our computer system and responded in three or four days," says Pat O'Leary, the human resources manager at UPS.  <p> The Association of Human Resource Systems Professionals, a Dallas trade group, says that 10 percent of companies with more than1,000 employees now use resume-scanning software. "We are going to run into this in all the Fortune 500 companies," says Martin Yate, the author of Resumes That Knock 'Em Dead (Bob Adams, 1995). Current users include <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:XRX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11657"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Xerox</b></a>, Salomon Brothers, Cornell University, <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:JNJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10824"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Johnson & Johnson</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:NU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11088"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Northeast Utilities</b></a>, and Bank of America.  <p> The software programs flash through resumes looking for keywords. Those with the most "hits" bubble to the top of the electronic pile. When Disneyland needed to hire a mechanical engineer to keep Pirates of the Caribbean and other rides running, its computer program searched resumes for the keywords theme park, down time, Audio-Animatronics, HVAC, fluid mechanics, and ride and system design, says Mark Neynaber, senior professional staffing repat Disneyland. When hiring a pilot, UPS Airlines plugs in words such as "727, 767, airline transport pilot's license, and 10,000 hours flight time," O'Leary says. "If we're doing minority hiring, we might add OBAP [Organization of Black Airline Pilots]."  <p> The growing use of computers in resume screening requires a change in approach for job hunters. The old rules called for lots of verbs--created, developed, launched. But the new software looks for nouns--vice president, marketing, Spanish speaker. A computer scanner sometimes will kick out or misread resumes that aren't printed in a common typeface and plain text on white paper, or ones that use gimmicks like underlining and italics. <p> Joyce Lain Kennedy, author of Electronic Resume Revolution, suggests adding a "keywords" section--a long paragraph that simply lists every skill, degree, credential, job title, and previous employer you can legitimately claim. (Help-wanted ads are a good place to hunt for possible keywords.) The rest of the resume, she says, should follow a traditional format.   <p> When Marc Portner went looking for a new job in information systems, he included in the middle of his resume a keyword section that listed, among other things, <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple</b></a> Macintosh, <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM </b></a>PC, DEC Microvax, HP 3000, HP 9000 Unix series, client server, Cobol, Fortran, <a name="NASD:ORCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14337"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oracle</b></a>, PeopleSoft, and 20 other software languages."I put in everything I've ever worked on, learned or touched," says Portner.  <p> A headhunter forwarded Portner's resume to Vanguard Group, the mutual fund company based in Valley Forge, Pennsylvania. Tom Howard, a project manager with Vanguard, was searching the company's electronic resume database for a systems analyst with at least a bachelor's degree and experience with People Soft software, project management, and computer networking. Portner's resume hit every one of those words, and within 72 hours, he had been invited in for an interview and hired.  <p> Companies that use resume software say that job hunters benefit too, because it's easier to store resumes electronically than in paper files, and it's easier to search the database when jobs open up in the future. Also, the computer gives equal attention to all applicants.  <p> Says Disneyland's Neynaber: "Before, our recruiters had two and a half hours' worth of resumes to read every night. There's no way the person on the bottom got the same attention as the one on the top." Companies that invest in resume software use it for almost every job, from office assistants up to senior management.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS:  Technology Industry, Employment  

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:INTC">Intel Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:MOT">Motorola, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:XRX">Xerox Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:MCIC">MCI Communications Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:JNJ">Johnson & Johnson</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:NU">Northeast Utilities</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:AAPL">Apple Computer, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:IBM">International Business Machines Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:ORCL">Oracle Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  
