				<font size=5><b>Big Plays for Small Investors</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Big Plays for Small Investors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> BIG PLAYS FOR SMALLER INVESTORS <p>Institutional clients have long gotten the best deals on Wall Street. Now the little guy has a crack at them too.  <p> By Gretchen Morgenson  <p> Among all the arcane practices of Wall Street, the one that has caused the most consternation for individual investors may also be the one that has been the most entrenched: the bigger the account, the better the treatment. For retail investors, separate and unequal is the way that the financial world has always worked.  <p> Who gets first grab at hot initial public offerings? Big, institutional clients, who often leave nothing for small fry. If a broker offers an individual a crack at an IPO, you can bet it's because no one else is buying.   <p> Who can participate in those lucrative leveraged buyouts? Only the big bruisers. Ditto for sophisticated equity-hedging strategies,such as short-selling, and access to privately held real estate turnarounds.  <p> Although a couple of mutual funds have begun dabbling in short-selling and some real estate investment trusts claim to be turnaround experts, pure plays in these areas are very tough to find for folks with less than $1 million to invest.  <p> These investments fall into one of two categories: outright private placements and deals that are typically offered only to institutional clients. Spotting the good ones requires a combination of serious spadework, a deep understanding of the industry involved, and extreme patience--not to mention access. Unlike mainstream Wall Street analysts who are basically spoon-fed information by the companies they follow, the top-drawer professionals who survey the investment scene for undiscovered gems are independent thinkers who reject the conventional wisdom. They pride themselves on research that is proprietary.  <p> But before investors can even think about venturing into this exclusive arena, they usually have to get a foot in the door of a firm's private client group. Doing that at Goldman, Sachs requires $5 million in securities held in the account. At <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, high rollers typically have $5 million of investable assets in their accounts. Once they're inside, however, a world of investment alternatives opens up, including equity arbitrage, real estate deals, privatizations, leveraged buyouts, even derivatives. <p> Over the years, smaller investors have grown so used to being left with the financial equivalent of table scraps that most have accepted it as the way business is done. Yet some of the barriers are finally breaking down. A few firms and investment professionals are blazing the way. As these firms prove to the rest of the Street that more sophisticated deals can be done for retail folk, and done well, others may follow.  <p> For those early to the game, the timing couldn't be better. After getting hammered in equities and bonds last year, investors are searching for profitable alternatives. Financial assets have had such a run for so many years--stocks have returned a compound average of 14.4 percent for the past ten years while Treasurys have averaged 9.8 percent--that now may be a very good time to consider diversifying into newly available private investments. <p> "With the stock market perceived by many as overvalued now, private deals are a way to get higher returns," says Jeffrey Lynford, chairman of the Wellsford Residential Property Trust, a real estate investment trust listed on the New York Stock Exchange. Lynford has spent years in the private-investment arena. Early on, he was backed by former Treasury secretary William Simonand investor Ray Chambers, two men credited with starting the LBO movement in the 1970s with their company Wesray Capital. <p> But diversifying from plain-vanilla financial assets is tricky. For one thing, investors must find a professional or firm that specializes in the obscure and risky environs of LBOs, equities just out of bankruptcy, private companies, or distressed real estate. Stock pickers--whether at your local brokerage, favorite mutual fund, or neighborhood bank--are a dime a dozen. Tougher to locate are professionals who know how to do the research necessary to navigate the choppy waters of short-selling, distressed bank debt and mortgages, and other off-the-run issues. These are investments whose merits--and shortcomings--are not always evident to the untrained eye.  <p> Firms now at the forefront of the private-investment arena are providing clients with genuine opportunities identified by hardnosed research analysts, not the tax-avoidance tricks that characterized private deals in the past. Happily, too, the minimum account size required of investors has been reduced in some cases, widening the field. Today, at Dabney/Resnick Inc., a Beverly Hillsbased leader in giving individuals access to private deals, the minimum account size needed for decent diversification is $250,000. At Trilling Partners, a division of Paine Webber in Los Angeles that offers sophisticated equity-hedging strategies to individuals,the account minimum is $100,000. Hedge funds that specialize in shorting usually require $250,000 to begin.  <p> Because LBOs, real estate deals, and other private placements remain largely the purview of institutional clients or extremely wealthy individuals, information about them remains scarce. Billionaire investors like Revlon owner Ronald Perelman and Hollywood's Merv Adelson employ scores of staffers to hunt down assets worth acquiring and companies to buy, but smaller investors have no one to perform this due diligence.   <p> Yet it is just this niche--providing proprietary and what was once purely institutional research to retail customers--that a few firms are now trying to fill. Both founders of Dabney/Resnick--chairman and chief executive Judy Resnick and president Neil Dabney--are escapees from Drexel Burnham Lambert's high-yield institutional sales department. Of her experience there, Resnick says, "We saw extremely wealthy clients being offered all the good stuff and making very good returns and thought, Why couldn't individuals get this too?" So they left Drexel and set up their own shop. That was in July 1989; seven months later Drexel collapsed. <p> Another bit of good timing by Dabney/Resnick came in late 1990, when the junk bond market went into free fall. The firm was among the first to call the turn in high-yield securities, its specialty. The next few years saw junk bonds surge in value. Between May '91 and September '94, Dabney/Resnick Asset Management returned 70 percent for its clients. That translates to a 20 percent compounded annual return. The numbers are audited by accounting firm BDO Seidman.  <p> Trilling Partners, a boutique within the Paine Webber brokerage, is another group that brings institutional research to individuals. Headed by veteran broker Stan Trilling, the firm's five professionals scour the equity markets for small-capitalization stocks to buy and sell short, creating hedged portfolios that historically outperform long-only or short-only accounts in both good and bad markets. A broker since 1969, Trilling established his boutique in 1988 and has $85 million under management. Of that, $35 million is dedicated to small-cap longs and shorts. "I began offering my proprietary short ideas to institutions only in 1987," he says. "Now I have a 50-50 split between institutions and retail. "Between November '92 and February '94, one of the most woeful periods for short-sellers, Trilling's portfolio of ten picks and pans was up 169 percent.  <p> What are these firms recommending to clients now?   <p> LBOs. Since 1991, Dabney/Resnick has done ten LBOs of smallish companies. After the firm has toured company facilities, put management through the wringer, and pored over the financials, it uses client money to buy an equity stake in the outfit, typically investing between $1 million and $5 million. The firm takes a seat on the board and goes over budgets with management each week.   <p> Glenn Boschetto, head of Dabney/Resnick's LBO group, says: "We look for high current yields of between 11 percent and 13 percent and a kicker on the end when we sell the company. Total returns should be around 30 percent a year."   <p> Example: The buyout of Technicarbon, a manufacturer of carbon paper, in 1992. Dabney/Resnick invested some $3 million in retail investors' funds in the company, then sold it in 1994. Investors earned total returns of 29 percent a year.  <p> Surprisingly, the firm has little competition in the small end of the LBO market. Boschetto explains: "Most LBO funds have $200 million in assets and are looking to invest no less than 10 percent in each deal because they can't be spread too thin. These institutions won't look at an equity investment of less than $5 million, which works well for us." Investments are made with four- to five-year holding periods in mind. No short-term money is allowed.  <p> Clients' costs in a typical Dabney/Resnick LBO are roughly 1.5 percent of the value of the deal. The firm also invests some of its own money alongside investors'. This gives it exactly the same goals as its investors; the higher the returns, the better the payout.  <p> DISTRESSED REAL ESTATE. A newer area of opportunity for investors: office buildings in foreclosure or held by owners who want out. Dabney/Resnick's clients have bought four buildings in Florida and eight in Los Angeles, and the firm is looking to buy another three buildings in L.A. early this year. One of the deals, involving three office buildings in California, was conducted in December1993 for $46 million, with close to 90 percent financing by the sellers. Two of the structures were in foreclosure, and the other was held by a partnership eager to exit. Dabney/Resnick bought the buildings along with a new management team and almost immediately began increasing occupancies. One building, only 80 percent rented when the deal was done, now has more than 90 percent occupancy. In one year, the cash flow on it jumped from $2.8 million to $3.2 million.  <p> Jason Reese, who runs the firm's real estate group, says: "We're already in negotiations to sell for about $11 million a building we bought in the deal for roughly $8 million. Our annual rates of return should be 25 percent."  <p> The fees levied on investors in real estate come out this way: Dabney/ Resnick gets 7 percent of the money it raises from investors, but this money ends up being such a small percentage of the total deal size, almost all of its investors' funds go to work for them. Before any profit goes to the operating sponsor, the firm's investors must receive a full return on their capital and a 10 to 15 percent annual yield on top of that. When annual rates exceed 15 percent, the management partner that runs the buildings begins to participate in profits, on a sliding scale. If investors get, say, a 20 percent annualized return, the operating sponsor gets 20 percent of any profits on top of that. "That way," says Reese, "we align investors' interests with the operating sponsors'."  <p> DISCOUNTED BONDS. Because interest rates have gone up, a lot of high-yield bonds that were trading at 100 now trade at 70 or 80 cents on the dollar. Not all of them deserve such treatment, says Neil Dabney. Example: Trump Castle, whose bonds are trading around 50. With a coupon of 11.75 percent, the bonds' yield to maturity in 2003 is 26 percent.  <p> Dabney recommends them to his firm's clients because their prices declined precipitously on bad news. "The news on Atlantic City has been known for a year--that increased competition from Philadelphia gambling may hurt business," he says. "All of a sudden, the herd woke up, panicked about gaming in Pennsylvania, and got out."Why do the bonds look good? Pennsylvania gaming is no sure thing; it may come to ballot and be voted down, as happened last November in Florida. Even if gaming comes to Pennsylvania, Dabney believesthe Trump Castle bonds will recover from current levels if only because investor selling has been so overdone. Meanwhile, an almost 12 percent coupon, translating to a 23 percent current yield, is hard to beat.  <p> BACK-END EQUITIES. Citicasters, a TV-and radio-station company that has come out of bankruptcy, is another Dabney/ Resnick idea. The firm recommended Citicasters to clients last June when nobody on Wall Street followed the company; its stock--known as a back-end equity--was then trading around $18 a share. Now, First Boston is publishing favorable reports on Citicasters and the stock is around $22.  <p> Back-end equities, so-called because they come out of the end of a bankruptcy proceeding, can be good propositions because they're usually unfollowed by Wall Street and unloved by investors. Citicasters used to be known as Great American Communications, a company acquired by financier Carl Lindner in 1986. Enormous debt forced the company into bankruptcy negotiations in 1992. While there, it sold assets, turned a lot of its debt into equity, and reduced its borrowings from $640 million to $120 million. Most radio-station companies trade at 10 to 11 times broadcast cash flow; Citicasters trades at 7.5 times. For this reason, and because advertising at radio stations is up some 14 percent this year, the shares could trade between $30 and $34 per share in 18 months.  <p> SHORT-SELLING AS AN EQUITY HEDGE. The folks at Trilling Partners are well acquainted with the perils of short-selling; that's why they've spent the past ten years honing a system that limits the downsides in shorting while allowing for plenty of profits. "You can't let your ego get in the way about being right on a short," says Trilling. "You've got to have hard-and-fast rulesto limit your losses." Such as? If a stock goes against Trilling by 20 percent, he'll eliminate his position or buy equal amounts of the stock to "box" his trade. "Years when my performance was hurt were when I didn't protect myself from overzealous bulls," he says.  <p> Trilling's short and long picks are his own, not Paine Webber's. On the short side, he looks for stocks brought public by underwriters with a history of launching troubled deals; he also hunts for what he calls incongruities. These may include companies in an industry underwritten by firms with no expertise in a particular area or turnover in management just before an offering. "A company called Education Alternatives had a chief financial officer in its preliminary prospectus but no CFO in its final offering statement," Trilling says. "That looked suspicious." For this and other reasons,Trilling's clients began shorting Education Alternatives; the stock hit $48 in 1992 and is now $18.  <p> Trilling won't short a stock unless he can identify a trigger event that will force it to decline by 50 percent within 18 months. This makes him an "investing short" rather than a "trading short" and has helped protect his clients from the whipsaws experienced by other short-sellers in what has been a mighty dicey market. <p> Just over a decade ago, big firms were much more involved in offering private deals to investors than they are today. Oppenheimer & Co. and <a name="NYSE:BSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10191"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bear Stearns</b></a> were two of the key players in the field, raising money among investors in private placements. But as with many investments in the early '80s, these deals were driven by the need to reduce investors' taxes, not by especially promising returns. As a result, all manner of questionable real estate, equipment leasing, and oil and gas investments were created. Most ended up causing clients and firms big losses.  <p> This time around, things are different. The investment opportunities are genuine, not tax tricks. Best of all, smaller investors are no longer excluded.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Ethical Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
