	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Get Year-End Financial Checkup</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Get Year-End Financial Checkup</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>GET A YEAR-END FINANCIAL CHECKUP
Keep your wallet healthy, wealthy , and wise<p>By Bruce Upbin<p>As another year draws to a close, it's easy to let money matters get lost in the shuffle of holiday excitement. Now is a better time than later to straighten up your financial house. We asked the experts for their best year-end tips. Follow these and save:<p>-> REVIEW HEALTH BENEFITS. Most companies circulate forms that let employees adjust benefit plans by a Thanksgiving deadline. Pay attention. It may be the last time workers can take advantage of one of today's most cherished benefits -- employer-provided flexible spending accounts for health care costs. Many large corporations let employees set aside as much as $3,000 in pretax salary to pay for non-reimbursable medical expenses. By using pretax dollars for physicals and even the cost of traveling to the doctor, workers can cut non-reimbursed medical expenses by 40 percent or more. These plans are particularly advantageous if you are expecting your medical bills and insurance copayments to increase in 1995, but keep in mind they do not cover payments for elective cosmetic surgery. Although health reform, which would have killed these plans, looks to be dead in the water, Congress is still angling to eliminate this $31 billion perk.<p>Individuals should sit down with their checkbook, add up how much they spent on medical costs this year, and sock that amount away in a flex plan for 1995. "If you want to switch from your employer's indemnity plan to its health maintenance organization or preferred-provider plan, you'll probably want to lower your flex-account balance because you won't be paying as much for office visits," says Martha Priddy Patterson, chief employee-benefits analyst at KPMG Peat Marwick in Washington, D.C. Also, be sure to spend whatever is left in the 1994 flex account -- leftover balances cannot be rolled over into 1995 plans once the year is out. <p>Two-earner households should also consider having one spouse sign up for the other's health plan if each is now covered separately. Many companies who let employees drop company-provided health insurance will refund a portion of unused benefits back to employees. According to a 1994 survey of 489 companies by Hewitt Associates, a third of these employers refunded an average $618 annually back to those employees who waived their medical coverage; one in five reimbursed those who ditched their dental coverage an average $105 annually. Before exiting, however, workers should make sure employers will let them reenter, in the event of a layoff, divorce, or death. A company's benefits department can give more details about this option, but workers should be ready with proof that a spouse's plan will cover them.<p>The self-employed should tally up their health care costs and get set to write them off. Hill watchers agree that the 25 percent deduction for self-employed individuals' insurance costs, which expired at the end of 1993, will be reinstated for 1994 tax returns, thereby saving these taxpayers $2 billion. <p>-> BOOST RETIREMENT SAVINGS. As Senator Bill Bradley hollers that inadequate retirement savings is a "major security issue for Americans," Congress continues to take aim at retirement savings accounts, as it has for the last ten years. From limitations on IRA contributions to the new 20 percent withholding rule on certain plan distributions when taxpayers leave their place of employment, retirement accounts have gotten whacked. The latest blast: A little-known wrinkle in the Retirement Protection Act, a pending bill that is supposed to fix underfunded pension plans, may restrict 401(k) contributions.<p>If this bill passes, it would limit annual cost of living increases for 401(k) contributions. Frank McArdle, a partner at Hewitt Associates, a benefits consulting firm in Washington, D.C., explains: "Under current rules, if inflation increases to 4 percent, 1995 maximum contributions to 401(k) plans would increase to $9,609 from $9,240. The proposed new law would cap them at $9,500, which means a $109 increase in taxable income compared to current maximums." Barring that threat, put away the maximum allowed in these plans, and consider after-tax contributions as well. Also, explore other retirement-savings accounts such as SEPs or Keoghs if you earn income from projects separate from your job.<p>-> REDUCE YOUR INSURANCE PREMIUMS. Don't wait until a policy is up for renewal to begin cutting insurance costs. Insurance agents often slash premiums for home improvements or reduced auto usage before a policy's anniversary. "Installing new wiring or a burglar or smoke alarm can slice 2 to 5 percent off your premium," says Loretta Worters, a spokeswoman for the Insurance Information Institute in New York. "More sophisticated alarm systems can get you a 15 to 20 percent discount." Car poolers and home-office workers should also negotiate cheaper automobile insurance by arguing that they have a shorter than typical commute.<p>-> UPDATE FINANCIAL DOCUMENTS TO ACCOUNT FOR FAMILY CHANGES. Marriages, divorces, deaths, and births all should be properly reflected in financial paperwork. "Double-check trusts, wills, life insurance policies, and pension forms to ensure that all intended beneficiaries are listed," says Jeff Saccacio, a partner with Coopers & Lybrand in Los Angeles. And indicate children by their full name to avoid mix-ups from remarriages and adoptions. <p>-> STOP PAYING HIGH FEES FOR BANK SERVICES. Sky-high bank fees continue to silently suck up depositor money. Since 1990, the percentage increase in regular checking-account fees has risen three times the rate of inflation, according to a 1993 study done by U.S. Public Interest Research Group, a consumer-watchdog organization in Washington, D.C. "Recent bank mergers spell even higher costs for consumers because larger banks charge more for their greater variety of services," says Edmund Mierzwinski, a U.S. PIRG spokesman. Many bankers are eager to lower or eliminate fees for customers who consolidate several accounts at their bank. Also, consider using a mutual fund that gives check-writing privileges for monthly checks amounting to $250 or more, but watch out -- these checks can carry a $2-per-check fee and create a tax bill since they represent shares sold. <p>-> CONSIDER A FAT HOLIDAY GIFT TO KIDS. Now is when many parents consider shifting wealth to their more lightly taxed offspring. The IRS lets taxpayers give $10,000 each to as many people as they wish, tax free. It's a smart way to keep estates under the $600,000 mark, after which assets are taxed from 37 percent to as high as 60 percent. Trustees who make annual gifts to existing irrevocable life insurance or education trusts must mail beneficiaries a notice stating that a contribution was made on their behalf and specify the amount, or they won't qualify for the exclusion.<p>-> RETHINK INVESTMENTS. High-income taxpayers should take advantage of the spread between their top tax rates and the 28 percent capital-gains tax by investing in top-shelf growth stocks or growth funds. New York financial planner Norman Dawidowicz also suggests that investors ask fund managers or their bankers to pay out interest on liquid accounts, such as money markets, every six months instead of quarterly. While the interest income won't be immediately available, making this move by November 1 means the payout would be scheduled for April 1995, effectively shifting tax owed to next year.<p>-> CONSOLIDATE YOUR DEBT. Borrowers who pay 15 percent interest in dealer financing for a $25,000 car, or 18 percent or more on a $10,000 credit card balance, should consider cutting that cost by consolidating this debt into a 8.5 percent home-equity loan or credit line. Cardholders who roll over balances, as 65 percent do, will save $950 transferring a $10,000 card balance at 18 percent to a home-equity loan at 8.5 percent (not including loan fees). Also, up to $100,000 in home-equity interest is still tax-deductible. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Government, Legislation, Retirement Investing, Insurance, Taxaton, Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
