	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Buy and Hold:  Rest of the Story</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Buy and Hold:  Rest of the Story</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Buy and Hold:  Rest of the Story</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Experts<p>BUY AND HOLD: THE REST OF THE STORY
You can do better than just holding tight in a bear market -- and it doesn't make you a market timer. Just a smart investor.<p>By James B. Stack<p>We all make a lot of our decisions by creating a pair of alternatives and choosing between them. In a political debate, one side might say, "The United States either supports Boris Yeltsin or lets the communists resume power." A friend having a career crisis might say, "Either I go back to college or I'm trapped in this dead-end job forever." Many an argument about investing comes down to this kind of choice, too: Either pursue a buy-and-hold strategy, staying fully invested in the market through all its ups and downs, or try to time the market, moving out near predicted tops and back in near bottoms.<p>Unfortunately, it's easier to make bad decisions than good ones this way. Too often the alternatives are described inaccurately -- for example, does college really guarantee a flourishing career? And almost inevitably, other viable choices are ignored.<p>The argument between buy-and-hold and market-timing strategies usually goes astray in just such a way. First, most studies supporting one strategy or the other are fantasies that have little to do with the way either works for real investors. Second, thinking in terms of these two choices blinds investors to a third way, one that I practice in my portfolio.<p>In a black-and-white, two-choices-only world, I'd be classified as a market timer. And in at least one way that's accurate: I do think buy-and-hold strategies contain major flaws. But I don't manage my portfolio in the hope of predicting market tops and bottoms, so I guess I'm not a market timer either. The Hulbert Financial Digest calculates that my published mutual fund portfolio has outperformed the Standard & Poor's 500 Index by 44 percent from 1986 through the end of 1993. My results, I believe, come not because I've invented some market-timing system that lets me call tops and bottoms but because my system lets me control risk by increasing the cash portion of my portfolio when I think the market has become too dicey.<p>The best way to demonstrate why the either/or choice between buy and hold and market timing is so misleading is to look at some of the studies that argue this side or that. Let's examine one that's been reported in many sources, including Worth (see "Stock Plays: Overcoming the Bear Market Blues," July/August 1994; to find it, download the file "July/Aug94 Advisor" in Worth Online's software library). According to this study, $5,000 invested in the S&P 500 Index at the stock market's peak each year for the past 20 years would be worth $465,397 at the end of 1993. A market peak is the worst time to buy, yet look at the results. Buy and hold, the study says, works.<p>But what exactly does this study prove? Almost nothing, it turns out. First, the study really says very little about the superiority of either market timing or buy and hold. Instead, it's an endorsement of dollar-cost averaging, a proven investment technique that virtually everyone on either side of the market-timing debate endorses. In dollar-cost averaging, an investor sets aside the same amount of money every month or every year and ignores market gyrations. In the case of a new investor building a portfolio, it can be an excellent strategy -- if that investor has many years to wait before needing his or her money.<p>Second, the study doesn't accurately describe the two alternatives. The period of the study -- the past 20 years -- is itself a source of distortion. It's common knowledge that the past decade hasn't been representative of the long-term profits available from the stock market. Returns have been much better than average, while bear markets have been infrequent and mild. Compared with the previous 40 years, stock market profits over the past two decades have been 49.4 percent above the historical norm. Bear markets (defined as a decline of 20 percent or more in the S&P 500 Index) have been just half as frequent and only two thirds as severe. <p>The timing of those bears is just as important as their frequency. Suppose the study had begun in 1955 and run for 20 years, so that the period ended rather than began with the steep 1973-74 bear-market decline. The outcome would be shockingly different. In this case, the investor's total profit would be only 36 percent. Imagine saving and investing regularly for 20 years and ending up with less than you could have earned from a savings account yielding 3 percent.<p>Buy and hold does make sense for the new investor. But the closer an investor is to retirement or to needing his or her investment capital, the more dangerous a buy-and-hold strategy becomes. The numbers are very clear.<p>Take a hypothetical investor who sets aside $5,000 a year. At an annual growth rate of 11.3 percent (the average return of the S&P 500 Index over the past 60 years with dividends reinvested), the investor's portfolio would be worth $369,826 in 20 years. Even if that investor had encountered a severe bear market like that in 1973-74 in the first year of his investment plan, the 44.6 percent loss from that bear would have had little effect on his ending portfolio.<p>But what if a 1973-style bear market struck in the last year of his investment plan? It could wipe out half his portfolio. Imagine how that could dramatically change retirement plans.<p>A student of bear markets can point to other flaws in buy-and-hold studies. For example, most buy-and-hold arguments and historical studies use blue-chip averages like the Standard & Poor's 500 Index and the Dow Jones Industrial Average in calculating bear-market risks and losses. Both are large-company indexes that ride through market downturns very differently from small-company indexes, like the Nasdaq or Value Line indexes.<p>Of course, it's one thing to point out the problems in these pro-buy-and-hold studies and another to prove that market timing is a superior, or even valid, strategy -- especially when most studies in favor of market timing are seriously flawed in their own way. To prove that market timing works, these studies often assume an ability to get in and out of the market at bottoms and tops. Market timing of this sort is virtually impossible.<p>But consider a third alternative. Most healthy bull markets share certain characteristics. These include declining or stable interest rates, broad participation and strong leadership among stocks, and an identifiable uptrend in market indexes. The more characteristics like these you can identify, the more aggressive an investment strategy you should employ. The fewer you see, the more cautious a course you should steer.<p>Merely knowing that the Federal Reserve had started to raise interest rates, or that the bellwether Dow Jones Utility Average was hitting a new 12-month low in January, both while the Industrial Average was frolicking at new all-time highs, should have been strong confirmation that the first half of 1994 would not be good to investors.<p>When indicators like these start pointing to danger, I move to reduce the risk of bear-market losses by shifting some of my portfolio out of the markets. Most investors who use portfolio allocation only shift their assets between stocks and bonds, staying totally invested at all times. But that doesn't reduce risk when, as was the case in the first half of 1994, bonds fall at the same time as stocks. And as we saw in the inflationary decade of the 1970s, bonds can tumble even further than stocks.<p>There is a better option, one that treats cash (90-day T-bills or a money market fund) as a viable investment alternative at specific times. <p>Let's look at how this kind of investment strategy would have worked over the past 40 years. Choosing such a long period avoids one problem I criticized in the buy-and-hold studies. To avoid overestimating an investor's ability to know when to make a move, we'll pick a very simple rule as a guide. We'll use a moving average to gauge the market's long-term trend. For example, let's use a 150-day moving average of the S&P 500. We can calculate that average by taking the closing prices of the S&P 500 Index on each of the last 150 days and averaging them. Then, we use this indicator to read the market. If today's close of the S&P 500 Index is greater than that average price, then we can conclude that the market is in an uptrend. If instead today's S&P Index is less than the moving average, the market is in a downtrend.<p>Now suppose we buy a mutual fund approximating the S&P 500 Index when the index is trading above the 150-day moving average. Suppose also that whenever the S&P Index falls below the moving average, we shift our portfolio into the safety of T-bills or a money market fund. <p>Over the past 40 years, such a strategy could have more than doubled an investor's total return from the stock market. For example, a single $10,000 investment made 40 years ago and never moved -- the consummate buy-and-hold strategy -- would have grown to $676,035 by June 30, 1994. If instead an investor used the moving average to determine when to step into cash, he would have a portfolio worth $1,341,448. That's about twice the profit. <p>The results come from risk management, not from picking tops and bottoms. Someone using a buy-and-hold approach over the past 40 years would have lost more than 20 percent on seven different occasions, with two losses exceeding 35 percent.<p>Meanwhile, the individual using the 150-day moving average to determine when to sit quietly on the sidelines in cash wouldn't have avoided all down markets. But the worst-case loss would have been a 15 percent loss. This strategy would have avoided every one of those 20 percent and 35 percent losses.<p>In 40 years this indicator never caught the exact top or bottom of the market. It merely introduced sensible risk management to this portfolio.<p>At my company, InvesTech, I use a combination of indicators that have a much broader scope than the simple 150-day moving average. Today, they indicate that the stock market is on a more tenuous footing than at any time in the past four years. For example, sentiment indicators, such as last January's record cash inflows to mutual funds, are convincing evidence that the bullish bandwagon is overcrowded. In addition, most market indexes have spent much of the year below their long-term moving averages. And our indicators of monetary conditions turned negative in the first quarter of this year, saying to me that for the first time since 1990, Federal Reserve policy is no longer investor friendly. Bottom line: This is a high-risk market in which capital preservation should be emphasized. That's why two thirds of my portfolio has been in cash since January.<p>There are alternatives to a blind buy-and-hold strategy. The wise investor knows that the best strategies don't just seek the highest possible return -- but the highest return with the lowest risk.
---------------
James B. Stack edits the InvesTech Mutual Fund Advisor from Whitefish, Montana. The newsletter earned the Hulbert Financial Digest's top ranking for risk-adjusted return for the period from 1986 to 1993.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Stock Market Trends

