		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-What Discount?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What Discount?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-What Discount?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Cover<p>WHAT DISCOUNT?
That's what investors ask when a supposedly cut-rate broker hits them up for a hidden fee or executes a trade at a ridiculously high cost. The way to avoid these traps is to be a discriminating consumer. Here's how.<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>It's been roughly ten years since discount brokerages began making serious inroads on Wall Street, stealing business away from established, high-profile firms like <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> and Smith Barney. The opportunity to trade stocks at cut-rate commissions drew investors first in a trickle, then a flood. Today, more than 13 million individuals -- roughly a third of all investors in the U.S. -- execute stock trades through discounters. According to the Securities Industry Association, discount brokers snared 14 percent of retail investors' commission dollars last year. That's up from 8.6 percent five years earlier.<p>The rise of discounters, however, hasn't necessarily made life easier for investors. Faced with higher costs, many cut-rate firms now charge for services that investors once got free. These fees, plus high execution and clearing costs, add up -- sometimes even negating the advantage of low commissions. At the same time, full-service brokers have responded to the competition by cutting their own prices. Some now offer their better customers commissions as low as those advertised by discount shops.<p>Amid all this is a confusing array of come-ons, multiple-fee structures, hidden charges, and bait-and-switch price gouging. Industry advertising even acknowledges the trend. "No hidden costs. Now there's a radical idea," trumpets an ad for Brown & Co., an affiliate of <a name="NASD:CHFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12961"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chemical Bank</b></a>. Ads paid for by StockCross, a Boston-based discount broker, ask, "What do you call an investor who uses a deep-discount broker to save money on trades, only to lose more on poor execution?" Answer: "A philanthropist."<p>Investors looking for a good deal -- or just trying to avoid being taken for a ride -- must be more discriminating than ever when shopping for a broker. It is important not only to know how the costs of trading add up at different firms but also to understand how these expenses can vary depending on specific needs. An investor who wants to dump ten shares of stock he got as a birthday gift may find his interests better served at one firm, while an active trader may discover a better deal somewhere else.<p>Commissions -- what a firm charges to execute a trade -- are still the most important thing to look at. According to a study conducted by New York investment firm Mercer, Inc., a trade of 200 shares of a $30 stock -- described as a typical trade -- will likely cost $151 at a full-service broker, $95 at a discounter, and $35 at a so-called deep-discount firm.<p>Next on the list are fees. Many discount brokers levy a host of supplemental charges for administrative services -- such as delivery of stock certificates, redemption of bonds when they come due, and mailing copies of past account statements or Value Line research reports. These services vary greatly among firms; full-service firms generally charge nothing for them. A few discounters and deep discounters also provide them gratis. Others bill for everything but walking in the front door.<p>The third critical area of investor costs is the trickiest to quantify. Unlike the out-of-pocket fees that show up on a statement, these costs become evident only when it comes time to tote up profits or losses on a trade. They are the sometimes-onerous costs associated with executions of stock trades on the over-the-counter or Nasdaq market.<p>Although performance in this area can also vary widely from one brokerage to the next, full-service firms generally outperform the discount or deep-discount houses. This isn't a major concern when it comes to trading shares on the New York Stock Exchange or the American Stock Exchange. Both of these markets have specialists who match sellers with buyers and try to get the best price on a stock for investors. But the over-the-counter markets have no specialists to match trades. That makes the spread between the bid and asked prices fair game. Some brokers pocket the difference; others pass the savings on to their customers. It's not unheard of, either, for some brokers to pad their profits by moving trades of New York Stock Exchange- or American Exchange-listed shares to the Nasdaq market. This little trick lets them nick their customers on the spread rather than allowing them the chance of getting a price between the bid and asked.<p>In many ways, recent events in the brokerage business resemble what happened in the mutual fund business not so long ago. Early in the 1980s, there were two varieties of funds -- no-load and front-end load. Then various hidden charges crept into the equation -- so-called 12b-1 fees that went to pay a fund's marketing costs, back-end loads, even declining back-end loads. What was simple became complex and more costly.<p>Even an investor's haggling skills can now make a difference in the choice of broker. That's because many of the full-service shops today will negotiate their commissions. How big a price break will they give? It may take some perseverance -- maybe even a threat or two -- but most will eventually come through with price breaks of between 25 and 50 percent for a good client. On 200 shares of a $30 stock, a 25 percent discount reduces a full-service commission from $151 to around $114. That's only $20 more than the commission on a similar trade levied by discounters like <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a> or Fidelity Brokerage, the two largest discount firms. <p>Another comparison: Fidelity's minimum commission on a trade of up to 100 shares or $2,500 is $30 plus 1.7 percent of principal. That adds up to around $72 on 100 shares of a $25 stock. Ditto for Charles Schwab. A full-service broker charges a nondiscounted commission of $85 for the same-size transaction, $63 if marked down 25 percent.<p>What about life with the so-called deep discounters? Terrific, assuming you trade often and in large size or you have a sizable credit balance in your account. To get the lowest rates offered by Fidelity's Spartan, an investor must have at least $20,000 to invest initially must make at least 40 trades a year. Such a player would pay flat-rate commissions of $25 to $30 per trade regardless of transaction size. At Kennedy, Cabot in Beverly Hills, customers must trade in lots of 5,000 shares to pay a 2-cent-per-share commission, versus the 5 cents per share on 100-share orders (with a minimum commission of $30).<p>But deep discounters aren't altruists. They make up for their generosity by charging substantially higher service fees, up to $25 to wire funds, $25 for bounced checks, and $5.95 for a copy of an S&P company report.<p>An investor who can cajole a full-service broker into providing a discount of 25 percent or more deserves a pat on the back. It's a good deal, because most full-service firms don't charge for administrative services such as dispensing company research reports and past statements or providing safekeeping for certificates. And working with a trustworthy broker can also save an investor from making an expensive investment mistake, such as buying on a hot tip or selling a stock too soon.<p>Choosing a discounter, on the other hand, can be like ordering dinner at a sushi bar -- everything has a separate price tag. Within the industry, the practice of soaking customers on a wide array of fees even has a nickname: "harvesting."<p>Harvesting an investor's money can include charges for past statements, the delivery of stock certificates, the execution of legal documents like stock powers or powers of attorney, and the transfer of an account to an heir. Customers can even be billed for inactivity in their accounts.<p>An investor who wants to transfer ownership of a stock certificate to someone else -- an heir, for example -- pays nothing at full-service broker Prudential Securities. But deep discounters like Fidelity's Spartan Brokerage or Sherwood's National Discount charge $35 and $25 respectively per security. At Oppenheimer, charges for a bond redemption are zero; at discounters, the fees can be as much as $50. Customers who like to read up on company or mutual fund reports published by S&P, Value Line, or Morningstar also must pay for the privilege. Charges vary from $3 to $5.95 apiece.<p>Discounter Olde charges $2 for extra monthly statements; Schwab charges $2.50 for back copies. Schwab proudly says it can retrieve stock quotes going all the way back to the original Woodstock at $3 per. Both these services are free at most full-service or discount brokers. Although almost all brokers charge customers some sort of fee for wiring funds from the firm to the client's bank, full-service brokers bill exactly what the bank charges, usually $15. Discounters charge up to $30 for each transfer. <p>Commissions and fees alone, however, do not tell the whole story. Unless an investor trades only blue-chip stocks listed on the NYSE, it's also critical to know something about how brokers execute trades.<p>How much of a difference can execution make? According to Perrin Long, a veteran brokerage-industry analyst at First of Michigan, the typical individual investor trades eight times a year in an active market. Let's look again at that typical trade of 200 shares of a $30 over-the-counter stock: Bid at 30, offer at 30.50, which means if you're a buyer, you'd pay $30.50, and if you're selling, you'd get $30 for your shares. <p>On the basis of these estimates, a broker who could routinely execute OTC trades at the middle of the bid/asked spread -- $30.25 a share -- would save about $400 for a typical customer over the course of a year. That $400 in savings would very nearly offset the difference in commissions charged by a nondiscounting full-service broker (about $1,208 annually in this example) and a discount broker (about $760 annually). Throw in two research reports and a couple of stock tender offers, and your discount broker has become more costly than the full-service firm. <p>Last year, Charles M.C. Lee, assistant professor of accounting at the University of Michigan's School of Business Administration, published a study in the Journal of Finance quantifying the excess costs borne by investors when their trades are executed on Nasdaq rather than on the New York Stock Exchange. Using a sample size of 332,121 matched buy executions in 1989, Lee found that in total dollars, the additional costs for investors executing off-Big Board trades was between $36 million and $47 million.<p>Most times, a good full-service broker will do a better job working stock trades for customers, getting prices that fall between bid and asked. With a discounter, investors almost always pay the asked or higher side of the market when they buy and get the bid or lower side of the market when they sell. <p>Some discounters assure their customers that they will, in fact, shop between the bid and the asked prices in an OTC stock on both limit and market orders. But, says Charles Schwab & Co. spokesman Hugo Quackenbush, "we do not generally shop around." He claims that during the time it takes to shop, the market might move against you. Barry Boyte, vice president for marketing at deep discounter Jack White & Co., says, "For a small order, say 100 or 200 shares, there's not much we can do. For a large order of 8,000 to 9,000 shares, we'd try to work the trade."<p>Discounters who refuse to work a trade probably do so because they own their own market-making firm and like the high margins associated with earning the spread on a trade. Discounters who don't own their own trading firms, or who don't trade in a specific stock, cannot work the bid/asked spread. Instead, they must give customer orders to larger firms for execution. They get paid for these orders -- roughly 2 cents a share -- by firms that execute them, a practice known as payment for order flow.<p>Proponents of this system claim investors aren't hurt by it. But opponents say payment for order flow encourages brokers to direct orders to markets where they will be most lucrative -- in other words, where spreads are wider. As Lee points out, "In light of these price differences, the broker's primary responsibility could potentially be compromised by order flow inducements."<p>Few investors realize that their equity orders have any value to market makers. That's because the amount of money a firm earns on its customers' orders is never revealed on statements or trade confirmations. It may not seem like much, but being paid to trade a stock is a way for brokerage firms to make money on investors' transactions. Although it isn't a cost that investors pay directly, it is certainly not returned in the form of a rebate.<p>Last October the Securities and Exchange Commission proposed a rule change regarding payment for order flow; it proposed that firms disclose to customers whether any payment for order flow has been made, the amount, and the brokerages involved. The proposal is currently being reviewed by the SEC's Market Regulation Division.<p>How can investors avoid paying a high price for a low commission? A good way to start is by asking other investors about their experiences with local brokers. Whom do they trust and why? Who has given them a good deal on trades?<p>When talking to a broker, there's nothing wrong with listening to the pitch about the firm's ultra-super-rock-bottom commissions. But afterward, ask for a complete accounting of the firm's fees. Question the account representative who answers the phone about payments for stock safekeeping, research reports, fees for wiring funds, and other charges.<p>Next, it's important for investors to consider how their own needs match what the broker has to offer. How often are they likely to use the different services? What will their year-end bill look like? If it seems too high, investors should try negotiating prices down before moving on to another prospect.<p>It's also a good idea to find out whether a broker is a market maker on a particular stock. If you are trading an OTC stock through a broker who is also a market maker, there's a very good chance the broker is earning money on both the spread and the order flow. Use this knowledge to try to negotiate a lower commission on such trades. On a listed security always specify that your trade be executed on the New York or the American Stock Exchange.<p>One indication of good faith is for a firm to include its Central Registration Depository number along with the 800 number for the National Securities Dealers' Investor Services Department in its literature. This allows investors to check whether a firm or its employees have ever had any disciplinary action taken against them.<p>Selecting a broker isn't the end of the battle. When making trades, it's important for investors to specify the type of order they want to make, limit, or market. Someone who wants in or out of a stock at any price should be prepared to lose the spread.<p>For large orders, it also helps to instruct the broker to execute it in one lot and not in batches of two or three. When the broker splits the trade, as it's called, it can mean paying commissions twice and three times over. <p>There may not be a lot of outfits out there that will work an investor's trades and provide good discounts. But they do exist. One example of such a firm is the midsize Dallas Research & Trading, founded in 1990, with offices in Dallas and Tampa. The firm negotiates on commissions, charges minimal servicing fees, provides detailed research, and never trades in issues for its house account that conflict with its customers' accounts. DRT also welcomes customers to its trading floor in Dallas to watch its brokers working orders on Selectnet, an automated order system that gives a price between the bid and asked.<p>Knowledgeable investors can get similar treatment not far from home if they spend enough time shopping around.  
---------------
Manjeet Kripalani is an associate editor at Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

