				<font size=6><b>94/09-High Risk, High Reward</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Who dares, wins -- and lowers overall portfolio risk at the same time. These eight aggressive plays could return 40 percent a year.<p>The retreat in stock and bond markets that marked the first half of the year has prompted many investors to rethink their portfolios. Should I ditch my risky investments and batten down the hatches? Or should I stay put and ride it out?<p>On Wall Street, at least, the conventional wisdom appears to favor caution: The easy gains are gone, so this is no time to be aggressive. Stick to rock-solid stocks, bonds, and mutual funds, and avoid the chancy stuff. At some point, the market will turn around. It always does. <p>Two things trouble us about this advice. First, as we pointed out in our last issue (see "New Strategies for Tough Markets," the cover story from Worth's July/August issue; you'll find it in the "July/Aug94 Cover Story" file in Worth Online's software library), there's a good chance that it may be some time before the markets regain their former vitality. With inflationary clouds still blowing in from the horizon, pressure continues to mount on the Federal Reserve Board to further hike interest rates. Meanwhile, foreign investors are showing less and less interest in dollar-denominated investments, reducing the overall demand for U.S. stocks and bonds. <p>Second, Wall Street's timid advice ignores one of the great paradoxes of investing -- that conservative strategies meant to reduce risk often end up doing just the opposite.<p>More than 30 years of research on building portfolios that increase return and lower risk won Harry Markowitz and William Sharpe the Nobel prize for economics in 1990. Among other things, their work demonstrated how cautious investors, in an effort to get out of risky stocks and bonds, can end up leaving entire slices of the investment pie out of their portfolios. The result, they found, typically increased -- rather than limited -- an investor's exposure to risk.<p>We all know, for instance, that the stocks of big dividend-paying companies, such as utilities, are individually less risky than other types of investments. Yet a portfolio composed only of utility stocks can be very risky indeed. Just since the beginning of this year, in fact, the Dow Jones utility index has lost about 20 percent of its value; a portfolio composed only of "safe" utility stocks would have been hit quite hard.<p>At the same time, a portfolio that had invested in the rise of the yen against the dollar by buying options in early January could have earned a 500 percent return by mid-July. Adding this riskier investment to a portfolio of utility stocks would have produced a much safer combination than utility stocks alone.<p>If the markets remain stagnant in the months ahead, the only way for investors to earn solid returns will be to increase their portfolio's exposure to risky asset classes. This doesn't mean leaping at the latest fad, or taking wild chances with big chunks of the family nest egg. But it does mean rethinking the role of risk in a portfolio.<p>With this in mind, Worth set out to identify a number of alternative investments that might serve this purpose. At the beginning of our search, we assumed investors would want to keep at least 90 percent of their portfolios in common stocks and bonds issued by established companies or governments. The remaining 10 percent, though, could be reserved for higher-risk investments whose potential performance wouldn't correlate closely with the rest of the portfolio. This allocation scheme helped establish our parameters for risk and return. <p>First, since this part of the portfolio is supposed to help reduce overall risk, we ruled out all instruments that come with an unlimited downside -- such as commodities plays that can end up losing more than the size of an investor's original investment. If things went truly sour, we wanted to lose no more than the 10 percent of the portfolio set aside for high-risk investing.<p>Second, we looked for investments that require $50,000 or less to play. Ideally, we hoped investors would be able to add more than one high-risk, high-reward candidate to a portfolio, a move that would provide even better diversification. For the same reason, we also wanted to avoid investment schemes that eat up huge amounts in commissions.<p>Third, we wanted to see potential for a big payoff. No sense taking a big risk for an extra one or two percentage points in performance. So we turned to the professional venture capitalists' definition of an investment home run as our benchmark: Each investment had to have the potential to return ten times the original capital in seven years. That's an effective annual return of 40 percent -- enough to make a big difference in the overall performance of any investor's total portfolio. <p>Fourth, we combed the landscape for investments in asset classes that aren't found in most portfolios. Adding more stocks, bonds, and mutual funds wouldn't do much to improve the diversification of most of our readers' portfolios. So we went looking for investments in currencies, real estate partnerships, venture capital, options, and other instruments that don't march in lockstep with garden-variety bonds and equities.<p>Last, we looked for pricing opportunities. Many of the individual asset classes mentioned above made strong moves this year. When the move was downward, we checked to see if lower prices had eliminated some of the risk while giving us more upside. As a well-known French contrarian adage of the 19th century says, "Achetez aux canons, vendez aux clarions." (Buy on the cannons, sell on the trumpets.)<p>We ended up with eight choices, and our menu is nothing if not eclectic. We found ways to earn this kind of potential annual return by buying busted real estate partnerships or shorting the recently all-powerful Japanese yen. In the battered field of emerging markets, we discovered a way to leverage Mexican bonds that could return 50 percent, as well as a way to bet on the recovery of the Hong Kong equity market. In Arakis Energy we found a company whose fortunes are closely tied to international politics and not the stock market as a whole. We even turned up two private deals that give an investor a way to share in the kinds of returns earned by professional venture capitalists. Finally, we found a way to transform bread-and-butter U.S. Treasury bonds into high-powered plays on the course of interest rates that could produce fivefold returns on invested capital -- in just a few months.<p>These eight plays aren't the only high-risk, high-reward deals that the inquiring investor will be able to find. And this list isn't meant to be the end of an investor's search for that one big payday. Instead, we hope that investors will use it as a guide in thinking about risk and reward -- in all probability the least understood part of investing -- and attempt to go beyond these eight examples. Even if you never put a single dollar into one of these deals but instead just use this article to think about the role of risk in your portfolio, you will already have earned a high return on your investment. <p>-- by Scott McMurray<p><p>PLAY 1:
LEVERAGING MEXICAN BONDS
---------------
TYPE OF PLAY: International bonds
PRICE: $20,000 buys $100,000 worth
POTENTIAL UPSIDE: 50 percent return in nine months, if the peso holds its ground
POTENTIAL DOWNSIDE: A currency devaluation eats up all the interest payments
CRUCIAL DUE DILIGENCE: Check the fallout from the August 21 presidential elections. A weak government could break the budget -- and the peso -- to buy domestic peace.<p>Anyone who likes volatile markets will love Mexico. This year, rebels revolted in Chiapas, the leading contender for the national presidency was shot, and the historically invincible Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) handled the investigation of the assassination so badly that it looked like the party could actually lose the presidency. Among the results: Mexico's peso plunged 9 percent, and the country's bond market got hammered as yields on government bonds soared to more than 16 percent.<p>So now, if Mexico remains true to form, it may be time for the pendulum to swing the other way.<p>Mexican Treasury securities, or CETES, are the most liquid of Mexican investments. CETES are auctioned weekly by Mexico's central bank in maturities of a few weeks to two years. Interest rates on three-month CETES hit 19 percent earlier this year, dropped to 9 percent, and then settled at around 16 percent.<p>To increase returns even more, investors can buy CETES bonds on credit by making something that's known as a forward purchase. This allows a 20 percent down payment, with the remainder of the price due at maturity.<p>Although not all brokers and dealers will arrange forward purchases, investors with established banking relationships in the U.S. should have little trouble. Other investors must hunt for a stockbroker who is willing to help.<p>Under ideal circumstances, a forward purchase of CETES would go something like this: An investor plunks down $20,000 to purchase a three-month, $100,000 note. The investor then rolls the note over three times while interest rates remain fairly stable (admittedly a bold assumption). In the process, the investor collects $16,000 of interest, paid in pesos. Borrowing costs, at 7.5 percent, run to $6,000, reducing the purchaser's net to $10,000, or a return of 50 percent in nine months. <p>Is there a catch? Of course. As events in the first half of 1994 proved, in Mexico everything can go wrong.<p>At the moment, the PRI faces a fight in the August presidential elections but should overcome internal bickering, troubled policies, and challenges from the right and the left to win. Despite the PRI's problems, there is no mandate for a change in economic policies. Economists argue that as long as the government holds its course, Mexico could earn an investment-grade rating on its debt in 1995.<p>A bigger risk may lie in the value of the peso. Mexico pegs the exchange rate of the peso to the dollar, which has worked effectively for several years to stabilize the Mexican currency. But as a result of this year's political uncertainty and the first effects of the North American Free Trade Agreement, the country is running a large trade deficit in goods and services. That deficit will put pressure on the new president to devalue the peso, some say by as much as 10 percent. <p>That's by no means a certainty, however, and economists are divided on when and whether the peso will tumble. A steady currency has been one of the underpinnings of Mexico's economic performance of the past six years. The central bank appears determined to support the peso. But currency traders could dump pesos and overwhelm any governmental efforts at stabilization.<p>The bullish case for Mexico assumes the government will hold its own against currency speculators. After 12 years of heroic effort, Mexico won't lightly abandon the economic policies put in place by Carlos Salinas de Gortari and his predecessors. Economists who believe that, including Ken Ackbaalii of First Interstate Bank in Los Angeles, argue that the Mexican economy will revive and the peso won't be devalued suddenly. "The prospects for Mexico look fairly good," Ackbaalii says. "We think the cross-rate between the dollar and the peso should remain fairly stable." <p>An investor putting money into the country now also has at least one major advantage over investors who did so in 1993: The market has already discounted a lot of bad news. "A year ago Mexico was a country that could do nothing wrong," says Nancie Dupier, a vice president at the Chase Manhattan Private Bank. "The markets are much more sensitive now" to bad news and, therefore, much more reasonably priced.<p>Even if the bulls are wrong, the downside in a bet on CETES is less than on many high-risk investments. If the peso is devalued 10 percent, the interest earned on the CETES over the course of a year will more than offset the peso's fall. Barring a radical political event in Mexico, the downside is a little bit better than breakeven. If the bulls are right, the upside could be spectacular. <p>-- by Gary Hector<p><p>PLAY 2:
UNDERWRITING NEW PRODUCTS
---------------
TYPE OF PLAY: Venture capital
PRICE: $30,000 for half a unit
POTENTIAL UPSIDE: Dividends of $25,000 to $43,750 year after year
POTENTIAL DOWNSIDE: No sales, no profits -- no exit
CRUCIAL DUE DILIGENCE: Run the numbers. What's the return if this is just a niche product?<p>When the stock market hits the skids and prices of public companies fall, many investors start scanning the quotes looking for cheap deals on the New York Stock Exchange or Nasdaq. Truth is, it's an even better time to look for bargains among privately held companies.<p>Privately held companies, of course, don't trade on the public stock markets. Experienced venture-capital investors, however, know that the price of private companies is normally pegged to public valuations. When the comparables go down, so does the price of private shares. <p>Right now, Reynard CVC Inc. of Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey, may present just such a bargain, especially considering that its founders have already rejected offers from two professional venture-capital firms who wanted to take too big a hunk of the pie. <p>Reynard is fairly far along for a venture-capital deal. It's not a company made up of two guys, an idea, and a garage. Its 36-year-old founder and president, Arthur Herr, invented and patented a superior package for compact discs. Both The New York Times and PC Magazine have provided big endorsements by calling Herr's Laserfile a dramatic improvement over the jewel box. The jewel box is the pesky plastic case invented by Philips that currently houses most CDs. It is particularly difficult for children, older people, and certain financial writers to negotiate. What's more, its flimsy hinges have a propensity for breaking when the box is dropped.<p>That's where the Laserfile comes in. It does away with breakable hinges, relying instead on a sliding drawer. When halfway out, the drawer can be bent downward, allowing a user to grasp the disc by the center hole and easily remove it.<p>Worldwide, the jewel-box market is enormous (2 billion units per year and growing fast). "That should rise to about 5 billion by the year 2000, with much of the increase coming from CD-ROMs," says Herr. If Reynard snatches just 5 percent of the market, Herr and his partner, Henry D. Sedgwick, project that the company would generate pretax profits of 20 percent to 35 percent on annual sales of $25 million.<p>To date, Reynard has sold 250,000 Laserfiles to an emphatically eclectic group of customers. They include late-night infomercial habitue Tony Robbins, the Acoustic Sounds music label, Macmillan Publishing (for medical CD-ROMs), and the United States Marine Corps (for CD-ROMs describing, appropriately enough, the use of CD-ROM technology during the gulf war).<p>Want a piece of the action? Reynard is trying to raise $500,000 to $1 million from private investors who, the company hopes, will want less than the venture firms demanded. Much of the proceeds would go toward marketing as well as toward producing molding equipment to be used by subcontractors who would make the Laserfiles.<p>For $30,000, investors can get the equivalent of about a 0.5 percent stake in the company, meaning that Herr and Sedgwick currently value Reynard at $6 million or so. That ownership stake will translate into a proportionate share in the company's distributable income. (Reynard will retain some earnings for working capital and other needs.) If the company ever gets to $25 million in sales and 20 percent to 35 percent in pretax profits, dividends (0.5 percent of annual profits) would come to about $25,000 to $43,750 a year on each $30,000 unit. Year after year.<p>Still, Reynard may never reach its targets. As the founders of many a bankrupt company can testify, producing a better product doesn't necessarily produce sales. Skeptics and competitors doubt that the company's product offers enough benefit to get customers to switch from the current jewel-box design. Unfortunately, it costs the same 10 cents to 11 cents to produce one Laserfile that it does to make a standard jewel box. Since the existing packaging doesn't seem to be driving compact-disc purchasers away, why should the industry switch?<p>"It's going to be hard to supersede the jewel box," says a spokesperson for Ivy Hill Corp., a printing and packaging subsidiary of Time Warner. Even with Time Warner's clout, Ivy Hill's own alternative CD package -- called the Fliptop -- has sold only 5 million units since its debut 18 months ago. "That's spectacular," says the spokesperson.<p>Reynard CVC (201-567-8998) is looking for 10 to 20 investors. Individual investors interested in finding other private companies can try one of the many venture-capital networks, such as the Technology Capital Network (617-253-7163) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, which holds regular venture-capital evenings that match investors and companies. <p>-- by Andrew Feinberg<p><p>PLAY 3:
DRILLING FOR OIL IN SUDAN
---------------
TYPE OF PLAY: Penny stocks
PRICE: $569 per 100 shares
POTENTIAL UPSIDE: A $5.69 stock could become a $75 stock in five years.
POTENTIAL DOWNSIDE: All the oil stays in the ground.
CRUCIAL DUE DILIGENCE: The civil war isn't over; will the rebels play ball?<p>Is Arakis Energy just another "story" stock -- you know, the kind the market has been hammering lately? Or is it a real blockbuster in the making?<p>Earlier this year, Arakis, a tiny oil-development company based in Vancouver, British Columbia, acquired a license to develop oil in a south-central patch of Sudan. This area is generally thought to contain at least 300 million barrels of proven oil reserves. Star stock picker Lawrence Auriana, comanager of the $1.2 billion Kaufmann Fund, believes the 12.2 million-acre area could ultimately prove to hold 600 million barrels of oil. Independent international oil consultant Daniel Johnston, who first looked at the potential of this project in 1983, agrees. "If there are 600 million barrels there," adds Auriana, whose small-company growth fund owns 250,000 shares in Arakis, "this could be a $75 stock in five years." <p>Auriana's numbers seem plausible, especially in light of the Triton Energy story. The development of a single spectacular oil field in the nation of Colombia -- the largest find in the Western hemisphere in over a decade -- propelled the Triton stock from $4.62 a share in 1990 to $52.50 a share in 1991. That field was bigger, at 2 billion barrels of proven reserves, but Triton owned only a 24 percent stake and the Colombian government was entitled to half of Triton's revenue. <p>Then why was Arakis (listed as AKSEF on the Nasdaq small-cap market) trading at a measly $5.69 a share on July 18? The answer has to do with transporting oil out of Sudan, torn by a bloody and intractable 11-year-old civil war. The war pits Muslims in northern Sudan against Christians in the south. Although the fundamentalist Islamic military government firmly controls the north, the south is devastated by war; more than 1.3 million of Sudan's people have died as a result of the fighting and the accompanying starvation. The 11 years of war have also created at least 1.8 million refugees, according to a U.S. Committee for Refugees report. The 1983 census, the last one done, put the population at 21 million.<p>This was why Chevron, which negotiated the original concession on the Arakis field in 1974, threw up its hands and walked away, despite spending more than $1 billion developing the huge finds. In November 1992, as the civil war dragged on, Chevron sold the license to an Islamic entrepreneur, who sold it to privately held State Petroleum. On January 25, 1994, State, headquartered in Calgary, Alberta, and owned by a group of Muslim businessmen, signed a share-exchange agreement with Arakis that made it a wholly owned Arakis subsidiary.<p>Until that time, Arakis was developing natural-gas reserves in southeastern Kentucky and had no international oil-exploration experience. Its revenues for the eight-month period ended December 31, 1993, were only $2,295,478. Investors in State received 6 million new shares of Arakis at $2.80 a share, about 32 percent of the company. <p>Arakis officials don't see the Sudanese war as much of a problem. In fact, they assert that it isn't even being fought. Lutfur Khan, the president of State Petroleum, who negotiated the company's oil-production-sharing agreement with the Sudanese government, flatly says, "There is no civil war right now." Khan says the government has entered into a peace agreement with rebel Christian forces.<p>Is this so? U.S. ambassador Donald Pettersen says in a telephone interview from Khartoum, "Of course the civil war is still going on." The multilateral peace negotiations involving Sudan's neighbors "have not produced anything yet," he says, adding that "in the absence of a negotiated settlement in which it is clear how resources will be allocated in the country, I don't believe rebel forces would be agreeable to exploitation of the oil." <p>Other experts on the situation in Sudan, however, see things differently. "The Heglig/Muglad area deep in Southern Kordofan, where the oil wells are located, is not affected directly by the war," says Peter Verney, editor of London-based Sudan Update. "A pipeline could be built without passing through any area of rebel conflict, but it would present a target for sabotage nonetheless." <p>Oil consultant Johnston notes that Triton Energy was able to develop its Colombian field despite guerrilla attacks that blew up one oil rig. A Colombian army garrison is stationed at the drill site, and last year guerrillas averaged one sabotage attempt per week on oil operations there. "Dealing with guerrillas, in a way, is just another cost of doing business," says Johnston. Arakis, meanwhile, says it is moving ahead full speed. It projects that it will be producing 65,000 barrels of oil a day by early 1996.<p>-- by Andrew Gluck<p><p>PLAY 4:
JOINING DISTRESSED PARTNERSHIPS
---------------
TYPE OF PLAY: Depressed real estate
PRICE: Less than $600 for two partnership interests
POTENTIAL UPSIDE: Up to 153 percent with current yield and very, very long-term appreciation
POTENTIAL DOWNSIDE: Long waits and the risk that you've picked the wrong property
CRUCIAL DUE DILIGENCE: Pick properties, not simply markets.<p>Although the best days of real estate investing had already come to a close by 1986, a visitor to the Chicago headquarters of JMB Realty Corp. wouldn't have guessed it. At the time, JMB was one of the country's largest and most successful sponsors of real estate partnerships. Pictures of skyscrapers that its early partnerships had helped finance lined the walls of its sumptuous offices.<p>Yet an investor who paid $1,000 for an interest in JMB's Carlyle Real Estate Limited Partnership XIV back then would today own a piece of paper worth just $10 to $115. Similarly, partnership interests in Carlyle XIII that originally sold for $1,000 traded for as low as $10 each last July.<p>Of course, not all 1980s-vintage real estate partnership interests would make a good swap for a rookie baseball card. But it's the cents-on-the-dollar partnerships that present real opportunities. At current prices, these partnerships come with built-in leverage that could give patient investors very attractive returns. <p>How attractive? According to Jon Hale, a broker at Securities Service Network in Sarasota, Florida, it's relatively easy to find partnerships in the secondary market that now pay annual yields of 9 percent to 11 percent. Ross Bowler, president of 2nd Market Capital Services, of Madison, Wisconsin, asserts that even higher returns, up to 20 percent, can be found among obscure partnerships where there are few market makers -- as opposed to the myriad deals put together by the likes of formerly aggressive partnership marketers like Merrill Lynch and Prudential Bache.<p>Want to really go for broke? Then consider so-called broken partnerships. These are deals that have gone so sour they aren't making any current payments to investors. Still, many own valuable assets -- assets that must sit in place, possibly appreciating, until the partnership is liquidated. <p>Unfortunately, waiting for liquidation to take place can turn an investor gray. These deals offer general partners huge disincentives to liquidate -- management fees that get paid each year even if the partnership isn't making any money -- and their official life may be as long as 50 years. Indeed, many partnerships offered in the 1980s won't liquidate until after the year 2030 -- making them the ultimate in buy-it-and-forget-it investments.<p>Still, the potential for a big payoff is there, says Ronald Baker, a principal at Invenex, an investment company that buys partnerships. Suppose that back in the 1980s, an investor bought ten units in partnerships for $1,000 each. Also suppose that those units were now available for $30 apiece. <p>Typically, the general partners and brokers would have taken up to 25 percent of the original investment at inception to cover selling, administration, and marketing expenses. They would have used the remaining $7,500, leveraged with borrowed money (typically two borrowed dollars for every dollar in capital), to purchase the equivalent of $22,500 in real estate.<p>Today, this real estate is probably still worth at least $15,000, the amount of the original debt. If it wasn't, the lenders would have foreclosed on the property. Thus, for $300 an investor can reclaim ten units and gain more than 95 percent leverage.<p>Now suppose that the property appreciates at 5 percent a year from here on out. At this rate, the total value of the asset controlled after year one will be $16,065. That's a 255 percent return on the original $300 investment. (A more conservative 3 percent appreciation produces a first-year return of 153 percent.) <p>Similarly, after four years, an investor would record a tenfold return. Over 40 years, the appreciation of the property would more than overwhelm the original debt. Note: It's very important to find limited-partnership units that don't carry huge passive tax liabilities. In worst-case scenarios, these can wipe out any gain. Have an accountant check out any deal.<p>Brokers at the few firms that deal in the secondary market for limited partnerships open their conversations with a chorus of bewares: No two partnerships are alike; their assets and income flows have to be studied carefully; some are tax-liability bombshells; good ones are hard to find. This is all generally true. Don't ignore the caveats.<p>A good way to research specific limited partnerships is with The Limited Partnership Locator, a directory of currently active public partnerships and investor contacts available for $200 through Partnership Consultants, Inc. (800-881-4188) or at a good business library.<p>-- by Ted C. Fishman<p><p>PLAY 5:
SHORTING THE YEN
---------------
TYPE OF PLAY: Currency
PRICE: $1,200 per option contract
POTENTIAL UPSIDE: An 11-fold gain within a few months, if economic fundamentals finally overcome politics and perception
POTENTIAL DOWNSIDE: Timing is everything. In three months $50,000 could disappear.
CRUCIAL DUE DILIGENCE: Follow Japanese politics. Government weakness keeps the yen strong.<p>Here's a chance to beat famed hedge-fund manager George Soros in the currency markets. All any investor needs is impeccable timing.<p>Early in 1994, believing that the Japanese government was about to lower interest rates, Soros bet that the yen would tumble. Instead, the yen strengthened and the dollar swooned. Soros, who had shorted the yen, took a $600 million loss that quarter at his offshore Quantum Fund. <p>Many experts still believe that Soros was right, just premature. The Japanese economy began showing signs of recovery in late spring, and the wilting dollar has put pressure on the Japanese government to lower rates. A strong argument can be made that, based on economic fundamentals alone, the dollar should not have fallen to a 50-year low against the yen this summer.<p>At least that would be the view of those who subscribe to the theory of purchasing-power parity, which compares the real purchasing power of individual currencies. For instance, Haruo Shimada, an economist at Keio University, calculates that at 100 yen to the dollar, the yen is 40 percent overvalued in comparison to the U.S. currency. <p>The Economist's "Big Mac" index -- a measure of what it costs to buy a Big Mac in various countries around the world -- also suggests the yen is overvalued by more than 60 percent. Although short-term factors like politics, trade deficits, and interest rates can heavily influence currency valuations, economic fundamentals usually assert themselves over the long run. This means that sooner or later, according to purchasing-power-parity theory, the dollar will rise and the yen will sink.<p>The big question is: When? <p>"I'm a dollar bull relative to the yen," says Eric Nickerson, an international economist at BankAmerica. "But we're probably not going to see the dollar strengthen against the yen until the fourth quarter." A major reason the yen is strong, Nickerson argues, is that the Japanese economy is weak. Japanese exporters can't get enough credit, so they are dumping dollars as soon as they get them. That's because they need yen to cover operating costs. As the economy strengthens and banks start making loans again, exporters will be able to borrow. They'll hold on to their dollars longer, and demand for dollars will rise, Nickerson says.<p>Based on this theory, Nickerson looks for the dollar to trade in a range of 105 to 130 yen for the next few years. With the dollar recently trading below 100 yen, that's a potential move of at least 5 percent to 30 percent -- enough to produce a high reward for investors.<p>Those who believe the dollar will strengthen against the yen can place their bets in the options market. (Most stockbrokers can execute this trade.) The place to start is the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, which offers options on yen-futures contracts. <p>A futures contract is an agreement to buy or sell a fixed quantity of yen, corn, pigs, or any other commodity at a specified price on a specific date. As the price of the underlying commodity fluctuates, the value of the futures contract, with its fixed price, changes as well. Obtaining an option to buy or sell the yen-futures contract is a step further removed. <p>A three-month option to sell (known as a put) 12.5 million yen -- worth about $120,000 -- costs about $1,200. If the yen drops below the price specified in the options contract (called the strike price), the investor who owns this put option will profit. <p>In this way, using just $50,000 in cash, an investor can control about $6 million worth of yen. A 10 percent drop in the yen would produce a gain of about $600,000, or a return on the initial $50,000 of around $550,000 -- 11 times the money at risk.<p>The flip side, of course, is that if the yen should rise by just 1 percent, the $50,000 investment evaporates entirely, since the right to sell at a price below the market is valueless. Yen options are an exotic investment. Even understanding the listings in the daily press takes some practice. The Mercantile's contracts are set not in yen per dollar, but in dollar per yen. A contract with a selling price of 105 yen per dollar translates to 0.95 cents per yen and would be listed as a 95 contract. <p>Options expose investors to the normal market, country, and currency risks. In addition, they add a time risk. Being right isn't enough. You must be right at the right time. The market recognizes that by making shorter options contracts (contracts that give an investor less time to be right) cheaper to buy. While a three-month yen option costs about $1,200, a nine-month option will cost from 20 percent to 300 percent more.    <p>-- by Gary Hector<p><p>PLAY 6:
DEVELOPING A VIDEO GAME
---------------
TYPE OF PLAY: High-tech 
PRICE: $35,000 to $50,000
POTENTIAL UPSIDE: $120,000 over three years, if your title hits 
POTENTIAL DOWNSIDE: A run-of-the-mill product returns $12,000 of a $50,000 stake.
CRUCIAL DUE DILIGENCE: Hang around software stores. What sells, and why?<p>Investors in the information highway took a bumpy ride over the last 12 months. Many publicly traded highfliers headed to the garage for an overhaul. Electronic-game maker Electronic Arts, for example, geared down from a 52-week high of $42 to a low of $12.75. 3DO, a company that may or may not revolutionize the quality of video games, flopped from $48.25 to reach as low as $9. <p>Nevertheless, the crash in high tech has created bargains in the private equities market for new media. The entry fee is a lot less than the $500,000 to $1 million minimum needed to play in most venture-capital deals.<p>Modeled on the Hollywood movie partnerships that did so well for early investors in the 1980s (and not so well for latecomers), these deals allow investors to buy a piece of an individual CD-ROM title in development for $35,000 to $50,000. The hope is that one of these titles will hit it as big as Rebel Assault, the best-selling CD-ROM title ever -- more than 500,000 units sold at retail, with about $25 to $30 a unit going back to the developer.<p>Although the Silicon Valley-Hollywood axis is currently awash in CD-ROM development deals, one company's plans will illustrate the opportunity for investors. Viridis, a Los Angeles- based company founded by Lee Barnes and Christopher Thompson in 1990, develops interactive products -- in effect acting as a digital studio for companies or individuals with ideas. For example, three Viridis projects for late 1994 release involve IVI Publishing of Minneapolis, the producer of the successful Mayo Clinic reference CD-ROMs. Sales of the most successful volume in that three-title series are estimated at 650,000. Other recent and current Viridis clients include Electronic Arts, 3DO, Philips Interactive Media, Nintendo, GTE, Trimark Pictures, Doubleday, and The Los Angeles Times.<p>Investors in Viridis deals get anywhere from 30 percent to 80 percent ownership, depending on the ultimate cost of producing a title (typically somewhere between $500,000 and $1 million). The stake translates into a comparable piece of the developer's gross from retail sales. Normally, a developer gets between 7 percent and 20 percent of the suggested retail price, so the investor could wind up with royalties of anywhere between 2.1 percent and 16 percent of retail. On a CD-ROM that sells 100,000 units at $30 each, the developer -- Viridis, in this case -- would get, say, 20 percent of $3 million, or $600,000, and an investor might get 20 percent of that, or $120,000. (A successful game can bring in other revenue too, maybe 10 cents a unit for a toy based on one of its characters.) Returns are spread over a number of years. A $120,000 return on a $50,000 investment, for example, would typically break down into $40,000 in the second year and $80,000 in the third.<p>"The investors would know upfront what the title is," Thompson says. "They would get a full treatment and understand the budget, the schedule, everything." <p>It's critical, then, to find a company that's capable of developing a hit game and to pick the specific product that will break out of the list of about 4,000 existing CD-ROM titles, most of which sell only 5,000 to 10,000 units. At that sales level, a $50,000 investment brings in royalties of $12,000. <p>"The key to investing in these companies is looking at the people behind them," explains Ted Hoffman, who runs the Seroti Group, a San Francisco-based investment-banking firm that specializes in financing interactive-multimedia companies. Hoffman also says that investors participating on a per-title basis should carefully check out quality, content, and the licensing deal. To determine quality, Hoffman recommends taking a look at the demo yourself, passing it around to friends who have an interest in the subject matter, and even conducting full-blown focus groups for feedback from proven CD-ROM consumers. <p>Also important to consider is whether or not a developer can attract quality partners with good ideas and names that have market clout. Viridis recently announced an alliance with ZM Pictures -- a Universal Studios-based production company doing interactive projects requiring film and video production. Its Sesame Street Numbers, a 3DO title, is slated for inclusion in the interactive-television test being conducted in Omaha, Nebraska, by U S West. <p>Viridis has signed up Geoff Workman of Sausalito Digital Partners (415-989-3552), a California-based fund that provides seed money for new media entrepreneurs, to coordinate this program for small investors.<p>-- by Curtis Lang<p><p>PLAY 7:
BETTING ON DEBT OPTIONS
---------------
TYPE OF PLAY: Interest rates
PRICE: $250 per option (approximately)
POTENTIAL UPSIDE: A fivefold return, if long rates move up half a percentage point
POTENTIAL DOWNSIDE: A move in the wrong direction, or no move at all, and the options are worth zero.
CRUCIAL DUE DILIGENCE: Perceptions count: Does the economy look like it's overheating?<p>Burned by rising interest rates and falling bond prices? Here's a way to get revenge.<p>Buy a put option on Treasury-bond futures. This way, you'll score a big gain if interest rates rise again. How big? Suppose that back in June, an investor believed interest rates on 30-year bonds were headed to 8 percent from 7.5. At the time, this investor could have purchased a put option on September Treasury-bond futures carrying an exercise price of 96. The cost of this option would have been about $250. Yet its value would have risen to $1,609 if rates had behaved as predicted. The downside risk, meanwhile, was merely the initial purchase price. Had rates held steady or moved the other way, the investor would have let the option lapse at its expiration date in the third week of August.<p>To rack up a big return in the options market, then, all that an investor has to know is which way interest rates will move and when. <p>Unfortunately, this information is not posted in advance for all of us to see. Markets that set interest rates are probably the most active and most efficient in the world -- meaning that at any given time the prices pretty accurately reflect the odds that rates will move up or down. Under such conditions, outguessing or gaining an edge is extremely difficult, if not impossible, for an individual investor. "The odds of winning on a trade like this are much less than 50-50," says James Florsheim, a senior vice-president of Chicago Corp., an investment bank and brokerage.<p>That's certainly true when these types of options are used solely as a speculative tool. But there's another reason why an investor may want to participate in this arena -- as a way of hedging a bond-laden portfolio. Using options to make a risk-heavy bet on a move in interest rates is an effective method for reducing interest-rate risk -- sort of like having insurance. (Remember: The value of a bond goes down as interest rates go up.) <p>The $1,359 profit described above would have offset the actual recent three-month total return of negative 3.89 percent on almost $35,000 in long bonds. A $500 put bet would have produced a $2,708 profit and a positive 3.89 percent return on the same portfolio. On the other hand, had rates moved the other way, the profits on the appreciation of the bonds would have cushioned or overwhelmed the losses on the options.<p>The chances of further interest-rate hikes loom large at the moment. The yield on Treasurys with a 30-year maturity hit 7.67 percent on July 14, and the consensus among economists is that the upward trend in rates will continue. The only real disagreements about this have to do with when the increases will happen and exactly how large they will be. When the Federal Reserve didn't boost rates at its July meeting, many economists immediately began predicting that the next rate hike would come at the Fed's August 17 meeting. Others said it wouldn't happen until September. A few expected two increases -- one in each month. Former Federal Reserve Board member Wayne Angell, now a Bear Stearns senior managing director, has commented that the current 4.25 percent Fed funds rate (the rate at which banks borrow overnight funds from each other) needs to be hiked to 5 percent. An increase of that magnitude would certainly push the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond above 8 percent.<p>The decisions of the Federal Reserve Board, however, aren't the only factors driving U.S. interest rates at the moment. The dollar was down almost 8.8 percent versus the yen and 7.7 percent against the German mark in the first six months of the year, more than wiping out any interest Japanese and German investors would earn from 30-year bonds. Figures from the U.S. Treasury Department show that foreign private investors bought just $1.8 billion more than they sold of Treasury notes and bonds in this year's first quarter. That compares with net foreign purchases of $12.9 billion in the same period last year. Only higher U.S. rates would entice these investors, a major source of financing for the U.S. national debt, to buy more.<p>Investors who agree with this view, especially those who are already heavily invested in bonds, should buy a put option. (For a description of put options, see "Shorting the Yen.") Right now, the option to consider for making a bet on a rise in long-term rates would be the October serial put option based on the December bond-futures contract. This option, which started trading on August 15, will expire in the third week of September, so investors buying this instrument are hoping that long rates rise before that time. Any stockbroker should be able to execute such a trade. <p>-- by Scott McMurray<p><p>PLAY 8:
BUYING HONG KONG WARRANTS
---------------
TYPE OF PLAY: Foreign stocks
PRICE: $447 for 100 warrants
POTENTIAL UPSIDE: A 20 percent rally would double investors' money in the next 12 months.
POTENTIAL DOWNSIDE: No rally, and the Hong Kong warrants expire, worthless, in a year or two.
CRUCIAL DUE DILIGENCE: Pay attention to what's happening in North Korea.<p>Up 116 percent in 1993. down 27 percent in the first six months of 1994. That's Hong Kong, where when China hiccups, the stock exchange develops appendicitis.<p>Buying or selling the Hong Kong stock market is basically a bet on the future of mainland China. Nearly all the companies included in the Hong Kong index, the Hang Seng, do a significant amount of business with mainland China, so their prospects are closely linked to the Chinese economy and Chinese politics. Part of this year's swoon, for example, resulted from frictions in U.S.-China trade caused by the battle over human rights and the extension of China's most-favored-nation status.<p>China's double-digit growth rate of the past few years helped propel Hong Kong stock prices higher in 1993. Earlier this year, however, investor concern about rising inflation sparked by that growth caused prices to fall. And with aging leader Deng Xiaoping expected to join Mao Zedong in the Communist hereafter before too much longer, it's impossible to predict how accommodating China will be toward Hong Kong's capitalists over the next few years. The British colony reverts to control by mainland China on July 1, 1997.<p>Still, the pullback earlier this year may have created a buying opportunity in a market likely to rally well into 1995. Firms such as PaineWebber and Bear Stearns predict that such a rally could take the market up 20 percent in the next 12 months. <p>If this is correct, however, why settle for 20 percent? Buying Hong Kong Stock Index warrants could turn a 20 percent move into a 120 percent gain.<p>A warrant is an artificial security, or derivative, created to let investors bet on a specific market move or to hedge another investment in the same market. The American Stock Exchange offers warrants that are based on an index of 30 Hong Kong stocks. They are listed on the exchange (under the name of the brokerage firm or other issuer) with a single quote price and can be bought and sold just like common stocks through any stockbroker.<p>For one and a half or two years (depending on their expiration date), warrants give the holder the right to buy or sell the cash value of the Amex Hong Kong Index at a specific price, called the strike price. Warrants that confer the right to buy, referred to as calls, usually increase in value if the index rises above the strike price. Warrants that confer the right to sell, called puts, work in an opposite direction -- they usually become more valuable as the index goes down.<p>The stock-exchange listing is almost the only thing the Hong Kong warrants have in common with common stocks. This derivative was constructed with leverage in mind, and no one should buy these warrants thinking that they are just another name for a basket of stocks. The five- or six-to-one financial leverage built into the warrants means that by buying certain call warrants, for instance, an investor could more than double his or her money based on roughly a 20 percent rise in the underlying Hong Kong Index. Of course, a similar move in the opposite direction and the investor holding call warrants is out of luck -- and money. Bad joss, as they say in Hong Kong.<p>Six different call warrants (each of the six is actually a series with various expiration dates) and four different put warrants trade on the American Stock Exchange. Investors willing to bet that the Hong Kong market is poised to rebound in this year's second half would buy call warrants, since calls appreciate as the index value exceeds the preset strike price. Put warrants are for investors who think there's still plenty of air to be let out of the Hong Kong market. Considering Hong Kong's slide so far this year, call warrants look like the smarter bet.<p>Call warrants that were issued by <a name="NYSE:PWJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11148"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PaineWebber</b></a> last October -- with a strike price of $440.09 -- and expire in October 1995 currently have the lowest strike price of the calls that trade on the Amex. These calls were trading at $4.63 at midyear. For every point gain in the value of the index, the cash value of the warrant increases about 6.5 cents. (The terms of a warrant series vary depending on when the warrants were issued and by which issuer. Each warrant offering has its own prospectus.) This means that if the index rose 88 points, the value of the warrant would jump about $5.72 in cash value (88 times 0.065) to $10.35 -- a 123 percent gain. On July 18, the Amex Hong Kong Index closed at 459.60.<p>Prospectuses on each series are available from the issuing firm. Other institutions who have issued Hong Kong warrants are <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a>, Salomon Inc., <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, and the Swedish Export Credit Corp.<p>-- by Scott McMurray<p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Bond Investing, Mutual Funds Investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
