	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Who's Afraid of Hedge Funds?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Who's Afraid of Hedge Funds?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Most of us, lately. But they still make a certain sense.<p>By Liliana Nealon<p>By definition, "hedging" means taking steps to reduce possible losses on a bet, risk, or speculation by betting or speculating on the other side of the equation. Despite their name, most so-called hedge funds don't really do this. It's more common, in fact, for hedge-fund managers to operate like speculators who take big, unprotected risks.<p>Witness the recent setbacks of some of the dominant global players like George Soros and Michael Steinhardt. These two had both been on a roll since 1987, but in the first half of 1994, both got badly burned by markets that didn't do what the hedge-fund managers thought they would. Soros dipped badly before a recent recovery and Steinhardt's fund is down 31.3 percent on the year, mostly on bets that European interest rates would decline, causing bonds to rise. Many hedge-fund players also gambled that the dollar would grow stronger, particularly against the Japanese yen. The opposite happened instead.<p>Even worse was what happened to David Askin, the hedge-fund manager of Askin Capital Management. Askin was forced to close his doors last spring when the $600 million he was managing for clients vanished with the implosion of fixed-income derivatives, in which he had invested heavily. <p>The press attention heaped on Askin and other such debacles may have chastened many investors about hedge funds. But some of these fears may be exaggerated. <p>According to MAR/Hedge, a monthly study published by New York-based Managed Accounts Reports, the median hedge fund lost around 2.5 percent in the first five months of 1994, the most recent figures available. That performance compares with a 1 percent decline in the S&P 500 and a 5.9 percent decline in the Nasdaq index of over-the-counter stocks.<p>A longer-term look also sheds a favorable light on hedge funds. Peter De Cicco, president of Portfolio Management Resources, a Fairfield, Iowa, investment-consulting firm specializing in alternative investments, says that in general, hedge funds have outperformed mutual funds since 1987. They have also fared better than their mutual fund counterparts in down markets: In 1990, when the median of hedge funds returned 9 percent, the S&P 500 declined 3.1 percent and mutual funds dropped by 4.8 percent.<p>The median of 49 "global macro" hedge funds (essentially the most freewheeling funds) tracked by MAR/Hedge returned more than 10 percent a year from 1991 to the end of 1993. The top quarter of managers returned better than 35 percent in 1993, better than 23 percent in 1991, and no lower than 19.9 percent since 1990. <p>With that kind of a track record, it still probably makes sense for investors with at least $100,000 to invest to consider hedge funds as a way to balance their holdings and propel returns. Before doing so, however, such investors need to take some cautions to heart. <p>For starters, remember that many hedge funds use leverage. This means that when someone invests $100,000 into a hedge fund, the money at play in the account can be many times that amount. Leverage heightens potential returns but also makes it easier to lose everything. <p>If a $100,000 investment is leveraged five times, for example, and the market drops 10 percent, the result will be a $50,000 loss, or half the initial investment. Since many hedge funds allow withdrawals only quarterly or biannually, or even annually, it's imperative that investors understand the risks associated with leverage in a fund. Any more than 2 to 1 leverage is ill-advised.<p>Another worry is "manager risk" -- very simply, the possibility that the fund is not in capable hands. De Cicco analyzed the performance and risk of 250 hedge funds over seven years and found that hedge funds offer lower market risk but higher manager risk than traditional investment vehicles. Therefore, De Cicco warns potential investors to check on a manager's background, years of experience in implementing a strategy, and a fund's organizational structure and risk control guidelines. <p>He also advises investors to rely more on managers who have part or all of their personal net worth invested in the fund. Most of this information should be available in a fund's disclosure document. If not, it's up to you to get answers to your questions. <p>Finally, check not only the overall size of the fund, but the speed at which it has grown. Studies show that funds that take on too much too fast have trouble digesting their new money, leading to reduced performance and difficulties in completing their new larger trades successfully. Moderate growth is often preferable.<p>Picking managers and funds that meet the above prerequisites may limit you to those managers with strong historical performance, missing the so-called "emerging managers" who may become the stars of the future. For the truly adventurous looking for the star manager of tomorrow, MAR lists new and emerging managers and conducts monthly reviews of their trading styles.<p>Keep in mind that hedge funds' historical double-digit returns do not come easy. The lackluster performance of 1994 could get worse before it gets better. Investors in hedge funds should have the stomach to lose it all. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

