<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Where to Invest $100 Million...</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Where to Invest $100 Million...</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
What do the top financial advisors tell their wealthiest clients, and what can the rest of us learn from it?<p>By Robert Clark<p>Personal finance has become a huge industry, but private bankers still command the top rung. They offer a variety of attractions: jumbo loans, platinum credit cards, good-natured check cashing, plus the occasional opera tickets and hunt-club luncheons. Yet there's a far more important reason why rich people flock to these gurus on high: Performance. Private banks offer a premium level of expertise in money management.<p>Getting access to all this financial acumen requires a fat wallet. United States Trust Co., the oldest trust company in America, recommends a client have at least $1 million of investable spare change. Brown Brothers Harriman & Co. requires a portfolio of $2 million. Union Bank of Switzerland, perhaps the world's largest private banker, turns up its nose at anything less than $3 million. At J.P. Morgan, it's $5 million. But even J.P. Morgan is a piker compared with the Wealth Management Group at Chicago's Northern Trust. There, getting past the receptionist requires a family worth of $100 million.<p>OK, suppose you've only been reading Worth for a few issues and so haven't quite reached multimillionaire status. Is there anything that goes on inside private banks you should know about? Well, they certainly don't peddle whole life insurance. And they aren't too keen on impressing their clients with a handful of supposedly hot stock tips. In fact, even though private bankers have access to the best securities research that money can buy, they place comparatively little emphasis on trying to identify highflying stocks. <p>The reason: Private bankers, by and large, are big fans of modern portfolio theory, which asserts that overall investment performance is far more dependent on the mix of asset classes in the portfolio than it is on the mix of individual stocks. Put another way, portfolios gain or lose largely because of factors that affect entire classes of investment. Economic and interest-rate trends are among the most familiar of these factors. <p>Individuals with less-than-institutional capital can and should take the same perspective. You may not have $100 million to entrust to Northern Trust, but you can manage what you do have in a manner similar to Northern Trust's. The key is setting the right goals. Private bankers start with where their clients want to go, financially speaking, and then they tailor-make standards by working backward. <p>For people with hundreds of millions of dollars in assets, the goal may be the conservation or increase of capital for several generations to come. Too distant for most of us, of course, but no matter. Setting a goal requires us to examine why we're investing in the first place, a useful and revealing exercise. A goal may be buying a bigger house, sending the kids to college, or securing a retirement. <p>Goals help put risk into some meaningful perspective. Many helpful-looking financial guides begin by asking investors how much risk they are willing to incur. But that gets the whole thing off on the wrong foot because there is really only one appropriate answer to that question: as little as possible. By setting the distance you need to travel, goals help you to figure how much risk you need to get there.<p>Private bankers excel at shrinking that risk through portfolio diversification. If you need and can tolerate high risk, a well-diversified portfolio of growth stocks will bring you a superior return, at times, without exposing you to the scariest prospect of all, losing a big chunk of your stake. A portfolio that mixes common stocks, mutual funds, and bonds entails smaller risks but also less generous returns. Private bankers usually allocate assets among investment classes according to sophisticated projections of economic growth and the direction of interest rates. Lacking their sophistication, other investors can mimic it by keeping emergency cash on hand, by dividing a portfolio between equity mutual funds and bonds, and by rejiggering it every six months to maintain the balance.<p>One guideline to follow for setting the mix: Make the percentage of bonds in such a portfolio equal to your age. If that seems too conservative for older people or too risky for younger folks, 60 percent stocks and 40 percent bonds is another way to go. Over the long term, this mix has thrown off a return of about 7.5 percent a year. Does your goal require more than that? Then your only chance of reaching it is to up your risk taking. Increase the stock proportion or buy riskier stocks. Historically, portfolios invested fully in small-capitalization equities have returned about 12 percent.<p>Private bankers are also high on foreign securities these days. Global diversification can increase return and reduce risk, promising the best of all worlds, or so it seems from historical experience. Buying heavily into the latest hot market, however, isn't the kind of diversification that is calculated to produce the best of both. This year's hot market is usually next year's dog. Next year's dog may be worth buying. Next year.<p>Private bankers and other professionals try to get ahead of the flow of money instead of following it. Patrick Moriarty, chief investment officer at Bank Julius Baer, believes that Asia remains the growth market of the '90s. Yet he has no money in Malaysia, Singapore, Taiwan, or Korea. Because they are hot, he believes that they're overvalued. He has put client money in such currently unpopular markets as Hong Kong and Japan. <p>Topflight advisors also try to avoid the things that gnaw away at wealth. Among them: Inflation, taxes, and advisory fees. These advisors know that the longer an investor needs to preserve capital, the more inflation becomes a concern. At only 3 percent a year, the buying power of a portfolio will have shrunk by nearly half in 20 years. And few private bankers expect such a low rate of inflation to continue. On the other hand there has been no 20-year period in this century in which stock prices shrank by even 1 percent, let alone 50 percent. For long-term investors, then, inflation is far more dangerous than bear markets. <p>A corollary: Investors can increase the market risk in a portfolio a lot before it equals the inflation risk. This generally means taking more risk than most people might consider wise. Growth companies, including those with small capitalizations, will increase market risk but disproportionately reduce inflation risk. Junk bonds and venture financing can also help defeat inflation. Many great family fortunes own diversified portfolios of startup companies. Northern Trust puts its clients in touch with venture-capital specialists who can help them find high-growth opportunities. Emerging equity markets, besides providing global diversification, also serve as inflation hedges. Private banks advise keeping about 10 percent of an investment portfolio in emerging-market securities.<p>Fees can be just as destructive as inflation. A highflying fund with an expense ratio of 2.5 percent or 3 percent a year won't return as much as slightly less dazzling performers with fees as low as 0.19 percent of assets a year. The difference could achieve or defeat your purpose in investing. Choose low-cost funds over high-cost funds.<p>Rich people also don't like taxes. Neither, of course, do the rest of us, but the rich have advisors to help minimize them. An old-fashioned and rewarding way of doing so is to keep portfolio turnover low to avoid the continual realization of capital gains and consequent taxes. Mutual fund investors should seek out funds that don't realize capital gains with distressingly taxable frequency.<p>Probably the best advice the wealthy get has to do with evaluating their money manager's performance. Simply put, measure it not by what he is paid but by what you are paid -- your net investment return after adjustment for expenses, inflation, and taxes. The wealthy are usually pleased to get a net real return of 2 percent to 3 percent a year. That's a true increase in wealth that they keep. The wealthy are not overly impressed by their portfolio performance compared with a market index. If the index drops 20 percent and you're only down 10 percent, you've beaten the market. But you've still lost money. You can't pay the mortgage with minus 10 percent. Or hire private bankers, either.
---------------
Robert Clark is a senior editor at Worth.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Investing Strategies

