<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-New Strategies for Tough Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-New Strategies for Tough Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Forget everything that the great bull market taught you about investing. Here's how smart investors will react to rapidly changing conditions.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>This year, the financial markets have changed course so quickly and so radically that investors may be forgiven for feeling a bit of whiplash. But it is not okay to think that the recent white-water ride in stocks and bonds is just a brief stretch in the river, scheduled to end around the next bend. The fact of the matter is, we've started a whole new adventure, one that will bear little resemblance to anything we've experienced lately.<p>How should securities investors respond? Strategies that worked so well over the past five years are now outmoded and need to be jettisoned. The market will punish investors who are slow to grasp this. Henceforth, careful fundamental securities analysis -- not investing with the crowd -- will carry the day. The largest gains will go to investors who resist initial public offerings, sector funds, and most bargain-basement losers. New inflationary expectations, higher interest rates, higher taxes, and an anomalously weak dollar have changed everything.<p>In short, it ain't gonna be easy any longer.<p>The changes have already begun. Markets are rarely static, but the turbulence in the financial arena since January should be your clue that the rules of the game are being revised. And in this game, Yogi Berra notwithstanding, it's not going to be deja vu all over again.<p>After years of stellar returns, stocks are taking back some of their rewards. Is it a full-fledged bear market? The debate makes lively cocktail chatter, but it is unenlightening. Will the bull resume after a short break in the action? Another question that misses the point.<p>Higher ground than where we are now may in fact be achieved by the stock and bond markets in the coming months. But don't be fooled: The heights will not be gained in the same manner -- or in the same types of stocks -- as in 1992 or 1993.<p>Veteran money manager Charles Johnson has seen many different kinds of markets over the years. Almost 40 years, in fact, have passed since he began running the nearly $3 billion Franklin Utilities Fund. "It is a different market," he says. "This year's rising interest rates, higher taxes, and weak dollar create a reluctance to buy U.S. securities." <p>Research by Mark Hulbert, editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, which tracks the returns of market-advisory newsletters, shows just how different today's investment terrain is and how difficult it is to prosper in. Comparing the performance of almost 200 newsletter portfolios in the first quarter of 1994 against their returns for the past five years turned up this fact: Fewer than one in four of the strategists Hulbert tracks beat the market both in the past five years and in the first quarter of 1994. Stated simply, what worked in the past works no more.<p>Why? Fundamental factors that drove the market ever higher have disappeared: low and stable inflation rates, interest rates that only went down, and a flood of foreign money into U.S. securities. These factors supported a three-year bull move in stocks and bonds.<p>The bulls, at times, went manic. IPOs ran hot and heavy, bringing big gains to those investors lucky enough to get in on the new shares. Taking a flier on whatever stock or sector the crowd was currently stampeding into -- investing with the herd -- became the winning technique. <p>That technique will be a loser over the duration.<p>The funny thing about markets is, the more they rise, the more risk investors believe they can take. Such was the case in 1993 and early 1994. As the stock market scaled new heights, investors felt more comfortable swinging for the fences, going for the long ball.<p>One measure: The amount of money investors borrowed from their brokers to buy stocks -- margin debt -- exploded to $61 billion in January. That's more than double the $28 billion indebtedness investors had outstanding at the end of 1990. <p>Meaning? Margin debt is a tip-off to how bullish investors are. Folks who borrow from their brokers to buy stocks are betting that equity prices will rise fast and furiously. That's because margin, like most kinds of borrowing, works its magic only in up markets. <p>Another indication of euphoria: Equities now make up the biggest portion of invested assets. For the first time since 1972, the percentage of assets invested in stocks exceeds the percentage in cash -- bank deposits, checking accounts, money markets. Even during the big bull market of the '80s, Americans kept considerably more cash in their portfolios than stocks. In 1993, the balance tipped the other way.<p>This is significant on two counts. One, it shows a commitment to stocks among investors that hasn't been seen since just before the hideous bear market of 1974. Two, it suggests that the U.S. investor is nearly tapped out where stocks are concerned. With almost 40 percent of their invested assets held in equities today -- a percentage not seen since 1973 -- investors aren't likely to move lots more into stocks.<p>Counting their gains, investors were comfortable with their stocks and bonds when 1994 rolled in. Then, without much warning, the market showed its dark side. <p>If the old market's winning ways had to do with lower inflation and interest rates, big foreign investment in U.S. stocks and bonds, and increasing corporate efficiencies, then the less-than-jovial ways of the new market have to do with rising inflation and interest rates, rising personal income taxes, and the flight of foreign capital. That all adds up to a marked slowing in demand for U.S. stocks and somewhat less of a hit for bonds.<p>Start with the specter of rising inflation -- bad news for financial instruments because inflation eats away at investors' real returns in both stocks and bonds. Increasing interest rates cause similar damage. Higher borrowing costs cut into corporate profits. New, higher-coupon bonds look more attractive than equities or lower-yielding bonds. Why take a risk in stocks, whose dividend yields are now 2.9 percent, when you can buy a low-risk two-year Treasury note and bag almost 6 percent? (For more about what you should do with your fixed-income investments, see the sidebar "Bond Market's New Climate" at the end of this file.) <p>Interest rates will almost certainly rise further. Traders look to the federal-funds futures market for clues. This market is one of the best indicators of what professional investors believe the future cost of money will be. Right now, the market in fed-fund futures says short money rates will be between 5 percent and 5.5 percent by year end. Present rates are 4.25 percent. <p>Foreign investors are also playing a big role in the market's current transformation. In 1993, overseas investors bought more than $110 billion in U.S. stocks and bonds, an all-time high. Most of this money poured into fixed-income investments -- especially U.S. agency securities -- but $21.5 billion of it, roughly one fifth of the total, went into stocks. <p>This is not small change. By year end, the $21 billion-plus placed in U.S. equities accounted for 3 percent of the rise in market value during the year on the New York and American Stock Exchanges and Nasdaq. <p>But now it looks as though foreign investors' ardor for American securities has cooled. Although figures for the first quarter's international money flows were not available at press time from the Commerce Department, anecdotal evidence says that foreigners are fleeing the U.S. markets. <p>Dan Dorrow watches the world scene as an international economist at <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>. He says that today's market reminds him of 1990, when foreign investment in the U.S. plunged after years of growth. Right now, he says, "if the Dow meanders, you won't see a lot of foreign buyers. Most firms overseas are recommending underweighting in the U.S. I don't see (the flows) turning around." (For foreigners' views on the American market, see the sidebar "Overseas Views On The U.S." at the end of this file.) It doesn't help that many overseas investors view President Clinton's ship of state as rudderless both in foreign and domestic seas.<p>Moreover, global investing isn't a one-way street. Now more than ever, U.S. investors are sending their money to foreign shores in search of better returns. According to the Securities Industry Association, U.S. investors bought almost $68 billion in foreign equities last year. That number exceeds the foreign purchases made by Americans during the entire decade of 1980 to 1990. Americans sending more dollars abroad and foreigners keeping them there add up to only one thing: bad news for U.S. stocks. <p>This across-the-board reduction of demand for U.S. stocks and bonds is a new phenomenon. During the entire 1980s, the U.S. was a net-capital importer. Every year, more money flowed into U.S. securities than flowed out.  Investors thought U.S. markets promised higher returns.<p>But the 1990s have changed that view. In the first year of the decade, the U.S. saw a net investment outflow of $12 billion, and the S&P fell some 7 percent. Then, last year, the outflow increased to $17 billion. In 1994, the shortfall is likely to be even greater. <p>That is a major reason for the dollar's paradoxical weakness. When interest rates go up, as they have done since February, the dollar usually gets stronger. This is because investment funds flow to instruments paying the greatest returns. So each increase in U.S. interest rates should, theoretically, increase the appeal of U.S. bonds. To buy bonds, foreigners must first buy dollars, effectively pushing the dollar higher against other currencies.<p>This, however, is not happening. After rates had gone up almost a full percentage point, the dollar was the lowest it had been against the Japanese yen since World War II, and at death's door against the deutsche mark. Only a dollar-buying spree by U.S. and foreign central banks in early May put a temporary stop to the slide. Even so, the dollar still looks sick.<p>A weakening dollar in declining stock and bond markets is a phenomenon that has occurred only three other times in the past two decades, according to Anthony Kolton of Logical Information Machines, a market-information company in Chicago. Kolton says these episodes took place in October 1987 during the crash and twice in 1990 -- in late February and early May. The most recent occurrence was on April 4. <p>In two of the periods before the most recent one, the stock market wound up significantly lower seven months after the weakness in the dollar, stock, and bond markets converged. The one time that the market recovered quickly, oddly enough, was during the 1987 crash. But twice in 1990, when the dollar, bonds, and stocks were all weak, seven months later the S&P 500 had weakened, too.<p>This leads Kolton to believe that stock prices will remain under pressure until well into the fall of 1994. The effect of rising income taxes on spending and productivity will also hurt. Stephen Moore, director of fiscal-policy studies at the Cato Institute, a libertarian think tank in Washington, D.C., and John Skorburg, an economist in Chicago, penned a study last fall estimating the economic implications of President Clinton's 1993 tax increase. Moore and Skorburg set out to assess what effect $265 billion in new taxes over the next five years would have on jobs, gross domestic product, and economic growth. <p>What they found: Through 1997, increased taxes will result in a $190 billion loss in gross domestic product. (Last year's GDP was $6 trillion.) In addition, the economic growth rate through 1997 will be 0.7 percentage points lower than it would be without the tax increases. Between 1994 and 1998, say the researchers, real GDP growth will likely average 1.2 percent, versus 2.6 percent in 1993. Such a performance, says Moore, "would be the worst turned in during any five-year period since the Second World War." <p>The stock market likes higher taxes no more than higher inflation. It may get the worst of both worlds. The last time taxes went up -- the 1990 increase that probably cost George Bush a second term -- the market fell 7 percent on the year.<p>Small wonder that stock prices are weak. Yet many investors seem to believe that if they just sit tight, stocks will resume their straight-up climb. The good old days -- 1989 and 1991, for instance, when the S&P made 27 percent and 26 percent, respectively -- are sure to return. <p>We'd love it if they did. But repeat performances are not what the stock market's all about. Still, we're not going to recommend putting your money in the mattress. All the news on the economic horizon isn't dreary. It's just that what good news there is won't benefit all stocks; it'll benefit the chosen few.<p>For instance: The economy is perking along at a roughly 3 percent growth rate. This type of moderate growth, if it can be maintained, is much healthier for U.S. stocks than a cyclical rebound of, say, 7 percent. The slower growth scenario that we're seeing now, says John Neff, manager of Vanguard's Windsor Fund since 1964, means that stocks could show three to four years of upward moves in response to earnings growth of 8 percent to 10 percent. <p>Corporations are certainly in fine competitive shape today -- another bit of good news. Whittling down their costs boosts profit margins. And more American companies than ever are operating globally, well positioned to take advantage of the economic recovery going on right now in Europe. <p>Indeed, sooner or later, stock prices will recover. Yet even if that happens tomorrow, capitalizing on it will require an investment strategy quite different from the past's. Looking in the rearview mirror may help improve your driving, but it won't add much in the way of gains on your tax return.<p>"Looking backward is not much of a guide," says Gail Dudack,  managing director and strategist at S.G. Warburg, an investment firm in New York. "But there is a greater risk of doing that now than there has been in years." Although investors may like to think that the markets of the 1980s will return, she observes: "The 1980s were very different; competitiveness was different, inflation was different, consumption was different."<p>What, then, will pay off in the new market? Here's our take on the new rules an investor should follow:<p>-> Avoid initial public offerings. No longer are IPOs likely to shoot straight up after they begin trading. Weak stock markets are, for the most part, inhospitable to new equity issues. Their after-offering trading reflects this shift in investors' psychology. <p>Of a group of 23 issues brought to market in the first weeks of April, roughly half were trading above their IPO prices by mid-month. That's not a bad ratio, but the gainers showed relatively modest increases: an average of $1.60 a share. Now that the market is less embracing, individual investors are more likely to be allowed to buy new offering shares. Stay away.<p>-> Steer clear of sector funds. Robert Markman, a Minneapolis money manager, believes that only two sectors are likely to move up for an extended period of time in the coming months: real estate and gold. "Every other sector looks ready for a fall," he says.<p>-> Find companies that will compete in and survive industry shakeouts. This advice comes from market strategist Dudack. She hunts for what she calls predator companies, those that will compete successfully in a world where prices of basic goods are coming down and profit margins get squeezed. Predator companies will also come through the many shakeouts that Dudack expects to hit various industries during this decade. "We ended the 1980s with a situation where the consumer is overstored, overcerealed, and oversupplied," says Dudack. "The likelihood is that not all these stores will exist at the end of the decade."<p>To become a predator, Dudack says, a company must be able to sell its goods both domestically and abroad and show sustained unit-volume growth in markets where profit margins are pressured. Companies that meet Dudack's criteria include <a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, and software supplier <a name="NASD:ORCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14337"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oracle</b></a>. <p>-> Buy companies that look good because of internal performance and not merely because their stocks are attracting touts and speculators. So says Paul Ullman, executive vice president and money manager at Cortland Associates in St. Louis, a firm with $140 million under management. Ullman has survived tumultuous markets since 1953 with his reputation -- and record -- intact. For the past six-year period, ending in March, his firm's equity portfolio turned in a 14.1 percent annual return.<p>Ullman is a classic value investor who says he has walked away from the stocks of more than 100 companies this year simply because the prices were too rich. What he looks for: "Companies with cagey management that are modestly leveraged, with niche markets, good research and development, and distribution control. They should also know where they're going over the next five years and be growing at between 10 percent and 12 percent." <p>For companies that meet these standards, Ullman is willing to pay a slight premium, say, between 12 and 14 times earnings. He's had to avoid most candidates because they're trading at prices much higher than that, such as 27 times earnings. But he thinks that prices will get more reasonable as the year wears on.<p>-> Find stocks that will participate in the coming surge in capital investment. Another industrial shift that smart investors can profit from: American corporations and -- to a lesser degree -- those around the world are increasing their capital spending. The 1980s saw an explosion in the supply of consumer nondurables such as apparel and foods. American corporations fell behind in capital investments in machine tools, computers, and other heavy equipment. Now companies are playing catch-up. Some heavy capital investors now are machine- tool maker Giddings & Lewis, chip maker <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Electric</b></a>.<p>-> In mutual funds, smaller is better. If you believe, as many market observers do, that the months and years ahead will reward stock pickers more than sector pickers, then you might want to switch your focus to smaller fund managers. That way, you're apt to get a bigger bang for your buck. <p>Money manager Markman says, "Whenever you have a selective stock market, smaller is better." That's because a pip-squeak fund with a $300 million market capitalization can buy both <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> and, say, Wholesome & Hearty Foods, the top performer on Nasdaq last year. The giant fund with a $3 billion market cap, on the other hand, can buy IBM, but not Wholesome & Hearty. Small stocks don't have enough shares outstanding to attract big investors. But small-fund managers can get in and gain.<p>We're not saying that the stock and bond markets are going to get less volatile or tricky any time soon. But these strategies should help you maneuver through any mayhem that comes along and position yourself for the eventual resurgence. Remember: Nostalgia for the good old days is okay among friends. It's not, however, okay in the markets.<p>Yet many investors cling to the beliefs and strategies of yesteryear for the very reason that they paid off well in the past. What are some of those outmoded methods? Here are the critical ones we think investors should avoid:<p>-> Buying stocks in anticipation of pleasant earnings surprises. Brokers and money managers today say investors continue to buy stocks that they believe will soon issue better-than-expected earnings reports. Last year, positive-earnings surprises, as they are known, generally made stock prices jump. Today, this kind of good news is greeted with yawns or selling. (See "Mauled by the Good-News Bears.") In the new market, traders sell on good news even when it is unexpected.<p>On April 4, for instance, semiconductor-chip maker <a name="NYSE:AMD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10037"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Advanced Micro Devices</b></a> reported record sales and operating earnings for its first quarter. The stock, which was trading around $31 the day the earnings came out, sank to $30.25 the next day. A month later, the shares were changing hands at $25 each. Betting that big moves will follow good earnings reports no longer works. <p>-> Shopping the "new low" list for cheap stocks. This strategy may have worked when the tides of a rising market eventually lifted all ships. It is a dangerous practice when prices are weak or static. Stocks often trade at new lows for reasons that have more to do with company fundamentals than with an overall market malaise. In a weak market, it's low today, lower tomorrow.<p>-> Waiting to sell a stock that's fallen because "it'll come back." Investors in Media Vision Technology, a computer-add-ons stock that was big with the momentum-investing crowd, probably used this excuse to avoid selling their shares in early March when the stock was trading around $30. After all, hadn't the shares hit $46 just months earlier? <p>Indeed they had. But waiting for Media Vision's comeback has proved costly; the stock is now around $2.75, and the company is under investigation by the Securities and Exchange Commission. Lesson: Stocks don't always come back to prices investors would like to be able to sell them for.<p>-> Buying shares with low price-to-earnings ratios. Usually, this is an admirable exercise. Late in a bull market, it can be frustrating and costly.<p>Take the case of <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford Motor Co.</b></a>, a healthy company that's selling cars like gangbusters around the world. Ford's earnings in the most recent quarter were awesome -- $1.66 a share, more than 60 percent above the same period a year earlier. Because the blockbuster numbers didn't boost Ford's stock much, its p/e fell a bit, to 12, significantly lower than the overall market p/e of 19. A good buy, right?<p>Maybe not. Back in 1988, Ford had smashing earnings of almost $11 a share and a p/e of less than 5. Yet investors who bought the shares on the strength of those numbers were soon disappointed. Although the stock traded around $55 in early 1989, it sank to around $25 in 1990.<p>What the Ford case demonstrates is this: Just because a company's shares carry a low p/e, that doesn't necessarily make them a good buy. Indeed, history teaches us that some stocks -- like Ford -- should be bought not when earnings are high but rather when they are in the pits.<p>Consider: After earning almost $11 in 1988, by 1990, Ford's earnings had declined to less than $2 a share. Then, in 1991, the carmaker showed a loss of almost $5 a share. Perversely, this was when smart investors should have been buying. The shares ended 1991 under $30 and never looked back, almost doubling to $50 by mid-1992. <p>-> Swinging for the fences. Emotional investors tend to increase their tolerance for risk in investments as markets move higher. Yet, in the interests of capital preservation, the opposite behavior should hold. By ratcheting down their portfolio's risks as the market skyrockets, investors would be doing the smart but tough thing: selling high. <p>Instead, investors often go for the long ball even though a bull market is in extra innings. This type of behavior includes making a speculative investment -- such as a position in an emerging market or a sector fund -- your portfolio's core holding. Or retirees buying aggressive-growth-stock funds. <p>Investment manager Markman has seen these behavior patterns. They worry him. "It's important to look not just at what will make it through a tough market, but what will emerge when the market turns up," he says. In this more selective market, he says, truly imaginative stock pickers are the only ones who'll thrive.<p>That's it: back to mind-bending industry research and the old-fashioned stock picking that Graham and Dodd made famous. Rescues by greater fools and capital gains on riskless Treasurys are no longer in the cards.
---------------
Gretchen Morgenson is executive editor of Worth.<p>---------------
SIDEBAR:
The New Climate For Bond Investors<p>Bond investors take heart: the worst is probably over. Not that the ride hasn't been traumatic of late. Bondholders used to the steady gains of the recent past -- total returns on U.S. Treasury 30-year bonds averaged 10.54 percent annually from 1989 through 1993 -- suddenly found their investments in a freefall. During this year's first quarter alone, the total return on the 30-year long bond came to a stunning minus 7.83 percent. Among the major bond funds, the carnage was only a tad less severe. In the span of three months, 20 funds with top ratings by Chicago-based Morningstar lost 6 percent or more of their value. <p>What happened to these supposedly safe instruments? <p>The broad picture, at least, is fairly simple to explain: We are now at the end of another interest-rate cycle. The decline in rates hit bottom last year. The Federal Reserve's decision to raise the federal-funds rate in February officially ended the cycle.<p>The recent behavior of the market, the wild rallies and drops, is exactly what happens in the typical transition between cycles, says Stan Carnes, chief portfolio strategist for the financial-services division at Lehman Brothers. Carnes sees the rest of 1994 as "a coupon-clipping type of year," one where bond returns consist of interest payments only and capital gains are virtually nonexistent. Actually, such a market is much closer to the historic norm than the last decade was. In the long run, ten-year Treasury notes return about 2 percent over inflation, says Carnes.<p>Here are some things bond investors should keep in mind: <p>-> Ignore the current popular advice to "move to quality" -- a notion favoring bonds that carry little credit risk. "The higher the grade (of a bond), the more it gets hurt" when rates go up, notes Eric Ryback, manager of the Lindner Dividend Fund. That's why Treasury bonds have gotten socked harder than junk bonds lately.<p>-> Readjust your expectations. Two-year Treasury notes, currently yielding approximately 6 percent, are a screaming buy, says Carnes. "If you're truly bearish on inflation, (you believe) it might go up to 4 percent. So the notes yield 2 percent real." That's still roughly equivalent to the historic yield on ten-year Treasurys.<p>-> For higher yields, consider bonds with longer durations. Risk increases with duration, but so does yield. Five-year Treasury notes pay more interest than Treasury bills  -- which pay off interest and principal in 90 days. If the bond market eventually comes to believe that the Fed has inflation under control, long rates may come down and investors holding notes with long durations could see some capital gains. At the same time, says Carnes, there's almost no payoff in yield for buying a 30-year instead of a 10- or 12-year bond. "It doesn't make sense to go out real long," he says.<p>-> In a coupon-clipping world, investors can manage interest-rate risk on their own just fine, without the help (and added cost) of a bond fund. The sure way to preserve principal is to purchase bonds you are willing to hold to maturity -- matching the duration of the bond with your investment horizon. "Laddering" is another tried-and-true technique. To create a 12-year ladder, for example, an investor would divide the amount that he wants to allocate to bonds into 12 equal parts and invest the first twelfth in a one-year note, the second twelfth in a two-year note, etc. Each year, as the shortest bond matures, that sum is invested in a new bond with a current 12-year maturity. Eventually, all steps of the ladder will hold bonds with the yield of 12-year instruments. But since the investor is holding them to maturity, he has no interest-rate risk.<p>-> Bond funds with unique strategies offer investors the best return on the fees they pay. Investors seeking yields above those offered by governments will need to look at lower-grade instruments from companies that are using the current period of economic growth to improve their credit ratings. That gives investors a chance to collect some capital gains as credit ratings improve. A good fund manager should be able to offer protection against higher credit risk through due diligence and by putting together a diversified portfolio. <p>-> Rethink the fees you are willing to pay. Expense ratios on funds in Morningstar's government Treasury category range from 1.25 percent annually for Midwest Leshner Treasury T/RA to 0.11 percent for Dreyfus 100 Percent U.S. Treasury Short-term. Midwest Leshner also carries a 4 percent front-end sales charge. Remember, we're looking at a future where returns are likely to be closer to 8 percent than 15.<p>-> Consider alternatives to bonds. Lately, Ryback says he has been buying convertible preferred stock. This hybrid security pays a big yield like a bond but is convertible into a company's common stock. The upside is thus a combination of yield and capital appreciation since the convertible goes up less than but along with the price of the common stock. Ryback has recently bought AMC Entertainment Preferred (AEN Preferred), which yields 8.2 percent and trades at $21, and Tosco Preferred (TOS Pr. F), which yields 6.8 percent and trades at $64. Both preferreds trade at a premium to the underlying common stock, but the premiums are only 21 percent and 2 percent, respectively. "That's not very much as long as the company is showing solid earnings growth," Ryback says. --Jim Jubak---------------<p>SIDEBAR:
Where Have All the Foreign Investors Gone?<p>We conducted an opinion poll of foreign investment houses in Asia, Europe, and Latin America. What kind of advice are they giving their clients about investing in the U.S. stock market right now?<p>Stay out. Contrary to the benchmark <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a> Capital International World Index, which recommends that portfolios be weighted most heavily in favor of the U.S. at 35. 8 percent (followed by Asia at 32.6 percent and Europe at 27.5 percent), most polled have the U.S. underweighted. Just one -- Union Bank of Switzerland, with $178 billion in assets -- has a 40 percent overweighting in the U.S. <p>"The U.S. is in a bear phase of a bull market," says UBS international strategist Tim O'Dell. "Increased bond yields and reduced confidence in the short term is upsetting the U.S. equity markets." O'Dell believes the U.S. market is much more sound than others. But while unconcerned about the weak dollar (UBS is fully hedged), O'Dell is puzzled by what he sees as one of the main causes for its weakness. "It's the U.S. institutions themselves that have been investing abroad so heavily," he says. "They've been overweighting their foreign portfolios." Here's what overseas players are saying about us.
-- by Manjeet Kripalani<p>"We're underweighted in the U.S. There're better opportunities elsewhere. The rest of Europe is moving into the investment-cycle phase, and the valuations aren't so stretched." 
-- Mark Tinker, market strategist, James Capel (U.K.)<p>
"Investing anywhere else (other than the U.S.) will give handsome returns over currency and equity markets."
-- Richard Griffiths, European equity strategist, Swiss Bank Corp. (Switzerland)<p>
"We would only play the U.S. markets through European stocks that have U.S. interests." 
--Christopher Clark, Credit Lyonnais (France)<p>
"The U.S. economy will be slowing down considerably. A lot of the tax hikes are threshold hikes; they'll bite in the second half of the year. Like FICA (federal insurance contributions). Now the risk is the U.S. will stop getting foreign investment flows."
-- Robert Brusca, co-chief economist, Nikko Securities (Japan)<p>
"Are we seeing U.S. earnings peak in the next four quarters? We see an upside of 10 to 12 percent, and then when you compare, there's better money to be made in Germany, France, the Netherlands. Europe is in the early stages of an earnings recovery."
-- Mark Spellman, Deutsche Bank (Germany)<p>
"The biggest problem is currency. It affects U.S. asset value when the dollar is devalued by the yen. We've been reluctant to invest in the U.S. right now."
-- Takeshi Abekura, fund manager, U.S. equity portfolio, Dai-ichi Mutual Life (Japan)<p>
"The tax issue is a lingering problem with the U.S. people and is perceived as something that will keep them from investing that extra dollar. I don't think people have realized that change. The administration has a credibility problem; that could be a wild card. The Dow is not indicative of the broad market; it's made up of all the companies that have been acting terrifically. For the first time, people are getting hurt by buying dips (securities with momentarily weak prices). Stick to cash this year. Capital preservation is important. The worst yielding thing used to be a cash position; now it's the best."
-- James Haber, portfolio manager, Tendentia Overseas Fund (Brazil)<p>
"The Mexican stock market has been very high, so investing in the U.S. stock market has not been very attractive. In foreign markets, the Far East is attractive."<br>
-- Bernardo Labarthe, international treasurer, Banco Union (Mexico)<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Stock Investing, International Investing

