		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Tea Leaves Can Be Deceptive</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Tea Leaves Can Be Deceptive</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Short-interest ratios are getting harder to interpret.<p>By Bruce Upbin<p>Short interest never was much of a guide to the future of stock prices. The surprising thing is that so many investors still rely on it. Our advice: Don't.<p>The short interest in any security is the number of shares that have been sold short -- borrowed, then sold -- but not yet bought back. Of course, one reason investors sell a stock short is that they believe its price will go down. If their prediction comes true, they can buy the shares back at a lower price and pocket the difference. <p>However, if a stock continues to move up in price, the shorts often try to wait it out or even add to their positions. Other shorts may join in the fray. These things can show up in the form of a rising total short-interest position in a company's stock. Eventually, though, the short sellers will have to buy the shares back to replace the ones they sold -- to cover, in Wall Street parlance, their short positions. Thus, the theory goes that when the short interest in a security sharply increases, it presages a sharp increase in demand for the security and a sharp increase in price. It doesn't matter whether the stock is a dog or a dynamo.<p>If that were always true, short sellers would always be wrong. They're not.<p>The theory survives partly because, like any and all speculative theories, it occasionally bears fruit. When short sellers blow it, they can blow it big; their potential losses are theoretically unlimited. Short squeezes still occur, when short sellers can't find sufficient shares to cover their shorts at market prices and are forced to go into the open market and bid up the stock's price to boost the supply. <p>This most often happens with hot stocks in extremely bullish markets, stocks that everybody but the buyers agree are overvalued and must come down. But bulls keep bidding the price up, reluctantly abetted by bears who are forced to cut their losses by covering their shorts. That makes short selling in hot markets a dangerous game and supports the theory that heavy short selling is bullish. <p>Philip Erlanger, president of Phil Erlanger Research in Acton, Massachusetts, cites a short-seller favorite, Biogen. Twice over the past three years, the stock doubled after big jumps in short selling. When the bears retreated and short selling shrank, the stock fell by 50 percent. The shorts were caught out, selling low and buying high.<p>Conversely, Erlanger says, "Very little short interest tells me there are too many bulls there" -- and a stock may fall. Even so, it usually takes a sharp overall market setback to send such stocks tumbling.<p>Short-interest figures lack reliability as market indicators today because hedging, arbitrage, and tax-deferral strategies account for a steadily increasing share of short selling. Suppose, for example, investors who already own a stock decide to sell an equal number of shares short. That increases the short interest, but the investors never need to buy shares to cover their shorts; they already own the shares. Some investors "short against the (safe-deposit) box," as the practice is commonly called, as a hedge in periods of extreme market volatility. <p>Then there is the tactic known as pairing longs and shorts -- buying <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a>, say, and shorting Ford as a hedge in an uncertain auto market. How can you tell whether pure bearishness, or hedging, accounts for an increase in short selling? "I'm as close to short information as you can get from the outside, and I can't even tell," says Michael Long, a short-sale watcher and general partner of Rockbridge Partners, an investment partnership in Charlotte, North Carolina.<p>The New York Stock Exchange, the American Stock Exchange, and Nasdaq each report the short interest in securities traded in their markets once a month. Both the NYSE and Amex lists indicate securities that may have had significant short selling through arbitrage or hedging. But nobody knows how much is attributable to those motives. Steven Bloom, chief economist at the Amex, thinks it may be as much as 25 percent of short selling.<p>Does the motive for it matter? Yes. Well-hedged short sellers, unlike out-and-out bears, lose neither sleep nor equity when their shorts lose. They won't panic and push prices up.<p>If short interest is unreliable on individual stock-price trends, how about the overall market? "Back in the '60s, '70s, and early '80s, the theory was that if short interest got to two times (average daily) volume on the New York Stock Exchange, you would get market advances," says Richard McCabe, chief market analyst at <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> in New York. Yet in recent years, the ratio has run between 3 times and 5.7 times the Big Board's average daily volume, through good markets and bad. <p>The ratio recently stood at 4.5, a bullish sign if judged by the old theory. Few experienced Wall Streeters believe that now. "The data no longer reflects whether people are bullish or bearish," says McCabe. If the bulls prove right, it won't be because of short interest.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
