<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-How Pick Your Spots in Stocks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-How Pick Your Spots in Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Why one pro thinks mid-cap shares will shine.<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>Mid-cap stocks -- companies with market values between $200 million and $5 billion -- have been riding a wave of popularity in recent years. With reason: In 1993, they returned almost 14 percent, versus the 10 percent gain shown by the Standard & Poor's 500 and the 11.3 percent earned by the Wilshire 5000 index of smaller companies. But it was not until this year that Lipper Analytical Services started ranking mutual funds that invest in these mid-range concerns. <p>Among the top performing funds in this category is <a name="FUND:BMCGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BMCGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bhirud Mid-Cap Growth Fund</b></a>, a $10 million portfolio run by Suresh Bhirud, former chief strategist at First Boston and Oppenheimer. A longtime bear who has recently been reborn as one of the market's more vocal bulls, Bhirud, 45, sees mid-caps as a great buy. "They're cheaper than the big-cap universe and have the same growth prospects as small stocks -- but without the volatility," he says. Last year he returned 12.2 percent, below the 15.6 percent average for the group. But in the dicey first quarter of 1994, he outperformed the S&P 500 by 5 percentage points, putting him second in the mid-cap category at 0.81 percent.<p>When shopping for stocks, revenues are better numbers to analyze than earnings in many cases, Bhirud says, because they are an absolute. Earnings involve more uncertainty, more room for management's maneuverings in areas like executive salaries, stock options, and other administrative expenses. Revenue growth can also point to turnaround situations. Bhirud looks first for yearly revenue growth of 10 percent to 15 percent, then checks for earnings increases of 20 percent or more.<p>Right now, Bhirud likes technology companies. He feels the sector is relatively cheap and will benefit as global demand for computers -- especially in Europe and developing countries like China -- picks up. Technology companies recently traded at an average price-to-revenue ratio of 2. As a comparison, the drug sector trades at three times revenues -- too dear in Bhirud's eyes.<p>Bhirud also favors cyclical companies in the steel, chemical, and copper industries, because he believes they'll benefit from the increased capital expenditure planned by many corporations. "We are in the third year of the economic recovery," says Bhirud, "the right time to pick these stocks." His choice in the sector is <a name="NYSE:WHX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11631"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wheeling-Pittsburgh</b></a> (NYSE: WHX, recent price $15.88), one of the few integrated steel companies now starting a turnaround. In the black after a year of losses, Wheeling still sells for less than half its per-share revenue. <p><a name="NYSE:CMZ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10340"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cincinnati Milacron</b></a> (NYSE: CMZ, recently $21) and <a name="NYSE:FLR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10594"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fluor</b></a> (NYSE: FLR, recently $49.25) are Bhirud's choices for companies that will benefit from increasing capital investment among automobile manufacturers and infrastructure industries. Machine-tool maker Cincinnati Milacron took $100 million in losses for accounting and cost-cutting charges in 1993; revenues still rose 30 percent. Among its largest customers is <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>. Bhirud estimates the company -- which was in the black for only two of the last five years -- will see positive earnings this year.<p>Fluor, an engineering and construction company, trades at half its per-share revenues. Fluor grew at an 18 percent clip in 1993, and Bhirud expects 20 percent annual growth in the near future. The 15 percent (and growing) annual expenditure on domestic infrastructure and the weak dollar make Fluor a top competitor for its only rivals, the Japanese, according to Bhirud.<p>Selections in semiconductor stocks include <a name="NYSE:LSI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13932"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LSI Logic</b></a> (NYSE: LSI, recently $22.38) and <a name="NYSE:NSM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11058"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>National Semiconductor</b></a> (NYSE: NSM, recently $20.75). This latter chip maker broke into the black in 1993 after four years of deficits. With 53 percent of its revenues made overseas, the company is positioned to benefit from European and Asian economic recoveries. Its shares trade at only one times revenues, versus two to six times for a typical mid-cap. Smaller LSI Logic in Milpitas, California, which makes custom integrated circuits, trades at 0.7 times revenues. Annual sales growth is a healthy 16 percent for this company, which services the telecommunications and computer industry; Bhirud expects current earnings growth of 23 percent to gallop to 50 percent this year.<p>Also on Bhirud's list is <a name="NYSE:ODP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14308"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Office Depot</b></a> (NYSE: ODP, recently $34.88), the country's largest office-supply superstore chain, with an efficient distribution system that he says will contribute to 40 percent annual earnings growth over the next five years. At 47 times earnings, it's not cheap, but the stock is still just 1.3 times per-share revenue. "It's the same concept as <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a> but in a different industry," says Bhirud.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
