<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Tempted Try Currency Trading</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Tempted Try Currency Trading</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
This reality check might change your mind.<p>By Liliana Nealon<p>Newspaper headlines describing big paydays in currency trades have given many investors the idea that they too can venture profitably into the world of currencies. They could not be more wrong.<p>The almost $1 trillion-a-day currency markets are dominated by a few players, understood by even fewer. The average trade here is $20 million, making it difficult, if not impossible, for individual investors to make money in currencies. Unlike other securities, currencies don't just follow domestic economic trends; they also react to political and global events. Neither are they closely correlated to other markets. Currency markets behave chaotically and are incomprehensible to many. <p>What novices in this market often forget is that when you buy one currency (say, the Japanese yen), you always and inescapably short the currency you're investing with (the U.S. dollar). Investors who would never sell short a stock happily short a currency, believing they are just long deutsche marks or yen. In truth, they're selling dollars, risking a short position in one of the world's wildest markets.<p>To prove how wild and difficult to navigate these markets are, study the action in currencies during the month of March 1994. As February ended, traders expected that the Federal Reserve Board would raise interest rates (good for the dollar), Germany might again cut its rates (good for the dollar), and that trade friction with Japan would escalate. The dollar opened March trading at 1.6970 against the deutsche mark and 104.38 against the yen. <p>March 1 brought a two-month low for the dollar against the D-mark, a sell-off sparked by expectations that the Fed's tightening would not be as severe as expected. Given this new scenario, an investor might want to buy dollars against the D-mark, as the interest rate differential between the two currencies narrows in favor of the dollar, and sell dollars against the yen. Japan's growing trade surplus is a reason to bet on the yen even though the country's in turmoil with low interest rates and a sick stock market. A higher yen is the only way the U.S. can balance trade.<p>As the month proceeds, the dollar remains soft, against both the D-mark and the yen, losing even more ground against the mark when a member of the German Central Bank says no to further rate drops. <p>Now an investor would want to be short the dollar, long yen and the D-mark. During early March, those would have been profitable positions. But on March 4, the dollar rallies on news of stronger-than-expected nonfarm payroll growth in February, possible U.S. trade sanctions against Japan, and big dollar buying by the Bank of Japan. The buck closes 105.75 against the yen and 1.7186 against the D-mark. <p>With this volatility, most small investors would have been automatically closed out of their short dollar positions with substantial losses. Institutional dollar players didn't fare any better; large losses befell hedge-fund folks George Soros, Mike Steinhardt, and others.<p>Enter Whitewatergate. On March 9, the dollar drops to 1.7000 against the D-mark. It holds up against the yen at 105.25. By the ides of March, we're back where we started the month in both currencies. But low inflation numbers send the dollar down to 1.6885 against the D-mark. OnSt. Patrick's Day, the dollar drifts back up to 1.6920 against the D-mark until the Bundesbank says it won't cut rates. The buck falls to 1.6768. <p>On March 22, rumors that the Fed will indeed raise rates boost the buck. When the Fed actually signals its rate hike, traders buy, then quickly dump dollars, guessing incorrectly that the Fed is fibbing. Against the yen, the dollar goes to 105.80; against the D-mark, 1.6875.<p>On March 24, the dollar gets trashed, falling to 1.6640 against the D-mark and 104.28 against the yen. Traders now sell dollars as U.S. rates climb. Weren't these guys selling a few weeks back because they thought the Fed wouldn't tighten?<p>April 1 at last. During March, the dollar traded in an almost 4 percent range against the D-mark and a 4.3 percent range against the yen. But today, the dollar opens at 1.6744 against the D-mark and 102.65 against the yen, 1.3 percent lower and 1.7 percent lower, respectively, than it was on March 1. <p>Given the volatility of this market, most investors would have been scared in and out of their positions at exactly the wrong moments. You're better off in a money market fund.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
