<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Power Plays</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Power Plays</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Think electric-utility stocks still mean easy money? You may be in for a shock. Here's how to play this evolving sector.<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>Last October, shares in <a name="NYSE:UEP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11542"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Union Electric</b></a>, a utility based in St. Louis, were trading at $44, just under their all-time high. For the first time in 40 years, the stock had surpassed $40. A broker suggested to a client that she sell her 700 shares of Union Electric and lock in a not insubstantial profit.<p>After much back and forth, she agreed. A couple of days later she telephoned the broker, audibly upset, and ordered him to cancel the trade. She had owned Union Electric for years and just couldn't part with it. "How can you tell me to sell that?" she asked. "It's a great company." He canceled the trade. A month later, the stock dropped to $38. It was recently at $36.13.<p>"People are locked in with their utility stocks," sighs the broker. "They love them. It's like a religion." <p>Worshiping stocks can be hazardous to investors' health. Think of the folks who clung to <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> shares, all the way from $100 in 1992 to $52 today.<p>Nowhere in the stock market is this reminder more timely than in the arena of electric utilities. Investors still cling to these shares for the same reason they always have: steadily increasing income and stable stock prices. Electric-utility stocks are portfolio basics for conservative investors. In fact, according to the Edison Electric Institute (EEI), the Washington, D.C.-based association of investor-owned electric utilities, 6.5 million Americans own utility stocks.<p>But the rude truth is, electric utilities aren't what they used to be. The business of generating and selling power to American homes and businesses is changing dramatically; gone are the days when utility companies were simple monopolies that built and operated power plants, then recovered their costs with rates of return guaranteed by state regulators. Demand is growing far more slowly, and the number of suppliers has increased. The industry now finds itself in a competitive arena in which some companies will thrive and others will not. <p>Indeed, last fall, for the first time ever, Standard & Poor's changed its rating for 47 electric utilities from stable to negative, citing fears of a long-term decline for the group. Add to this the recent increase in interest rates, and it becomes exceedingly clear that investors must reassess their utility holdings. Immediately.<p>"There is no historical precedent to this period," says William Tilles, a utility analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds. "The only time the industry saw such upheaval was in 1935, when the Public Utilities Holding Companies Act was passed." (With PUHCA, the huge interstate holding companies were broken up. The law was amended in 1992 with the Energy Policy Act.) As with any industry in flux, there will be winners and there will be losers. The trick is telling one from the other.<p>The forces of change short-circuiting the electric-utility industry date back some 16 years, to the Public Utility Regulatory Policies Act of 1978, which required local utilities to buy power from unregulated power generators, known as independent power producers, if the independents produced electric power more cheaply than the utilities could. Independents now account for 10 percent of the new capacity added annually.<p>That single law began the transformation of the utility business. Before 1978, utilities made money by building power plants; state regulators would then almost automatically figure the cost of that plant into the rate base. That meant rates would rise to allow the power company to earn a fair return on the new plant.<p>But in 1978 electric utilities were dragged, kicking and screaming, into a new world where they had to demonstrate that they were efficient producers of power. If a utility could buy power more cheaply than it could produce it, regulators demanded that the utility buy it. That cut down on the need for utilities to build new plants. Utilities couldn't simply grow larger by building another power plant, either. They now had to manage their assets. In some cases this had the desired effect of making the company financially stronger and lowering rates. But many electric utilities found themselves locked into unproductive long-term contracts, sometimes with pipsqueak independents. Desperate to get out of these arrangements, utilities entered into endless, expensive battles with the independents and state utility commissions. <p>At the same time, the steady growth in demand for electric power began to slow, further reducing the need for new power plants. Some of this decline was due to the increasing number of conservation programs utilities put in place over the last decade. Under pressure from state regulators, some utilities discovered that persuading their customers to use power more efficiently--by running plants and household appliances at off-peak hours or using energy-efficient lightbulbs--was more profitable than erecting new plants. In general, over this period, power-company revenues have declined, but earnings have grown. EEI estimates place that growth at 9.7 percent (excluding write-offs) in 1993. <p>Slower economic growth will also hurt utilities. According to the EEI, demand for electric power grew at a rate of 3.5 percent last year; for the next six years, the group expects demand growth to drop to 2 percent annually. And this comes at a time when the industry's average return on equity is already slipping. It fell from an annual rate of 13 percent five years ago to 10.5 percent currently.<p>There are no signs that any of these trends are about to reverse, either. Even if the much-discussed electric car gets off the ground, it is unlikely to produce much demand growth--just 2 percent of the vehicles in 14 states are mandated to be electric by 1998. Moreover, Congress passed the Energy Policy Act in 1992, which granted access on the nation's electric grid to wholesale generators--meaning independents and regulated utilities could both now sell their power to other utilities beyond their service territories. It is entirely possible that unregulated independents will soon be allowed to sell power directly to utilities' industrial customers. <p>These recent changes in laws and the economics of the business are so seismic that investors must rethink their investment assumptions. "No longer are utilities strictly owners of assets; they have become buyers of power," says James Doudiet, formerly chief financial officer at Northern States Power and Northern Indiana Public Service and now an independent utility consultant in Minneapolis. So utility investors must ask new kinds of questions. How efficient is management? Does the company have too many workers? Are old plants, especially aging nuclear-power plants, adding too much costly overhead?<p>So confusing is the scene that even the so-called experts can't agree on what investors should do: <p>-> Drop electric-utility stocks altogether, some advisors say. This option certainly can be a shock to investors who have long considered utilities the most dependable investments in their portfolio. And if they've owned utility stocks for a long time, investors may have a hard time facing the tax consequences of a sale.<p>-> "Hold," says Dean Witter, employing the bafflegab Wall Street is famous for. The brokerage firm believes the market has overreacted to the sharp recent rise in interest rates. The selling in utility stocks, it says, has been consequently overdone.<p>-> Ignore apocalyptic statements about the industry's demise--and buy, says Roger Conrad, editor of The Utility Forecaster in Alexandria, Virginia. "Electric utilities are good defensive stocks right now," he says. <p>-> Switch from utility stocks to electric-utility funds, says Edwin Bragdon, portfolio manager of the Eaton Vance Traditional Total Return Fund, which has $631 million in assets. Instead of being forced to choose between one or two stocks, investors get safety in numbers. Bragdon seems unworried about the effects of increasing competition in the utility industry. "We've had competition for 40 years, and it'll stay with us. It's the new buzzword that scares, just like nuclear was in the '80s," he says. <p>Last year utility funds beat the S&P 500's total return of 10.08 percent with an average total return of 14.7 percent. But Chicago-based Morningstar, which ranks thousands of mutual funds, believes that performance isn't sustainable. That's because roughly 10 percentage points of last year's gain came from price appreciation, and the remaining 4 came from dividends. And now that interest rates have started to rise, the prices of utility stocks are headed downward. Faced with nothing but mixed messages, investors have a right to be confused. <p>Begin any reassessment with a clean slate. Forget, first of all, about investing in utilities for the long term. Consultant Doudiet says that to make money in utility stocks today and in the future, investors must shorten their time horizon and invest for the medium term--a three- to five-year span. <p>Also forget about sky-high dividend yields. A focus on generous dividends has served investors exceedingly well in the past, but from now on they'd better concentrate on sustainable dividends. That's because companies that spend almost all of their profits making dividend payouts will in many cases be the least likely to succeed in the increasingly competitive energy arena. (For more on this, see "Stocks With Juice and Some Shocks to Avoid.") And ultimately, they won't be able to sustain those high payouts.<p>Here's why. Since demand growth for power is declining, utilities' sales growth will have to come from other operations. Utility companies most likely to prosper in the future are already diverting some of the cash that would typically go to shareholder dividends and putting it into other, nonregulated businesses. Note that these businesses are, in the most promising cases, energy-related. Utility companies learned their lessons from disastrous 1980s diversifications into unrelated areas like insurance and real estate.<p>Traditional utility investors looking solely for high current income should consider the utility's preferred stock, says St. Louis money manager David Eidelman. These issues are more like bonds than stocks; a company struggling to cope with diminishing cash flows may cut its common-stock dividend, but most are loath to cut preferred-stock payouts. <p>It is still early enough in the shift from income-only utility investing to an income-and-growth focus that investors can take advantage of the change. The industry's average dividend-payout ratio--the percentage of earnings a company pays out to shareholders--remains at a very high 82 percent. In contrast, the oil industry's historical dividend-payout ratio, for example, ranges from 50 percent to 55 percent. Look for electric companies with dividend-payout ratios around 60 percent--or, since numbers like that are still uncommon in this sector, ratios that are headed down. This information is easily found in annual reports.<p>Next, look for electric utilities that serve a wide geographical area--like Columbus, Ohio's American Electric Power Co., which serves customers in seven states. Companies that operate in several states are less susceptible to the rate-cutting whims of a single state regulatory body. <p>Avoid utilities that have a large nuclear exposure. Very few companies have the necessary reserves to withstand huge decommissioning expenses--what it costs to take apart a nuclear reactor at the end of its useful life and safely dispose of the radioactive pieces. Coal-dependent utilities also face a risk that's difficult to quantify: Federal clean-air rules could force the purchase of expensive equipment to reduce pollutants that cause acid rain.<p>But do be on the lookout for utilities with smart and aggressive managers. Without the comfort of regulated returns, these companies must be run more like highly competitive consumer-oriented firms. <p>Which companies are well placed to ride out the waves of change? <a name="NYSE:NI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11040"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>NIPSCO Industries</b></a>, a utility holding company in Hammond, Indiana, is one. A turnaround story, NIPSCO suspended its dividend in 1986 thanks to a nuclear plant that had to be written off and a payout rate that exceeded earnings. It now has a reasonable 59 percent payout ratio and several nonregulated businesses that will provide new growth. It owns, for instance, the 14th-largest gas-distribution business in the U.S. and co-owns a recently opened facility in the United Kingdom that will generate power by burning worn-out tires.<p>New Orleans's <a name="NYSE:ETR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10524"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Entergy Corp.</b></a> is a well-diversified utility covering four states in the South. It has a 61 percent payout ratio and is sitting on $564 million in cash. It recently completed a $2.3 billion merger with neighboring Gulf States Utilities, giving Entergy geographical dominance. Gulf States' coal-based generation will also increase Entergy's capacity by about 30 percent and help reduce its heavy nuclear dependence. Entergy took a write-off of approximately $1 billion on its nuclear operations in 1989. <p>Entergy is one of the few utilities investing in technology as part of its conservation program. The company has put several million dollars into developing the "smart meter." This will allow customers to monitor their energy usage more efficiently and will eliminate the need for meter readers. <p>Other utilities are following Entergy's lead into add-on services for utility customers. The smart meter and other new technologies will allow utilities to increase revenues even while rates decline, much like the telephone companies have done with extras like call forwarding and call waiting. <p>Like many U.S. electric utilities, Entergy went global last year, investing $90 million in three consortia of recently privatized Argentine electric power companies. With construction in the U.S. virtually at a halt, electric companies are stacked with excess manpower and expertise looking for projects. <p>But even the best can falter here. Most of the opportunities are in newly industrialized countries with limited infrastructure and high political and currency risks. The 25 percent returns that U.S. companies were counting on when they ventured abroad last year are now expected to be more like 16 percent--a mere 5 percent over domestic rates. That seems like a thin reward for taking on these added risks.<p>Eighteen U.S. power companies have invested abroad so far. Investors should stick with utilities that operate and build, rather than own, plants overseas. Kansas City, Missouri's UtiliCorp United was the first to go abroad--in Canada in 1987. The country's only family-run electric utility currently operates--but doesn't own--facilities in the United Kingdom, Australia, and New Zealand--all stable, English-speaking countries with business cultures similar to that of the United States. "We prefer not to venture beyond our area of comfort or knowledge," says Frank Costanza, vice president of the company's unregulated subsidiary, UtilCo. Foreign operations bring in 12 percent of net income.<p>In California--which sometimes is best viewed as a foreign country--San Diego Gas & Electric's innovative management has maneuvered ably through the state's troubled waters. SDG&E benefits from the presence of independent power producers: It buys 50 percent of its power on the open market. Last July, it sent a proposal to the California State Utility Commission to adopt performance-based rate making. This system would base SDG&E's allowed return not on capital invested but on its ability to keep prices competitive. If prices stay below a specific benchmark, stockholders and customers benefit; if not, both share the costs. The commission is scheduled to decide on the proposal this month. <p>Another criterion for today's utility investors to consider: Companies should be low-cost producers of electricity. Two of the best in this regard are Richmond, Virginia-based Dominion Resources and Portland, Oregon-based PacifiCorp, according to Ernest Liu, utility analyst at Goldman, Sachs. Conversely, Consolidated Edison Co., SCEcorp, Oklahoma Gas and Electric, Centerior Energy, and Texas Utilities are high-cost producers. Centerior recently cut its dividend.<p>Entergy, which otherwise seems a model investment, also sells power at an above-average price. At 6.8 cents per kilowatt hour, Entergy's industrial rate is far higher than the national average of 4.9 cents. But this cost should come down, thanks to smart acquisitions of nonnuclear energy providers.<p>Price wars between utilities won't do investors any good, either. Last year, Public Service Gas & Electric in Newark, New Jersey, won away a customer from Delmarva Power, considered the lowest-cost producer in the region, by offering a discount to win the business. Obviously, that discount ultimately cuts into Public Service's profits--and the amount of cash available for distribution as dividends to investors, too. Such price cutting also puts pressure on margins at low-cost producers, which are forced to lose the business or match the discount. Over the long term, investing in the low-cost producer is a better strategy, but that doesn't mean that investors won't feel some short-term pain as the utility industry works through its new economics.<p>Another warning: A utility with high exposure to industrial customers can be trouble. These big customers are the ones getting the discounts and are very good at cherry picking for the best deals among competing utilities. But be careful not to use this screen too simply. Long Island Lighting, for instance, has almost no industrial customers. However, high unit costs (16 cents per kilowatt hour) leave it vulnerable to municipalization, the political equivalent of a hostile takeover by the utility's customers. When this happens, the town becomes the owner.<p>While the economics of the power business have been changing, so too have some of these companies' chief executives. Members of the new breed are likely to be young--like UtiliCorp's 40-year-old head, Richard Green--and come from outside the industry. LG&E Energy's Roger Hale came from the telephone industry--first AT&T, later BellSouth. Western Resources' John E. Hayes came from Southwestern Bell five years ago. SCEcorp's John Bryson is a former lawyer and state water-utilities regulator in California.<p>Prior to joining Entergy in 1991 as its new chief financial officer, Gerald McInvale was CFO at Frito-Lay, a subsidiary of PepsiCo. Although his consumer-goods background may seem out of place, it is appropriate in today's complex utility arena. As McInvale says: "We don't count on regulators anymore. We expect to earn our way through the market. Instead of growth through a regulated return on equity, we'll have growth through cash flow."<p>Power sold like potato chips? Don't bet against it. What was once a corporate backwater is fast becoming an industry every bit as competitive as consumer packaged goods or personal computers. Investors should behave accordingly.
---------------
Manjeet Kripalani is an associate editor of Worth.<p>May 1994
Worth magazine/Features<p>Mortgage Wars
When mortgage lenders battle over market share, home buyers can find great deals.<p>By Andrew Feinberg<p>Ready! Fire! Aim! The mortgage industry is going to war, and it's a fight that will benefit consumers. Examples: In the 12 states in which it operates, customers of Home Savings of America can now put down as little as 5 percent on a $300,000 mortgage, and Home Savings will waive the normally required mortgage insurance. Its rates start as low as 6.6 percent.<p>In Greenbrae, California, a mortgage lender recently offered a broker at Pacific Guarantee Mortgage a rebate of one full point - that's 1 percent of the mortgage loan amount, or $2,000 on a $200,000 loan - to get the firm's business. Other lenders have offered rebates of a quarter point to a half point.<p>In Fairfax, Virginia, George Mason Bank is offering home-equity credit lines at prime minus half a point for a line of $50,000 or more. The annual rate: 5.5 percent on owner-occupied homes.<p>Wait a second. ...  Aren't these developments contrary to the recent news about rising interest rates?<p>Well, yes, they are. Back on October 15, 1993, the average interest rate on a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage was just 6.83 percent, according to HSH Associates of Butler, New Jersey, which tracks mortgage rates nationally. By March 18, the rate was 7.85 percent, and the prognosis is for more of the same. Rates on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages will be 8.1 percent by the end of the year, predicts David Lereah, chief economist of the Mortgage Bankers Association.<p>Yet at the same time, mortgage lenders have stepped up efforts to gain, or hold on to, market share. They know that rising rates inevitably will slow new financings and bring an end to the boom that saw more than 10 million mortgages refinanced in 1992 and 1993. So they are striking back with a sale just in time for spring, the traditional peak of the home-buying season.<p>Unlike the deals that got the savings and loans into trouble in the 1980s, the mortgage industry this time around is trying to practice restraint. Thus, most of the bargains that lenders are offering focus on upfront terms rather than on cutting interest rates on 30-year loans. Lenders are stretching out payments and reducing the amount buyers must put down  - in some cases, to zero. Lenders have slashed introductory rates and then slashed them again. Points, the cost of getting a new mortgage, have in many cases disappeared. <p>Comparing all the new packages is time consuming, but certainly worth the effort. The skirmishing in the mortgage industry has also given borrowers more leverage. "Today's consumer is much more in the driver's seat than he has been in recent years," says Keith Gumbinger, an analyst with HSH Associates. "Especially if you have triple-A credit, you should ask, 'What can you do for me that's better?' Play one lender off against another. Realize that six months ago, there were 500 people at the lender's door ready to write contracts, and now there are only four or five."<p>Before plunging into the complicated task of comparing mortgage options, buyers should keep a few things in mind about the state of today's real estate market. Yes, home-sales activity has picked up, but clearly, housing prices haven't yet run away from would-be buyers. So there's reason for patience. Nationwide, the median price of existing homes rose just 3 percent last year, to $106,800. The median cost of a new home crept up 3.7 percent to $126,000. Prices will move up another 3.5 percent and 5 percent, respectively, in 1994, predicts Lereah.<p>Of course, national numbers don't always apply. In hot markets like Richland/Kennewick/Pasco, Washington (up 21 percent in 1993); Green Bay, Wisconsin (up 11.8 percent); Salt Lake City/Ogden (up 11 percent); and Boise, Idaho (up 10 percent), it may seem as if prices are leaping 3 percent a month. In Los Angeles (down 7.1 percent in 1993); Orange County, California (down 6 percent); and Hartford, Connecticut (down 4.1 percent), the bottom, apparently, hasn't yet been glimpsed.<p>A potential borrower who hasn't been in the market for a decade faces a bewildering array of new mortgage sources. For example, in 1987 the U.S. survived with only 7,500 mortgage brokers. By the end of 1993 there were 18,000. And in contrast to ten years ago, the industry is a lot less local. In 1984, S&Ls, by and large small local lenders, controlled 53.5 percent of all mortgage lending for one- to four-unit properties. But their share eroded to 19 percent by the end of 1993. Aggressive mortgage bankers, such as Countrywide Funding, which often operate on a national rather than local scale, now control 52 percent of the overall mortgage market. All those lenders mean that no market is too small for cutthroat competition.<p>"I was surprised how badly the lenders seemed to want my business," says a Maryland man who recently closed on a new home. He shouldn't have been; the battle lines are clearly visible - especially in realtors' offices.<p>"Every week now, 50 different lenders try to call on me," says Joan Reilly, manager of Coldwell Banker Realty Pros in Potomac, Maryland. "They're getting more aggressive about offering gourmet lunches, setting up cocktail parties, or just stopping by to drop off food."<p>And, of course, cheap money. "If Countrywide notices on a certain day of the month that we haven't done our normal amount of volume, they'll be on the phone saying, 'We miss your business,' and offering rebates," says Bob da Costa, president of Indian River Mortgage, a Vero Beach, Florida, lender. <p>Smart home buyers should take advantage of all this. "These days," says John Lucas, vice president with ARCS Mortgage, a Bank of New York company headquartered in Calabasas, California, "everything is negotiable." But everything is much more negotiable with some lenders. Generally speaking, it's easier to wheel and deal with mortgage bankers and mortgage brokers than with large banks and S&Ls.<p>Adjustable-rate mortgages, or ARMs, are a place, however, where S&Ls are likely to be aggressive. Surviving S&Ls see rising rates and the end of the refinancing frenzy as their best chance to regain market share for ARMs, traditionally their strongest product. Adjustable mortgage rates are likely to stay artificially low this year, and the spread between adjustable and fixed mortgage rates has widened by an average of more than three eighths of a percentage point. <p>Borrowers looking for a bargain on rates might also check out home-equity loans. During 1992 - 93, home-equity lending lost market share to refinancings. In response, lenders have actually dropped home-equity rates. Instead of offering credit lines at the once prevailing rate of prime plus one and a half percentage points, many lenders are now dangling lines at prime.<p>The industry has also introduced a crop of exotic mortgage options designed to pull in business without cutting profit margins too severely. Some of these may actually be great opportunities for specific home buyers.<p>For example, a 40-year mortgage, a product just reintroduced in many markets, makes a home slightly more affordable in the short term by reducing the monthly mortgage payment. But the added cost over the life of the loan makes sense only for buyers who don't plan on staying put long and need the extra cash flow now. The monthly payment on a $200,000, 30-year, 7.75 percent fixed-rate mortgage is $1,433. For a 40-year deal it's $1,353. Over the life of a 40-year mortgage, however, the home buyer will pay $133,000 more. <p>Borrowers who want to keep their monthly payments down might also consider another alternative, the delayed first-adjustment ARM. These can lower the initial interest rate by 0.375 to 0.5 percentage points. Then, after a specified period, the fixed rate on this mortgage becomes adjustable. For example, a borrower might pay a fixed jumbo mortgage rate of 7.375 percent for ten years, after which the interest rate becomes adjustable at one-year intervals. On a $275,000 loan, using this alternative (called a ten-one because it looks like a fixed mortgage for ten years and then becomes an adjustable-rate mortgage with a rate that changes once a year) could save $13,800 over the first ten years - a great deal for a home buyer who can predict when the family will be moving on to another house.<p>A no-equity refinancing is another option that may be a good deal for the millions of homeowners who have the worst of both worlds: a high-rate mortgage and a house that has declined in value. Many of these homeowners lack the 20 percent equity stake traditionally required to refinance.<p>No-equity refinancings cost about one point more than prevailing 30-year rates, and while refinancing at 8.75 percent isn't everyone's idea of a great offer, it might be a godsend for people stuck with higher-rate mortgages.<p>Interest rates aren't the only rates that matter. Income taxes need to get factored into any decision about how big a mortgage to take, how little to put down, and what rate is best. Rising income-tax rates mean that carrying tax-deductible debt, such as a mortgage, costs less than it did last year. Making a somewhat smaller down payment makes sense, since the value of the mortgage deduction is greater this year. A buyer can actually afford a little more house because of changes in the tax code. Those same changes slightly diminish the appeal of 10-, 15-, and 20-year mortgages. But the tax code still hasn't made a 40-year mortgage a good deal for most home buyers. <p>No matter how how many numbers you've crunched, don't forget to check out the lender. Doing business with an obscure outfit offering a seemingly miraculous package may be asking for trouble. One quick way to check on a lender is to call your state banking department to find out about any recent complaints. (Checking out a mortgage broker is more difficult in the 13 states that don't require a broker to obtain a license.) Once the lender survives this initial screen, ask for the names and phone numbers of satisfied clients. Then roll up your sleeves and get ready to drive a hard bargain.<br>
---------------<br>
Andrew Feinberg is a contributing editor of Worth.  "Downsize Your Debt," his first book, was published last year by Penguin.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing, Homeowner, Banking Industry, Economy, Taxation

