		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Harsh Reality of Market Timing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Don't follow the so-called experts--they're lost, too<p>By Jonathan D. Pond<p>As an investment strategy, market timing has proved to be a loser. Yet it seems as winning as ever, pitched by self-professed market timers in newsletters, mutual funds, and timing services. These folks claim to have a system that spots market bottoms and market tops. It makes you wonder why they haven't left the timing business years ago and retired to their yachts on the Mediterranean.<p>Here's why: They can't afford to. According to data gathered by a publication that rates the timers, The Hulbert Financial Digest, only 2 market-timing newsletters out of 65 were able to beat the Wilshire 5000 index over extended periods in the 1980s. In 1993, timers did slightly better overall than the S&P 500, according to Hulbert, because of the large gains in gold, favored by timers. Still, most individual timers still lagged the index. <p>But, the timers respond, if they merely pull you out of the market in time to avoid large losses, your investments will profit accordingly. Even should they call the bottom right only half the time, they say, it'll save you from half the bear markets that ravage investors. Market timers make bearishness a specialty; as the saying goes, they've foreseen nine of the past four bear markets. <p>One fundamental truth has made buying and holding securities a sounder strategy than market timing: Over the long term, securities prices have increased. The market has concluded business down in only nine of the last 40 years. This means that if you did nothing but hold, you would be right three years out of four.<p>Selling at the wrong time--trying to time the market, in other words--could have proved disastrous. For instance, $1,000 invested in stocks over the past 40 years would have grown to $86,550, contrasted to only $8,670 if the money had been kept in Treasury bills. If you had missed the 34 best months for stocks, however, your $1,000 investment would have amounted to only $4,492; even T bills would have been better, according to Ibbitson Associates, a Chicago-based investment-consulting firm.<p>Does that seem like a risk-averse strategy for investing? That's how the market-timing services promote it; but investors who entrust their money to market timers probably will pay a stiff price for mediocre results. These services move you in and out of mutual funds depending on the dictates of the timers' systems. Typically, it will cost you 2 percent of the assets under management. Half of the fee generally goes to the market timer, who does all the work. The other half goes to your financial advisor, who initially selects the timer and subsequently has to explain why the performance is so poor. In addition, your money pays the usual mutual fund expenses.<p>But let's hear from a market timer. Here's a January 1994 memorandum, with performance statistics (above), sent by one market-timing service to financial planners who had steered risk-averse clients to it:<p>"Well, as you can see from the attached performance numbers, 1993 was a bummer of a year. Your clients' quarterly statements will be in the mail the last week of the month.<p>"Not much more can be said that hasn't already been said. We trust and fully expect that 1994 will get us back on the right path. The long-term performance numbers are still very good and we remain fully confident and committed to our market-timing program. <p>"The long-awaited correction has yet to occur, but we are confident that it is imminent. You may find some comfort in the fact that, from the few numbers I have seen so far, our 1993 performance is not out of line with other market timers. Although most have numbers slightly better than ours, none are anywhere close to the buy-and-hold numbers. It was just not a good year for market timing. It is interesting to note that in almost every case when our program had a poor performance year, the following year was a very good performance year. We can only hope and pray!"<p>Actually, smart clients can do more than that. They can take their money out.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

