<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Case Against Using Limit Orders</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Case Against Using Limit Orders</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Indecisive investors love them. Successful investors don't.<p>By Justin Mamis<p>Investors in the stock market all too often try to win the brilliance prize: Buy at the bottom eighth, sell at the very top tick. Ironically, this need to be correct on the market or on a stock often leads to behavior that practically guarantees that the investment will go wrong.<p>An example: The use of stop-loss or limit orders when either selling or buying stocks. Investors in search of perfection use limit orders when they would like to buy a stock but don't want to pay the going price for it. When it comes time to get out of a stock, investors place stop-loss orders to sell their shares above the market price. Both actions are all about being right in the market - buying beneath the market and selling above it. The perfect trade.<p>Limit orders to sell appear particularly attractive now, given investor skittishness over high stock prices. This is ironic because limit orders tend to result in deeply imperfect trades. <p>The use of limit orders characterizes an indecisive, insecure investor. Is this the right time to sell? Is this the best price? No investor wants to be wrong, so hedging and hesitancy take over. Limit orders become the escape. <p>This is particularly harmful to investors' health on the sell side. When you miss a stock that you wanted to buy because you placed a limit order beneath the market, you have experienced only an opportunity loss. But when you miss out on selling a stock because it never quite reaches the price you want, you will encounter actual losses.<p>Late last fall, stockholders of <a name="NYSE:LTD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11471"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Limited, Inc.</b></a>, the retailing giant, might have noticed a few days of sagging action in their shares. The stock kept running out of steam just shy of its previous rally high of $24. Worried about this apparent weakness, an investor could have done one of two things: Sell outright, at the market, or place a limit order to sell on the next bounce, at $23. <p>As it turned out, there was no next bounce. The stock had been lagging for a reason: Sales were slowing at Limited stores. A few days later, the stock opened at around $17. It hasn't risen above $20 since. The investor using a market order to sell his Limited shares could have gotten something north of $22 per share. The investor using the limit order would still be holding the shares and carrying a loss.<p>By limiting the price at which he'll sell, the investor has compromised with his anxiety about not being right on the market. He has also let his fear of ending the transaction keep him where he doesn't want to be - in a weakening stock. This is equally true whether the reason for selling is to take a loss or to lock in a gain. Taking a loss is to surrender all hope. Turning a gain from potential to realized profit is to surrender potency. Once he has sold, an investor no longer possesses the powerful feeling that owning a rising stock provides. The act of selling becomes a form of dying, as the Elizabethan poets wrote. If die we must, why not do it at the exact top tick in the stock?<p>Why is it dysfunctional behavior to place a limit order to sell above the current price? Because the order will be executed only if the stock still has the ability to rally, a characteristic that makes it a stock worth holding. You can see in the Limited example how much downside vulnerability can fester in a stock that is unable to go up just that little bit more. <p>Missing a stock on the buy side is also dumb. You want to buy a particular stock, but you're not sure if you should act now. Is this the low? Should you wait for a dip? Entering a buy order under the market requires a desired stock to turn weak or to become even weaker than it has already been. It isn't smart to buy a weak stock. Using a limit order, you're guessing that you can pick the exact moment when a weak stock will revive. Not likely.<p>Some investors have a fetish about buying a stock at its low. It's as if they know something the entire universe of professional traders, money managers, and analysts doesn't: that such a stock has on that very day and price hit bottom. This can be disastrous. Think of how much money was lost, over the years, by investors thinking they were getting the low in <a name="NASD:WANG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12443"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wang Laboratories</b></a>, a stock that went from almost $42 to 25 cents. Instead, investors should pursue strong stocks. And these will probably not come back down to accommodate anyone's lower-than-market limit price. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Stock Market Trends<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
