<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Electronic Investing in Seven Easy Steps</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Electronic Investing in Seven Easy Steps</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						For less than $3,000 you can bring Wall Street to your desktop. Here's how, in seven easy steps.<p>Edited by Jim Jubak<p>Every morning at 8:30 Tulsa time, as the new York Stock Exchange opens for business, a pajama-clad Bill Moore treads across the green shag carpet that covers the floor of his son's former bedroom and sits down at his <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> 486 computer with a cup of black coffee. He squints at his screen and logs on. <p>Moore hits F3 for news stories that might affect his portfolio. F4 brings up the prices of the 50 securities he watches during the day: short positions first, then long positions on gold, oil, medical, and other stocks. Another key connects him to Prodigy's on-line brokerage service. Moore, a 56-year-old entrepreneur and former CPA, performs this early-morning ritual faithfully. He calls it "saying grace over each stock." His daily devotion has earned him an average 14.6 percent annual return over the last three years on the $150,000 stock portfolio he manages electronically.<p>Welcome to the next revolution in investing. Wall Street doesn't have to be in New York anymore; it's just as easy to execute a trade or generate reams of analysis from a desktop in Manhattan, Kansas. After spending less than $3,000 on computer hardware and software, any investor can look at the same numbers the professionals do. "Whatever flag gives them the signal to buy or sell," Moore says, "I try to see it--and act on it--the same day they do. "The first generation of investing software brought mass-market products such as Quicken and Managing Your Money, two programs that let you put your checkbook on a computer, record stock purchases and sales, and calculate the value of a portfolio. But it's the second generation of software that promises to create the real revolution. Unlike the earlier programs, which did little more than help people keep track of their finances, these new programs are designed to make the user a better investor. They can create a portfolio and then test the mix to improve performance. They can search the universe of U.S. mutual funds looking for just the right balance of risk and reward or tear apart the trading pattern of any stock to find the right time to buy or sell. They can be programmed to follow a stock until it finally hits an investor's price-to-earnings target and then flag the stock as a buy. Right now, only a small percentage of all investors use these more powerful programs, but they've made a big impression among more experienced practitioners. More than 35 percent of the American Association of Individual Investors' 160,000 members use computers to manage their portfolios; more than 17 percent use them to analyze mutual funds.<p>Software programs like these once would run only on the powerful workstations that crowded the desks of brokerages on the Street. But the sinking price of computer power means that these programs will now run on almost any recently purchased IBM compatible or Macintosh. Consider what this means for the individual investor with the right software. No more buy or sell signals missed waiting for an investment newsletter. No more finding out crucial news only after the professionals have made their moves. No more thumbing through the stock tables in the Wall Street Journal to follow the price movements of individual stocks and then charting them by hand. <p>Performing any of these tasks is easy with the right software. But the number of choices is mind-boggling. There are more than 500 different investment programs for IBM compatibles on the market, nearly twice as many as there were two years ago. Macintosh users don't have such a broad range of choices; they have to make do with just 81.<p>We set out to fight our way through that jungle, separating programs that will make you a better investor from those that are badly designed, overhyped, too simple or too complex for the task at hand, or just plain wrong in the advice they give. This is the first time, we believe, that anyone has reviewed investment programs both as software and for the quality of their advice. Our team of four reviewers spent three months running more than 100 software programs. We measured each one on a portfolio of stocks, bonds, and funds to see which packages gave us an edge.<p>What follows is a step-by-step approach to becoming a computerized investor. Beginners can start with the simplest of the seven steps on the next page and discover software that will make them better investors right now. More experienced computer users and investors can dip into later stages to find more advanced help. We think even Bill Moore might learn a trick or two. 
--Carla Koehl<p><p>STEP 1: Getting started
Buying a computer is not unlike buying clothes for a two-year-old. At that age, kids are growing so fast that parents with any foresight buy clothes just a little bit bigger than their child needs today. It's the same with computers. Nobody wants to pay for power that will never be used, and no one wants to buy a machine that's just right now but might be too small in the near future.<p>So where do you start? Rule one: Don't base your hardware-buying decisions on the small print on software boxes. The program you want to run may specify that it "requires an IBM AT with 640K of memory, a hard disk, and DOS 3.0 or higher." That doesn't mean you should buy a machine with those precise specs. You'll need more power, and you'll want more speed.<p>Just ask Richard Maturi, who reviewed some software programs for this story. Maturi is an experienced computer user. He runs word processing, database, and spreadsheet software programs daily. We sent him only software that, the boxes said, would run on his machine. But two of the programs refused to load. The error messages kept saying his machine needed more memory. Why? Software manufacturers aren't out to deceive you, and they certainly don't want to sell you software that won't run when it gets home. But they also don't know anything about what software you already might have installed on your machine. In all probability, at least some of that software is using part of the available active memory (called RAM, for random-access memory), the kind that's called into use when you run a program. For example, almost every computer in the country now runs a screen-saver program--when you leave your computer idle for a while, flying toasters or swimming fish magically fill up your screen. Well, there goes some available RAM.<p>No machine works very well when pushed to its performance limits, and computers are no exception. Unless you really want to spend a lot of time loading and unloading programs and reconfiguring the machine's memory, get more RAM than you expect you'll need. It won't cost you significantly more, and you won't have to upgrade your computer when the next generation of memory-gobbling software comes out.<p>The hardware we recommend will cost about $2,000. If you are buying an IBM compatible--and the financial world is oriented toward the PC--go for a 486 that runs at a speed of at least 33 megahertz. (The first number refers to the generation of Intel chip the machine uses as its central processor; the second refers to the speed of the specific version of that chip used by this machine.) The price differential between a 486 and the slower 386 chip isn't significant anymore. If you are interested in a system you can brag about, buy a machine that comes with one of Intel's brand-new Pentium chips. Although it won't make a significant difference in running any of the software we reviewed, your friends will be impressed, provided you hang around with computer engineers. We suggest 8 megabytes of RAM. The difference between a 486 machine with 4 megabytes of memory and one with 8 is only about $200. <p>Graphics make comparing one investment with another easy, so get the graphics memory to run them--1 megabyte of graphics RAM will do. Buy a 14-inch color monitor--insist on SVGA (for an IBM) with a noninterlaced screen, and don't worry what the jargon means.<p>Get a 200-megabyte hard drive to store all the numbers you'll want to crunch. Nothing is more frustrating than having to reorganize three years of financial records because the data has outgrown the available space. Again, the extra cost for moving up from a 140-megabyte drive is minimal.<p>If you want to buy a Macintosh--not our first choice for investing applications--it will cost about the same. We recommend any Mac that uses a <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> 68040 chip--that means anything in the Quadra line numbered 610 or higher. <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple</b></a> introduced a significantly more powerful chip, the Power PC, this winter. Anything in the older 68040 line can be upgraded to that chip for about $750. Right now it's important to make sure that the programs you want to run come in Macintosh versions. The Power PC, though, should be able to run programs written for IBMs at reasonable speeds. RAM and hard drive should follow the guidelines for the IBM. Eventually, you will also need to buy a modem--a necessity for downloading stock prices, for example. Same with a CD-ROM drive. But adding these later makes good sense. External add-on drives and modems work just as well as those that come installed in the computer at purchase. And faster devices are coming to the market every day. It's much easier to update an external device than one that's inside the box.<p>As any parent knows, sometimes it's wise to postpone a purchase until a child's a little older.<p>WHAT YOU'LL NEED:
--Computer: IBM compatible 486DX/33 (or faster) with 8 megabytes of RAM, 
1 megabyte of video RAM, and a 200-megabyte (or larger) hard drive, estimated street price $1,500; or Apple Macintosh Quadra 610 (or faster) with 8 megabytes of RAM and a 200-megabyte (or larger) hard drive, estimated street price $1,400.
--Color monitor: 14-inch (SVGA for IBM), 1024 x 768 line noninterlaced, $400.
--Options: Antivirus software: Virex, $49.95, or SAM, $69.98. Surge protector 
with circuit breaker, $50.<p>
STEP 2: Choosing a Fund
You've bought the computer and set it up on your desk. Now you want to do something with it. Chances are you've also brought home one of the mass-market financial planning programs that are often bundled with computers these days. In your excitement over the prospect of actually being able to organize all of your various accounts and expenses in one place, you might even be tempted to use one of these programs to make your first foray into computerized investing. Stop immediately. Before any of these programs can be remotely useful, you'll have to spend hours entering data. In fact, if you were as organized as, say, MECA Software's Managing Your Money requires you to be, you might not need the program in the first place. <p>So why not start off with something a little easier and more immediately useful? Like picking a mutual fund. To do this, we suggest one of our favorite programs, Mutual Fund Expert Pro Plus from Steele Systems Inc. No data to type in. Easy to navigate. Within half an hour you'll be digging out stellar investment candidates--and checking up on the funds that you already own.<p>Pop the first of two disks into the floppy drive and hit install. Wait a few minutes, remove the first disk, insert the second, and hit "Enter." When installation is finished, less than ten minutes and ten keystrokes later, the screen will ask you, "Load a mutual fund data file?" Hit "Enter" twice and the first 19 of 4,182 equity and fixed-income funds fill the screen (with data current as of the end of the previous month). Above the name of the fund and columns giving the objective, ratings for return, and risk are commands such as "Locate" and "Rank."<p>You can scroll through the list or ask for a report on a specific fund. How about the Strong Discovery Fund? Hitting "Locate" and then typing in "Strong Discovery" takes the screen to the fund, number 3,681 on the database. At the bottom of the screen, it says, "F7 for single fund." That key puts the entire history of Strong Discovery on the screen. Year-to-date performance: 22.99 percent. The five-year average annual return: Almost as good at 20.45. These are great returns. But look at the year-by-year numbers: That average includes just a 1.92 percent gain in 1992 and a loss of 2.74 percent in 1990. Obviously volatility is an issue here. Steele rates the fund a B on return but a D on risk. <p>That, of course, raises a question: What funds get an A on either return or risk, or both? The program allows you to screen the entire universe of funds. From the "screen" menu highlight "Five Year Average," ">" (the symbol for greater than, in case you've misplaced your old math textbooks), and "20.45." You'll discover that 72 funds beat the five-year return on Strong Discovery. Finding out whether any funds outperformed Strong Discovery and took less risk, as measured by beta, is just as easy. (Beta is a number that compares the volatility--the tendency to move up and down--of a specific stock or fund with the market as a whole. A beta of 1 means the fund is perfectly correlated with the market and rises or falls just as it does. A beta of more than 1 means it's more volatile--and therefore perhaps riskier.) Strong Discovery has a beta of 1.33. Of the 72 funds that bettered its five-year performance, 42 of them show a beta of less than 1.33. <p>Mutual Fund Expert also offers crisp, clear graphics that produce charts as easy to read as any software we reviewed. Pick any fund from the 42 now displayed on the screen, say, the Kaufmann Fund. Moving the cursor down to the name of the fund and hitting "Graph" in the command line brings a new screen into view. It names the fund and then gives two benchmarks. Specifying a five-year time period and simply hitting "Enter" brings up a graph of the fund versus the performance of the S&P 500 and the average aggressive growth fund. The Kaufmann Fund outperformed both indexes every year: $10,000 invested in that fund five years ago would have grown to $32,540 at the end of 1993. The same amount with the S&P would have reached just $19,749. <p>Of course, all you are going to get from the Steele program is a fund's past performance. The program won't give you a clue about when the conditions that led to that return will change. But all you need from this program is one good fund idea to pay for your entire electronic investment.<p>WHAT YOU'LL NEED:
--Software: Mutual Fund Expert Pro Plus
--Time commitment: Time to install: 10 minutes. Time to get up to speed: 30 minutes.
--Techinical Requirements: The program will run on a IBM 286 with 512 kilobytes of memory. Worth recommends an IBM compatible 386 with at least 1 megabyte of memory. Computer must have  3 megabytes available space on hard disk. DOS and OS2 versions. 3.5-inch or 5.25-inch drives. Help line (310-478-4213) available 8 A.M.-5 P.M. (PST). 
--Costs: Annual subscription, which includes program (with info on 4,200 funds) and four quarterly data updates, $399. Program plus monthly updates, $599. Other versions with fewer funds cost less--for example, Mutual Fund Expert Personal (3,300 funds) with monthly updates costs $185.
--How To Order: Steele Systems, 800-237-8400, ext. 752.<p>STEP 3: Researching a STOCK
No one program is going to do everything, although software developers keep marketing programs that promise just that. Right now it's pretty common, in fact, for the best program at tackling one investment task to come hidden inside a package that's pretty terrible at most other investment tasks. The best program we found for researching a stock is buried inside one of those do-it-all personal-finance systems that, on the whole, we think is pretty bad. There's an important lesson here, and you're smart to learn it early: When it comes to software, it's sensible to cannibalize. If a program does just one function well, it might be worth owning. For stock research, we suggest Reality's WealthBuilder by Money magazine, a software package that extravagantly bills itself as a "complete financial planning system." They should scrap the planning. That part of the program requires hours of entering needlessly detailed information and, after all that, spits out amazingly wrongheaded advice. It gave one of our reviewers, for instance, the questionable recommendation to put 10 percent in cash for a tax-deferred account, and its manual says, "Traditionally, investment advisors recommended that you keep between 5 percent and 25 percent of your investment capital in gold." Guess we talked to the wrong advisors.<p>Where WealthBuilder comes through is in the wealth of information it offers after you've learned to ignore all the financial-planning parts of the program. The basic version comes with stats on 2,500 mutual funds and 500 stocks (later, after you've bought a modem, you can download data on another 4,500 stocks through WealthBuilder). The numbers come from first-rate sources, Morningstar and Standard & Poor's, respectively. S&P also provides data on thousands of bonds, and Veribanc and the Bank Rate Monitor rate CDs and money market accounts. News comes from Dow Jones, Money magazine, and a wide sampling of other magazines and newsletters.<p>Keeping all this data up-to-date is easy with WealthBuilder, which boasts one of the easiest-to-use communications packages we came across. Clicking on the telephone icon gets a list of items available for update. Click on the arrows next to "Mutual Fund Quotes" or "Newspaper Updates" to tell the program to download the latest info in each category. Then click "Connect" and wait about five minutes. The program automatically dials (you've already given it the necessary information when you set up the program for the first time) and updates the prices on your machine before it hangs up. The program even gives you something to watch while this happens: hourly updates on the Dow, S&P, and Nasdaq, along with such basic information as market volume.<p>When you enter the stock database, an initial alphabetical list gives basic information such as price-to-earnings ratio, yield, and stock price. By going to the "View" menu, you can request various other types of data--"Earnings," for example, gives the same alphabetical listing but now emphasizes estimated 1993 earnings per share, actual 1991 and 1992 earnings, the mean estimate among Wall Street analysts for 1993 earnings, and projected five-year earnings growth.<p>From here an investor can go in either of two directions. Interested in a specific stock? Wealthbuilder has access to all the information an S&P or printed analyst's report provides except for industry outlook and a recommendation on the stock. All you do is highlight the stock and go up to the "Research" menu on the command line and click "Report." Going the other way, an investor can sort the universe of stocks looking for buys or sells. For example, clicking just three times results in a ranking of the stock database by projected five-year earnings growth. From this beginning an investor could construct either more complex screens--high growth rates and low price-to-earnings ratios, perhaps--or just look at reports for any of these stocks.<p>For all its particular strengths and weaknesses, WealthBuilder also illustrates three peculiarities typical of investment software. General-purpose programs like this are usually harder to use than specialized software--for example, sorting mutual funds on this software is more difficult than on the best mutual fund packages. Second, while a program like this is limited to relatively basic information--and an experienced investor will want more--it still doesn't explain how to use the data that it does provide very well. For instance, what is the best screen to use for picking stocks? Only the most sophisticated and expensive programs actually spend much time explaining the rules of investing. And third, while the investing part of a mass-market package like this may be harder to use than is necessary, its user interface puts most of the more sophisticated packages to shame. No one will get bogged down loading WealthBuilder, figuring out how to start it, or using the communications software. <p>WHAT YOU'LL NEED
--Software: WealthBuilder
--TimeCommitment: Time to install: Ten minutes. Time to get up to speed: Three hours.
--Technical Requirements: The IBM version (3.1) will run on a IBM 286 with 512 kilobytes of memory. Worth recommends a 386 with 1 megabyte of memory, a hard disk, DOS 3.3 or higher, and an EGA, VGA, or higher graphics card. Macintosh version (3.0) requires 2 megabytes of RAM, a hard drive, and  System 6.05 or higher. A 2,400-baud or faster Hayes-compatible modem is necessary. Product comes on 3.5-inch disks, but 5.25-inch disks are available. Help line (215-277-7600) available 8:30 A.M.11:30 P.M. (EST) M-F and 9:30 A.M.-11:30 P.M. Saturday. 
--Costs: Current versions of software list for $109.95. Updates from previous versions cost $49.99. On-line data requires annual subscription at either $9.95 or $17.95 a month. News clipping service is an additional $6.95 a month. 
--How To Order: Reality Technologies, 800-346-2024 <p>
STEP 4: Designing a Stategy
There's obviously more to investing than picking stocks and mutual funds. Like having a strategy. But helping investors work out their investment goals is the weak link in computerized investing. Almost every portfolio manager we tested failed at the basic task of helping an investor define his objectives and figure out how to reach them with the least risk possible. <p>Take the new version of Microsoft Money, which hit the shelves in early February. It offers on-line banking and state-of-the-art features, called "wizards," that are supposed to "simplify savings and retirement planning." And very welcoming graphics: When you open the retirement planner, beach chairs and palm trees fill the screen. The weaknesses show up about six questions into the planner, when the program asks, "What is the current return on your retirement savings?" Once you've entered all your investments into the ledgers in <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>Money, you'll know this, of course, but all that effort won't get you where you need to go. It won't tell you what mix of investments--bonds, small-cap stocks, utilities, etc.--will give you the best chance at earning the return you need with the least risk.<p>To get that part of the answer, we ran two other programs, one from Frontier Analytics called Allocation Master--clearly designed and priced (at $795) for the professional financial planner serving multiple clients--and the other, a subprogram embedded in the 1994 edition of  Managing Your Money ($79.95). Neither is anywhere near as pretty or new as Microsoft Money. But both answer the important questions.<p>Allocation Master begins with a bare-bones first screen. No palm trees here, just a menu bar across the top. Click on "Efficient Frontier" under "Asset Mix," and the screen shows a graph charting risk versus return. A black line represents the points where maximum return meets minimum risk at all levels of return. Moving the red dot, which represents the current portfolio, to new positions on the graph changes a pie chart at the top that shows a recommended asset allocation.<p>The asset-allocation function in Managing Your Money is designed around the same theories of portfolio efficiency as the $795 spread. Someone using this program can't specify asset classes as precisely as in Allocation Master, but it does offer an extremely intuitive way to study market scenarios. <p>For example, we put our entire portfolio into big-cap stocks, then told the program to use data from 1986 to 1992 to analyze that strategy. The program indicated expected returns would range between a high of 40.4 percent and a low of minus 15.4 percent. Resetting the data to the 1972--1977 period--the time of the last great bear market in stocks--suggested investing in something else. The best expected return in that period was just 2.8 percent with a downside possibility of losing 30.1 percent. <p>An investor applying a mix-and-match strategy could use Intuit's Quicken ($69.95) to keep records, WealthBuilder to pick stocks, and Managing Your Money to allocate assets. Since data in each of these programs is electronically portable, you'd only have to input a portfolio once. Such a best-of-all-worlds system would cost only around $200 at current street prices.<p>WHAT YOU'LL NEED
--Software: Microsoft Money ; Allocation Master ; Managing Your Money 
--Time Commitment: Time to install: 15 minutes each. Time to get up to speed: One hour each.
--Technical Requirements: Allocation Master and Microsoft Money come only in IBM versions: We recommend a 386 with 2 megabytes of memory. For Managing Your Money we recommend an IBM 386 with 1 megabyte of memory or a Mac with 2 megabytes.
--Costs: $69.95 for Microsoft Money; $795 for Allocation Master; $79.95 for Managing Your Money.
--How To Order: Microsoft Money: Microsoft Corp., 800-426-9400. Allocation Master: Frontier Analytics, 310-301-3988. Managing Your Money: MECA Software, 800-820-7457.<p>
STEP 5: Plugging in the Street
It's time to challenge wall street head on. The steps we've suggested so far should be enough to convince even the most confirmed technophobe that software can make anyone a more effective investor. Now how about running a program that has beaten some of Wall Street's best in head-on competition?<p>In 1992 the Wall Street Journal asked Macro*World Investor to go up against three human (remember them?) analysts in putting together a stock portfolio for the year. The program came in second, with a gain of 47.6 percent. Pretty impressive, but we wanted to find out just one thing more--how much did the human operating this software need to know to tackle this hotshot program?<p>To test Macro*World Investor, a $700 program that works by correlating economic and financial trends with the price history of a stock, we decided to evaluate a single stock in the portfolio of a hypothetical investor: 200 shares of Safety-Kleen Corp., a leader in the business of waste-fluid recovery from dry cleaners and auto-repair shops. Our investor bought her shares at $23.75 in January 1993. In November, the stock was down to $13.75. Should she sell for the tax loss, hang on, or buy more? <p>She's not starting from complete ignorance. From some of the software we've recommended already, she knows Safety-Kleen's recent price performance (down from a high of $29) and the direction of its earnings and revenues. Earnings have dropped, and revenue growth has slowed. This could be a fallen growth stock waiting for a recovery. Or the company could have hit a wall. The annual report claims that environmental violations--since corrected--are partly to blame, along with sluggishness in the U.S. economy and in Europe, where Safety-Kleen has invested in an expensive expansion. Management expects business on both continents to pick up. Should our investor believe management?<p>Macro*World has some advice. In fact, the program has screen after screen of it--seemingly every economic indicator can be crunched, bunched, sliced, or diced. For instance, under "short-term alerts," the first item is "capacity utilization." The program says there's an 88.9 percent chance that this U.S. economic indicator is headed up. As for Europe, industrial production in Germany is running at an extraordinarily low level. But fourth-quarter 1993 could be the low point for real growth in Germany's gross domestic product, Macro*World says. Looks like management could be right.<p>Next, our investor asked Macro*World if any of the macroeconomic factors it tracks have in the past accurately predicted changes in Safety-Kleen's price. It identifed six "leading indicators," ranging from initial unemployment claims to the domestic sales of trucks. Short term, the program was pessimistic on the stock, but the one-year forecast seemed promising: "The long-term trend is increasing over the next 12 months to $23.44."<p>Macro*World isn't a crystal ball. Sometimes, its correlations seem odd--the program found a connection between the exchange rate for the Italian lira and the price of Safety-Kleen--and it gives an investor only hedged recommendations; it never gives a simple "buy" or "sell." In this case, it noted that there was a 70 percent chance that Safety-Kleen would behave the way the program predicted.<p>Oh, by the way, our investor decided to hold on to her position. Safety-Kleen finished the year at $17.<p>WHAT YOU'LL NEED
--Software: Macro*World Investor
--Time Commitment: To install: 20 minutes. To get up to speed: Four to eight hours.
--Technical Requirements: Like most DOS-based programs, this requires very little memory: 512 kilobytes would be sufficient. Worth recommends an IBM 386 with EGA, VGA, or higher graphics card. A modem (9,600 baud) and communications software is required to download stock prices. Both 3.5- and 5.25-inch disks are available.
--Costs: The current version sells for $699.95 ($200 discount may be available; inquire). Software comes with six monthly data updates. Additional updates cost $39 each.
--How To Order: Macro*World Research Corp., 800-841-5398<p>
STEP 6: Timing Your Moves
Now it's time to wade into the deepest, murkiest waters of computerized investing: technical analysis, a controversial stock-picking method that has spawned a multitude of software packages. <p>Technical analysts, the soothsayers of the modern investment world, study financial entrails. Unlike fundamental analysts, who attempt to forecast stock prices based on such factors as sales and earnings, or econometric analysts, who work backward from the behavior of the economy, technical analysts study the trading patterns of stocks themselves. This method's adherents believe that all the information investors need to predict price movements is contained in past price movements. Detractors say the idea is nonsense. Sometimes, they'll admit, the predictions come true, but only because so many technicians are looking at the same signals. If enough people believe, for instance, that Tuesday's dip in the moving average is a sell signal, well, it becomes a sell signal. It's more reasonable to take the middle ground in this debate. Technical analysis does have its merits--the past movements of a stock's price indisputably contain valuable information about the mass psychology of the market. But technical analysis is certainly not the only method an investor should use. Checking market psychology before buying or selling--decisions that take into account fundamental and econometric factors--seems reasonable to us.<p>But the limitations of technical analysis are not why investors should reject most technical-analysis software. The problem is that most of it is useless to an investor who hasn't made a life's study of the field. What good is it to graph a stock using 80 indicators without understanding any of them? We're convinced that there are so many technical-analysis programs on the market because crunching large quantities of numbers and turning them into endless pretty graphs is exactly what computers are best at.<p>But we did find an exception--Equis International's MetaStock. It's not only one of the most powerful technical-analysis programs we ran, it is also the only one that might actually teach an investor how to use the methodology. MetaStock is scarily large--it eats a lot of memory--and expensive. The core program isn't cheap at $349 for the least expensive version. Add-on programs--Downloader ($195), Pulse ($249), and Technician ($249)--are each as large as any other whole program we tested. The Downloader is the only add-on most investors need to consider.<p>For once, all this power has made a program easy to use. MetaStock's tutorial will have a novice up and running in about four hours. A help feature tells an investor what the 80 predefined indicators that come with this program mean. But MetaStock is not merely for the novice. Users can track moving averages and draw trend lines for individual stocks or groups of stocks, such as all airline stocks. The program can apply any of the standard technical indicators or use one that an investor has created. The explorer feature can search the stock database for investment candidates. A test feature lets the user back-test any system he has designed to see how it would have done in the past.<p>Hindsight may be 20/20, but even so, it's rarely this clear. We decided to graph Merck's recent performance. The picture clearly shows how, from the end of 1992 to August of 1993, it sank from $45 to just below $30. Since then, it's bounced back to $35. The graph also shows that most of this retracing has occurred without any increase in volume. Running the momentum and the moving-average convergence/divergence indicators shows that this stock is currently in a mild upswing. Certainly nothing in these indicators makes the stock a screaming buy now, but an investor who had fundamental reasons for liking the stock would know that the current price is reasonable.<p>The Downloader can fetch price data by modem from CompuServe. Membership in the MetaStock Quote Club--$9.95 a month--gives an investor an 80 percent discount on historical quotes. Of the products that we tested that promised simple downloading from an on-line service, this was one of only two (WealthBuilder was the other) that worked without a glitch.<p>WHAT YOU'LL NEED:
--Software: MetaStock
--Time Commitment: Time to install: 30 minutes. Time to get up to speed: Four hours
--Technical Requirements: No use skimping on the memory or the power here: This needs an IBM 386 (a 486 would make life easier, as would a math coprocessor). Worth recommends 2 megabytes of memory and EGA, VGA, or higher graphics. Get a fast modem (9,600 baud) for updating data. Product comes on both 3.5- and 5.25-inch disks. Help line (801-265-9998) available 10 A.M.-7 P.M. (EST), M-F. 
--Costs: MetaStock comes in two versions--it's $349 for the one that uses end-of-day prices and $495 for MetaStock RT, which uses real-time prices. The Downloader costs $195 for a version that will use multiple data feeds. A version that will work with just one feed (Dial/Data) sells for only $69.
--How To Order: Equis International Inc., 801-265-8886<p>
STEP 7: Knowing Your Limits
If, for $3,000, you can have access to all the information and all the processing power of a Wall Street professional, does that mean you'll automatically become an invincible trader? Sorry, it doesn't work that way. Better access to information doesn't necessarily produce better results. No matter how many megabytes you have sitting on your desk, technology will never take the place of brains, guts, and intuition <p>Nothing better illustrates the promise--or the limitations--of computerized investing than Telescan Analyzer. This is the most comprehensive product we tested. A Telescan user has tools to match any Wall Street broker. The product itself isn't expensive at the moment--Telescan is offering it for $12.75 in shipping--but on-line charges run $45 a month, even if you don't sign on until after 8 p.m.<p>Telescan provides both fundamental and technical data --more than 200 variables and screens in all, and an investor can use up to 40 of them simultaneously. Want to find technology stocks with strong cash flow, rapid projected earnings growth, and a recent price breakout? Telescan will provide a list ranked in descending order of attractiveness.<p>Retrieve news items from Reuters, UPI, the Business Wire, and more. Get S&P company reports and S&P MarketScope, which includes features such as "Touted on TV," complete with the latest sputterings of Wall Street Week, Dan Dorfman, et al. Or call up sample issues of 22 newsletters. An investor can even find complete insider-trading filings. Getting quotes, of course, is a snap, and a one-page screen in "Special Reports" provides a technical snapshot of almost any stock. <p>But the software won't tell an investor what to do with all this information. In fact, the glut of available data makes it even more imperative that an investor have a well thought-out and tested system. Otherwise, it's easy to imagine drowning in a sea of prices, services, opinions, and analytical tools.<p>Say you want to use Telescan Analyzer to research chip-maker Intel. You discover that Intel's price-to-earnings ratio has shown wide volatility in the past. Pull-down menus instantly deliver analysts' projections on future earnings. You can analyze fundamentals, such as profit margin, or look at 80 indicators that search for patterns in the movement of the stock's price. In fact, there are almost no practical limits on what you can find out about this stock--except for what it all means. <p>So before you dive in, subject yourself to a brief self-examination. It doesn't require fancy equipment, just a pencil and paper. Write down your top three financial goals and the time frame for each. Summarize your philosophy for picking an investment in a single paragraph. List the three most important rules for buying an investment, and then write down one rule for when to sell.<p>If you can't do these things, read, take classes, talk to more experienced investors, run a mock portfolio, and research why the stocks in it go up and down. Above all, remember that perhaps the only thing that's more dangerous than a little knowledge is an investor who thinks that wisdom comes in the box along with the software.<p>WHAT YOU'LL NEED:
--Software: Telescan Analyzer
--Time Commitment: Time to install: 30 minutes. Time to get up to speed: Four to eight hours.
--Technical Requirements: Worth recommends an IBM 386 or better with 2 megabytes of memory, a hard disk, and an EGA, VGA, or higher graphics card. A 1,200-baud  Hayes-compatible modem is required (though we recommend 9,600 baud). Product comes on both 3.5- and 5.25-inch disks. Help line (800-324-4692) available 8-midnight (CST) M-F and 9-6 weekends.
--Costs: The software is currently available for $12.75 in shipping and handling. The data service costs $45 a month for unlimited nonprime time use or 41 cents a minute nonprime and 94 cents a minute prime time. 
--How To Order: Telescan, Inc., 800-324-8246. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing, Investing Strategies, Technology Industry

