<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Star of the Screen</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Star of the Screen</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
For years, Eddie Trieber thought he was programmed to lose money. Then he learned to trust a computer.<p>By Curtis Lang<p>This is a belief system," says Eddie Trieber, practicing psychologist, attorney-at-law, and electronic investor, peering deeply into the screen of his <a name="NASD:GATE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16706"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gateway</b></a> 486 late one night. He's describing the sheer number-crunching power at his fingertips. "How else are you going to explain risking $10,000 on a couple of squiggly lines on a screen?" <p>Thanks to the numbers and graphs that march across his screen, in 1993 Trieber was up 28 percent, about 10 points better than  the Wall Street pros he hires to manage the majority of his portfolio. But don't think that his computer made him a genius overnight. It took years of hard work and spending too much money on courses, videotapes, investment newsletters, and hot lines before Trieber arrived at his disciplined computerized trading system. His story is a salutary lesson in the power and limitations of computerized investing. <p>"I love trading," Trieber says. "It's a challenge. There is a kind of self-discovery that goes on. It affords some sense of mastery over something that's essentially out of your control. I've got money in the stock market, and I want to feel like I have some relationship to how it's doing. The only way I can do that is with information."<p>Trieber spends an average of ten hours a week analyzing the stock and bond markets. He has systems at his Manhattan home, at the Greenwich Village office where he runs a private psychology practice, and at his Wall Street office, where he consults for corporations interested in enhancing employee performance. All day long, stock quotes come in on a 15-minute delay from Signal, a widely used quote service. At home each night, Trieber inputs the hourly Dow price data by hand into his system, a custom he carries over from the days when real-time data was extremely expensive. He downloads end-of-day information from another quote service, Dial/Data, which takes about ten minutes. <p>Then the real work of stock picking begins. Trieber begins by running through his database, which contains several hundred stocks and bonds and the indexes he follows. He applies nine screens, both to individual stocks and bonds and to representative market sectors and various indexes, between 80 and 100 times in all. "I like to look at the averages," he says, "but I also look at the stocks that make up the averages."<p>His two favorite analytic tools are MetaStock, which analyzes market trends, and TechniFilter Plus, which searches his database for the buy and sell signals he has programmed into his system. <p>When the system's working, it kicks out potential buys like <a name="OTC:WWTK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15134"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> Weitek Corp.</b></a>, one of Trieber's most successful plays of 1993. At the end of 1992, Weitek, which makes accelerators, processors, and controllers for <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> PCs and <a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a> workstations, was down $1.42 a share for the year. Trieber decided to look at the stock  when it got a recommendation in one of the newsletters he reads.<p>A lot of investors might have decided to make an iffy buy like Weitek based on that mention alone. Trieber went with what his computer told him. When he took a look at the stock in May 1993, he focused first on price patterns and trading ranges. Graphing Weitek's price movement on MetaStock, he noticed that the stock, which had been languishing at around $7 a share, had recently moved up. Then, still using MetaStock, Trieber applied one of his favorite indicators of stock-price momentum, moving average convergence/divergence (MACD), a screen that measures the rate of change of stock prices. <p>When he ran the stock's price history through that indicator, he liked what he saw. "It broke out of its trading range, came back to the breakout point, and then you got a fresh buy signal," indicating a second attempt to move up, Trieber says. He bought the stock at $7.13, assuming that he'd sell in a few months. After starting to get sell signals from the MACD, Trieber sold out on August 17 at $12.50. The stock topped out at $14.38 in mid-September. Recently, it traded at $8.68. <p>Trieber wasn't always such a successful or disciplined investor. In fact, before he discovered the PC in 1986, he regularly lost money in the stock market. He's convinced that he was psychologically programmed to lose. "It started when I was about eight years old," Trieber says.<p>Trieber's father ran a service station in the Bronx. In his family, his mother always handled the family finances. Her forays into the stock market ended woefully; despite the fact that she invested early in such eventual winners as Texas Instruments, she wound up constantly losing money. Her broker regularly churned her account, leaving her with less and less money and leaving Trieber with a lingering feeling that he had to make up for her bad luck.<p>Trieber himself started investing with just $2,000 in 1966, allowing his broker to pick stocks for him for the next four years. "I was convinced I'd lose money, actually," Trieber says. "Just like Mom." But he didn't realize this consciously until a broker pointed it out to him in 1970. The broker, who was racking up small gains for Trieber, told his client that he had a nervous habit of selling too quickly or, more often, too late. It was as if Trieber expected to lose and thus set himself up for failure. The observation rang true to Trieber and angered him. "My mother lost money, so I was determined to make it back," he says.<p>In 1980, Trieber, then 34, began trading intuitively. Unfortunately, his gut feelings tended to produce nauseating drops in the value of his portfolio. For the next five years, he lost $5,000 to $10,000 annually. One year he even speculated on commodities. Three months later, he was down $36,000. By the mid-1980s, he finally decided he needed help. His emotions were getting in the way of his ability to trade wisely, so he turned over the bulk of his portfolio to professional managers. The smaller portion of his portfolio he would manage himself.<p>Around this time, Trieber got to know Gerald Appel through a psychological association that both belonged to. Appel had published articles on the technical analysis of bonds and was developing a system for trading mutual funds. He introduced Trieber to technical analysis and became the first of his instructors on investing. "You develop a system and you follow it rigorously," says Trieber. "I learned that from Jerry."<p>Eight years later, Trieber has come a long way from the days when he constantly panicked himself into bad trades. He still subscribes to numerous investment newsletters and hot lines, and he still takes courses on investing -- not in an effort to discover a new system but out of a desire to hone the one that works so well for him. "I think that people should learn certain basic tools and use them over and over before they go and learn something else," he says. He's also aware that his computer can offer too much of a good thing. "The mistake most people make is they use too many indicators" in an effort to validate their buy and sell decisions, Trieber says. "This is very personal. Everybody has to find their own way."<p>That doesn't mean that Trieber goes it alone, however. Early every morning he calls one of his brokers, Seymour Teman of Bear, Stearns, to compare notes and chart a daily trading strategy. <p>Pretty sophisticated for an investor once programmed to fail.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Sotck Investing Strategies

