	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Burned Alive</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Burned Alive</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Seduced by get-rich-quick promises, investors once again are flocking into the volatile world of commodities trading. Heres why most will get...<p>By Scott McMurray<p>The thousands of years in which humankind has speculated in commodities should have (but havent) produced a rule that goes something like this: If it trades in a pit, forget it. As far as ordinary investors are concerned, commodities futures are a losing proposition. The odds of being one of the few who do make a bundle are just too ridiculous. Commodities are the stuff of the investment worlds original less-than-zero-sum game. Think of it this way:  If a futures market consisted of just two traders, one going long against the others shorts, eventually both would end up broke.<p>Unless, of course, fresh money gets thrown into the pit. And that, folks, as Ross Perot might put it, is where you come in.<p>Commodities markets are curious and arcane places. Most people with an interest in money have at least heard about them as arenas where high-stakes bidding takes place over relatively mundane things like wheat, heating oil, pork bellies, and money itself, in the form of contracts to purchase foreign currency or Treasury bonds. Professional commodity traders stand on the steps of pits where the action resembles the inside of a popcorn machine. The traders yell and signal to one another to buy or sell contracts. The contracts set delivery of the commodities for a future date, which is why commodities are also known as futures. <p>Beyond that, however, outsiders often have a great deal of difficulty grasping exactly how these markets operate. In some ways, thats a good thing, because it stops a lot of people from ever even trying to trade commodities in the first place. Others, however, just cant resist the urge. The lure of huge profits or the desire to play with the big boys eventually draws them in. <p>Today, there are three ways individuals can venture into the futures markets. They can use a discount broker, hire a manager to handle their account, or buy into one of several types of pooled funds offered by the big financial-services companies. Which vehicle investors choose essentially depends on whether they prefer quick and dramatic losses or a slower chipping away at their principal. 
Currently, financial marketers are touting the so-called managed commodities (or futures) accounts and fundsthe trendiest way to invest in futuresas the hot new way to get roasted in the markets. They dont say this, of course. They call it the undiscovered investment of the decade. The occasion is the prospect of the first sustained boom in commodities since the early 1980s.<p>This boom has occurred because many investors now believe that the easy money in stocks has already been made, or they have grown impatient with the plodding action in the bond market. So they are increasingly turning to commodities, which at least promise some excitement. Example: In November of 1992, when Dean Witter, Discover & Co. opened its Select Futures fund to new investors, the brokerage firms marketing people thought they might raise as much as $100 million in three months. Five days later, the fund had hauled in $115 million. Over the past three years, the amount of money entrusted to managed futures accounts and funds has nearly doubled, to $25 billion. Managed futures funds hardly pose a threat to the U.S. stock market, capitalized at $4 trillion-plus, but, says Patrick Arbor, chairman of the Chicago Board of Trade, Weve barely scratched the surface in terms of the potential growth for managed futures. <p>The growth is taking place despite the dismal track record such funds have had in the past. A few publicly held futures funds were organized in the early 1980s; most lost money and closed, and those that survived have barely hung on. Four public funds started by Thomson McKinnon between March 1979 and December 1982 began trading with total assets of $20.3 million. By the end of last year, losses, commissions, and investor withdrawals had reduced the figure to $1.5 million. <p>Fresh money, however, obviously doesnt pay much attention to history. Some of it is coming from people who think of themselves as investors and are hoping to hedge their securities portfolios. Their thinking goes something like this: Since commodities tend to rise in price when the securities markets fall and vice versa, why not balance their stock portfolios with a futures fund? If inflation jitters push stocks down, commodities will rise because they are among the costs that create consumer price inflation. The problem is that its really not possible to consider yourself an investor and be a player in the commodities markets at the same time. Hedging rationales aside, playing the futures game ultimately boils down to a short-term bet on the direction of prices, up or down. That, by definition, makes anyone who joins the game a speculator, not an investor. <p>DO-IT-YOURSELF LOSSES<p>Dentists may be able to pick the winners among toothpastes, but four out of five dentists in the futures markets get pasted themselves. Most doctors also lose money, and so do lawyers, accountants, architects, self-employed businessmen, farmers, and pensioners. It doesnt matter a whit how successfully they have invested in securities or real estate. Even professional commodities brokers and fund managers will tell you its a suckers game.<p>This is not to say that the government should shut down the commodities markets tomorrow on the grounds that they serve no purpose other than to make their own members rich. The commodities markets play an important, even critical, role in the marketplace, and even speculation in commodities has usually served useful economic ends. For users and dealers in goods as diverse as soybeans, copper, gold, lumber, sunflower seeds, and cash, buying or selling their goods for future delivery permits them to stabilize costs. The gains or losses on their futures contracts offset their gains or losses on the physical commodities they own or will need to buy. Their transaction costs amount to an insurance, or hedging, premium. Speculators provide the grease that helps make these markets work. They help make the hedging possible by taking some of the risk that hedgers wish to eliminate. Far from being an evil, the risk in speculation is the reason for its existence.<p>The risk, however, isnt something that an investor with any instinct for self-preservation should want to take on. Our own numbers show that 90 percent of individual futures traders eventually lose money, says John Frawley Jr., president of ML Futures Investment Partners, a subsidiary of <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, the nations largest brokerage firm. Its not a pretty picture. <p>Discount brokers who earn much of their income from individual commodities speculators, and therefore have an interest in getting individuals to speculate, share this bleak view. Nine out of ten discount customers in the industry lose money, says Steven Greenberg, president of Alaron Trading Corp. Its very unfortunate. William Mallers Jr., president of the Chicago futures-trading firm First American Discount Corp., says 80 percent to 90 percent of his firms 9,400 customers have lost money trading futures, and they keep losing it. Our customers are mostly hobbyists, says Mallers. They almost ask for these odds.<p>But wait: If there is a winner and loser on each side of a trade in the commodities game, then why arent the odds more like one to one?<p>The answer:  Transaction costs. These are commissions, largely, and they keep the odds in the houses favor. Futures contracts expire and new contracts begin trading every few months; new contracts generate fresh commissions. The market is inherently volatile, and traders have to buy or sell frequently in order to cut losses or realize gains. If a broker is trading an account for a customer, regulators dont consider that the account has been churnedexcessively traded to generate commissionsunless the commissions reach about 18 percent a month of the customers equity. At that rate a customers cash can easily disappear within six months.<p>Commissions take such a huge bite that they can neutralize even a big gain. Last November, for instance, First American Discounts futures customers appeared to have had a great month, trading for an overall gain of $1,041,292 on 28,353 contracts. Before commissions, that is. After commissions, which averaged about $25 per contract, plus other transaction fees and surcharges, the original gain shrank by 76 percent, to $248,768. And First American is a discount broker. At a full-service firm, the commission bite could have run 50 percent to 100 percent higher, in which case the investors would have taken a loss, despite their remarkable success on their trades.<p>If commissions alone dont kill you, leverage will. Futures trading requires sufficient equity to make good-faith deposits of 2 percent or 3 percent up to 15 percent of the value of a contract. Futures exchanges set this requirement in the expectation that it will cover at least a single days change in the value of the contract. In contracts for pork belliesuncured baconthe required deposit is a fixed amount per contract that works out to about 4 percent of the price. Thats a leverage ratio of 25 to 1. Thus, should the underlying commoditys price drop 4 percentsomething that might happen in the course of a normal days tradingthe speculators margin could be wiped out. On the other hand, a 4 percent price jump would double that equity. <p>So who risks these odds? The typical amateur tends to be an investor who has made some money in securities and real estate and decides to put some money in futures, say $50,000. The investor finds the leverage appealing, thinking of it as a tool that could provide huge profits very quickly. The following scenario is hypothetical but hardly atypical:<p>Our speculator isnt necessarily unsophisticated. He has studied several price charts and decided the trends are pretty obvious; no need to pay someone for no-brainer research, so he opens an account with a discount broker and buys 50 pork belly contracts on margin for $1,000 each. Each contract is for 40,000 pounds of uncured bacon. At 55 cents a pound, the contracts are worth $22,000 each, a total value of $1.1 million in contracts secured by his $50,000 equity on deposit.<p>Within minutes of his buying, prices in the pits begin to diverge from the path his charting signaled, and pork bellies end the day down their daily limit of two cents a pound. The bullish trend seems to have ended. Why? Nobody knows for sure. There are rumors that the government has underestimated the number of hogs being readied for slaughter; that, of course, would increase the supply of bacon and bring the price down. Should our speculator sweat two cents a pound? After all, he held on to his real estate for two years before it paid off. But this is different. That two cents a pound means that each contract is now worth $21,200$800 less than at the beginning of the day. Since he owns 50 of these contracts, hes out $40,000. At this point, it would be unwise for our investor to hold his position; another two-cent drop at the opening the next day would wipe him out. So he sells his contracts at the close, paying $1,000 in commissions. His original $50,000 stake has been chopped down to $9,000. All this between 8:45 a.m. and 1 p.m., trading hours in the pork belly pit.<p>Back at his charts, our speculator wonders how he could have been so stupid. Clearly, last weeks chart showed a head-and-shoulders pattern he should have seen before, signaling a turn that he should have waited out. Two days later, convinced that the upward trend has resumed, he buys nine contracts with his $9,000. Again, for reasons that seem hazy, the market plunges and closes down the limit. After a trading loss of $7,200 and commissions of $225, he is now down to $1,575. Of course, if he had instead decided to hold on to his original losing position, he would have been required to deposit $30,000 in additional margin, increasing his potential loss to $80,000.<p>These are very unforgiving markets, says Patrick Arbor. Failure is punished, and punished severely.<p>CANT ANYONE HERE PLAY THIS GAME?<p>Even casual readers of the business press have heard of the megastars of the futures game, traders such as Paul Tudor Jones, John W. Henry, and Monroe Trout. These are the bright lights who have spun fabulous fortunes out of paper-thin margins. So some investors inevitably conclude that the real trick to playing the commodities game is to put their money in the hands of one of these guys. Sound good? <p>One small problem: They probably dont want anything to do with you. Jones and Trout havent taken on any new accounts in a while. Henry will let you in the door, but only if you are willing to risk $1 million of your equity. And then theres a second drawback to professional management, and it makes the first one actually look pretty good: Most professionals cant beat the futures markets over the long term. According to Martin J. Gruber, a New York University finance professor and analyst of the futures markets, a study of past data suggests that at any given time no more than a few dozen of the industrys 2,500 commodities-trading advisors can be expected to have managed a series of consistently winning trades. A trader may have a hot hand for a while and may attract scads of new cash, but sooner or later, the phenomenon of regression to the mean rears its ugly head; the high performers winning streaks turn to averageor worseand new investors feel as if theyve been taken. <p>Take the case of Richard Dennis, the erstwhile mega-trading legend of Chicago. He started with several thousand dollars in the mid-1970s. Within a decade, he was worth nearly $200 million. By 1984, he was so convinced that he had figured out the commodities markets that he began teaching his techniques to neophyte traders, dubbed turtles by their rivals in the pits. <p>In retrospect, one thing can be said for Dennis: He was a great teacher. Among advisors with more than $10 million under management last year, the three top performers were all Dennis protgs. But Denniss own fortunes began to turn in late 1987. By early 1988, two of his funds had taken sickening plunges, losing more than $50 million, or nearly 50 percent of his investors money. After settling investor lawsuits against him for reckless trading, Dennis started trading for customers again in 1991. He had a 42.6 percent gain that year, according to Managed Account Reports, a service that tracks managed futures accounts. Between March and August of 1992, however, the customers money dwindled to $40.5 million from $86.5 million. Then, according to people in the futures business, a large corporate investor withdrew from a Dennis fund. By the end of September 1992, Denniss funds under management amounted to only $2 million, and he ranked 275th out of 284 trading advisors whose performance was tracked by Managed Account Reports.<p>Last year, he recovered somewhat, but only after making his clients swoon. By the end of May, he was reduced to trading just $84,000 in customer money. He ended the year with $261,000 in customer money under management. <p>Robert Kogen, president of L. Lawrence Products, a manufacturer of eyeglass and earring accessories in Huntingdon Valley, Pennsylvania, says he lost all of the $10,000 he invested in a Dennis fund in 1988. I knew that futures can be treacherous and volatile, he says. The appeal was that Dennis supposedly had a system that allowed him to limit the downside and maximize the upside. That turned out not to be the case. Kogen has now sworn off futures.<p>LISTENING TO MOMS<p>Are there people with foolproof trading systems? Not exactly, though consistently successful advisors do share one trait: They manage cash as if it were the rarest of commodities, rarely risking more than 20 percent of their customers money at a time and keeping the balance in Treasury bills or other cash equivalents. As a rule, responsible advisors wont chance more than 1 percent of the total they manage in a single position; the less money they leave on the table, the longer they stay in the game. <p>Among the 2,500 trading advisors around, many accept accounts in the $10,000-to-$25,000 range. Most of the established advisors charge management fees of 2 percent to 6 percent of account assets a year, plus 15 percent to 20 percent of quarterly profits, if any. Customers also pay commissions, usually somewhat above the rate charged by discount brokers. To attract customers, however, some managers of small accounts waive a management fee.<p>A firm called Alaron is typical of the industry. Housed in cramped offices above Chicagos Lyric Opera, the firm made its name by specializing in pork belly futures. It is run by two brothers and a sister, Steven, Michael, and Carrie Greenberg, who virtually grew up with pork bellies. Their father, Joel, has traded them for more than 25 years, and he used to talk bellies with the kids around their Winnetka, Illinois, dinner table and hold mock trading sessions in the family hot tub. Steven Greenbergs trader-identification code, which appears on the badge that admits him to the pit at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, is oink. Last year, it should have read ouch.<p>In less than two weeks last July, the equity in Alarons customers accounts swooned by 57 percent. The Greenbergs had made a huge bet that pork belly prices would fall last summer and sold the futures. When pork belly prices rose instead, several months worth of trading profits were wiped out.<p>The Greenbergs say they learned their lesson. They changed their trading strategies, mainly by expanding their activities in markets other than pork bellies. They also hired a professional meat-industry analyst to help them. A late year-end rally allowed them to recoup customer losses. <p>In a field where even pros like the Greenbergs suffer staggering losses, there is obviously no science to picking a reliable advisor. Nonetheless, the industry wants to help you. Just find yourself a MOMa manager of managers. MOMs provide a variety of accounting, administrative, and other services to traders and advisors. Three such MOMs are Kenmar Advisory Corp. of New York, Rand Financial Servicesa wholly owned subsidiary of Monroe Trouts trading fundand Peters Capital Management of Chicago. Firms like these analyze customers risk tolerance and other characteristics in order to match them with compatible traders. Esther Eckerling Goodman, senior executive vice president of Kenmar, concedes that this process can be hit-or-miss. As an industry, she says, we need to do a better job at predicting future performance based on past results. This is a tough job, considering the unreliability of past results.<p>John Welsh, senior vice president at Rand Financial, educates smaller customers about the risk of losing all their money. As a MOM, he tells them not to put more than 10 percent to 15 percent of their investable assets into futures. Then, if theyre still game, he often encourages them to consider one of the smaller managers that Rand tracks. <p>Fundamental Trading is such a firm, one that Welsh identifies as a rising star. On the 14th floor above the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, Jeffrey Kaplan, Fundamentals sole proprietor, keeps an office on one side of a hallway leading to another traders office. He shares a desk in the hallway with two other futures traders.<p>Kaplan, 41, has the gravelly voice of a trader who paid his dues on the Merc trading floor shouting out orders. After 13 years there, a ruptured spinal disc, and a broken marriage, he gave up the pits in 1991 to go upstairs to trade via video screen and telephone (in the securities and commodities markets, traders off the floors and out of the pits are always upstairs, even if they work in a basement). Rand Financial processes his trades and brings him retail customers.
Welsh is high on Fundamental because Kaplan follows one of his favorite maxims: Plan your trades and trade your plan. As the name of his company suggests, Kaplan makes most of his trading decisions based on whats known as fundamental news, ranging from government crop reports to central bank actions to raise or lower interest rates, as opposed to following or trying to anticipate price trends in markets. Last year, assets in Kaplans managed accounts rose by 73 percent; in 1992, they were up 24.5 percent. But a review of Kaplans disclosure document, sent to all customers, shows how rocky the going was. Kaplans accounts were down roughly 60 percent for the year at the end of March, following sizable back-to-back monthly losses. He quickly rebounded and had accounts back to where they had started the year by June.<p>Most of the percentage gains in Kaplans accounts over the past two years came from trading less than $100,000 in customer funds. Additional customers, some provided by Rand and others attracted by Kaplan, boosted the end-of-1993 equity in customer accounts to more than $1 million. Welsh makes no apologies for steering small customers to small traders. Everybody wishes he wouldve put money with Paul Tudor Jones when he was just getting started, Welsh says. Besides, he observes, its a futures-market truism that traders tend to have their best years when they are managing relatively small amounts of money.<p>WALL STREETS ANSWER<p>For as little as $5,000, any one of wall Streets leading financial packagers can put investors in a managed public futures fund, technically a limited partnership. Interests in these partnerships are pooled and placed with one or more professional managers. The partnership structure limits the risk to the money a partner has invested; hell get no margin calls. (Many funds are liquidated automatically if total equity drops to 50 percent of the initial amount placed in the fund.) Another popular type of fund, called a guarantee fund, aims to ensure that investors will at least get their money back.
Sound good? Maybe so, if your idea of fun is to read through mind-numbing disclosure documents that may run 200 pages long. I dont see how any investor can make an informed decision [after reading disclosure documents], says Michael Harkins, a principal at Peters Capital Management, a manager of managers. Its almost as if the government is encouraging public customers to open their own account and speculate in futures.<p>But its not just the disclosure documents that may prove daunting. Wall Streets version of one-stop futures shopping is not cheap. After paying brokerage, management, and incentive fees, investors in the Dean Witter Select Futures Fund, for instance, need to make 12.16 percent a year just to break even. That doesnt count redemption charges of 3 percent, 2 percent, or 1 percent for customers yanking their money out after one year, a year and a half, or two years with the fund.<p>Even though managed futures funds now carry much lower expenses than they did a decade agoyearly charges of 19 percent and 20 percent characterized many of the early fundsthe average futures fund is nonetheless a substandard investment vehicle. Public funds have produced an average annual return of about 9 percent since mid-1984, according to an index of public funds tracked by Managed Account Reports. The Dow Jones Industrial Average, by comparison, has averaged 17.7 percent a year since then, according to Lipper Analytical Services in New York.<p>About three fourths of the futures-fund expenses goes straight to the brokerage houses. Dean Witter Select Futures lets brokerage commissions take as much as three fourths of 1 percent of fund assets a month, or 9 percent a year. This money doesnt leave the Dean Witter fold. The general partner and operator of the Select Futures fundand all Dean Witter fundsis Demeter Management Corp., a subsidiary of Dean Witter, Discover & Co. It pays commissions directly to Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., the broker subsidiary of the parent. Through mid-1993, the fund had generated $10.8 million in commissions and other transaction fees for Dean Witter Reynolds.<p>Like other broker-sponsored funds, the Dean Witter fund acknowledges this and other conflicts of interest, noting in its prospectus: Because both the General Partner and DWR are subsidiaries of the same parent entity, DWRs brokerage commissions outlined above have not been agreed upon in arms-length negotiations. A few pages later the prospectus even points out that most brokerage customers with more than $1 million in assets pay commissions at negotiated rates which are substantially less than the rate paid by the [fund]. To defend such lucrativeand completely legal self-dealing, the prospectus argues that Dean Witter isnt as bad as some of the brokerage firms out there: The General Partner believes that the brokerage commissions charged the partnership are less than the brokerage rates charged certain other public commodity pools.<p>Still, the Dean Witter fees are a bit rich, at least compared with newer public funds. Merrill Lynchs Global Horizons fund, launched in January, charges 7.5 percent a year for commissions. (In return for lower upfront commissions, however, ML Futures Investment Partners gets a share of profits.) Merrill Lynch estimates that the fund still needs to make 10.4 percent in the first year to break even, excluding early-redemption charges, according to the prospectus. Merrill Lynch officials said they couldnt comment on the fund beyond whats included in the prospectus because it remains open for investment.<p>The balance of the annual charges to the Dean Witter fund are about average for recent futures funds. They consist of a 3 percent annual management fee paid to the advisors trading for the fund and 17.5 percent quarterly incentive fees paid to the advisors out of profits, if any, earned in the quarter. Dean Witter is a respected player in the futures-fund business, but the aggregate return after expenses of 13 of its funds last year, including the Select Futures fund, was 5.5 percent, according to figures given to Managed Account Reports.<p>For every Select Futures fund that does well, there are such clunkers as Dean Witters Principal Guaranteed Fund. As its name implies, the guaranteed fundand dozens like it offered by other brokeragespromised that investors would at least get their money back at the end of a certain period, usually five years. The principal-protection feature has made guaranteed funds hot sellers. When the Principal Guaranteed fund was offered in September 1988, it raised what was at that time a record $252 million.<p>Guaranteeing that principal will be protected is no guarantee that a fund will make much money. The Dean Witter fund couldnt even keep up with anemic money market rates, producing a paltry 0.8 percent annual return. As a result, investors had yanked all but about $30 million out of the fund by the time it matured last September and stopped trading as a guaranteed fund. <p>Then there is Prudential Securities Aggressive Growth futures fund. When it was being put together last year, the fund must have looked like an odds-on winner. Its two advisors, Colorado Commodities Management of Boulder and Chicagos Sj Inc. (pronounced show), were respected advisors with enviable records. Yet the Prudential fund began sinking almost from the beginning of trading last August. By year end it lost 18.2 percent. Colorado Commodities dismal performance accounted for most of the loss; a trading program in currency and financial futures lost 31 percent of its value, while Sj lost 3.5 percent in its foreign financial futures program. <p>Colorado Commodities was caught betting that the yen would rise last August when the U.S. Federal Reserve began dumping the currency to bring it down and the dollar up. Colorado Commodities also wagered that the deutsche mark would rise. Then the Bundesbank lowered its discount rate, cheapening the mark against the dollar. Bad luck? In the commodities markets, its happening to somebody all the time.<p>The industry itself views the reemergence of managed futures as a historic development. Bristling at comparisons of the futures pits with gambling casinos, executives of futures exchanges and leading brokerages in Chicago and New York promote futures not as a speculative vehicle but as a means of diversifying stock and bond portfolios and lessening their volatilityand even as assets of a special class. <p>But the industry, which got its start in Chicago 150 years ago, still has some selling to do, even among the futures faithful. Im not sure our customers think of futures as just another asset class, says Mallers of First American Discount. Futures trading is a long shot, and people ought to trade it like its a long shot.<p>The idea of futures as an asset class is absurd on its face, says Andrew Davis, a former futures options trader and now president of Rock Island Securities, a Chicago brokerage firm. Thats like defining casino chips as an asset class."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
