<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-When Rates Go Up Again</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-When Rates Go Up Again</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
When we siad last year that interest rates were going to start rising, we didn't realize what an opportunity it would be.<p>By Robert Clark<p>With all the uncertainty and volatility in the securities markets, it's probably a good time to invest. Or buy a second home.<p>No, we're not taking our financial cues from Beavis and Butt-head. That's the message the market is delivering.<p>Normally, we would ignore such a message. This magazine takes a long view of investing. For most people, we believe, buying sound investments and holding them has proved to be the best strategy, no matter what the market and the many readers of its entrails seem to be saying at the moment. We deviated just a degree or two from the course last June. In an article called "When Rates Go Up, "we anticipated the interest-rate bump that finally struck this February and suggested what investors could do to prepare and even profit from the rise.<p>Rates will probably continue to rise, by 1 or 2 percentage points over the next year or so, boosting money market yields as high as 5 percent and long-term government bonds above 8 percent. What should investors do about it now?<p>Last June, we recommended conserving cash by keeping it out of long-term certificates of deposit or annuities, by borrowing for necessary big-ticket purchases such as washers and cars, by refinancing high-rate mortgage loans, and by not paying off low-rate mortgage loans early. For investors who haven't done those things already, there's still time, but it's running out.<p>More important, investors can manage their portfolios to exploit the high probability of additional interest-rate increases. Bonds still look like sells. Some stocks look like buys, at least on market dips. Real estate--housing, in particular--looks like the closest thing to a sure winner around. Those who thought that the 1980s housing market had died and gone forever are likely to be surprised by a historic resurrection. <p>Many investors have made large profits on bonds they bought in the past five years, when interest rates were exceptionally low. The market value of those bonds has already dropped with the rise in interest rates and yields. Because rising rates do more damage to the market value of long-term bonds than short-term bonds, it makes sense to sell 20-year or 30-year bonds and buy Treasury notes with maturities under three years. That will greatly lessen the risk of additional capital loss. By late February, the market value of 30-year Treasury bonds had dropped about a percentage point (or $100 on a $1,000 bond) from the 1993 high. Additional interest-rate increases will cause the market value of the bonds to fall further.<p>Profit-taking bond investors should consider putting cash into stocks instead of short-term fixed-income securities. But not necessarily right now; they should buy only on the sell-offs in the stock market that interest-rate increases will provoke. <p>All this presupposes continued economic recovery and a year or more of steady interest-rate increases, but allows for occasional inflation scares that verge on panics. Those are likely to be much more threatening than the one-day sell-off that excited the securities markets when the Federal Reserve Board raised short-term interest rates by a quarter of a point in February.<p>Fed chairman Alan Greenspan's goal is to keep inflation down without weakening the economy. To do both by manipulating interest rates and banking reserves has always been tricky, but it seems to work more or less satisfactorily from time to time. As long as Greenspan and his colleagues at the Fed are successful, corporate earnings should continue to improve. Higher earnings drive stock prices higher--unless unanticipated interest-rate increases knock them down. The stock market seemed to underreact to the Fed's first upward nudge in interest rates in February. Not only was the increase small, but it also had been widely anticipated. A second quarter-point rise has been widely anticipated as well. In the view of the market, inflation has been held at bay, a view that consumer price indexes have seemed to confirm.<p>Any threat to that view, such as renewed inflation or unanticipated interest-rate increases, should cause an overreaction. And such threats are bound to emerge. The consumer price index shows only where prices have gone, not where they're going. Forward-looking indicators, however, show the inflationary factors that will cause actual price increases later (if prices haven't already begun to move). In the fourth quarter of 1993, the economy grew at an annual rate of nearly 6 percent. For nine months running, consumer spending showed solid gains. In February, the Labor Department reported that hourly wages had risen at an annual rate of 8 percent. The proportion of the country's total manufacturing capacity that is being used--perhaps the most reliable pointer to inflation--nearly reached a 14-year high. As increasing demand for their goods forces manufacturers to rely on their less-efficient facilities, their costs--and prices--increase.<p>All told, the index of leading economic indicators took its largest jump in eight years. In fact, in a recent report economist Ed Hyman of the ISI Group noted 28 signs of a strengthening economy. <p>So could the economy overheat, encouraging inflation? With sharp increases in earnings and spending, prices rise. Lenders get repaid in cheapened dollars. To recoup their losses, they'll raise their borrowing rates. Because the biggest borrower of all is the U.S. government, sharply higher interest rates could wreck President Clinton's budget projections, worsen the already huge budget deficit, and once again invoke the early-1980s specter of printing-press government finance and an endless cycle of price increases and interest-rate increases.<p>That's exactly what the Fed is trying to prevent, of course, without snuffing out the recovery. As long as the economy grows, the inflationary potential will remain. Whenever the market becomes overly concerned with it, stock prices will fall. That should provide a buying opportunity for the bullish.<p>If history is any guide, interest rates will rise considerably above the level that the Fed and the bond markets already have set. James B. Stack, a Fed watcher and editor of the InvesTech Market Analyst, tracks Fed decisions and interest rates. In six of the past seven economic recoveries, he says, once the yield on one-year Treasury bills has bottomed and begun climbing (as it has now), short-term interest rates have risen by 2 percentage points within 18 months.<p>As rates move upward, prices on utility shares, which had declined steadily since August, will continue to weaken. Interest-rate increases particularly depress utilities because their share prices, largely determined by their dividend yields, make them move like bonds in the market. Prices on bank and brokerage shares and other stocks whose issuers are heavy borrowers will also weaken as interest costs rise. On the other hand, home builders, retailers, airlines, automobile manufacturers, and others will do well in an improving economy. Because rising interest rates make most investors jumpy, the portfolio dullards--stocks with high per-share earnings and book values--will be less volatile and thus less anxiety-producing than speculative growth stocks.<p>Real estate seems golden. Specialists in real estate predict a good market this spring. The prospect of higher interest rates may persuade buyers to buy sooner rather than wait. With about a six-year backlog on the market, the supply of housing won't vanish. That will continue to put pressure on sellers to keep prices affordable. All this makes the spring market the best buyer's market we're likely to see for a long while. Beyond that, when the housing supply finally shrinks, look for the biggest boom in housing prices since the mid-'80s.<p>Buyers: Don't panic, but buy soon. Sellers: You can afford to wait. Few home sellers will be able to resist the coming opportunity to unload. Those who do resist, like true contrarians, will reap the biggest gains.<p>Robert Clark is a senior editor at Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Investing Strategies, Bond Investing, Real Estate Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
