<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-New, Neutered Nature of Risk</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-New, Neutered Nature of Risk</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Dwindling returns on truly secure investments have blinded many of  us to the very real dangers of the markets.<p>By Justin Mamis<p>The language of investing, like the English language itself, changes perpetually. Just as Wall Street invents new products for investors to buy and sell, so do the titans of finance invent new words to describe them. <p>Creating words for newfangled Wall Street products is fine. Reinventing or redefining the vocabulary of investing--what's happening today--is not.<p>Particularly worrisome is the redefinition of one of the most basic of investment concepts: the nature of risk. Webster defines risk as "the possibility of loss or injury" or "to expose to hazard or danger." But today, the idea that an investor might actually lose on an investment has been modified by attractive thoughts of the enormous profits. Eager to justify their leaps into investments with greater potential for loss, investors have defanged or detoxified the nature of risk. <p>This often happens after a bull market is well under way. Citizens who previously--and correctly--viewed stocks as more risky investments than, say, bank savings accounts begin to alter their perceptions of risk. As stocks climb higher, they begin to look safer than they did previously. Savings accounts, meanwhile, may begin to look risky on the grounds of lost opportunity. A sure sign this is happening now is the widespread flight from federally backed investments, such as savings accounts and certificates of deposit, into noninsured investments like mutual funds.<p>It's critical to remember, however, that the thinking behind this trend is grounded partly in an illusion. Stocks are never as safe as savings accounts. The level of risk in an investment does not change from one market climate to another. The only thing that changes is the way people view risk. And today they're viewing it much more sanguinely than they should. <p>Think of it this way: Say you're driving on a highway at the 55 miles-per-hour speed limit and everyone around you is going 75. Although you may normally like to drive within the limits, because you know that it's safer to travel at slower speeds, you're likely to feel comfortable about speeding up. Why not? Everyone else is. You know what they say about safety in numbers--suddenly it seems safe to drive 75. <p>Psychologists have studied this behavior in children and adults; it is sometimes known as disinhibition. William Golden, a New York City psychologist and an assistant professor at New York Hospital's Cornell Medical College, counsels people on their approaches to money matters. Disinhibition, he explains, is an outgrowth of several human tendencies. <p>First is the intense need to conform. Golden cites a study in which a group of subjects was given two obviously different sets of lines and asked to identify which of the two were longer and which were shorter. In most cases, the subjects identified the short lines as the long ones when the other folks in the group did too. Says Golden: "We don't want to be different. We will even change reality in order to conform."<p>In the money world, this translates to: Everybody else is rushing into riskier venues. I will too, so I can conform.<p>Another factor that creates disinhibition is something called vicarious learning: If people are rewarded for a certain type of behavior, they will be able to influence many others to do the same thing. Although this is most often studied in children, it is commonly seen in adults. For example, well-behaved children who watched others act aggressively and badly had no trouble mimicking the antisocial behavior if they had witnessed a reward given to the children who did it first. Says Golden: "You see exact duplication of this in adults who invest. Vicarious learning increases the likelihood that others will exhibit the same behavior. "All my friends made money in risky stocks; I should invest in them, too. <p>Disinhibition in the investment world is especially troublesome because such changes in perception usually occur late in the game. That's the reason so many folks want to buy Compaq now that it's $88 a share, even though they rejected it at less than half that price in 1993. And it's why Argentina is now okay investment turf--not so much because of its improving economy, but because the economy of another south-of-the-border country--Mexico--has already soared. From this perspective, the Latin American defaults of less than ten years ago appear not as significant as the events of the last ten months.<p>In the late stages of a bull market, investors may even become numb to warnings of risk. The phrase "past performance is no guarantee of future results," for instance, loses its meaning--just as smokers learn to ignore the surgeon general's warning on cigarette packs. Suddenly, nobody cares to see what's buried in the fine print.<p>But there's a funny thing about markets: They're ongoing, evolving, ever changing. This is their nature, and it's the only thing we can be sure of about them. Obviously, those who invested early on in emerging markets such as Malaysia and Thailand have bagged their profits and deserve our admiration. But should those past gains drive new investors into these markets now?<p>There's nothing wrong with intelligent speculation. However, investments that used to be "more speculative" are now being viewed as "tolerably speculative" at just the time when the odds of losing on these investments are heightened. With so much investment money chasing so few companies and such a limited supply of shares, prices have already soared. When it's time for all these folks to sell, who's going to be buying? "Emerging" markets have been described by some as a large room with a very small door. <p>Where else has risk chameleoned into something safe? Electric-utilities stocks--traditional sources of decent dividend returns--are being pitched as risk-free. Here again, market life is never that simple. <p>Let's say a utility is trading around $20 a share and pays $2 a year in dividends, a yield of 5 percent. Sounds great. But what happens when interest rates go up and utility stocks drop? In just a few weeks last autumn the Dow Jones Utility Average slid more than 10 percent; so now your stock is selling for $18. You're still getting your 5 percent yield, of course, but the fact is, you've lost the equivalent of an entire year's income in the 10 percent decline. Sure, it's only a paper loss, but your net worth has declined and your capital has diminished, all for the sake of current return. <p>You can use semantics to pretend it's not a real loss, but consider this: Had your money stayed in CDs another year, yielding peanuts, and now you bought that utility stock at 18, your yield would have improved to 5.5 percent (not counting the 2 percent you would have earned on your CD). That's certainly better than pretending that you can't really lose by buying utility stocks.<p>Remember: What's safe hasn't changed its nature. Government bonds, bank CDs, insured savings accounts--all remain safe. The problem is they have become undesirable to investors who want higher yields than these investments currently provide. Investments don't change; investors' needs do. But just because your needs have changed doesn't mean that the definition of market risk has. Risk--the potential for loss--is a constant. Same as it ever was. <p>Justin Mamis is a senior vice president at Hancock Institutional Equity Services in New York City. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
