<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-The Futility of Chasing Insiders</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-The Futility of Chasing Insiders</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>Outsiders needn't panic when execs dump shares<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>Conventional wisdom says insiders know what they're doing when they buy and sell their company's shares. And individual investors pay close attention to the activities of insiders when they buy and sell stocks. <p>As it happens, the conventional wisdom is only partly right. Insiders often lose money on their own stocks, and their transactions can be very misleading. What's more, changes in executive compensation and in procedures for reporting insider transactions have made it harder for outsiders to interpret available data. As a result, investors should be choosy about which insider-trading data they watch. <p>Securities laws require officers, directors, and owners of more than 10 percent of a company's stock to file reports outlining their purchases and sales regularly. Transactions in one month must be reported to the SEC by the tenth of the next month. Press and on-line services disseminate these reports. Insider sales shown on these reports__called Form 4s__are ambiguous. Insiders, like most of us, buy securities that they hope will rise. Those who sell may be bears, or they could need cash or want to diversify a portfolios. <p>Insiders often make this claim. George Shirk, research analyst for the Insiders newsletter, says, "They'll tell you anything rather than say they feel the stock is heading down."<p>Insider moves are a less reliable indicator now than they used to be, thanks in part to the proliferation of option grants given to high-level executives. Selling shares acquired by option has become so routine that the trades have lost any value as a bearish signal. Melloan JFYI, Shirk mentioned that his newsletter rates companies based on the amount of insider trading, but they exclude gifts, private placements, and options trading. Executives seem to treat these options as paychecks rather than securities__and cash them accordingly. <p>The purchase of stock through the exercise of options may also be meaningless. "If an insider has the option to buy a stock at $4 a share when it is trading at $8, then it is a good business decision, not necessarily an indicator of where he feels the stock is going," says Shirk. <p>Even when it's clear that an insider has sold, it's not always clear when the sale took place. Consider the sales reported on SEC Form 144, which accounts for the disposition of restricted or privately issued stock. Although it cannot be resold publicly for two years, executives can dispose of their shares privately, at a discount from market value, in agreements with brokers. The brokers hold the shares until the waiting period has ended and then sell them publicly. Form 144 reports the sale but doesn't show when the executive got out and at what price. <p>Another problem with 144 reports: Insiders have up to 90 days to complete their sale. Outsiders are in the dark about the details.<p>Some insider transactions are more meaningful than others. Repeated sales or buys by many insiders usually are more significant than a single transaction. Microsoft's Bill Gates sold 2.6 million of his company's shares in 1992, for example, but he held on to more than 80 million shares, and the stock has risen since. On the other hand, when a slew of executives unload chunks of shares at once, take note. Such was the case last November with Spectrum Information Technology, a wireless-communications concern whose top dogs exercised more than half their options when exApple chairman John Sculley joined the firm. News of the options sale and an investigation into the stock's volatile trading patterns came out in January, and the stock tanked.<p>Before jumping to any conclusions about trading patterns, make sure the company involved isn't one such as Compaq Computer, a well-managed concern that allows insider transactions only within a limited time after quarterly financials are published. Such a rule makes transactions seem more concentrated and significant than they may be. And insider selling following a company's initial public offering may signal nothing more than an insider's need for cash after a start-up's lean years. <p>Keep in mind that insiders__honest ones, at least__are not short-term investors. The six-month rule on buying and selling requires them to hold at least that long. And their bargain-hunting instincts usually encourage insiders to buy early. Robert Gabele, president of CDA/ Investnet, a Fort Lauderdale information-service company that tracks insider trading, says it usually takes three to six months after big insider buying to have an effect on a company's stock. That gives outsiders time to investigate the company before they buy. And, remember, insider purchases in the public market at the public's price are one of the most bullish signs of all.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Stock Invsting Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

