	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Games Investors Shouldn't Play</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Games Investors Shouldn't Play</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>If a broker pitches one of these "strategies," say no <p>By Gerald Perritt<p>There's nothing like a long bull market to turn investing into fun and games. Many investors have done so well in recent years that they're allowing themselves to be talked into playing for thrills as well as money. Unless that's really what you want to do, here are some of the more dangerous games brokers are pushing today that you ought to be wary of:<p>COVERED-CALL WRITING<p>equipment: A portfolio of dividend-paying stocks. The stocks must have corresponding exchange-listed options.<p>object: To earn about 15 percent a year with little risk, in dividends and option premiums.<p>play: It begins with a pitch from a broker. He persuades you to write (or sell) call options against shares of stock you own. The buyer of the options pays you a premium for the right to purchase your shares at a fixed price--usually higher than where the market is currently trading--within the next three to nine months. If the value of your shares never rises to the purchase (or "strike") price, the options expire worthless, letting you hold on to your stock and earn additional income.<p>risks: Stocks that do rise sharply in price will be called away--that is, purchased by the options buyer--depriving you of most of the gain. If prices fall sharply, the loss will wipe out your premium income. In certain phases of a market, options become overvalued, rewarding those who play this game. Today is not one of these times. Over the long term, covered-call writing will produce mediocre returns. But don't expect your broker to volunteer that fact; he's likely to tell you of big returns in writing options. Most of these claims do not include the costs of commissions.<p>LEVERAGE<p>equipment: A margin account and a high tolerance for risk.<p>object: To get rich quick with little capital.<p>play:Start with $2,000 in equity in a margin account. Find a stock that is about to soar and buy it. As the value of your stock increases--called equity--buy more, sell at the peak, and repeat the process until you're rich as Croesus.<p>risks:This is a table-stakes game. If you buy a loser, your equity may be wiped out, forcing you to put up more money or leave the game. If you buy a stock that goes nowhere, you're still a loser because you must pay interest on the money you borrowed. Only if the stock rises quickly will margin work for you. <p>INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS<p>equipment: A full-service (full commission) broker whose firm underwrites hot issues and who feels compelled to do you a favor for all the business you've given him.<p>object: To get in on the ground floor of the next Snapple or <a name="NASD:SBUX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15745"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Starbucks</b></a>.<p>play: Buy as many shares as your broker can get you. Sell at the top, preferably hours after you bought them.<p>risks: It's not the next Snapple or Starbucks because if it was, the big institutions would have gotten there first. Overall long-term returns on new issues are mediocre. Three or more years after their initial public offering, fewer than one in six new issues has outperformed the market; nearly half have lost half their value. Only the big boys have a chance of getting sufficient shares in the few truly hot issues.<p>ACTIVE TRADING<p>equipment: Price and volume charts and a knowledge of technical trading terms.<p>object: To run up lots of small gains on volatile securities.<p>play: Trade frenetically.<p>risks: Recurring commission and other transaction costs erode winners' gains and magnify losers' losses. Even using a discount broker, a trader who turns over his portfolio three times a year will run up transaction costs of 6 percent  of his portfolio's value.<p>CLOSED-END-FUND IPOS<p>equipment: A full-service broker with a firm that underwrites closed-end funds.<p>object: Be the first on the block to own a new fund.<p>play: See IPOs. This game differs mainly in that 1) you can buy all the shares you want, but 2) you shouldn't. <p>risks: Prices on new issues of closed-end funds usually decline in the first 120 days after the offering. The offering price represents the value of the underlying portfolio securities in the fund plus underwriting fees and costs, including selling costs. Those costs amount to a new-issue premium that usually disappears within a few months. Better to wait until the premium has disappeared. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
