<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Back To Basic Industries</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Back To Basic Industries</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
These cyclical stocks may be ready to take off<p>By Robert W. Casey<p>For the next round of winners in cyclical stocks, look to basic industries--forest products, chemicals, and metals--and to energy. At this stage of the bull market and the economy's recovery, their time has come. <p>Don't dismiss the autos, yet, even though they always blossom early in a recovery. Auto stocks delivered back-to-back gains of 42 and 62 percent in 1992 and 1993 as the economy finally started to stir from its 1991 low point. Other cyclicals recover later.<p>Sector investing in cyclical stocks looks easier than it is. Business cycles vary notoriously in strength and duration, making timing even trickier than usual. Stock prices usually reflect the most predictable news. Still, there are some opportunities for investors with a medium-term time horizon. <p>Earnings estimates of securities analysts provide some clues on what to expect from cyclicals. Don't pay too much heed to individual company reports or industry roundups. In the aggregate numbers lies a clearer picture. <p>The people at Institutional Brokers Estimate System collect analysts' forecasts, providing useful consensus reports to Wall Street. According to IBES, aggregate forecasts for 1994 earnings growth among basic industries including forest products, chemicals and metals producers, which tend to be highly cyclical, come in at a strong 48 percent, up sharply from the group's 1993 earnings growth of 4 percent.<p>While IBES tracks consensus among analysts, it also tracks disagreement. In the perverse world of Wall Street, analysts' discord creates greater potential for gains than consensus does. When earnings estimates for a stock or industry group cluster close to the average figure, that signals a trend that stock prices already reflect. If estimates vary widely, stocks in the group are more likely to be undervalued or overvalued, creating opportunities for investors and traders. These are called earnings surprises.<p>So where do the greatest disagreements turn up where '94 earnings are concerned? The three leading sectors are energy, basic industries, and consumer durables. Reasons for the varying opinions differ. In consumer durables, analysts argue over whether or not the auto industry--which dominates the sector--will have another banner year. For basic industries and producers of metals and paper, the uncertainty over inflation in raw materials clouds their prospects. It's unclear whether these producers could raise their prices if inflation jumps.<p>Most interesting is the disagreement over energy-industry earnings. "There's usually a lot of divergence among analysts forecasting energy earnings, but this year it's even higher than normal," says Bill Quinn, an IBES analyst. "A good portion of that is just the uncertainty surrounding the price of oil itself."<p>That makes oil an outstanding bet for investors right now. So says Robin Shoemaker, an analyst at Lehman Brothers. His view is that the two-year-old slide in oil prices may soon end. The stock market, he says, is unrealistically skeptical of OPEC's ability to control oil production. But OPEC eventually will force price increases, benefiting U.S. companies such as <a name="NYSE:ARC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10142"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Atlantic Richfield</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:PZL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11164"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pennzoil</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:P"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11182"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Phillips Petroleum</b></a>. The domestic oils also make a good sector play on the business cycle. <p>"The recovery will increase demand for petroleum products," says Shoemaker. "That will boost earnings, particularly in the refining, marketing, and petrochemical areas." The oils will be ripe for a positive-earnings surprise.<p>Should you jump into the other sectors where analysts disagree? Those are tougher calls. Auto demand continued strong in the early months of this year, boding well for all of '94. The prospects for inflation are anybody's guess. But following the Federal Reserve's winter hike in interest rates, you can assume the prices of the cyclical stocks already reflect a modest increase in inflation. If you think that's all we'll see, this may be a good time to buy. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:ARC">Atlantic Richfield Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:PZL">Pennzoil Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:P">Phillips Petroleum Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
