<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-The Sole of the Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-The Sole of the Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
What does it mean when a laggard starts to rise?<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Does this bull market have legs? The answer may lie in the S&P shoe index. The Dow finished 1993 up 13.7 percent and the S&P 500 climbed 7 percent, but the rising tide was not smooth sailing. As typically happens in a slow-moving economic recovery, one sector booms and then quickly drops back as investors move into the next hot group. In the first quarter of last year, for example, stocks in the building-materials sector ran up almost 15 percent. They dropped back 8.3 percent in the second quarter, while a related group--home-building stocks----climbed 10 percent. In the third quarter, home builders surged again--up 17 percent----while shares in building-materials makers rose almost 8 percent. Also in the third quarter, makers of household furnishings and appliances made the list of top ten performers for the first time. In January, investors continued their love affair with the home front: Mobile-home makers jumped 9 percent.<p>Shoe stocks, in contrast, were the dogs of 1993, down almost 25 percent. In fact, most consumer-goods sectors--retailers, food processors, and toy makers--lagged the Dow. But now they're moving. Shoe shares ranked 11th among industry groups in January. Of course, the stocks had taken such a tanning that perhaps the only way they could go was up. And strong fourth-quarter sales figures at Timberland Co. (up 41 percent) and Nine West Group (up 20 percent) may indicate a simple shift in fashion. <p>Will the surge last? Keep your eye on other consumer stocks; if they start to rise, it would indicate a change in leadership. And that would mean this bull's still got a way to run.--Jim Jubak<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
