<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Retailers Rebound From Snow</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Retailers Rebound From Snow</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Stock opportunities in last year's weather reports<p>By Derrick Niederman<p>The "storm of the century" that hit the East Coast in mid-March of 1993 is about to provide a delayed payoff to investors who are paying attention as we near the anniversary of the storm. <p>The key is the yearly changes in company financials. Good year-to-year comparisons tend to push stocks up, and bad comparisons tend to push them down. And that's where the storm comes in. By looking for companies whose sales figures were hit hardest by the storm, we've compiled a list (see table) of companies that are poised to post outstanding yearly comparisons this March. And even though it seems too easy to anticipate, it's a good bet that the stocks of some of these companies will go up after the numbers are released.<p>The storm came on a weekend, when people are inclined to shop and eat out. For companies dependent on consumers spending time outside their homes, it was a disaster. The table shows the storm's effect on "same-store sales" figures. Most stores were down more than 5 percent, and even those that were up (such as <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>) did worse than expected. The comparisons were particularly poor for regional operations in the storm's path, including discount retailer <a name="NASD:BSMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15162"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Filene's Basement</b></a>, based in Boston (down 7 percent), and <a name="NYSE:SHN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11351"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Shoney's Restaurants</b></a>, headquartered in Nashville (down 8.8 percent). <p>Within six weeks of the storm, the stocks in the table declined an average of 18.5 percent. Why did the market react so strongly to an obviously onetime event? As hard to believe as it may be, many investors react only to the numbers. Instead of taking the weather into consideration, they conclude that the company must have lost its touch. Companies already known to be experiencing problems were hit the hardest. For example, Filene's Basement (whose stock was off 40.3 percent) has struggled in its expansion beyond the flagship Boston store. But the poor comparisons caused by the weather made many investors believe that the growth problem was worse than they had thought. The double whammy made Filene's the biggest loser on the list.<p>Wall Street also punished some companies whose sales remained up, because those results were still below expectations. <a name="NASD:CBRL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13128"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cracker Barrel Old Country Store</b></a>, a family restaurant chain, posted a sales gain of 5 percent but saw its stock drop from 31 to 25 as investors accustomed to 8 percent to 9 percent sales gains bailed out. <a name="NASD:SPLS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14790"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Staples</b></a>, one of the leaders in office-supply superstores, posted flat sales, which didn't sustain the stock's high multiple. Within two months, Staples shares had fallen from 27 to 16.<p>As long as there isn't another far-reaching blizzard this winter, the March sales figures should be better than they were last year, and they should benefit each company on the list. But not all these stocks still have equal potential for today's investors. Staples and Cracker Barrel, for instance, have each staged full recoveries from their declines. Cracker Barrel's rebound was so swift it hit a record high last May, up 36 percent from the April low. It may go up more, but probably not as dramatically.<p>Fortunately, a few laggards remain, and that's where the greatest opportunities lie. The restaurant chains--Shoney's, <a name="NYSE:PIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14429"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Piccadilly</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:RYAN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14624"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ryan</b></a>'s--are all trading within $1 of their pre-'93 storm prices and could be considered rebound candidates even without any "weather bounce." All three have made improvements in their appearance, menus, and pricing strategies, and they are are modestly priced relative to current earnings. All they need is a catalyst to help investors recognize the advances they have made--and favorable March comparisons could be just the thing. <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

