		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Habits of Seven Highly Effective Investors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Ranging from college professor to playwrite to horse trainer, these individuals have made successful investing a way of life.  The secret, they say, is in the details, from knowing what to read to learning when to sell.  Their stories show how anyone can play the game and win.<p>By Andrew Feinberg<p>ENJOY THE PROCESS
JACK ROSENZWEIG<p>Jack Rosenzweig--ponytailed vegetarian, Harley rider, gentleman farmer, and CEO--enjoys the stock market. In fact, keeping it fun is key to Rosenzweig's success as an investor. <p>Rosenzweig lives on a 110-acre farm in Glen Summit, Pennsylvania, and is co-owner, with his wife, of a "moderately profitable" $40 million conglomerate called Humbold Industries. That doesn't leave Rosenzweig with much time for anything that feels like work. <p>Rosenzweig's techniques--which might strike some as hopelessly inefficient and outdated--have two things in common. Each ritualistic step is pleasurable in and of itself, and each is woven into the fabric of his busy days. Rosenzweig values the techniques not because they work in the market (although his portfolio is up 30 percent a year since 1990) but because they work in his life.<p>For example, he listens to CNBC for three hours every morning (World Business and The Money Wheel), while dressing and reading his four daily newspapers, and three hours every evening (MarketWrap and Business Insiders), while lifting weights and running on his treadmill. He gets his stock quotes from the ticker and every night charts the progress of each holding by hand. "Sure, software could do it faster, but I work on a computer at the office all day," he says. It takes him just 15 minutes a night to chart his 20 stocks and update his portfolio's progress using a calculator. (He was up $325,000, more than 32 percent, for the first 11 months of 1993.) The charts help test the information that Rosenzweig gathers from a discovery process that begins with all those hours spent half-listening to his television.<p>In October 1993 he became interested in Plum Creek Timber Company Ltd. when it was mentioned positively both in the Wall Street Journal and on CNBC. What attracted him? First, the fact that he had never heard of the company despite its size--it has one of the world's largest holdings of standing timber. And second, its high dividend (then 6.7 percent) and a relatively low price-to-earnings ratio of 11. But what made this a hot prospect? Only one Wall Street analyst followed it. <p>So he called Plum Creek's investor-relations officer and had her FedEx a large package of information. Then he talked to Evadna Lynn of Dean Witter, the lone analyst, for half an hour. Did it really seem like a good story to her? Eventually, he elicited her projection that Plum Creek, then trading at $66, would have more than $7 per share in free cash flow in 1995. Rosenzweig bought 1,000 shares. A month later the stock hit $76.75.<p>A contrarian, he's particularly attentive to negative news about companies. "People panic too fast, and TV helps clue me in to when the crowd's reaction may be overdone," he says. Among his better plays: Buying 1,000 shares of Motorola at an average price of $51.66--virtually its low tick--during the height of the cellular-phone brain-cancer scare. "I'm a former science teacher, and when I saw the stock drop 20 percent to 25 percent in a matter of days, I said, 'This is ridiculous.' Buying when everyone else is bailing out is fun." <p><p>HABITS<p>Time commitment: 17 to 22 hours a week on investing.<p>Portfolio size: $1 million.<p>Reading: The Wilkes-Barre Times Leader and the Hazelton Standard Speaker.<p>Trading activity: 40 to 50 trades a year.<p>Tools: Charts his investments but does not use a computer for tracking or research.<p>Portfolio breakdown: 75 percent of his liquid assets are in stocks; rest of liquid assets in money market funds. <p>Leverage: Does not trade on margin; has never purchased futures, options, gold, or silver. Has never sold short.<p>Won/lost ratio: 90:10.<p>Main reason to buy a stock: "Because I think it will go up. I'm adding to my position in Placer Dome because I think there is about to be a stupid push in gold."<p>Main reason to sell: "Because I've lost faith in the company."<p>In a bear market: "I would keep my utilities and precious-metal stocks. I would probably sell some stocks and move some money into cash."<p>Investment personality: "My investment style is contrarian."<p>PICKS<p><a name="NYSE:PCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11196"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PLUM CREEK TIMBER CO. LTD.</b></a> (PCL, recently $24 after a 3-1 split): Huge undervalued timber holdings, a price-to-earnings ratio of 14--below the market average. <p><a name="NYSE:PNC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11138"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PNC BANK CORP.</b></a>  (PNC, recently $29.25): The nation's 11th largest bank, PNC should soon start to realize the benefits of its recent acquisition binge. <p><a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>WALT DISNEY CO.</b></a>  (DIS, recently $41): Beaten up lately as investors have overreacted to Euro Disney's atrocious start, Rosenzweig says. <p>
LEARN AS YOU EARN
MARYLIN BAITZ<p>Since Marylin Baitz began investing four years ago--after inheriting a low-six-figure sum from her grandmother's estate--the 40-year-old part-time horse trainer from Cincinnati has concentrated on one thing: her own growth as an investor. Like most novices, Baitz began by buying mutual funds. But after two years, she felt confident picking her own stocks. Now she has the confidence to invest aggressively, with an emphasis on the rigorous analysis of undiscovered stocks. "I was a math major in college," she says. "And I'm very mathematically inclined."<p>Take two recent coups. In August 1993 she bought into an initial public offering of Glenway Financial, a Cincinnati savings and loan that went public at $14. By December the stock was at $20. In September 1993, she bought shares in another obscure local company, the Future Now, a computer reseller with $700 million in revenues, at $11. By December it was up to $13.75.<p>Baitz owns no bonds, no bond funds, no balanced funds, and no asset-allocation funds. She keeps only a small amount in cash. "My goal is to achieve a 15 percent annual return, and you can't expect to get that by buying bonds," she says.<p>The Glenway Financial play perfectly exemplifies Baitz's hardheaded approach. As a rule, she considers IPOs a suckers game that depends on underwriters dumping stocks on unwitting fools looking for quick profits. But Baitz saw long-term prospects at Glenway Financial. "I had been a customer of the S&L for seven years, and I liked everything about it," Baitz says. "They have small, neat branches that are short on glitz, with no evidence that they're spending my money unwisely. Unlike many other places I've banked, they have very low staff turnover, which I take as a positive sign." <p>As a depositor, she bought her shares without paying a commission. Another plus was meeting Dennis Betz, Glenway's president, who came over to chat one day when he overheard Baitz asking a teller questions about the S&L. "I asked him why I should buy his stock," Baitz recalls. "He talked about Glenway's steady growth and its acquisition strategy." Baitz decided to put her money, well, where her money already was. <p>A month later, she went local again with the Future Now. Baitz was struck by the disparity between the computer reseller's impressive sales and earnings growth rates--100 percent and 35 percent, respectively--and its below-market price-to-earnings ratio of 9 (at a time when the market as a whole was trading at a multiple well over 20). <p>Was this a buying opportunity, or was the low multiple warning her away from a turkey? Baitz decided to do some more of her own special brand of research.<p>"They had made 28 acquisitions in the preceding year, which was fine--if they were also generating real internal growth. But a lot of fast-growing companies just use acquisitions as a shell game. That kind of growth can be an illusion." When she checked, however, she learned that the Future Now had an internal growth rate of 28 percent. "I sought candid assessments from some of their local customers," Baitz says. "All were enthusiastic and said they'd do business with the company again." That sold her on the stock.<p>HABITS<p>Time commitment: Spends five to six hours a week on investing.<p>Portfolio size: Six figures.<p>Reading: Better Investing, Standard & Poor's research reports, and Value Line.<p>Trading activity: Averages ten trades a year.<p>Portfolio breakdown: 98 percent of liquid assets in stocks, 2 percent in money market funds, no foreign stocks.<p>Leverage: Doesn't trade options or futures, doesn't sell short, never trades on margin.<p>Won/lost ratio: 85:15.<p>Main reason to buy a stock: "Because I like its earnings-per-share growth record."<p>
Main reason to sell: "Because earnings per share start to decline."<p>In a bear market: "I don't think I'd change anything."<p>Investment personality: "Aggressive."<p><p>PICKS<p><a name="NASD:FNOW"></a><b>The Future Now</b>  (FNOW, recently $13.25): One of the country's largest and fastest-growing computer resellers. <p><a name="NASD:STJM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14778"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>St. Jude Medical</b></a>  (STJM, recently $27.25): This leading heart-valve maker is buying back its stock. At a price-to-earnings ratio of 12, the company is dirt cheap, says Baitz. <p><a name="NASD:BMET"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12777"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Biomet</b></a>  (BMET, recently $10.63): This beaten-down maker of replacement hips and knees has also been buying back its stock, which has climbed since it hit a low of $8.38.<p>LEVERAGE YOUR KNOWLEDGE
MICHAEL KATZ<p>
I'm stunned at the number of people who have potentially profitable information under their noses but don't take advantage of it," says Michael Katz, 50, of Tiburon, California. <p>Rather than blindly follow the advice of analysts, "experts" of dubious lineage, and media tips, he believes in focusing his active trading (about 30 percent of his seven-figure portfolio) on stocks he knows as a result of his more than 20 years in the video game and toy business. His resume? Katz is president of the entertainment electronics division of Triax Technologies, an Albany, New York, maker of enhanced video game controllers. He's also been president of video game maker Sega Enterprises, head of Atari's video game unit, head of new products at Mattel, and vice president of marketing at Coleco of America.<p>In 1993, his trading account rose 50 percent for the first 11 months of the year. On the job Katz talks to retailers, vendors, and venture capitalists--industry people who are suppliers, customers, competitors, or friends. Using this network of contacts, he stays on top of industry events, trends, and players--mostly for work. But it also plays into his needs as an investor. <p>Last spring, for example, the buzz had a software company called Spectrum Holobyte set to merge with rival MicroProse Software. Katz thought the deal made strategic sense, and he knew and respected the managers at both companies. He also knew the smart money was backing Spectrum Holobyte--in this case, Kleiner Perkins Caufield & Byers, a powerful Silicon Valley venture-capital firm that had already put its money behind such high-profile companies as Electronic Arts, 3DO, and Crystal Dynamics. "I assumed that Kleiner Perkins would improve the management, increase R&D and get other strong investors interested in the company," says Katz. He began buying shares of Microprose (the name of the surviving company) in late June at prices ranging from $6 to $8.50. He sold in October at $14. "The stock started falling back. Video game sales at retail weren't that good. And I didn't want to be a pig."<p>No sector of the market is as susceptible to hype as the video game industry is right now. Katz believes this presents as much opportunity for the canny investor as danger to the unsuspecting. "Hype is very short-lived, and the industry is even more receptive to hype when it's hot, as it was recently," he says. "I always try to gauge the interest level of the investment community, the average investor, and the press." <p>Katz knows that the game must sometimes be played at warp speed. "If there's a press conference about a hot new product that is known in the industry but not yet widely written about, you can expect some upside move [immediately] after the conference," he says. "If you don't get that move, think of bailing out."<p>Case in point: In August 1993, the industry rumor was that Atari would form a joint venture with <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>  to produce its Jaguar video system. Katz bought 20,000 Atari shares at $2.25. When the stock hit $2.75 several days later, Katz sold, figuring that it had made its move. Within a week, the stock hit $5. Had Katz blown it? No. After an October Atari press conference announcing the details of Jaguar, he plunged back in, repurchasing 5,000 shares at $5. The next month he sold at $12. <p>Katz never waits around for the trade press or newspaper business pages to tell him where to put his money. He says both are always too late. For instance, in April 1993, he bought stock in Activision, a video game maker, because he'd heard from acquaintances that Gerard Klauer Mattison, a New York brokerage firm, had agreed to raise money for the company. "Gerard Klauer is pretty knowledgeable and has a very good track record in the industry," Katz says.<p>He also regularly consults his broker of six years--a refugee from Commodore, one of the early players in the home computer and game market--about timing and strategy. And he tries to be aggressive only within clearly defined parameters. The upside should be mouthwatering, the downside limited to a point or two. And he no longer looks for more than a double on any investment. <p><p>HABITS<p>Time commitment: Five to six hours per week.<p>Portfolio size: High six figures.<p>Activity: Averages 20 to 40 trades a year.<p>Tools: Doesn't chart investments, but intends to begin using a computer for tracking and research.<p>Portfolio breakdown: 70 percent of liquid assets in stocks, 30 percent in cash, oil, and real estate; 20 percent of stocks owned are foreign.<p>Leverage: Uses options a lot, sells short occasionally, rarely trades on margin.<p>Won/lost ratio: 60:40.<p>Main reason to buy a stock: "Because I expect fast appreciation within 12 months."<p>Main reason to sell: "It's reached my target, or I sense that it's at a high."<p>In a bear market: "I would try to profit aggressively on the downside. I would buy puts and sell some stocks short. I would hold my international funds."<p>Investment personality: "Unconventional, gut investor. Nothing I do is statistically grounded."<p><p>picks <p>Blockbuster Entertainment (BV, recently $31.63): Not just a video-rental chain, Blockbuster is set to emerge as an entertainment-retailing powerhouse. <p><a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a>  (AAPL, recently $29.13): Still a powerful franchise despite a steep stock decline. Should hit $40 this year, Katz says. <p><a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>  (WMT, recently $26.75): Years of selling to Wal-Mart have made Katz respect it enormously. Will hit $35 by April, he says.<p>
NARROW THE FOCUS
DICK BRUKENFELD<p><p> For Dick Brukenfeld, nothing concentrates the mind like an investment that returns nearly 1,000 percent. Before 1975, the 60-year-old Westchester County, New York, playwright and former Village Voice theater critic was just another stock market duffer, buying and selling without much strategy and basically breaking even. Then in 1975, he bought some stock in Radiofone, an electronic-paging company of which his cousin was an officer. The $5,000 investment was really just a favor to a family member, but it ended up changing Brukenfeld's life. Over the next seven and a half years, Brukenfeld watched Radiofone stock rise from  $1.50 to $26. The message: Learn one industry; learn everything about it. <p>"I believe in concentration," he says. Now Brukenfeld owns some 25 telephone, cellular, paging, and cable-TV stocks. His holdings are broad enough that when the stocks of BellAtlantic and Telecommunications Inc. soared following their merger announcement in October, Brukenfeld already owned chunks of both. "Ideally, you want to know as much as possible about an industry so you can filter out the BS," he says.  <p>His favorite bell ringer was Mobile Communications Inc., a small cellular-phone company based in Jackson, Mississippi. "I asked about the prospects for cellular," he says. "I wanted a pure play." The stock soared from $4.25 in 1982 to $27.25 in 1989. That year BellSouth acquired the company, kept the cellular assets, and  spun it off as a new wireless entity called Mobile Telecommunications. But Brukenfeld wasn't finished. "I learned that Mobile Communications CEO John Palmer and his team, whom I respected enormously, were staying with the spin-off," Brukenfeld says. He put an additional $100,000 in the spin-off at $4.50 a share. After 18 months he sold two thirds at prices ranging from $5 to $6 a share. But he kept 10,000 shares; the stock's now above $20. <p>"When you concentrate on one area, you're not at the mercy of the market," he says. "If you really know the business and the company, you know when it's the market that's going crazy." A focused investor who knows the fundamental values of the companies in a sector should be able to tell when that sector itself is getting overvalued. "I'm not buying telecommunications in the U.S. now because there's too much hoopla," Brukenfeld says. "I'm concentrating on foreign communications plays."<p><p>habits<p>Time commitment: Seven hours a week.<p>Portfolio size: Low seven figures.<p>Reading: Four financial newsletters: Adrian Day's Investment Analyst, Richard Band's Profitable Investing, Vivian Lewis's Global Investing, and Bob Bishop's Gold Mining Report.<p>Trading activity: Averages ten trades a year.<p>Techniques: Doesn't chart investments or use a computer.<p>Portfolio breakdown: 60 percent of liquid assets in stocks, 30 percent in bonds, 10 percent in cash; 30 percent of stocks are foreign.<p>Leverage: Never sells short; occasionally trades on margin. Bought silver in the 1960s; presently owns IBM calls.<p>Won/lost ratio: 70:30.<p>Main reason to buy a stock: "Because I know enough to feel comfortable owning it."<p>Main reason to sell: "Because I'm disenchanted with management. I sold my Multimedia stock when they began to syndicate Rush Limbaugh."<p>In a bear market: "I would look for stocks that are down solely because of the market."<p>Investment personality: "I'm focused and concentrated."<p><p>picks<p><a name="NASD:MTEL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14149"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mobile Telecommunications Technologies</b></a>  (MTEL, recently $23.75): Down from a high of $38, this wireless messenger company is poised for significant growth, says Brukenfeld. <p><a name="NASD:AT"></a><b>ALLTEL Corp.</b>  (AT, recently $27): A very aggressive Ohio cellular and telephone company. Also does data processing for banks.<p><a name="NYSE:FN"></a><b>Franco Nevada</b>  (FN, $93 Canadian) Traded on the Toronto Stock Exchange, this owner of gold-mine leases and profit participations has a ten-year record of acquiring assets at bargain prices.<p>DO LOTS OF HOMEWORK
ANNE CAREY<p>
 Five years ago, all anne carey really knew about investing was that she and her husband, Joe, were getting lousy returns on their retirement money. After weeks of her prodding, Joe finally said: "Okay, go ahead and lose some of our money. That'll cure you." Since then, her investments in mutual funds and individual stocks have risen more than 15 percent annually. <p>What's her secret? <p>Homework. Carey, a 49-year-old political science professor at Jefferson State Community College in Birmingham, Alabama, did what academics do best: She studied. Her initial syllabus included Richard E. Band's Contrary Investing for the '90s, William E. Donoghue's Lifetime Financial Planner, John P. Dessauer's Passport to Profits, and John Train's New Money Masters--because it included a profile of superinvestor Jim Rogers, who's from Alabama and is a cousin of one of her friends.<p>But books would only take Carey so far. She also needed some classroom time. So she attended a seminar offered by Legg Mason on income investing and enrolled in Investing 101 (yes, that's the course's real name) at Jefferson State. She subscribed to the Value Line Investment Survey for a year without ever acting on any of its recommendations. "Since I didn't have enough time to use it properly, I decided not to use it at all," she says. Unlike many novices, she never relies on friends for advice. "I would take their advice if I thought they studied as much as I did, but they don't," she says. Eventually, she decided to focus on international investing, mixing in some conservative income-oriented instruments with growth stocks and funds. Today, 6 of her 15 mutual funds are international, and her successful picks include T. Rowe Price New Asia and Scudder Latin America, both up more than 50 percent in the first 11 months of 1993. She picked those winners because her extensive reading left her feeling bullish on Asia and Latin America but bearish on Japan. So she sought out a no-load Asia fund without any Japanese holdings. <p>Closed-end single-country funds look like an intriguing next step in international investing to Carey, but not at any price. "I recently began subscribing to Morningstar's Closed End Fund research," she says. "I'm interested in some of the funds, but they are selling at premiums and I refuse to overpay."<p>Carey's husband never got to appreciate his wife's investment skills: He died of cancer in 1991. But she was grateful for the head start she got in finance. It helped her deal with the sudden responsibility of managing an estate in the high six figures. "I knew I didn't want a bank trust department to manage my money because I'd heard and read the horror stories," she says. Some banks actually lost money for clients during the '80s--which took work. She has done much better on her own.<p><p>habits<p>Time commitment: Six to seven hours per week.<p>Portfolio size: High six figures.<p>Reading: The Wall Street Journal, Investor's Business Daily, and Worth.<p>Trading activity: Averages five or six per year.<p>Technique: Doesn't chart investments or use a computer for research.<p>Portfolio breakdown: 50 percent of liquid assets in stocks, 25 percent in bonds, 25 percent in cash; 25 percent of stocks are foreign.<p>Leverage: Never buys futures or options,  never sells short, doesn't trade on margin.<p>Won/lost ratio: 80:20.<p>Main reason to buy a stock: "Because I think it will grow."<p>Main reason to sell: "Because I think it is fully valued."<p>In a bear market: "I will ride it out. I look at a framed chart from Investor's Business Daily. It graphs the performance of different investments since 1942. It tells you that markets go down but then come back up."<p>Investment personality: "I look for value and growth."<p><p>picks<p><a name="NASD:CCIP"></a><b>Citicorp Convertible Preferred P</b>  (CCIP, recently at $19.63): A conservative way to participate in Citicorp's upside, Carey believes. <p>Scudder Latin America Fund ($20.14 net asset value): The no-load fund has holdings in Mexico, Brazil, Argentina, and Chile. <p>T. Rowe Price New Asia Fund ($21.05 net asset value): A no-load option for investing in Asia minus Japan. <p><p>WAIT FOR THE REWARDS
BILLY WILLIAMS<p>
Billy Williams believes in long-term commitments. The average tenure of a stock in his portfolio: Ten years.<p>Indeed, the 56-year-old retired highway designer from Jonesboro, Georgia, says he approaches every stock he buys with the intention of holding it forever. He acquired shares of Ford in 1983 at a split-adjusted $12 a share. The stock hit $50 in 1989, but by 1991 it was back to $25. Williams held on even as Wall Street jilted the stock. "The cycle had turned against Ford, but the company was still fundamentally healthy," he says. Ford recently traded at $64.75.<p>Old-fashioned as his approach may be, Williams's buy-and-hold-forever strategy has driven his portfolio upward at a compound annual rate of 21 percent since 1961. <p>To interest Williams, a prospect must be fast-growing and, ideally, an industry leader. But it can't be trendy or in a business that laymen can't understand. If it passes that initial test, he runs a screen on the company's numbers. Profits must have risen at least 15 percent annually for the past five years, and the last quarter's earnings must be higher than the preceding quarter's.<p>Each month 15 to 20 companies pass the first screen and are subjected to more rigorous analysis. Projecting each company's sales and earnings five years into the future, Williams looks for companies that are growing significantly faster than the market average.<p>The survivors then face another hurdle. Williams calculates each company's average price-to-earnings ratio over the past five years; he will only buy a stock that is currently trading below that average. And he won't buy any stock unless its projected high five years from now (the future earnings projection multiplied by the highest price-to-earnings ratio of the last five years) is at least three times the projected low (future earnings multiplied by the lowest ratio from that period).<p>Once he's done this analysis and made a purchase, Williams is determined not to pay too much attention. His goal is to avoid the second-guessing that undermines so many stock pickers, and so he reviews the prices of his 25 stocks just once a month. <p>Genuine changes in a company's fundamentals--and not a transitory event like a price move --trigger most of his portfolio adjustments. "If one of my companies has disappointing earnings, I'll hold on if the explanation seems justifiable," he says. "The question is always: Knowing what I now know, would I buy this stock today? If the answer is yes, why worry?"<p>Even when his system leads him into turbulence, Williams holds on. Consider his response to the nearly unbelievable ride he's taken with T2 Medical, the home-infusion-therapy company that last year admitted its books were cooked. Williams bought the stock at $3 split-adjusted in 1988, watched it soar to $67, then held on as it nosedived to $5.25. Recently the stock traded at $7. "It doesn't bother me," he says. "I make mistakes, but the system works." <p><p>habits<p>Time commitment: 40 to 50 hours a week. Reads about investments two hours nightly.<p>Portfolio size: $400,000.<p>Reading: Better Investing.<p>Trading activity: Five or six trades per year.<p>Techniques: Just getting into charting but does use a computer for tracking and research.<p>Portfolio breakdown: 90 percent of liquid assets in stocks, 10 percent in cash; 5 percent of stock portfolio in foreign stocks.<p>Leverage: Bought options long ago, but "it wasn't worth the effort." Never uses margin; sold short once.<p>Won/lost ratio: 80:20.<p>Main reason to buy a stock: "For its history of good earnings and its growth prospects."<p>Main reason to sell: "Because the company's fundamentals reverse."<p>In a bear market: "I wouldn't change a thing."<p>Investment personality: "A long-term fundamental investor. My approach has proved itself as far as I'm concerned."<p><p>picks<p><a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a>  (HD, recently at $41.13): A chance to buy here on a slight pullback, with the potential for a double or a triple in the next two or three years. <p><a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola Co.</b></a>  (KO, recently $43.75): "A great, low-risk way to play worldwide consumer growth," Williams says--expect 15 percent annual earnings increases year after year after year. <p><a name="NYSE:CCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11803"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Carnival Cruise Lines</b></a>  (CCL, recently $47.25): A terrific franchise in a booming industry, Carnival should grow at double the industry's 12 percent annual rate. "I've sampled their product, and I really like it."<p><p>GET PAID TO WAIT
ISSAC ZISSELMAN<p> Nobody would mistake isaac zisselman, a 52-year-old New York City tax and estate attorney, for an Eastern mystic. When he recommends calm, it's for totally pragmatic reasons. "It doesn't pay to get excited," Zisselman says. Calm, on the other hand, can be very lucrative, especially since Zisselman tries to invest so that he gets paid in cash for staying calm.<p>Nice dividends help keep him from worrying, he's noticed. In 1987, believing that the commercial real estate market had hit bottom, Zisselman established his largest equity position ever by buying into Storage Equities, a real estate investment trust (REIT). Storage Equities is the largest publicly traded operator of self-storage warehouses for individuals and small business--what's called mini storage--in the country. He liked the company's geographic diversity and the low maintenance required by its properties. So he bought the stock at $12.<p>Zisselman didn't worry when the stock failed to move. It helped that he'd noticed that insiders were increasing their stake in the company. But more importantly, he was pocketing more than a 10 percent dividend while he waited. He also didn't worry as the market for commercial properties continued to weaken, or when Storage Equities slashed its annual payout in half, or when the stock tumbled to $9. "Obviously, I had been early," he says. "But I still believed the long-term story. And it mattered that management did, too." <p>Zisselman, in fact, felt so at ease he bought even more Storage Equities shares, lowering his average cost to $11.25. At that new $9 purchase price, and despite the dividend cut, Zisselman was now getting paid 9.2 percent to wait for the upturn. As 1992 ended, the stock was still at $9 and insiders were still buying. Zisselman continued to wait. The turn finally arrived in 1993: REITs became hot properties and Storage Equities finally rewarded its believers. It soared to $15. Zisselman's capital gains came to 33 percent, his dividends to almost as much.<p>"I'm more mellow than almost any investor I know," says Zisselman. It hasn't hurt his mood any that his portfolio has returned 15 percent to 20 percent annually for the last 15 years--and that's another aspect of Zisselman's calm. He aims low. Whereas many investors might expect returns as high as 30 percent a year, Zisselman is happy with 10 percent. In 1993, he bought a large position in Philip Morris at $48, right after the company's announcement that it was cutting the price of its flagship Marlboro brand. The stock had traded as high as the low $80s earlier in the year.<p>The investment seemed all but risk-free to Zisselman. "At the time, the ten-year Treasury bond was yielding 5.7 percent, and Philip Morris was yielding 5.4 percent. So I asked: 'In ten years, which is likely to give me a better total return?'" <p><p>habits<p>Time commitment: Seven hours a week.<p>Portfolio size: Seven figures.<p>Reading: Wall Street Journal, Forbes, and Business Week.<p>Trading activity: Five to ten trades a year.<p>Tools: Doesn't chart investments, doesn't use a computer.<p>Portfolio breakdown: 50 percent of liquid assets in bonds, 45 percent of liquid assets in stocks, 5 percent in cash. Also, significant real estate investments and a partnership interest in venture-capital fund. No foreign stocks.<p>Leverage: Has used options but would not now; rarely uses margin; has never sold short.<p>Won/lost ratio: 80:20.<p>Reason to buy a stock: "Because I believe there's a strong potential for growth of the company." <p>Reason to sell: "Because it's now fully valued and I have an alternative investment that will generate a greater return."<p>In a bear market: "I would sit tight."<p>Investment personality: "I am a long-term value-oriented investor."<p><p>picks<p><a name="NYSE:SEQ"></a><b>Storage Equities</b>  (SEQ, recently $14.38): The REIT yields 5.9 percent, and insiders continue to accumulate the stock. <p><a name="NYSE:BMY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10232"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bristol Myers Squibb</b></a>  (BMY, recently $57.75): Drug giant has a price-to-earnings ratio of 13 and double-digit growth prospects.<p><a name="NYSE:GTE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10620"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GTE</b></a>  (GTE, recently $37.83): Zisselman's chosen way to play the information superhighway.<p>Andrew Feinberg is a contributing editor at Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
