				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Finding Gold in the Pink Sheets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
A worthwhile tactic for adventurous investors<p>By Rod Fadem<p>The fear of so-called pink-sheet stocks is well founded. They are obscure issues. They trade infrequently and demand is sporadic. So they certainly aren't for the casual investor.<p>But the pink sheets do offer potentially large rewards for serious investors who carefully select undervalued companies that have a good chance of becoming listed on Nasdaq at a later date. What's more, there's a way to do this type of investing that adds some safety: Pick one or more of the handful of financial stocks currently trading at close to their book value. These are the mother lode of the pink sheets. As their stock rises up the ladder of the over-the-counter market, they also typically rise in price.<p>The pink sheets are on the bottom rung of the OTC ladder, a place where dealers trade thousands of companies without any quotes or volume figures appearing on a quote machine or in the newspaper. Instead, the National Quotation Bureau distributes pink sheets to brokerage firms every morning with quotes and dealer telephone numbers for every stock. These stocks sometimes trade only once or twice a month. <p>The next level up is the "bulletin board": an electronic pink-sheet system in which dealers show only bid and ask prices but no volume. It is more likely that a company on the bulletin board will later list on the largest OTC market of them all--Nasdaq.<p>The National Association of Securities Dealers Automated Quotations System is a nationwide network of computer terminals, where market makers enter their quotes on stocks they trade. There are two levels of Nasdaq, one for small-capitalization companies and one for large. To be listed, Nasdaq's small-cap market requires companies to have $4 million in assets, $2 million in stockholder equity, at least 300 shareholders, and a minimum bid price of $3 a share. The large-cap market--known as the Nation<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
