<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Six Stock Plays That Will Benefit Your Portfolio and Your Conscience</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Six Stock Plays That Will Benefit Your Portfolio and Your Conscience</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Curtis Hartman<p>Too often, socially responsible investing is like oatmeal: the right thing to do, but not very exciting. Sure, it's become big business recently, with its own newsletters, mutual funds, and even an index that has been outperforming the S&P 500. But the stock-picking methods tend to focus as much on what companies don't do--pollute, discriminate, or contribute to the arms race, for instance--as what they actually do get accomplished. We decided to take a more positive approach. Here are six companies that meet the screens of the socially responsible investor but are also fueled by dynamic visions. Don't worry: we haven't chosen companies that merely do good, but ones that are poised for real growth. <a name="NYSE:SMD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14839"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sunrise medical</b></a> founder richard chandler didn't set out to reinvent the wheelchair; he was just following a hardheaded business plan to grab a bigger share of the market of products for the disabled. Walter Minnick, CEO of <a name="NASD:TJCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14873"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TJ International</b></a>, may argue passionately for preserving the old-growth forests of the pacific northwest, but his altruism has a bottom line: saving these forests forces up lumber prices, creating a bigger market for his engineered-wood products. These are companies built for the future, each an innovator in its growing field. but none of them is a wall street favorite. not yet, at least.
SUNRISE MEDICAL<p>When Richard Chandler started torrance, california-based Sunrise Medical (SMD) in 1983, he had a simple plan. He'd seen the demographics: The country was getting older; demand for wheelchairs, crutches, and bathroom aids for the aged and disabled could only grow. And no one company dominated the market. So he borrowed $4.5 million and bought two dozen small companies that made products for the disabled, hoping to create a mini-conglomerate with national marketing clout and economies of scale.<p>Buying the companies was easy, but getting them to work together wasn't. Sales grew to $140 million a year, but profits shrank. Then he went to Japan and came back determined to copy the best of what he'd seen at companies like Toyota and Matsushita. Since then, Chandler has done for the wheelchair what Nike founder Phil Knight, another student of Japanese management style, did for the running shoe. Sunrise Medical now controls 55 percent of the U.S. market in ultralight manual wheelchairs and has under sponsorship 50 disabled athletes who compete in everything from track and field to tennis, took 44 medals at the 1992 Paralympic Games in Barcelona. <p>THE SOCIAL PAYOFF: <p>Chandler's vision is more altruistic than creating the wheelchair version of $120 basketball shoes. He wants to make an entire range of products that improve the customer's daily life and to make them better, more cheaply, and more efficiently.<p>Wheelchairs used to come one size fits all, in one color, black, and one style, clunky. Sunrise chairs are custom-made, each designed around the specific user's height, weight, and performance choices. Its wheelchairs weigh half as much as standard chairs and are made from the same aluminums and carbon fibers used in high-tech racing bikes. But the company makes more than wheelchairs. Sunrise spends $5 million a year on research and development, churning out 60 new products a year. The biggest triumph: a portable toilet that cost $600,000 to develop. Injection molded and made from lightweight composites, it's more comfortable than the conventional metal product, rust-free, and 20 percent cheaper. <p>PROSPECTS: as the u.s. population gets older and more of the disabled insist on integration into the active mainstream, the opportunities can only grow. What's more, any health-care reform from Washington will favor home and nursing-home care and will play to Sunrise's low-cost, product-driven strategy.<p>Chandler's trip to Japan gave him the vision to turn Sunrise into a company built for the 21st century. He shut down or sold off the non-performers, curtailed new acquisitions, and reorganized his work force into self-directed teams. He adopted just-in-time manufacturing, keeping only the inventory he needed for that day's production and shipping product out as soon as it was finished.<p>It worked. Between 1988 and 1992 sales rose 72 percent, up to $244 million, with a 275 percent gain in net income and a 62 percent increase in earnings per share. By 1992, Chandler was ready to start making acquisitions again, launching an ambitious program of global expansion aimed at making Sunrise a $1 billion enterprise by the year 2000. <p>THE INVESTOR'S PERSPECTIVE: until this year, sunrise was a Wall Street darling, trading as high as $38.25, 40 times 1992 earnings. But today the company is out of favor and trading in the high20s, although fiscal 1993 brought record sales of $315 million and earnings per share rose to $1.20. At that price it's a buying opportunity, according to White Mountain Investment's Harold Janeway, who has been accumulating the stock for the Working Assets Fund. <p>Kidder Peabody analyst Joel Ray suggests Sunrise has been a victim of misguided short-term earnings comparisons. Quarterly earnings reports were down in the first two quarters of 1994 because of dilution from a February '93 stock offering and unfavorable foreign exchange rates. But "the bottom line continued to grow," Ray says. He remains "very optimistic" that earnings comparisons and share prices will come back, too, and sets a price target of $30 within the next 12 months, or 20 times his fiscal 1994 earnings estimate of $1.50 per share.<p>
THERMO ELECTRON
A company that makes companies<p>Although he launched Waltham, Massachusetts-based <a name="NYSE:TMO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11473"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Thermo Electron</b></a> (TMO) as a small lab-instrument maker in 1956, George Hatsopoulos had huge ambitions--to spot emerging trends and develop technologies to meet them.<p>In the 1960s that meant transforming heat to power for space exploration. In the '70s, after the oil embargo, the focus broadened to energy conservation of all kinds, such as testing equipment to increase plant efficiency. In the early '80s, Thermo developed technologies to clean up polluted soil, de-ink reycled paper, and monitor air and water pollution. Then the company hit the wall. By 1983, with $200 million in sales, it was too big to keep its entrepreneurial edge. So Hatsopoulos decided to make the business small again, spinning out its divisions one at a time and selling a minority position to the public. <p>There's nothing in the Fortune 500 like it: Over the last decade 12 distinct companies have flowered from Thermo's roots, 8 of them publicly traded today. Hatsopoulos has built a $1.2 billion business not by developing technologies or products but by creating new companies. <p>THE SOCIAL PAYOFF: Thermo is an innovation machine, a $62 million R&D budget supporting some 560 researchers, all of them looking for the next product and the next potential public company: natural-gas trucks and fluorocarbon-free industrial refrigerators, a microwave camera to help helicopter pilots land in fog, a new digital mammographer to speed the diagnosis of breast cancer. Nothing is wasted. The development of a "cardiac assist device" for heart patients yields a bio-compatible plastic that spawns a $4 million business in catheters and tubing, which, in turn, yields a new scent strip for magazines, odorless until broken open, which debuted in Vogue last spring. <p>PROSPECTS: By 1983 thermo had grown too big to move fast. Stock options didn't motivate the research teams anymore; the company was too big for them to connect their work to financial reward. It was getting harder to raise capital, too, since Wall Street penalized it for the R&D drain on earnings. By spinning off divisions and selling between 10 and 20 percent of the equity to the public, Hatsopoulos solved both problems. <p>Other companies spin off divisions, of course--but generally the weakest parts, with the cash going to the parent. Thermo spins out its jewels--businesses promising a 40 percent return on capital within five years--and gives them the IPO cash. Each company runs on its own, with its own executive team and board of directors. Management compensation is tied, through stock options, directly to the market's evaluation of their performance. Thermo provides strategic planning, cash investment, and shareholder relations for all of them, as well as central administrative and legal support, and holds a majority on the board.<p>The results would please any venture capitalist: ten straight years of sales and earnings growth. Hatsopoulos predicts eight more spinoffs by 2000.<p>THE INVESTOR'S PERSPECTIVE:Wall Sreet has been slow to endorse Hatsopoulos's strategy. As recently as 1992 the stock was down to $37 a share, 17 times then-current earnings. But there was value there; the parent company holds between 50 percent and 85 percent of the the equity in its spin-offs. The stock has risen steadily since then, however, as the spin-offs have been growing a collective 20 percent a year, swelling the parent's operating income. But even today--adjusted for a recent three-for-two split--Thermo still sells at a discount; as the value of its spin-offs grows, so does Thermo.<p>Thermo, analysts say, is for the long term. "This is a company I'd buy personally to put my kids through college," says Lisa Rideout, director of investment for the Private Bank, a division of the Bank of Boston. Before the split, NatWest Securities analyst Paul Knight was looking for Thermo's shares to rise to $75 by the end of 1993. "The best years are still ahead," he says. "They could have a 50 percent increase in operating income this year and next and a 35 percent growth rate over the next five years." <p>SALICK HEALTH CARE
Round-the-clock treatment<p>Back in the summer of 1983, Dr. Bernard Salick was in the middle of the biggest deal of his life. One of the pioneers of for-profit medicine, Salick was negotiating to buy back a chain of 24-hour kidney-dialysis centers he had founded and sold a decade before. Then his six-year-old daughter, Elizabeth, was diagnosed with bone cancer, and his focus changed.<p>The months of chemotherapy and surgery that followed brought the family's life to a standstill: There were appointments to be scheduled all over Los Angeles and, eventually, New York--questions about X-rays and drugs, diet and psychology, endless travel and constant frustration. And the costs were staggering, well into five figures for a single week of inpatient care alone.<p>Salick bought his kidney centers, but they would be only a small part of the company he launched after Elizabeth's recovery. Convinced he could design a system to spare cancer patients the nightmare his own family had gone through and cut costs at the same time, he started opening dedicated outpatient diagnostic and treatment centers. Ten are running today--24 hours a day, seven days a week.<p>THE SOCIAL PAYOFF: As an outpatient facility, <a name="NASD:SHCI"></a><b>Salick Health Care</b> (SHCI) saves insurance companies the cost of an expensive hospital stay and lets patients keep as much of their daily routine as possible. Treatment is available around the clock, before school, after work, or over a weekend, and Salick centers offer every aspect of care under one roof, from radiation treatment and chemotherapy to reconstructive breast surgery and psychological counseling. <p>For-profit medicine remains controversial, so Salick Health Care sets up its centers as long-term exclusive alliances with major institutions like Cedars-Sinai in Los Angeles or large academic teaching hospitals like the University of Kansas. Instead of hiring its own doctors, Salick provides facilities for physicians affiliated with the hospitals and takes over all of the mechanical aspects of care, as well as offering advice from internationally known specialists in fields such as breast cancer, bone cancer, and solid-tumor treatment.<p>PROSPECTS: Salick has grown steadily at 32 percent a year for the last 5 years, up to $95 million in revenues in fiscal 1992, with a $6.9 million profit and earnings of 88 cents per share. But it's barely touched the market: 1.1 million new cancer cases are diagnosed each year. And managed-care facilities such as Salick's centers are key to every version of health-care reform currently under discussion in Washington.<p>Salick hopes to start two new centers each year and is currently negotiating with several hospitals, including Massachusetts General and UCLA. "It can be hard to get an academic institution like that to make a decision, though," CFO Leslie Bell says. Salick has to convince medical staff, the administrative staff, the trustees, and the private attending doctors, "and they all start out jealous of their turf, believing they are the be-all and end-all." It's good medicine, Salick tells them--better patient care at a lower cost. And it's a good deal: Salick funds the center's development and pays a percentage of its revenues to the allied hospital.<p>THE INVESTOR'S PERSPECTIVE: salick is a growth stock and a value stock, says Joel Ray of Kidder Peabody, the only analyst who tracks the stock. First offered in 1985 at $10 a share, Salick shares were trading last October at just over $15. Still, Ray thinks Salick has a bright prospects. "Earnings will grow erratically," he says. "It costs a lot to get each new center going. But once they're going, they run very efficiently."<p>Rian Fried has been buying Salick for his Clean Yield Mutual Fund since last year. "When Wall Street turns back to health care, its gaze will eventually fall on Salick and precipitate a well-deserved rise in the stock," he predicts. In the past Fried has avoided for-profit health-care chains "because the incentives to compromise quality in search of a profit is too great." But Salick is different, Fried insists, capable of providing "the highest level of care and a comfortable environment without running in the red."<p>TJ INTERNATIONAL
Knocking Wood<p>TJ International (TJCO), based in Boise, Idaho, is the nation's top manufacturer of engineered-wood products. Unlike conventional lumbering, which saws round trees into rectangular products and converts only 40 percent of a tree into structural lumber, TJ peels, shreds, or flakes logs, converting 75 percent of the wood fiber into structural products like beams and floor joists. Rather than cut down the old-growth forests of the Pacific Northwest--home to the famously endangered spotted owl--TJ uses scrap wood or small second-growth trees, farmable weed species. <p><p>THE SOCIAL PAYOFF: saving the old-growth forests of the Pacific Northwest doesn't mean killing the home-construction business. "We represent the supply-side response to the spotted-owl problem," says Walter Minnick, TJ's tree-hugging 51-year-old CEO. "Engineered wood is an example of using technology to help solve a very sharp public-policy issue. In an age of vanishing resources, that's compelling logic." What's more, engineered wood is knot-free and stronger than regular lumber. Wal-Mart recently contracted TJ to build the joists for the roof of its prototype "eco-store" in Lawrence, Kansas. TJ boasts that this job alone saved 87 18-inch-diameter, 120-foot-tall trees.<p>Minnick is an anomaly in both the forest-products industry and the environmental movement: He's served on the board of the Wilderness Society and worked in the Nixon White House. Not surprisingly, there's a large degree of enlightened self-interest behind his environmental activism. The government policies that endanger old-growth forests also make regular lumber far cheaper to produce than engineered-wood products. He wants the government to curtail its practice of allowing private lumber companies to cut on public lands at a loss to the taxpayers and advocates setting aside that land for wildlife and recreation. Minnick even has a '90s-style buzz phrase for his new approach: "reinventing the forest." <p><p>PROSPECTS: A lifelong republican, Minnick, not surprisingly, emerged as a strong Clinton backer. Under the Bush and Reagan administrations, when government policies kept timber prices low, engineered-wood products cost up to 90 percent more than regular lumber. But conventional-wood prices have risen steadily since Clinton's inauguration and drastically cut TJ's price disadvantage. So even though the housing market remains slow, TJ is gaining market share. In the first six months of 1993, sales were up 36 percent over the first six months of '92, even as housing starts rose only 3.4 percent.<p>Those numbers have brought Boise Cascade and Louisiana Pacific into the engineered-lumber business. But TJ has a head start on the competition; the company claims two thirds of the current market, a broad distribution network, and the largest direct sales force in the industry. What's more, TJ's capacity is growing, with three current plants expanding, another scheduled to come on-line in 1995, and one more on the drawing boards. <p>THE INVESTOR'S PERSPECTIVE: <p>TJ's shares are priced relative to lumber, not earnings. As lumber goes up, so does the stock. So the price is volatile, capable of moving from $24 (adjusted for an October 4 split) to $20 and back up to $26 within a few weeks. But with lumber prices potentially doubling within the next two years, there is still room for long-term growth. Dennis Moran, who follows the company for A.G. Edwards, is enthusiastic about TJ's prospects: "It will take three things to make this a $100-a-share company--and the first two have already happened," he says. "They need to be producing at full capacity--and they are running three shifts a day, seven days a week. They need lumber prices to approach parity--and that's happened too. Now all they need is for housing starts to move up."<p>
SHAMAN PHARMACEUTICALS
Antifungal in the jungle<p>Most drug-company scientists work in crisp white coats, rarely leaving their high-tech labs. The doctors and ethnobotanists at <a name="NASD:SHMN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15954"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Shaman Pharmaceuticals</b></a> (SHMN) tend to wear jeans and hiking boots and hump through the rain forests of Ecuador or Thailand's Golden Triangle. Their research techniques are essentially anthropological; they look for medicinal plants by following a native healer through the rain forest, videotaping the root he recommends for a cough or cutting a leaf and stem he says soothes a fungus. <p>There is nothing new about medical drugs from plants, of course. Quinine comes from Peru's cinchona tree and digitalis from foxglove; Eli Lilly annually sells $100 million worth of cancer drugs harvested from the rosy periwinkle. But San Francisco-based Shaman's field-driven method of finding them is unique and cost-effective; it only pursues compounds that have been used in three different geographical areas for similar symptoms. "Major pharmaceutical firms typically screen thousands of chemical compounds to find one marketable drug," CEO Elizabeth Conte says. "We screen 100 plants to get 50 with an indication of activity. And these compounds have a long history of use, thousands of years, so it's more likely they'll be safe and active in the clinical process."<p><p>THE SOCIAL PAYOFF:<p>Shaman is a fulfillment of the dreams of environmentalists: a green business that is also good business. It's not just that Shaman develops drugs; the company also provides a market-driven rationale for preserving rain forests in Southeast Asia and the Amazon. By identifying harvestable products, Shaman gives local people a powerful reason to preserve the rain forests, now being cut at a rate of 129,600 acres per day. <p>PROSPECTS: shaman has had an unprecedented hit rate and today holds "perhaps the richest product pipeline ever created in three years," according to SG Warburg's Kevin Wilson. By 1993 Shaman had screened more than 450 plants, 260 of which showed enough activity to warrant further study. Two products, both patented, were moved into clinical trials in record time: one for viral respiratory infections, with a potential U.S. market of $400 million and an international market of $800 million, and a second for herpes, with a market potential of $900 million. A third product, an antifungal, is expected to enter trials soon. <p>Conte is quick to stress that her company has more to offer investors than just a feel-good story. Shaman has a solid cash position, spends it slowly, and has forged alliances with such industry giants as Eli Lilly, Merck, and Italy's Invernio della Beffa. Last spring Richard Ring came to Shaman as COO after 12 years as vice president for product development at Genentech, hired to help Conte bring products to market. <p><p>THE INVESTOR'S PERSPECTIVE:Shaman may be the most politically correct stock currently being traded, but it's also being touted as a good, though highly speculative, growth play. In January, its IPO was well-received enough that it had to be increased from 2.5 million shares at $14 to 3 million shares at $15. Ten months later, it was trading at a dollar or two below the offering cost. <p>At that price, according to the two analysts who cover the stock, Shaman is a buy--even if the company has no products on the market yet and hasn't announced yet when it will. Since the company has no earnings, the only thing investors have to go on are projections. Joyce Albers of First Boston expects Shaman to introduce its antiviral in 1995 and anticipates earnings of 20 cents per share to follow in 1996. In 1997, she's expecting that Shaman will roll out its herpes treatment. Gazing into a crystal ball, she projects sales of $221 million with earnings per share of $4.73 by 1999. Based on the present value of these projected earnings, she's predicting the stock will be at $30 within the next six months. Warburg's Wilson doesn't expect the company to show earnings until 1997 and consequently sets a lower target price of between $20 and $25 for the next six months. But his long-range projections, which include the introduction of the antifungal drug, push the company to $291 million in sales in 1999 and $518 million by 2001 (we said this was a speculative play), with earnings per share of $8.86 and $16.55, respectively. <p>EDUCATIONAL ALTERNATIVES
Learning the bottom line<p>Chris Whittle wasn't the first entrepreneur to look for profit amid the rubble of America's public schools. While Whittle's vaunted Edison Project begins to look more and more like an Edsel project, another company, <a name="NYSE:EAI"></a><b>Educational Alternatives Inc.</b> (EAI), is already teaching students--and turning a profit. Its founder, John Golle, spent seven years developing and testing a for-profit education model and has been running nine public schools in inner-city Baltimore since 1992. <p>Unlike Whittle, who aims to build expensive new private schools from the ground up, EAI's John Golle works within the system--taking over public schools and making them work by changing classroom dynamics and eliminating administrative waste. In addition to its five-year, $134 million contract with the Baltimore schools, EAI also operates a pilot school in Miami.<p><p>THE SOCIAL PAYOFF: All children are capable of learning well, Golle insists, but only if schools are set up to meet the needs of students, not for the convenience of administrators, politicians, or bureaucrats. Golle's goals aren't just profits. "It's personal," he says. He's driven by the anger and frustration he felt watching his own learning-disabled son struggle unhappily through the public schools in the early '80s. "They tried to change him to fit and took away his self-esteem and his love of learning," Golle says bitterly. "Today my son is a statistic on some educator's chart."<p>Golle made big promises. The Minneapolis-based EAI would go into one of inner-city Baltimore's grittiest neighborhoods and take over eight elementary schools and one middle school, promising to boost attendance, restore order, involve parents, and improve student skills. And they'd do it in the existing buildings, with the existing staff, and just slightly over the school district's budget: $5,549 annually for each of some 4,800 kids.<p>EAI's initial reforms were hardly radical. Golle cleaned the halls, fixed the toilets, and installed cameras and security guards to monitor entrances and halls. Then class size was cut to 15, and classroom walls were taken out; rows of desks were grouped into small clusters and surrounded by computers. Grades and even grade levels were taken out, too. Each student was tested and then given a personal learning plan, developed and reviewed in regular teacher-parent conferences. <p>EAI's trademarked teaching system, Tesseract, costs more per student than the existing system, but the company saves money by eliminating waste elsewhere. Unionized custodians were let go; maintenance was subcontracted to a private service. Unionized teacher's aides were replaced by better trained and less expensive education-student interns. The accounting firm Peat Marwick was hired to provide systems for staffing, purchasing, and finance. It took until last February to get Tesseract into classrooms, but in the program's first three months, the average student advanced almost 90 percent of a full grade level--nearly three times the benchmark. <p>PROSPECTS: The Baltimore superintendent of schools is already looking for ways to give EAI more work. And there are 14,000 school districts in America, all potential EAI customers, "but it's not an easy sell," Golle says. Most public schools are conservative, battled over by school boards, superintendents, politicians, unions, teachers, and parents. <p>Golle says selling is getting easier as glowing reports from Baltimore--and Wall Street--spread. At the end of fiscal 1993, EAI turned its first profit, sending its stock up 50 percent. On the new-business front, EAI is currently in negotiation with school districts in California, Wisconsin, Florida, and Arkansas, with nine potential contracts ranging from $25 million to $225 million each.<p><p>THE INVESTOR'S PERSPECTIVE: eai is a good long-term speculative buy, given "its leadership position in a potentially huge market," says Mitali Shrivastava of Franklin Insight. Initially offered at $5 a share in 1991, by October EAI was trading in the low 30s. Shrivastava predicts 30 percent annual growth over the long term, but EAI is still a volatile stock. Depending on which contracts the company signs, earnings could range from 60 cents to $3.42. <p>Michael Moe of Dain Bosworth compares EAI's prospects to those of a biotech firm. "It's hard to get people to try something new," he says. "But Golle is a visionary. This could be a $1 billion company in five years; I can't think of another company with that potential." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Socially Responsible, Social Responsibility

