	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Too Many Contrarians</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Too Many Contrarians</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
The easy pickings may be over for contrary investors, simply because there are now so many of us.<p>By Leo H. Dworsky<p>Nineteen Ninety-four could be a difficult year for contrarians. For one thing, there are now too many of us. Years of grazing off undervalued stocks in a long bull market have fattened our bellies and increased our numbers. Contrary opinion is in favor. We have become a crowd, a bunch of walking oxymorons. <p>What is going to happen? Perhaps the same thing that happens in the natural world when one species becomes overpopulated. Numbers will be winnowed, probably by a combination of harsher climate, insufficient nourishment, and the predation of rival species. <p>The $64 billion question is: Has the practice of buying stocks that are out of favor become the conventional wisdom? And if so, how can contrarians, who normally feed off the conventional wisdom, survive a situation in which they may have quietly become the majority and are, in effect, feeding off themselves?<p>Note the plethora of contrarians in the world today. It used to be that the species was limited to cabdrivers, Vermonters, and curmudgeons of a certain age. Now they (we) are everywhere: in banks, insurance companies, and wherever money is managed. David Dreman, a well-known contrarian, manages billions of dollars for individuals and institutions. Sanford C. Bernstein & Co., another contrarian, was managing $21 billion at recent count. And the Fidelity Contrafund, a relative pip-squeak a decade ago, passed the $5 billion mark this past year. The Contrary Opinion Forum, an annual Vermont event now in its 31st year, had a record turnout last fall. Worst of all, there are now contrary-opinion columns in Forbes, SmartMoney, and, alas, in our own publication. Heaven help us all.<p>There are two possible solutions to this dilemma. The benign solution, which I recommend, would have a significant portion of us volunteer to change spots; if not forever, at least for the time being. We might agree, for the next year or so, not to invest in out-of-favor stocks but to consider instead growth, quality, and uniqueness (even if already somewhat recognized) or perhaps even cash.<p>If we don't do this, a less benign script may unfold. Contrarians, insisting on stocks that are out of favor, may find themselves with stocks that deserve to be out of favor. If there is one major weakness in contrary investing, it is the tendency to buy too soon--on the way down but well before the turn. Contrarians are often too preoccupied with the fact that a stock is unpopular and not sufficiently sensitive to the reality of a changing underlying trend. <p>Let me be specific. Four major stock groups are out of favor in the current market, and probably for good reason. They are retail, tobacco, packaged foods, and drugs. In all four cases I expect the problems to persist throughout 1994 and perhaps well beyond.<p>The retail group has had its stars, but overall the trend has been negative. <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MES"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10984"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Melville</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:LTD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11471"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>the Limited</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:DDS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10463"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dillard Department Stories</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:DH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10440"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dayton-Hudson</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:LDS"></a><b>Longs Drug</b>, and <a name="NYSE:DFI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13243"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Duty Free International</b></a>, among many others, have come a cropper during the past year. In my view, the outlook for most of these stocks and for the retail industry in general is likely to deteriorate further. <p>Why? Because the American consumer, upon whom retailers depend, faces three whopping problems in 1994. Problem one: Materially higher taxes in the upper brackets, affecting not only the well-to-do but those who use them as role models. Keeping up with the Joneses is an honorable American tradition, but first the Joneses must buy something. Problem two: The crash in short-term interest rates, which has meant lower income for retirees and others who rely on their capital. Problem three: The double-barreled impact of disemployment--the real impact on the buying power of the unemployed and the psychological impact on those who fear they too will lose their jobs. There's also a trend toward lower-paying jobs. Positions for middle managers are disappearing, while employment for night watchmen, health care workers, and french fry cooks is growing. Whatever else happens next year, I expect consumer spending to be disappointing.<p>The tobacco situation is pretty straightforward: a growing bias against smoking in the United States reinforced by much higher cigarette taxes and an increased concern with smoking-related health costs. Just because <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> lost nearly half its value in the last year doesn't make it attractive, other than as a tax-loss bounce. It has long-term problems in tobacco and probably also in its giant food business (Miller Brewing, Kraft General Foods). <p>The packaged-food industry is full of stocks that are now out of favor: J.M. Smucker, <a name="NYSE:BCU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10225"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Borden</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:RAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11254"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ralston Purina</b></a>, Pet, <a name="NYSE:CAG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10388"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Conagra</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CPC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10268"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CPC International</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CQB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11551"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chiquita Brands</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:GRB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10650"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gerber Products</b></a>, etc. Even Heinz, <a name="NYSE:GIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10639"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Mills</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:K"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10841"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kellogg</b></a>, blue chips all, have languished for more than a year now. Different companies have different problems, but all of them suffer from the squeeze on consumer income and the growing encroachment of private labels, not to mention increasing competition within their ranks. These stocks could remain out of favor for some time to come. <p>Finally, there are the major drug companies. As is well-known, drug prices increased at three times the rate of inflation during the past decade, which, along with steadily growing demand, produced exceptional earnings growth. Under any government health plan, demand will continue to grow, but the era of pricing freedom is over. Merck, the industry leader, has certified this reality by offering to acquire Medco Containment Services, a cut-rate drug provider, for an incredible $6 billion.<p>Drug stocks may not go down in the next year. They have already been through a two- year wringer. But other than the occasional, unexpected drug blockbuster, there is no reason for them to go up very much. The squeeze on margins will continue to squeeze the p in p/e ratios. <p>About 400 years ago, in Shakespeare's Henry VI, Dick the Butcher declared: "The first thing we do, let's kill all the lawyers." He might have said "kill all the contrarians" except we weren't a certified guild in those Elizabethan times. If Dick the Butcher exists today, he is in the market itself, ready to kill any orthodox contrarians who blithely come his way. Contrarians should keep this in mind as they wend their way through 1994. Go light on contrary opinion and heavier on some of the other investment styles. Let the other fellow buck the fundamentals.<p>Leo H. Dworsky, an editor-at-large for Worth, has been observing markets--with a skeptical eye--for many years.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
