	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Does the Boss Payoff?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 November 1993
Worth magazine/Features<p>DOES THE BOSS PAYOFF? 
To canny investors, it isn't how much a CEO makes, but how much he delivers<p>By Graef Crystal<p>The end of the cold war brought tough times to California-based defense contractor <a name="NYSE:ROK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11283"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rockwell International</b></a>. After rising consistently during the early '80s to a high of around $30 in April 1987, the company's stock had drifted steadily downward. By April 1992 it was languishing at $23.63. Someone needed to pull the stock out of the dumps. Who better for the job than the company's CEO, Donald R. Beall? A 54-year-old engineering whiz who took over at Rockwell in 1988, Beall knew the company--and its problems--inside out. <p>To make sure Beall concentrated on fixing those problems, the board of directors voted him a monster stock option--two grants covering 320,000 shares. Half the shares carried a strike price (what Beall would have to pay to buy the shares) of $24.50, the market price of Rockwell stock on the date of the grant. The other half carried a strike price of $31.50. This meant that Rockwell's stock would have to appreciate by 29 percent before Beall would make any money on this half of his grant.<p>In early April 1993, roughly a year after the grant, Rockwell's stock hit $31.50. In mid-September, the price was hovering near $36. Shareholders had to be pleased. <p>But was Beall's performance worth its cost? After all, in one year, the board had given Beall a little more than $4 million--and he had seen his 320,000 options appreciate as well. Did the Rockwell board--and shareholders--get good value for that money?<p>Pondering that question raises even larger ones. Can investors identify good and bad stocks based on what a company pays its CEO? Are excessively paid CEOs good for shareholders or bad? A return-on-CEO-pay ratio would give investors a way to measure companies much like the more common return-on-equity ratio. After all, it's not the size of a pay package that should concern investors. It's the return on the pay package--the relationship between the pay and the performance--that counts.<p>To see if a return-on-CEO-pay ratio could in fact be constructed, I studied the compensation paid to the CEOs of the country's 200 largest corporations. In each case, I measured the compensation against the performance of the company's stock. My first conclusion: Big compensation packages, by and large, are not closely related to good performance. In fact, some of the best CEOs, from a shareholder's point of view, are underpaid. An investor interested in reaping above-average returns might simply invest in these overachievers. <p>Nor are compensation packages closely related to the size of companies. The disparities among payouts to CEOs in similar circumstances were much greater than I had expected. Indeed, about 89 percent of the variation in CEO pay levels was pure noise; it had nothing to do with company size or executive performance. Clearly, ten years of investors and corporations battling over executive compensation hasn't gotten us far. <p>Yet some big investors have declared victory in the executive-compensation wars. It makes me think of that Childe Hassam painting of Fifth Avenue festooned with American flags: "The fight is over, and we've won!" As proof that the battle is won, institutional investors display the scalps of recently departed CEOs John Akers of <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>, James Robinson III of <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a>, and Paul Lego of <a name="NYSE:WX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11627"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Westinghouse</b></a>.<p>But if the war is over and institutional investors and shareholder activists have won, then why did the median pay package for 180  major-company CEOs increase by 21.6 percent between fiscal 1992 and 1993? (All compensation figures are based on a company's fiscal year. For details on what's included in my compensation calculations, see "Calculating Return on CEO Pay.") That 21.6 percent increase far exceeds the median return of 11.4 percent that shareholders in these 200 companies received during the same period.<p>Although this comparison seems clear-cut, deciding exactly who was "overpaid" and by how much in the world of executive jets and multimillion-dollar bonuses isn't easy. The fairest way to judge all these CEOs is against the pay and performance of their peers. To do that, I calculated the average compensation of the 200 CEOs in my study (after doing a little statistical cleanup to eliminate anomalies like the low-paid owner-CEO Warren Buffett and the extremely well-paid Sanford Weill): $3.2 million a head, or $640 million for all 200 heads. I then redistributed that $640 million on the basis of just two factors: company size and company performance. I placed 75 percent of the weight on company performance. That gave me a figure representing what each CEO should have earned.<p>I used that figure to select my ten best CEOs for 1992, those who returned a lot for their pay in comparison to their colleagues. I looked for chiefs who had held their jobs for at least three years and who combined a modest pay package with a performance in the top quarter of the 200-company study group.<p>How about the ten worst CEOs? My first cut yielded a list of executives who performed in the lowest quarter and who had been overpaid by $1 million or more. But five of those, interestingly, are CEOs no longer, and therefore not of much interest to current investors. Four retired, resigned, or were ousted: Kenneth H. Olsen of Digital Equipment, Akers of IBM, Robinson of American Express, and Richard K. Eamer of <a name="NASD:NMFS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43108"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>National Medical Enterprises</b></a>. The fifth, Theodore Cooper of Upjohn, died.<p>I replaced those unfortunates with five CEOs a little bit further down the overall list; they were in the bottom third in performance and overpaid by at least $750,000.<p>The difference between the two groups--the best and the worst--is pretty striking. The median CEO on the ten-worst list earned $4.2 million last year; the median ten-best CEO earned $2.9 million. Yet, the median CEO on the ten-worst list earned a performance IQ score of 89, 11 percent below average. Of the 200 companies studied, only 17 percent had a score this low. The median CEO on the ten-best list earned a score of 112. Of the 200 companies studied, only 18 percent scored this high.<p>The median CEO on the ten-worst list earned $1.8 million more last year than he was entitled to, based on company size and his (there were no women in my sample of CEOs) return to shareholders. Put another way, he was paid a little less than twice as much as he was worth.<p>As bad as all these averages and medians sound, the actual details--particularly surrounding the ten-worst CEOs--are likely to be even more aggravating to investors. Consider John A. Georges, the CEO of <a name="NYSE:IP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10800"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>International Paper</b></a>. In 1992, he received a grant of 112,632 stock options designed to boost his long-term performance and a grant of contingent shares worth $529,463, again to motivate his long-term performance. Generous?Yes. Generous enough?No. That same year he received $205,494 under a third plan to reward him for his past performance. All this came on top of a hefty annual bonus of $555,000.<p>Clearly, Georges is doing well.But what about his stockholders? Georges, who has been running International Paper for nine years, earned a performance IQ score of 93, putting his performance below all but 32 percent of my sample. How would Georges have ranked if he hadn't been so generously motivated?<p>Some CEOs get fired for performing like Georges. Others receive even greater rewards. <p>Roughly seven years ago William P. Stiritz, head of Ralston Purina, was promised $16 million worth of free shares if he could get his company's stock up to $50 per share and keep it there for ten consecutive trading days. He did so, though he was aided, at least in part, by his decision to buy back more than 50 percent of his company's shares. But a curious thing happened. Once he reached his goal and took title to his $16 million in shares, his company's stock price leveled off and soon began to decline. The stock recently traded near 40.<p>If Stiritz is still hanging on to the $16 million of free shares, they are worth only about $13 million today. Still, that's a nice payoff for performing in the bottom 16 percent of the 200 companies in my study group.<p>The ten-worst list also seems to be pointing to some emerging underperformers. These "faded glories" include pharmaceutical makers <a name="NYSE:BMY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10232"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bristol-Myers Squibb</b></a> and Syntex. What turns a CEO into a faded glory? In both of these cases, a disturbing change in the trend line of the CEO's performance scores. The performance scores for ten-year total return were, respectively, 106 for Richard L. Gelb at Bristol-Myers Squibb and 100 for Paul E. Freiman at Syntex, or slightly above average on a very long-term basis. But for the one-year period ending 1992, both men's scores dropped sharply, to 81 and 73, respectively. <p>If the ten-worst list is dominated by stories of underperformance and overpayment, the ten-best list is full of CEOs who took home comparatively little. John F. Woodhouse, the CEO of food distributor <a name="NYSE:SYY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11423"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sysco</b></a>, apparently doesn't need much of a financial boost to run his company well. His only long-term incentive was an option grant on 4,494 shares. One high-performing CEO, Josh S. Weston of <a name="NYSE:AUD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10148"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Automatic Data Processing</b></a>, received no long-term incentives whatsoever in 1992.<p>In a class by himself is <a name="NYSE:AVP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10152"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Avon Products</b></a> chief James E. Preston. He agreed to cut his annual bonus and to freeze his salary for five years in return for a greater grant of stock options. He won big, but so did stockholders:Avon's shares rank in the top 18 percent of the 200 companies in my study group based on performance.<p>Two other CEOs on our list have also turned in first-rate performances for shareholders over the long term. John H. Bryan has been at the helm of <a name="NYSE:SLE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11323"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sara Lee</b></a> since February 1975. During those 18 years, Bryan has engineered a compounded total return for his investors of 24 percent a year, enough to rank him higher than all but 11 percent of the companies in my study group for this same period. The other star performer is D. Wayne Calloway, head of <a name="NYSE:PEP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11166"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PepsiCo.</b></a> Beginning May 31, 1986, and ending July 31, 1993, Calloway produced a compounded total return of 20.3 percent per year.<p>Two of the CEOs who would have made our ten-worst list had they still been top dog--Kenneth Olsen and John Akers--show how a little knowledge about executive pay can help investors quite a lot. It's neither the absolute amount of the compensation nor even the nature of it that investors ought to consider when evaluating the performance of a company's CEO. It's the pattern that develops over time as a board rewards a CEO.<p>I used to be a consultant to Kenneth Olsen, the ex-CEO of Digital Equipment. If I brought up the subject of bonuses, he became apoplectic. "Annual bonuses pit brother against brother, and they lead to short-term decision-making, which is lethal in our business," he declared. So computer maker Digital relied instead upon base salaries and stock options, the latter of which were supposed to provide a long-term incentive. <p>Nice idea, but it didn't work for Digital. When the 67-year-old Olsen, whose 1992 total compensation came to $5.7 million, announced his retirement in July 1992, Digital was about to announce its third consecutive quarterly loss and a $1.5 billion "restructuring charge" for the layoff of 20,000 workers. Digital's stock had declined below $40 from its 1987 peak of $199.<p>Not that paying bonuses is a guarantee of splendid returns. In fiscal 1992, IBM paid its now-departed CEO John Akers a bonus of $375,000, even though he lost the company $5 billion that year. That gives new irony to the electronic memo Akers circulated to IBM's workers in June 1991. "When everyone realizes that IBM is a business, run by businessmen, and affected by the business environment and not a fraternity or club they've joined with lifetime benefits, then we can parade into the future to reap earned rewards," Akers wrote. If the board of directors is willing to pay $375,000 for a $5 billion loss, imagine the bonus they'd be willing to deliver for breaking even. Small wonder that Louis V. Gerstner jumped at the chance to become Akers's successor.<p>Unfortunately, the directors sitting on the boards of the companies on our ten-worst list seem to reward their CEOs' underperformance. The median CEO on this list received stock options in 1992 that had an estimated present value of $1.5 million--virtually triple that of either the best CEOs or the 180 other CEOS.<p>One proposed accounting rule might change this kind of counterintuitive thinking. The Financial Accounting Standards Board wants to require companies to reduce their reported earnings by the estimated value of stock-option grants. Were underperforming companies required to take a big hit to their earnings every time they tried to bail out a poor-performing CEO, they might change their behavior.<p>Clearly, the battle over executive pay isn't over. And it never will be until the typical CEO starts putting his company's fortunes--and his shareholders'--before his own. In the meantime, investors large and small should consider avoiding the shares of companies that overpay subpar CEOs. Who knows?That might just get their boards' attention.
------------------------------------------------------------
Contributing editor Graef Crystal is an expert on executive compensation and editor of the Crystal Report.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
