	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-The Worth Guide to Mutual Fund Investing:  A Better Way to Choose</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 ***NOTE TO AOL READERS***
Due to the technical limitations of AOL, we are unable to upload the charts and tables for this story.  <p>
By Robert Clark<p>Mutual funds were supposed to make investing easier. no more. like fast food and personal pagers, America's favorite investment vehicle is starting to look like another good idea gone berserk. At last count, there were 4,300 funds competing for our savings and retirement dollars, more than the total number of companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange and the American Stock Exchange combined. Investors trying to choose the best funds are now forced to cut through a beauty pageant of sales pitches and performance claims.<p>The task has become so complicated it's almost tempting to recommend avoiding stock funds entirely. There are just too darn many of them. But $391 billion (the amount that has flowed into mutual funds so far this year) can't be all wrong. And with money market funds and certificates of deposit offering returns that hardly outpace inflation, the mutual fund is unavoidable. <p>But not every fund out there is going to turn up a winner. In the short run, a broad market correction could wreak havoc in the whole industry, making even the paltry gains offered by CDs look good. A 2 percent return is, after all, a lot better than a 20 percent loss. So it's important to pick the right fund and to know exactly what you want to get out of your fund before going in. Understand that mutual funds are long-term tools for building assets. They should be timed in years, not months or weeks. If you want to try for a quick killing, go to the racetrack.<p>If you're serious about investing, the thing you need is a good strategy. Currently, the most popular approach among investors is to pick funds that already have stellar track records and hope the performance continues. Statistics about past performance are readily available in many newspapers and magazines. <p>But while the past is prologue, it is not always the best guide. Suppose a fund's past success has left it with more money than it can now properly manage. Or suppose its strategy works great in one kind of market but not in another. Or suppose the boss who ran a hot fund left his job six months ago only to be replaced by an incompetent fool. In 1989, the <a name="FUND:STIVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/STIVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lexington Strategic Investment fund</b></a> returned 61.2 percent to investors. The next year, it lost 43.3 percent. The year after that, it was down another 18.9 percent.<p>It's also a pretty good bet the next ten years won't look anything like the last ten, when practically everyone turned up a winner. Leading stock funds returned in the neighborhood of 20 percent a year, while the leading bond funds nearly beat the S&P 500 stocks. We can't predict the future, but it's a fairly safe bet those two things will not happen again.<p>Just looking at past performance also ignores other important factors--like the fees and tax advantages associated with various funds. Hefty customer charges can easily turn a winning stock market performance into a mediocre return. Taxes can eat up the rest. <p>Fortunately, there's a much better way to select funds--one that considers past performance but doesn't entirely rely on it, either. Our system begins from a different place altogether: the specific needs of the investor. The most important question we ask is, Why are you investing in the first place? <p>Is it to save up for a house? To build a retirement fund? To send your children to college? Or is it because you need a steady stream of income now? The objective is critical because it suggests a time frame for your investment strategy. And that's the real key to selecting the right mutual fund: the time frame.<p>Why?<p>The amount of time you have is what dictates how much risk you should take or, to put it another way, how much stability you should seek in a fund. Once you understand those factors, you'll be able to make better decisions. It's sort of like knowing what you are going to use a car for before you race off to the dealer to buy one.<p>In general, the shorter the time frame, the less risk you can afford, so the more you'll want a fund that delivers consistent performance. Investors with longer time frames, on the other hand, can usually accept more risk and less stability in order to earn a higher long-run payoff. <p>Suppose you want to save for a down payment on a house. That probably means you'll want to be able cash out in two or three years. That short a period gives you little margin for error--unless you're willing to keep postponing the purchase. The best buy for this type of investment is a fund that will deliver steady upward performance. It also means avoiding funds with large up-front commissions. You won't earn them back. <p>Conversely, funding a retirement that's still 20 years away means neither consistency nor up-front commissions are as big a deal. If year 12 is a bad one, there's plenty of time for the market to recover. Instead, the enemies of long-term investing are consistently poor performance and high annual expenses, both of which can seriously erode a fund's ability to provide compounded returns. <p>Finally, if your investment horizon is somewhere in the middle, say four to ten years, you'll want a fund that offers a balance between both extremes. Solid performance with reasonable consistency. <p>So, with the help of Morningstar Inc. in Chicago, we've developed a rating system specifically designed to identify funds that are best suited to each investment strategy: short range, medium term, and long haul. Our system selects the funds that offer the best chance of meeting investors' specific needs.<p>To do this, we looked at 572 funds from four perspectives. The first is past performance, including three-, five-, and ten-year annualized returns. The second is what the fund charges in the way of up-front commissions and annual fees. Third is risk, which we measure based on the consistency of a fund's performance, as well as its largest loss. Last, we take a look at management. We evaluate this based on a manager's tenure, the size of the fund, and the rate of buying and selling in a fund, called turnover. <p>Probably the most conservative feature of our system is that we only evaluate funds with at least a ten-year history. That way, we can be confident that we've seen how a fund has performed under a variety of conditions. It also helps weed out funds that have succeeded on pure luck. Yes, there are some good funds with less than ten years under their belt. But why take a chance on one of these when there are so many good ones with proven track records?<p>To find out which mutual funds will do best in different time frames, we weight our grades to emphasize different factors. For short-term investors (one to three years), we focus on consistency, the largest one-quarter loss, and the up-front commission. For mid-term investors (four to ten years), we increase the emphasis on performance while decreasing the emphasis on the commission. For long-term investors (more than ten years), we place a heavier weighting on performance and expenses. <p>In this issue, you'll also find a special worksheet that will help you build a custom portfolio, depending on your own specific objectives. It's a personalized approach for investors who know that solutions that are right for others may not be right for them.<p>It's important to keep in mind that you don't need precise projections to plan a portfolio of funds. Instead, you simply need to make reasonable assumptions, save regularly, make solid investments, and monitor your progress. Every couple of years, you may want to make adjustments if the performance of your portfolio has been below expectations or if the costs of your goals have risen faster than expected. When doing so, however, keep in mind that a portfolio that's running ahead of schedule should be treated as a cushion for any down years, not an opportunity to scale back.<p>If you're planning for the long term, the best advice we can give is not to meddle too much once you've adopted a strategy. If you are planning for retirement, assume that you won't be touching this money until you are 65. If it looks like you want out early, there'll be some options. If you work longer, you'll simply have more money. <p>How much will you need? Few people want to retire on less income than they have now. Yet most also find their expenses after retirement are lower. Retirees no longer need life or disability insurance, their mortgage may be paid off, and they won't have to save anymore. Investors should assume they'll need a post-retirement income equal to about 75 percent of current income. (And don't count on help from the government. If you haven't already, it's time to face the fact that Social Security may not be there to help.)<p>To assure that you'll have a portfolio large enough to support yourself at the 75 percent rate, you'll want the equivalent of at least ten times your current income. That assumes that your portfolio will pay an average return of about 7.6 percent a year, which is a fairly safe guess. According to Ibbotson Associates in Chicago, the stock market historically returns about 10.2 percent a year over a long time. And the bond market historically returns 4.8 percent.<p>The only question remaining is how to get there. And that's what our worksheet is designed to help you do. It tells investors how to use the rules of thumb outlined above to calculate how much they need to invest for each goal. And we show you which mutual funds we consider the best for each investment time frame. <p>We also offer a few solutions for investors who find that the savings required by all their goals is more than they can handle. First, we suggest revising their needs and extending the time to meet them. But if that doesn't work, we offer one last alternative: investing in funds that offer the best possible chance for super-high returns.<p>Historically, the only assets that have outperformed the market are the stocks of small companies. The folks at DFA Research tell us that since 1926, the stocks of small companies have returned about 12 percent a year, compared with 10 percent for the S&P 500 stocks. That extra 2 percent may not seem like very much, but over many years it can have a dramatic effect on a portfolio and therefore the amount an investor needs to save from each paycheck to reach a specific goal. But that 2 percent also represents significantly higher risk. For these motivated--and, we might suggest, younger--investors, we offer a fourth grouping: mutual funds that own companies that average no more than $350 million in market capitalization (the total value of a company's stock). There are not many funds that do this well, so we only list five. <p>Our approach to tailoring a portfolio can also be adapted to stock investing, as long as investors buy an array of stocks broad enough to cushion the blow from any serious mistakes. Short-term investing is probably most suited to conservative bonds and preferred or utility stocks, while a mid-term portfolio could also include conservative common stocks, particularly those that pay high dividends. (Zero-coupon bonds are also excellent tools for college investing.) Long-term investing lends itself to placing more aggressive bets on growth or value stocks, where the risk is higher but the potential gains are high enough to outdistance inflation. <p>It's a system designed to take mutual fund investors from their needs through solid planning to specific solutions.<p>-------------------------------------------
Robert Clark is a senior editor at Worth. <p><p>The Ultrasafe Funds<p>Investors are understandably nervous today about where the markets are headed. With stocks reaching new highs regularly, price-to-earning ratios approaching historic levels, bond returns rivaling stocks over the past ten years, and interest rates more likely to go up than down, we're entitled to our jitters. Some pundits tell us that the fact we're nervous is a positive sign--it means we haven't succumbed to the unbridled optimism typically found during the last leg of a bull market. But such assurances don't seem reassuring at all.<p>Nervous or not, people making regular investments to meet their financial needs should stay the course. After all, systematic investing, such as dollar-cost averaging, was designed to see us through trying times like these.<p>The alternative to staying the course--trying to time the market, anticipating its ups and downs--is difficult at best, dangerous at worst. Market timing is just a form of predicting the future, a skill that no one to date has proven proficient at over the long haul.<p>But what about investors who have sold a house, changed jobs, or inherited a windfall, and find themselves with a sizable amount of cash to invest now? With money market and CD yields so low these days, putting the money there doesn't seem a viable solution. Consequently, we formulated the Worth ratings to identify those mutual funds that have the best chance of beating money market rates while providing a safe haven from which you can move capital into the markets more aggressively when you feel like it.<p>First, we asked the mutual fund analysis firm of Morningstar in Chicago to set up the Worth system to emphasize fund consistency and low loads; this gave us a list of consistently performing bond funds. Then we screened for funds that own  bonds with less than two-year maturities. Short-term bonds are far less sensitive than their long-term brethren are to moves in interest rates, particularly those upward movements that can reduce a bond owner's principal.<p>The result is the list of funds here, which offers investors an alternative to the stock and the long-term bond markets while providing the potential for attractive returns. The perfect place to park your nest egg until times are a little less trying.
--R.C.<p><p>BREAKING INTO A CLOSED FUND<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>
To groucho marx, the only club worth joining was one that wouldn't have him as a member. And a lot of investors feel the same way about mutual funds. Nothing is as enticing as a fund that has closed its doors to new investors. The attraction becomes irresistible when a closed fund such as <a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend</b></a> or <a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn</b></a> comes out on top of a mutual fund rating, as both have done this year. "People want what they can't have," says Eric Ryback, who manages the Lindner Dividend, which stopped accepting new investors in March. <p>Fortunately, there are several ways that investors can crack open a closed fund. Funds close to new investors for several reasons, most of which make the fund a better place to invest. A manager will close a fund if it threatens to grow too big or if the market has bid up the types of securities the fund buys to unacceptable levels. Sometimes funds close because the manager finds the overall market too risky. Managers may close a fund only to open it up again when conditions change. Others are closed permanently. <p>How can new investors get in? Some funds that have closed will accept new investors who simply try very hard. "If an investor is so determined to get in that they write you long letters explaining why they want to be in your fund, then they are a valued customer," says a star manager of a closed fund who asked for anonymity. "If a fund allows those kinds of people in, they're customers for life."<p>Some closed funds make an exception for spouses, siblings, parents, children, or in some cases grandparents of an existing shareholder. Ace portfolio manager Ralph Wanger of the $1.9 billion Acorn Fund says, "Most funds won't do a lot of detective work [to ensure a new shareholder is really a relative]. We're not about to hire a bunch of unemployed Russian secret police to make sure nobody insults us by giving us what we want."<p>Another way to break open a closed fund: Have a friend who is an existing shareholder in the fund--or even a stranger contacted through a classified ad--transfer shares to you. A fund can't stop a shareholder from transferring ownership unless a fund's registration statement specifically prohibits it. In fact, San Diego discount broker Jack White Co.'s Connect program matches buyers with sellers of closed funds, although they don't seek sellers for specific funds. There's some paperwork involved in transferring shares and getting the new account established. But once you're in, you're in forever. Most funds don't limit additional purchases, even to shareholders who own just one share.<p>Here's a list of some of the top funds in the Worth guide that are closed but perhaps not impenetrable: <p>Acorn Fund. Invest in Acorn's sister fund, <a name="FUND:ACINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn International</b></a>, and you can later transfer into Acorn. There's a 2 percent redemption charge on the international fund if the transfer is made less than 60 days after an initial investment.<p><a name="FUND:JAVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JAVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Venture</b></a>. If you're a sibling, parent, child, or spouse of an existing shareholder, Janus Venture will let you in.<p><a name="FUND:LOMCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LOMCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CGM Capital Development</b></a>. Permits transfers to relatives.<p>Lindner Dividend. Manager Ryback says his fund is hermetically sealed but admits that a handful of "hard luck" cases--people who had account applications sitting around for a year until receiving their retirement money--have squeaked through. Ryback expects to reopen his fund to new investors early next year.<p>-------------------------------------------------<p>
The Top Five Fund Chiefs<p>By Jim Jubak<p>
Ralph Wanger, manager, no. 1 long-term fund<p>Biography<p>Born in 1934 in Chicago. Joined the mutual fund industry in 1960 when Irving Harris of Harris Associates offered him a job: "Sounds great. What do we do?" said Wanger. Manager of Acorn Fund from its inception in 1970, first for Harris Associates and then for Wanger Asset Management. <p>Fund Objective<p>Small-company growth fund that concentrates on long-term capital gains.<p>Fund Strategy<p>"We are eclectic," says Wanger, who practices both growth and value investing. "Just because you like lobster doesn't mean you won't eat steak." Wanger style is research intensive: Acorn's portfolio is always full of companies that no one else has heard of. Up to 25 percent of the portfolio can be in foreign stocks.<p>Worth Rating: 9.530<p>Wanger's long-term record is second to none--Acorn has returned an average of 17.4 percent annually over the last ten years. Important for long-term investors, Wanger's minimal turnover (just 25 percent a year), low expenses, and zero load put more of an investor's money to work in the market.<p>Current Favorites<p>Wanger is still holding two of his biggest winners, <a name="NYSE:IGT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13812"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>International Game Technology</b></a> (IGT) and <a name="NASD:LBTYA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51395"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Liberty Media A </b></a>(LBTYA). Foreign favorites include Electrobras, the Brazilian utility, and Cafe de Coral, a Hong Kong fast-food chain.<p>Caveats<p>Wanger closed the Acorn Fund to new investors in July 1990. Assets are now at $1.9 billion.  Wanger launched Acorn International in September 1992; the fund holds many of the same foreign stocks as the Acorn Fund. Acorn International already has $500 million in assets.<p>
ROBERT RODRIGUEZ, MANAGER, NO. 1 HIGH-RETURN FUND<p>Biography<p>Born in 1948 in Los Angeles. University of Southern California. Started managing money in 1974. Has managed <a name="FUND:FPPTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FPPTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>FPA Capital</b></a> for First Pacific Advisors since 1984. <p>Fund Objective<p>To maximize total return for long-term investors who aren't afraid of volatility. The fund was down by 31 percent in the third quarter of 1990.<p>Fund Strategy<p>Rodriguez calls himself a classic value investor. "I prospect in areas that are out of favor" to find stocks with low price-to- earnings, low price-to-book- value, and low price-to-cash-flow ratios. Typically, he owns only 25 to 30 stocks. <p>Worth Rating: 9.000<p>FPA Capital's ten-year average annual return of 16.31 makes this fund seem an odd choice for investors looking for extra return. But Rodriguez has earned those numbers during a long-term small-cap slump. Historically, small caps outperform their bigger brethren by about two percentage points a year. Rodriguez's ability to outperform his group in tough times makes this fund a good bet for investors who need the maximum long-term return.<p>Current Favorites<p>Rodriguez buys only one to four new stocks a year. This year he's bought two. <a name="NYSE:AGL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10114"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Angelica</b></a> (AGL) makes and launders uniforms for hospitals and hotels. "I've been buying it at about $1 above book [value of $21 a share]," says Rodriguez. <a name="NYSE:NX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11239"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Quanex</b></a> (NX) is another fallen angel. In 1992 it got bid up to $31 when people thought the maker of steel tubes was one of the then-fashionable mini-mill steelmakers. It has traded as low as $14 before climbing to a recent price of $17.75. Book is $11. <p>Caveats<p>FPA Capital charges a 6.5 percent load.<p>
ERIC RYBACK, MANAGER, NO. 1 MEDIUM-TERM FUND<p>Biography<p>Born 1952 in Detroit. Idaho State University. Manager of Lindner Dividend Fund since 1982. Completed buyout of Lindner Management, now Ryback Management, in 1993. <p>Fund Objective<p>"I make an effort to pay as much [income] as I can without getting too volatile."<p>Fund Strategy<p>Ryback applies a value-investing strategy to an income fund. He looks for out-of-favor companies and mixes common and preferred stock, bonds, and, this year, real estate investment trusts and privately placed stock. "My goal is to do 20 percent a year." In early September he was up 14 percent for the year.<p>Worth Rating: 7.870<p>For investors with a time horizon of four to ten years, Lindner Dividend provides high returns with low risk.<p>Current Favorites<p>"Right now the fund is very defensively designed for any upward move in interest rates," says Ryback. He recently bought <a name="NYSE:IPC"></a><b>Illinois Power</b> (IPC), looking for a dividend increase to 5 percent from its current 3 percent, and <a name="NYSE:SRP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11353"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sierra Pacific Resources</b></a> (SRP) and <a name="NYSE:PGN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11201"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Portland General</b></a> (PGN), which both yield about 5.5 percent.<p>Caveats<p>Lindner Dividend is currently closed to new investors. Ryback says he'll reopen the fund (it was previously closed from 1984 through 1987) after the next correction or if interest rates rise in 1994.<p>
JAMES COUGHLIN, LEAD MANAGER, NO. 1 ULTRASAFE FUND<p>Biography<p>Born 1936 in White Plains, N.Y. Senior investment officer at Retirement System Investors since 1984.  <p>Fund Objective<p>To provide income and preserve principal while earning more than money markets.<p>Fund Strategy<p>By keeping maturities short and quality high, Coughlin aims to limit volatility.<p>Worth Rating: 8.567<p> The fund's average annual total return during the last ten years was 7.1 percent. <p>Market Opinion<p>"We're seeing a correction to an abnormal period that's long overdue," Coughlin says.<p>Caveats<p>The fund is registered for sale in just 11 states: Maine, New Hampshire, Connecticut, Delaware, Florida, Illinois, Maryland, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, and Rhode Island, plus the District of Columbia.<p>IAN MACKINNON, COMANAGER, NO. 1 SHORT-TERM FUND<p>Biography<p>Comanager MacKinnon born 1948 in Niagara Falls, N.Y. Head of Vanguard's fixed-income group. Comanager Robert Auwaerter born 1955 in Philadelphia. <p>fund objective<p>To provide high current income with low risk by investing in corporate issues with maturities shorter than five years. <p>Fund Strategy<p>The fund earns returns higher than its group--currently about half a percentage point higher--by keeping a very tight lid on expenses.<p>Worth Rating: 8.640<p>To earn its top rating, Vanguard F/I Short-term Corporate combined a ten-year annual rate of return of 10.33 percent with  minimal risk and volatility.<p>Market Opinion<p>Auwaerter and MacKinnon see rates tending higher, but don't foresee any sharp spikes upward. <p>caveats<p>None.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Retirement Investing, Bond Investing

