	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-How To Pick Stocks Like Pros</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
On-line services bring Wall Street into your home office for a fraction of what the institutions pay<p>By Robert N. Veres<p>One of the reasons individual investors have remained at a disadvantage to professional money managers in the stock-picking business is that detailed financial data--like that used by the pros to uncover promising stocks--has been unavailable to the common man or woman. <p>Slowly but surely, however, information barriers are coming down. Databases are starting to migrate from the world of professional investors to the masses, bringing a new freedom for individuals to do their own stock picking.<p>Consider, for example, the two-month-old newsletter published by Chicago-based Zacks Investment Research. Zacks is best known in the institutional world since 1978 as a one-stop shopping mall for research reports. For $3,500 a year and up, a user can dial in on his computer and find out what hundreds of analysts at 185 different equity research firms are saying about any stock. Check out <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>'s latest earnings projections and detailed write-ups on the company published by <a name="NYSE:BSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10191"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bear Stearns</b></a>; Smith Barney Shearson; <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>; A.G. Edwards; and a throng of others. Particularly revealing: Run through the previous reports put out by these hotshots and see how close their numbers came to reality. <p>Now Zacks has begun selling a composite of all this information, for an affordable $249 a year, in a monthly publication (that includes biweekly updates and a hotline updated daily) called Analyst Watch. Readers don't get the individual reports; instead, they receive a consensus view of earnings estimates--basically an average of the views of every analyst who follows the stock. The newsletter also lists the numbers of brokers issuing buy, sell, or hold recommendations. In all, Analyst Watch offers 50 key numbers on over 4,000 companies. "This is our first real product for the individual investor," says Ben Zacks, executive vice president with the firm. <p>Investors with a personal computer can tie into a number of relatively new equity databases that offer up-to-the-minute trading information on even the most obscure pink-sheet stocks (those that don't trade on any exchange). One of the more interesting offerings is the Free Financial Network, a so-called bulletin-board service established by the Small Investor's Software Co. in Amityville, New York. By dialing a phone number in the 212 area code, would-be stock pickers can read or download reports on about 7,300 different stocks, as well as information on mutual funds, options, and futures. The cost? "We don't charge for the bulletin-board service," says James Kellndorfer, president of Small Investor's Software, which sells a market-timing software program. "Anybody who wants to dial in is welcome to the data."<p>Investors who have about $600 to spend on a program might look at Telescan Stock Market Analyzer, a comprehensive market database published by Telescan in Houston. Investors can access Telescan by dialing a local phone number into the SprintNet Data Network; the opening screen offers a summary of the business news of the day, as reported on two news wires: Reuters and Comtex, a composite of other services around the world. Users interested in a specific stock can call up news articles about that company and scan trades made by company executives or other insiders over the previous two months. (The database also lists a number of on-line investment newsletters that dispense advice to subscribers--at an additional cost.)<p>The real power of Telescan lies in its heavy-duty searching capabilities. Suppose an investor wants to find companies that meet a strict set of criteria. Perhaps he wants a current price-to-earnings ratio no higher than 16--the historical average for the S&P 500 but well below most stocks in today's market. And he is looking for a price-to-book-value ratio of not more than 3 and a dividend yield of at least 2 percent.<p>And, on top of all this, the investor wants growth. So he asks the computer to show him stocks with five-year earnings growth higher than 10 percent, five-year dividend growth above 20 percent, and a growth in book value above 20 percent a year for the last 20 quarters. He also specifies a debt-to-equity ratio below 25 percent, so he won't have to look at companies burdened with heavy interest payments. And he only wants to look at stocks with a market capitalization above $100 million. <p>Log on, give Telescan the specifications, and about 35 seconds later (using a 2,400-baud modem) out comes a single stock that, believe it or not, meets all these criteria: <a name="NYSE:NWL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11073"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Newell Co.</b></a> (NWL), a NYSE-listed concern trading at around $31 a share. As you can see, Telescan pleases even the most particular investors.<p>Never heard of Newell? To learn more about it, turn to another part of the database, called Marketguide, and summon up a summary report. There you'll find that Newell manufactures cookware, cabinet, and window hardware and that it recently acquired Stuart Hall, a school- and office-supplies manufacturer. Also revealed in the summary is the fact that Newell's stock is trading near its 52-week low of $30.75, well below its 52-week high of $43.63. The report also includes a complete balance sheet and cash-flow statement for each of the previous two years and year-to-date information for the current one. <p>To get a sense of how the stock has moved historically, you can see how the company's stock price has behaved every week since 1973, displayed in a graph. You can call up an overlay screen and watch how price movements in the stock almost exactly track changes in the company's book value--until recently, that is, when book value rose while the price per share slid. Telescan also offers investors its own composite index, which represents daily stock prices divided by the sum of five different indicators over the last 20 years<p>The cost? Telescan offers a variety of packages; the most attractive costs $45 a month for unlimited access to the system between 6:00 p.m. and 7:00 a.m. <p>Investors who don't want to do their research by modem might prefer MarketBase, a service out of Needham Heights, Massachusetts, that tracks over 5,500 stocks, offering historical data for the past five years. For $695 a year, MarketBase sends out monthly diskettes containing all the latest stock market information, which can be stored on a computer's hard disk. The service is also available weekly for $2,300 a year.<p>Although MarketBase's information doesn't go back as far as Telescan's and isn't as current, the program itself is more user-friendly. Investors can select their own criteria and search for stocks that meet them, then call up summaries or balance sheets and income statements. The database also has a helpful "sort" function, which allows users to rank all 5,500 stocks according to dividend yield, price to earnings, price to book, or any of over 100 other ratios.<p>So far, the heaviest users of MarketBase and Telescan appear to be professional investment advisors, but that will likely change soon. After all, ten years ago, even institutional investors and fund analysts had trouble getting this kind of detailed data. It's only a matter of time before it finds its way onto the monitor of the average consumer. Then mutual funds may just discover they've got some new competition: their own more financially enlightened customers.<p><p>DEALS ON DATA:
Analyst Watch, from Zacks Investment Research, 800-399-6659; $249 a year for monthly publication, printed biweekly update, and access to telephone hotline with information updated daily.<p>Free Financial Network, from Small Investor's Software Co., 516-789-9368; free (regular phone charges only).<p>MarketBase, 800-735-0700; one-time trial disk $59; quarterly subscription $345 a year; monthly $695; weekly $2,300.<p>Telescan Stock Market Analyzer, 800-324-8246; $45 a month for unlimited access at night plus 94 cents a minute for access during prime time; $99 a month reduces prime-time charge to 16 cents a minute; $500 a month for 24-hour access.<p><p>Robert N. Veres edits and publishes Inside Information, a monthly newsletter for professional financial advisors.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Stock Investing Strategies

