<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Cheap is Beautiful</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Cheap is Beautiful</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
When times are tough, tightwad companies often outperform their more free-spending brethren. Ditto for their stocks.<p>By Stuart Weiss<p><a name="NASD:SBOS"></a><b>Boston Bancorp</b> works hard to maintain its image--just look at its corporate headquarters. It's a dump. "And they're proud of it," says Thomas O'Donnell, thrift analyst at Prudential Securities.<p>The company, parent of South Boston Savings Bank, operates out of a three-story building located in a part of town that most executives wouldn't even visit. "The walls need paint, the uncarpeted floors are covered with scuffed tiles, and the furniture would be hard to give away at a garage sale," writes O'Donnell in a recent report. <p>Just because the walls need paint doesn't mean O'Donnell hates the company. He loves it. Boston Bancorp's expense ratio--1.18 percent--is about half the industry average, and it has made money every year since 1983. The stock has risen steadily over the past decade to its current $35.50 a share, yet its price-to-earnings ratio is a modest eight. "Their ragtag corporate office is symbolic of a cost-cutting mentality," says O'Donnell. "They bought some properties from the RTC and finally got some decent furniture, but they're kind of embarrassed about it."<p>When you want to buy shares in a company, what information do you use to make your decision? The annual report? A broker's recommendation? If it's a consumer-goods company such as <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a> or <a name="NYSE:PEP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11166"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pepsi</b></a>, you can taste the products. But unlike Wall Street analysts, individual investors rarely get to meet management or tour company facilities. Most of the time, you base decisions on columns of lifeless numbers that may be outdated by the time you see them. <p>One active approach individual investors can take is to conduct an on-site visit. Drive to a public company in your locale and do a little reconnaissance. Walk into the lobby; tell the receptionist that you're thinking of investing in the company's stock and ask to see a copy of the most recent annual report. While you're there, look around. Is it a Taj Mahal or a bare-bones office park? Check out the parking lot. Do the executives drive flashy cars?<p>"I love to see frugal offices," says Suzanne P. McGrath, a managing director at Piper Jaffray in Portland, Oregon. "When I go to companies that display affluence, I can't help but wonder if their priorities are on running the business or on taking more for themselves." One of her favorites is <a name="NYSE:FMY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13519"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fred Meyer</b></a>, a Portland-based chain of variety stores. The stock sells at $34, 15 times 1992 earnings. "You walk in the front lobby, and it's obvious that they haven't had a decorator," she says. "The floor is covered with warehouse-gray carpet. Each office is divided by portable walls." And the address? Let's just say you wouldn't want to take a stroll after dark in that part of town. But Piper Jaffray likes the stock because the company is a low-cost, high-profit merchant.<p>Not all companies with low-rent headquarters produce high-powered earnings, of course. The supermarket giant <a name="NYSE:SWY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11308"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Safeway Inc.</b></a> is one such exception. Its corporate headquarters, a warehouse-like office located in the bowels of Oakland, is nobody's idea of glamorous. But keeping headquarters rent low hasn't been enough to keep earnings high at Safeway recently. In 1992, the company saw earnings decline almost 30 percent from 1991.<p>To be sure, investors have made money buying shares in glitzy companies. <a name="NYSE:NKE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14254"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nike</b></a>'s corporate headquarters, across town from Fred Meyer, might as well be worlds away. But Nike has done well over the years and so have its shareholders.<p>What about investors' love affairs with gaming companies? Their corporate headquarters are usually as gaudy as the casinos they own. Exception: <a name="NYSE:PRH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43989"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Promus Cos.</b></a>, based in Memphis. The company runs Harrah's casinos in Nevada and Atlantic City as well as Embassy Suites and Hampton Inn Hotels. "It's probably the most efficiently run gaming company out there," says James J. Murren, analyst with C.J. Lawrence in New York. Promus's headquarters is a large house built in the 1930s. "They got it for a good price," Murren says. In the past two years, the stock has zoomed from $11 to $65.<p>Visiting the "executive offices" of <a name="NYSE:LFB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10914"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Longview Fibre</b></a>, a paper manufacturer located in Longview, Washington, could give anyone a headache, thanks to deafening mill machinery. Headache or no, Longview has made money every year, even as its competitors--<a name="NYSE:LPX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10918"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Louisiana-Pacific</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CHA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10317"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Champion International</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:GP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10648"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Georgia-Pacific</b></a>--lost money. Furthermore, the company has never cut its dividend. How frugal is Longview? Its 1992 annual report, excluding the financials, consists of just three pages with not one color photograph. The stock trades at a price-to-earnings of 19, far less than Georgia-Pacific's 26.<p>In the computer industry, first prize for low-cost operations goes to <a name="NASD:NOVL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14287"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Novell</b></a>, a network-software maker. The company's Provo, Utah, office looks like any other short glass box in Silicon Valley, except for one thing: Real estate in Provo costs a lot less. Chairman Raymond J. Noorda drives a pickup truck to work and makes a relatively modest $200,000 a year. "It's a very frugal company," says Richard H. Kimball, a telecommunications analyst with Montgomery Securities. "The executives stay in Holiday Inns and don't fly first class." At $19.50, is the stock still a buy? Yes, says Kimball, adding that Novell is the dominant player in the fast-growing operating-systems market for local area networks. <p>Skimpy annual reports. Low-rent headquarters. Guys who drive pickup trucks. Maybe they're all emulating the most famous aw-shucks, regular-guy CEO there is: Warren Buffett. As chairman of Omaha-based <a name="NYSE:BRK.A"></a><b>Berkshire Hathaway</b>, Buffett pays himself $100,000 a year in salary. Don't worry, though; he's far from poor. He owns more than $8 billion worth of Berkshire Hathaway stock, which sells for $16,710 per share.<p>The company earned over $407 million in 1992 on revenues of $3.03 billion, and the stock has consistently beaten the S&P 500 in price appreciation for nearly 30 years. "We have no legal, personnel, public-relations, investor-relations, or strategic-planning departments," Buffett wrote in his 1992 annual. "We see the simpler, low-cost operation as more likely to operate effectively than its bureaucratic brethren." Investors looking for promising stock market ideas, take note. <p>Stuart Weiss has written for Business Week and CFO Magazine.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies<p>

