	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>A Good Time to Incorporate</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-A Good Time to Incorporate</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Advisor  
<p>
 A GOOD TIME TO INCORPORATE 
<p>
With the tax code changing and medical costs rising, professionals
should consider restructuring  
<p>
 By Mary Rowland  
<p>
 As writers, my husband and I are self-employed and are grappling
with soaring health-care costswhich we pay ourselvesand spiraling
taxes. Last December our accountant suggested that we look into
forming a C corporation, which would allow us to write off all
our medical expenses, including insurance. He did some projections
that showed we would save a pile of money in 1992 under the C
corp structure. But with year-end projects closing and the holidays
coming, we felt we didn't have enough time to sort through all
the pros and cons, so we put it off until 1993.  
<p>
 Procrastination, of course, has a price, and for us it recently
went up. First, the New York legislature passed a bill that sent
the cost of health insurance skyrocketing; the premiums for our
family of four nearly tripled. Then, one of our kids needed some
treatments that we had to pay largely out of pocket. By June,
we'd run up $10,000 in medical expenses we could have deducted.
Our accountant only shook his head sadly and repeated, "You have
to form a C corp."  
<p>
 With President Clinton's tax proposals promising to raise the
top income bracket five or six percentage points above the bottom
corporate rate, small-business owners are scurrying to their
accountants to convert their subchapter S corporations into C
corps. In most cases the benefits can't make up for the double
taxes that C corps often incur. But for self-employed professionals
whose business income comes solely from the services they provide,
a C corp can make a lot of sense.  
<p>
 Both C corp and S corp are named for sections of the tax code;
the primary difference between the two is that a C corp is taxed
directly as a business at corporate rates, whereas the income
and expenses from an S corp flow through to the owners, who are
taxed at individual rates. As taxpayers are only too aware, the
Clinton administration has proposed a top tax rate of 39.6 percent
(including the so-called "millionaire's surtax"), while the highest
rate for a C corporation with revenues below $10 million will
remain at 34 percent .   
<p>
 Unfortunately, this doesn't mean that a C corp is automatically
a better way to go. In most cases it isn't. The problem is that
a profitable C corporation often saddles its owner with double
taxes. Some of the corporation's revenues can be paid out to
the owner as salary, on which he pays taxes at the individual
rates, and is deducted as expenses by the corporation. But the
corporation pays taxes on any profits it makes, and to get what's
left of those profits, the owner has to pay himself a dividend
and then pay tax on that too. Why not just pay everything out
in salary? For many businesses that produce a product or that
grow in value, the IRS limits the salaries they may pay to a
level that is customary in their respective industries. But in
most cases, self-employed professionals may pay themselves all
the revenues less expenses in salary and bonus. And that means
no corporate taxes, and therefore no double taxation.   
<p>
 Why all the fuss? Because unlike the owner of a S corp or even
a sole-proprietorship, the owner of a C corp can deduct all of
his and his family's medical expenses. And with many one-person
and small family businesses getting buried by medical costs these
days, it can make quite a difference. Insurance premiums can
run $10,000 or more, and often there are substantial costs that
insurance does not cover. Under current tax law, none of these
expenses are deductible by a sole proprietor unless they exceed
7.5 percent of adjusted gross income. Often that means no deduction
at all. Says Michael Janicki, a partner at Arthur Andersen &
Company in New York, "C corps look better because of the favorable
treatment of fringe benefits."   
<p>
 A C corporation can deduct insurance premiums and any share
of health-care costs, such as deductibles and copayments, as
well as anything that the IRS considers a medical expense and
is not covered by insurance. That includes dental care, eyeglasses
and contact lenses, preventive care (such as check-ups, well-baby
visits, and mammograms), transportation to the doctor, psychiatric
care, and even drug or alcohol treatment. The IRS even includes
hair transplants, health spas if they are prescribed by a doctor,
orthopedic shoes, and Navajo healing ceremonies.  
<p>
 There are other advantages to C corporations as well. A business
owner can buy up to $50,000 of group life insurance and have
the corporation pay for it as a deductible expense. The corporation
can also pay for disability insurance. Unfortunately, if the
corporation pays the premiums with pre-tax dollars, the benefits
will be taxable. But taxpayers often get around this by paying
the premiums themselves and having the corporation reimburse
them. Owners of a C corp may also be able to put more money into
retirement plans than they could as individuals. In some states,
retirement contributions are not deductible for a sole proprietor,
but they are if they're made by a corporation.  
<p>
 There can be some additional tax savings, too. President Clinton
proposes removing the $135,000 ceiling on the Medicare tax. By
deducting the cost of benefits before taking their salaries from
their corporations, business owners may reduce the amount of
income on which they pay Medicare tax. For example, in New York
City, a sole proprietor pays 4 percent of net profit as an unincorporated
business tax. A small C corporation would pay 2.65 percent. In
California, income taxes are higher for an S corporation, too.<p>
<p>
 A drawback of the C corp is the possibility that the IRS might
claim that the compensation taken out is unreasonably high. Remember,
the C corporation works only when the owner takes all the incomeminus
expensesas salary. As long as one person is providing all the
services that generate revenues for the business, it is fairly
straightforward to take the money as salary and bonus. "If you
are talking about $100,000 to $300,000, it would be OK," says
Thomas C. Lenz, a tax manager in the Chicago office of accounting
firm McGladrey & Pullen. "But if a guy is running some type of
manufacturing business, it might be tough to justify a $1 million
salary."  
<p>
 The key issue is whether the owner is generating all the revenues
of the business or whether employees and equipment are doing
some of the work in building its value. A one-person business
almost always avoids this problem. "In a personal service corporation,
there is no value to the company," says Thomas Ochsenschlager,
partner at Grant Thornton in Washington. "You may have a desk
and a computer and that's it." Still, the corporation should
document what the salary will be and the formula for the bonus.
"Typically, small companies don't keep meeting minutes at all,"
says Mary Smalligan, a partner in the San Francisco office of
Deloitte & Touche. That's a problem in the face of an IRS challenge.<p>
<p>
 Most accountants agree that family businesses and businesses
with more than one revenue earner should usually consider an
S-corp structure. But for professionals who can legitimately
pay themselves what the business makes, a C corp can save a bundle.<p>
<p><p>
<p>
Mary Rowland, a columnist for the Sunday New York Times, writes
about personal finance from New York City.  
<p>
  <hr>  
