<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-To Thine Own Self Be True</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-To Thine Own Self Be True</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Margaret Opsata<p>John and Linda Cifarelli and their daughters, two-year-old Nina and five-month-old Annabelle, moved into their Burlington, Vermont, lake-front home in August 1988. Four months later, with accumulating snow in the overnight forecast, the family turned on, for the first and last time, the gas-powered driveway de-icer that had come with the house. By morning, Nina and her parents were dead, poisoned by carbon monoxide fumes that had seeped into the house from the de-icing heater in the adjoining garage. Little Annabelle and an overnight house guest survived.<p>The state of Vermont charged the previous owner of the home, Stephen Converse Brooks, with three counts of involuntary manslaughter for failing to disclose the dangerous condition of the heater to the buyers. The prosecutor argued that Brooks was well aware of the problem because his girlfriend and child had been hospitalized for carbon monoxide poisoning only a year earlier. But the former Republican Party chairman for Burlington and Chittenden County maintained that he had had the defective appliance disconnected soon after his near tragedy. He blamed the local gas company for reconnecting the device without alerting the Cifarellis to the danger. The jury, however, concluded that Brooks had been criminally negligent, and the judge sentenced him to 15 years for each death.<p>Caveat emptor__"let the buyer beware"__has been the rule of thumb in real estate transactions dating back to English common law. But these days, a new credo, caveat venditor ("let the seller beware"), may be more accurate.<p>Indeed, although it is unusual for a former homeowner to face a prison sentence, today sellers can incur severe penalties for not disclosing material defects in their properties. Courts generally support the view that buyers should be told not only about malfunctioning equipment, but also about roof leaks, plumbing problems, structural flaws, hazardous wiring, and any other conditions that could jeopardize health, safety, or property value. Some juries have even ruled that a seller is obliged to reveal that a murder or suicide occurred on the premises or that the house may be haunted.<p>And to save home sellers from this legal onslaught of litigious home buyers, an industry has sprung up, offering products from errors-and-omissions insurance to home inspections. But in most cases, people would be better off keeping their money and just telling the truth. <p>HOME WARRANTY<p>One such booming business is sales of home-warranty protection, which is growing by 50 percent a year, according to John M. Kinker, president of the National Home Warranty Association and founder of his own home-warranty company, Guaranteed Homes, in Lake St. Louis, Missouri. A handful of national firms and dozens of regional and local companies offer service agreements for repair or replacement of heating or air conditioning system components and of built-in appliances that work at the time of sale but break within 12 months. Home warranties have a $35 to $200 deductible and they cost between $350 and $500. By purchasing warranty protection for buyers, sellers are told, their houses may sell more quickly and their chances of being sued for equipment failures should diminish.<p>It's true the cost is relatively low, but then what's the real chance that something will happen in the first year after sale? If the need for this kind of coverage didn't exist while the seller lived in the house, why is it necessary now?<p>Moreover, sellers who decide to buy a home warranty cannot do so on the open market__the only people who offer the policies are real estate brokers, who earn up to $60 for each contract they sell, if they are fortunate enough to do business in a state where such payments are permitted. In addition, brokers who agree to sell home warranties can also receive discounts on their own errors-and-omissions insurance, a product designed to protect them from suits by disgruntled customers. <p>E&O INSURANCE<p>People who've put their homes on the market over the past few months may have been offered one such new product, "sellers' errors and omissions insurance," from Homeowners Marketing Services (HMS) in Hollywood, Florida. Their high-powered sales brochure, which is illustrated with realistic-looking bullet holes and pictures of spent cartridges, advises buying the new insurance "before you become a target" of buyers who can sue for "any situation or condition that happened in the past, is scheduled to happen in the future__or even might happen in the future__that may directly or indirectly affect your property value." <p>For only $200, payable at closing, a seller can buy $100,000 of E&O coverage for one year with no deductible. (Sellers who list with HMS member brokers automatically get $25,000 of insurance with a $5,000 deductible.)<p>Again, the cost is low (free if sellers take the automatic coverage), but the benefits may be equally as valuable. The HMS brochure describes coverage for "Innocent omissions. Accidental errors. Frivolous statements you don't even think twice about, that turn out to be false or misleading." A better strategy may be to think twice about any representations and to provide a full and frank disclosure about the house.<p>HOME INSPECTIONS<p>Another group that stands ready to serve home sellers for a price are the companies that provide home inspections. For $250 to $350, an inspector will provide a written report on the current condition of a home, pointing out existing and potential problems with construction and equipment. <p>"We promote home inspections at the time of listing, so the seller can have a report available for buyers to peruse," says Kenneth T. Austin, chairman of Bound Brook, New Jersey-based HouseMaster of America, the largest franchiser of home inspection companies in the country. For an additional $95, a HouseMaster inspector will walk a prospective buyer through the home to explain the report. <p>Proponents contend that a home inspection can focus attention on details like rust stains or cracks that the seller might not otherwise disclose because they seemed so insignificant but which, to a trained professional, are clear symptoms of trouble ahead that buyers should know about. "Homeowners could have problems if they knew about a condition but ignored or lived with it," says Harry S. Rosenthal, general counsel to the American Society of Home Inspectors. <p>However, an inspection also can reveal unpleasant surprises, such as construction that is not up to code or high levels of radon gas__facts the seller would then be obliged to disclose to prospective buyers. "Once you have an inspection, you can no longer say you didn't know about it," Rosenthal points out.<p>Consequently, a home inspection may do more harm than good, at least from a legal standpoint. "The last thing you want to do is uncover an expensive problem like a leaking underground oil tank," says Gordon C. Duus, who heads the environmental practice at the Hackensack, New Jersey, law firm of Cole, Schotz, Bernstein, Meisel & Forman.<p>People who sell protection products want sellers to believe that they could be liable for not disclosing defects they knew nothing about. But, in reality, courts do not expect homeowners to have X-ray vision or to be psychic. The buyer has to show that the seller knew or should have known and concealed the information. "Ignorance is a defense," emphasizes Harvey A. Miller of Cole, Schotz. Adds Diane Tiberend, an associate at the law firm of Cox, Castle & Nicholson in Irvine, California, "A homeowner does not have any obligation to rip the house apart to check it out before selling it." Of course, if the buyer requests an inspection, it will be hard to refuse. But let the buyer ask.<p>DISCLOSURE FORMS<p>The cornerstone of any seller's defense is disclosure, and to be sure they've covered everything, many realtors recommend use of a disclosure form, a detailed questionnaire about the condition of the property. To date, nine states (Alaska, California, Kentucky, Maine, New Hampshire, Ohio, Rhode Island, Virginia, and Wisconsin) have made seller-disclosure forms mandatory, and more state legislatures are considering the idea. Unfortunately, some forms actually do more harm than good. "A good disclosure form should protect the seller, but some are so awful that they put the seller in a completely untenable position [by asking questions no reasonable person could answer]," says Jerilyn Coates, an agent for 15 years with Carriage Trade Realty in Wayne, Pennsylvania. "I have seen some that even I couldn't fill out for my own house."<p>A disclosure form is a legal document; anyone who fills one out should seek the help of a real estate attorney, who can advise what disclosures are required by law and how best to word the responses. A lawyer typically charges from $400 to $1,200 for this kind of advice, but this should not add to the costs of sale, because most states require sellers to be represented at closing anyway. Having an attorney review the disclosure statement (and, later, the sales agreement) is really only getting full value for the fee.<p>Attorneys advise clients to be factual and forthcoming but not to volunteer extraneous information and never to guess at answers on a disclosure form. If a form asks the age of the roof, for instance, the seller may be tempted to estimate the time based on what the previous owner may have said or the recollections of a neighbor, who is pretty sure the roof was installed right after her youngest child had the chicken pox. However, unless the seller has a receipt from the roofing contractor or other written documentation that firmly fixes the date, the correct response should be "I don't know."<p>AS IS<p>Do the words "as is" added into the contract really protect the seller? Not according to HMS. "If you think putting 'as is' in the contract lets you off the hook  you may be wrong. And it could cost you a bundle," proclaims the bullet-riddled brochure. However, the examples of "innocent omissions" and "accidental errors" that HMS supplies seem neither innocent nor accidental: "not remembering" to mention that a halfway house is being built next door, misrepresenting the zoning, warranting plumbing and mechanical systems without inspections, promising that a home will double in value over a short period of time. Some would say that homeowners who behave so irresponsibly deserve to be sued.<p>The truth is, offering a house "as is" does protect sellers who allow inspections requested by buyers, offer no warranties, and make clear that buyers have no future rights or remedies for undiscovered problems. The words "as is" may frighten away some buyers, but these people are likely to be litigious sorts who are better avoided anyway.<p>Rather than falling prey to scare tactics, sellers can save the money they might otherwise spend on protection products and perhaps stay just as safe simply by being honest, choosing a broker whose interests are inseparable from the seller's, and following the advice of an experienced real estate lawyer every step of the way. <p>As further protection, clauses in the real estate contract that have the prevailing party in a lawsuit agreeing to pay the attorneys' fees for both parties should be lined out. Some lawyers view such provisions as a free ticket to a fishing expedition, since they get paid regardless of the outcome. "People are more cautious about litigation," Tiberend notes, "when they have to pay for their own lawyer." <p>An award-winning journalist, Margaret Opsata has written about real estate investments for the past 20 years.<p>-----<p>BE OPEN WITH LIMITS<p>If a prospective buyer requests an inspection and is willing pay for it, homeowners should agree to it, as a token of good faith and to show that they have nothing to hide. But they should also establish some ground rules. Since buyers often procrastinate, there should be a time limit for inspections, so the house will not be kept off the market by a buyer who eventually backs out of the deal; a clause, for example, stating that if the buyers do not meet a deadline, they waive any right to claim for damages. 
Decide in advance who will pay to repair any problems the inspector finds. "We try to put dollar limits on what the seller will spend__for example, anything up to $3,000 the buyer must take care of; anything over that amount, the seller will consider fixing, or we will renegotiate the contract," says Harvey Miller of Cole, Schotz. 
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Insurance Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

