<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Review: New Threads for Online Services</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Review: New Threads for Online Services</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ted C. Fishman<p>
For some time now the big four online services -- America Online, CompuServe, Prodigy, and Microsoft Network -- have catered to investors with financial news and data, discussion groups, and electronic brokerage services. Over the past year, however, these features have come to look slight next to the abundance of investor options available on the World Wide Web. But now all four services have reinvented themselves and co-opted the encroaching competition by melding Internet access into their programs. Because online access is indispensable for individual investors, here's a quick look at the four options in their New Year's clothing.<p>
Behind the familiar front of America Online ($19.95 a month for unlimited use) is a vastly faster service and a built-in version of Microsoft's superb browser, Internet Explorer. AOL content is now linked to external Web sites. In a news item that mentions AT&T, for example, a click on the company's name takes users to AT&T's Web site. Some of AOL's content providers, such as Morningstar and Fidelity, have retooled their areas to take advantage of AOL's new features. And to counter the many excellent portfolio-tracking services on the Web, AOL, like its competitors, has improved the tools with which users can track stocks.<p>
CompuServe ($9.95 a month for five hours; additional time and premium services extra) has done an even better job of integrating the Internet into its system by creating road signs and routes back to its own, orderly world. CompuServe still caters primarily to business users. Its investment forums remain the most wide-ranging and have the most informed, dedicated participants of any online discussion group around (the relatively high fees probably screen out yappers and gadflies). The area devoted to taxes -- H&R Block is CompuServe's corporate parent -- is especially strong.<p>
For the average investor, there are few reasons to opt for Prodigy Internet ($19.95 a month for unlimited use), which has been spun off from its precursor, now called Prodigy Classic -- at least not until the investor areas from Classic are moved to the new version. Microsoft Network ($19.95 a month for unlimited use) is the swankest and most reliable service; yet beyond some online banking options and a moving ticker tape, it, too, has slim investor appeal. America Online offers the best combination of price and information. CompuServe is worth the extra cost for hard-core information junkies and those seeking the online fellowship of informed investors.<p>
KEYWORDS:
online, AOL, Internet, Web, WWW

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

