<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Cover: The Guardian</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Cover: The Guardian</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						THE GUARDIAN
As the author buys property and accumulates wealth, he gets ever closer to the poorhouse. What is it about land?<p>
By Richard Todd<p>
I've never met a piece of land I didn't like, an attitude that can get a person into trouble. I am not alone. Many of us walk around with a case of land fever. We love nature -- that's part, but by no means all, of the story. (In candor, I know many an apartment dweller who loves nature more than I do.) We love nature, but more exactly we love land, need to live on it, and want to own ever more of it. This hillside and that meadow and the tract of woods with the little brook going through it -- they all look attractive in one way or another, and the price always seems, if you take the long view, so reasonable. After all, this is land, and as the real-estate broker will tell you, "They aren't making any more of it." <p>
The real-estate broker, you may note in passing, lives in a big house on a small plot in town and maybe has a time-share in the Cayman Islands, but no matter -- he speaks my language. Land is real and land is earnest. You can walk on it, you can fence it, you can dig in it, and when you dig you can hold the soil in your hands. Of course, all these are qualities of a less attractive concept called illiquidity.
You can always sell land -- but maybe not today or tomorrow or this year. That doesn't bother people like me, because in our view we are accumulating wealth, not making deals. We tend to agree with the 19th-century economist Henry George, who argued, in Progress and Poverty, that land is the source of all wealth. (We tend not to agree with his corollary, that government should therefore raise its revenues from a tax on landholdings alone.)<p>
An embarrassing portion of my net worth is accounted for by the 150 acres and "the buildings thereon" that I currently occupy in a rural corner of Massachusetts. It occurs to me sometimes that this state of affairs may result from actual mental deficiency, a lack of talent for abstract thinking.<p>
Here is the problem. People like me think that $50,000 worth of trees, rocks, and rills is fundamentally more valuable than $50,000 worth of blips on the Merrill Lynch computer. I know this is crazy -- a price is a price -- but even as I write, it doesn't seem crazy. Thank God for the few blips I have, or else my banker would never write a mortgage, but they nonetheless don't feel the way acreage feels.<p>
It should be obvious that the syndrome I'm describing is all about land and not much about real estate, or real-estate development. There are people who are very good at real estate. They are the ones who stop at the edge of town and see a pasture and imagine its hills leveled, and they see "feeder roads" and cul-de-sacs, and they seem to have lots of daughters and nieces after whom to name these streets. They have a transformative vision, give them credit for that, and with the help of some misguided laws, they are largely responsible for some of the regrettable things that have happened to the American landscape in recent years. They have been the financial engineers of the placelessness that plagues our country, the homogenized world in which people find themselves living at someplace called 1347 Darlene Drive.<p>
No, I am talking about a sensibility that has less to do with speculating and more to do with collecting. The land collector tends to be biased against development -- a paradox worth thinking about if you consider your land as wealth. The preservationist instinct runs strong in the land collector, and investment and preservation make uneasy bedfellows. Buy-and-hold is the collector's strategy, which is a recipe often enough for becoming land poor, a condition I achieved in a modest way sometime ago. I languish there still.<p>
Some people are obviously more prone to becoming obsessed with land than others. An ethnic thing? Ancestors victimized by the Enclosure Acts may well leave a genetic marker. A male problem? Well, you could argue that. One need look no further than the phrase "virgin land" to see that long ago land was feminized in men's imaginations, and it has often been pointed out how the land has served as an escape from women. (Its roundedness more bearable, more comprehensible than theirs?) The feminist historian Annette Kolodny has traced this theme in her book The Lay of the Land, arguing that the American West has been alternately romanticized and abused in a pattern that parallels the woes of women and men.<p>
But I don't know -- all of this wants to take us toward a notion of landholding as the last bastion of that sorry and familiar figure, the aging, raging white guy. It's got to be less sordid than that. The truth is that some men and women of various persuasions seem to need the comfort of dirt beneath their feet and an eyeful of field or forest before them. It starts as simply as that. Then it gets more complicated. One trick is to achieve land poverty while avoiding actual bankruptcy. Another trick is to emerge with your conscience intact. Certain rules apply.<p>
First, a rudimentary sense of balance. Years ago an old New Hampshireman gave me some useful advice. He was talking about a neighbor of his, a wealthy man who had bought a farm and was adding to it. It stood at 400 acres and was growing, as the owner made extravagant offers for adjoining property. "The trouble with that fellow," said my mentor, "is that he hasn't figured out that you can't own your abutter." <p>
True, owning your abutter ultimately takes you from sea to shining sea. I admit my sympathies were with the gentleman farmer, who wanted only to own what he could gaze upon and maybe a little bit more. That's what I wanted in those days, too, and I haven't really outgrown the impulse.<p>
The need to have dominion over your surroundings may be one of the least attractive qualities of the landowning personality. It explains, incidentally, why the serious collector may not be especially keen on views. The better the view, after all, the more likely it is to involve abutters you cannot own. I have a bit of hilltop land. It has an old farmhouse, which needs...work, and visitors (out of kindness) seldom remark on it; they say instead, "What a nice view." It is a nice view. But it makes me a little uncomfortable. I feel easier on my lowland field, which is not a place you'd ever stop to look at if you were to pass by on the road. All I see from my field is my own tree line.<p>
Recalling now and then that you can't own your abutter can be a comforting check on desire. But the inverse is also true. Your abutter's land is the piece you most want, and when it's available you should (almost) always buy it (a serious land collector maintains a fund for this purpose). If everyone made a practice of buying his abutter instead of complaining about the person who does, then life in rural America would be truly peaceful. Recently, land adjoining me (a psychologically revealing usage, I know) came on the market. It was a strange piece, shaped more or less like a watering can, with fully 20 of its 90 acres accounted for by the spout, a corridor of land that separated two more-rational tracts, one of which is mine. I did not really want this gerrymander, but there it was, and I wanted it not in unknown hands. I was ready to go again to the bank. But happily on this hill I have a neighbor who is afflicted with the collecting impulse, too. He bought it. I was immensely grateful. My abutter bought my abutter, and since I can't own him, all is quiet again on my eastern front.<p>
An awareness of the finitude of land animates the psyche of the land buyer. But it's important to remember that Gertrude Stein was right when she said, "In the United States there is more space where nobody is than where anybody is. This is what makes America what it is." It was truer in 1936, when she said it, but it is still true today, as a cross-country flight on a clear day will remind you. This should be a cautionary fact for the land buyer, though paradoxically it usually isn't, since the very existence of wide-open spaces makes you want to own them, keep them, save them. (I experience a disorientation, a vertigo, while visiting the city, but in another sense I am free: There is no place there that I covet.) Part of the problem with the American landscape is that we have too much land, not too little, and the abundance has encouraged the sprawl that so demeans us. But the bottom line for the landowner counting assets is that there is a rational supply-and-demand reason your net worth does not seem to be mounting as fast as it might in other markets.<p>
Gertrude Stein was right, but most of our great American writers prove less than reliable sources of advice for the landowner. Buy into the American landscape and you buy into a package of cultural confusion that starts in the first European apprehension of the New World as a second Eden and continues to the latest Ralph Lauren ad. Think of Thomas Jefferson, who scorned cities, saw the new republic as a garden, and eloquently lobbied for a nation of farmers. His agrarian vision still appeals to me -- but what a lot of mischief it has caused! (Anyone who thinks about it for long knows that only in the salvation of our cities is there a hope for preserving the countryside.) Think of Mark Twain and Huck's escape to the territory. And think then, above all, of Thoreau.<p>
Henry David Thoreau was a genius, Walden is the absolutely essential American book, and never will the reader exhaust its richness, its humor, its paradox. Don't get me wrong, but Thoreau, if you consider him as the cultural icon he has become, has a lot to answer for. <p>
If there is a single idea popularly associated with Thoreau it is the value of a direct, unmediated relationship with nature. In Thoreau's woods, removed from the distortions of civilization, one can learn to "live deliberately," "to drive life into a corner, and reduce it to its lowest terms, and, if it proved to be mean, why then to get the whole and genuine meanness of it...or if it were sublime, to know it by experience."<p>
That stirring call! Who can fail to heed it, or at least to want to heed it. Thoreau dismisses not only corrupt urban existence but the agrarian life as well, in favor of a direct association with the natural world. Everyone remembers the passage early in Walden in which Thoreau has sport with those Concord residents who have had the "misfortune" to have inherited a farm: "How many a poor immortal soul have I met well-nigh crushed and smothered under its load, creeping down the road of life, pushing before it a barn seventy-ffive feet by forty, its Augean stables never cleansed, and one hundred acres of land, tillage, mowing, pasture, and woodlot!"<p>
Thoreau, wisely, was not a landowner; he borrowed the site for his cabin from Ralph Waldo Emerson. He seems to have been tempted once or twice to buy a farm, to judge by his account in Walden. He writes amusingly of actually having agreed on a price with the owner of "the Hollowell place," only to have the owner back down, offering Thoreau $10 to release him from the deal. Thoreau gallantly declines the money and imagines that he is selling the farm back to the man, for nothing: "I sold him the farm for just what I gave for it....I found thus that I had been a rich man without any damage to my poverty. But I retained the landscape, and I have since annually carried off what it yielded without a wheelbarrow."<p>
Thoreau "retained the landscape," though it ought to be said that the farmers created it. A learned paper could be written on Thoreau's relationship to farming, but my own literal-minded heart has always had a soft spot for the farmers of Concord. I have thought of them when reading Walden and when I'm in the contemporary town. With their townspeople, who had an idea of what a village street should look like, they made Concord beautiful, a beauty from which, mercifully -- despite the efforts of the 20th century -- it has not fully recovered. The farmers made Concord beautiful -- Thoreau made it sacred.<p>
The problem with Thoreau is only that his latter-day disciples think that you can have it both ways -- that you can buy into his blessed relationship with nature. Many a new landowner, as I have observed firsthand, set out literally to live a version of Walden. Such a pilgrim has doomed himself already by buying land. He will discover that you cannot live at Walden Pond. He will find himself not removed but, in some ways, more connected to the world than ever. To own land is to become implicated in what happens to it.<p>
Despite your preservationist inclinations, the overwhelming likelihood is that one day, if you own land, you'll sell some. I have and have regretted it. When I saw something built that altered the surrounding countryside for the worse, I felt as guilty as if I had done it myself.<p>
The problem is that in some higher sense you can't sell land. That is, you never quite get rid of it, even after the papers are passed. There are all sorts of practical differences between land and other assets, but perhaps the most important difference is emotional, moral. When you sell 500 shares of Intel into the market, "your" stock may be bought by a young family assembling a college-tuition portfolio or by a young drug dealer parking some cash. You don't know, and it would be insane to care. That is the freedom afforded by fungible assets.<p>
When you sell land it's a different story. You know who's buying it. You can learn, and you should, what the buyer plans to do with it. With the sale you ratify the plans. As it happens, you have extraordinary practical powers in this situation, powers that greatly exceed those of the state. You can restrict your deed to forbid further division of the land; you can even determine how many trees may be removed. If the land is to be built on, you can specify where and what, down to the siding and the pitch of the roof. All these restrictions compromise the marketability of the land, but they may not necessarily reduce its value.<p>
Once you own a piece of land you become part of its history, part of its future, and so you might as well become an active part. But landowning, which so often starts in a simple desire for refuge, can thus lead to a kind of megalomania. There is a grandiosity even in preservation, an appropriation of the commonwealth into one's own breast. The greatest contemporary land collector, Ted Turner, has said -- and one knows that he's only half joking -- "If I want to save the West I'll have to buy it."<p>
In heavy moments you ask yourself, Who am I to want to own my "viewshed"? Who am I to try to stop development? If I have more land than I need -- and pray, how much does anybody not spending full time feeding people "need"? -- then who am I to stand in the way of others? Why should I replace the wisdom of the market in allocating places in the woods?<p>
Good questions, and you should be ready to answer them. I have reached my own answers, and they have to do with the gratitude I feel toward people who kept the rural landscape intact before me and who, when they built, built wisely. It is true that the nation faces more immediate and heart-wrenching problems than preserving its hayffields. But those landscapes occupy a place in our culture, and the argument for them is the argument for opera or for art museums. They are one of the reasons we are moved to solve the other, more pressing problems -- they are one of the many pleasures awaiting those rescued from life's exigencies.<p>
I have come to think that the only answer for the landowner is to face your hubris. You wake up one day to the fact that you do have actual power over a corner of the earth and that you have to use it some way. I don't know of another small investment that so tangibly affects the world. The ultimate price and pleasure of buying land is that you have to form a vision for what's to become of it.<p>
KEYWORDS:
land, property, intellect, environment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

