		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Cover: Be Careful Out There</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Cover: Be Careful Out There</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Clint Willis<p>
Let's assume, for the sake of argument, that you don't have a few million dollars to build a diversified portfolio of properties. You have to get it right the first time. That means paying as little as possible -- and avoiding disasters. <p>
Unlike some places, the United States doesn't have a lot of unexploded land mines buried around the country. But land can still blow up. So ask these questions before you buy any property: <p>
Why is it for sale? Say the land is being sold by a bank's trust department. Chances are it's a liquidation, and the bankers have been instructed to unload the property. They want to sell the land and will be businesslike about it. <p>
Compare them to the guy liquidating his grandmother's estate. Since it was Grandma's land, he may attach sentimental value to it and expect a higher price in compensation. Then there's the couple getting a divorce who may bicker over the price and timing of the sale, or there's the land speculator with lots of time to find a buyer. <p>
How long has it been on the market? If the land has been for sale for six months or a year, the seller might be ready to entertain a lower bid than he originally hoped for. But maybe you aren't interested: A large tract of land might take a long time to sell because it's on the wrong side of town or the hunting is bad or there is a glut of similar farmland in the area...which brings us to another question. <p>
What's wrong with it? Some land cannot be used for the purposes that would make it most valuable. Say you plan to develop your land or hope to sell to a developer one day. If you're not connected to a municipal sewer system, you should probably perform a percolation ("perk") test, which costs about $200. This test measures the ability of the land to absorb water. If your property fails the test, any prospective developer will have to haul gravel onto the land to create a leach field that can support a septic system. That job could cost more than the land itself. <p>
Make your initial contract for a piece of land conditional upon inspection of the property. In addition to a perk test, you may need a survey ($20 to $50 an acre) to determine if your property includes wetlands and to identify borders. You also might want to check for hazardous waste ($1,500 and up). And you'll need a title search ($100 to $250). <p>
Will the view last? If you buy land that abuts a national park or other government-owned preserve or a wetland, you won't have to worry much about ugly buildings cropping up. At the very least, make sure that your property is big enough to shelter you from the sight of the pink house that your nearest neighbor decides to erect next year. <p>
How much will it cost to keep the land? Since you usually cannot borrow money to buy land, you might avoid debt. But you will have to pay property taxes, and you might have to cover liability insurance and upkeep, such as pruning around power lines and maintaining fences. Make sure you will have the cash -- and take into account those costs when you figure your potential return. <p>
Is it worth the trouble? Finding the right piece of land at the right price and checking it out could take scores of hours. It took us roughly 300 hours of phone calls and other research to find a dozen or so interesting properties in our price range -- and we didn't buy them, which would require still more work. <p>
Count on investing additional time and effort if your plan calls for the land to generate income. For example, you might have to find timber companies to buy your wood or tenants to live in your cabin. Try to figure out how much time that will take before you put money into a property -- and then double that. If you're still interested...don't say we didn't warn you.<p>
KEYWORDS:
property, investment, rental

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

