<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Cover: Piece of the Action</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Cover: Piece of the Action</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						A PIECE OF THE ACTION
Fifteen acres of heaven in Oregon, an ocean view in Maine, an orange grove in Florida, and a dozen other ways to turn a dream into an investment.<p>
By Clint Willis<p>
In 1957, my father and some of his friends each paid $1,200 to buy half-acre plots of woodland an hour from New Orleans. Their plan: build houses, move in with their families, and spend weekends playing volleyball and drinking bourbon-and-Cokes around a communal swimming pool.<p>
I saw the property only once, when we drove there some years later to chop down a Christmas tree. "A gangster bought some of the lots, so we never developed the land," Dad recently explained. "I sold mine 20 years later, for around $2,000."<p>
Let's see. I figure that before taxes and after inflation my father's $1,200 stake shrank around 25 percent. <p>
Fact is, it's hard to get rich buying land. Not impossible, but hard. We learned a lot of lessons when we set out to find appealing properties priced at $150,000 or less. For instance, banks don't like to lend money for raw land; state and local zoning laws can restrict use of the property; and, of course, land doesn't pay dividends. Quite the contrary: The costs of owning it -- taxes, maintenance -- can be considerable. Then absentee owners can suffer various indignities, such as the guy who decides to build a garden on your land, or the fellow who sets up a beekeeping operation there, or the homeless person who takes up residence -- or the kid who digs a tunnel in the side of a hill on your property, gets stuck, and has to be helicoptered out to a medical center. All these things happened to clients of Howard Hallengren of Falcon Real Estate Investment in New York City. When buying land, he notes dryly, "there's a lot to consider." <p>
Anything else? Land prices can be volatile, and the price direction is hard to predict: Changes in demographics, zoning, inflation, commodity prices, tax law, and luck all play a role. You can't rely on Wall Street analysts or investment newsletters to help you find and evaluate parcels for investment. And there is no central regulatory body equivalent to the Securities and Exchange Commission to oversee land and real-estate brokers or to set federal guidelines about the information brokers provide and the claims they make. <p>
You may find it impossible to assemble a diversified portfolio of land parcels, since you'll need at least $50,000 to $150,000 to buy just one promising piece. And it can be difficult to sell at any given time; thus, you may be stuck with your choice for years.<p>
In short, buying land ain't like buying a mutual fund. <p>
That said, are there any reasons to invest? <p>
Several.<p>
Land provides diversification. Stocks and bonds aren't much help during periods of rising inflation, but in some cases land can be. True, we haven't been through such a period for 16 years, and no one is looking for prices to move sharply higher this year or next. But contrarians exist, and some are interested in land. Bill Barnett, a broker with Joyner & Company in Richmond, Virginia, notes that pension funds have begun buying timberland in his state. "We didn't see pension funds buying land ten years ago," he says. <p>
It can be fun. A property can provide recreational or other uses while you're waiting for the value to appreciate. We found parcels close to sailing, fishing, skiing, hunting, hiking, and horseback riding. You might have to slap together a cabin to take advantage of these resources, but even that's not always necessary. Some parcels come with a cabin.<p>
Getting rich isn't out of the question. The fact that there aren't armies of analysts following land can work in your favor. You're more likely to stumble on neglected bargains. Also, many properties offer income opportunities that will cover taxes and other costs and perhaps boost your investment's total return.<p>
And there's always the chance you'll get lucky. Developer Lyle Anderson says that in his early days of buying and selling he made an occasional killing on raw land. "I once had a piece of property on the west side of Phoenix, several hundred acres, that the freeway ultimately went through," he says. "In 15 years, it had gone up 60 times in value." (Anderson now builds golf-course developments, such as Desert Mountain in Arizona -- over 8,000 acres with four courses and million-dollar homes.)<p>
Still, you probably shouldn't count on a freeway to bail you out. Instead, draw a bead on more fundamental issues by asking questions like: Where should I buy? What income will the land generate? What factors might affect the land's market value in the next 5, 10, or 20 years? (See "Be Careful Out There.")<p>
If after weighing all the pros and cons you decide you still want to buy land (or at least look at some parcels), turn to your local classifieds and check out for sale signs on rural roads; you might find a little gem not advertised anywhere else. We also looked in The Wall Street Journal's classified section and Islands magazine, which led us to a few properties. Most of our properties, however, were found through real-estate brokers. The Realtors Land Institute in Chicago (800-441-5263) provided the names of several hundred brokers; we called more than 30.<p>
The brokers told us again and again that it's hard to make money investing in land -- especially when you have only $150,000 to spend. But nevertheless, a number of them ended up singling out one property they -- and we -- thought might work.<p>
They often backed up their claims with numbers about timber cuttings, farm yields, taxes, and the like. And the claims weren't outlandish; if anything, they struck us as conservative. We sometimes found ourselves contemplating projections that promised -- get this -- single-digit annual returns. And not once did anyone suggest that a piece of land would double or triple in the next year. Wall Street could teach these people something about hyperbole. <p>
One way to make money in land is to buy property with development potential -- with the idea of developing it yourself (building a house on it, for example) or holding it until a real developer buys it from you. Developable land is often found on the outskirts of cities or towns in fast-growing regions. <p>
The fast-growing region that appeals to me (and everyone else) is the Pacific Northwest. I started calling brokers.<p>
Seattle? Too late. Bend, Oregon (population: 32,000), is more like it. Cool nights, low humidity, 250 days of sunshine a year, easy access to mountains, lakes, powder snow, clean rivers, and national forests. In short, telecommuter heaven. "A lot of people who do their work via fax and modem are moving here," confirms Kitty Warner, who has owned Duke Warner Realty in Bend for 30 years. <p>
Warner allows that our $150,000 may get us 20 acres 20 miles from Bend with a mountain view and easy access to skiing. But her best candidate turns out to be only seven miles outside of town: 15 acres on Gosney Road, offered for $139,500. The land is owner financed -- requiring 25 percent down and payment due in full at the end of the third year. The sellers bought a 60-acre plot and built on 30; they split the remaining acres into two parcels, including mine. Thus, the land is surrounded by other large plots. It has views of the snowcapped Cascades. I can ride horses onto 600 acres owned by the Bureau of Land Management. <p>
The property can't be divided again, so unless I want to fight zoning authorities (no way) I must abandon hopes of building a subdivision. But there is "septic feasibility" and paved access, which help. The property has been surveyed, there is a well, and it's zoned MUA-10 (multi-use agricultural). I'd have to apply for permission to work at home, but that shouldn't be a problem. Best of all, the land is 20 miles from Mount Bachelor's skiing, 25 miles from pristine trout-fishing lakes, 7 miles from the Deschutes River (white water), and 25 miles from Smith Rock (rock climbing). <p>
Expenses? I'd have to maintain the water system, trees around any power lines, and the road, including snow removal, but I could share some of those costs with my neighbors. Livestock is limited to horses, cattle, sheep, and llamas. So I could build on the land, ski every weekend, and sell when I get too old to ski. Or I could hold on to the land and sell it to a software designer from Northern California if Bend continues to grow and land prices surge. Warner figures that the parcel could appreciate between 5 and 15 percent a year. That's not bad, even after taxes of $640 a year.<p>
Back in Virginia, Bill Barnett has what might be a better idea -- if I'm willing to think like a real developer. For $97,000, he will sell me four adjacent lots totaling about 78 acres of former timberland on a state road in Fluvanna County (population: 16,000). The land is five minutes outside Palmyra, a sleepy village that is 20 miles from Charlottesville and 60 miles from Richmond. The owner (a timber company) will finance 75 percent of the purchase at 11 percent.<p>
Why Fluvanna County? Barnett says people from Richmond and Charlottesville are moving to the countryside between those two cities in search of better value and a more rural lifestyle. Writer John Grisham has a place in Albemarle County, which is about a 30-minute drive from my plot. And billionaire John Kluge has bought more than 10,000 acres south of Charlottesville during the past 15 years or so. The county even has vineyards -- surely a sign of a yuppie haven in the making. <p>
Also, Motorola has bought a site 40 minutes away. The company plans to build a $3 billion microchip factory that will eventually employ 5,000 people. Fluvanna County also has taken steps to reduce the amount and raise the quality of development; this ought to help support the value of lots already approved. <p>
The wooded parcels themselves stand on an elevated ridge across the road from a pasture and, on a clear day, offer views of the distant Blue Ridge Mountains. The land is surveyed, a driveway has been built, and the soil test has been done. Taxes are negligible: $111 a year for all four plots. Barnett won't commit to predicting the rise in value of this particular parcel, but he says a well-selected property should double in value within five years. <p>
Now we're talking, and I'm getting even more ambitious. Jeff Wooster, a broker in Bar Harbor, Maine, says he has 54 acres in Ellsworth (population: 6,200). Ellsworth is the gateway to Acadia National Park on Mount Desert Island, which receives over four million visitors every year; it's also a commercial center for the area. The land is in a suburban residential neighborhood about a mile from downtown Ellsworth. It will cost me $125,000 or so; I can spend the other $25,000 in my budget building a road, doing tests, and getting approvals to divide the land.<p>
Wooster has a plan: Let's say I create 40 plots, which I then sell for $15,000 apiece. I offer owner financing, selling for $5,000 down and financing the other $10,000 at 10 percent over ten years. The down payments alone yield $200,000 (assuming I sell all the plots), and I get another $65,098 a year in loan payments. At the end of the decade, I have made $850,000 on my $150,000 investment. Before taxes, that comes to around 19 percent a year -- which is almost double the historic return of blue-chip stocks.<p>
Could be risky. Maybe I should buy the land and wait for a real developer to get interested in Wooster's plan.<p>
Land on the ocean or a lake-shore is likely to rise in value as baby boomers start buying second or vacation homes. Trouble is, that land is already too expensive for someone with only $150,000 to spend. <p>
Or so I figured. Mostly I was right, but Jeff Wooster came up with another idea. For $149,000, I can have four acres of land with 200 feet of shore frontage in tony Bar Harbor -- renowned vacation spot for upper-crust New Englanders and a hot spot for tourists during the high season. I've heard enough about Bar Harbor and its affluent denizens to be surprised at the low price. Besides, the place has access to great sailing, fishing, hiking, rock climbing, and sea kayaking. <p>
This property, incidentally, has a modest three-season cabin tucked away in a corner that I can rent out or use myself. But I'm really interested in the land. It has enough room for a larger, year-round house. Thus, it may be easy to resell to someone with real money -- Bar Harbor money -- or I can sell a portion of the lot and keep the cottage for myself. <p>
Feeling greedy, I decide to see if I can buy a whole island. Mary Reid, a salesperson with the Muljat Group in Bellingham, Washington, says that she recently sold a piece of an island -- "a few acres of rock out in the open" -- for $250,000, and that she knows of a bigger island with an airstrip and appraised at $1.65 million.<p>
Could I do better closer to home? I work in Portland, Maine. Portland has its harbor on Casco Bay, which has some 360 islands of its own. Ralph Ashmore, a local broker, tells me I can have a half to one and a half acres on an island for $100,000 to $190,000.<p>
His best idea: For $119,900 (reduced from $124,000), I can have just a bit more than half an acre facing the ocean on the back side of Peaks Island, a 15-minute ferry ride from Portland. I can buy the land and invest $200,000 or so to build a four-season home and live there year-round (the kids can commute to school on the ferry). Or I can buy the land and hold it with the idea of building or selling later. A trip out to the island, a chat with brokers there, and a walk around the property tell me I'll regret not buying this. The summer-rental market is strong; a house on my property might fetch $1,200 a week. Of course, together the land and house will cost me more than $300,000. Still, water views, lighthouses, rocky shores, the sound of the ocean.<p>
Before I set out to find a farm to buy, I talked to my friend Einar, who grew up on a beef farm in northwestern Pennsylvania. Einar warned me of cattails, which indicate unfarmable wetlands; of Budweiser-swilling hunters, who at the end of a deerless day don't always draw the line at cow murder (during hunting season, Einar dresses his dog in a yellow vest and ties it to the house); and of gory accidents (a neighbor lost a foot to a bushhog). "Don't do it," he warns.<p>
Ignoring Einar, I set out posthaste. After all, I just want to make some money off farmland. I don't actually want to be a farmer. Most people who set out to buy a farm for investment look for one that might find itself in the path of residential or other development. Meanwhile, they contract with real farmers to rent the land from them. <p>
Terry Riley, a broker in eastern Maryland who specializes in farmland, tells me to look for property with good road frontage and no wetlands (watch for cattails). Trees can be a problem: You or the developer may have to chop them down later. Zoning is an issue: How many houses could a developer put on the land? <p>
I also must find something to do with the farm while I'm waiting for it to appreciate. The obvious solution is to lease the farming rights -- but in some places that barely covers taxes. In other regions, you can lease the land's hunting rights for as much as $10,000 a year. (The Eastern Shore of Maryland is good for this; western Pennsylvania isn't.) <p>
Riley can't think of anything that's selling for less than $300,000 -- and neither can any other brokers I call in his neighborhood. Calls to Iowa and Wisconsin yield nothing much. A broker in Walla Walla, Washington, a town of 28,870 with the oldest continuous symphony orchestra west of the Mississippi, says he might be able to find me a 30-acre parcel on which to grow concord grapes -- my own vineyard! -- but doesn't. <p>
I do better in Minnesota. Howard Sturm, a broker in Cannon Falls, can sell me 121 acres in Kenyon, a town of about 1,400 people 50 minutes outside of Minneapolis. The seller wants $200,000, but I can borrow $50,000 of it at 8 percent over 15 years. The land is suitable for soybeans or field corn; it has a "crop-equivalency rating" of 88 to 90. Sturm informs me that anything higher than 75 is considered good, so I should not have a problem renting the land to a farmer or contracting with the local Green Giant factory, which will buy my product and provide the seed.<p>
Sturm figures I could own and manage the farm from Maine. All I need to do is come out once and meet some farmers who will rent from me; Sturm will find them and help me develop a crop plan. Doing it this way, he figures, I'll earn $13,920 a year. That is a 7 percent return -- before taxes ($2,080), disaster insurance ($464), and interest on the loan ($2,509). Those costs bring the annual return down to 4.4 percent.<p>
If I'm willing to hire a farmer to plant and harvest on my behalf -- I take the risk and get all the profit -- I might earn as much as $45,240. Subtract $20,880 for expenses such as seeding, fertilizing, weed control, and harvesting, then trim for taxes, insurance, and interest payments on the loan, and I'm left with a 9.7 percent return.<p>
Land broker Barbara Douglas in Winter Haven, Florida, has a warmer proposition: a 6.5-acre orange grove outside Winter Haven (population: 25,000) on the shores of Lake Confusion. Asking price: $65,000. <p>
The grove should produce 400 boxes of Valencia oranges an acre -- about $16,250 a year at $6.25 a box. After annual expenses of $1,640 an acre for fertilizer, weed control, harvesting, and taxes, I'd have around $5,590 left. That's an 8.6 percent annual return, excluding insurance, while I think about whether I want to develop the land or sell to someone who will. <p>
Douglas reckons I can divide the property into 15 lots of 15,000 square feet each. That leaves 20 percent of the acreage for road frontage. Then I could sell all of the lots for roughly $20,000 apiece -- a total of $300,000, for a $235,000 profit and roughly a 292 percent total return. That assumes I sell the lots, of course -- but with Winter Haven developing into a bedroom community for Orlando and Tampa, prospects could be good.<p>
My father refused to take me hunting during my youth in south Louisiana. But for $150,000 I figure I can buy a property to rival the hunting estates of the early Russian nobles. <p>
Having read William Faulkner's story "The Bear" as a youngster, I start my search in the South. It turns out that buying raw land just for hunting can be very expensive; in fact, I might be better off leasing land from someone else for a few bucks an acre each year. Then Mike Callaway, president of Land Brokers in Ringgold, Georgia, suggests another way to make buying the land worthwhile: Sell the trees on it. "We've seen a dramatic increase in the value of forest products on hunting lands," he says. Callaway recommends that anyone buying rural land with trees call the Association of Consulting Foresters of America (703-548-0990); the organization will suggest a qualified forester who can appraise trees.<p>
Broker Harold Hudgens Jr. -- Huddy to his friends -- of the Albany Land Company in Albany, Georgia, notes that most hunting properties in his region fetch more than my paltry $150,000 stake. But after some rummaging, he finds a 273-acre parcel 25 miles outside of Albany (population: 113,000). The price just happens to be $150,000. About 198 acres is cutover woodlands. He says the remaining 75 acres is suitable for such crops as cotton, soybeans, peanuts, and wheat. Deer, turkey, and dove abound.<p>
For income, I can rent out the cropland at $25 an acre annually; that's $1,875. Then I can rent out hunting rights for the property at around $15 an acre each year; that comes to another $4,095. Annual taxes: $1,095. <p>
Tommy Bell -- a consulting forester in Blakely, Georgia -- tells me I can add to my income if I plant timber at a cost of around $75 an acre. The first cutting, in ten years, will earn me an estimated $95,550. The second cutting, in 21 years, will earn about $143,000. <p>
As near as I can make out, that's about a 6.1 percent annual return over the next decade. I might do a bit better if the fees I charge for farming and hunting rights rise with inflation. Hudgens figures I'll get at least another 3 percent in annual appreciation from the land, even if inflation remains low. <p>
An advertisement in The Wall Street Journal leads me north to Dan Christmas, president of Christmas & Associates, a land-acquisition and sales company in Tupper Lake, New York. Christmas tells me that the western Adirondacks are getting attention from European buyers who want investments with good long-term growth potential. He also notes that film star Patrick Swayze was rumored to have looked at some land in the area back in 1995. What's more, demand for the region's hardwood trees is the highest it has been in several years. As a result, land prices have edged up approximately 10 percent since 1992 -- but they're still well below their peaks back in the late 1980s. <p>
Christmas's best offering: 200 acres near Cranberry Lake, some 45 minutes from Lake Placid (site of the 1980 Winter Olympics). Price: $149,000. The acreage is about six hours from New York City and six miles from the nearest major road. It's surrounded by great tracts of paper-company land, so parcels this size rarely come on the market in the area. <p>
The state-owned Five Ponds Wilderness is two miles away; it's a great place to canoe and go fly-fishing. There are plenty of grouse and deer for hunters, and the property has a good trout pond. "This is 200 beautiful acres in an area where real estate has been depressed," says Christmas. "It's like buying stock in Coke after a bad quarter." <p>
Christmas figures I can lease the land to hunting and fishing clubs in the area for around $6 an acre; that's $1,200 a year. And if I'm willing to let loggers cut 30 percent of the spruce, balsam, cherry, yellow birch, and other trees on the property, I can hope to clear $100,000 right away and another $100,000 in ten years, when I let them cut again. <p>
But let's say I don't want to log the land. The trees will add some value -- perhaps $2,000 a year -- simply by growing. If I build a cabin, I can rent it out part of the year for maybe $3,000 or more. Annual expenses will amount to around $1,000 or so a year for road maintenance and $5 to $7 an acre in taxes. Total annual return: 20 percent if I let someone log the land and a meager 3 percent if I don't. <p>
There's a lot of property out there. How about 270 acres of ranchland in southern Colorado for $159,900? The land is surrounded by 8,000 acres owned by the Bureau of Land Management, offers views of the snowcapped Sangre de Cristo Mountains and Spanish Peaks, and is ideal for horses, skiing, and mountain biking, says Sarah Harsch, an agent in La Veta, Colorado. Billy Long of William Long & Associates in Aspen tells me I can find more ranches in my price range in relatively isolated places like western Idaho.<p>
Then there's Alaska. Stuart Watkins, a broker in Anchorage, says I can pay $110,000 (cash only) for 160 acres west of Soldatna, on the Kenai Peninsula -- great fishing country south of Anchorage. "There's road access, so you could put up a subdivision with lots of room for recreation," says Watkins. <p>
But I don't want to become an Alaskan real-estate developer. No problem. Watkins has 40 acres in Talkeetna -- a jumping-off point for the climbers who attempt Mount McKinley each year. Or I can have 80 acres in the outback for $150,000. The land includes a mine. "I had some friends who bought a mine and found a hunk of gold as big as my hand," says Watkins. "They traded it for a Caterpillar tractor so they could keep mining." <p>
What happened? The mine flooded, and the tractor was ruined. Like the man said: There's a lot to consider<p>
Additional reporting by Sean Donahue, Mark Klimek, and Carol Pickering.<p>
KEYWORDS:
property, investment, bargain, deal, environment, development

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

