				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Personal Adviser:  Judgment Day Is Too Far Away</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Is your appeal no longer appealing? Cash up front might help.<p>
By Teri Karush Rogers<p>
Even after losing at trial, deep-pocketed defendants have been known to appeal cases endlessly, forcing strapped opponents into skimpy settlements. Now little-guy plaintiffs can take heart: San Franciscobased Judgment Purchase Corp. will chip in -- for a stake in the spoils.<p>
Let's say your $1 million judgment is appealed, and you barely have money for gas, let alone legal expenses. You call JPC, which judges your case winnable (as it does in only 20 percent of the cases thrown its way) and offers you, in a typical example, $200,000 in exchange for $300,000 out of any money you collect. After paying your lawyers, you keep whats left of the 200 grand. If you win your appeal, you give JPC $300,000 from your settlement. And if you lose, you owe bupkes.<p>
KEYWORDS:
court, litigation, trial

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

