<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Personal Adviser:  Tainted Paint</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Personal Adviser:  Tainted Paint</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						New rules force home sellers to disclose lead hazards<p>
By Kathleen Murray<p>
If you don't have young children, you probably haven't worried about lead paint in your home, but a new law may change that. Under federal regulations that took effect late in 1996, anyone selling a home built before 1978 (when lead paint was banned) must now disclose to the buyer knowledge of lead-based paint and its hazards on the property. <p>
Government officials estimate that nearly two-thirds of these pre-1978 homes (about 64 million) contain lead. That isn't necessarily a danger; lead paint is usually not hazardous unless it is chipping, peeling, or released in the air during remodeling. But high concentrations of lead can damage the brain, central nervous system, and kidneys, particularly in children under six. <p>
Before you have your home tested or the lead removed, however, you should understand what the law does and does not require. First, it doesn't require you to have your home tested for lead. If your house is on the market, you have to tell the buyer about lead paint only if you're aware of its presence. "The answer may be 'I don't know,'" says Daryl Jesperson, executive vice president with realty company Re/Max International. "And that's perfectly fine and legal."<p>
The risk you run is that a problem may come to light before the sale is final. The regulations allow the buyer ten days to have the house inspected for lead; the discovery of lead could affect the price or even scotch the sale. And once you know this information, it must be passed on to other prospective buyers. <p>
Patrick Connor, a lead inspector in Baltimore, estimates that 60 percent of his residential business in the past year has been from sellers who want to find lead before it can hurt their home's market value. "You're not going to have the EPA lead police out there," he says. "But you're going to have consumers who walk if they don't like what they see."<p>
Getting a home tested for lead will cost $200 to $400. If it's a home you want to buy, you may be able to get it done more cheaply as part of your home inspection. If you live in one of the 17 states that have lead-certification programs, you should hire a certified inspector. Otherwise, look for an inspector who has completed the EPA-required curriculum. For information and referrals on qualified inspectors, call the National Lead Abatement Council at 301-924-0804 or the National Lead Information Center at 800-424-5323. Or try HUD's lead-information Web page at http://www.hud.gov/lea/leahome.html, which also provides referrals on inspectors.<p>
A basic inspection will identify areas where lead is a problem and suggest a plan of action. Beware of evaluators who immediately recommend complete removal, also known as abatement, which can cost $10,000 or more. Some cities require abatement under certain circumstances, but removal should be considered only as a last resort. "Unless the house is completely dilapidated, abatement is usually more risk than it's worth because it generates a lot of dust," says Stephen Weil of the National Lead Abatement Council. <p>
Often you can reduce the lead to a safe level simply by having a contaminated area professionally treated; this runs about $200 (you can do it yourself for about $50). Connor also recommends using ski wax on painted wooden window frames and spraying Teflon on painted hinges as safeguards to keep paint from chipping.
"The point is not to be lead free but lead safe," says Connor. "And everything you need to do that you can usually buy at the Home Depot."<p>
KEYWORDS: 
mortgage, real estate, homeowner, upkeep

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
