<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Year-End Checkup</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Year-End Checkup</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Keep your medical and savings plans in good shape<p>
By John Fried<p>
Planning a little year-end housecleaning? Your employee benefits deserve as much attention as your basement or closet. The end of the year is the deadline for opening many savings plans, and it marks the season of open enrollment for many employee-benefits options. That means now is the time to make sure you're taking advantage of what you've got and to make your changes for the upcoming year. Investigating these options should help you close 1996 with a solid "just did it" rather than a regretful "should've done that."<p>
Open a flexible spending account if your company offers this valuable option. Flexible spending accounts allow you to set aside pretax money that can be used to reimburse you for almost any medical expense except cosmetic surgery. The money is deducted from your paycheck on a regular basis, but the flex account is credited with the full year's balance on January 1. A common strategy: Put enough in the flex account so that it covers your medical deductible for the year.<p>
These accounts must be established for 1997 by year-end. You cannot, however, roll over money from your flex account from year to year. "In simple terms, use it or lose it," says Paul Fronstin, a health-care economist at Employee Benefit Research Institute.<p>
If you already have a flex account and haven't used all your money for 1996, make an appointment with the dentist or buy yourself an extra pair of reading glasses. That's your money in there, and if you don't spend it now, it goes back into your company's coffers at the beginning of next year.<p>
Many employers offer similar flex plans for child-care expenses, such as day care. These expenses are generally easier to estimate on a yearly basis because they involve regular weekly or monthly costs. The Internal Revenue Service has set a limit for dependent-care accounts of $5,000. (Regular flex accounts have no such IRS limits, though employers usually limit them to about $5,000.)<p>
Reassess your 401(k) plan. Many employers require you to make changes to your account now for the following year. "There are two basic decisions to consider when you're rethinking your 401(k) plan," says Paul Yakoboski, a benefits expert from EBRI: "How much you are putting in and how that money is invested." Most financial planners agree that you should put in at least as much as your company will match. In addition, Yakoboski suggests that employees assess their plan's asset-allocation method and consider whether their money is properly invested for their expected retirement needs. (For more information on allocating assets in a 401(k), see "Making It Personal" in the November issue of Worth.)<p>
If you already have a 401(k) plan established for this year but wish you could put more money into the account before the end of the year, it may not be too late. Some employers allow employees to increase their contribution or add a lump sum before year-end.<p>
Rethink your company's choices in health benefits, particularly if you're expecting a big change in your medical expenses next year. Perhaps you have a child who needs braces. Orthodontics may be covered at different rates under different plans offered by your company. Or perhaps you're expecting a baby and the obstetrician you want to use isn't in your HMO. In a case like that, it might be worthwhile to switch to a point-of-service plan or a preferred-provider organization, each of which allows you to go outside the program's network for an additional expense. Given that HMOs tend to cost more up front, leaving the HMO may pay for the increase in unreimbursable doctor's bills. If your expenses return to normal next year, and the HMO becomes the best option again, you can always switch back.<p>
And finally, if you earn income outside your regular job or are self-employed, consider self-employment plans (SEPs) or Keoghs as retirement-savings opportunities. Even if you cannot put money in one immediately, a 1997 Keogh account must be set up by year-end. Any money you put in before April 15, 1997, can be deducted from your 1996 taxes. A SEP can be set up any time before April 15, but you must decide between the two before the end of this year.<p>
KEYWORDS: 
finance, bills, budget<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

