<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Modem Operandi</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Modem Operandi</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Now ten years old, E-banking is ready to take off<p>
By Jeff Blyskal<p>
More than a decade ago, when Citibank's automation ber alles policy put human tellers on the road to extinction, the Citi sank some $100 million into banking by home computer. It was the next logical step for inhuman banking. It was paperless, even bricks-and-mortarless. It was also a flop, because only 13 percent of households had a PC at the dawn of home computing.<p>
But Citibank's hallucinations have finally proved visionary. The rest of the world has caught up. Nearly 40 percent of American households now own a PC, and 26 percent have a modem. Not surprisingly, E-banks are sprouting like Web sites: More than 50 institutions now offer online banking. One bank serving customers in all 50 states, Security First Network Bank (<A HREF="http://www.sfnb.com">http://www.sfnb.com</A>), exists almost exclusively on a server computer in Atlanta. SFNB has $14 million in deposits in almost 5,000 accounts opened through its Web site; it also has two physical branches, in Atlanta and Pineville, Kentucky.<p>
The explosion in the number of electronic banks isn't the only reason to think this technology is poised to take off. The major drawback of E-banking is that your PC won't accept or dispense cash, but magnetic-cash-card technology is in the works. Next year in New York City, Citibank and <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan</b></a> plan to launch smart cards that have a computer chip able to store up to 100 digital dollars. The cards will work at point-of-sale terminals much like ATM cards can now be used at supermarkets and gas stations. This could be the technology E-banking needs to make it the system of choice for bank customers.<p>
All E-bank accounts let customers do pretty much the same things: make direct deposits, pay bills, check balances, transfer funds, maintain a balance ledger. Paying bills with paper checks and other hard-copy transactions are still permitted, too. Online banks typically let customers open and manage other accounts at the same bank as well -- credit cards, loans, certificates of deposit. Institutions accessible through Quicken or Microsoft Money (for Windows 95) let users download account data directly from the bank. <p>
Competition will take place almost solely on the basis of price. Banks that exist primarily online -- like SFNB and Oneonta, New Yorkbased Wilber National Bank (<A HREF="www.wilberbank.com">www.wilberbank.com</A>) -- charge only basic checking-account fees. Other banks, including Chase, <a name="NYSE:PNC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11138"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PNC</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:WFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11619"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wells Fargo</b></a>, require customers to open an old-fashioned checking account plus an online link to that account; they hit the customer for fees on both, with fees for the E-account ranging from $4.95 to $7.95 per month. A typical consumer -- with 21 bills and other payments, four deposits, and four ATM withdrawals per month, keeping an average daily balance of about $1,800 -- can pay as little as nothing to as much as $161 a year for an E-account, versus zero to $132 for regular checking at nine banks we studied.<p>
For now, E-banking appeals mainly to young, upscale customers -- just the sort banks are eager to entice. "PC-banking users are a very attractive customer base, because the more they get into using their PC, the more likely they'll consolidate their accounts with you," says Neal Chambliss, a group vice president at PSI, a financial-research firm based in Tampa. Once you're in the electronic tent, the bank can get you to buy a CD or sign up for a credit card -- the relationship thing. No wonder farsighted Citibank charges nothing for its PC Banking.<p>
KEYWORDS: 
e-banking, electronic banking, account

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

