	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Do This Now: Get College Credit</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Do This Now: Get College Credit</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Apply for scholarship money through the Internet<p>
By Ellen DePasquale<p>
Are you looking at a college-tuition bill that causes you to consider taking a second mortgage? Before you head to the bank, take a seat at your computer; the Internet could be your safety net. Countless Web sites offer information on financial aid from a wealth of resources. You can find government assistance, information on individual schools, scholarship-search firms, and searchable online databases. <p>
Perhaps the most comprehensive site is FinAid, the Financial Aid Information Page (<a HREF="http://www.finaid.com">http://www.finaid.com</A>), which is sponsored by the National Association of Student Financial Aid Administrators. FinAid offers numerous links for every financial-aid category listed above and is well organized and easy to navigate. Another helpful site is fastWEB (<a HREF="http://www.fastweb.com">http://www.fastweb.com</A>). Its primary attraction is a searchable database of scholarships from around the country. The database asks for relevant information, including the student's name, address, age, sex, grade-point average, selected major, first choice in schools, hobbies, work experience, and any military participation by the student or his or her parents. My search took approximately 15 minutes and returned 11 scholarship opportunities to apply for. Lastly, stop by the U.S. Department of Education (<a HREF="http://www.ed.gov/">http://www.ed.gov/</A>) for the Student Guide to Financial Aid, which offers various helpful sections, from "Finding Out About Financial Aid" to "Applying" to "Choosing a School Carefully."
KEYWORDS:Internet, college, university, Internet

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
