<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-Against All Odds</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Against All Odds</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						After all the partisanship, 1996 brought serious legislation that will affect how you save, buy, and retire -- and 1997 could be just as busy<p>
By Morey Stettner<p>
As President Bill Clinton faces off against a Republican-controlled Senate and House of Representatives for the next two years, citizens may be expecting an avalanche of overheated rhetoric and political posturing accompanied by very little actual legislation. But if the first two years of Newt Gingrich's Republican Congress were any indication, partisan squabbling does not always mean gridlock.<p>
Skeptical? Consider a surprising truth: The Republican 104th Congress passed a flurry of laws that will have a long-lasting impact on how you plan for retirement, pay your taxes, and make decisions when buying insurance. Recent legislation has also created consumer safeguards in a host of areas. Here's how to make the most of the new laws in 1997, along with other changes that might be in store in the year ahead. <p>
Tax incentives for saving <p>
With the help of the 104th Congress, you can stash away more money now for your retirement later. Several new laws offer new opportunities for tax-deferred savings. <p>
The enormous law that increased the minimum wage -- the Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996 -- also created dozens of tax breaks. For example, the law raises the maximum amount that a nonworking spouse can put into a spousal individual retirement account from $250 to $2,000 -- effective in tax years after 1996. That makes a one-earner couple's new total contribution limit $4,000 (or $2,000 per spouse). <p>
The expanded limits apply even if the IRA is not tax-deductible, which is the case for savers who also participate in a qualified retirement plan at work or who do not meet IRS income standards. Couples who don't invest the full $2,000 apiece may want to allocate the larger share of the IRA contribution to the younger spouse to delay required distributions in later years.<p>
Highly paid family members who work for the same employer also get a break for their retirement planning. Under the old "family-aggregation rules," married couples working for the same company couldn't contribute as much to their 401(k)s as individuals could. Those rules are repealed for tax years beginning after 1996. "Before this law, married people and their kids under 19 were treated as one individual for purposes of compensation," says Joseph Unger, a tax partner at M. R. Weiser & Co., an accounting firm in New York. "As a result, their contribution to a qualified retirement plan was aggregated. Now you are no longer put at a disadvantage for being married if you work at the same firm. The law puts married couples on par with other employees at the company."<p>
The minimum-wage law also cut some slack for higher-paid employees who want to beef up their 401(k)s. Prior to the law, some highly compensated workers were not allowed to  invest the annual maximum ($9,500 in 1996) in their 401(k)s. That's because those earning a salary of more than $66,000 a year and in the top 20 percent of their company's earners could not contribute proportionately more to a 401(k) than lower-paid employees. The limit has now been raised to $80,000. The proportion of employees considered to be highly compensated affects the maximum contribution, but in general, if the company's plan allows for a contribution of, say, 10 percent, an employee making $80,000 used to be able to contribute no more than $6,600. Now that person can contribute up to $8,000.<p>
And more people can join the 401(k) party. The law allows millions of employees of trade associations and other nonprofits to have 401(k) plans instead of less flexible 403(b) plans.<p>
The law lets IRA holders wait longer to begin tapping their savings. Plan participants were previously forced to begin withdrawing IRA funds by April 1 of the calendar year after they turned 70 and a half. Now, if they keep working beyond that age (and they own less than 5 percent of their own business), they can wait until the year they retire to receive plan distributions. Employed septuagenarians who do not need IRA money right away can let the funds grow tax-deferred for as long as they continue to work.<p>
"Most people don't want to be drawing down their pension while they're still working," says David Certner, senior coordinator of economic issues for the American Association of Retired Persons. "This postpones it until they actually do retire."<p>
Tinkering with Social Security<p>
Seniors who choose to continue working between the ages of 65 and 69 have another reason to cheer: They'll get more Social Security benefits. A law that passed in March raised from $11,520 to $13,500 the cap above which Social Security recipients start to lose a dollar in benefits for every three dollars they earn, and this limit will increase to $30,000 by 2002. <p>
Another new law eliminates Social Security's check-in-the-mail method of payment. New Social Security beneficiaries who have a bank account are now paid electronically through direct deposit. By 1999, all current beneficiaries will have to use direct deposit, too.<p>
"We're working with the banking industry to promote direct deposit as a safer and more efficient way to get  Social Security benefits," says Tom Margenau, spokesman for the Social Security Administration in Baltimore. Margenau says it costs 42.5 cents to mail a paper check, but only 2.5 cents to pay by direct deposit. The Social Security Administration expects to save $115 million a year by 1999 by paying beneficiaries electronically.<p>
Retirement Savings Plans<p>
Lump-sum distributions from retirement plans used to be frowned on by the government: Anyone withdrawing more than $155,000 in one year faced a so-called excess-distribution penalty of 15 percent. But another aspect of the minimum-wage law opens a three-year window for retirees to take out their savings without facing the penalty.<p>
"This is an opportunity for people with large balances in their plans to pull that money out without getting socked," says Dennis Coleman, principal at Kwasha Lipton, an employee-benefits consulting firm in Fort Lee, New Jersey. "The primary rationale for the government doing this is to raise revenue. A lot of people will use these three years to withdraw lots of money. And those withdrawals will be taxed. This means the government will collect more tax sooner. It's really a way to accelerate tax revenue." The penalty will be reinstated in 1999.<p>
Unger warns that one provision of the law is more curse than blessing for taxpayers. After December 31, 1999, taxpayers can no longer use five-year averaging to reduce taxes on lump-sum pension withdrawals. Five-year averaging allows taxpayers to receive a pension payout all at once but treat  it as taxable over a five-year period. "It's a negative move, because five-year averaging is very beneficial," Unger explains. "They repealed it because it was too complicated, and they wanted tax simplification. But it does not help. If anything, it'll cost some taxpayers money."<p>
Insurance as a Tax Write-Off<p>
Most people treat insurance simply as a financial necessity. But the Health  Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 -- better known as the KennedyKassebaum bill -- tosses some tax breaks into the mix.<p>
This modest stab at health-insurance reform makes health benefits more portable for job switchers and offers a particularly appealing prize for the self-employed: bigger tax deductions. Starting in 1997, self-employed workers can deduct up to 40 percent of their health-care expenses; the deduction increases to a whopping 80 percent in 2006. The law also lets individuals withdraw IRA funds without penalty prior to age 59 and a half to pay medical expenses that exceed 7.5 percent of adjusted gross income. <p>
New tax breaks are now in place for people who buy long-term-care insurance, which helps cover extended stays in nursing homes as well as ongoing custodial care. Starting in 1997, premiums for long-term-care insurance will be partially tax-deductible as a medical expense -- the older you are, the more you can deduct. Counting long-term-care policies as a medical expense will make it easier for many older taxpayers to surpass the threshold -- 7.5 percent of adjusted gross income -- above which they may start deducting medical expenses. Employer-paid premiums will not count as income for an employee.<p>
In addition, up to $175 a day in long-term-care benefits will be tax-free, and the limit will be indexed for inflation after 1997. Similarly, chronically ill individuals can exclude from tax $175 a day in accelerated life-insurance benefits. This will enable policyholders to get cash from their life-insurance policies while they're alive.<p>
Until now, it was unclear whether proceeds on so-called viatical settlements -- in which terminally ill individuals sell their life-insurance contracts in exchange for lump-sum payouts on part of the death benefit -- were taxable. The law makes the benefits tax-free to those defined as terminally or chronically ill. <p>
Consumer Protection<p>
Congress is often reluctant to enact new consumer laws for fear of alienating some deep-pocketed segment of the business community. But certain industries are handy punching bags for politicians, especially when their constituents complain about shoddy treatment. For example, new legislation makes it easier for consumers to evaluate the terms of a deal when buying a home or leasing a car. <p>
A year-end spending bill that Clinton signed on September 30 simplifies home-mortgage disclosure forms. "Instead of all the duplicative disclosure statements that list all the things you'll have to pay, the new law requires the Federal Reserve Board and HUD to come up with a one-page summary," says David Runkel, communication director of the House Banking Committee. "All mortgage firms will have to use the same, simple form."<p>
Disclosure forms for auto leases will also be easier to decipher. As of October 1, 1997, auto dealers and finance companies must clearly reveal the numbers that determine lease payments. Consumers will be able to ascertain the gross cost of a vehicle, its residual value, and the lease fees and other charges that inflate the monthly payment.<p>
The same law also regulates misleading lease ads. "There have been a lot of complaints about auto leasing," Runkel says. "Ads will be policed more carefully so that they provide set information on the total amount of the lease over the life of the lease, not just come-ons for low monthly payments."<p>
The mother of all consumer bugaboos -- credit bureaus -- also received some long-overdue congressional attention. Beginning in October 1997, consumers will find it easier to correct errors on their credit reports and learn when their credit history has been used against them -- say, to deny them insurance coverage or an apartment lease. In an acknowledgment of how irritating it can be to phone a credit bureau, the law requires these companies to set up toll-free numbers where callers can easily reach a live person, not just descend into automated Touch-Tone hell.<p>
Speaking of 800 numbers, one of the last laws passed by the 104th Congress established a toll-free hot line through which consumers can research the background of  a financial planner. "When you are picking a financial planner or investment adviser, one of the things you can do is check out  the person's background to determine if he or she has any previous enforcement action, lawsuits, arbitration cases, or any history of misconduct," says Jeff Duncan, legislative director for Representative Edward Markey, one of the law's sponsors. "You can already get information on a stockbroker using the NASD hot line [800-289-9999], but you cannot get information on a financial planner unless he is also registered as a stockbroker, which many are not." The new hot line should be ready some time in 1997. Duncan says that the number will probably be the same as the NASD hot line, but that has not been firmly established. <p>
The New Congress: Looking Ahead<p>
The 105th Congress is expected to grapple with tax reform, the privatization of Social Security, and the continuing health-insurance crisis. Beltway insiders who track legislation expect some hotly contested debates.<p>
"It'll be a big Congress for taxes," predicts Bill Mattea, legislative director for Senator Carol Moseley-Braun of the Senate Finance Committee. "Last year we went through this whole Congress without any significant change to the tax code, yet there was lots of talk about major changes. At the same time, ordinary people are paying much more in payroll taxes than in income taxes. That's something that'll be discussed in more detail in 1997."<p>
Then there's the perennial fight over the capital-gains tax cut. James Wickett, tax-policy analyst for the National Federation of Independent Business, says 1997 could bring a "technical-correction package" to the Small Business Job Protection Act that could both fix some legalistic, technical mistakes in the law and break new ground. "I wouldn't be surprised if the capital-gains tax cut was considered as part of that package," he says.<p>
Representative Bill Archer, chair of the House Ways and Means Committee, has declared that his top two priorities in 1997 are a capital-gains tax cut and a child's tax credit. "We will also continue our efforts to abolish the tax code itself," adds Ari Fleischer, the committee's spokesman.<p>
At the same time, Social Security's future will take center stage. A caucus co-chaired by Representatives Jim Kolbe and Charles Stenholm is exploring market-oriented solutions, such as privatization. And Congress will propose a number of new bills to prolong Social Security's financial survival. <p>
"You will hear the words 'Social Security' a lot this year," says Michael Tanner, director of health and welfare studies at the Cato Institute. "But nothing will pass in the 105th Congress. These things take a few years to move through the system. My guess is that by 1999 a privatization law will pass." Clinton has talked of appointing a bipartisan commission to map out recommendations for Social Security's future, but the last such panel, chaired by Senators Bob Kerrey and John Danforth in 1994, didn't result in any action. Any real changes in Social Security will emerge from Congress.<p>
On the health-insurance front, Clinton has far less grandiose goals than his 1992 promise to extend coverage to the much-ballyhooed 37 million uninsured Americans. Now he proposes to guarantee six months of insurance to those who lose their jobs and to offer coverage to one million poor children. Senators John Kerry and Edward Kennedy have introduced a bill that would subsidize premiums for working-class families who can't afford private insurance but whose incomes are too high for Medicaid. Outgoing Labor secretary Robert Reich has also suggested a law to help retirees at risk of losing the health insurance provided by their former employers, although the mechanism for doing so has yet to be worked out. <p>
Finally, a bipartisan consensus is emerging to expand IRAs. "There has been discussion to convert existing IRAs into new IRAs you can use to buy a first home or fund college tuition," says Mark Luscombe, principal analyst at tax publisher CCH in Chicago. "Proposals by both Clinton and the Republicans can make possible the use of even nondeductible IRA funds on a tax-favored basis -- one more reason to get into a nondeductible IRA now." <p>
Some of these ideas may appear a little unlikely given a president and Congress that don't seem to have many goals in common. But if Clinton continues to appropriate Republican themes to secure his place atop America's political center, and if a defanged Newt Gingrich and his GOP cohorts continue to speak of moderation and bipartisan cooperation, we may hear less of gridlock and more of results.<p>
Morey Stettner, a frequent contributor to Worth, is author of The Art of Winning Conversation (Prentice Hall).<p>
KEYWORDS: legislation, government, law, economy

					</font>
