				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Sovereign Citizens<p>
John Brant's excellent article "<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9609F08.html">Citizens of no Country</A>" (September) brought to mind a couple of questions: When sovereign citizens "travel" in their "personal property," do they use their own network of roads, or do they travel on highways that my "Monopoly money" maintains through taxes? When potential sovereign citizens pay Jeffrey Thayer for his House of Common Law course, do they give him troy ounces of gold, or does he accept "Monopoly money"?
Albert T. Tarzia
Leonia, New Jersey<p>
Sovereign citizens may seem radical, but that does not make them wrong. If it did, the original patriots who founded this country, the founders of the state of Texas (who took up privately held arms and appropriated land for themselves), Abraham Lincoln, and Martin Luther King Jr. would today be branded the same. We must never make the assumption that the government knows best. This country was born from freethinkers, and from freethinking comes our strength.
Jim E. Compton
Corsicana, Texas<p>
You devote over nine pages to people who choose not to be part of society, although they travel on taxpayers' roads and certainly expect some protection from the roving gangs that would fill the void if we had no police. I assume they don't care whether or not the food products they buy are ever inspected, or the cafs they frequent. If their houses catch on fire, do they just watch them burn? Most of us would agree that the government is too intrusive and that far too much of our income goes toward taxes that subsidize waste, needless programs, and inefficiency. But there are better and more reasonable solutions. Being more responsible in all we do is the first step. The frontier no longer exists, and we have to develop a spirit of cooperation, not confrontation. 
James M. Power
Memphis, Tennessee<p>
John Brant's story on sovereign citizenship is laded with little ironies that reveal the crass hypocrisy of this movement. If these sovereigns were truly serious about divorcing themselves from the government, they wouldn't be driving their unlicensed vehicles on tax-supported roads, flying commercial air carriers that rely on the tax-supported air-traffic-control system, or touting their movement on cable programs whose owners' franchises are awarded by local governments. Too bad Brant didn't follow them into the bathroom so we could learn if their dedication to their cause extends to shunning the tax-supported sewer system in favor of outhouses and chamber pots. I doubt it.
D. MacDonald
Chicago, Illinois<p>
Track Star<p>
Bravo! Erik Hedegaard expresses feelings that every computerized investor has, regardless of whether he uses FastTrack, Morningstar, MetaStock, or any other of the lesser-known software products ("<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9609F07.html">The Secret of My Success</A>," September). I'd love to see more articles examining investor feelings toward online newspapers and magazines, investing via the Internet, etc. Surely, FastTrack isn't the only high-tech investing product around with a committed, enthusiastic following. How do real people really feel about investing technologies? What high-tech qualities lead to investing success?
Paul Charbonnet
Investors FastTrack
Baton Rouge, Louisiana<p>
Individual Initiative<p>
Sarah Teslik is an American hero for her efforts to fight the executive greed, mismanagement, and board nepotism that exist in many corporations ("<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9609U03.html">No Quarter</A>," September). She is doing a great job on behalf of individual shareholders (like myself), helping to protect us from the excesses of the Archer Daniels Midlands of this country. May she continue and be cloned tenfold!
Charles R. Henry
Danville, California<p>
Social Problems<p>
James K. Glassman's column on Social Security did absolutely nothing to help solve a very serious problem ("<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9609E01.html">Social Insecurity</A>," September). Social Security is a social-insurance program that provides a reliable base of income for millions of retirees, survivors, and the disabled. Social Security, in combination with Medicare, distributes among all working families the burdens of caring for the elderly and disabled. With the demise of defined-benefit pensions, we need Social Security more than ever. No prudent person should want to rely on the vagaries of the capital markets as a sole source of retirement income. The privatization program urged by the profiteers would do just that.
Mel Aaronson
United Federation of Teachers Pension Committee
New York, New York<p>
I urge all publications to beat the drums for cutting out cost-of-living increases except once every three or four years -- and making that one a 5 percent increase. That would be a great savings, and I believe that most senior citizens, including me, would be willing to forgo the annual increase. But the American Association of Retired Persons and similar organizations keep trying to convince Congress this is a no-no. Glassman's idea of compensating wealthier retirees and cutting them out of Social Security is a good one. I believe most would be willing to give it a try.
Annette Culler-Penney
Upperville, Virginia<p>
Risk and Reward<p>
Walter Mead writes that this country had 4.2 percent growth from 1960 to 1973 ("<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9609E02.html">Growing Pains</A>," September). He asks, "We did it once; why can't we do it again?" We probably could. The only question is: Where can we find another Vietnam?
Lawrence R. Dworkin
Wallingford, Pennsylvania<p>
Follow-up<p>
Californians will be voting this fall on a proposition that would increase the ability of individual investors to launch so-called strike suits, in which a company gets hit with a class-action suit alleging securities fraud. Andrew Tobias unsuccessfully sought to deter such suits last March with Proposition 201 and wrote about it for Worth ("<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9610C01.html">Ralph Nader Is a Big Fat Idiot</A>," October). Proposition 211, which will appear on the November 5 ballots in California, would allow pensioners to file the type of class-action lawsuits in California state courts that have been curtailed in federal court, as Tobias reported. Opponents of the measure argue that its purpose is to create a climate in which lawyers can file frivolous lawsuits in the hopes of gaining out-of-court settlements from large corporations. Bill Clinton and Bob Dole have both said that they are opposed to Proposition 211.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
