	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-A Master of His Discipline</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-A Master of His Discipline</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Bill Gross hates excess -- that's why he's so good at running bond funds.<p>
By Michael Peltz<p>
Pacific Investment Management co-founder William Gross can be brutally honest. Taken aback by the April death of 328-pound baseball umpire John McSherry from a heart attack on the field in Cincinnati, only seven pitches into the season, Gross wrote in his monthly newsletter, Investment Outlook: "He'd been killed by his fatness, by a billion molecules of sink clogging, Drano-resistant cholesterol that fed on his coronary artery and sucked up his life's blood like a vampire in the heat of the night."<p>
Why does the man widely considered one of the premier authorities on fixed-income investing care about the weight of an umpire? Gross says his graphic description of McSherry's inability to control his eating -- "the man, it seemed, was a Cuisinart with limbs" -- was meant to be instructive. "I thought there were some good lessons to learn about the importance of discipline and willpower," says the trim six-foot, 175-pound bond trader.<p>
**Self-discipline is the key to PIMCO's success.**<p>
Self-discipline has been the key to Gross's success since he, James Muzzy, and William Podlich founded PIMCO 25 years ago in idyllic Newport Beach, California. The firm now manages $81 billion, mostly in institutional assets. In 1987, PIMCO introduced one of the first no-load mutual-fund groups, PIMCO Funds. Today, 15 of its 22 eligible funds have four-star or five-star Morningstar ratings. "Bill Gross and PIMCO are a fixture in the fixed-income markets in the same manner as Warren Buffett and Peter Lynch are in stocks," says Morningstar analyst Mark Wright.<p>
Unlike other bond managers who have often been sideswiped chasing high yields, PIMCO hasn't wavered in pursuing what Gross calls "total return" -- yield plus capital appreciation. "The big mistake investors make is they reach for yield and bid up the price of bonds," explains Muzzy. Applied with Gross's discipline, PIMCO's total-return strategy shows that an active fixed-income manager can beat the indexes. (For a story on managers who never beat their bogeys, see "<A HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/M9611I02.html">Losers Out of the Gate</A>.")<p>
**When the firm's strategy backfired early this year, a disaster was thwarted by other well-placed investments.**<p>
Last year and this have shown exactly how the discipline works. PIMCO turned very optimistic on interest rates back in the spring of 1995, a strategy that proved highly successful until early this year, when long-term Treasurys plummeted as rates shot up from 6 percent to 7. That would have been a disaster for most fixed-income managers. Yet, through August, the <a name="FUND:PTNAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PTNAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Total Return Fund</b></a> was down only 1.36 percent for the year, thanks to well-placed sector bets on mortgage-backed securities, European bonds, and high-yield debt. "Outside of interest rates, they've gotten everything else right," says Morningstar's Wright, who isn't worried about the fund's recent underperformance.<p>
Switching among different types of bonds is critical to PIMCO's strategy as the firm's 13 traders search a universe of 54,000 domestic and international securities for undiscovered values. Currently, the firm is still heavily weighted in mortgages, which represent about 40 percent of its portfolio, but it has reduced its non-U.S.-bond exposure from 20 percent to 5 percent.<p>
**PIMCO's total-return strategy has been going strong since the mid-1970s.**<p>
Gross developed PIMCO's total-return strategy during the mid-1970s, when active bond management was just gaining credibility. Gross persuaded management at Pacific Mutual to reorganize PIMCO from an equity manager to a bond manager after the 197374 market slide.<p>
PIMCO had $5 billion under management by the early 1980s, but the markets were getting increasingly complex. Wall Street's investment banks had begun raiding academia for Ph.D.'s, whose fancy options-pricing models helped their traders value bonds more accurately. In 1984, Gross brought in "computer geek" Frank Rabinovitch and charged him with upgrading the firm's computer systems and software.<p>
Today, PIMCO's network of workstations and servers has roughly the same computational power as two Cray supercomputers. Every Friday night, after PIMCO's portfolio of 1,500 securities has been updated, the computers kick into high gear. Some 12 hours and 200 trillion calculations later, the firm's portfolio managers know the precise duration for each institutional account and mutual fund.<p>
**Adjusting duration is PIMCO's most valuable part of its strategy.**<p>
Adjusting duration -- which measures the rate of change of a bond's price with respect to its yield -- is probably the most valuable tool for implementing PIMCO's long-term strategy. The longer the duration, the more sensitive a bond is to movements in interest rates; so, when PIMCO is optimistic and expects bond yields to fall, it lengthens duration. Conversely, when PIMCO turns negative, it shortens duration. Currently, the firm's duration is about 5.9 years, a full year longer than the Lehman Aggregate Bond Index.<p>
Gross and his team deploy their strategies from the firm's high-tech trading room, set against a panoramic view of the Pacific Ocean. The portfolio managers are divided into two camps: the generalists, Gross, Rabinovitch, David Edington, John Hague, and William Powers; and the specialists, including high-yield expert Benjamin Trosky and international-bond maven Lee Thomas III. "The generalists make sure the portfolios are structured similarly," says Muzzy, "while the specialists are there to find the best buying opportunities." The generalists, including Gross, do most of their own trading, which they say can add as much as 50 basis points to performance. "If we're wrong on our large secular [interest-rate] bet, we can make up for it on the trading side," says Edington.<p>
**PIMCO also devotes heavy consideration to its top-down analysis of the economy.**<p>
PIMCO's investment strategy is top-down driven, based on the firm's long-term economic forecast. Unlike many other bond managers, PIMCO doesn't employ an economic guru to divine the direction of interest rates. "We don't have a single economist here," says CEO William Thompson Jr. "Every portfolio manager is expected to do his own economics homework."<p>
The cornerstone of PIMCO's top-down approach is a weeklong retreat each spring for its 58 investment professionals to discuss global macroeconomic trends. Gross loosely presides over the forums, and prominent academics are brought in to stimulate discussion. This year's meeting featured Harvard University economist Jeffrey Sachs, best known for his work advising former Eastern-bloc countries on how to move from Communism to capitalism.<p>
Like Sachs, PIMCO has been studying the globalization of capital markets since the fall of the Iron Curtain in 1989, but with an eye to its impact on bond rates. "As more and more nations have jumped into the capitalistic pool," explains Gross, "the multitude of swimmers has made it increasingly possible for production to migrate to the world's cheapest ports of call." Low-cost labor in emerging countries like China restrains wages in the developed economies of Japan, Germany, and the U.S. and leads to low inflation. Demographic trends also play a big role in damping inflation: As the populations in the major developed countries get older, they are more likely to save than to spend.<p>
**Gross is backing bonds -- the 15-year bull market can't go on forever.**<p>
The case for holding bonds has rarely been stronger, Gross believes. The 15-year-old equity bull market -- and the oversize returns that investors have come to expect -- can't go on forever. "Even if the economy is growing at 5 percent a year, companies can't continue to manufacture profits at double-digit rates of return," says Gross, noting that declining profits will ultimately translate into lower stock returns. In a world where equity returns mimic hat sizes, he adds, investors will be happy to get 7 percent income from bonds.<p>
Still, it is going to take more than Gross's salesmanship to get retail investors back into fixed-income funds. According to the Investment Company Institute, an astonishing $40 billion flowed out of bond and income mutual funds following the brutal market of 1994 (see chart above), when long-term Treasury bonds lost 7.8 percent. "The sell-off in the bond market in 1994 scared people away, and they never came back, even though 1995 was a strong year," explains Fred Quirsfeld, a senior portfolio manager at American Express Financial Advisors.<p>
To Gross, that just means many investors will miss out on some attractive returns. With inflation in check, PIMCO believes long-term Treasury rates will stay between 5 percent and 7 percent during the next few years. Recent rates, of course, have bounced above 7 percent, but that only increases Gross's resolve. "Bonds have a clear place in this market," he says. "Investors will be very glad to own them during the next recession."<p>
Even in this market, though, investors should approach bond mutual funds circumspectly, says Gross. "As with stock funds, it's very important to find fund families with very low expenses. If you're only going to get 7 percent a year, to pay close to 1 percent in fees is preposterous."<p>
**Changes at PIMCO are making it difficult for individual investors to take advantage of their strategy.**<p>
The problem is that PIMCO has made it harder to follow Gross's advice. In the past, individual investors could invest in several PIMCO funds through Charles Schwab's fund marketplace for a minimum investment of only $1,000. But last year, PIMCO eliminated that no-load distribution channel because it competed with a new line of load funds offered by <a name="FUND:PVLAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PVLAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PIMCO Advisors</b></a> that was created when PIMCO spun off from Pacific Mutual Life Insurance and merged with Thomson Advisory Group in November 1994.<p>
PIMCO offers its no-load funds via special relationships with Schwab, Fidelity Investments, and Jack White & Co. These funds, however, require higher minimums or, in the case of Schwab and Fidelity, a relationship with a registered investment adviser. <p>
But there is a little-publicized way for investors to get Gross's expertise in a no-load version -- by turning to the <a name="FUND:HABDX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HABDX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Harbor Bond Fund</b></a> or the <a name="FUND:FBDFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FBDFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fremont Bond Fund</b></a>, both of which Gross manages as a sub-adviser. "They essentially mirror the Total Return Fund," says one PIMCO watcher, noting that those funds' recent six-month and one-year records matched those of their bigger and better-known cousin. That's welcome news for would-be investors who are unwilling to use a fee-based adviser but still want to avoid the steep charges of the PIMCO Advisors funds: Loads for the A shares of a Gross-managed PIMCO Advisors fund start at 4.75 percent, while the deferred-load B shares carry 1 percent annual 12b-1 fees plus expenses of 2 percent.<p>
Accessing genius, it seems, occasionally has its price.<p>
<img src="/imgs/p132cht(475X210).gif" width=475 height=210><p>
KEYWORD:
mutual fund, investing, bond, Treasury

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

