		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Fees? What Fees? Oh, Those Fees!</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Fees? What Fees? Oh, Those Fees!</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jim Jubak<p>
If the mutual-fund companies applied as much effort to the investing process as they do to the creation of new ways to charge fees, investors would be a lot better off. That has been especially true in recent years. Fund marketers have displayed unusual creativity in developing schemes for lining their pockets in new and more complicated ways.<p>
Take Legg Mason as just one example. The Legg Mason Value Trust, a large-cap growth fund, looks like a no-load fund. There's no sales charge for buying shares and none for selling. An investor might be forgiven for thinking that all he or she pays is the 1 percent annual management fee -- not unreasonable for a large-cap growth fund.<p>
But that 1 percent isn't all a shareholder in this fund has to cough up. Legg Mason also collects an additional annual fee of .95 percent. That not-so-tiny charge, dubbed a 12b-1 fee, is deducted from fund assets to pay for distribution and marketing costs and can add up fast. For example, an investor who holds the Legg Mason fund for five years would wind up paying a total of 4.75 percent of assets in 12b-1 costs, making the fund nearly as expensive over time as many of the funds sold with old-fashioned front-end loads by <a HREF="http://www.ml.com/">Merrill Lynch</A>, <a HREF="http://www.painewebber.com/">Paine Webber</A>, or <a HREF="http://www.aimfunds.com/">AIM</A>. This is why we have begun factoring 12b-1 fees into our rating system.<p>
**Fund investors looking for a true no-load are finding an increasingly narrow range of choices.**<p>
Sadly, fund investors looking for a true no-load fund are combing through an increasingly narrow range of choices. This group -- composed of those funds that don't impose any sales charge or 12b-1 fee -- has fallen to 251 funds, or 35 percent of the 719 funds on our list. And while traditionally investor-oriented fund families, such as <a HREF="http://www.troweprice.com/">T. Rowe Price</A>, <a HREF="http://www.scudder.com/">Scudder</A>, <a HREF="http://www.strong-funds.com/java/welcome.htm">Strong</A>, <a HREF="http://www.vanguard.com">Vanguard</A>, <a HREF="http://www.janusfunds.com">Janus</A>, and <a HREF="http://www.twentieth-century/">Twentieth Century</A>, are all still holding the line, one more no-load family will bite the dust on October 25. That's when the sale of Michael Price's Mutual Series funds to the Franklin Templeton Group will close; the funds will then add a 4.5 percent sales charge for new investors.<p>
Nor is the fund industry cutting fees in other areas to make up the difference. The average maximum sales charge -- 2.82 percent -- was virtually the same for this year's group of funds as for last year's. The expense ratio dropped slightly, from $1.33 per $100 in 1995 to $1.24 in 1996, but that had more to do with our decision to remove the very smallest funds and sector funds from our list this year than with any industry trend.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
