	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-A Word to Stockpickers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						This may be the one time it makes sense for you to read a whole story devoted to the subject of mutual funds. Why? Because the asset-allocation strategy and model portfolios we describe here can work just as effectively for investors who make their own stock selections as for those who buy funds. Investors can easily classify stocks by employing the same criteria we use to place mutual funds into five asset groups. By doing so, investors who own stocks (or a combination of stocks and funds) can ascertain whether their overall portfolio is strategically balanced to meet their needs.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
