<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 6/11-Trust but Verify</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>6/11-Trust but Verify</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Attaching some strings to trusts can help you and your children<p>
By Claire Poole<p>
When she turned 25, a Houston woman, the scion of a wealthy family, was given $110,000 from a trust fund her grandfather had set up in the early 1960s. Instead of investing and saving the money, she lived off it for four years while she attended graduate school, lived the high life in New York, and traveled, including spending one summer in Paris. Now in her 30s and starting a family, she'd like to turn back the clock. "I didn't learn how to manage the money," she says. "I learned how to spend it."<p>
Unfortunately, it's a common problem for many trust-fund children. Parents and grandparents want to hand down their hard-earned riches so their offspring never have to be without. But usually a trust is a lot of money -- and responsibility. Who's to say they won't blow it on a Ferrari or a trip around the world? <p>
**There are methods to making sure your heirs use their trust funds wisely.**<p>
But there is a way to keep your children from turning into trust bums. Trust funds are not boilerplate documents and can easily be written with a few strings attached. These so-called incentive trusts are increasingly popular among wealthy individuals who want to bolster their children's initiative by making them jump through a few hoops before receiving their inheritances.<p>
"[Clients] are becoming concerned that their wealth will have a very destructive impact on their descendants," Stephanie Denby, an attorney with the Chicago law firm Schiff, Hardin & Waite, recently wrote in the trade journal Trusts & Estates. "Long criticized as 'ruling from the grave,' incentive trusts are now increasingly being used to direct the development of beneficiaries."<p>
The trick in crafting such a trust is to have one broad enough to cover unexpected changes in fortune but specific enough to protect your children from themselves. Here are several ways:<p>
**Spread out the wealth.**<p>
Spread out the wealth. Your child doesn't have to get the entire wad when he or she turns 21. It's more likely to sap his or her initiative than to help. Many attorneys suggest staggering principal payments over several years -- decades, if you want. <p>
The most common ages to break out a trust are 25, 30, and 35. Why? At 25, the kids are out of college and working or in graduate school. At 30, they've probably established a career and married and are considering buying a house. At 35, they may be having children and beginning to save for their kids' college education and their own retirement. <p>
You could also distribute earnings only until they hit a certain age -- retirement, perhaps -- and then hit them with the principal. Michel Kaplan, a tax and estate lawyer in Nashville, had one wealthy client who didn't distribute the balance of his children's trust fund until they turned 50 and 60 years old. "Real wealthy people look at money as something to pass on to the next generation," he says. "So the bigger the estate, the longer you want to hold it in trust."<p>
But don't hold back too much, or your kids will never learn how to manage their money. "A lot of parents think they're doing the child a service by keeping it from them," says Martin Shenkman, an estate-planning attorney based in New York City and author of The Complete Book of Trusts (John Wiley & Sons, 1993). "You have to get the child used to the money so they'll develop the maturity to deal with it." <p>
**Include incentives.**<p>
Include incentives. If you want to instill your value system in your children, you can build in some hurdles they must clear to get a chunk of the money. These provisions can be as general as finishing college, earning a living, or raising a family, or as specific as making a 3.5 grade-point average, earning $100,000 a year, or taking over the family business. <p>
Jon Gallo, a Los Angeles attorney specializing in estate planning, recently structured a trust so the children would receive 15 cents on the dollar for the first $15,000 they earned in income, 30 cents for the next $15,000, 60 cents for the next $15,000, and 100 cents once their income reached $45,000. "The more successful the child is, the more matching comes out of the trust," he says. <p>
But Gallo doesn't advise using a trust to do your teaching for you. "You can use a trust as an incentive toward productive behavior," he says. "But there's nothing an estate planner can do if the parents don't teach their children the appropriate virtues."<p>
Incentive trusts can also backfire. Say you want your children to get a big chunk when they finish college. But what if Junior isn't academically inclined and starts a small business instead? Make the trust broad enough to cover all legitimate definitions of success.<p>
**Take a family-bank approach.**<p>
Take a family-bank approach. You can set up a pool trust for the entire family that will provide only for health, education, and well-being until the funds are fully distributed. It would be up to the trustee to decide if the children's needs fit the amount they want to tap -- and if they can handle it.<p>
For instance, Michel Kaplan has a client with a $6 million estate. He has two daughters, both of whom are successful in their careers and happily married. He also has a son in his late 30s who has never held down a job for more than six months. When the client dies, what should happen with his son's $2 million share? "It's a real dilemma," Kaplan says. "He doesn't want to cut him out, but he doesn't want to give him a free ride either." Kaplan suggested the client set up a trust in which the trustee has the broad authority to pay out or withhold money depending on the child's ability to handle his affairs.<p>
That means it's vital to choose your trustee wisely. You really shouldn't manage the trust yourself, because of possible tax and legal consequences, and your attorney would probably run into conflicts of interest. So in selecting an independent trustee, you want someone who has enough latitude to make the right decisions but also understands your wishes.<p>
You could go with a bank or a trust company. But many won't look at you unless you have at least $250,000. And the fees can be high -- 1 percent per year for the first $500,000 in assets, with the fee declining with additional funds. Plus, institutions are not as sensitive to family concerns. If that's important to you, consider a family member or friend, one who has the same values as you and doesn't mind doing a little extra paperwork come tax-time. <p>
But there's peace of mind in parking the trust with a bank or trust company that will manage it, invest it, and deal with difficult beneficiaries. "Relatives are good at understanding the situation and doing the right thing," Kaplan says. "But typically they're not good at investment management, filling out tax returns, and getting the money out on a timely basis." <p>
The solution? Have a family member and a bank or trust company as co-trustees. "That way, you can delegate all the administrative paperwork to the corporate trustee and allow the family member to help make decisions on discretionary distributions to family members," Kaplan says.<p>
**Allow for emergency needs only.**<p>
Allow for emergency needs only. Prudent parents may want to allow the trust to distribute earnings or principal only in dire situations, such as if the child develops serious health problems, is sued, or finds himself or herself unemployed and with a family to support. Items can even be paid directly by the trustee, so there's no chance that the money will land in the hands of the beneficiary -- a good safeguard if your child is a spendthrift or a drug addict.<p>
D. John Thornton, a Boise, Idaho, attorney specializing in high-end estate planning and wealth preservation, has a client in New York whose son is a successful surgeon in Los Angeles. But his parents have never forgiven him for marrying out of his religion and moving to L.A. In this case, the fund allows the son only emergency provisions but provides very broadly for his children.<p>
**Consider a limited partnership.**<p>
Consider a limited partnership. A limited partnership can basically do the same things as a trust, but it's structured differently. Instead of having a trustee, you would establish yourself as the general partner. That would eliminate the middleman, i.e., the trustee. "It allows the parent to call all the shots, including how to invest the money and when to dole out the distributions," says Gideon Rothschild, a New York estate-planning attorney. "A limited partnership is a darned good way to do that."<p>
The parent typically retains a small ownership interest in the partnership (say, 1 percent), assigning the rest to his or her children. If the parent dies, only that 1 percent would be included in the parent's estate, and an appointed successor would take over the partnership. If a successor was not named, the partnership would be liquidated, and the proceeds would go to the children. <p>
There are tax incentives, too. Income from a trust fund is taxed at the top personal rate of 39.6 percent as soon as it crosses $7,900 a year. The child's share of income in a limited partnership would be taxed at his or her bracket, which could be as low as 15 percent. 
There are a few drawbacks. The start-up costs are higher -- typically $3,000 to $5,000 versus $1,000 to $2,500 for the standard trust. Then there's the concern that the child might waste the partnership's distributions. The solution? Put each child's partnership interest in a trust. "Now you have another layer of control," Martin Shenkman says.<p>
Whatever route you choose in setting up a trust, make sure your children are adequately covered for life's little emergencies but can also make mistakes along the way and learn from them. "Remember," says Shenkman, "you can't rule from the grave."
KEYWORDS: death, will, trust fund, inheritance, heir, estate planning

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

