				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Flying in Cyberspace</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Great last-minute airfares appear on the Net every week.<p>
By Rudy Maxa<p>
Every Wednesday, American Airlines, <a name="NYSE:U"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11527"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>USAir</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:NWAC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17160"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Northwest Airlines</b></a> post cut-rate weekend deals on their World Wide Web sites for flights on which the airlines think excess seats will be available. The rules are fairly simple: You must travel that Saturday and return the following Monday or Tuesday. In the case of USAir, you may return on Sunday. American also tosses in deals with Avis (<a HREF="http://www.avis.com">www.avis.com</A>) and <a name="NYSE:HLT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10733"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hilton Hotels</b></a>. Both American and USAir allow you to register your E-mail address on the Web sites so that each Wednesday you'll be automatically notified of special bargains. You must visit Northwest's site to see each weekend's offerings.<p>
The deals usually involve the airlines' hubs, so American offers a good mix of flights to and from Chicago, Dallas/Fort Worth, and Miami. USAir specializes in flights to and from Pittsburgh, Washington, Boston, and Charlotte, North Carolina. And Northwest's menu includes plenty of flights to and from Minneapolis/Saint Paul. American generally offers the most options, USAir comes in second, and Northwest is third. The savings are extraordinary if you can travel on short notice -- as much as 75 percent off walk-up fares. Some recent examples: Chicago to Dallas/Fort Worth round-trip on American cost just $129, while USAir charged only $79 for a round-trip ticket from New York City's LaGuardia to Pittsburgh. For more information, check out American Airlines at <A HREF="http://www.amrcorp.com">http://www.amrcorp.com</A>, USAir at <A HREF="http://www.usair.com">http://www.usair.com</A>, and Northwest at <A HREF="http://www.nwa.com.">http://www.nwa.com.</A><p>
KEYWORDS: 
travel, airline, bargain, fare

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
