	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-From One Highway to Another</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-From One Highway to Another</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ted C. Fishman<p>
One of the obvious virtues of the aptly named World Wide Web is that it brings the world into your house. This makes it a great resource for those who want to get out and hit the road, too. Start with maps. Map Quest (<A HREF="http://www.mapquest.com">http://www.mapquest.com</A>) covers the entire United States, and users can scale the maps of most populous locations down to the level of a few city blocks. Plug in a pair of points, and the site will calculate a route and the driving distance between them. There's also an address finder. If old-fashioned foldout road maps are still needed, thousands can be ordered at Travel Search (<A HREF="http://www.travelsearch.com">http://travelsearch.com</A>). Of course, knowing where you're going doesn't mean you're home free. Check MSNBC's weather pages (<A HREF="http://www.intellicast.com">http://www.intellicast.com</A>) for forecasts anywhere in the country, or call up a real-time satellite photo of North America at Yahoo Weather (<A HREF="http://www.wni.com/yahoo/">http://www.wni.com/yahoo/</A>). If Houston is your destination, information about a different kind of travel hazard can be found at AccuTraffic (<A HREF="http://www.accutraffic.com">http://www.accutraffic.com</A>), which provides maps of current traffic flows; the service is being developed for another nine cities. Finally, if you want something other than franchise food, the Web site of Roadside (<A HREF="http://www.usa1.com/roadside/index.html">http://www.usa1.com/roadside/index.html</A>), the magazine of diner aficionados, lists blue-plate specials in various parts of the U.S.	

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

