<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Taking a Walk Over Fees</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Taking a Walk Over Fees</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Even the managers thought investors were paying excessive fees for the Quantitative Numeric Funds<p>
By Michael Peltz<p>
"It felt like they put a gun to our heads," says Edward Pittman, looking back on the day early last March when he received a fax from *Numeric Investors' John Bogle Jr. and Langdon Wheeler. The partners were resigning as sub-advisers to his Quantitative Group of Funds to start their own mutual funds. Like many a falling-out in the fund world, this one was about fees. But Bogle and Wheeler weren't complaining that they were making too little money. Instead, these managers were quitting because they thought the Quantitative Group was overcharging investors.<p>
Both the <a name="FUND:QBNAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/QBNAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Quantitative Numeric</b></a> and <a name="FUND:QNIIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/QNIIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Quantitative Numeric II</b></a> Funds have high expense ratios -- 1.97 percent and 2.34 percent, respectively, including annual 50-basis-point 12b-1 fees to pay for marketing the funds -- as well as a 1 percent charge when investors cash out. Nonetheless, because of Bogle's performance (annualized returns of nearly 22 percent for the  past three years through June 1996, a full six percentage points better than the Russell 2000 index of small-cap stocks) and name recognition (his father is chairman of Vanguard Group), the first Quantitative Numeric fund sold well enough to close to new investors. But Quantitative Numeric II struggled to attract assets. "Financial planners looked at the fee structure and turned up their noses," says Wheeler.<p>
"Expenses should come down during the life of a fund," says Bogle, "but after the fund closed, expenses were still 180 basis points." Both funds even continued to charge 12b-1 fees to cover the cost of marketing, although the closed fund no longer needed to be marketed. Wheeler and Bogle's new funds carry no 12b-1 fees and cap expenses at 1 percent. Pittman, a former Securities and Exchange Commission attorney, argues that the 50-basis-point 12b-1 fee was, in essence, a commission for financial planners. <p>
The Quantitative Group, which has turned over management of its Quantitative Numeric funds to Robert von Pentz of Washington, D.C.based Columbia Partners, has refused to let the partners use the "Numeric" name on their funds. Instead, they are listed under "n/i." "It's making it hard for people to find us," says Wheeler.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:QBNAX">Quantitative Numeric</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:QNIIX">Quantitative Numeric II</a><br>

					<p>
	
					<p>

							
</td>
	</tr>
