	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Caught in the Overdraft</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Protection from bad checks could mean exposure to more charges<p>
By Tom Nawrocki<p>
Callback service makes it cheaper to dial from abroad<p>
Banks often advertise overdraft protection as free, but if you're not careful about paying the amount back right away, the strings attached to this protection may cost you a bundle.<p>
Almost all banks charge interest on the overdraft from the day it happens -- at Citibank, the annual rate is a healthy 18 percent. What's more, even when you put enough money in your checking account to cover the overdraft, the cash doesn't automatically cover the loan. New York's Chemical Bank deducts as little as $25 a month to pay back an overdraft; if the amount loaned is more than that, the interest piles up until the customer writes a check specifically earmarked to cover the overdraft.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
