	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Quickening the Pace</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Quickening the Pace</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Review  <p> QUICKENING THE PACE  <p>  <p>QUICKEN DELUXE <p><a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a>, $59.99 <p>Available for Windows and Mac  <p> MANAGING YOUR MONEY PLUS <p>MECA Software, $99.95 <p>Available for Windows and Mac  <p> KIPLINGER'S SIMPLY MONEY <p>4Home Productions, $69.99 <p>For Windows only  <p> MICROSOFT MONEY <p><a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>, $34.95 <p>For Windows only  <p>  <p>By Timothy Middleton  <p> Games are fun, and the internet may still be fresh and exciting, but the main reason for adults to use a PC at home is Quicken. What began in the era of <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple</b></a> II computers as an automated checkbook is now, in the multimedia Windows age, a suite of database and on-line tools and sophisticated financial calculators, souped up with audio and video prompts and tutorials. This is what it's like having a financial adviser at your elbow--an adviser with infinite patience, pushing for on-time mortgage payments and maximized savings; an adviser that doesn't shirk the dirty work of uploading electronic bill payments and downloading bank and credit-card statements. Oh, and it analyzes popular mutual funds, too.  <p> Quicken has spawned three serious rivals, so it's no longer the only servant in town. All the personal-finance programs do the basic heavy lifting, which consists of putting a checkbook and other household accounts on a hard drive. (About that hard drive: Be sure to back up your data on a floppy, as all four programs recommend; Windows 95 is still crashing my Pentium 120 at least once a week.) The elimination of drudgery is stunning: Paying bills by printing checks from your computer takes a fraction of the time it used to the old-fashioned way, by hand at the kitchen table; paying electronically takes seconds. (Don't worry if Aunt Ruth doesn't have an electronic account; the bank willcrank out a paper check for her.) Reconciling a checking account is equally easy, especially if that account is at one of the scores of institutions with on-line links to one of these programs. Finally, the creation of an electronic checkbook means a database now exists, so you have a budgeting, planning, and tax-preparationtool at the ready. Throw in your other accounts--an amortizing loan, perhaps, plus a portfolio--and you can swiftly summarize your net worth, freshly updated with each transaction.  <p> A couple of the programs outperform Quicken in particular areas.Managing Your Money Plus on CD-ROM is better for investors: It's far superior for such transactions as covered and naked shorts, zero-coupon bonds, stock options, and buying on margin--it even tracks gold bullion. Triggers remind the user to buy or sell certain securities; they also note when bonds mature and options expire. (Many of these higher functions work best when you have a companion CompuServe account.) And Andrew Tobias is on board to provide often droll advice.  <p> Kiplinger's Simply Money, by contrast, incorporates advice from Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine and offers the strongest suite of tools for small-business users. Its graphic interface also works fastest with a mouse. And while the others have dropped their  manuals for on-screen help--close to useless, in my experience--Simply Money has kept a good, fat manual.  <p> Still, Quicken remains the best total package. Managing Your Money and Simply Money are essentially stuck in a losing game of catch-up. The latter, for example, has no multimedia for beginning users and not nearly enough sophistication for advanced ones (you might bully it into handling small prepayments of principal each month on a mortgage, but the process is awkward). Managing Your Money lacks the elegance and eciency of Quicken. And as for Microsoft Money, well, Microsoft's attempt to buy Quicken's corporate parent, Intuit, was such a public admission of itsown product's failure that when the deal fizzled Microsoft backedout of serious competition and served up a bare-bones packagewhile bragging that Money is "user-friendly." The check-writingand on-line banking functions are indeed fine, but the financial calculators aren't very numerous.  <p> Quicken, meanwhile, keeps moving forward. The newest version,the CD-ROM-based Quicken Deluxe, adds an Internet link, on-line banking capabilities, and a tutorial called Finance 101, which provides home-finance basics. It's clear why some users become Quick-en fanatics, putting it on their laptops or using it to track pocket change. Not that you have to, of course: Even as a checkbook and nothing more, it's one of the smartest tools you can use. <p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

