	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Cents and Innocence</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Cents and Innocence</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Cents and Innocence</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Review  <p> CENTS AND INNOCENCE  <p> ZILLIONS <p>Consumers Union, $16 (six issues)  <p> PIGGYBANKS TOMONEYMARKETS <p>KidVidz, $14.95  <p> <a name="FUND:SRYIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SRYIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>STEINROE YOUNG INVESTOR FUND</b></a>  <p>Stein Roe &Farnham  <p> PARENTBANC  <p>ParentBanc, $14.95  <p> WORLD OF MONEY ALLOWANCE KIT  <p>Summit Financial Products, $39.95  <p>  <p>By Hillary Johnson  <p> "George Washington is dead,"Tyrone announced when I picked him up from pre-school the other day. He's four.  <p> Upon questioning Tyrone's teacher later, I found the subject that day had been not American history but the rudiments of the cash economy. Dollar bills had figured large. And so, I thought, thus it begins: with death. Taxes would not be far behind. Later that night, during the 36th screening of Free Willy, Tyrone made his first, clumsy attempt at purchasing. "I want to buy that whale," he said with heartbreaking conviction.  <p> I launched into a long explanation about the kinds of things money can and can not buy, at the end of which he frowned and declared forcefully, "George Washington is dead!" At this point I considered it time to teach Tyrone the facts of life. With that in mind, I looked around and saw there were a fair number of products designed to do just that, to teach children the basics about money. So with a hopeful eye I started to sample.  <p> Being a writer, I start with a magazine, Zillions: Consumer Reports for Kids. I like any publication that asks the eternal question,"Why can't you bring your own food into movie theaters?" Zillions prints articles debunking carnival games and letters from kids about the advertisements they hate, e.g., "It bugs me when commercials bring people closer together." In a consumer landscape that is all too gung ho and gee whiz when it comes to the young, healthy skepticism can be quite refreshing. Kids can appreciate both rebelling and being in the know, which this magazine promotes. My favorite kids' product by far.  <p> Inspired, I pluck up my courage and order a prospectus for the SteinRoe Young Investor Fund, a mutual fund that invests primarily in securities that "affect the lives of children or teenagers." In other words, <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a>, and the like. In 1995 the fund had a 39.8 percent return. Hey, kids, geese really do lay golden eggs!  Next to cynicism, enormous profits are the best formative experience a child can have in relation to finance.What I like about this fund is that (1) since it's written for kids, I can understand the prospectus and (2) if I open a custodial account in Tyrone's name I can't have a midlife crisis ten years from now, cash in, and move to Burma. Nor can the IRS, if it ever decides to collect that $5,000 I owe from 1985, nab Tyrone's college money. Yet while the idea of a fund in my son's name is nice--assuming someone puts real money into it (Tyrone will have trouble with the $50 monthly minimum)--mutual funds are too abstract and not much fun for young children.  <p> I explored ParentBanc, a checkbook for kids. The idea here is that I hold Tyrone's allowance, and when he wants money he cashes a check. The hitch is that I am not covered by the FDIC and can't guarantee that his four dollars will always be available for withdrawal. (If they come up with a kiddie credit card, sign me up--him up, I mean.) Besides, I'm not sure what the point is: Any parent anal enough to keep this goofy system going is bound to raise a compulsive checkbook balancer anyway.  <p> No less silly is the World of Money Allowance Kit, which is really a piggy bank. It's made up of three plastic book like boxes: one for spending, one for savings, and one for investment. Fine--except spending money belongs in your pocket, and investment money belongs in an investment fund. And piggy banks should be shaped like pigs.  <p> Tyrone likes videos, so I pop in Piggy Banks to Money Markets, aimed at 5- to 12-year-olds (I always jump the gun on age brackets).This video has won so many awards that it kind of scares me, and it does give a thorough and clear presentation of cash economies, stock markets, and consumer credit, as well as the costs and profit margins involved in running a lemonade stand. Okay, so it's a good video. But must it be so humor-less and well-meaning, like a sex-ed film?   <p> And there's the rub:When adults talk (down) to kids about money,they fail to acknowledge that money, like sex, is one of the complicated subtexts of every book and video they will ever see, that it's the root of all evil and good, sociologically speaking, and that they will never, ever understand it fully.  <p> Another problem: Most of these products treat money as a thing instead of an instrument. It's probably better for children to learn about value by trading marbles or baseball cards with one another than by writing checks to their parents. The willingness to part with value, the emotional and physical value invested in things, is more apparent in these childhood rituals than in toys that fetishize the transaction itself. Why get so caught up in shiny checkbooks, the inscribing of sums, the sound the check makes being torn out?  <p> I've come to realize that Tyrone instinctively understands the American economy without reference to the concept of money. He knows there's a qualitative difference between his paid baby-sitter and friends who come over, he knows that when we go to the store there is some kind of "price" we pay for the things we take, and he understands the sometimes desperate necessity of something called work. Indeed, he understands economics better than he will once he is able to re-cathect all of his desires onto the popular fetish object known as the dollar bill.  <p> Even if, in this house (for now), George Washington is dead as smelt. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

