	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Europe When It Sizzles</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Europe When It Sizzles</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Insider tips for the hottest time of the year<p>By Rudy Maxa<p>Europe is very big with Americans this summer, as anyone 
trying to book a flight there knows. So how do you beat the crowds and travel smart? Here with a compendium of basic advice, survival tips, and insider shortcuts.<p>> Concierges from Inter-Continental hotels around the world compiled their personal tips for cities from Amsterdam to Warsaw in a free booklet, Concierge Confidential. Call 800-327-0200.<p>> Ruesch International, a foreign-currency consultant, will send you a free pocket-size guide that gives the value of the U.S. dollar in 24 currencies; send a stamped, self-addressed envelope to Foreign Currency Guide, c/o Ruesch International, 700 11th Street NW, Washington, D.C., 20001.<p>> Arrange auto rental before leaving the U.S. -- it's cheaper. If you need a car for longer than 17 days (or three weeks with some firms), consider leasing. Try Kemwel (800-678-0678) or Renault Eurodrive (800-221-1052; from western states, 800-477-7116).<p>> If you're staying in one place in Europe for longer than a week, renting an apartment or home -- or a farmhouse or castle -- might make sense. French Experience (212-986-1115) lists about 100,000 apartments and homes in France; other French options include Interhome (201-882-6864) and Prestige Villas (800-336-0080). For apartments, villas, or luxurious farmhouses in Italy, call Italian Rentals (202-244-5345).<p>> One of the British Isles, the Island of Jersey, 14 miles off the coast of France, has some of the cleanest beaches in Europe and no value-added tax.<p>> Book London theater tickets from the U.S. by calling Edwards 
& Edwards at 800-223-6108.<p>> Want to see the Mona Lisa pronto? Avoid the crowd at the main entrance to the Louvre in Paris by going around back to a little-known door on the Seine side of the rear wing of the museum. There's rarely a line, even in l't.<p>> Planning to drive in France? Before leaving the U.S., call the French tourism office (900-990-0040) and ask for help planning an itinerary. You'll receive precise directions and notes on sites and hotels along your route. It's 95 cents for each minute you talk with a travel planner, but the average call lasts only three minutes.<p>> Taxis in Brussels are expensive. Don't make the tab higher by tipping -- it's included in the fare. If you're going downtown from the airport, consider taking the 20-minute ride on the shuttle train to Brussels's Central Station for only three dollars one way.<p>> In Barcelona, pharmacies that are closed must post the name and address of the nearest open competitor. Or call 010, the city's 24-hour information line, to find the nearest open location as well as to get other tourist information.<p>> If you're taking the train to Florence, make sure your ticket is to the Santa Maria Novella, the central station in town, and not the inconvenient Campo di Marte station. <p>> Instead of staying in the city of Venice, which can be crowded, hot, and humid in the summer, consider the nearby resort island of Lido, where the beach is spacious and trees and lush landscaping keep temperatures pleasant. Top hotels: the Hotel Excelsior and the Hotel des Bains (call 800-325-3589 for either). Don't be surprised when the reservation agent answers "Sheraton": The American company bought most of the Italian CIGA chain's luxury properties last year.<p>> Don't leave visible luggage in a rental car anywhere in Europe. Don't pull over to the side of the road just because someone tries to convince you something is wrong with your car. In Russia, don't hesitate to be rude and shout or push if you're suddenly surrounded by a group of people in a market area; they're most likely going through your pockets as they crowd you.<p>> To receive your value-added-tax refund upon your departure from most major European airports, you sometimes must display the goods purchased. The desk is usually on the other side of the airport security check, so don't put those items in your checked luggage.<p>> And, finally, if you were frustrated in attempts to get tickets to Europe this season through an airline frequent-flier program, that's because the airlines allocate very few award seats during prime travel time. And you waited too long. Moral: Book now for next summer. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
