<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Clean Up Your Credit</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Clean Up Your Credit</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Even scrupulous chargers can fall victim to reporting errors.<p>By Ellen DePasquale<p>You've always paid your credit-card balances in full and have never made a late payment on anything. Your credit report is spotless, right? Maybe not. A Consumers Union study found that almost half of all credit reports contain some sort of error -- from incorrect dates to credit accounts that don't belong to the reportee. <p>To check your credit report, write to each of the three credit bureaus -- TRW (P.O. Box 8030, Layton, UT 84041), Equifax (P.O. Box 105873, Atlanta, GA 30348), and Trans Union (P.O. Box 390, Springfield, PA 19064). Include your full legal name, mailing address, prior addresses over the past five years, Social Security number, birth date, and a copy of a document (such as a utility bill or driver's license) that shows the address is correct. According to the Fair Credit Reporting Act, if you have been denied credit within the past 60 days, you are entitled to a free report. Otherwise, TRW offers one free copy each year, Trans Union charges eight dollars, and Equifax charges up to eight dollars, depending on the state (call 800-685-1111 for information).<p>If you find an error, send another letter and a copy of the report, asking that the credit bureau either verify or remove the item in question. By law, the creditor has 30 days to verify the information. So if the bureau doesn't respond to you within 30 days, it must remove the item from your report. If you don't receive a response within 30 days, write and demand a corrected report. Your last resort, if there is still no answer, is to threaten to go to court. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Mortgages

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


