<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Goliath in a Green Eyeshade</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Goliath in a Green Eyeshade</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						As the financial giants move in on the independent planners' turf, who reaps the benefits?<p>By John DeMott<p>For all our clients, the quality of our advice makes a difference," coos the commercial on CNN's Early Edition. "The difference is <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>." On ABC's This Week With David Brinkley, <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a> claims that "nine out of ten people would recommend American Express Financial Advisors to a friend." The financial giants of the world have begun entering your living room, where once only invited guests -- like your friendly neighborhood financial planner -- were welcome.<p>The biggest player in the world of institutional financial planning is Merrill Lynch, with 13,000 financial consultants in 880 branches. Merrill's primary target: a growing flock of busy, well-heeled baby boomers, now cracking 50, with net worths starting at about $100,000 -- more than 500,000 U.S. households in all. Merrill has roughly 300,000 financial plans in force, with a goal of adding 150,000 more this year. For its high-net-worth clients, Merrill draws on teams of specialists in every area from insurance to estate planning to assist the financial consultants in its branches.<p>After unsuccessful pilot missions with a couple of banks, American Express has rebranded its IDS subsidiary as American Express Financial Advisors. Amex has 26.7 million cardholders worldwide, but only 250,000 of them are clients of American Express Financial Advisors.<p>Are these gargantuan financial planners any good? Absolutely, say some of their clients. Claire Fillinger of Portland, Oregon, a retired registered nurse, dumped her independent adviser and moved her business to American Express Financial Advisors' Bob Farnes after she and her husband attended one of the half dozen investment seminars Farnes holds monthly in the Portland area. "I detected a lot of honesty in his presentation," Fillinger says. Of her previous adviser, she says: "There were occasions when I felt he wasn't presenting the entire picture but just what was to his benefit in getting him a commission. I don't really like that sort of thing."<p>Farnes gets commissions on top of his planning fees when he sells American Express investment products, such as IDS mutual funds, all types of insurance, and cash-management accounts. Does this mean that Amex's financial planners are at heart just salesmen for Amex products? Farnes says he wants to put investors into the best products, Amex's or no. The Fillingers had a long-term health-care plan, for example, that was clearly superior to anything Amex sold -- so Farnes advised them to keep it. As it happens, Claire Fillinger's portfolio does have about $200,000 worth of Amex products in it -- about 40 percent of the total. But she claims Farnes didn't put any extra pressure on her to buy them. "They're the better investments for me now," she declares.<p>However, independent planners say that examples like the Fillingers make the strongest case against their institutional brethren -- that planners at these places can't be objective, that they're really not in the business of planning but in the business of selling plans tied to the products they push. "It belittles the art of financial planning," says Terry Siman, a lawyer and financial planner and principal of Executive Financial Services in Spring House, Pennsylvania. "It reduces lifetime decisions to what is the right thing for you to buy." The big investment houses, he charges, have "polluted" the meaning of financial planning "when you know that the planner sitting in front of you earns X percentage of his income from doing this planning and Y percentage from selling you products."<p>Even other big companies that market financial plans concur. "I wouldn't call Merrill Lynch and American Express competition," says Steven Weinstein, managing director of Arthur Andersen Financial Advisers, which joined four of the other Big Six accounting firms in registering with the Securities and Exchange Commission as an investment adviser last year. Andersen sells no financial products of its own, only advice. "Those are people who are selling products," Weinstein says. "We're objective advisers who help our clients select the best products that make the most sense."<p>Amex and Merrill admit that casting themselves as planners helps increase sales of investment products by entwining the customer in ways more complicated than merely selling a stock or bond now and then. (It also pulls in nice fees: At Amex, they average $185 an hour, $43 million in all for 1995.) But they support their claims of disinterestedness by pointing out that their plans aren't linked to specific products. "Our plans are neutral," says Merrill Lynch senior vice president J. Arthur Urciuoli. "You could write a Merrill Lynch plan and have it implemented anywhere. It's just a blueprint." At Amex, the advice comes with no strings attached: If you don't like it, you can get your money back -- guaranteed. Amex senior financial adviser Michael Tilles says, "The analytical work I do stands on its own."<p>The independents' ultimate concern, of course, is that they'll be crushed by their monster competitors, with all their financial and human resources and, most important, name recognition. The giants agree that these areas constitute a real advantage for them. "We can provide more support and more tools to our financial advisers," says Amex Financial Advisors CEO Dave Hubers. Among them: a staff of CPAs and lawyers that's large and getting larger. Amex is gobbling up small accounting firms all over America -- as many as 45 this year and next -- to team with its financial planners, says Robert Basten, president of Amex's Tax and Business Services.<p>The smaller planners are also concerned with being outgunned in the increasingly lucrative scramble for corporate business, a prime market for all the big players, whether or not they sell their own financial products. Andersen, for one, has an entire division devoted to this part of the business. "I'm just a lonely planner," says Siman. "There's no way for me to compete" against deals drawn up between "Johnson & Johnson corporate and Merrill Lynch corporate." For all of that, though, he says that none of his 70 clients has deserted him for the big investment houses.<p>Some smaller planners say they aren't worried because the big companies will find financial planning is a tougher, more expensive racket than they realize. But the bigger companies will be formidable competitors with deep pockets and thick skins. Not even a pending $2 billion lawsuit against Merrill after the 1994 Orange County bankruptcy seems to have tainted its reputation.
If the big brokers ever convince the general public that they've put their clients' interests ahead of their own, "it will be much harder for the independents to compete," says Madeline Noveck, a planner with Novos Planning Associates in New York City. "I'm flying just under their radar right now."<p>But investors like Claire Fillinger are clearly on the screens of the big institutions, and that's fine with her. "I just want to be able to live in the style to which I've become accustomed," she says, "and Bob Farnes is doing that quite well for me."<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:MER">Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:AXP">American Express Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
