<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Little By Little</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Little By Little</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Little By Little</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Review  <p> LITTLE BY LITTLE  <p> By Laurence Hooper  <p> <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>APPLE</b></a> MESSAGEPAD 120  <p>$699  <p> CASIO Z-7000  <p>$600  <p> <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>HEWLETT-PACKARD</b></a> OMNIGO 100 <p>$349  <p> <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MOTOROLA</b></a> ENVOY, MOTOROLA MARCO <p> $1,000 each  <p> PSION SERIES 3a <p>$399  <p> SHARP ZAURUS ZR-5800  <p>$650  <p> For the past few years, dropping $750 on a personal digital assistant -- a portable, computerized Filofax -- has been the mark of either a rube or a gadget freak. Epitomized by the Apple Newton, these gizmos were simply too big, too expensive, andtoo useless for any normal person. The Newton itself, of course,drew a special kind of ridicule because it purported to recognize whatever handwriting users scrawled on its screen -- but much of the time spat back gobbledy gook.  <p> I've always thought the derision a bit harsh. Okay, so these palmtops, as they're called, didn't live up to their early publicity.Still, they were way stations en route to a PDA that many busy types would pay money for. Personally, I'm waiting for the day when a PDA includes all the now standard features -- a slot foradd-in cards, plus a date book, address book, memo pad, and alarm clock -- and adds three important attributes: It fits in my pants pocket; it communicates wirelessly; and it costs less than $250.(Some people also want PDAs to swap information with their regular computer, but that isn't high on my list.) In the meantime, it's 1996, and we're faced with a second generation of PDAs. Most are better than their predecessors -- smaller, lighter, more powerful. For input, they use a stylus-type pen, a keyboard, or both. And mercifully, they've come to market without any of the hype from 1993. Here are the pros and cons of several machines I tested.  <p> The Apple MessagePad 120 (a successor to the Newton) is expensive and elegant, and it has mostly overcome the Newton's inability to read handwriting. What's more, a bunch of companies have developed software for it, which means you can expand its capabilities.It even comes with Intuit's Pocket Quicken to track spending. <p> But the machine is just too big to carry around. I knew I was in trouble when I gathered all the little add-ons that make the MessagePad work well -- a keyboard, a modem, a recharging stand -- and then realized that lugging a regular notebook computer would be easier.  <p> Two siblings from Motorola, the Envoy and the Marco, have the same problem: They're heavy and awkward and come in carrying cases that could fit a notebook computer. Unlike their competitors, both come fully equipped to send and receive wireless E-mail.For me, that's a huge plus: I hate being out of touch, so on-the-road communication is perhaps the biggest reason I'd buy a PDA.  <p> Because the Marco runs the Newton operating system, it's basically a MessagePad with wireless capability. The Envoy -- the hippest toy in Hollywood right now -- uses different software, from a company called General Magic. I'd seen this software before and disliked its childish quality: You navigate by tapping on cartoon-like pictures of a desk, rooms, buildings, and so on. But I have to admit it has grown on me. What hasn't grown on me is the pain of having to type with a stylus, since there's neither hand writing recognition nor a keyboard.  <p> The Casio Z-7000 is a nice machine marred by annoying touches, such as a hard-to-read screen and a dinky stylus, but it's a bit more compact than the MessagePad and feels more rugged. With a few tweaks, its next version might be worth a look.  <p> The Z-7000, MessagePad, and Motorola PDAs all have one thing in common: They depend on pen input because they lack a built-in keyboard. The other machines I tested, however, are variations on a clamshell design, with a keyboard on one half of the shell. Despite having a bias against Chiclet keyboards, I found they work quite well when teamed with a pen-style interface. The clamshell devices are cheaper, too; shoppers should focus on them.   <p> The Psion Series 3a is an admirably small gadget and fairly powerful as well. I don't really like the aesthetics of the case or the screen graphics, though. It's purely personal, but if I'm carrying a machine, I want it to reflect my style. If you're a gray-flannel type, however, consider the Psion.  <p> The Sharp Zaurus ZR-5800 comes on like a hopped-up calculator, but it handles the standard tasks pretty well. I especially liked what may seem a silly feature, the ability to paste ready-made symbols into documents (great for drawing maps). I also felt I could drop this solidly built PDA with impunity -- an important quality for a portable machine, albeit one I was scared to test with a trial model.  <p> My favorite device is the Hewlett-Packard OmniGo 100 OrganizerPlus. Unlike the other clamshell machines, it folds over backward to become a pure pen-input machine -- yet unlike most pen machines, it's decently priced and has a keyboard. Its GEOS operating system is my cup of tea, and the handwriting recognition works well if you're willing to bend your habits a little. In many ways, it's the best of all worlds.  <p> Still, the OmniGo doesn't fit in a pocket. A coat pocket might work, but what happens in the summer? And it doesn't have built-in wireless communication, either. This peeved me -- was no machine perfect? -- until I read about a system called WyndMail.  <p> Wynd Mail, which also works on the MessagePad, allows you to send or receive wireless E-mail; you can also connect to any fax machine, pager, or even telephone -- a synthesized voice will read a message aloud. It works with an add-in card from Megahertz that weighs just a few ounces. (Radio Mail, a competitor, works with this card, too, though not on the OmniGo.)  <p> I'll admit that this is an expensive solution: The Megahertz All Points card alone lists for $499. But I tried it and found it works just fine. If the OmniGo were just a bit smaller and the wireless card a lot cheaper, I'd say we have a workable combo here. While I can't really recommend the OmniGo for general users, now's the time for gearheads to pounce without embarrassment. <p> Perhaps it's no surprise that none of these machines meets all three of my requirements; technology doesn't move that fast. So I'll wait for the next turn of the crank -- most likely from Hewlett-Packard. If I need wireless communication in the meantime, I'll get a Megahertz card for my Macintosh PowerBook. Unless I can put it in my pocket, I don't need another machine right now.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:AAPL">Apple Computer, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:HWP">Hewlett-Packard Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:MOT">Motorola, Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
