	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Let Your Mouse Do the Walking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Let Your Mouse Do the Walking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Review  <p> LET YOUR MOUSE DO THE WALKING  <p> By Ted C. Fishman  <p> The most welcome advances in computer technology are often those that take old, familiar services and make them better and cheaper.Consider the telephone-directory-assistance sites now available on the World Wide Web. <a name="NYSE:NYN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11044"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nynex</b></a> Connection (http://www.niyp.com) has turned the business listings in the nation's yellow pages into a free database that can be searched by business name or type. To this capability Switchboard (http://www. switchboard.com) has added 90 million residential listings. Then there's the brand-new World Yellow Pages Network, or WYP.NET (http://wyp.net). In addition to simple searches, WYP.NET lets users look up businesses by zip code. And there's an on-line utility for finding the zip+4 code for any street address. But the site's most intriguing feature, also free, invites users to set up their own WYP.NET mini-Web page (text only, 300 words max), which will pop up whenever someone searches for their address. Those who already have sites elsewhere can add hyper-links. This may well be the form that all on-line directories take in the future.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunication Industry, Technology Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
