<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Compounding is Cool</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Compounding is Cool</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Compounding is Cool</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Review  <p> COMPOUNDING IS COOL  <p> By Ken Kurson  <p> GET A FINANCIAL LIFE: PERSONAL FINANCE IN YOUR TWENTIES ANDTHIRTIES  <p>By Beth Kobliner, Fireside, $11  <p> TIME IS MONEY: A MILLION-DOLLAR INVESTMENT PLAN FOR TODAY'S TWENTY- AND THIRTY-SOMETHINGS <p>By Frances Leonard, Addison-Wesley, $12  <p> Writing for novices about any complex topic is like having friends follow your car -- go too fast and you lose 'em, go too slow and you get rear-ended. When it comes to writing about money for youngish adults, however, calibrating the sophistication of the material is made more difficult by another critical element-- cool. That is, not only must the information be understandable without insulting the reader's intelligence, but its presentation must connect with its media-savvy, hipster-lite twentysomething target. It's an audience with a telepathic suspicion of jargon and get-rich-quickism, so the right tone is as important as the right information.  <p> Get a Financial Life, by Beth Kobliner, comes close to succeeding on both fronts. Comfortable with the vocabulary and attitude of a generation that's still characterized more by Slacker anomie than Friends effervescence, Kobliner has written a broad-ranging primer in the breezy magazine-speak befitting a contributing writer for Money. (She's loyal, too -- by the halfway point she's mentioned Money seven times.)  <p> Get a Financial Life also knows when to shut up. Because itranges from credit cards to car insurance to taxes, too much information on any one topic could easily send a reader scurrying for the comfort of MTV. Plenty of real-life examples, presented as illustrative side bars and laden with phone numbers, effectively keep monotony at bay. The quality of information is uniformly high, and there isn't a single chapter that doesn't contain useful but not obvious advice alongside a clear and well-presented blueprint.The investing section, for instance, covers everything from "What Is Stock?" to a deft explanation of the impact of inflation on the returns of various investments.  <p> The investment strategy Kobliner recommends, however, is oppressively conservative. Here's how she summarizes it: "I'm willing to stick my neck out and recommend a middle-of-the-road approach." Her program calls for a mix of 50 percent stocks, 30 percent bonds,and 20 percent cash, which had me wincing at the costs of missed opportunities. Kobliner dismisses the process of determining the appropriate level of risk for each individual with a couple of "Do you like to gamble?" questions and proceeds to recommend a strategy far more tentative than the old saw that says the percentage of stock in a portfolio should equal the investor's age subtracted from 100.  <p> Time Is Money, by Frances Leonard, sets much less ambitious goals for itself: It covers only the investment side of personal finance. Despite its allegiance to a single topic, however, Time Is Money haphazardly handles its sole insight -- that young people have a longer time horizon than old people. Compound interest is a hell of an idea, but writer-lecturer-attorney Leonard has a tough time filling an entire book with interesting examples of its magic, which may explain why a goofy quiz -- not to mention a blank page here and there -- follows every chapter. Leonard is a snappy and funny writer when she's not trying so hard, but references to "humongous bucks" and a <a name="NYSE:HDI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10706"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>"Harley-Davidson </b></a>big-twin"ring false.  <p> Mistakes are sprinkled throughout the book. A 0.5 percent back-endload would not mean a $50,000 hit on a $1 million redemption (it would be $5,000); a 403 percent increase is not a quadrupling of principal (it's a quintupling). But more troubling than mathematical errors is a structural flaw that runs through Time Is Money.All four of Leonard's recommended strategies employ a model that calls for monthly contributions of a manageable amount through one's 67th birthday. Yet the book's calculations depend on the assumption that 11 monthly deposits will be made after that 67th birthday.  <p> Money is a topic greeted by most young people with an enthusiasm usually reserved for jury duty. My experience editing a personal-finance magazine aimed specifically at those nauseated by the phrase" personal finance" has taught me that the only way to reach these readers is to convince them that nonaction spells disaster. Neither of these books is as urgent as it should be. The terror, bewilderment,and plain ennui that personal finance is capable of inspiring in most twentysomethings are blithely disregarded; both writers maintain that a bright future awaits any young investor who squirrels a way a couple bucks a month. And maybe that's true. But the message needs bigger teeth and more desperation to have a chance at cracking the jaded facade of today's young Americans.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
