<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Trucks in a Tux</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Smart%20Consumer>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Trucks in a Tux</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Are luxury SUVs just a vehicle for raising prices?  <p> By Jim Mateja  <p> It has become as de rigueur to have a sport-utility vehicle in your driveway as Blass and Givenchy in your closet -- not the real Messrs. Blass and Givenchy, of course, but the clothes they design. You get the point. Even more fashionable than your blue-collar SUVs are the newest niche vehicles emerging in the sport-ute line: Lexus, <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyota's</b></a> luxury division, now offers theLexus LX 450, while Acura,<a name="NYSE:HMC"></a><b> Honda's</b> alter ego, counters with the Acura SLX. Lincoln-Mercury and Infiniti will soon join in with, respectively, the Mountaineer (late this spring) and the QX4 (late fall), while Mercedes will unveil its AAV (All-Activity Vehicle) in the 1998 model year.  <p> What is a luxury SUV? At a press conference last November, Jim Press, Lexus division general manager at Toyota, described theLX 450 as "King Kong in a tuxedo: a blue-collar work machine gone black-tie." In other words, a four-wheel-drive truck with leather seats.   <p> What's troubling about these new models is that all but one is built from the same platform as an existing -- and less expensive-- SUV. The LX 450 is a dressed-up Toyota Land Cruiser, the SLX a dolled-up Isuzu Trooper, the QX4 a Nissan Pathfinder, the Mountaineer a version of the <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> Explorer. The Mercedes AAV is the only one that began life on a clean sheet of paper.   <p> Yet the LX 450 starts at $47,500, about $7,250 more than a Land Cruiser, while the SLX starts at $33,900, about five grand more than a Trooper. The QX4 should come in around $40,000, a few grand more than its progenitor.   <p> Mechanically, the luxury SUVs don't differ a whit from the vehicles that spawned them. The LX 450 has the same 4.5-liter, 212-horsepower six-cylinder as the Land Cruiser, the SLX the same 3.2-liter,193-horsepower V-6 as the Trooper. Where they depart from their host models is in subtle refinements to justify -- or allow buyers to rationalize -- the higher price tags. The luxury SUVs offer plusher interiors, with leather upholstery and just about every power system available as standard features. There are also top-of-the-line sound systems, air-conditioning, and sunroofs. Since all the creature comforts are standard, options are held to a minimum. <p> But for $40,000, you'd expect some new technology and engineering innovation, and neither the LX 450 nor the SLX provides any gee-whiz features -- except that the premium SLX has a button in the console that flattens the outside mirrors against the vehicle body to avoid contact with car-wash brushes and mailbox doors. Neat feature, but for $40,000 don't you want a bunch of neat features?  <p> This is plain and simple badge engineering -- sticking a new name on an existing model, as if the consumer is too dumb to realize he or she is paying for camouflage. Jim Press disagrees."If we had taken a Corolla and made it a Lexus, then that would have been badge engineering," he says. He argues that since theLX 450 comes off the Land Cruiser, a semi-luxury model itself, it doesn't deserve the badge-engineering rap, but that's a difference without a distinction.  <p> If function is more important than designer labels, stick with the current crop of compact SUVs: the Chevy Blazer, Ford Explorer,and Jeep Cherokee. For value, check out mini SUVs, which offer the same features as the compacts, only in smaller packages for less money. You'll miss only the leather seats.  <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
