						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> TRAVEL THROUGH CYBERSPACE <p>Cash in your frequent-flier miles without leaving your chair <p> By Laura Koss-Feder  <p> The next time you want to redeem your precious frequent-flier miles or hotel points, you may need only to sit down at your computer. The new Status site on the World Wide Web (http://www.status.com) allows members of travel programs to take stock of what they've earned and order coupons good for their travel awards. American and United Airlines and <a name="NYSE:MAR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10958"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Marriott</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:HLT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10733"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hilton Hotels</b></a> are now linked to Status; discussions are under way to add several other airlines and hotel chains. Car-rental companies could be brought on board by summer.  <p> Status users are given identification numbers and passwords to protect the confidentiality of their information. The site also provides links to sites on such topics as currency exchangerates, airline on-time statistics, and locations of airport lounges. <p><p>
