	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Software with Style</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Software with Style</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> SOFTWARE WITH STYLE <p>One $95 program takes most of the hard work out of style analysis for individual investors  <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> Some say style-analysis software is a revolutionary new product that will change how we analyze mutual funds. Others call it voodoo. Our conclusion after evaluating all three of the leading packages designed for institutional investors: Style-analysis software does offer valuable insight into how a fund earns its returns --  but like many powerful financial tools this one can all too easily produce misleading results in the hands of an inexperienced investor or financial adviser.  <p> Style-analysis software characterizes a mutual fund's style of investing based on finding the best match between a fund's monthly returns and the performance of some combination of indexes. It therefore eliminates the need to decipher a fund's investment strategy by poring over outdated fundamentals and lists of portfolio holdings that mutual funds report only twice a year.  <p> But that doesn't mean this software is easy to use correctly--  or that it should replace all other kinds of analysis. The investor operating the software must know enough about an individual fund to pick the right indexes for comparison. For instance,we deliberately tried to trick one of the programs by matching the <a name="FUND:VFINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VFINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard Index Trust 500 Portfolio</b></a>, which replicates the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index, with some unlikely indexes.The software fell for this ruse, telling us that the Vanguard fund behaved as if 42 percent of its assets were invested insmall-cap growth stocks, 29 percent in corporate bonds, 18 percent in British stocks, and 12 percent in Canadian equities. Together those indexes explained 82 percent of the fund's returns. That's not a very useful conclusion.  <p> "People say you can just run the fund's total returns through a computer, and it will magically ferret out what the fund invested in," says Don Phillips, president of Morningstar. "I think that just like every other shortcut in the investment universe it's fraught with peril."   <p> Style analysis, however, will show details about a fund's strategy that are hard to pick up using other methods. It reveals, for instance, that <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Magellan</b></a> has a surprisingly large foreign exposure because it owns stock in so many multinationals that collect earnings in foreign currencies.  <p> Instead of the institutional programs we tried, investors might consider a product from Advisor Software in Orinda, California. Advisor Software's $95 program, Style Data (800-738-6369), doesn'trequire the user to learn the ins and outs of dozens of financial indexes or statistical techniques such as regression analysis.Instead it reports the results of style analyses performed bytrained experts who have compared 5,200 funds with the most appropriate12 indexes. (You'll need <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> Excel for Windows version5.0 to run the data.) Investors can see the style of their fundsor search for the best way to combine different styles. They can also look up the styles of individual funds for free at the company's World Wide Web page (http://www. advisorsw.com). <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

