				<font size=5><b>Creditworthy at Last</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Creditworthy at Last</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996
Worth magazine/Personal Adviser<p>CREDITWORTHY AT LAST
Visa and MasterCard team up to secure Internet charges.<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Afraid cyber-thieves will snatch your credit-card number when you buy something on the Internet? Visa and MasterCard recently joined forces on a new technology called SET (Secure Electronic Transactions), which scrambles credit-card numbers so that only the receiving merchant or bank can access the data. That means Joe Hacker will have a much tougher time copying your number and charging his spring wardrobe to your account.<p>To display the Visa or MasterCard logo in an on-line store window, a merchant must be accredited by a member bank. "You'll know you're not dealing with some college kid who's set up a Web site that looks like a fancy store," says Richard Lonergan, executive vice president at Visa.<p>The entente between Visa and MasterCard has eased concerns that there would be several different payment protocols coexisting on the Web. The credit-card titans plan to start testing SET on the Web this spring and hope to make it available to consumers by the end of the year. "This technology should allay security fears," says Edgar Dworsky, director of consumer education at the Massachusetts Executive Office of Consumer Affairs. "Eventually, you'll be more likely to get your credit-card number ripped off when you're ordering something over a cordless phone."<p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
