	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Mind Your Mortgage</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Mind Your Mortgage</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> MIND YOUR MORTGAGE <p>If your lender made a mistake with your mortgage payment, would you know it?  Here's how to keep tabs on your tab.  <p> By Ellen DePasquale  <p> In an effort to turn our 30-year fixed-rate mortgage into a15-year mortgage, my husband and I recently started making monthly prepayments. We used our computer to generate an amortization table so that we could see exactly how our prepayments would reduce the principal balance and shorten the length of the loan. After making our first prepayment, we called the automated customer-inquiry service offered by our lender to check the payoff figure against what we had calculated.  <p> We found that our prepayment hadn't been credited. When we asked about it, the human customer-service department told us that our principal prepayment had been mistakenly credited to our escrow account, where it would be used for items such as real estate taxes and mortgage insurance. If we hadn't checked our figures, we would have received a sizable reimbursement when the bank assessed our escrow for the coming year, and in years to come, our principal figures would have been far off our lender's. <p> "Homeowners have too much trust in the lending institutions," says Richard Allridge of Allridge and Associates, a financial-planning firm in Bethesda, Maryland. The majority of homeowners Allridge works with do not monitor their mortgages, despite the fact that banks make many errors in handling them. Adjustable-rate mortgages, precisely because of their adjustability, are a particular problem: According to a 1991 study by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, 38 to 46 percent of all ARMs are adjusted incorrectly usually in a way that works against the homeowner.  <p> ARMs are particularly susceptible to mistakes resulting from banks' using the wrong index to figure out mortgage rates. The index most commonly the interest rate on one-year Treasury bills, though other durations can be used is agreed to in the mortgage contract, along with the dates on which the mortgage will be adjusted. Banks can err on either count.  <p> The first step toward finding a bank error is getting information on mortgage payments. Banks usually have customer-service departments that can tell borrowers how each payment was applied, but most borrowers get mortgage information solely from the interest statement their lender provides for tax purposes each year. If asked, most lenders will also provide a more detailed, month-by-month record of each payment made, and where the money went to interest, principal, escrow, etc. With that in hand, the borrower can double-check that each payment was properly applied.  <p> Personal-finance programs for home computers have made it much easier for borrowers to evaluate their bank's numbers. I  used Bankonit!, a fairly primitive program that I got via mail order, to calculate amortization tables for my loan, but software has gotten much more sophisticated than that. LoanWatch ($149 from Compu-Share; 800-928-2456) manages several types of loans, including fixed- and adjustable-rate mortgages. It produces amortization tables, recalculates the principal in light of prepayments, and even checks the index through updates sent every adjustment period.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Homeowners, Real Estate, Mortgages

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
