<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Middle-Class Medicaid</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Middle-Class Medicaid</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Middle-Class Medicaid</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> MIDDLE-CLASS MEDICAID <p>The elderly can protect assets with long-term-care insurance. <p> By Donna Fenn  <p> Forty-three percent of the over-65 population can expect to spend time in a nursing home an average of 2.5 years, commonly costing $30,000 to $65,000 a year. Medicare won't foot that bill, and Medicaid kicks in only for those who've spent their assets down to poverty level. But a growing number of states are linking long-term-care insurance to Medicaid in a way that will let people protect their assets.   <p> Connecticut, Indiana, California, and New York are the original participants in a three-year-old program called the Partnership for Long Term Care, which helps state governments set up alliances with private insurers. Illinois, Maryland, and Iowa are in the final stages of implementing partnerships, and seven other states have passed the legislation needed to get started. David Guttchen, the project director of Connecticut's program, says he has received requests for information from over 25 states.   <p> Consumers who purchase partnership insurance policies can apply to Medicaid under a special set of eligibility rules when their insurance benefits are exhausted. In Connecticut, Indiana, and California, every dollar paid out by a partnership policy for long-term care protects a dollar of assets from Medicaid eligibility requirements. So if an insurer has paid a claimant $75,000 in benefits, he or she can keep that much in assets and still be eligible for Medicaid.   <p> New York's plan is even more generous: A certified policy that covers three years in a nursing home or six years of home health care results in total asset protection. Any subsequent care is covered by Medicaid, no matter how much money a participant has in savings. "For middle-class people with $50,000 to $250,000 in assets, these are particularly valuable programs," says Mark Meiners, director of the partnership's national office at the University of Maryland Center on Aging. <p>  <p>Anne Rich, a 49-year-old accountant in Cheshire, Connecticut, bought long-term-care insurance two years ago. "It's good to know that I won't have to go into poverty if I ever need Medicaid," she says. "It helps you keep a little of your dignity." Rich pays about $1,000 a year for $100,000 worth of coverage. Rates rise steeply as the insured gets older; a 70-year-old buying coverage can pay four times as much as a 55-year-old.  <p> The partnership puts several restrictions on the types of insurance eligible for the program. For example, the policy must offer both home-care and nursing-home coverage. Each insurer should know which of its long-term-care plans fit the criteria.  <p> While interest in the plans is widespread, several states, including Massachusetts, Colorado, and Michigan, are at a standstill because of a law that requires new plans to restrict the asset-protection coverage to the insured's lifetime. When the participant dies, states would recover any Medicaid spending from the remaining protected assets. Several bills now in Congress have proposed removing that restriction to encourage the creation of the partnerships. <p> The partnership programs have their critics. "At a time when Medicaid resources are scarce, the state may be spending on individuals who are clearly not impoverished," says Howard Bedlin, legislative representative for the American Association for Retired People. But Gail Holubinka, director of New York's partnership program, contends that people are already artificially impoverishing themselves to qualify for Medicaid. "In 1988, 60 percent of New Yorkers entering nursing homes were Medicaid-funded from the beginning," she says. "Does that sound right to you?" Holubinka argues that the partnership encourages people to be financially responsible for their long-term care, saving Medicaid money in the long run. And with Congress discussing cuts in Medicaid funding, creative solutions like this one should continue to gain popularity. <p> ------ <p>Joining the Partnership  <p> For more information on partnership policies, the program office numbers are:   <p> California: 800-434-0222 <p>Connecticut: 800-547-3443 <p>Illinois<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Legislation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
