	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Maana, Havana</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Maana, Havana</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Maana, Havana</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> MAANA, HAVANA <p>Cuban cigars don't light up today's brand of smoker.    <p> By Manjeet Kripalani  <p> Observant sorts who wander through the newly fashionable cigar bars in America have noticed something missing: the fabled Cuban cigar. They are available to those in the know; industry insiders estimate that 5 million to15 million Cuban cigars are smuggled into the U.S. every year, of the 150 million premium cigars smoked. But the new breed of American cigar smoker has gotten used to going without Los Cubanos.  <p> Prior to the Cuban embargo, the tobacco in all premium cigars sold in the U.S. came from Cuba. After 1962, American companies shifted their production to the Dominican Republic and Honduras, both of which now produce cigars of excellent quality. American cigar tastes have also changed. The baby boomers and Generation X crowd responsible for the stogie's resurgence premium cigar sales in the U.S. have tripled since the 1970s prefer a milder cigar to a strong Cuban Cohiba. And Cuban cigars lost their champion after Fidel Castro stopped smoking them eight years ago. But the most basic reason may be that they just don't make them likethey used to.  <p> The decline of the once-magnificent Havana is illustrated by cigar strategies in Canada, a land unhindered by a trade embargo with Cuba. Take Thomas Hinds, Canadian tobacconist. In Toronto, Hinds used to do a brisk trade almost exclusively in Havanas. After reading of the high ratings of Dominican and Honduran cigars in Cigar Aficionado magazine, Hinds offered his customers a tryout. "I brought in brands that sold well in the U.S.," says Hinds."I sold out. Now Canadians who smoked only Havanas are smoking 60 percent Cuban and 40 percent non-Cuban cigars." Hinds attributes the popularity of the latter to the excellent quality of the hand-rolled new comers. Emboldened by the success of non-Cubans, Hinds set up shop in July in Beverly Hills, where he sells all manner of non-Havana cigars.   <p> Cigar lover Chuck Caulkins, a 39-year-old marketing executive in New York City, is a baby boomer who has been smoking cigars for 15 years. He remembers the old Havanas and thinks that their time has passed. "These days, the draw isn't smooth, neither is it rolled smoothly," Caulkins says. "And why pay $20 in the black market for a Cuban cigar when you can get an excellent, complicated non-Cuban for $7?"   <p> Indeed, why pay top dollar for a smoke that ain't that good?" You know the Americans they're the first to say, Oh no, I don't get my value here,' " says Christoph Kull, president of the U.S. operations of Davidoff of Geneva. In 1989, Davidoff closed its Cuban operations, thinking the quality of its product no longer met the company's exacting standards. It now makes its cigars in Honduras and the Dominican Republic.  <p> President Clinton recently decided to loosen communication and travel restrictions to Cuba, although lifting the embargo will most likely have to wait until Castro meets his end. What will happen then, when the fragrance of those Havanas comes wafting over to U.S. shores?  <p> "Nothing," says Robert Kemp, publisher of The Cigar Monthly. "Cubans will be a big deal in New York and Los Angeles, prices will rise, then the craze will fade and people will go back to smoking non-Cuban cigars. A lot of people couldn't care less about Cuban cigars."  <p> ------ <p>Smoke 'Em if You Got 'Em: The Best Non-Cubans  <p> By Teri Karush  <p> Even in places where Cuban cigars are legally available, such as Canada, non-Cubans have made their mark on the stogie community. "People who smoke only Cuban cheat themselves of the opportunity to experience a rich breadth of flavors," says Peter Dobbs, general manager of Thomas Hinds Tobacconists in Toronto. "It's like drinking only French Bordeaux. Imagine never tasting a fine California cabernet sauvignon or Italian Barolo." Here's Dobbs's take on some of his most popular non-Cubans:  <p> Puros Indios (Honduras): "Gorgeous wrapper leaf, broad range of character. A cigar you crave over and over again."  <p> Arturo Fuente Opus X (Dominican Republic): "For anyone who's a big smoker of Cuban cigars. Has every flavor, nuance, and enjoyment of a great cigar."  <p> Ashton Maduro (Dominican Republic): "A subtle, mild, meaty flavor that's fat and filling. Not heavy or hard. A cigar for everyone." <p> Don Lino Havana Reserve (Honduras): "A more mature tobacco. Aged well. Tastes like it's ready to be smoked. More full-bodied than most non-Cuban cigars."  <p> Thomas Hinds Honduran Selection Robusto (Honduras): "A creamy, mushroomy nuance. It's not designed to kick you in the butt. A simple cigar to understand, one everyone can appreciate." <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

