	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Double Dialing for Dollars</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Double Dialing for Dollars</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Double Dialing for Dollars</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> DOUBLE DIALING FOR DOLLARS <p>Two long-distance plans are better than one.  <p> By Ellen James Martin  <p> America's mailboxes have been swamped lately with come-ons from companies reselling phone capacity from the major carriers: VoiceNet, Valu-Tel, Ameracall, Atlas, and hundreds more. They boast ofbig discounts in comparison with <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>,and <a name="NYSE:FON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11560"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sprint</b></a>, and in some cases they're right. But there's no need to pick a reseller over a long-distance giant. Since the resellers usually offer their deals through access codes (usually a five-digit prefix, an 800 number, or a 950 number), callers can stick with their major carrier and dial in to the little guys only when the prices make it worthwhile.   <p> For instance, Sprint heavily promotes its Sprint Sense program,which gives subscribers in most states a flat rate of 10 cents a minute on evenings and weekends. But the price jumps to 22 cents a minute during daytime hours on weekdays. Using Telegroup, a typical reseller, during work hours cuts the charges almost in half: a flat rate of 12.9 cents per minute on domestic calls at all times. Or for heavy-volume callers, VarTec Telecom charges10 cents a minute around the clock, but with a five-dollar monthly fee. The choice of plans is virtually endless: The Long Distance Resellers Source Book, published every spring and fall by Phone+magazine ($12.95; 602-990-1101), lists more than 600 resellers and their plans.   <p> Mixing and matching phone plans does have its limitations. If you use an  access code without registering with the company, you may not get the best rates. On the other hand, the market is so competitive that callers can often negotiate rates below the standard discounts. <p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
