	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Cruise Control</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Cruise Control</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Cruise Control</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Adviser  <p> CRUISE CONTROL <p>Are you a Princess, a Celebrity, or a Royal Viking?  <p> By Rudy Maxa  <p> It's 1996, and this is not your father's cruise ship. You know the one, where every passenger collects Social Security and a walk on the wild side means staying up for the midnight buffet. According to the Cruise Lines International Association, babyboomers make up 52 percent of cruise passengers. So even though the number of passengers dipped slightly last year, cruise lines are ordering up more and bigger ships in anticipation of a baby boomer surge and are also trying to differentiate themselves from one another. How do you know which one is right for you? Let's generalize: <p> Romance: You want short cruises on a budget? Consider Carnival Cruise Lines, Kathie Lee Gifford's favorite. Four of the world's ten largest cruise ships are Carnival ships, and they attract a first-time passenger looking for a casual, moderately priced cruise. For a more upscale experience, consider the Royal Caribbean, Princess, Celebrity, and Norwegian lines. Expect better wine lists, less passenger density, and larger cabins. But remember, two ships in the same line can be quite different, so it's important to choose a specific ship, not just a certain line. A seven-night Caribbean cruise on Carnival's Celebration ranges from $529 to$964, not including airfare; a similar cruise aboard the Princess line's Regal costs between $799 and $2,039 per person, not including airfare.  <p> Family fun: Cunard's legendary Queen Elizabeth 2 offers English nannies on board. Many ships have "camps" for kids, including some from Carnival, Royal Caribbean, and Premier. Premier, like some others, also offers special "single parent" deals. Don't trust your travel agent always check with the cruise line to make sure the trip you're considering caters to kids.   <p> Luxury: Check out brochures for ships of the Seabourn, Cunard, Silversea, Radisson, Renaissance, and Crystal lines. For a larger tab, you'll find gourmet food, select wines, outside cabins only, no pressure to participate in structured events, fewer feathers in the stage shows, plenty of caviar, open sittings at dinner, and no plastic cutlery even at outdoor dining sites. Fares on Seabourn for a five-night Caribbean cruise range from $2,475 to $4,250, including airfare; a seven-night cruise on Cunard's Sea Goddess I costs $4,500 to $6,800 with airfare.   <p> At the top end of the luxury scale, Cunard's Royal Viking Sun was rated the best cruise ship in the world by the bible of the industry, the Berlitz 1996 Complete Guide to Cruising and Cruise Ships. It has everything you can possibly imagine on a luxuryship, casino, gym, library, even a golf club with an electronic golf-course simulator. The Royal Viking Sun set sail in January from Fort Lauderdale on a round-the-world cruise; fares for the entire 114-night trip started at $40,000.  <p> Seniors: In general, you'll find an older crowd on longer voyages, such as transoceanic trips, than on Caribbean island-hoppers. Many lines, including Cunard, Regency, and Royal, provide male guest hosts to serve as dining and dancing partners on longer cruises, where the passengers tend to be mostly female.<p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
