	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Be My Virtual Valentine</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Be My Virtual Valentine</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> BE MY VIRTUAL VALENTINE <p>This year, let your modem do the walking.  <p> By Dean Robinson  <p> A rose on a computer screen may not smell that sweet, but at least you can see the Valentine's Day flowers you order over the Internet. Your inamorata in Arizona deserves flowers, but should you go with roses to say "I love you" or a  modest bouquet that says "I really like you"? Dial up the Flower Link Web site (http://go.flowerlink.com/html/menu1.html), click the search option, and enter a zip code. Up pops the Web site for Tucson's Inglis Florists, which includes a menu of prices and, best of all, pictures of arrangements. Say, that Crystal Keepsake bouquet doesn't look half bad.  <p> If you want to comparison-shop, other outfits that deliver nationally have their own Web sites, such as 1-800-Flowers (http://www.1800flowers.com),which also sells flowers via CompuServe and <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b>. You can even get economic forecasts and find out why roses cost so much more in February.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
