<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Bank Robbery?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Bank Robbery?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Bank Robbery?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> BANK ROBBERY? <p>Bank customers are still being sold mutual fund investments they don't understand   <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> In 1992, Roy Burgess, an 81-year-old retired minister from Dothan, Alabama, put his life savings into a mutual fund bought through his bank AmSouth. By the time he sold the <a name="FUND:PGMAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PGMAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pilgrim Adjustable U.S. Government Securities fund</b></a> now an Astra fund in early 1995, he had lost $20,000 of his $90,000 nest egg. On Burgess's behalf, the Worth Advocate contacted the Alabama State Securities Commission. Burgess filed a formal complaint, claiming that his goal had been to protect his principal and that he had never been advised about the risks of the fund.  <p> The Securities Commission has since launched an investigation that could help him and six other clients of AmSouth Investment Services recoup lost principal totaling $200,000 plus interest. <p> But the larger issue raised by the Burgess case is: How many bank customers are being sold funds as if they were as safe as a federally insured savings account?   <p> Banks got into the fund business in the 1980s and certainly haven't established an unblemished record. For example, last year arbitrators at the National Association of Securities Dealers found a "prevailing environment of improper business practices" at First Union National Bank's brokerage. Other major banks,including NationsBank, GlenFed, and Great Western, face class-action lawsuits by customers over fund sales.  <p> Some 200 formal consumer complaints about bank-sold funds were registered with state securities regulators in the first half of 1995, according to the North American Securities Administrators Association. "I think it's just the tip of the iceberg," says Denise Voigt Crawford, Texas securities commissioner and chair of a NASAA committee examining the issue. Complaints to the Securities and Exchange Commission's Office of Investor Education and Assistance, while small in number, more than doubled last year.  <p> Guidelines issued in 1994 were supposed to make banks, which sold $60 billion in mutual funds that year, clean up their acts. Regulators required banks and thrifts to disclose to potential investors four mutual fund risks, including potential loss of principal and lack of coverage by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation. But according to a survey by the General Accounting Office, which sent employees to banks to pose as potential fund customers, just one in three banks and thrifts mentioned all four risks. One in five mentioned none.   <p> New rules soon to be released by the NASD will take another shot at reform. They address such dubious practices as bankers' passing on information about customers' accounts to fund brokers, and brokers' paying fees to bank employees for referrals of customers .Unfortunately, under pressure from bankers, the NASD has weakened these rules.  <p> Investors who feel they've been misled by their banks can file a complaint with their state securities commission, the SEC, and federal and state banking regulators. The state commission will know if other complaints have been lodged against a given bank. Finally, customers can consult a lawyer who specializes in securities arbitration. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Mutual Funds Investing, Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

