	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>They've Got Your Number</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-They've Got Your Number</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> THEY'VE GOT YOUR NUMBER <p>Telemarketers may already have your credit card in hand  <p> By Dean Robinson  <p> Some telemarketers may have more than your phone number with which to irritate you--they may already have the numbers and expiration dates of your credit cards. Several telemarketers have taken advantage of the fact that providing confidential information is not technically illegal by selling card numbers to other marketers.   <p> Late last year, the Federal Trade Commission, in the first case of its kind, settled with ten corporations involved in the unauthorized sale or rental of consumers' credit-card numbers to direct-marketing third parties. The direct marketers had been contacting cardholders and--without revealing that they had credit-card information in hand--charging their accounts as soon as the cardholders agreed to test products or services on a "free" trial basis. The defendants were banned from providing confidential credit-card information to third parties; they also agreed to pay nearly $300,000, which will be returned to consumers.  <p> "No law explicitly says you can't sell credit-card numbers," says Lucy Morris, an assistant director for credit practices at the FTC. This means that consumers must rely on the FTC, whose mandate is to fight unfair or deceptive practices, and on the marketers themselves.  <p> "You bring a case to send a message," says Morris. A strong message may have been needed, too. William Reihl, a spokesman for the American Telemarketing Association, says his group does not have specific rules safeguarding the use of credit-card numbers. Direct Marketing Association guidelines state that numbers should not be rented or sold "when the consumer has a reasonable expectation that the information will be kept confidential.  <p> Morris says that individuals can protect themselves from potential problems by taking the standard credit-card precautions: don't engage in transactions you haven't initiated, know who you're dealing with, and remember that the Fair Credit Billing Act gives you the right to dispute charges to your account. She doesn't think consumers need to worry about most vendors selling cred-card numbers. "I don't think legitimate companies do this," she says. On the other hand, Morris concedes she doesn't know how widespread the practice of selling credit-card numbers is. And there is one area where vigilance is justified: the Internet. "That's where people are giving out their credit-card numbers," she says. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency, Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
