				<font size=5><b>The Future Is Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-The Future Is Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> THE FUTURE IS NOW <p>The end of the century comes early for check writers  <p> By Tom Nawrocki  <p> End of the millennium watch: Before long--maybe as soon as your next batch of checks--you're going to have to write the whole year on the dateline as opposed to tacking a 96 on to the preprinted19.   <p> "All our new check designs will not have the 19 on the dateline so they will be able to transcend the turn of the century," says Stuart Alexander, vice president of corporate communications for Deluxe Corp., which prints more than half the nation's checks and is the world's leading check printer. "The existing check designs as they are updated will also have that change made, so that the entire check inventory will be changed over well before the end of the 1900s." And after 2000 arrives? "We'll cross that bridge when we get to it," says Alexander.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

