	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Little Dish, Big Choice</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Little Dish, Big Choice</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Little Dish, Big Choice</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> LITTLE DISH, BIG CHOICE <p>From the Cleveland Browns to CNBC in 150 channels  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> A few months ago, Ted Sturman invested in the future to buy back a piece of his past. Sturman, a psychology professor at the University of Southern Maine in Portland, sorely missed the sports teams of his native Ohio--so much so that he laid out nearly $700 for a satellite-TV system that offers him the sportschannels shown to the Clevelanders back home. "Now, I can watch an Indians game at night or settle down with the Cleveland Browns on a Sunday," says Sturman, who's lived in Portland for just over a year. "I see local commercials from Ohio that bring me back to my childhood."   <p> The system Sturman bought, however, hardly harkens back to the Volkswagen-size satellite dishes of yore. The new satellite-TV systems are more like Hot Wheels cars: smaller, sleeker, and soon to be very affordable. Although not quite two years old, small-dish satellite-TV setups are already found in almost 2 million American households.  <p> Until the birth of these compact systems, a satellite-TV dish spanned ten feet and cost around $2,000. Today, a system requires an investment of just $200, nestles inconspicuously on the roof of a home or apartment building, and delivers exclusive programming. And with newcomers joining the satellite market soon, prices are expected to drop and choices to multiply. "Once the competition heats up, they'll probably start giving the hardware away just to get eyeballs," says James Scott, editor of Satellite TV Week.  <p> For now, though, two small-dish satellite systems are available: the RCA Digital Satellite System, which offers two programming choices--DirecTV and USSB--and Primestar. The RCA dish costs $550 to $1,000 (depending on the model) plus $199 for installation; Primestar leases its dish for an up-front payment of $200, including installation.  <p> But before beaming into space, know that network broadcasting is not always included, meaning no Seinfeld or X-Files unless the viewer gets a basic cable hook-up ($10 to $25 per month plus installation) or adds an antenna to get the local network affiliates. Or the satellite company will zap you a network signal from a distant city for a nominal fee.  <p> DirecTV, which runs $29.95 a month, boasts a 65-network-channel menu similar to cable's (CNN, CNBC, etc.), 29 audio-only channels, and 7 movie channels. And sports zealots take note: DirecTV offers an NFL package (choose any of 13 games every Sunday for $139), an NBA package (all 700 regular-season games for $149), and an NHL package ($99 for the whole season). Last year, DirecTV offered its Major League Baseball package for free, but next year's edition will carry a price tag that has yet to be announced.   <p> For premium channels, you need to add USSB to the mix. USSB carries 21 programming options for $34.95 a month, including five HBO, three Showtime, three Cinemax, and two Movie Channel channels.   <p> With Primestar, which for $45 a month offers 90 channels, in addition to the standard cable lineup, you can click from 16 regional sports networks to movie channels that show only westerns or mysteries. There are also three HBO and two Cinemax channels airing different shows, thanks to feeds from different time zones. Primestar also offers season-long sports packages similar to those on DirecTV.  <p> New providers are coming: By mid-December, AlphaStar will launch programming, and EchoStar will debut next February. "Unlike cable, the satellite industry is wide open to competition," says Scott."There will be better prices and wider variety as new companies emerge." After all, there's plenty of room in space. <p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Telecommunications Industry, Homeowner

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
