<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Hit the Info Highway</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Hit the Info Highway</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Hit the Info Highway</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> HIT THE INFO HIGHWAY <p>Car-lease shoppers have begun cruising the Internet  <p> By Ellen DePasquale  <p> In increasing numbers, potential car buyers are becoming potential car leasers, and thousands of them have turned to a new resource: the information superhighway. Leases now account for 30 percent of all deliveries of new cars, up from just 7 percent a decade ago, according to Business Trend Analysts, a Commack, New York, marketing research firm. It's only natural that leasing information should sprout up on the Internet.  <p> The Internet helped David Goldstein, owner of a software-production company in Seattle, make his decision to lease. While waiting in a car dealership to look at a $13,700 Plymouth Neon last February, Goldstein noticed an ad in a local paper for a leasing deal on an Infiniti. That night, he downloaded some numbers to his home computer from several online services and crunched out some leasing costs. He found that his monthly outlay would be the same for purchasing the Neon as for leasing a $24,325 1995 Infiniti G20. <p> "I was able to plug in the figures I had and determine that the Infiniti payment should come to $208 a month," Goldstein says. "The dealer came back with $210, which I accepted." Indeed, luxury-car dealerships seem to be the best place to hunt for leasing bargains--partly because of manufacturer subsidies and partly because of strong resale values, both of which help lower monthly payments.   <p> If leasing seems worth pursuing, the first step is to find out how much the dealer paid for the car which will determine how much he's willing to take for it. CompuServe offers car datasheets that include the manufacturer's suggested retail price and dealer invoice prices as well as charges for available options. Each sheet, provided through an agreement with Automotive Information Center in Acton, Massachusetts, costs $1.50. Prodigy and <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b>, as well as CompuServe, provide access to magazines suchas Car and Driver and  Consumer Reports that have information on car values. The online services also provide user forums, such as CompuServe's Automobile Forum, where people around the country offer tips and opinions on leases and car models.  <p> With price information in hand, a shopper can then check out FinanCenter's Auto, Boat, and RV Loan Department, a division of Banker's Portfolio Exchange in Tucson, Arizona (the Internet address is http://www.financenter.com/resources/autoloan/index.htm). This site helps calculate the cost of leasing a car and offers a downloadable page of key clauses in lease agreements, which illustrates various ways in which contracts can be written. It also identifies points that should be specified and negotiated with the dealer, such as charges for excess wear, early termination, and excess mileage.  <p> Those who decide to lease can then use the Internet to set up a deal through the Auto-By-Tel web site (http://www.autobytel.com). This service maintains a database of dealers who pay a fee to Auto-By-Tel to receive requests from potential buyers or leasers. Prospective leasers enter their name, address, phone number, and type of car desired; a dealer in the area will then call with his or her leasing terms. Armed with all the other information leaned from the Internet, leasers will be ready to negotiate. The leaser has to go to a dealer showroom only to sign the papers and pick up the keys. Thanks to the Internet, the traditional haggling over price has become more of a contest between equals. <p> MEANWHILE, ON YOUR LOCAL DRIVE  <p> You don't need to explore the Internet to get help with a car lease. The CD-ROM Popular Mechanics' New Car Buyers Guide 1996 ($29.95 from Books That Work; 800-242-4546) offers similar information to help shoppers make up their minds about a car lease. It provides sticker prices and dealers' invoice prices as well as lease-versus-buy calculations.  <p> There are also several software programs that can help in understanding the leasing process, the terms, and the monthly-payment calculation. The best are Expert Lease ($99.95 from Chart Software; 800-418-8450), a stand-alone application that includes MSRP and dealer invoice prices, and AutoFinII, a spreadsheet that works with Lotus 1-2-3 and <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> Excel ($49 from Village Software; 800-724-9332).Both of these programs can instantly calculate how changing one element of a lease affects monthly payments. Given data suchas the length of the lease, any capitalized-cost-reduction payments, residual value, and the interest rate, they will calculate an expected monthly payment to compare with a dealer's offer.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

