		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Investigating Inventory</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Investigating Inventory</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> INVESTIGATING INVENTORY <p>Inventory numbers can be a crystal ball into a company's future--and its stock value  <p> By Maxwell Dale  <p> Everyone who has taken an introductory course in economics knows that a balance sheet is a snapshot of a company's assets and liabilities at a single moment in time. Yet balance sheets also hold a prediction of the future--one investors should know about. <p> This prediction is found on the line entitled "inventories"--the dollar value of the finished goods and supplies a going concern has on hand. Because companies usually have to commit to making something before they can sell it, a large inventory generally reflects high expectations; a small one, the reverse.  <p> A company can get into deep trouble when its sales predictions go awry in either direction. If an automaker builds more minivans than people want to buy, its only recourse is to slash prices--at the expense of profit--to move the goods.  <p> Earlier this year, <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a> found out what happens when a company guesses too low. Apple built too few new Power PC machines,causing a backup in demand, lost sales--and again, lost profits. <p> Effective inventory management is especially critical for retailers, since few make their own goods. This is why securities analysts who follow retail stocks pay so much attention to inventory numbers heading into the all-important Christmas selling season.  <p> In the end, a retailer's success during the holidays depends almost entirely on how good a job it does predicting consumer demand for each line of goods it sells. Stocking up on Mighty Morphin Power Rangers when people want G.I. Joes is an example of the biggest mistake a retailer can make: It must then sell the Power Rangers at discount while losing G.I. Joe sales to a more prescient rival.  <p> Investors who want to keep tabs on a company's ability to manage its future need to understand the relationship between production, inventories, and sales. Higher production will lead automatically to higher inventories unless sales keep pace.  <p> That's why rising inventories are often an early sign of trouble--sales are not meeting managers' expectations. Expect price cutting and curtailments in production (even layoffs) to follow.  <p><a name="NYSE:ANN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14959"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ann Taylor Stores</b></a> is a case in point. The company's stock peaked at $44 a share last December but then collapsed to $17 during the next ten months as its sales weakened and it cut back an aggressive expansion program. A full month before the peak in the 1994 share price, however, Ann Taylor's third-quarter inventory showed an unexpected 31 percent increase--a jump that far exceeded sales growth.  <p> There are some times, though, when a rise in inventories is positive: It may mean a company is confident about a new product launch and is stocking up. To tell the difference, investors need to know the story management has to tell. Next, they should compare that with their own opinion--will that new cherry-lemon-kumquat soft drink really fly off the shelves?--and with the way the sales, inventory, and production numbers have been tracking. A company that manages its inventories well is a company in touch with the future.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economic Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
