	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01S-Days of Wine&Heavy Statuary</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Days of Wine and Heavy Statuary</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-Days of Wine&Heavy Statuary</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special Issue <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> DAYS OF WINE AND HEAVY STATUARY  <p>Experts give the lowdown on seven art markets  <p> By Carlos A. Rosas  <p> Art, the maxim goes, is not an investment. Of course this is true: Art is bought to be savored, adored, experienced, then bestowed upon a  museum for the public's edification. But it's also true that a lot of art moves in and out of dealers' and collectors' hands, finds its way to auction blocks all over the world, and goes up and down in price. Here are some of the categories art auctioneers and other experts will be watching in 1996. <p> WINE <p>Last november, Sotheby's kicked off its three-session wine auction with an evening sale, a distinction generally reserved for the best (or most hyped) impressionist paintings. This capped wine's recent journey from a commodity that the big auction houses in New York were prohibited from handling state law changed in 1993 to one capable of bringing out the swells. Prices have risen accordingly: One bottle of 1900 Chteau Margaux sold for $10,975 at a Sotheby's sale last June. Still, experts say there are some very fine wines that can be had for much less.   <p> Fritz Hatton, Christie's New York: "I suggest 1981 red Bordeaux wines. It is an A-minus vintage that can be picked up, in some cases, for less than half of what the celebrated 1982 wines cost. Consider Chteau Gruaud-Larose: A 1981 case recently sold for a little over $300 versus a 1982, which fetched close to $1,000. Similar scenario with Lafite '81 cost about $850, '82 cost over $2,100. My only warning is that the '81 wines will not be as long-lived as the 1982 or 1986 wines, which also got a lot of fancy press. Still, 1981 is a good value and is ready to be consumed now."  <p> Bruce Kaiser, Butterfield & Butterfield's, San Francisco: "1984,1985, 1986, and 1987 California vintages are all sought after, but for my money I would think about the 1989 vintage. It could be rated as a B or B-plus wine that you can buy at C prices. Think about this comparison: A case of Dunn Vineyards Howell Mountain Cabernet Sauvignon 1986 can sell for as much as $1,000 at auction, while a case of the 1989 can sell for under $550." <p> Serena Sutcliffe, Sotheby's London: "In general I feel that lunatic prices are being paid for a few things, but there are bargains out there, too. Vintages such as the 1988 red Bordeaux can be under valued. Few realize that the '88 vintage will have the longest life anywhere from 10 to 30 years. I feel 1978 red Bordeaux have been overlooked as well. They are lovely and ready to drink. Second wines from younger vines that have a faster maturation also have lower prices. An example is Chteau Margaux's second wine, Pavillion Rouge du Chteau Margaux. A case of it from 1982 is estimated at about $500 a steal."  <p> CONTEMPORARY INDIAN PAINTINGS <p>There is a classic formula to creating a new art market, little known to people outside the trade. It begins when an art dealer or collector "discovers," then buys up, an artist or genre that has been forgotten, neglected, or dismissed as trivial. Deep pockets are  not obligatory, for the work shouldn't be expensive. Over time this does take time and patience the collector/dealer accumulates a nice little stockpile, from which pieces are eventually dribbled out to other collectors in the key markets of London, Paris, and New York. Prices rise slightly, press is garnered, a glossy coffee-table book or serious monograph appears, and then, if all has gone well, the artwork reaches the secondary market the auction block where money is made.  <p> This is loosely how contemporary Indian painters like M.F. Husain, Anjolie Ela Menon, S.H. Raza, and F.N. Souza came to be introduced to international auction shoppers. During the past 30 years, Chester Herwitz, an American handbag manufacturer from Worcester, Massachusetts, and his wife, Davida, have amassed more than 3,000 paintings and works on paper by contemporary Indian artists. They began exhibiting them during the 1980s in the major markets, then offered a consignment of 219 selections to Sotheby's New York in an inaugural sale last June. The sale realized $1.2 million and established a record auction price for M.F. Husain, a member of the Progressive Artists Group formed in Bombay in 1948, a year after India won its independence. Both Christie's and Sotheby's plan sales for this year. Opinions differ as to the strength (and direction) of this market.  <p> Carlton Rochell, Sotheby's New York: "It is a good time to buy Indian contemporary art because in time it could out pace the traditional material everyone associates with Indian art, such as Mughal miniatures. In fact, that was how this market was tested. Sotheby's London would include several lots of contemporary Indian painting in traditional Indian art sales. After seeing that these lots had sold well, we realized work by living Indian artists could stand on its own."   <p> Michael Ludgrove, Christie's Australia: "It is dangerous to predict if the market will continue to grow; the prices realized were rather healthy. After all, there is not a great academic body of work about contemporary Indian painting, [although] the best works are not as [expensive] as comparative Western art." <p> COLORED DIAMONDS <p>Until the turn of the century, when the supply was exhausted, pink and blue diamonds were mined in India and collected by that country's princely rulers. Since then, the stones' rarity has kept all but the truly well-heeled (the Shah of Iran comes to mind) from even browsing in this market. The record for a colored diamond at auction is $9,902,500 for an emerald-cut, 20.17-carat blue stone sold at Sotheby's New York in October1994.   <p> Yellow diamonds are a dime a dozen compared to blues and pinks but are rarer than colorless diamonds. Unlike the blues and pinks, which are sold as individual stones, yellows are mounted in jewelry. For comparison, a rectangular-cut fancy intense 3.66-carat yellow diamond ring sold at Christie's New York in 1993 for $145,500.<p>Edward J. Landrigan, Landrigan Verdura, New York: "Thirty years ago when I started at Sotheby's, most people regarded colored diamonds as an oddity or a curio. Then I was thrilled if I sold a colored [blue] diamond for about $1,000 a carat. It seems that price records are constantly being broken at auction in Geneva and New York, and knowing that there are very few players in that strata, I wonder if Newton's law of gravity wouldn't apply if only a couple of them dropped out."  <p> Ronald Winston, Harry Winston, New York: "Colored diamonds are fully and consistently on the rise because of the enormous rarity of the stones."  <p> Bonnie Selfe, Cartier, New York: "I am not surprised by the increase in prices for colored diamonds, and I believe they will continue to rise. There is considerable demand for them from Asian buyers."  <p> EUROPEAN WORKS OF ART <p>Turn-of-the-century robber barons had a penchant for tapestries, bronzes, marbles, and the like, which encouraged a steady stream of works from Europe into the U.S. But taste has lightened up considerably since World War II, and though Medieval, Renaissance, and Baroque items may attract interest from museums looking toupgrade existing collections, there is currently a real paucity of high-end collectors. At a Sotheby's New York sale last year, several top bronzes from London dealer Cyril Humphris's inventory failed to sell. Lesser examples did better.   <p> Margaret Schwartz, Sotheby's New York: "Religious themes in art can be tricky, and 70 percent of what I sell is religious. Not everyone wants a Gothic Madonna. When you consider that a very good quality bronze with a secure attribution to a master or his workshop is available for $20,000, you realize the field is under appreciated compared to later sculpture or paintings." <p> Alice Duncan, Christie's New York: "Compared to old master pictures, Renaissance bronzes are terribly undervalued. I feel the loss of major dealers has had an effect on the market; they're not around to train collectors. It is a very good market for objects, whether bronze, marble, or terra cotta under $200,000. Under $50,000 there is also a good market; $15,000 to $50,000 enjoy a healthy market. The top end is tricky."  <p> Anthony Blumka, private dealer, New York: "I'm a fourth-generation works-of-art dealer whose family started in Vienna about 150 years ago. The flow of work has been from the U.S. back to Europe for some time now, and that makes sense [because] it is a European taste and sensibility, not necessarily an American one. Consider maiolica [tin-glazed earthenware produced in Italy during the Renaissance]. It's the one area in the field that sells for what it's worth, and most of it goes back to Italy."  <p> LATE 19TH-CENTURY AMERICAN FURNITURE <p>Post-1820 American furniture has yet to achieve the high prices or desirability of Philadelphia Chippendale and New York Federal, though it's not for lack of trying. Classical revival American furniture, made of mahogany or rosewood, was trumpeted as a promising category in the mid-1980s. (Long time collector Richard Jenrette of Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette has adorned his investment-banking firm's New York offices with classical revival pieces.) But as much as this category has been appreciated on a curatorial level for a number of years, passionate collectors are still few and far between.  <p> Interest is now moving toward the Herter Brothers, members of the Aesthetic movement who carried out high-style commissions for clients like E.H. Harriman and Jay Gould during the 1870s and 1880s. Some experts say that because Herter Brothers furniture had its first comprehensive museum catalogue and traveling museum show just last year, the market with a few notable exceptions has not caught up.  <p> Margaret Caldwell, private 19th-century decorative-arts dealer, New York: "Private collectors are intimidated by Herter furniture because of the pieces that came up at Butterfield & Butterfield's, one in 1988 and one last summer. Each sold for well over a quarter of a million dollars. If you were willing to do a lot of work as a serious collector, you could seek out examples by the Herter Brothers' exact contemporaries. Late 19th-century New York cabinet makers such as Alexander Roux, Leon Marcotte, and Pottier & Stymus are less known, but they produced some very good pieces. Still, I purchased a set of ten walnut dining chairs, possibly by Herter, just last fall at Sotheby's in New York, for less than $6,000. You couldn't pay less for a set of ten chairs unless you made them yourself with plywood."   <p> Margot Johnson, 19th-century American decorative-arts dealer, New York: "Prices for late 19th-century American masterpieces such as furniture from the Herter Brothers' commissions for Mark Hopkins in San Francisco and William H. Vanderbilt in New York have only begun to rise. Although I am shocked at how quickly prices have risen for the best Herter furniture, I believe that in time they will equal the prices of the best 18th-century American furniture." (Johnson purchased both a forementioned lots of Herter furniture at Butterfield's in 1988 and 1995.)   <p> Elaine Whitmire, Sotheby's New York: "Institutional interest in the field of late 19th-century Americana is substantial, but only at the top level. Many private American collectors associate Herter Brothers and their contemporaries with dark, ornate Victoriana, and that keeps them away and the prices down. A four-piece maple bedroom set from a known Pennsylvania commission by Herter Brothers sold for below the low estimate at Sotheby's last year when it fetched $12,650."  <p> 19th-CENTURY PHOTOGRAPHY <p>Just two years ago photography dealers were still encouraging collectors to look at 19th-century daguerreotypes and other early images as an under appreciated part of the popular collecting area of photography. But unique-image daguerreotypes (those made from a process that doesn't allow duplication) failed to attract more than a small group of collectors. Now that's changing: The former record price for a daguerreotype sold at auction was set at Swann Galleries, New York, in 1992 $63,800 for a Cincinnati street scene taken around 1851 by African-American photographer James Presley Ball. That record was broken last October when Sotheby's New York sold a circa 1846 daguerreotype of the U.S. Capitol building by John Plumbe Jr. for $189,500.   <p> Daniel Wolf, photography dealer, New York: "I have seen enormous growth in the 19th-century field with the prints of Felix Teynard, for instance, going from $500 to $35,000 for the rarest example of his work. Images from the last century proved to be the strongest category in the recent fall auctions, with all the good pieces selling. The same wasn't true if you looked at the 20th-century offerings. The one neglected area within the 19th-century market is American landscape photography. William Henry Jackson's work from the 1870s can be found for $4,000 to $7,000, and prints by Frederick Monsen and Carl Moon, from 1900 to 1920, are available for about $5,000."  <p> Denise Bethel, Sotheby's New York: "To be fair about the strong prices for daguerreotypes last fall, you should consider that not since the early 1970s had a comparable collection come up for sale. Still, anyone looking to get into 19th-century images should do it now. If prices continue to rise, 20th-century photography will be undervalued."  <p> JADE AND JADEITE JEWELRY <p>The strength of pan-asian economies has produced an array of new collectors in several categories of Asian art and art deco jewelry and this has encouraged international dealers and auction houses to expand existing operations and open new ones. Christie's and Sotheby's opened branches in Shanghai within days of each other in April 1994.  <p> Jade and jadeite jewelry, a thriving, complex market with great cultural significance for Asians, is a hot category. As  always, the best is in fashion: Christie's Hong Kong sold a 27-bead apple-green jadeite necklace, known as the Mdivani necklace, in October 1994 for $4.27 million. This was one of the most expensive items ever sold by an international auction house in Asia. The necklace had previously been sold in 1988 by Christie's Geneva for $2.2 million.   <p> Sam Bernstein, jade dealer, San Francisco: "Collectors should stay away from judging jade by size. You're not collecting rocks; you're collecting art. In spite of great demand for top pieces in Hong Kong, Taiwan, and mainland China, I feel jade is under valued by 20 percent to 30 percent when compared with Asian art in another medium, such as sculpture or porcelain. Where as a Shang dynasty bronze might cost $100,000, an equally rare and fine jade would probably sell for $20,000."  <p> Amanda Miller, Butterfield & Butterfield's, San Francisco: "Pure white or mutton fat' jadeite is very desirable right now in Hong Kong and the West, as is apple-green jadeite. While collectors always seek out purity and consistency of color, the color itself goes in and out of style. Up to 1994 prices were high for lavender jade; then collectors heard that white jade could be treated to take on a lilac coloring. They've stayed away since, keeping prices for lavender pieces down. Toughest to sell are small pieces called toggles buckles, pendants, miniature carvings. That's the most under valued area of the market. Two small circular19th-century white Nephrite plaques, about 2 inches in diameter, sold for a little over the low estimate, just over $600 for the pair." <p> Antonia Tozer, Spink & Son, Ltd., London: "Last year Spink's participated for the second time at the Tresors art fair in Singapore, and we'll be back this spring. Asians have a passion for jadeite jewelry. For about $15,000 a collector bought a good three-strand apple-green jadeite necklace last fall."  <p> Carlos A. Rosas writes on art and antiques for Antique Internationaland Town & Country.  <p> <p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
