	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Mortgage-Free: The Case Against Ownership</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Case Against Ownership</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> MORTGAGE-FREE: THE CASE AGAINST OWNERSHIP  <p> By Nick Ravo  <p> Jason Thomas, a 25-year-old computer consultant, always assumed he would buy a home when it came time to settle down and raise a family. That was before he actually began house hunting last year.  <p> "It's crazy,'' says Thomas. "I can get a nicer house for less money if I rent rather than buy. Then, if I invest my down payment, I can get 8 to 12 percent. I'm not going to get that kind of return on real estate these days.'' Thomas, who is also studying to be a chartered financial consultant, now lives with his wife and daughter on three acres in Glen Ellen, California, in a two-bedroom bungalow that rents for $800 a month.   <p> Renting has never been part of the American dream. Young couples and hard-working immigrants might rent with anxious dignity--until they could afford to buy. But otherwise, the popular perception of renting included images of creaky tenements with thin walls, dubious neighbors, and thugs for landlords.  <p> Ownership, on the other hand, implied solidity, probity, and solvency. Think of Ozzie and Harriet, Donna Reed, the Cleavers--the significant moments in the lives of these archetypal Americans took place "under their own roofs.'' The material anxieties and vulgar squabbles of the Kramdens were strictly for the struggling. <p> Over the past decade, though, the nation has begun to revise these cultural orthodoxies. Fear of layoffs, the falling realestate prices of the late 1980s and early 1990s, and rising concern about crime and the quality of public schooling have all made many Americans less willing to take on the long-term, often illiquid financial commitment of buying a house.  <p> "Renting makes it possible and affordable to live in a nicer neighborhood, and personally, I value that,'' says Jonathan Cohen, an investor-relations writer who lives in Palo Alto, California. "I place the schools and the general ambience of a top neighborhood above the extra financial gain I might--or nowadays might not--enjoy by owning a house in a poorer area.  <p> "I live next door to executives who make twice as much as I do," Cohen says. My wife and I enjoy that as a kind of revenge."  <p> Thomas and Cohen represent the future, even though 13,700 Americans buy homes every day and 63 million (64 percent of household heads) own them. Real estate also remains our primary source of personal wealth, with about $8.7 trillion invested in homes, roughly $5.6 trillion of which is homeowner equity--$500 billion more than individuals collectively invest in mutual funds, stocks, and bonds. But while home ownership rates are creeping upward to record levels as the overall population ages, they are falling for Americans under 35, despite interest rates and prices that, in many areas, have made houses more affordable today than at any time in the past 20 years.  <p> America's long romance with real estate is testimony, in part, to Madison Avenue's success in convincing us that social enfranchisement, security, and happiness can be found behind a white picket fence. But even more important have been the federal government's financial incentives. "The government wants you to buy a home, whether it makes sense for you economically or not," says Marc Eisenson,the publisher of The Pocket Change Investor, a newsletter based in Elizaville, New York, that offers advice on reducing personal debt. "It's good for America, as they say."   <p> The primary reason banks bother to make mortgages in most cases is that government-chartered agencies like Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac purchase the loans. Then there is the mortgage-interest deduction--amassive middle-class tax shelter, which, if eliminated in the name of tax reform, could push home prices down 15 percent. "We would expect homeownership to decline to perhaps around 50 percent,''says Kenneth T. Jackson, professor of history at Columbia University and author of Crabgrass Frontier: The Suburbanization of the United States.  <p> Why does the government--the Clinton administration recently declared its intention to encourage home ownership--want to make every American a burdened borrower? Well, real estate, like defense contracting, creates jobs--in construction, financial services, timber, consumer appliances, household furnishing, and a host of other industries. And since the Great Depression, when jobless armies tramped the roads, prompting fears that the civil order was crumbling, the government has recognized its interest in promoting social stability through home ownership, which helps to knit our diverse population into financially and emotionally rooted communities.  <p> This was not always a major policy consideration in Washington. Prior to 1945, banks often required a 30 or 40 percent down payment on mortgages and were reluctant to lend to any but their wealthiest borrowers. Only after World War II, with the government determined to find jobs and homes for millions of veterans, did it become common, even expected, for young couples to buy a home with 10 or 20 percent down and a bank loan. Such low-down-payment mortgages (paid for by G.I. Bill benefits) helped build Levittown, thenation's first planned suburban community, and innumerable similar developments. Donald L. Bartlett and James B. Steele note in their book America: What Went Wrong that in 1952, with "the opening of Levittown, Pennsylvania, the world's largest planned community, a symbol of the flourishing middle class ... it took a factory worker one day to earn enough money to pay the closing costs on a new Levittown house, then selling for $10,000."   <p> Houses were homes then--not investments. Anyone looking to make a killing bought stocks, which posted phenomenal gains during the Eisenhower era. Real estate had appreciated about 2.5 percent annually after inflation over the previous century--roughly the same as bonds, according to Karl E. Case, a Wellesley College economics professor and a principal in Case Shiller Weiss, a real estate research firm in Cambridge, Massachusetts--and the equity that accrued to home owners was likened to a savings account.  <p> Inflation changed all that. As late as the 1965, for example, a new four-bedroom colonial on one acre in a middle-class suburban development like Pleasant Hills, in Bel Air, Maryland, near Baltimore, cost $30,000. But as inflation began to accelerate, in step with the escalating Vietnam War, so did home prices. And following the Arab oil embargo of 1973-74, inflation soared for the next six years. Again, home prices followed suit.   <p> Even after inflation was stamped out by Federal Reserve chairman Paul Volcker in 1981, real estate speculation continued unabated, fueled by the demographic bulge of baby boomers buying first homes and by new tax laws that let developers, especially of condominiums, take real estate losses against other income.  <p> Thus, by the mid-1980s much of the nation (Texas and the oil-patch states being a notable exception) was experiencing full-blown real estate inflation, even though overall inflation had been tamed. "In 1985, in the Northeast, people thought the only thing dumber than not owning a house was not owning two,'' says Karl E. Case. "People were nuts. And when that happens, prices rise as part of a self-fulfilling prophecy."  <p> And why not? By the late 1980s, that home in Pleasant Hills was listed for $240,000, a $210,000 profit on a $30,000 investment made mostly with borrowed money. And the capital gains could be sheltered or deferred.  <p> The relationship between individual earnings and home ownership changed during this period. Modest homes became golden egglaying geese for those who bought early and unattainable luxuries for those who came later. As Bartlett and Steele note, by 1991 the $10,000 Levittown house cost $100,000 or more, and it took a factory worker 18 weeks to earn enough money to pay the closing costs.  <p> The bubble burst in the early 1990s. Prices fell substantially in many areas, a phenomenon unseen since the Great Depression. In Beverly Hills, the median home price fell about 30 percent from July 1990 to July 1994. Prices in some Boston suburbs fell as much as 50 percent.  <p> "In past recessions, like in 1981-82, prices were sticky; people just took their homes off the market for a while and waited out the downturn,'' Case says. "In 1990, though, the bad economy lasted a lot longer.'' The result was that many people sold at a loss, while others simply lost their homes.  <p> The market's fall also transformed yuppies and buppies intonebbies--negative equity baby boomers--whose mortgages often exceeded the value of their homes. This term was coined by ShermanWhipple, a demographer and market strategist in Hingham, Massachusetts. In 1991, Whipple surveyed 1,000 homeowners in southeastern New England with a median income of $70,000, 17 percent of whom were professionals or managers between the ages of 35 and 54. While12 percent of the survey sample had negative net worth--were "underwater," in mortgage-banker parlance--three quarters of the nebbies were from the apparently prosperous baby boomer group.  <p> In a 1993 study, Freddie Mac (the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation) found that 12 percent of the borrowers in its portfolio did not have enough equity in their homes to refinance. Generally, lenders will not allow a borrower to refinance and get a lower mortgage rate unless they have a loan-to-value ratio of no more than 80 percent, which means the outstanding home loan is no more than 80 percent of the home's assessed value.  <p> Jonathan E. Gray, a securities analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein, a Manhattan research and money-management firm, estimated that 5 percent of home owners have negative equity today. That's about 5 million households. The situation is perhaps two or three times worse in California, says Gray, and prices there continue to decline by 2 to 6 percent per year.  <p> "What we have are people who have cashed out of the American dream,'' Whipple says. "These are people who are spending or losing the equity in their homes. This equity is what they were supposed to use for their retirement or for the children's college education, and now it won't be there when they need it.''  <p> This financial debacle has led many potential home owners to cease assuming that, for financial and cultural reasons, they should buy. Instead, they are looking closely at costs to determine whether renting makes more sense--especially if they expect to move in a few years or they live in an area of falling or stagnant housing values.  <p> Ted C. Jones, chief economist with the Real Estate Resource Center at Texas A&M University in College Station, Texas, says that people who remain in a home long enough to hold a mortgage-burning party on a 30-year loan are rare. In fact, the average home owner stays put 11.8 years, according to the Chicago Title Co. The average household--renters and buyers--stays under the same roof for only about seven years.  <p> "The longer you are going to be in your house, the longer it is going to make sense to buy,'' Jones says. "But if you're going to be in your home three years or less, then definitely rent, unless you are living somewhere when prices are rising fast. <p> "Buying for three years and then selling just produces a lot of grief and expenses and the illusion of equity, in large part because you are mainly paying interest, and then you usually have to pay a 5 to 7 percent commission to sell,'' Jones says."That may also hold true for people who own a home for as long as five or even seven years, too, depending on appreciation."  <p> Homes can depreciate, too, as the nebbies discovered. Take a $200,000 house bought with 20 percent down. If it falls 20 percent in value over three years, the home will be worth $160,000--the same as the initial mortgage balance, which has been reduced little, if at all, by the first 36 mortgage payments. (Payments are almost all interest in the beginning.) In other words, 100 percent of the down payment is gone. Poof! Out the window--just like rent.  <p> Actually determining whether renting or buying is financially the best deal involves weighing numerous factors such as time in the home, maintenance expenses, fees, tax savings, potential investment gain on the down payment, appreciation, and the costs of renting a comparable house. "It's best left to a computer,'' says Steve Lyons, author of the book-software combination called HomeBuyer. The Real Estate Center at Texas A&M also sells software that will help crunch the numbers, as does Mitchell A. Levy, a financial analyst in Cupertino, California, and author of Home Ownership: The American Myth. (Levy's wares are available onthe Internet; send E-mail to mlevy@mythbreakers.com, or searchthe World Wide Web at http://www.mythbreakers.com.) "If you are going to buy a house, have the right reasons, emotionally or financially,'' Levy says. "Don't just jump on the band wagon because everyone else is doing it or because your family and friends say you have to.''  <p> Determining how much your home must appreciate for you to breakeven is probably the key part of the rent-buy calculation. For example, Levy's spreadsheet computed that if Jason Thomas bough this home for $250,000, using a $50,000 down payment and taking a mortgage for the remainder at 7.5 percent interest, the home must appreciate at 4.8 percent annually over seven years for Thomas to break even. If the home didn't appreciate, he would save $88,580 over seven years by investing the difference between his $1,440 mortgage payments (including the mortgage interest deduction) and his $800 monthly rent, and by investing the $50,000 down payment for an 8 percent average annual return.   <p> Even if Thomas's rent were $1,200 month, a comparable home would have to appreciate at 4.4 percent annually over three years, 3.2 percent over five years, or 2.7 percent over seven years to break even with renting. At $1,500 a month rent, buying looks like a better proposition, as the amount of appreciation needed falls to 2.8 percent over three years, 1.6 perent over five years, and 0.9 percent over seven years.  <p> Some investment professionals suggest gauging the overall return on investment (your down payment) to help calculate whether buying or renting is the best deal. They caution, though, that to offset the high returns made possible by leveraging, four percentage points must be deducted annually as compensation for risk, three percentage points for the lack of liquidity, and two percentage points for the work involved in managing the property. That means you need at least a 9 percent annual return on your down payment to start--or about a 2 percent annual appreciation on a house bought with a standard 20 percent down payment.  <p> "And don't forget to subtract 6 percent in sales commissions at the end when you sell the house,'' Levy says. "The minute you purchase your house, it's worth 94 percent of what you paid for it."  <p> And what about those tax benefits? The big ones (other than the rollover of a gain if the seller buys a more expensive house or is over 55) apply to mortgage-interest and property-tax deductions, and they are less substantial than most people realize, largely because the federal government already gives taxpayers a $6,550 standard deduction or $3,900 each when two single people buy a home. That means that the first $6,550 in mortgage interest (or $546 a month) they pay gives them no tax benefit, because they already have it whether they own a home or not.  <p> A couple in the 28 percent tax bracket, who pay $8,577 annually in mortgage interest and $2,500 in property taxes totaling $11,077, may think they are saving 28 percent of $11,077, or $3,102. Actually, their tax benefit will be 28 percent of $4,527 ($11,077 minus the $6,550 standard deduction). That amount is $1,267.56, or $105.63 a month.  <p> "That's 11 cents back for every buck they spend on interest and property taxes,'' said Eisenson. "What a deal.''  <p> Of course, for most people, the decision to buy a home has never been entirely, or even primarily, a financial one. Putting down roots, finding a place in a community, being seen as a mature, responsible person--these considerations often have equal or greater influence than money. The type of home we choose, its location, and the way we landscape and decorate it are approved, often admired, forms of giving public expression to an identity.  <p> Doubtless this is still the case, but what has changed is that renting, too, is becoming for many a route to self-definition. People are rethinking the premises of ownership. Does owning a home really help create or enhance success and security? Certainly, it's hard to make that argument if your neighborhood is full of laid-off aerospace workers or people whose homes are worthless than they paid for them. Moreover, if, in the 1950s, the suburbs were regarded as utopian havens from the city, that is no longer the case. From drugs to pollution, urban ills are now also suburban ones.  <p> "We decided to rent, and it was a lifestyle rather than a strictly economic decision,'' says Jonathan Cohen, who owned a home in Santa Cruz, California, before deciding to rent a two-bedroom cottage for $1,490 a month in Palo Alto. "We gained tremendous flexibility in being able to relocate when and if necessary. I feel more secure knowing I can move on short notice, particularly with all the layoffs going on.''  <p> This view is likely to spread in an era of service-sector McJobs, serial careers, and diminished material expectations. The baby boomers, now ages to 32 to 49, bought their homes in one huge wave from about 1970 to 1987, pushing up prices in a classic short-supply/high-demand economic equation. But who will buy those dwellings when boomers start to retire in a decade?  <p> Don't count on the baby boom let--anyone under 16 or so today--or the so-called Generation Xers. These kids may be ready to buy houses when their parents are ready to sell, but if real income remains flat or continues to decline, then they won't be able to afford them.  <p> "It's becoming more and more difficult for young people to take their place in the American dream,'' says Katherine Newman, a Columbia University professor of anthropology and the author of Declining Fortunes: The Withering of the American Dream. "Much more difficult than for the generation that came of age after World War II. A home today requires two-income households, long commutes, sometimes families deciding to have fewer kids and more day care. The American dream of the future will be simply holding on to a job, and that's becoming harder and harder forAmericans, and it will have a powerful effect on housing markets.'' <p> As a character in Douglas Coupland's novel, Generation X: Tales for an Accelerated Culture, says, "When someone tells you they've just bought a house, they might as well tell you they no longer have a personality. You can immediately assume so many things; that they're locked into jobs they hate; that they're broke; they they spend every night watching videos...."  <p> Nick Ravo is a reporter with The New York Times. He can be reached at nickravo@nytimes.com.  <p>  <p>TO BUY OR RENT, THAT IS THE QUESTION  <p> Intelligently deciding whether to buy or rent entails a number of variables--and every individual's situation is unique. There are, however, a few key considerations. These tips are based on Home Buyer: The Book & Software Home Buying Kit by Steven A. Lyons (Stratosphere Publishing, 1995).  <p> * Because of its exponential effect on a home's value, appreciation has the most dramatic impact on profit and loss. Estimate future appreciation in the area you plan to buy by its performance over no less than the past 12 years. Don't be dissuaded or unduly encouraged by sharp price dips or increases in just the past few years.  <p> * If home prices in your area are near the nationwide median of about $110,000, then there is room for substantial future price increases. If prices considerably exceed the median, as in California and Hawaii and parts of the Northeast, they maybe hitting a ceiling.  <p> * If appreciation averages 3 percent annually over the next12 years, then the typical home buyer, purchasing a $110,000 home, will fare slightly better than the typical renter paying the national median rent of $450.  <p> * Don't fixate on tax savings. Homeowners can benefit from huge tax write-offs, particularly after selling, but if appreciation is zero, you probably are better off renting.  <p> * How well a renter invests a down payment and the difference between the monthly mortgage payment and the rent are important. A renter who parks the down payment in the bank will have difficulty coming out ahead of a home buyer, as will the renter who fritters away the monthly differential. Astute investors, however, canerase any advantages home buying may offer.  <p> * Homeowners do not have access to their down payment. The renter, however, does, and can use it, whether to act on an investment tip or to take a cruise around the world.  <p> * Nonfinancial issues may be as important as financial ones. Renters may not want to physically maintain a house. Or they may want to live in a school district where they can't afford to buy. Conversely, the security of owning may outweigh its potential financial disadvantages.  <p> * Remember that homeowning is riskier and more constraining than renting. If real estate values drop or if a fire devastates your rented home, you can simply walk away. But an owner may never completely recover from such a blow. Conversely, homeowners can't be forced to vacate at the end of a lease.  <p> * While you may improve your home by painting it, adding a built-in book case, or landscaping, as a renter you never own or profit from the results of your hard work.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Homeowers, Real Estate, Mortgages

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
