	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>1 Rm W/Ocean Vu to Rent Cheap</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-1 Rm W/Ocean Vu to Rent Cheap</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995   <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> 1 RM W/OCEAN VU TO RENT CHEAP  <p> By Rudy Maxa  <p> Once upon a time, there were two basic hotel-room rates: the general or "rack" rate and the package rate. Today, the lodging industry is a consumer crapshoot <p>Your best deal may be to book through a relatively new group of wholesalers called hotel consolidators, who buy large numbers of hotel-room nights and pass the savings along to last-minute customers. Whether you are in San Francisco, Washington, London, or Paris, consolidators can save you a lot of money. And when a particular hotel or every hotel in an entire city here or abroad is sold out, a consolidator may be your best shot at a bed for the night.  <p> Consolidators require nothing more than a credit card number; most use it to guarantee your reservation, and you pay the hotel. Cancellation policies vary, but most require a 24-hour notice. <p> Here are some representative savings: <p>Hotel Reservations Network (800-964-6835) offered a room at the elegant Rihga Royal in Manhattan for $237 a night, including the 13.25 percent hotel tax (all prices and availability areas of July 1995). When the hotel was called directly for a weeknight room, the rate quoted was $295, before tax. The consolidator's rate amounted to a savings of about $100 a night.  <p> The Essex House overlooking Central Park said its lowest rate, a national corporate rate for a double with no view, was $243, excluding tax. HRN offered a tax-inclusive rate of $189, saving almost $91 per night. And while the recently renovated Drake Swissotel on Park Avenue said over the phone that its cheapest weeknight rate was $224, not including tax, HRN offered a tax-inclusive rate of $160 nearly $100 per night less.  <p> In Beverly Hills, California, the Summit Hotel on Rodeo Drive offered a "special promotional rate of $150 a night," excluding hotel taxes of 14 percent.  HRN charged $113, including tax, for a room on the same night about $60 less.  <p> HRN, based in Dallas, lists rooms in most major U.S. cities, as well as some in Europe, including London and Paris. HRN is open Monday through Friday, including most holidays, from 8 a.m.to 6 p.m. Central time.  <p> The catalog of properties from New Yorkbased RMC Travel Centre (800-782-2674) includes hotels in all major U.S. and Canadian cities (except Honolulu). Rates for the Essex House and the Drake were identical to those offered through HRN. An oceanview room at the trendy Shutters on the Beach in Santa Monica, California, cost $275 a night, but $400 before tax if you had reserved through the hotel. RMC is open for business Monday through Friday from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. Eastern time.  <p> Among other consolidators, Quikbook (800-789-9887), which calls itself "America's Number One Hotel Discounter," advertises discounts of up to 70 percent in 21 U.S. cities. Room Exchange (800-846-7000) promises discounts in all major U.S. cities, the Caribbean, Mexico,and Hawaii. You prepay for your room and receive a voucher which is fully refundable if you cancel 48 hours before arrival. The company also has started listing European and Asian properties, such as London's Dorchester ($285 plus a 17.5 percent tax, or about $80 below the regular rate) and Hong Kong's deluxe Peninsula (starting at $259, about $100 less than the hotel rate).  <p> There are also regional specialists, such as Central Reservation Service (800-548-3311), which offers reservations in Miami, Orlando, Tampa, and New Orleans as well as for some New York and Los Angeles properties. California Hotel Reservations (800-576-0003) specializes, naturally enough, in California and recently added Portland, Oregon, and Seattle to its portfolio. Atlanta-based Hotels Plus (800-235-0909) specializes in discount hotels in England and mainland Europe, as well as the Middle East and South Africa. <p> As in any bargain hunting, shopping around pays off. And just because one consolidator has nothing available on the date you want doesn't mean another won't.   <p>     <p> Travel Tips  <p> Calling a hotel directly for a room is often (but not always) better than calling a central reservations number, because locals respond to day-to-day business conditions. For example, when I called a reservation clerk at Ma Maison Sofitel in Los Angeles, she said that, since business was slow that day, she'd extend the weekend rate of $129 before taxes, $30 less than the normal weekday rate. (Hotel Reservations Network offered a tax-inclusiverate of $148.) <p>Hotels will often give you a corporate rate even if you don'twork for a corporation, so always request it (unless there's a lower rate). Also, watch for advertised specials, such as Hilton's1995 summer rates for its foreign hotels, which undercut the consolidator prices. <p>In the United States, hotels of ten equal or undercut consolidators' rates on weekend stays.  R.M.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
