<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Boot Up Your Financial Advisor</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Boot Up Your Financial Advisor</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Boot Up Your Financial Advisor</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>BOOT UP YOUR FINANCIAL ADVISOR<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Till now, personal financial software has offered little more than bookkeeping. For example, <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a>'s Quicken, with 8 million users the most popular application software ever sold at retail, keeps records on mutual funds and balances your checkbook. The product has an extremely loyal following, but there has always been some question whether such programs are really worth the data-entry work they entail.<p>"People who use checkbook programs like Quicken for household expenses are detail freaks--they'll write a check at the grocery store and then go home and rebalance their checkbooks again on a computer," says Dave McClure, who advises CPAs on accounting software.<p>Among programs that take on more complex tasks, Andrew Tobias's Managing Your Money (from MECA Software) has long been a top-rated best-seller. It too can balance a checkbook, but it also assists in financial planning, helping to calculate how much must be saved monthly to pay for a child's college education or how large a mortgage a home buyer can handle. What Managing Your Money can't do is generate an overall financial plan from the answers it provides to various personal finance questions put to it by the user.<p>Intuit has now jumped into that gap with Quicken Financial Planner, a major advance in personal-finance software. While this program won't replace the judgment and flexibility of a skilled financial advisor, it is a true financial-planning tool.<p>It's also extremely easy to operate. Users enter data about income and expenses, loans and assets, and projected retirement savings in ten stages, each involving a series of questions. Assistance can be called up by clicking on the help icon, and the well-known financial journalist Jane Bryant Quinn offers still more detail on topics such as investing, borrowing, and credit card debt.<p>The program uses your answers to create reports on your income, expenses, cash flow, investment portfolio, and net worth. QFP demonstrates in detail where you will be spending your money, how your investment portfolio will grow, and what your estate will be worth. <p>QFP also lets you, in a sense, enter your future into the projections. If your spouse plans to quit working from 2001 to 2005, you can see how it will affect cash flows and retirement savings year by year. Similarly, if you expect your children to attend college from 2008 to 2014, you can assess the impact on your budget. Using the program's "special expense" calculator, you can also plan to buy, say, a new bedroom set in 2000 or pay for a bar mitzvah in 2006.<p>The program does have some limitations. "If you could love and hate something at the same time, this is it," says David Drucker, a financial planner at Malgoire Drucker in Bethesda, Maryland, who examined the program at our request.<p>"It's about as smart as a bad financial planner," says Drucker. Someone who didn't know a 401(k) from a profit-sharing plan and who relied on QFP to run his or her financial life could be in for trouble.<p>"My clients often put the wrong numbers in the wrong boxes when filling out a questionnaire for me," says Drucker. "And if they do it with these software packages, they'll get wrong answers."<p>The program can occasionally become confusing, as in the section requesting data on employer contributions to 401(k) and other tax-deferred retirement plans. Quicken says that the software will be updated annually to keep up with tax-law changes and in response to user comments.<p>Another problem is that the program doesn't address every possible financial situation. For instance, federal laws give retirees a choice about how to take distributions from an IRA or pension plan, which can affect tax liability and cash flow. QFP uses what's known as the "term-certain method" of distributing those assets, but many retirees are better off using a "recalculation method" to take retirement distributions. The program, however, doesn't offer this option.<p>"A 65-year-old who uses this package could do himself a disservice," says Drucker. Intuit concedes that the program doesn't focus on retirees and was developed with an eye toward providing easy financial planning for baby boomers.<p>One last criticism is that the software can't be creative on your behalf. In my case, the program withdrew $56,000 from my wife's tax-deferred retirement fund in 2011 and another $31,000 in 2012 to pay for our kids' college tuition. But by then I'll be just three years away from retirement, and instead of paying a 20 percent penalty on withdrawals from the retirement fund, we'd be much better off borrowing money from my 401(k) plan, paying the interest on the loan (which is much lower than the penalty), and repaying the loan when I hit 59 and a half and can make withdrawals penalty free. <p>These are relatively minor criticisms. QFP brings us a long step closer to the day when we'll all be our own best financial planners. At a suggested retail price of $39.95, this program is a great investment. QFP requires Windows 3.1, 4 MB of RAM, and 16 MB of available hard-disk space. The CD-ROM version requires at least a 486-based PC with a sound card and speakers, running Windows 3.1 with 8 MB of RAM and 16 MB of available hard-disk space.<p>With the release of QFP, Quicken has simultaneously published the Parents' Guide to Money CD-ROM (requires Windows 3.1, 4 MB of RAM, 3 MB of available hard-disk space, and a 16-byte sound card and speakers; retail price, $29.95), a "fast and easy" way for parents and those expecting to become parents to "take control of the financial challenges of parenting."<p>Guide is a much less ambitious tool than QFP. It isn't powerful enough to generate budget projections of special expenses--summer camp, the cost of a new bedroom set--or the changes in college savings schedules required by, say, one spouse quitting work to remain home with the kids for five years.<p>Basically a talking book, Guide features video clips of parents and financial advisors talking about child care, life and health insurance, and college costs. The financial-planning portion of the product consists of ten worksheets on which users inscribe their monthly budgets, insurance policies, and child care costs.<p>Some limitations notwithstanding (it lacks a serious retirement planning aid, for example), Guide can be of real help to people who want to identify and quantify the fundamental fiscal impact of having children. It will be particularly useful for young couples just starting out.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Family Finance, Retirement Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

