<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Poor Man's Arbitrage</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Poor Man's Arbitrage</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Poor Man's Arbitrage</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> THE POOR MAN'S ARBITRAGE  <p> By Nick Ravo  <p> Arbitrage: the elegant french word conjures images of sleuths snooping around for inside stock information. The reality, however, is legal and not terribly romantic.  <p> There are two kinds of arbitrage: pure and risk. Pure arbitrage is a game for those with the money and technology to execute huge, lightning-fast international trades. It entails purchasing something a stock, currency, or commodity in one market and immediately reselling it in another to profit from a price discrepancy. Anarbitrageur might buy silver contracts in London and instantly short the same kind of contracts selling at a higher price in New York. The profits are razor thin, but if the operation is repeated frequently, with millions of dollars of capital invested each time, annual returns can be sizable.  <p> Risk arbitrageurs do things differently. Typically, they buy big blocks of stock (or options) in a company targeted for takeover. Because the company's stock usually trades slightly lower than the takeover offer, arbs pocket the difference if a deal goes through. They lose a bundle if it doesn't.  <p> For instance, on April 27 the Justice Department said it would oppose the proposed merger of <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> and <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a> on antitrust grounds. On that day Intuit was  trading at around 83, Microsoft at around 79. Last October, Microsoft had offered 1.34 of its shares for each Intuit share (or about $106 a share). The arbs who bought Intuit at 83 expected a postmerger profit of about $23 per share. But after the Justice Department revealed its opposition, Intuit plummeted to 68. If the deal falls through,the price could fall to around 40, where Intuit was trading before the merger was agreed upon.  <p> Arbs often bet on possible takeovers, not just announced deals, making educated guesses based on networking with other investing pros, monitoring consolidation in a particular industry, and searching the financial press for rumors of merger activity.There is also a mutual fund that invests solely in risk arbitrage: the <a name="FUND:MERFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MERFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merger Fund</b></a>, run by Westchester Capital Management of Valhalla, New York (see Fund Profile, June).  <p> Another way to arbitrage individual stocks is SIP arbitrage. This technique involves buying and immediately selling stocks offered at a discount in shareholder investment plans by a small number of companies. SIPs are usually part of a dividend reinvestment plan, or DRIP. "It's poor man's arbitrage," says Charles B. Carlson,vice president of Dow Theory Forecasts in Hammond, Indiana, which publishes DRIP Investor, a newsletter on discount stock programs."Any reasonably sophisticated small investor can do it."  <p> Seventeen companies provide discounts of 2 to 5 percent on cash purchases of restricted amounts of stock made through their SIPs and DRIPs. National City Corp., a bank in Cleveland, restricts cash purchases of discounted stock to $500 a month. United Mobile Homes, a real estate investment trust in Eatontown, New Jersey, allows purchases of as much as $40,000 a quarter. (Directories of DRIPs and SIPs with descriptions of how each operate are available from Standard & Poor's at 800-221-5277 or Dow Theory Forecasts at 219-931-6480.)  <p> To make an optional cash purchase in a SIP or DRIP offering discount stock, you must be a shareholder of record in the company, meaning you must own at least one share of stock in your own name (some companies require five or ten shares). Through a deep-discount broker, have the share transferred from the brokerage's name known as the street name into your name and mailed to you. You may also be able to buy one share through The Moneypaper (800-388-9993), First Share (800-683-0743), or the National Association of Investors Corp. (810-583-6242, ext. 22).  <p> Once you are enrolled in the SIP, mail a check to the company to buy its discounted shares. On the stock purchase date listed in the prospectus, call the company to find how many shares you bought at what price, then call your broker and sell short (that is, sell with the promise to buy back) the same number of shares on the same day.  <p> When the discounted shares arrive in the mail, put them in your brokerage account and cover your short position. You have now locked in the discount as profit, minus taxes and commissions.  <p> Suppose your brokerage account contains $4,500. You enroll in United Water Resources' DRIP, write a check to the company for $3,000, and ask the company to mail you the stock. This would buy 234 shares at 12.83, based on the May 8 price of 13.5 less a 5 percent discount. On the same day you short 234 shares at13.5 and collect $3,159. (You probably need at least $1,600 in your margin brokerage account to short this much stock.)  <p> When the shares arrive, use them to cover the short sale. You keep $3,159 from the short sale $159 more than you paid United Water Resources. Do this once a quarter and annual earnings will surpass $600, about 20 percent, on your $3,000. Those with deep pockets can earn more, investing in several stocks and through several accounts.  <p> Unfortunately, this route to easy money has been exploited so frequently by small investors and limited investment partnerships that specialize in arbitraging discounted stock that the number of firms offering discounts has declined for several years. However, new SIPs may pop up, Carlson says, when the strong market falters. He adds that the recent increase in popularity of DRIPs could soon raise the number of plans that also offer discounts.  <p> Not everyone approves of SIP arbitrage. "People who do this are defying the purpose of the plans, which are set up for employees, customers, and long-term investors to create a loyal base of shareholders," says Vita Nelson, editor of The Moneypaper. Companies now often limit how frequently shareholders can sell discounted stock. Other firms, such as American Water Works, may boot frequent sellers from plans.  <p> Also, many discount stocks, such as United Mobile Homes, are thinly traded. Shorting them or even selling them in a large block can be difficult or impossible. "We had two physics Ph.D.s recently who opened up a few accounts and tried this, and they found out how hard it is to sell a lot of shares at one time," says Eugene W. Landy, chairman of United Mobile Homes.  <p> The biggest barrier to pure arbitrage profits is that many companies now calculate the discounted price based on a daily high-low average over 10 to 12 days rather than just on the day of the purchase. That makes the phone call to verify purchase price all the more crucial. In the best-case scenario, the discount could increase because of the ups and downs in the pricing period. In the worst case, the pricing period could make the stock even more expensive than the market price the only real risk involved in this form of arbitrage.    <p> Nick Ravo is a reporter for The New York Times. He can be reachedby E-mail at nravo@aol.com.  <p> COMPANIES TO SIP FROM <p>*<a name="NYSE:AWK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10104"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> American Water Works </b></a> <p>5% discount, $5,000 per month maximum (609-346-8200)  <p> * <a name="NASD:BGAS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12766"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Berkshire Gas </b></a> <p>3% discount, $3,000 per quarter maximum (413-442-1511)  <p> * <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan </b></a> <p>3% discount, $2,000 per month maximum (212-552-1143)  <p> * <a name="NYSE:ETW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13251"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>E'Town </b></a> <p>5% discount, $2,000 per month maximum (908-654-1234)  <p> * <a name="NASD:FTCG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13405"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First Colonial Group</b></a>  <p>5% discount, $1,000 per quarter maximum (610-746-7300)  <p> * <a name="NYSE:FTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10578"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First Union </b></a><p>3% discount, $10,000 per quarter maximum (704-374-6782)  <p> * <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors </b></a><p>3% discount, $2,500 per month maximum, or 25 cents for every GM share you own up to a maximum of $25,000 per month (800-331-9922)  <p> * <a name="NYSE:HCN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12009"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Health Care REIT </b></a><p>4% discount, $5,000 per quarter maximum (419-247-2800)  <p> * <a name="NASD:MNRTA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14159"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Monmouth REIT</b></a> <p>5% discount, $40,000 per quarter maximum (908-542-4927)  <p> *<a name="NYSE:NCC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11048"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> National City </b></a><p>3% discount, $500 per month maximum (800-622-6757)  <p> * <a name="NASD:OLDB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14319"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Old National Bancorp</b></a> <p>2.5% discount, $3,500 per quarter maximum (812-464-1296)  <p>*<a name="AMEX:PMC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12262"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> PMC Capital </b></a><p>2% discount, $10,000 per month maximum (305-966-8868)  <p> * <a name="NYSE:RMR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11247"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Resource Mortgage Capital</b></a>  <p>3% discount if stock is above $16 and company is issuing shares, $30,000 per quarter maximum (804-967-5840)  <p> * <a name="NYSE:SUB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11523"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Summit Bancorporation</b></a>  <p>3.5% discount, $5,000 per month maximum (201-701-2666)  <p> * <a name="AMEX:UMH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11505"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Mobile Homes</b></a>  <p>5% discount, $40,000 per quarter maximum (908-389-3890)  <p> * <a name="NYSE:UWR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11561"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Water Resources</b></a> <p>5% discount, $3,000 per quarter maximum (201-767-2811)  <p> *<a name="NASD:WBAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15154"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> Westport Bancorp</b></a><p>5% discount, $3,000 per quarter maximum (203-222-6911)  <p> Source: Dow Theory Forecasts  
