		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Dialing Deals</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Dialing Deals</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> DIALING DEALS  <p> By Kathleen Murray  <p> The rate skirmish among long-distance phone carriers is beginning to look like the Hundred Years War. <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:FON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11560"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sprint</b></a> collectively spend more than $1 billion a year trying to steal each other's callers with promises of big savings. But all that advertising money disguises very small distinctions. The competing discount plans offer "savings [that] really are comparable," says Charles Bain, a researcher at Washington, D.C. based Telecommunications Research & Action Center, a public interest group that tracks long-distance rates.  <p> Since the beginning of the year, the Big Three have each marketed new, less expensive calling plans. AT&T's True Savings will cut 25 percent from its standard rates if you make at least $10 worth of long-distance calls in a month, 30 percent if your bill is over $50. MCI's New Friends and Family discounts MCI's standard rates by 25 percent once monthly charges hit $10, 50 percent for calls to other MCI users specified on the Friends and Family list customers give to the company. Sprint Sense, eschewing discounts, has gone to a flat-rate plan, charging customers 10 cents a minute for night and weekend calls and 22 cents a minute for daytime calls.  <p> The resulting phone-bill differentials are minimal. A recent TRAC survey shows that for 50 long-distance calls a month, mostly made at nights and on weekends and totaling about 522 minutes, MCI will bill $52.72, Sprint $57.33, and AT&T $58.24. The discount plan offered by a rapidly growing new phone company, LDDS, based in Jackson, Mississippi, is comparable.  <p> Naturally, the carriers insist these savings are a big deal. "Even if it's only $3 [a month], that still adds up," says Chris Mannella, MCI's director of brand marketing. "We've still got the lowest rates out there."  <p> That may be, but standard rates are going up at all the major phone companies, even as they steadily drop in the various savings-plan rates. This is a crucial distinction, because carriers do not automatically give current users their lowest rates. In fact, Recent studies by PNR and the Yankee Group, two consumer-research companies, show that two thirds of long-distance users may still pay standard rates.  <p> According to TRAC, there's also little difference in the voice quality of the major services. So why take the time to switch? Ken McEldowney, executive director of Consumer Action, a consumer-advocacy group in San Francisco, says because of the intensifying competition, now is a good time to evaluate your long-distance service, if you haven't done so in the last six months. A heavy user one who spends $150 a month could save more than $500 a year over the standard rate.  <p> AT&T commands 60 percent of the market and charges the highest standard rate. A person billed at that rate who paid $63.15 monthly for long-distance service could reduce that to $44.20 by switching to AT&T's True Savings plan. To get the best deal, start by asking carriers specifically for discount-plan rates. Once you have the competing plans, look at your own calling pattern. "No one plan or company is best for everyone," McEldowney says. MCI's New Friends and Family plan, for example, is often cited as the low-cost leader. But that assumes you're calling other MCI customers that you've listed as regular contacts.  <p> If you make a lot of calls during the day, a plan like Sprint's Most II, which offers volume discounts of up to 35 percent, may cost less than the Sprint Sense flat-rate plan. Flat rates, including LCI All America and LDDS Home Advantage, may be cheaper if your call volume is light or if your calls are coast-to-coast.  <p> Alternatively, if you travel abroad frequently, you might find AT&T worth the slightly higher cost. American travelers often report that AT&T makes it easiest to dial the U.S. direct from overseas as well as get access to American operators.  <p> McEldowney recommends looking at bills for at least three months to determine your calling pattern. For the most recent TRAC study of rates, services, and features, send a stamped, self-addressed, business-sized envelope and $3 to TRAC, P.O. Box 12038, Washington, D.C. 20005.   <p> Currently, all carriers face intense rate pressure as the Baby Bells and even cable companies get set to offer long-distance service. So, once you've found the right plan, relax until the next round of discounts.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
