	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> ADVISOR BRIEFS  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> FOREWARNED IS FOREARMED <p>As municipalities increasingly weather financial storms, municipal bondholders may be concerned about the health of their investments. Securities and Exchange Commission rule 15C-2-12, which takes effect in July, mandates that all municipalities give underwriters ongoing financial information on their bond issues and their own fiscal health. You can now retrieve this information with a phone call to 1-800-BOND-INFO, which provides access to up-to-the-minute price information and credit ratings for more than 650,000 municipal bonds. J.J. Kenny, a New York bond-evaluation firm, began a three-month trial of the service on May 15. Other partners in the venture are the Public Securities Association and Standard & Poor's. <p> Callers must have the name of the bond's issuer, issue date, maturity, and coupon rate. Hours are 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. (eastern time) Monday through Friday, and the cost is $9.95 for 25 prices, payable with a credit card.  <p> MOVING MADE SIMPLE <p>Moving from one home to another is among most people's least favorite activities. MovePower, a Southport, Connecticut, relocation company, says it can make this trial a little less stressful. For $79.95, MovePower steers people to discounts on mortgage processing fees, up to a 45 percent discount on van-line and insurance costs, and up to $1,500 cash back on real estate commissions (the company does collect a referral fee).  <p> If you're selling a home, MovePower will also compile comparative sales data for houses in your neighborhood and attempt to find the most energetic brokers by getting the total dollar volume of homes they have sold, how quickly they sold them, and how close they came to the original asking price. For more information, call 800-692-3786. <p>  <p>LEAVE HOME WITHOUT IT <p>There are almost 200,000 Cirrus- and Plus-affiliated automatic teller machines in the United States, but your ATM card can also get you cash in Europe and elsewhere. Nearly 200,000 Cirrus and Plus ATMs dot the globe outside the U.S., and the number is rapidly growing. Most European bank machines offer a preferred exchange rate comparable to the wholesale rates banks charge each other, saving customers some 3 to 5 percent per transaction.   <p> The standard PIN code outside the country is four digits, so if your code has more than that, ask whether the first four digits will work. If not, change your code before departing. Cirrus and Plus offer toll-free numbers for ATM locations, but keep in mind that the machines are scarce or nonexistent in some places, among them Denmark and Switzerland for Cirrus.  <p> COMPUTER MAP YOUR VACATION <p>Planning a road trip this summer? Let Rand McNally's Trip Maker software map the fastest or most intriguing route. Type in your starting point and destination, and the program quickly gives you a suggested route, the estimated driving time, and suggested overnight stops. The program also tells you when and where to pick up each road, lists the attractions along the way, and lets you choose the quickest, shortest, or most scenic way to travel. Cost: $79.95, in Windows and CD-ROM formats. To order a copy, call 800-284-6565.  <p> UP, UP, AND TAXED AWAY <p>If you plan on using frequent-flier miles to travel to a vacation spot this summer, remember that if the flights on which miles were earned were paid for by your employer, the IRS will consider this use as taxable income. While no court has ruled on the taxation of frequent-flier miles and the IRS says it has no guidelines for auditing them, travelers should still beware. Some taxpayers have been audited and slapped with a tax bill.  <p> To protect yourself, travel-tax expert Richard Meyer of Highland Park, Illinois, says you should telephone the airline you are flying, ask for its lowest fare for your flight, and keep a record of it. Or cut out an advertisement in the newspaper showing a lower rate. If you are audited, this information will preventthe IRS from randomly assigning a higher value to your flight.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Banking Industry, Travel Industry, Bond Investing, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
