	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> ADVISOR BRIEFS  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald and William P. Barrett  <p> Cheaper Mortgages <p>A computer system just introduced by Freddie Mac may save 20 to 50 percent on mortgage closing costs. The government-sponsored mortgage corporation says the Loan Prospector can complete a remote home appraisal in less than 72 hours, versus two weeks for the traditional on-site version. The system decides which homes qualify for expedited appraisal by comparing them with historical data on similar properties (the system has 4.6 million property transactions in its database). If a home meets the Prospector's criteria, in some cases the bank appraiser can dispense with an interior inspection.  <p> Thus far, Citicorp Mortgage, PHH US Mortgage of Mount Laurel, New Jersey, and Countrywide Credit of Pasadena, California, have signed on to use the system.   <p>  <p>Fore! <p>Here's an interesting real estate investment trust twist: National Golf Properties, a REIT based in Santa Monica, California, owns 74 golf courses in 23 states and Britain and intends to acquire15 more over the next 12 months. Morgan Stanley, which along with Smith Barney underwrote the company's 9.7 million-share offering at $20.38 per share back in 1993, forecasts the acquisition binge will boost the share price from a recent $19.75 on the New York Stock Exchange to $23 by next April. The REIT, whose ticker symbol is TEE, posted a recent dividend yield of 8 percent.  <p>  <p>Deposit Uninsurance <p>Look around the one office of Home Savings & Loan Association of Oklahoma City and you'll notice a lot of signs saying "Deposits not insured by any government agency." The little S&L, with $8 million in deposits, dropped its Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. coverage last year. In return, savers get higher deposit rates. Home Savings offers nationwide money-market rates at 6.7 percent, compared with, say, 3.75 percent at New York's Citibank. A four-year certificate of deposit throws off 7.5 percent, a good 1 percent above the recent national average. The FDIC says eight financial institutions have voluntarily given up deposit insurance since1984. Before you consider putting your money in an uninsured S&L, ask to receive financial statements, Home Savings cranksout two a year and watch the ratio of deposits to loans, called the equity-to-assets ratio. If the ratio is below 5 percent, yank the account even if you have to pay several months' CD interest penalty.   <p>  <p>Investors@stocks.com <p>National Discount Brokers, in conjunction with Portfolio AccountingWorld-Wide (PAWWS), recently introduced a stock-trading programon the World Wide Web. Investors who log on to NDB Online can buy and sell stocks and get stock quotes. Investors can also receive free use of PAWWS' portfolio accounting system, worth $8.95 per month. Trades are confirmed via E-mail, phone, or fax. The brokerage demands a hefty $5,000 cash or security deposit in an account before trading may begin. It charges a flat $20 fee for Nasdaq and OTC trades and $25 for listed trades of up to 5,000 shares. NDB Online says it will provide a high level of security for its customers by using a <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape</b></a> server with RSA encryption. The National Association of Securities Dealers reports no complaints against the company, but if an investor is dissatisfied, the transaction fee will be refunded. NDB Online's address is at:http://pawws.sccapl.com.  <p>  <p>Leave the flying to heirs <p>Each year deceased frequent fliers take an estimated $60 million worth of miles with them. But according to Frequent Flyer magazine in Secaucus, New Jersey, some major airlines will let you bequeath those miles to your heirs. While it is against their official policy, United, <a name="NYSE:U"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11527"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>USAir</b></a>, and America West will give good customers this last privilege. Donald Witte, director of marketing services at USAir, says the airline will transfer the miles to an existing frequent-flier mileage account or set up a new one, so long as it receives a letter of request, preferably from the executor of the deceased's estate.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning, Banking Industry, Travel Industry, Mortgages, Technology Industry, Government Adgencies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
