<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Why We Buy</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Why We Buy</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Why We Buy</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Features<p>WHY WE BUY
The Silent persuasion of boxes, bottles, cans and tubes.<p>By Thomas Hine<p>The packaging industry claims a piece of just about every business. More important, it claims a piece of every consciousness. 
At any given moment, whether you're in your house, on the street, or where you work, it's likely that at least one package is within your field of vision. Probably you don't notice it there, just being--tempting, informing, and reassuring through color, form, and suggestion.<p>During an average trip to the supermarket, we're exposed to more than a thousand different packages a minute, all stimuli to which we respond in a primitive, semi-conscious manner. Is this a food or a poison? A friend or a foe? Dense with images and messages, the supermarket is a sort of information rain forest in which products compete for survival. Retailers, using the marketing data produced by checkout scanners, quickly determine which products will live and which will die.<p>The supermarket itself is a sort of package, carefully designed to route consumers along a particular path. Nearly all open onto the fruit and vegetable section, employing the profusion of colors, textures, and smells to literally get shoppers' juices flowing and to prepare them to respond with equal visceral ardor to the more abstract consumables that will follow. This is where you'll find the great natural packages, like oranges and bananas, whose peels--vivid, endearing, and unmistakable advertisements for the edible insides--constitute a sort of packagers' Holy Grail.<p>The difference between, say, a coconut and a cereal box is that the latter, like all man-made packaging, is calculated to evoke thoughts and feelings--about health, beauty, athletic prowess--that mask the actual contents of the box. This is not new; 17th-century English patent- medicine sellers understood that the shape of their bottles was far more important than the miraculous liquid they held.<p>Packaging in its modern form arose in the last quarter of the 19th century. In 1886, "the man in Quaker garb" first appeared on an oatmeal box. Henry Parsons Crowell, a merchandising genius who proclaimed that God had chosen him to get rich, owned a mill that could produce more oatmeal each year than Americans had ever consumed. His insight was that he could sell more oatmeal by packaging it in small quantities and giving it an identity. His oatmeal was no longer simply a food for horses and Scots, but, as an early advertisement proclaimed, "a delicacy for the epicure, a nutritious dainty for the invalid, a delight to the children."<p>Quaker merchants had a reputation in 19th-century America as shrewd but fair dealers, leading some peddlers to affect Quaker dress. Crowell, who gave much of his wealth to evangelical Protestant causes, wasn't a Quaker, but the Quaker image, printed in four colors on the newly perfected cardboard folding box, endowed his homely grain with personality. By making a commodity into a friend, Crowell could survive lower-cost competitors and years when the price of oats was high. Within a few years of the Quaker's appearance, there were countless imitators. <p>"Good packaging creates companies," says Elinor Selame, principal of BrandEquity International, a design firm, and past president of the Package Design Council. Campbell's Soup is a good example. Its red-and-white can was adopted more than 90 years ago. Before that Campbell had colorfully illustrated cans, with a different brand name for each product. The red-and-white icon was a radical simplification that enabled the company to be identified not with a few products, but with a wide range of condensed soups.<p>For generations, Campbell's successfully sold not so much a line of soups as the idea of soup itself. The Campbell's can signified warmth, stability and nourishment, home. In fact, it had stopped meaning "food." "Our research showed that almost everyone has a can or two of Campbell's Soup in the cupboard," says Del Macaulay, the company's former package-design chief. "The problem was to get them to eat the soup." <p>And so the pioneering package recently underwent a major redesign to transform Campbell's from something to save into something to eat ... right now. The familiar red-and-white, gold-medalled can--originally based on the Cornell University football uniform--was given a full-color photograph of the soup at the bottom of the label.<p>"When we did tests of how people perceived Campbell's Soup, everyone knew it was in a red and white can, but not much else," says Macaulay. "They couldn't even tell us whether the red is at the bottom or at the top." The tests suggested that the can could be modified with little risk, as long as the red and white remained. (The red's at the top, by the way.)<p>In a sense, the redesign was a step backward to the way Campbell's soups looked a century ago. But new and old are elusive qualities in the world of packaging. One of the most successful product launches of the 1980s, which depended almost entirely on packaging, was the Classico pasta-sauce line. The mason jars in which the sauces are packed suggest that your grandmother might have "put them up." The labels' vague but highly evocative illustrations, and sauce names taken from cities and regions of Italy, create an aura of sophistication. These are sauces for people who travel.<p>While Classico is a new product in a partly nostalgic package, Murphy's Oil Soap is a very old product that was reborn in a new package. After many decades in a cylindrical plastic bottle, the brand was dying. The company moved to a flattened container, which provides a bigger selling surface. But the real difference for Murphy's seems to have been the addition of a handle. <p>"When the handle was introduced, without any special advertising or promotion, Murphy's started to sell so fast, they were having trouble keeping it in the stores," says Richard Gerstman, whose firm did the redesign. Shoppers had unconsciously associated Murphy's with 19th-century drudgery. "The handle demonstrated that the people who make Murphy's care about making the product easy to use," Gerstman says. Once that was established, the old- fashioned natural quality of the product became an asset rather than a liability.<p>The handle is perceived as the product--just as much as soap itself. And in fact, most consumers make no distinction between packages and their contents. This was the critical discovery of Louis Cheskin, a pioneer in the psychology of packaging. During the 1930s, Cheskin did a series of experiments with identical products, one in a package marked with circles and one with triangles. Eighty percent of consumers said they preferred the product with circles because of its higher quality. "I had difficulty believing the results after the first 200," Cheskin wrote later, "but after 1,000, I had to accept that many of the consumers transferred sensations from the circles on a container cover ... to the contents of the container."<p>This principle of "sensation transference" has been confirmed repeatedly. In a test of a deodorant, one design actually caused subjects to develop skin rashes. Tide, the first heavy-duty synthetic detergent, introduced in 1947, came in a box designed by Donald Deskey Associates, but its principles are pure Cheskin. The only other well-known detergent on the market was Dreft, which was intended for delicate items and sold in an elegantly designed box. By contrast, Tide had to demonstrate its power. <p>Cheskin's beloved circles were used, concentric and incomplete at the outer edges. The shopper mentally completes the circle, making the box feel larger. The arresting, caustic orange and yellow express the power of the detergent, while the word Tide, floating in the foreground in reassuring blue, indicates the product's strength wouldn't be damaging. <p>The basic Tide design, which has been extended to liquid-detergent bottles and more compact box shapes, continues to be effective. "Tide tests as Sylvester Stallone," says Stan Gross, a psychological researcher who, among other things, encourages his subjects to compare products with fictional characters and movie stars. "It doesn't beg the question. It gets your clothes clean."<p>While all packages make products understandable, some make them urgently salable. For example, the products in the Gillette Series grooming line, including shave cream, razors, aftershave, and skin conditioner, come in ribbed, rounded, metallic-gray shapes, looking at once vaguely sexual and like precision engineering.<p>"We wanted the package to convey a premium, upscale, high-tech masculine look," says Robert Leger, vice-president of business management for Gillette toiletries. "Some of this had to do with sizing, how they feel in a man's hand versus a woman's hand, and with the pearlescent metal colors."<p>The striking appearance, along with a uniform pricing strategy, has encouraged retailers to display the more than 20 different items together, while those of Gillette's competitors are dispersed on various shelves. The point of the line, which took $75 million to develop, Leger says, was to increase the price Gillette and its retailers could charge for each product, given that our population is not increasing and there is little prospect for unit growth. "The strategy is working," Leger says. "We've gone from zero to $150 million a year in two-and-a-half years."<p>Innovation is a two-edged sword, though. Shoppers, studies suggest, are by nature conservative. "The things that people take home from the store become a part of their identities," says Davis Masten, head of Cheskin+Masten, a market-research firm. <p>The delicacy of this relationship is illustrated by the Ocean Spray Cranberry Juice Cocktail Refill, an innovative package that appeared doomed to failure but was saved by a single word. The product is an eight-ounce carton that features a picture of the more familiar 48-ounce Ocean Spray bottle. But this didn't make sense to consumers, who confused the concentrate package with a single-serving juice carton. Moreover, most people had not realized that the bottled juice was also made from concentrate. (That's spelled out in the small print.) They didn't buy.<p>The product was saved by the word refill. Matching the word to the picture of the bottle, shoppers, already accustomed to detergent and household-cleanser refills, felt reoriented and reassured. The product is now earning its place on supermarket shelves. "There's an element of manipulation in packaging," says Masten, "but what the game is really about is clarity."<p>Possibly, but clarity doesn't rule out complexity. Consider Tom's of Maine toothpaste, with its old-fashioned box and tube, pale colors, almost clumsy type, and copy listing every natural ingredient in the all-natural product. This package flatters potential purchasers with the suggestion that they are too sophisticated to be seduced by slick graphics and vibrant colors. Indeed, it hints that smart, discerning people aren't affected by packaging.<p>Of course, having put this bit of mass-market Maine into your cart, you've proved both propositions false. You may think you've picked substance, not packaging. But what you've bought is a package that's effective because it tells you, ever so subtly, exactly what you want to believe. <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/7pages.gif"><br>About 7 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
