<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Does Your 401(k) Measure up?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Does Your 401(k) Measure up?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Does Your 401(k) Measure up?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Features<p>DOES YOUR 401(K) MEASURE UP?<p>By Jeff Blyskal<p>Does your employer offer a 401(k) plan that will allow you to take care of yourself in old age? Or are you slaving for an outfit that still thinks Social Security will be around to protect retirees for decades to come?<p>To answer those questions, you need to look at three essential elements of your 401(k) plan. First, the amount of pretax earnings you are allowed to contribute. If your plan lets you kick in as much as the law permits, count yourself among the fortunate and make sure you take advantage of this option. Many plans let participants contribute only a fraction of the amount that's legally allowed.<p>Next, examine how much your employer chips in on your behalf. The best plans match employees' contributions dollar for dollar. The worst don't contribute a penny.<p>Finally, look critically at the investment choices available in your 401(k). Ideally, you should be able to choose from a number of options and construct a safe and well-balanced portfolio--not one that puts all of your savings in one pot, as some antiquated plans still require.<p>These are the variables we focused on as we evaluated the nation's 100 largest 401(k) plans. And these plans provide a good picture of the state of 401(k)s in 1995: With some $200 billion in total assets, they collectively account for nearly 40 percent of all the money invested in 401(k)s and cover an estimated 3 million employees.<p>Lately we've heard much talk about a trend toward improved 401(k) programs at many large companies. We did find some evidence of this in our reporting. Last summer, for instance, <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> made sweeping changes in its program, boosting the maximum employee contribution to 12 percent of salary from 9 percent and hiking the corporate match to 50 cents per employee dollar from 30 cents. "We always look at what other employers are doing and work to stay competitive," says IBM  spokesman Tom Beermann.<p>Nevertheless, the IBMs of the world remain few and far between. Many of the programs we checked up on were downright substandard; we deemed at least half deficient in one or more important respects. <p>Our rankings of the top 100 show how well each plan serves all of its members as a group. In some cases, plans may do a better job for participants with above-average incomes than they do for middle- or lower-income employees. Our ratings also don't account for other retirement-savings programs the employers may offer, such as pension or profit-sharing plans. A low grade on our list, therefore, doesn't necessarily mean that a company is a benefits scrooge. <p>But there's little excuse for bad marks, either. Regardless of what other retirement programs they provide, we don't think there's any reason that companies should prevent employees from taking advantage of the tax breaks allowed under section 401(k) of the Internal Revenue Service code. Our grading system, in fact, is quite generous on this score: A company program can earn a better than average final score even if it doesn't contribute a nickel to its 401(k) program itself. All it has to do is let employees contribute as much as they are allowed to under the law as well as provide them with a solid menu of investment options. At the moment, though, many employers fail to meet even this modest goal.<p>Our list of the biggest programs comes from Judy Diamond Associates, a Washington, D.C., research firm. To get up-to-date details about the structure and benefits of each plan, we went to the employers themselves. Eighty willingly cooperated, but 20 refused. So we turned to inside sources. We then supplemented whatever intelligence we were able to collect with data that all employers are required to file with the Internal Revenue Service, Department of Labor, and Securities and Exchange Commission. When we finally had everything we needed, we sent faxes to each of the 20 companies that had refused to help. In the end, ten of these declined to confirm our results. <p>Employee Contribution
we began our analysis with the premise that, because the IRS already restricts the total amount an employee can contribute to $9,240, there's no logical reason for plans to slap any additional handcuffs on participants. Many, however, do just that. <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a>, for instance, limits an employee's contribution to 8 percent of annual salary--which prevents most of the company's workers from reaching the IRS limit. Under the Philip Morris plan, a manager who earns $70,000 can defer no more than $5,600. That's $3,640 less than the IRS allows.<p>On average, the programs in our survey set a cap of 14.6 percent. Yet, according to our math, even that figure is too low. In order to allow a $45,000-a-year employee to contribute the maximum amount, the ceiling should be set no lower than 20 percent. Among the 100 plans we surveyed, only three companies--<a name="NYSE:JNJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10824"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Johnson & Johnson</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:WX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11627"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Westinghouse</b></a>, and American Airlines--have caps this high.<p>Grading on the curve, we awarded the top three plans in our survey an A-plus for their performance in this area. We gave plans with 14 percent caps a C. Plans that limited contributions to less than 6 percent got an F. <p>Company Contribution
Most companies match a certain percentage of an employee's contribution. This obviously is an important wealth builder, and given the gradual demise of old-fashioned pension plans, it is often the biggest commitment a company makes to funding the retirement of its employees. Employer contributions aren't subject to any IRS limits.<p>On average, the top 100 plans we looked at contribute 66.4 cents for each dollar put in by their employees (26 of the plans we looked at match dollar for dollar). The average limit on employer contributions for the plans in our survey was 5.2 percent of annual salary. <p>Here again, we graded employers on the curve, giving A's and B's to plans that exceeded the average and assigning average or below-average plans C's, D's, and F's. We took off a full grade for plans in which all or part of the company's contributions is in the form of company stock--a practice we don't like because it restricts an employee's ability to diversify his or her portfolio.<p>Once we had these first two grades for the 100 plans--both dealing with contribution limits--we averaged the two to produce a total plan-structure grade. Here's what it means, in dollars, to participate in a plan with an A rating for contributions:  Diligent savers earning $60,000 annually can load as much as $64,200 into their 401(k)s in just five years. In contrast, a D-rated plan can limit an employee's 401(k) savings to as little as $22,500 over five years. Neither of these figures, of course, takes into account investment returns. <p>Investment Options
a meaningful menu here serves a crucial purpose. As a plan's account balance grows, the risk of investment losses is reduced if the assets are appropriately diversified. <p>The basic investment principles of asset allocation suggest that every plan should offer three options at the least: a diversified stock fund to provide a chance for high returns, a fixed-income fund (preferably investing in a diversified portfolio of bonds rather than guaranteed investment contracts) to give more stable returns, and a money market fund so the participant can get out of the markets if need be.<p>We didn't reward companies just for offering a plethora of choices. The Levi Strauss plan, for example, has eight options, but three of them are Fidelity balanced funds. That's overkill in one area, especially when there's no fixed-income option. <p>We awarded a C grade to plans that met our minimum standard of three choices. Surprisingly, 55 percent of the plans didn't meet even this commonsense level. In most cases, the plans lacked only one of these choices--typically a money fund--but the plans at MetLife, <a name="NYSE:XON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10537"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Exxon</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:WAG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11601"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Walgreen</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:ABT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10030"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Abbott Laboratories</b></a> were missing two.<p>We gave extra credit to plans that went beyond the basics and provided meaningful alternatives within the larger categories. In stock funds, for example, the best plans offered large-cap, small-cap, and international equities funds. On the fixed-income side they offered balanced, asset-allocation, and government-bond funds. <p>Under this system, a plan with nine meaningful options--all three basics and six of the extra-credit alternatives--got a perfect plan-choice grade: an A-plus. Only four plans--those from <a name="NYSE:BCC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10222"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boise Cascade</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:UIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11548"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Unisys</b></a>, and the <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> salaried and hourly employees plans--scored this high. The plan-choice grade in the table shows how each employer measured up in the area of choice.<p>The final step in our analysis was to combine the plan-structure grade and the plan-choice grade to produce the overall plan grade by which the 100 plans were ranked. In general, the best plans allowed employees to plow lots of money into the plan and gave a relatively high number of meaningful investment choices. The worst plans did poorly on both counts.<p>What if your company's plan isn't large enough to be on our charts? Or suppose you want to know how well your plan serves you, as opposed to all of its participants? It should be simple enough to gather up some basic information about your plan. With that in hand, you can use averages from our list to evaluate your 401(k) and produce a letter grade. Turn to "Grading Your Own Plan" for details.<p>Employees, of course, can't choose their 401(k) plan. But neither are they stuck with whatever their company has thrown together. As investment vehicles go, this one is still young, says Ted Benna, president of the 401K Association, a group that advocates improvements in 401(k) plans. The plans are evolving. Many companies seem to be earnestly trying to find out and deliver what employees want, and they are making improvements. Now is the time to lobby for meaningful change.<p>Employers and employees alike need to recognize that a plan can be improved for relatively little or no cost. For example, a typical pension plan costs a company 4 to 6 percent of payroll, versus just 1.5 to 2 percent of payroll for a 401(k). Beefing up the pension plan by 50 percent would cost 2 to 3 percent of payroll; to do the same thing for the 401(k) would cost just 0.75 to 1 percent. Furthermore, some improvements, such as simply allowing employees to contribute a larger percent of salary, add virtually nothing to plan costs.<p>Companies also look over their shoulder at the benefits competitors are offering. It is no coincidence that Conoco, <a name="NYSE:AN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10108"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Amoco</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:TX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11458"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Texaco</b></a>, and Marathon Oil are bunched together near the top. They're competing for the same industry pool of employees. A good 401(k) plan is one lure. <p>----------------------------------<p>WHAT YOU DON'T KNOW CAN HURT YOU<p>Would you put $30,000 into a mutual fund without first understanding what you're investing in?  Of course not. Yet millions of workers with 401(k) plans do this all the time, making their investment choices with little or no information about their plan's objectives or the quality or safety of its holdings.<p>One reason for this: A quirk in federal securities law releases 401(k) plan sponsors, trustees, investment managers, and any other fiduciaries from normal disclosure obligations. No prospectuses, annual reports, or financial statements are required. "If a 401(k) plan is using pooled investments run by a private money manager or in-house, those funds would not be in our database, because we can't get information about them--there's no access," says Paul Reis, an analyst at Morningstar, the mutual fund rating and data firm. More than 80 percent--or $438 billion--of all 401(k) assets reside in such pooled investments. <p>How could almost a half-trillion dollars in 401(k) assets have slipped through the regulatory cracks? Blame the U.S. Department of Labor, which has jurisdiction over corporate pension investments but hasn't kept pace with industry trends. In a 1992 study, then-SEC chairman Richard Breeden recommended that Congress eliminate the disclosure exemption for pooled-investment vehicles servicing 401(k) plans, among others. The SEC also suggested that employees receive prospectuses and semiannual and annual reports about the underlying investments. <p>Sound as it was, Breeden's take-charge approach violated bureaucratic etiquette. "Breeden was not afraid to step on anyone's toes, and the Labor Department saw the recommendations as a turf issue," says a government source with knowledge of the episode. "The current chairman [Arthur Levitt] is more willing to work with other regulators." So last year, Levitt and Labor Secretary Robert Reich met to find a more tactful solution. Eventually, the two agencies agreed to work with the Employee Benefit Research Institute on a survey aimed at learning what kind of information and educational materials 401(k) plan sponsors are giving participants.<p>Richard Hinz, a Labor Department research director, says he has "no idea what we'll find." Experts in the private sector, however, already know. "The information employees are getting is absolutely atrocious," says Tom Schlossberg, president and CEO of Diversified Investment Advisors, a registered investment advisor serving pension-plan sponsors. "In many companies, plan participants deal with someone in the HR office who knows little more than the participant does about investing and is frightened about giving any advice."<p>Some companies aren't waiting for the government to figure out what to do. The <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyota Motor</b></a> Manufacturing U.S.A. 401(k) plan gives its members prospectuses on its two publicly traded mutual fund investment options, a prospectus on the <a name="FUND:AETBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/AETBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Aetna Bond Fund</b></a> investment pool, and a detailed, reader-friendly prospectus-type booklet explaining the <a name="FUND:INEAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/INEAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IDS Trust Income Fund</b></a>. MassMutual provides concise two-page profiles of its separate bond and equity accounts, giving sufficient information for those interested in only a quick read; investors who want more detailed information about these institutional funds can get a 20-page prospectus. <p>-------------------------------------<p>GRADING YOUR OWN PLAN<p>We rated the top 100 401(k) programs based on how well they serve all of the participants in each plan. Nevertheless, if your employer's plan isn't on our list or if your income is well above average, the scores won't apply to you personally. The worksheet below shows how to grade your plan yourself. All you need is some basic information, a few averages from our study, and a calculator. You'll start by computing a plan-structure score, go on to calculate a plan-option score, and then average the two to get an overall grade.<p>PLAN-STRUCTURE SCORE
1. Write down the maximum percentage the plan allows you to contribute. (For example, 0.07.) _________
2. Multiply your annual salary by this amount. (For example, $100,000x0.07 would be $7,000.)  Write the result here.__________
3. Divide this number by $9,240, the maximum amount the IRS allows employees to contribute to a 401(k) plan. (So that's $7,000/$9,240, or 0.76. Write the result here._________
4. Next, write down the percentage of your contribution your employer matches. (For example, if your employer matches each of your dollars with 75 cents, write 0.75.) ________ 
5. Multiply that number by the maximum percentage of your salary that your employer will match. (For example, 0.75x6 percent comes to 4.5.) This is your match value. ________ 
6. Divide your match value by 3.66, the average in our survey. (4.5/3.66, or 1.23 in this example.) ________
7. Subtract 0.1 from that score if your employer matches your contribution in company stock instead of cash._________ 
8. Last, to benchmark your company's score against those in our survey, divide that result by the best dollar-match value in our study: 2.23. Write that number here. __________
9. The average of the maximum contribution figure (no. 3) and the match value (no. 8) is your plan's structure score. _______ Multiply by 100 to convert this into a whole number. <p>PLAN-OPTION SCORE
10. Give your plan a 75 (a C on our scale) to start. Subtract 10 points if your plan doesn't offer a money market fund, 10 more if your plan doesn't offer a diversified stock fund, and 10 more if it doesn't offer a fixed-income fund. Company stock doesn't earn any credit here. The lowest your plan can earn in this part of the scoring is a 45. Then add points if, besides the basic stock fund, your plan offers an international fund, a large-cap fund, or a small-cap fund. Give your plan 4 points for one option, 10 points for two, and 14 points for all three. Do the same with bond funds beyond the basic option, awarding 4, 10, and 14 points for plans with balanced funds, asset-allocation funds, and government-bond funds. This is your plan's option score. Write that number here. _______ <p>OVERALL SCORE
11. To calculate your plan's overall score, simply average the structure (no. 9) and option (no. 10) scores. _________<p>LETTER GRADES
To convert each score to a letter grade, follow these last three steps. 
12. Your plan's structure grade will be the structure score______ divided by 79 and multiplied by 100.
13. Your plan's choice grade will be the option score________divided by 103 and multiplied by 100.
14. Your plan's overall grade will be the overall score______ divided by 77 and multiplied by 100.<p>And in case you've forgotten the old grade-school scale: 
A+ 100-97, A 96-93, A- 92-90, B+ 89-87, B 86-83, B- 82-80, C+ 79-77, C 76-73, C- 72-70, D+ 69-67, D 66-63, D- 62-60, F 60 and below.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement Investing, Employment, Mutual Funds Investing

