		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Doing Due Diligence Domestically</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Doing Due Diligence Domestically</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						A company has caught your eye, and you want to conduct due diligence before deciding whether to invest. From your home office, the obvious solution is to use an online data service, but which provides the best and most cost-effective information?<p>We asked Van Kasper, a San Franciscobased stock picker, to suggest a fast-growing, somewhat obscure company for us to research. Kasper chose Odwalla Inc., a maker of fruit and vegetable juices virtually unknown outside the San Francisco Bay area. Kasper's firm, Van Kasper & Co., helped underwrite Odwalla's initial public offering.<p>Three sessions on Prodigy provided progressively more data, ultimately yielding a detailed three-page report and a one-year price history--for under five bucks. We learned that Odwalla, based in Davenport, California, operates primarily in Northern California and Washington and that sales rose 60 percent in the quarter ended last November, to $6.3 million. The company made a net profit of $126,000 for the quarter, versus a year-earlier loss of $89,000. The stock was over $16, up from $10.25 in November.<p>The report listed the company's top officers, address, phone number, various financials, return on equity, and a comparison of Odwalla's performance against industry averages. Hambrecht & Quist Group, an aggressive San Francisco investment bank, was listed as owning 19 percent of the company, which it took public in December 1993.<p>Like Prodigy, <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b> offered an easy-to-use quote service, and its free Hoover's Company Profiles lists 7,300 companies, though not Odwalla. Hoover's reports are comparable to Prodigy's but contain less financial detail.<p>AOL had a Business Week story that included Kasper's forecast that Odwalla's earnings would rise from 12 cents a share in the last fiscal year (ended August 1994) to 30 cents this year and 50 cents next year. Investor's Daily, also on AOL, had an article describing Odwalla founder Greg Steltenpohl as a former artist who said he is "learning to respect the fruit." The article mentioned Odwalla's recent acquisitions of juice companies in Denver and Bellingham, Washington, and said the company is "building a fanatically loyal following that other juice makers lack." ID said the company was expanding its product line and aggressively marketing the health benefits of its drinks. The San Jose Mercury News, which runs its own Mercury Center on AOL, had the interesting news that Hambrecht & Quist had sold several thousand Odwalla shares.<p>All the AOL data was free, save the $9.95 monthly charge. Not so with <a name="NASD:CSRV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43062"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CompuServe</b></a>, except for a bare-bones rundown of Odwalla through the business report service. A search of CompuServe's premium services revealed that Odwalla's stock is rated a moderate long-term buy by Vestor, an online stock-advisory service. IBES, a company that compiles earnings estimates from Wall Street brokerage houses, forecast earnings in line with Kasper. We downloaded three Dun & Bradstreet reports for $22.50 and found them less detailed than the $3.95 Prodigy report. For $17 we could have obtained the company's financial statements from Disclosure Inc., which puts Securities and Exchange Commission documents online. Another $25 buys a list of major Odwalla stockholders. InvesText, which puts stock analyst reports online, charges $20 to search for a report and $20 for each one downloaded (brokerage houses give these away). But most of what we needed was in the Prodigy material.<p>CompuServe also archives dozens of California newspapers, from which we learned that by 1989, the earliest article date, Odwalla offered its employees 100 percent health and dental insurance, flexible workweeks, time-off programs, hot lunches, and a music festival, and used recycled plastics.<p>The company was founded in 1980 when Steltenpohl bought a $225 juicer to sell fresh-squeezed orange juice to restaurants in Santa Cruz. By December 1993, when it went public, Odwalla had a 65,000-square-foot plant in the San Joaquin Valley and was selling juice through supermarkets, health-food stores, and restaurants. Its product line had grown to more than 25 all-natural juices. The articles also described a lot of volatility. Odwalla lost $427,000 in 1993, made $39,000 in 1992, and lost $895,000 in 1991.<p>We left CompuServe richer in information but dazed by the pricing system. Each service charges differently; one may charge $45 an hour to search for information, and the next will charge per search or per report. Our cost--$42 plus the $9.95 monthly fee--could have been much higher. <p>Our final stop was Dow Jones News/Retrieval, with articles from more than 1,400 publications. We limited our search to the Wall Street Journal and the Dow Jones News Wire, finding six articles that added little to what we already knew. In one story, however, a dietitian questioned why one Odwalla serving provided several times the recommended daily amount of key vitamins, as claimed. Our Dow search took just four minutes but cost $37. Searching further could add hundreds in no time, making the service practical only if your budget is unlimited.<p>After our investigation, we knew a fair amount about Odwalla's history, leadership, products, and prospects, enough to make an informed investment decision. Prodigy provided the best value; its company profile and a new Homework Helper research tool put it a bit ahead of CompuServe and AOL. CompuServe, the most comprehensive of the three, was also by far the most expensive. None of them is truly comprehensive, so the wisest strategy at present is to cover yourself by subscribing to more than one service. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:AMER">America Online</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:CSRV">CompuServe Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
