	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Shopping for Plastic Money</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Shopping for Plastic Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Shopping for Plastic Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> SHOPPING FOR PLASTIC MONEY <p>Choose a credit card wisely by avoiding these come-ons  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> Americans sure love their credit cards. Total card debt reached $327.7 billion in October 1994, an increase of 16.6 percent since October 1993, according to the Federal Reserve. But what looks like a borrowing binge to economists is still a starvation diet to credit card issuers, who want more consumers to feast on evermore plastic. This explains the blizzard of credit card offers now piling up in mailboxes. According to Behavior Analysis, a credit card consulting firm in Tarrytown, New York, issuers sent out 1.2 billion solicitations between January and June 1994; 20 million consumers took the bait. But credit card offers loaded with perks often pale when put under a microscope. To start 1995 off right, be extra careful when you see one of these come-ons: <p> SEEMINGLY LOW RATES. About three quarters of all new cards issued each year carry teaser rates--low initial interest charges that begin to rise in a relatively short time. Last May, <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> urged borrowers to transfer debt to its 9.9 percent variable-rate Mastercard. Associates/Unocal now offers a 7.6 percent variable-rate card. Problem: issuers can hike rates suddenly. Just weeks after GM introduced its card, it upped its rate to 11.15 percent. After six months, the rate on the Associates/Unocal card zooms to prime (currently 8.5 percent) plus 10.9 percent.  <p> FREE FREQUENT-FLIER MILES. United, American, and <a name="NYSE:CAI.A"></a><b>Continental</b> are now urging their cardholders to get a free mile for every dollar charged. But these deals work best for folks who charge big and pay up each month (68 percent of cardholders carry a balance). Since most frequent-flier deals require 25,000 miles for a free ticket, it will take the typical spender with annual average charges of $2,200 at least ten years to earn a ticket, according to a 1994 study by Bankcard Holders of America. The study also says cardholders who carry the average annual balance of $1,100 on a Continental card would spend $264 yearly in interest, which does not go toward the free ticket.  <p> CASH BACK ON INTEREST CHARGES. Mellon Cornerstone MasterCard will return interest payments to those who use its prime-plus-8.9-percent card, so long as they use it at least once a year and carry a balance. But after two years, just 10 percent of interest fees is refunded, with an additional 5 percent tacked on each year thereafter. According to the deal, a cardholder must wait 20 years to recover costs.  <p> REBATES. The Discover Card's 17.4 percent annual interest rate carries a 1 percent rebate on all charges. Cardholders get a check back from Discover at year end. CoreStates Bank and US West Banks also offer rebate deals. Drawback: These lures often carry high spending thresholds. Discover Card holders must accumulate $3,001 in charges before receiving the full 1 percent; according to RAM Research, a credit cardtracking firm in Frederick, Maryland, most Discover Card holders charge about $1,000 and get back 0.25 percent, or a piddling $2.50. Says Robert McKinley, editor of RAM Research's Card Trak newsletter: "The interest rates on these cards are very high" and often wipe out rebates if a balance is carried.  <p> INTEREST-FREE GRACE PERIOD. Nearly every card touts a 25-day grace period during which interest payments on earlier charges are waived. But a closer look at the application's disclosure box reveals that balance-toting cardholders can get stung if their issuer calculates interest through the average daily balance method, which means interest charges toll daily on outstanding balances.  <p>  <p>THE BEST CARDS FOR 1995  <p> AFBA Industrial Bank (800-776-2265)  <p>Rate: Prime plus 2.9 percent for the first year, prime plus 6 percent thereafter. No annual fee.  <p> <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan</b></a>/British Airways (800-955-2748)  <p>Sign-up bonus of 4,000 miles. One mile for each dollar charged, a five-year redemption period, and high annual cap of 80,000 miles makes this card the best frequent-flier deal. Its maximum rate is prime plus 10.9 percent.  <p> Diners Club (800-234-6377)  <p>Frequent-flier miles, free collision coverage on car rentals, and free luggage insurance. You get two months to pay in full; after that, you pay a $20 late fee plus 2.5 percent on the balance. Annual fee: $80.  <p> GE Rewards MasterCard (800-437-3927)  <p>A rebate card that returns 1 percent cash on  purchases over $2,000 annually. Rate is 16 percent; no annual fee.   <p> The GM Card (800-846-2273)  <p>Five percent rebate on purchases toward leasing or buying a GM auto. Rebate maxes at $500 annually on standard card, $1,000 on the gold. Deal lasts for seven years. Maximum rate is prime plus 10.4 percent, with a $39 annual fee.  <p> USAA Gold Card (800-922-9092)  <p>Rate is the yield on a three-month T bill plus 7 percent. No annual fee.  <p> Wachovia Bank (800-842-3262)  <p>Rate: Prime for the first year, then prime plus 3.9 percent. Annual fee: $18; $28 for gold.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Financial Products
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
