<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Calculating the "What Ifs"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Calculating the "What Ifs"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Software for testing both portfolios and theories.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Rather than fiddle with pencil and paper, investors are increasingly relying on computers and portfolio-tracking programs to keep tabs on their investments. In the process, some also are discovering another nifty use for these software tools: testing hypothetical portfolios.<p>To illustrate how this can be done, we turned to Captool, a $129 program from Techserve (800-826-8082). The price is somewhat expensive for a portfolio tracker (though not Techserve's most expensive), but the program has built a loyal following among active investors who rely on its ability to show exactly what part of a position in an individual stock was sold on a specific date. <p>A less expensive version of the software, PFROI ($59), is also available, but it doesn't include one feature that we wanted to sample: a stock-evaluator function that lets users analyze securities based on their fundamentals. To test Captool, we employed the portfolio of the 50 new blue-chip stocks recommended in Worth's June 1994 issue.<p>Running a "what if" exercise is possible only if the designers of the investment portfolio to be tested state explicit investment goals. For a large-cap stock portfolio, the objective might be to outperform the Dow Jones Industrial Average or the Standard & Poor's 500 index. For a portfolio of smaller stocks, the benchmark might be the Russell 2000. <p>Investors also need to account for the portfolio's intended risk level. Portfolios that are riskier than a benchmark index can often outperform that index over some time periods because of the added risk. If that's the case with your portfolio, it's important to know that and factor it into your thinking. This wasn't an issue with the Worth blue-chip portfolio. We designed it to beat the Russell 1000 while taking on less risk. <p>We wanted to know if Captool could tell us whether our portfolio has been achieving the goals we set for it. At the time of our test, the portfolio was only a few months old -- hardly enough time to establish a very substantive track record. Nevertheless, one advantage of Captool is that it lets users pick virtually any time frame they want. We could, for example, have tested this portfolio to see how it would have done in 1993, or we could have chosen some specific up or down market from recent history. <p>For the purposes of the test, we focused on the six-week period that began May 20 (the first day a subscriber could have read about the portfolio in Worth and gone out and bought the stocks) and ended July 1. <p>Some of those weeks showed exactly the kind of downward volatility most likely to test the risk level of the Worth 50. During the week of June 20, for example, the Dow Jones industrials declined on four of the five trading days, dropping 34.88, 33.93, 25.68, and 62.15 points. The market advanced 16.80 during the one positive session. <p>We started by entering hypothetical buys of $5,000 for each stock into the transactions function of Captool. The process was easy and relatively straightforward: For each stock we created a single transaction record that included the price at the time of our hypothetical purchase. The program's use of stock symbols rather than full company names made input less time-consuming. (The symbols then let us download daily prices electronically from Compuserve via modem. The program can also use electronic prices from Dial/Data, Dow Jones News/Retrieval, and GEnie.) That gave us a starting portfolio, based on May 20 prices, worth $250,000. (Had we factored in the costs of brokerage commissions, the portfolio would have been valued at approximately $247,250.)<p>Then, moving to a function called valuation, we downloaded prices for July 1. The result: Portfolio losses of slightly more than 0.6 percent in the period, or $1,592. The S&P 500 and the Russell 1000, two indexes that represent the size of companies in our portfolio and the universe of our original sample, declined 1.9 percent and 2.1 percent, respectively. In a down market, the Worth portfolio behaved exactly as designed.<p>We also decided to see if Captool could help us find the ideal time to purchase individual stocks. Back when we published our story about the Worth 50, we urged investors to buy the stocks only when their prices were within a certain range. To set this level, we used a formula that considered relative dividend yield, earnings-growth rate, and historic price-to-earnings ratio.<p>Captool's valuation function made it easy to group the 50 stocks into categories that corresponded to our original timeliness ratings (stated as a scale of one to three stars, with three stars indicating the most timely buys). We could then check to see what had happened to the price of each stock since we made the original recommendation. For example, we rated <a name="NYSE:FDO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10546"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Family Dollar Stores</b></a> as a two-star stock. Since then, however, Captool told us that the stock's price had declined to $13.63 a share from $15.63 during our test period. Family Dollar was now more of a bargain -- and thus ready for an upgrade to three stars.<p>Over time, of course, an investor following a portfolio needs to be able to update fundamental statistics on each company as well. Here we found Captool's share-evaluator function disappointing. It lets an investor generate a spreadsheet for each stock that includes revenues, earnings, and dividends per share -- plus beta, a standard risk measurement that our portfolio didn't employ. But we don't think that's enough information to make a proper evaluation. Moreover, because the program doesn't provide an electronic source for downloading fundamental data, all this information must be researched from other sources and then entered by hand. Given these limitations, we felt that it probably isn't worth paying the extra $70 for Captool just to get this function. At $59, PRFOI does everything else. The more expensive cousin still leaves the fundamental investor at his desk with pencil and paper. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:FDO">Family Dollar Stores, Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
