<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Reality Check for Investors</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Reality Check for Investors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
You're in a good mood, but is the stock market?<p>By Alvin H. Danenberg<p>Warren Buffett once observed that the stock market often behaves like a manic-depressive businessman. At the peak of his mania he sees only favorable factors affecting his business, and therefore he prices shares outlandishly high. At the nadir of his depression he expects to be bankrupted at any moment, sometimes lowering the price on his concern below its liquidation value. This wide range of behavior has little to do with reality, which remains unchanged. Only the businessman's -- or the market's -- grasp on reality changes.<p>How does an investor know whether the market is in an ebullient or a morose mood? By checking out the value ratio, an indicator that helps identify the temperament of the market. <p>To figure the value ratio, simply divide the price of the stocks in the Standard & Poor's 500 index by the amount of dividends that group of stocks paid to shareholders during the prior 52 weeks. Walter J. Rouleau, editor of Growth Fund Guide, an investment newsletter about no-load mutual funds, coined the term value ratio in 1981 to identify this indicator.<p>The meaning of the ratio lies not in any claim to infallibility; like all market systems, an investment strategy based solely on the value ratio is foolish indeed. But being mindful of where the ratio stands now can give investors a clue to where the market may be headed in the near term. In midsummer the value ratio stood at over 34, which is considered high. Since 1871, in fact, the ratio has exceeded 34 -- equal to a dividend yield on the S&P 500 of 2.9 percent -- only 7 times. Conversely, the ratio has fallen below 16 -- equal to a dividend yield of 6.3 percent on the S&P 500 -- only 11 times.<p>As for the meaning of this high value ratio, history offers the following: When the ratio rises above 34, the S&P on average has lost 41.2 percent of its value before bottoming out. On the other hand, when the ratio falls below 16, the S&P has risen an average of 240 percent before hitting its next top.<p>For investors who are committed to stocks for the long haul -- five years or more -- the value ratio can be quite useful when applied to the timing of purchases and sales of no-load mutual funds. When the value ratio exceeds 34, sell equity funds and buy into short-term bond funds or money market funds. When the ratio equals or shrinks below its historical mean -- 23, or equivalent to an S&P 500 dividend yield of 4.3 percent -- shift into equity funds. In extreme depression, when the value ratio languishes below 16, switch a portion into aggressive-growth funds. In the bull market that will probably follow, these funds will be the right place to be. As for short-term investors, the current high value ratio suggests that the best bets are short-term bond or money market funds.<p>Tracking and responding to value ratio won't make you as successful an investor as Warren Buffett. It's not an exact science, nor is it a comprehensive strategy. However, value ratio is a good reality check on overall equity prices, which can get carried away on the upside as well as on the down, and it provides an objective check against an investor's intuitive notions of market overvaluation and undervaluation. <p>If nothing else, consulting the value ratio will enhance your probability of success in up markets and reduce the probability of being wiped out in declines. It's just one of many indicators to consider, but it shouldn't be overlooked. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

