<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Due Diligence</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Due Diligence</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
What every investor should know about reading a financial statement. Second in a two-part series. (Part one appeared in the June 1994 issue of Worth.)<p>By Jonathan Burton<p>The infamous accounting high jinks that took place at a company called MiniScribe back in the late 1980s fooled even the sharpest of accountants. The computer-disk-drive maker, run by Quentin Thomas Wiles, a well-known turnaround artist, appeared to be flying high in 1987. With the company racking up record sales and earnings, the stock reached an all-time peak of $18.25 a share in May of that year.<p>Unfortunately, MiniScribe's books were a complete fiction. As detailed in a 1991 complaint filed by the Securities and Exchange Commission, the company had counted unsold product as revenue. Employees had even gone so far as to place bricks in cardboard cartons and ship them as finished disk drives. In 1988, MiniScribe's directors, alarmed by the company's mounting accounts receivables and inventories, launched an investigation. After they discovered the ruse, Wiles resigned. The company filed for bankruptcy in 1990. By then, the company's stock had dropped to 25 cents a share.<p>As the MiniScribe case shows, even audited financial numbers don't always mean what they seem to mean. But that's no excuse for tossing out your calculator, either. Although it isn't possible to catch everything, investors should still closely examine the public financial data that companies publish. Important signals are often there to be spotted. Are earnings as strong as the company has been boasting? Will the trend continue? Or are there unexpected land mines on the road ahead?<p>Last month, Worth reviewed three lines on a financial statement that help answer these questions -- accounts receivables, inventory, and gross margin. We also gave examples to show how an investor who knew what to look for could uncover trouble before it was too late. This month, we return to the subject by dissecting three other important items: expenses, quality of earnings, and depreciation. Understanding all six items should provide a solid start for any investor who wants to perform due diligence on a stock. The payoff is often well worth it, as the following examples show.<p><p>EXPENSES:
The inner Chambers<p>As the decade began, Chambers Development had all the clear markings of a stock to own for the '90s. In 1991, the developer and operator of landfills, based in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, reported that earnings rose 45 percent, to $49.9 million, or 83 cents a share. Net sales approached $322 million, a tenfold increase from just five years earlier. This growth was powered by the acquisition and rapid development of new landfills.<p>Wall Street did not let this performance go unnoticed. Brokerage-firm analysts widely recommended the company through most of the year, and its stock began to rise in price, leaping from $16.13 in January 1991 to $37 a year later. Yet, on March 17, 1992, in a tersely worded statement, Chambers revealed that its profit growth had been overstated. As it turned out, the highly profitable company was not so profitable after all. In October 1992 Chambers restated income for 1991 and several prior years, wiping out $362 million in earnings and retained earnings.<p>What happened? The rapidly expanding company had been spending money to buy and develop land for future landfills and had recorded the costs as capital expenses. In other words, it treated these costs as money spent to create long-lived assets. That had the effect of pushing a substantial portion of these expenses into the future, rather than treating them as current costs to be charged against income.<p>This can be a murky area in accounting. Typically, companies and accountants say that anything that is used up in a period is an expense that should be deducted immediately from the bottom line. Nevertheless, as the stockholders of Chambers would learn, the company had been capitalizing items that clearly should have been treated as ordinary expenses, things such as, as the company's statement says, "executive administration, public affairs, and financial services." <p>In the wake of the March 1992 disclosure, Wall Street trashed the garbage-processing company. On March 18, the price of Chambers's class A shares fell more than 60 percent, closing at $11.13 a share from $30.50 the day before. Shareholders sued, and the dust still hasn't settled. A company spokesman declined comment on the matter.<p>Was there a way an investor could have seen this coming and jettisoned the stock before it got crunched?<p>Chambers reported in its annual statements that it capitalized costs, but all companies do that. Few companies, however, capitalize costs to the extent that Chambers did -- a fact ignored in the management discussion that accompanied the company's financial statements. But there were other clues.<p>Tucked near the bottom of Chambers's balance sheet under the heading "other assets" is a line called "deferred costs." This nebulous category is often a dumping ground for expenses that companies want to delay. "Whenever you see an asset called 'deferred anything,' hold on to your pocketbook," says Loren Kellogg, publisher of Financial Statement Alert, which analyzes companies and their accounting methods. <p>In Chambers's report for the quarter ended September 30, 1991, filed with the SEC on November 8, deferred costs totaled $32.7 million. This number was 32 percent higher than it had been a year earlier, when deferred costs amounted to $24.8 million.<p>Investors curious about what costs were being deferred could have found some cursory answers in a footnote to the 1990 annual report. Deferred costs, the company said, included "development costs for waste collection and security guard service contracts." It added that these expenses were being spread over three to ten years. Security-guard contracts? Remember, this is a category on the balance sheet that is supposed to describe long-lived assets. <p>Another reason for investors to worry was the sheer size of these charges compared with Chambers's earnings, which totaled $35.3 million in the first nine months of 1991. Had the company charged the entire $32.7 million in deferred costs against current earnings, its net income would have been only $2.6 million.<p>Moreover, Chambers's deferred expenses were rising at a rate that eclipsed the 22 percent growth in the company's revenue. This is important to note because, as Greg Drahuschak, first vice president at the Pittsburgh branch of brokerage house Janney Montgomery Scott, explains, "If the revenues don't continue, eventually you're going to have earnings difficulty because the [deferred] expenses are going to come home to roost." <p>In a healthy company, revenue growth usually should match or surpass growth in deferred costs. If not, then the company could be understating current expenses and padding its bottom line. As long as revenue increases, a company has a good chance of keeping this ball in the air. But a dip in growth can bring the ball crashing down. No investor wants to be there when that happens.<p><p>QUALITY OF EARNINGS:
The lesson of <a name="NASD:EAIN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16075"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Education Alternatives</b></a><p>In July 1992, the Baltimore City School District took a radical step in an effort to revive eight of its public elementary schools and one middle school. It hired Education Alternatives, a young Minneapolis-based company, to manage them. Under the five-year contract, the school board agreed to pay the company what it would have spent to run the schools -- $27 million per year, or about $5,550 for each child enrolled. In return, the company promised to spruce up the schools, cut class sizes, and improve teaching methods. Profits, the company claimed, would come from the efficiencies it could bring to public education.<p>At the time, Wall Street viewed Education Alternatives as a company poised to ride a crest of civic displeasure over public schools. The company itself certainly didn't discourage this view. "The potential for the future success of Education Alternatives continues to be phenomenal," chairman and chief executive John Golle wrote shareholders in the company's 1993 annual report. <p>This optimism, incidentally, was also reflected in a story in Worth's December 1993 issue. "EAI is a good long-term speculative buy," we wrote in an article about companies that promise to improve the world.<p>The company's financial statements also painted a rosy picture. For its fiscal year ended June 1993, Education Alternatives reported earnings of $1.1 million, or 18 cents a share, against a loss of $1.5 million a year earlier. In response, investors bid up shares last November to a 52-week high of $48.75. At that lofty price, the company had a market value of more than $300 million.<p>Then the bottom dropped out. This spring, the price of Education Alternatives stock plummeted, falling to as low as $9.75 a share before rebounding to around $15 a share in mid-May. <p>Despite the suddenness of this drop, investors who had continued reading Education Alternatives' financial statements could have seen the roller-coaster ride coming before it was too late.<p>Keep in mind that a stock's price, especially the price of a share in a young, hot growth company, is influenced more than anything else by its earnings and expected earnings. Investors need to know not only the amount of the earnings, but also where they are coming from and how reliable they are. <p>On November 15, 1993, Education Alternatives filed its quarterly report for the period ended September 30, 1993 with the SEC. Among other things, this document disclosed that the company had earned $330,000, or 4 cents a share. This was a sharp reversal from a year-earlier loss of $186,000. But an investor who probed just a little further could have discovered that the day-to-day operations of Education Alternatives were still actually losing money -- to the tune of $383,000 during the quarter. This number was listed under the line "operating loss" in the company's financial statements.<p>So how was it that Education Alternatives had been able to report a profit? Looking at a section entitled "Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations" would have revealed that Education Alternatives had received $728,000 in investment income from the proceeds of a May 1993 public stock offering. In other words, its profit had come largely from investors -- not as the result of any improvement in its operations.<p>In the absence of any earnings from operations, an investor might wisely ask whether the company's high stock price was justified on other grounds, such as revenue growth. But here, again, there was reason to suspect that Wall Street had overvalued Education Alternatives.<p>Yes, the company had signed service contracts for big numbers like $27 million. But a $27 million service contract isn't the same as $27 million of revenue generated by a company selling a product. For one thing, a service contract can be canceled on short notice -- 90 days in the case of Education Alternatives' arrangement with the Baltimore schools. For another, Education Alternatives was passing most of this revenue on to pay such things as salaries for teachers previously paid by the school system. It could count this money on its own books, but it wasn't as if the company had actually done something to create this revenue. The teachers, still technically employees of the school system, were the ones doing that. "That's not revenue," contends Howard Schilit, an accounting professor at American University and author of Financial Shenanigans: How to Detect Accounting Gimmicks and Fraud in Financial Reports. "Revenue is what they earn by providing their consulting service."<p>Education Alternatives may yet become a major force in an emerging new industry, charged with reforming the nation's public schools. But Wall Street clearly jumped the gun on the company's stock, bidding it up to heights justified by neither the company's earnings -- of which there were none -- nor its revenue growth -- which was less substantial than it appeared to be.<p>The lesson: When it comes to earnings, understand how a company is counting its chickens. If the bulk of its net income is from sources other than the business itself, the company should be asked how it plans to turn this onetime gain into long-term performance. If the bulk of the revenue could disappear when a single customer walks out the door, an investor needs to decide how that risk should be figured into the price of the stock. If the company counts revenue differently from the typical company, an investor should ask hard questions about why. If a company can't provide convincing answers, it's probably because there aren't any.<p><p>DEPRECIATION:
A distorted image for <a name="AMEX:AMS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11714"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Shared</b></a><p>Why buy when you can rent? That was the premise behind an innovative San Francisco-based company called American Shared Hospital Services: Offer mobile magnetic-resonance-imaging machines and other diagnostic equipment on a shared basis.<p>Doctors and hospitals rushed to sign up. In 1990 total revenues hit $61.5 million, up from $42.1 million two years before.<p>Finally, the company, which had gone public in 1984, looked ready to soar. True, a $30 million junk-bond offering in 1988, done with the help of financier Michael Milken, had increased its debt load. And losses in 1989 and 1990 reached a combined $6.3 million. But 1990's revenue growth made it look like the company's risky bet might be on the verge of paying off.<p>The third quarter of 1991 brought another positive sign. The company had earned a profit, reporting a net income of $30,000, or 1 cent a share. The one analyst who ventured a prediction at the time, according to Institutional Brokers Estimate System, forecast per-share earnings of a penny in 1991 and 20 cents in 1992. By October, the stock had risen to $5.13 a share from $1.63 in January 1991. In February 1992, it was at $9.63 a share. <p>The company's 1991 10-K (the "annual report" filed with the SEC), publicly available at the end of March 1992, reported that American Shared had earned nearly $2 million, or 70 cents a share, in 1991. That was certainly good news. Yet in the same report, management declared "substantial doubt about the Company's ability to continue as a going concern." Once that bit of information was digested, it's surprising only that the stock didn't sink faster. It ended 1992 at $3 a share. Recently, the shares traded at 69 cents.<p>Once more, it's time for us to say that investors could have seen all this coming. The tipoff appeared in an earlier financial statement prepared by the company: its September 30, 1991, quarterly report. The critical item: "Depreciation and amortization." <p>When a business acquires inventory, property, or a piece of equipment, it books the item on the balance sheet as an asset. The company then depreciates the cost of this asset over the number of years the item is expected to maintain its value. Thus, a $10,000 car with a useful life of five years would be depreciated annually at $2,000. Each $2,000 would be charged as an expense  -- deducted from total income. And each year, the car's value as an asset would decline accordingly on the balance sheet.<p>But depreciation is another one of those accounting areas that comes only in shades of gray. What is the useful life of an asset? A company that writes off the cost of an asset over a longer horizon is trading a current hit to earnings for a future one. If a company assumes a $10,000 car will last 10 years, for example, then it deducts a depreciation expense of only $1,000 every year for 10 years. Conservative companies generally depreciate assets faster than average. <p>Note this: Changing depreciation accounting in midstream can radically alter a company's financials. And that's exactly what American Shared did in 1991. In fact, this change in how it handled depreciation was equivalent to 80 percent of its $2 million profit for the year.<p>The company's September 30, 1991, quarterly report provided the tipoff that the company had decided to make this move. It showed a 12 percent decline in depreciation expense for the third quarter. This was a bright red flag. <p>In a note accompanying the financials, management explained that certain of its MRI units were now being written off more slowly. Management, however, did not spell out the change or how it had affected net earnings. This omission itself should have raised another red flag. The company had actually decided that equipment formerly depreciated over five years would now be expensed over seven and eight years.<p>American Shared, though silent about this back then, now defends the change as being simply prudent. "As we reviewed our depreciation policies, it became apparent to us that we were depreciating the equipment too quickly, and it was realistic to depreciate them over a longer life," says Richard Magary, a company spokesman. "It wasn't done to change earnings; it was done to more appropriately express the life of the equipment."<p>But a former company insider tells the story a bit differently. "The real reason for lengthening depreciation was so they would not be in default with the bondholders," he says. And indeed, the company's10-K covering all of 1991 credits the accounting change as helping boost stockholders' equity to a point just above the minimum net worth needed to satisfy creditors. The accounting change didn't keep American Shared above the minimum for long. A 1994 reorganization plan would give bondholders effective control.<p>Depreciation is one of the easiest places for a company to turn when it needs a boost to earnings or balance-sheet assets. Any change in depreciation accounting will add a onetime gain to net earnings. Most companies list that gain as an "extraordinary item," although American Shared did not. Sometimes, such moves are completely justified. But management should be able to make a good case. A change in depreciation may mask deeper problems in the business. If so, investors will soon find one of their own assets unexpectedly depreciating -- their stock.<p><p>Before MiniScribe tossed a brick at his reputation, Quentin Wiles told an interviewer for California Business how he came to be known as Dr. Fix-It, a miracle worker raising sick high-tech companies from the dead.<p>"Most entrepreneurs can't tell when their companies are getting in too deep," he said. "I don't blame them. After all, you have to be somewhat of an egomaniac to start a company."<p>In ways, though they wouldn't want to admit it, shareholders have similar qualities. They believe in something -- a rumor, a perception, a hunch -- and they lay their money down. After that, they often close their eyes and go to sleep, only waking up when a noisy decline in the stock's price alerts them that something has gone wrong. That's no way to be the part owner of a business.<p>Reading the financial statements won't always help an investor spot trouble. Some disasters just can't be dodged. But making money in the stock market is hard enough. Why not use the tools that are available?
---------------
Jonathan Burton is a senior writer at Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

