<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-How to Get a Eurorefund</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-How to Get a Eurorefund</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>This month, an army of Americans will descend on Europe to celebrate the 50th anniversary of D Day. Many tourists will bring back less money than they're entitled to -- perhaps hundreds of dollars less, if they splurge on the Champs Elysees.<p>The reason? Upon leaving most European countries, visitors may reclaim the value-added tax they've paid on certain purchases. But many don't: U.S. citizens left $30 million in Europe last year -- and they'll leave even more in 1994, says World Travel & Tourism Council, a research group. VAT is like our sales tax. In most countries it tops 10 percent; a few places (Portugal, for instance) may charge twice that much. VAT is usually included in the sticker price, so it's easy to forget about.<p>Reclaiming VAT is simple but tedious. If you spend a lot while traveling, however, the bother is well worth it. Some tips:<p>-> Business travelers can reclaim the VAT they've paid on car rentals and hotel rooms. Tourists get refunds only on goods.<p>-> Not all countries require stores to cooperate with the VAT-refund program. Keep an eye out for "tax free" signs -- or ask merchants about their policy. Some stores will do the paperwork for you.<p>-> At most stores, the drill involves showing a passport, then asking for refund forms and a mailing envelope. When you leave the country, a customs official will stamp the forms. You then pop them in the mail and, several weeks later, get a refund check -- in foreign currency.<p>-> Some banks may take these checks. Better yet, ask Ruesch International (800-424-2923) to convert them for $2 a check.<p>-> Too lazy for all that? Try a service called Europe Tax-free Shopping. From kiosks near customs points in 23 countries, ETS will buy stamped ETS checks -- issued instead of refund forms by many stores -- for a 20 to 25 percent fee. That's a lot to charge for convenience, but ETS can pay in dollars.<p>-> Finally, consider having goods shipped directly to the U.S. Merchants will often deduct any VAT on the spot. But beware: This makes sense only for fairly big purchases. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

