	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-The Frequent-Flier Fallacy</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Would so many travelers go to so much bother to earn airline
mileage if they knew what a mile was really worth?<p>By Jeff Blyskal<p>A New York businessman has two days of meetings in Chicago. He could wrap up his work in time to get home to his family by 7 p.m. the second day. But instead, he schedules a three-day trip and stays in a different hotel each night. Rather than flying a direct route on the airline he prefers, he opts for another carrier and a circuitous route with several connecting flights. A taxi from O'Hare would give him more time to prepare for his meeting, but he actually rents a car at the airport, returns it downtown, then rents a second car for the trip back to the airport.<p>What could induce anyone to engage in such masochistic behavior? Answer: The quest for frequent-flier miles.<p>In a world where ledger books are always supposed to balance, the rules that forbid getting something for nothing seem to have been suspended when it comes to frequent-flier programs. They are a "terrific deal," swears Earl Quenzel, vice president of marketing programs at <a name="NYSE:CAI.A"></a><b>Continental Airlines</b>. Travelers would be "foolish not to take advantage of frequent-flier miles if they're there," adds Bruce Chemel, managing director of marketing programs at American Airlines. Many of us seem to agree: Countless people think that flying a roundabout route and artificially boosting the number of car rentals and hotel stays are economically rational acts. We love it when phone companies and credit cards offer us free mileage, and we rarely stop to ask whether these truly represent a good deal.<p>But are frequent-flier miles really worth it? And are some programs better than others? In looking into this issue, we set aside the romantic notion that flying is a luxury. We also hacked our way through the confusing jungle of airline pricing. What did we find? Well, for one thing, a frequent-flier mile has a lot less value than most people think it does. And that's before the industry's announced plans to devalue the worth of these promotions even further. Airlines are boosting award requirements by about 25 percent and putting more obstacles between the frequent flier and a free ticket. <p>Our research also found that some airline frequent-flier programs aren't nearly as good as their reputations. Plus, many of the accepted consumer rating systems for these airline promotions are flawed, sometimes seriously. For example, a major annual frequent-flier opinion survey, conducted by InsideFlyer magazine, rated Continental Airlines' OnePass program No. 1 for six years running. Yet by our count, Continental actually provided members with an effective discount of just 4.6 percent, well behind our first-place pick: Southwest, with a discount of 6 percent. And USAir, considered above average in other ratings, came in dead last on our ranking--a product of that short-haul carrier's high fares--with a dreadful 1.5 percent discount.<p>Our legwork also turned up some other surprising things about frequent-flier promotions: <p>-> For all consumers go through to rack up mileage, few cash in their awards. In 1992, only 1 in 14 American AAdvantage members collected a travel award. That same year, only 1 in 25 Continental OnePass members got a free ticket. <p>-> Free tickets are becoming harder to obtain because of the restrictions airlines impose and because of the limited number of seats available. On <a name="AMEX:TWA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TWA</b></a>, for example, "25 percent of frequent fliers with enough miles required for an award don't collect because they are unable to schedule a flight," says Geraldine Frankoski, director of Ralph Nader's Aviation Consumer Action Project.<p>-> Compared with other frequency marketing programs in other industries, the airlines' frequent-flier promotions offer consumers a relatively small discount. In other words, when it comes to ticket giveaways, big carriers are definitely on the stingy side.<p>-> Airlines have unusual flexibility to change their minds about what they are willing to shell out in return for the mileage customers rack up. It's for this reason that New York State assistant attorney general Andrea Levine says, "But for the fact that the U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that we have no jurisdiction over airline [advertising], we would be regulating frequent-flier-program marketing practices under the deceptive-business-practices statutes."<p>To calculate the true value of frequent-flier programs, travelers need to understand one thing: These programs are not giveaways. The airlines may have started these programs purely as marketing devices, but they are now often lucrative profit centers. All those award miles put dollars in the airlines' pockets and passengers in their seats.<p>Frequent-flier programs are now so much a part of travel that many people never stop to analyze them. What little press scrutiny there is generally follows the airline marketing departments' lead and focuses on helping the consumer navigate the Alice in Wonderland rules. It's rare that anyone has questioned the economic fundamentals of such plans. Last year, for instance, Fortune magazine explained how any business traveler could "Be a Smarter Frequent Flier" by contorting his or her normal behavior patterns to match the pretzel-shaped complexities and ever-changing requirements of frequent-flier-program rules. The publication never even stopped to ask whether such an effort might be worth it in the first place.<p>Of course, employers have long groused about employees collecting free tickets at company expense, though most firms have thrown in the towel on the issue. According to a survey of 749 corporations by Runzheimer International, a travel-consulting firm in Northbrook, Illinois, 88 percent of companies now agree that frequent-flier spoils belong to employees. Call it a reward for the pain in the neck otherwise known as business travel.<p>The Internal Revenue Service, which hardly ever shrinks from slapping a dollar value on abstract commodities, hasn't tackled this subject either. "There's a section of the tax code that says if income is not specifically excluded, it's taxable," says agency spokesman Kenneth Hubenak. "But there is no published IRS position specifically addressing the taxability of frequent-flier miles."<p>The airlines have been content to let the public misunderstand. Everyone knows that carriers rue the day American Airlines invented frequent-flier programs in 1981. Airlines are now slaves to frequent fliers, the story goes. And the growing liability of 1.4 trillion frequent-flier miles piling up like thunderheads on the Great Plains in July threatens the survival of the entire industry. The airlines would slay this monster in a minute, consumers are told, but no airline wants to be the first to eliminate its program unilaterally for fear of being at a competitive disadvantage. You'd almost think frequent fliers were fleecing the airlines.<p>Before you swallow that line of reasoning, ask yourself this: If frequent-flier programs are such a bad deal for providers, how come practically every telephone company, rental-car outfit, credit card issuer, and hotel in America has been so anxious to hop on the frequent-flier bandwagon? It sure ain't because the parade leads straight to the poorhouse. And it certainly isn't because frequent-flier programs are such a great deal for consumers. No, the real reason is that these programs are one of the most lucrative marketing schemes ever invented. Now guess who pays the price.<p>In the end, the airline executives we talked to conceded that frequent-flier programs are the greatest thing for carriers since the DC-3--the aircraft, introduced in 1936, that first made transporting passengers profitable. "Frequent-flier programs are not going to go away," says American's Chemel. "We don't want them to go away. The only people who want them to go away are those who don't understand them." <p>"The airlines without a strong frequent-flier program are the ones who want to get rid of them," says Evelyne Gaidot, vice president of business marketing at TWA.<p>The truth is, airline frequent-flier programs make money. They are not simple giveaways. "That's how we justified the programs economically," says Rolfe Shellenberger, who was American's manager of market plans in 1981 and is now a California-based management consultant at Runzheimer International. "When we developed the original plan, we figured if we gave the frequent flier a free ticket to Hawaii, a free Hyatt hotel room, and a free Hertz car rental, he would dig into his jeans and pay a couple hundred bucks for a ticket for his companion. Eighty-five percent of that ticket revenue would be incremental [extra revenue the airline otherwise wouldn't get], and it would pay 90 percent of the cost of the administration, the promotions and direct mail, and the award itself."<p>The extra expense of flying one more nonrevenue body (in what would have otherwise been an empty seat) is small. "On a transcontinental flight, you're talking about a couple more pounds of jet fuel, a meal, and a small allocation for passenger displacement and revenue dilution," says Donald Garvett, vice president of Simat, Helliesen & Eichner, a New York- based travel-industry consulting firm that specializes in aviation. The airline's incremental cost amounts to about a penny per mile, or $48 on a transcontinental round-trip. <p>No wonder the other U.S. majors jumped to imitate American--United did so in a matter of days. Consumers went wild. The first year, 1.8 million fliers accumulated 86 billion miles. A year later, membership rose to more than 3 million, and the number of bankrolled miles doubled. <p>Clearly the plans hit a psychological bull's-eye. Frequent-flier miles were seen as a classic something-for-nothing winner. "It's amazing how people play the game to get ten more miles here, a hundred more there," says Rick Boubelik, manager of <a name="NASD:NWAL"></a><b>Northwest</b>'s WorldPerks program. And the something wasn't just cash or a pocket calculator--it was an airline ticket. "Flying has always been a big dream of everyone since the days when air travel was considered elite," says Boubelik. Frequent-flier memberships quickly became status symbols. Long before these programs existed, an executive's importance was measured by the number of miles he flew per year. But the airlines now provided a monthly statement that confirmed those status miles.<p>The timing couldn't have been better for the airlines, either. The perk provided a distraction from the annoyance of the airlines' increasing use of hub-and-spoke systems that were forcing more and more travelers to change planes to get where they wanted to go.<p>The contradictions in the frequent-flier philosophy emerged just as quickly. These programs attempted to market prestige to the masses. To be fair, it seems likely that American didn't anticipate exactly how attractive its program would be to the infrequent flier. The airline's real target was the very, very frequent flier--the elite 3 to 5 percent of business travelers who fly 50,000-plus miles per year--not every Joe and Jane with a boarding pass and a garment bag.<p>American expected the frequent-flier program to attract about 350,000 top travelers--approximately doubling the number of Very Important Travelers that the airline's SABRE computer system identified for special treatment. Instead, millions piled on, creating two distinct classes of frequent flier: the elite corps of very frequent fliers who the airlines believe are really worth pampering, and everyone else.<p>Today, with some 30 million people belonging to at least one of these hardly exclusive frequent-flier clubs, the airlines have explicitly separated the two classes and spelled out the special treatment available for superhigh-mileage fliers--bonus mileage rates; complimentary upgrades; preferred seating, check-in, and boarding; and much more. "When there are irregular operations at the airport because of weather, we take the 100Ks [passengers who fly more than 100,000 miles a year] to a special lounge so they don't have to stand in long lines during cancellations and rescheduling," says Gayle Bock, United's director of marketing programs. "We handle them with white gloves and care." <p>To look at it another way, miles are worth more if they result in special treatment and less if they don't. Frequent-flier miles are one of the few currencies in the world that is worth more or less depending on caste membership.<p>Indeed, it's crucial that consumers think about frequent-flier miles as a currency; the airlines clearly do. Miles became a currency in the second year for the programs, 1982, when the first sizable number of free tickets--some 368,000--were issued. That effectively put frequent-flier miles on a par with deutsche marks, pounds, and francs, even though you'll never find the exchange rate listed in any financial pages.<p>But the big players in this market, the airlines and their marketing partners, know the rate. They have to: The banks, rental-car companies, long-distance phone services, and hotels that award frequent-flier miles to their customers pay the airlines for these miles--on average between 1 and 2 cents a mile, according to Randy Petersen, publisher of InsideFlyer magazine, and other industry sources. That revenue stream helps keep the frequent-flier programs at American, United, Continental, Northwest, and TWA profitable, "even before you look at how much the program increases revenues," says TWA's Gaidot.<p>Petersen, a leading expert on frequent-flier programs, says 48 percent of all miles now accumulated are awarded by the airlines' marketing partners. "Airlines love that financial shift," he says. "If they have a lot of partners buying miles, they've got money coming in from someone else. I estimate American takes between $125 million and $150 million a year just from the partners affiliated with its program." <p>At this point a consumer ought to ask again why banks and phone companies give away frequent-flier miles rather than cash discounts. Frequency marketing--giving a discount or a bonus to loyal customers--has been around since the 1940s, the heyday of promotions like Green Stamps. Rewarding frequent buyers has its own economics: A company wants to give the premium that combines the greatest perceived value with the lowest cost. The airlines' partners could certainly give cash or other discounts to frequent users, but they choose to give airline miles--a currency they have to buy.<p>That would certainly suggest that frequent-flier miles are a better deal for these marketers. And there is really only one possible explanation for that: Consumers consistently overvalue frequent-flier miles.<p>What's the real value? for the most part, the people who rate frequent-flier programs seem to regard this as an unknowable mystery. The numbers are too hard to figure, they assert, because of the ever-changing nature of air fares. Consequently, most ratings of frequent-flier programs amount to subjective judgments that don't test program quality.<p>Yet the necessary numbers are, in fact, available. You just have to know where to look. Our ratings of the major airlines' programs distill millions of marketplace purchase decisions, the plethora of constantly changing fares, the advantages and disadvantages of individual airline route systems, and the gobbledygook of frequent-flier program rules to rank the airlines on a simple and key indicator of true performance: the effective fare discount.<p>Here's how this method works. At the end of each year, the infinity of fares boils down to something called average yield per revenue passenger mile, or RPM. This is what an airline collects on average for flying one paying passenger one mile. Because of differentials in costs, markets served, route lengths, and management savvy, the average yield varies. Among the majors in 1992, it ranged from just 9.9 cents per RPM at TWA to 19.1 cents per RPM at USAir. Using this figure, it's possible to calculate how much money the average passenger shelled out to rack up 20,000 miles (40,000 at Delta, that airline's minimum award level since 1992). Multiplying an airline's RPM by 20,000 miles gives half the cost/benefit equation. (Our calculation assumes 10,000 miles earned from flying and 10,000 earned from hotel and car rental partners, since 48 percent of miles are earned from airline partners.)<p>Of course, a traveler also gets to fly all those miles he's actually paid for. Our method attempts to calculate the discount, represented by frequent-flier miles and awards, that a flier receives from the airline for being a good customer.<p>The average number of dollars spent to fly the 20,000 miles necessary to earn a domestic award typically ranges from $3,626 to $6,555, depending on the airline involved. The average cost of a free travel award at <a name="NYSE:DAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10448"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Delta</b></a> is an unusually high $7,527 because of that airline's higher mileage requirement. At Southwest the average cost of a free travel award is an exceptionally low $929, because the <a name="NYSE:LUV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11377"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Southwest</b></a> Company Club gives frequent fliers a free ticket after only eight round-trips rather than 20,000 miles. The average frequent flier on Southwest collected his free ticket after only 7,104 miles.<p>The next thing we did was calculate what a free ticket is worth once an airline has dispensed it to the customer. According to travel-industry consultant Garvett, carriers price their restricted discount tickets at about 6 cents a mile. He explains, however, that frequent-flier tickets have to be considered even less valuable than that. "If I'd had to pay for the free ticket at even the lowest fare, I wouldn't have taken the trip," says Garvett.<p>Now we can construct a value curve to estimate what one free ticket is worth. Obviously the value to consumers is greater than the 1 to 2 cents per mile that outside marketers pay the airlines. So we'll use that figure to establish the low point on our value scale. The high point would be the 6 cents it would cost to purchase a comparable discount airline ticket. So, giving frequent-flier programs every benefit of the doubt, we set the value at 5 cents in our calculations. Multiplied by the average number of miles per free round-trip at each airline--about 25 percent greater than the average round-trip, since travelers try to maximize the value of their awards by using them on longer flights--the dollar value of a free ticket ranges from $56 on Southwest (1,110-mile average free round-trip) to $208 at United (4,168-mile average free round-trip).<p>From there, it's easy to calculate the frequency discount a flier gets in each program. Think of the free ticket as a rebate for being a good customer. The effective discount measures how big a rebate each airline offers. The average effective discount is just 3.3 percent. The best is only 6 percent. That average is significantly below the discounts offered by other kinds of frequency marketing programs. "Hotel frequent-guest programs generally provide a 5 percent effective discount," says Richard Barlow, president of Cincinnati-based consultants Frequency Marketing Inc. In retailing, frequency marketing programs like Neiman Marcus's InCircle, Saks First, and <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a> Best Customer also provide a 5 percent discount.<p>Of course, the airlines' effective discount can shrink considerably below even these levels for the 32 percent of business travelers who pay higher than average full-coach, business class, or first-class fares. <p>Airline frequent-flier programs do, however, best one class of frequency marketing program, the affinity credit card. <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a>, Diners Club, and most Visa and MasterCard affinity cards usually award one frequent-flier mile per dollar charged to the card. That translates to an effective discount of just 0.7 percent on the $20,000 (or $40,000 at Delta) spent on a credit card to earn the $152 value of the average free ticket.<p>There is another way to measure the frequent-flier discount, but this paints an even more negative picture of the programs. So far, these numbers haven't considered the costs to the consumer in the way these programs alter behavior. Frequent-flier programs push travelers away from the low-fare, low-frills carriers, because these small upstarts often don't offer frequent-flier programs that tie in with the major airlines. In effect, to earn that "free" ticket, travelers pay more for air travel than they have to.<p>For example, earlier this year, you could have flown round-trip Newark to Chicago on Kiwi International Airlines for just $208 unrestricted. The same round-trip on an apples-to-apples unrestricted United ticket cost $882. Kiwi has been having trouble getting business travelers from large corporations--because of the lack of a frequent-flier program. Small businessmen and entrepreneurs, however, are flocking to Kiwi. Think they know something?<p>To rack up 20,000 miles for a free domestic ticket on United, a frequent flier would have to make 14 round-trips at a cost of $12,348. Fourteen round-trips on Kiwi would cost just $2,912. That means the United flier's company would be paying an extra $9,436 so its employee can collect one free ticket worth, on United, about $208. That's a very expensive perk. Meanwhile, the entrepreneur who flew Kiwi would have no free ticket, but with the $9,436 in his pocket, he could buy 45 more Newark-to-Chicago round-trips or 26 trips to and from Palm Beach, Florida. Call it a negative discount of 324 percent.<p>That example brings up one of the most common reasons that travelers don't worry about the cost or value of frequent-flier programs. If the company is shelling out all that money for expensive tickets and the employee is collecting the free ticket, why should he care if the discount is only 3.3 percent and the average free ticket is worth just $152? The company pays the freight and the ticket is gravy, isn't it? Well, before taking those "free" miles to the bank, frequent fliers should see if they're paying any of the costs that seem to sneak into the mileage game. How about the annual fees of $35 to $85 on an affinity card and an annual interest rate of 15 percent to 21.6 percent? A non-affinity, low-rate card would charge more like 10 percent to 14.5 percent and would certainly have a lower annual fee--or perhaps no fee. Of course, that card wouldn't let a traveler win a free mile for every dollar he charges. It doesn't take much of a fee or too many interest payments to erase the value of a $152 free ticket.<p>All affinity cards limit the user to a single airline. Those credit cards that give the traveler more freedom come with higher costs. The American Express and Diners Club mileage programs allow members to apply earned miles to any participating airline. But the annual cost of this extra flexibility is $80 for a Diners Club membership that includes enrollment in the mileage program and $80 to $100 for Amex green and gold respectively (for every year after the first year of enrollment).<p>The disciplined frequent flier who has dodged that cost should next consider the cost of buying another ticket for a travel companion--some 75 percent of award recipients travel with a partner. And what about some of the other add-on costs? To manage miles in a disciplined way, many travelers buy The Official Frequent Flyer Guidebook ($14.99) and add an annual subscription to either InsideFlyer ($33) or Frequent Flyer magazine ($24). A TravelWare computer program ($149) will help manage miles and plan the travel gymnastics necessary to boost mileage accrual. Some frequent fliers even buy insurance to protect their miles from airline bankruptcy and expiration. Award Guard coverage offered by Colorado Springs- based Frequent Flyer Services costs as much as $139 per year. Sure makes sense as a way to protect that $152 ticket.<p>And express delivery of an award--two to three days instead of three to four weeks--costs $35 to $70, depending on the airline. A couple thousand miles short of an award? Continental will sell a frequent flier the last 20 percent needed for 2.5 cents per mile, which seems like the airline itself values its miles pretty cheaply. <p>The biggest cost may be the hardest to quantify. How should we value the time many fliers spend obsessing over maximizing mileage, keeping up-to-date on program rules and special offers, rescheduling travel and flying roundabout routes to boost mileage, going out of their way to stay at a hotel partner that will award miles, and undertaking extra travel to accrue enough miles for an award?<p>The frequent-flier-program member who recognizes the economic facts of life and takes a more casual approach toward the game still gets caught in a massive catch-22. Dump the affinity card, publications, software, insurance, and express award service. Pay no attention to concentrating all travel on one airline or doing business only with the program's travel partners. Don't worry about how many miles you've got, how many you need for an award, or when they expire. Vow never to make any unnecessary travel. And chances are good you'll wind up collecting no award. An estimated 30 percent of all accumulated frequent-flier miles will never be used, says L. John Eichner, of Simat, Helliesen & Eichner.<p>As grim as this picture is, frequent-flier awards are likely to become even less valuable in the future. One of the most valued perks--the free upgrade to first class--is becoming harder to get as frequent-flier programs grow in members and miles. And the airlines, worried about the huge number of miles in frequent-flier accounts, have started to devalue this currency.<p>The free upgrade has become especially valued by business travelers in the current economic environment. A lot of companies are cutting back, and business travelers can't buy first-class seats. But frequent-flier-program members can upgrade from coach to more comfortable business or first class. The only problem for the nonelite flier, however, is a few hefty direct costs. Typically, a first-class wanna-be must start with a full-fare coach or business-class ticket. The upgrade can cost around 10,000 miles on domestic flights and up to 30,000 internationally. Frequent fliers can pay cash instead, from $25 for a 500-mile trip to $140 for a 4,000-mile journey. They can upgrade only if there are seats available and generally have a 50/50 chance of success. But "forget it for the five o'clock to Logan [Boston] or DCA [Washington National]," says Northwest's Boubelik. Travelers seeking standby upgrades have to arrive at the gate two hours before departure to improve the odds of getting what they want.<p>Next year, the cost of a free domestic ticket will rise 25 percent, to 25,000 miles on American, United, and USAir, with other airlines sure to follow. That will erode the effective discount of the deal and make it harder to collect.<p>In 1992, Alaska Airlines, American, AmericaWest, Northwest, and United added another new twist by imposing expiration dates. So at American last year, 20 billion miles --$200 million worth--expired. Poof!<p>Nevertheless, these changes, and the mileage increase proposed for 1995, haven't solved the basic problem--a growing imbalance in the supply and demand of free seats, caused largely because the proliferation of travel partners has made it much easier to add miles. "The liability of frequent-flier miles is growing, but the capacity for free seats is a constant," says Boubelik. "If we raise the mileage requirement higher, fewer people can earn the miles they need for a free ticket and we're better able to meet consumer expectations." In other words, consumers should lower their expectations. Boubelik sees award requirements eventually rising to 50,000 for a domestic ticket and 150,000 to 200,000 for international. "We've now got so many ways to earn miles, we've got to adjust the award chart up to burn off the excess," he adds.<p>Not all consumers are willing to quietly see their frequent-flier miles devalued. Chicago attorney Spencer Marks brought a class-action suit against American Airlines on this issue in 1988. "American Airlines gives out all these miles, but they don't have enough seats for people to use them," says Marks. "It is my understanding that American and United have grouped their frequent-flier award seats in with their maxi-saver seats. Those are the least expensive seats, and they sell out first." The case is still pending.<p>In 1987 Marks successfully sued United when it abruptly raised the mileage for an upgrade to 15,000 from 10,000. "I thought that was inherently wrong; if the customer completes his end of the deal and the airline says he suddenly needs more miles when he tries to cash in, the airline has breached the contract," he says.<p>United settled in 1989, but it was a Pyrrhic victory for consumers. Now United and all the airlines have put language in their program contracts stating that the airline can change the terms of the program at any time with sufficient notice. That means a frequent flier's accumulated miles are subject to any method of devaluation and use restriction that the airlines can dream up. <p>"You shouldn't be able to unilaterally change the terms of a deal in midstream, and there's no question that this rises to the level of deceptive business practices," says Andrea Levine of the New York attorney general's office. Unfortunately, when the National Association of Attorneys General tried to issue guidelines for airline ads, the Supreme Court said in 1992 that only the U.S. Department of Transportation had the authority to regulate airline advertising. Under deregulation, the department has done nothing to stop the practice.<p>Given this trend, the smart traveler will reorder his priorities. Instead of picking the airline or the route that gives the most miles or exclusively flying just one airline in an attempt to earn a free ticket, search for undervalued basics such as a better fare, better safety, and better service.<p>Travelers who can use Southwest Airlines don't have to chose. Southwest, which ranked first in service quality, also had the best frequent-flier program. But customers of other airlines aren't that lucky. For example, Continental, whose frequent-flier program provided the second-best effective discount, rated last in service quality. <p>Which to choose: Service quality or the frequent-flier come-on? Considering the questionable bargain that frequent-flier programs turn out to be, we think the answer is obvious.
---------------
Jeff Blyskal is a contributing editor of Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

