	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Unneeded Bite Out of Wallet</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Unneeded Bite Out of Wallet</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Ask any kid: Braces are mostly about vanity<p>By Bruce Upbin<p>Back in the dim mists of prehistory - the 1940s and 1950s - there were children who never smiled. Doing so would have revealed the dirty little secret that bound itself with wires or rubber bands to their teeth: braces.<p>Today, there may well be children who never smile because they don't have braces.<p>Braces are in vogue. In a compulsively self-improving society, children know that braces will enhance their looks, and they know that other children know it. The rubber bands and retainers come in rainbow colors, permitting children to mix and match their mouth gear to their clothing and other accessories. "It has become a social phenomenon," says Dr. Jeffrey Sulitzer, dental director of U.S. Healthcare in Blue Bell, Pennsylvania. "Kids want braces."<p>Orthodontics has become a growth industry. New cases measured on a per-doctor basis rose 6 percent between 1989 and 1992, the most recent numbers available. The gross income of the U.S. orthodontic industry amounts to a mouth-numbing $4 billion a year.<p>If your kids want to join the club, here are some things you should know:<p>The average fee for a course of treatment is about $3,300, but actual fees vary widely depending on the practitioner's experience and the materials and procedures used. Insurance barely makes a dent in the total cost. If you carry dental coverage at all, it is probably indemnity coverage that stalls at around 50 percent of the full course of treatment up to a lifetime maximum of $1,000 or two years, whichever comes first. Most plans - managed-care plans, for instance - omit coverage on extras like clear or lingual (behind the teeth) braces. Surgical procedures and interceptive orthodontia - troubleshooting before problems begin - are also excluded from these plans. <p>The reason for the paltry coverage is that orthodontia, like other elective procedures, "is a luxury item - you don't live or die from having straight teeth," says Robert Mehlman, national dental director of Aetna Health Plans in Hartford, Connecticut. Another reason coverage is minimal is that one third of orthodontists won't lower their fees to what insurers consider reasonable. Orthodontic fees rose 5.3 percent in 1992; that's less than the 7.4 percent increase in all medical-care costs in 1992 but still above the consumer price index's 2.5 percent rise.<p>What accounts for the high cost of orthodontia? It can't be the materials. The orthodontist's rubber bands, nickel-titanium wires, and stainless steel brackets cost around $300 a patient. "We're charging for our time. It's all we have," says Dr. Sewell Chason, an orthodontist in Bangor, Maine. "It's no different than a surgeon in an operating room, except that the situation is not a life or death one."<p>According to a survey by the American Association of Orthodontists, six out of every ten people who walk in for an orthodontia exam eventually begin a course of treatment. Among patients who return a second time to hear the orthodontist pitch his plan of treatment, the acceptance rate rises to nine of ten. <p>Orthodontists can usually make a case for straightening out young teeth to improve their bite. Half of all patients are referred by dentists who spot developing bite problems. Permanent teeth tend to erupt all over the place, first in the back, then in the front, and finally in the middle. This can lead to crowding, says Dr. David Forbes, director of orthodontics at the Northwestern University School of Dentistry. "An ideal bite is rare," he says.<p>Doctors say uncrowded teeth are easier to clean and that, by having them straightened, people can lower the likelihood of gum disease, tooth decay, and loss. But a direct correlation has never been made between less crowded teeth and cleaner teeth. "You'd think crowding would make it more difficult to clean teeth and gums," says Forbes. "But clear-cut proof has not been made. If one doesn't diligently brush, one can miss areas, crowding or no crowding."<p>Whether or not teeth will hold their alignment once the braces are removed is another question parents need to consider. In a study of 600 former patients by orthodontics professor Robert Little of the University of Washington-Seattle, 70 percent of the patients' teeth had slightly moved toward their original positions ten years after being treated for crowding. Since adult jaws continue to narrow over time, doctors are increasingly asking patients to consider wearing removable retainers for longer periods of time, sometimes indefinitely, to keep their teeth from crowding again.<p>Questions of value notwithstanding, young people know why they want braces. According to one doctor's survey, 85 percent of parents with kids under the age of 16 took them to an orthodontist simply to improve their looks. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
