<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Legal Help That Comes in a Box</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Legal Help That Comes in a Box</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>It can save time, but it's hard to sue for malpractice<p>By Stuart Weiss<p>There's nothing like a legal- software package to turn a virtuous layperson into a virtual lawyer, satisfying the deepest desires of ordinary human beings to dispense instant justice and protect their wealth simultaneously. Want to disinherit your undeserving spouse? Click! Reward a deserving niece or nephew? Click! Revoke or change a power of attorney? Click! <p>If it all smacks of a game or simulation, you're better off thinking of it that way. Software publishers warn you not to substitute their programs for living, breathing legal counsel. Far more visibly, however, their packaging touts the 50-state legal validity of the documents produced by the software. Between the promise of court approval and the threat of egregious error, the real value of the applications becomes obscured. <p>One sobersided argument is that running your legal work through a computer program before taking it to a lawyer will save him time and you money. This argument is probably overstated but does have some merit. When you visit a lawyer, the meter is on the minute you make eye contact. The preliminary work--fact gathering and document printing--could be done at home on a PC. Of course, the time you save is reduced by the several hours of work it takes to install and learn a program. Think of this as a cost. And if your hard disk is crowded with intriguing applications that you never had time to learn, you have another reason to hesitate before adding to the clutter. <p>One of the more comprehensive programs is It's Legal for Windows, by Parsons Technology, which sells for $69. On ten megabytes of hard-disk space this program gives you a library of documents and the procedures for editing them. You can draw up wills, contracts, corporate minutes, prenuptial agreements, sales contracts, living wills, and more. There are probably several dozen such packages for $100 or less. The Parsons program is one of the best in this class, and also one of the biggest sellers. <p>Certainly it's smart to learn as much as you can about a legal topic before visiting your attorney. 'I wouldn't object to a client running through a program before coming in," says Paul M. Stokes, a trusts and estates attorney with Kelley Drye & Warren in Miami, 'because 25 percent of my time is spent on education. I think it's possible to develop software that leads you through a number of questions. At some point, it should say, 'Go see a lawyer. Press F1 for a list of lawyers in your neighborhood.'"<p>In general, few lawyers think much of consumer legal software. This probably would be the case even if the programs were more valuable. But even putting their self-interest aside, some of their objections seem sensible.<p>Computers are easily satisfied with the answers to the questions they pose. That can create serious factual and legal errors in computer documents. 'How many children do you have? "the legal software asks a couple drafting a will. The husband and wife, each with children by previous marriages, may answer 'one" if they're thinking only of the one they had together, the one they want to inherit their estates. A thorough human lawyer, however, would determine whether other children by previous marriages might assert a claim.<p>Lawyers 'serve as a double-checker," says Evelyn Capassakis, an attorney and manager in the New York office of accounting firm Coopers & Lybrand's personal financial-services division. She adds, though, that legal software can be helpful in preparing a balance sheet. 'The financial questions," says Capassakis, 'tend to be more cut-and-dried" than the personal questions.<p>Legal software can give careless users a spurious sense of confidence. 'Just because the boilerplate is being done for you doesn't mean you're obtaining an appropriate end product, "says Scott Kamin, an attorney in Portland, Oregon. 'Human affairs are like snowflakes. No two are alike."<p>Says Lynn Jahn, group leader at Parsons Technology, 'Our intent is not to replace a lawyer. If you look carefully at the [It's Legal for Windows] help system and the manual, there are a lot of places where we advise you to go see your attorney. A lot of attorneys aren't computer literate yet, so I can understand their fear of this." Computer literate or not, lawyers must stand behind their work in a way that software publishers do not: Human lawyers can be sued for malpractice. Publishers place so many disclaimers on these products that it would difficult to sue them successfully for that.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
