<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Searching for Hidden Perks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Searching for Hidden Perks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Don't miss out on your employer's benefits<p>By Mary Rowland<p>Despite continued cost cutting by many employers, not all the news on the benefits front is dour. Many companies are actually adding to the roster of perks that they offer employees. The new trick, though, involves learning what the benefits are.<p>"The hot benefits area is work/family opportunities," says Rosanna Z. Milley, a principal at the Apex Management Group in Princeton, New Jersey. "But most employers are not giving out information. You have to find out about them yourself."<p>Why are companies staying mum about these goodies? It's hard to generalize, but a cynic might suspect some employers are downplaying benefits to keep costs low while still complying with new laws or showing off--at least on paper--to the board of directors, outside consultants, Wall Street, and human-rights groups. Whatever the reason, employees now have to play detective to avoid missing out on obscure but valuable perks. <p>Here's what to look for:<p>--Maternity leave. If you're expecting a child, your human-resources department will provide the basic leave policy. But to get the real lowdown, you should talk with a number of employees who have recently had babies. Find out what kinds of arrangements the mother and/or father got. For example, some companies allow employees to stockpile vacation and personal days to use as leave when the baby comes--if, that is, they make such plans in advance. Others have a number of options for parents returning to work. "Many companies have a lot of phased back-to-work options that are known only to the underground network," says Angela Watson in the Washington, D.C., office of the Wyatt Co., a benefits consulting firm. "Maybe you can work 50 percent of the time and get 50 percent of pay or even 100 percent of pay." <p>The company may also agree to job sharing or working at home; ask about it. In smaller companies it may be even easier to cut extraordinary deals. "Family leave is often not formalized," says David Oberkircher, a consultant in Wayne, Pennsylvania. "You can pioneer a new program simply by asking." <p>--Adoption benefits. Many companies pay $1,500 to $5,000 toward the cost of adopting a child. "But you won't find it in the company manual," says Maureen McCoslin, a consultant in the Dallas office of Hewitt Associates.<p>--Sick-child care. When a child has an illness such as the chicken pox, some companies will pay for someone to take care of him or her so an employee doesn't have to miss work. Johnson & Johnson, for instance, offers this kind of child care.<p>--Free overnight child care for business travel. "My company reimbursed me $600 or $700 last year for overnight child care," Hewitt's McCoslin reports. "But many of our employees don't even know about the benefit."<p>--Financial-services perks. Many companies offer a credit union, which can be a great deal for employees, with low-interest-rate loans and credit cards and higher interest rates on savings accounts. Many have no-fee checking. Employers may also hook up with a bank that offers no-fee checking to employees as well as home-mortgage loans and refinancings at lower fees and with much less red tape.<p>--Concierge or errand services. "Some employers have begun to contract with an outside service to come in and pick up dry cleaning and shoe repairs and do grocery shopping," McCoslin says. <a name="NYSE:PEP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11166"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PepsiCo</b></a>, for example, offers such a service to employees at its corporate headquarters in Purchase, New York. <p>--Discounts. These can range from fleet discounts on cars to $2 off on movie tickets and $11 discounts at theme parks. Some companies offer their employees discounts on computers and the opportunity to pay for them through payroll deductions. It's just a matter of hunting them down. Paging through a policy and procedure manual of a client--CALTEX Petroleum Corp.--McCoslin discovered that it offered employees fleet discounts. "When you buy a car at the fleet price, there's a difference in both price and quality of service," she says. Yet the company didn't consider it important enough to make any sort of general announcement. "Most of these things are just word of mouth," McCoslin says.<p>--Wellness benefits. A number of companies offer free checkups, immunizations, mammograms, and blood-pressure and cholesterol testing. Some also offer a free health-club membership or a reimbursement for part of the club's fee.<p>--Career-development training and educational-assistance benefits. Often companies will pay for all or part of further education such as college or graduate school for their employees. Many of today's business leaders have M.B.A.s they got while on the job, at their employers' expense.<p>Some companies are beginning to add work/family coordinators, which is an excellent starting point for tracking down newly available benefits. Another place to look is at a company's employee assistance program, or EAP. Most big employers have them--81 percent of the firms surveyed by Hewitt Associates in 1993. Under the umbrella of the EAP, an employee might find dependent-care referrals, financial, legal, and tax advice, family and marital counseling, physical-fitness programs, stress counseling, crisis intervention, supervisory training, elder care, and help with on-the-job performance problems. <p>"Research is the key," Milley says. "If you know one of these areas will have an impact in your life this year, or that you will have a specific kind of demand, you have to start poking around to see what resources are available." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
