<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-It's Economic Indicators, Stupid</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-It's Economic Indicators, Stupid</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Is Wall Street celebrating the wrong numbers?<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Economists on wall street worried about inflation have been greeting each statistic issued by the U.S. government with great sighs of relief. Payrolls rose only 183,000 in December, way below the 215,000 expected. And in December, the producer price index actually fell 0.1 percent. No inflation in sight means no threat of a rate increase by the Federal Reserve, or so say the economists.<p>But the Fed is probably examining different numbers to get its own inflation read. That's the view of James Stack, Fed watcher and editor of The InvestTech Market Analyst. A review of Fed tightenings in 1983, '84, and '87 tells Stack that the Fed's key indicators include capacity utilization, consumer-credit demand, and the consumer sentiment and consumer confidence indexes. Those numbers paint a picture that's likely to cause a fretful Fed, Stack says.<p>Capacity utilization, for example, measures the percentage of productive capacity that is currently in use. Utilization hit 83 percent in November, up from 78.9 percent a year earlier and 77 percent during the recession's low. Rising numbers like these are signs of inflation to come.<p>Stack is now watching the consumer-confidence numbers most closely. The consumer confidence index ended 1993 on the strongest two-month bounce in its 25-year history. Preliminary consumer-sentiment numbers point to a 7-point rise in January, which would bring that index to its highest level since 1989. "Will this latest surge in consumer confidence fall back as the economists are expecting?" Stack asks. Or will it remain high and worrisome? The Fed will be watching.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

