<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Putting Age Before Booty</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Putting Age Before Booty</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Who wins, who loses with age-weighted profit-sharing<p>By Donald Jay Korn<p>This story is for small-business owners who'd like to know how to keep a greater share of company profits for themselves. It's also for small-business employees who'd like to know what their bosses might be up to. The subject: "Age weighted" profit-sharing plans.<p>For anyone who owns a small business, such plans offer a tempting arrangement. This is especially true for very small companies, such as professional practices or other businesses where one or two people generate virtually all the revenues with clerical or administrative help from their staff.<p>The owners of such businesses often don't like plain vanilla profit-sharing programs because the federal government, in its efforts to ensure the fair treatment of all employees, requires that they distribute profits based on a percentage of income that's the same for everybody, regardless of their position or level of contribution to the company. Thus, if the owners determine that 15 percent is the figure that their outfit will pay, then an $18,000-a-year employee gets $2,700 and an $80,000 employee gets $12,000. The only adjustment is a cap on the upper level of income. It makes no difference if someone makes $200,000 or even $2 million a year; the base compensation for profit-sharing purposes is capped at $150,000. This cap increases with inflation.<p>Enter the age-weighted profit-sharing plan as approved by the Internal Revenue Service last summer. The idea behind this new scheme was to allow larger contributions on behalf of older employees, because they have fewer years for their funds to compound. Age-weighted plans pass the nondiscrimination test because they are based on tomorrow's projected benefit rather than on today's contribution. That is, $5,000 put in a plan today will be worth a lot more at retirement to someone who is 30 years old than it will be to someone who's 55. <p>Naturally, the major beneficiaries of an age-weighted plan are the older participants, which in smaller companies tend to be the owners. "If you have one 50-year-old owner while all the employees are low-paid, in their 20s and 30s, a simple age-weighted plan might be a good match," says Marjorie Martin, an actuary and director of technical information services at benefits consultant Sedgwick Noble Lowndes in Roseland, New Jersey.<p>However, a plan structured this way may not delight younger principals, whose share can slip sharply. An age-weighted plan also can force employers to make a large contribution on behalf of a low-paid but elderly employee (or even cause companies to shy away from hiring older people even though they're otherwise qualified).<p>The solution to these age-weighted problems lies in a further twist called "comparability" plans, which take age-weighting a bit further. In them, the company can designate groups of employees based on virtually any objective standard it wants and then apply the age-weighting to the average age of each group. For instance, a business might designate an owner group and a group containing the other employees. If the owner group has an average age of 47.5 while the employee group averages 29, much larger contributions could go to the older group, which includes the owners. "I recently helped a professional practice restructure a plan so that the principals' contributions went from 50 percent to 83 percent of the total," says Norman Newman, a partner in the New York law firm Winston & Strawn. <p>As pleasing as this result may be for business owners, it's not the only reason for establishing a comparability plan. "Frequently, employers want to do more for their long-term, most valued employees," says James Thomas, director of retirement-plan marketing at the New England, the Boston-based insurance giant. A comparability plan might include the owners in one group, key employees in another group, non-key workers in a third group. As long as the most valued employees are older than the others, comparability plans can boost their retirement contributions.<p>Obviously, comparability plans won't work where owners are younger than other employees or if an employer wants to use the profit-sharing plan to attract talented young people. They can be more expensive than other profit-sharing plans because of the costs of having an actuarial firm calculate the age-weighted projections.<p>There's a larger potential hitch down the road. Last fall, the Labor Department proposed legislation that would eliminate age-weighted retirement plans. Today, the outcome is still anybody's guess, but plans that already exist may be grandfathered in. For small-business owners, that emphasizes the need to take advantage of one of the best tax shelters available before it's too late. On the other hand, if you are a young employee of a small business, make sure your boss doesn't see this article any time soon. <p>Look to funds that have superior five-and ten-year numbers. These are funds that have proved their ability to survive tougher times.
 <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Small Business Ownership

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
