<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-An Opportunity to Defy Gravity</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-An Opportunity to Defy Gravity</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Demand is up, but so are the yields for muni bonds<p>By Robert N. Veres<p>A peculiar thing happened when Congress raised income-tax rates last fall: The yields on tax-free municipal bonds actually went up. Way up, in fact. <p>All things being equal, this shouldn't have happened. The increased demand from investors with a new incentive to seek tax-free returns should have pushed up bond prices, causing their yields to fall. But all things weren't equal.<p>At the same time that Congress boosted tax rates, the market was growing concerned that the general decline in interest rates had bottomed out and might now begin to creep upward. Municipal borrowers rushed to refinance before this happened and flooded the market with new issues of bonds. The increased supply exceeded the increase in demand, forcing yields up and creating even better opportunities for tax-burdened investors.<p>By mid-November, taxable 20-year Treasury bonds were yielding about 6.35 percent. But high-quality munis of the same maturity were yielding up to 5.65 percent. For someone in the 40 percent tax bracket, that's equal to a taxable yield of 9.42 percent. "This is one of the few times, historically, when even people at a 15 percent tax rate should look at munis," says Judy Shine, a financial planner in Englewood, Colorado.<p>Investors who want to take advantage of today's high muni rates have several options. They can buy mutual funds that invest in munis, or they can buy bonds directly. Mutual funds probably make the most sense for people with less than $10,000 to invest. Investors in high-tax states often like funds that invest only in bonds from their state, to escape state as well as federal taxes. However, in-state funds have generally underperformed diversified funds in recent years.<p>Also beware of funds with risky portfolios (bonds with the longest maturities and/or the lowest credit quality). Although such funds were handsomely rewarded when rates were still declining, some of the highfliers recently have been taking a beating. <p>Muni-fund investors should look past the three-year rankings to funds that have superior five- and ten-year numbers. These are funds that have proved their ability to survive tougher times. Before investing in a fund, check its performance during three periods that were especially hard on munis: fourth-quarter 1993, October 1992, and the first three quarters of 1987.<p>Taxpayers who buy muni bonds directly should avoid several traps. Remember that muni income can increase taxes for people who receive Social Security. And be wary of brokers who recommend buying munis with 20-year maturities or longer. These provide higher tax-exempt yield, but if interest rates rise during the next 20 years, the value of these bonds will get hammered. <p>One good approach takes advantage of the refinancing frenzy. When a bond issue is refinanced, it is typically not paid off immediately. Instead, the issuer "retires" the old debt by purchasing Treasury bonds to be held until the bond is paid off, also known as the call date, removing the credit risk entirely. The old issue becomes AAA-rated short-term paper, with a high coupon rate. <p>Because these bonds are priced above their par value, many investors avoid them. This creates bargains for those investors who understand their appeal. "Retail consumers don't like to pay 109 cents on the dollar for a bond," says Ray Kuipers, who runs the bond-trading desk at Nathan & Lewis Securities in New York. "So you can usually get a better price and more bang for the buck."<p>The bang, in this case, is tax-exempt yield. Recently, Bear, Stearns in New York was offering bonds issued by the New Jersey Health Care Authority, originally paying 8.38 percent a year, for a price of 115.5. The bonds are now prerefunded, with a maturity of a little over four years at a price of 102. That means investors who bought them on the recent offering got a current yield of 7.25 percent and a yield to maturity of 4.25 percent. Compare this with the 4.05 percent annual yields typical for five-year munis priced at par. <p>These refinancings won't go on forever. Nor, alas, will today's low interest rates. Opportunistic investors will act quickly.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
