<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Concealing the Conflicts</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Concealing the Conflicts</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						  
Why some financial planners claim to be both fee-only and commission-based<p>
By Jill Andresky Fraser<p>
How do you pay your financial planner? Sometimes it's not easy to tell. Labels such as "fee only," "fee offset" and "fee and commission" obscure rather than reveal how planners earn their livelihoods. For example, "fee based" refers to a commission planner without ever using the "C" word.<p>
The result of this confusion? People are probably paying more than they should and possibly getting bad advice. "If people don't understand a planner's compensation structure," warns Barbara Roper, director of investor protection at the Washington-based Consumer Federation of America, "they can't assess whether his or her recommendations are really independent--the way they would be from a true fee-only planner--or whether they might have been influenced by commissions or other payments." <p>
Some planners operate two practices, one fee-only and the other commission-based (labels vary, but that's what they mean). In some rare cases planners hide those connections--which is illegal. But even when they disclose both types of practices to their clients, an important question arises: Does this arrangement reduce the conflicts of interest that commissions entail or merely mask them?<p>
The National Association of Personal Financial Advisors, a professional organization for fee-only financial planners, believes that operating two kinds of practices simply masks the conflicts. "Under our definition, a fee-only planner is compensated solely by the client," explains Andrew Hudick, a Roanoke, Virginia, planner who is NAPFA's vice president of membership. "There are a lot of people out there who call themselves fee-only planners but cannot qualify for membership in NAPFA because they also operate affiliate brokerage or retirement-planning businesses where they receive commissions."<p>
How do these combined practices work? Jeffrey Franklin runs such a practice in New York City, which he says he has structured "so that there is a fee-only side that does financial planning for a fee and a fee-and-commission-based practice." As a commission-based planner, he sells insurance and investments, largely mutual funds. "In my mind there's a Chinese wall between planning and implementation," he explains, using the industry euphemism for distinguishing between giving advice and selling products. "You can use one person to do both or you can use two people to do both, and I'll work either way."<p>
Both Franklin and NAPFA's Hudick are diligent about explaining their compensation structures so clients understand what they're paying for. Others aren't so diligent.<p>
"People who want to shave the edges and get away with confusing clients can do so," says Ellyn Brown, a professor at the University of Maryland Law School.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  
		<a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  
		<a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  
		<a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b><p>
		<font size=-1><i>&copy; 1996 Capital Publishing Limited
