<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Q&A</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Q&A</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1993
Worth magazine/Q&A<p>Q&A<p>Edited by Bob Clark<p>Q: I am very interested in real estate investing, but I am confused on a couple of issues. Can you tell me about the tax-free exchange of appreciated property: Is it possible, for instance, to swap investment real estate for publicly held shares of a real estate investment trust (REIT) or some holding without incurring a taxable event?<p>
A: The short answer is no; you can't make a tax-free swap of investment real estate for shares in an REIT. But you can make a tax-free swap of one investment property for another investment property. Tax on the gain is postponed until you subsequently sell or exchange the new property.<p>Basically, for the exchange to qualify as tax-free, your current property must be traded for property of a "like kind." The exchange can't be done for an immediate resale, and you can't exchange U.S. real estate for foreign real estate.<p>It may appear simple, but the law in this area is very complicated. Investors shouldn't attempt a tax-free exchange without the advice of an experienced real estate tax attorney.<p>
Q: I've heard that Bill Clinton's new tax bill is more beneficial to those who donate appreciated assets, like stocks, to charity. If this is so, what are the benefits?<p>A: You heard right. Under the new tax bill, upper-bracket taxpayers who give a lot will have more to feel good about. For one thing, the higher marginal tax rates imposed on the so-called rich (loosely defined as anyone who makes more than a member of Congress) mean that they get a higher tax deduction for charitable donations. But the big news involves charity-minded taxpayers affected by the onerous alternative minimum tax (AMT). <p>Under the old tax law, people who made a donation of property that had appreciated well beyond its original cost risked losing a portion of the tax benefit. This was because, under the AMT, some of the property's appreciation had to be added back to the taxpayer's net income. Under the new law, gifts of appreciated property that have been held for one year or more are excluded from AMT calculations. This is good news both to those who want to make large donations and to the charities who will receive them.<p>
Q: There's been a lot of hoopla about investing in international stock funds, but I haven't seen much on foreign bond funds. Should a fixed-income investor like myself consider the global market? <p>A: For the past three years international bond funds have underperformed almost all categories of U.S. bond funds. But there are compelling reasons for income-oriented investors who have traditionally shied away from foreign bond funds to take a look at them now. <p>Today the U.S. has the lowest bond yields of all the world's major economies, except Japan. At the end of August, ten-year U.S. Treasurys were yielding 5.5 percent against 8.8 percent in Norway, 7.5 percent in Sweden, and 9.6 percent in Italy. Even in the U.K., where interest rates have fallen sharply, ten-year government bonds yield 6.8 percent.<p>Higher yields abroad are not unusual. In the last 30 years, foreign bonds have yielded 3 percent more on average each year than their U.S. counterparts.<p>Interest rates are falling in major European countries as central banks ease credit to stimulate flagging economies. That opens the way to the same sort of capital gains that bond investors reaped in the U.S. earlier this year. Although European rates have already dropped significantly in the past two years, many market strategists think rates could continue to drop in 1994. Investors interested in capitalizing on any further decline in European rates can do so by investing in one of the many global bond funds that have recently come to market. <p>In addition to interest-rate risks, investors in foreign bonds must accept the risk that weakening foreign currencies can wipe out some or all of the earnings made in foreign bond markets. As last year's turmoil in Europe showed, currency movements can play havoc with the total returns on foreign bonds. <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>'s Short-Term Global B fund, for example, lost 3.3 percent in 1992, largely due to currency changes. Many funds now hedge against adverse currency movements, though the cost of such hedging reduces investment income. But because bond markets around the world move in different directions at different times, the returns on a diversified global portfolio should outweigh the risks. <p>
Q: I would like to know if it's really a good idea to keep all my cash and securities in my brokerage account, what they call the "street name," as most brokers suggest. Also, how safe are large accounts ($500,000 to $2.5 million) that are said to be covered by the firm's insurance?<p>A: If a brokerage firm holds an investor's certificates, they may be held in either the investor's name or in the name of the firm, known as the street name. If your stocks are held in your firm's name, the brokerage shows up on the list of the corporation's shareholders, even though you are the actual owner.<p>Having a brokerage firm hold your stock makes it easier to sell your shares in a hurry. It is also the only way to borrow against your shares. But the primary advantage to having the broker hold your securities in a street-name account is that the firm takes responsibility for safeguarding them. All firms are insured against loss of the certificates. <p>But don't confuse insurance against certificate loss with insurance against market loss. The value of Wang Labs stock held in street name, for example, is chump change today, even though it is still insured against theft or loss by brokers. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, International Economy, Bond Investing, Real Estate Investing, Taxation, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
