<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Excess Baggage</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Excess Baggage</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
How do your parents affect the way you think about money?<p>By Mary Rowland<p>I am a schizophrenic where money is concerned, and I know precisely why. Growing up in rural Minnesota, my father had some of the fanciest cars, trucks, and equipment around. Budgeting, saving, investing, were not in his vocabulary, and lack of money never stopped him from buying or doing things. My mom, on the other hand, was frugal from childhood. She didn't spend money on herself, and she derived no enjoyment from the things that money could buy.<p>Not surprisingly, growing up with parents that were such polar opposites had an effect on me. As might be expected, given these conflicting genes, I developed something of a confused money mind-set. Although it's easy to understand, it is nonetheless difficult to shake off. Sometimes I refuse to spend money on things I need, like new socks or underwear. Sometimes I splurge and spend what I don't have. And then I lie awake at night and fret about it. <p>Feeling neutral about money comes hard. Most purchases have two prices--one financial, one emotional. And psychologists say that most of our money attitudes, values, and phobias are either adopted from our parents or developed as a rejection of our parents' ideas. "There are patterns in our thinking about money that go way back to the nursery," says Linda Barbanel, a New York psychologist who specializes in money issues and is the author of Piggybank to Credit Card: Teach Your Child the Financial Facts of Life, due out in February from Crown. "As a child, you hear and assimilate attitudes about money before you really understand them."<p>For those with similar or other money problems inherited from well-meaning parents,take heart.There is a strong case to be made for trying to work things through, and yes, it can be done. Feeling comfortable with money is an essential ingredient to a contented life. <p>Experts say that most people have several dysfunctional areas. If you're head over heels in debt, you know that's a problem. But many money problems are more subtle; in fact, they're almost subliminal. Take me, for example. I am financially responsible. I have life and disability insurance, a retirement account, and college accounts for the kids. I know how to pick a good mutual fund. I am a risk taker. But spending money gives me a headache. On vacations I find myself compulsively trying to create some type of money-to-fun index. How much are we spending? Are we having $2,500 worth of fun yet? Shop till I drop? Buying school clothes, going out to dinner, or buying a pair of shoes can be agonizing for me.<p>Fortunately, there are solutions to even the most deeply rooted money misconduct, and they don't require years of therapy. First we need to spend some time thinking about how our parents dealt with money, how it has affected us, and whether we are happy with the result. "As adults, it's very important that we think about what our parents taught us and what we believe," says Esther Berger, author of Money Smart: Secrets Women Need to Know About Money (Simon & Schuster). "We all need to evaluate where our attitudes come from, what shaped them, and where we are going today--to separate out money and emotions and learn to deal with money on a logical plane." <p>Not only is this self-examination good for your soul, it is also good for your kids' souls. After all, most of us don't want to pass on our own dysfunctional money attitudes to our inheritors as we would the antique silver. "People should be willing to work through them and solve this now," Berger says. "Some of the crazy things that guide our money decisions as adults can have very negative repercussions for our children.'' No sense continuing the chain.<p>Ideally, the experts say, parents teach their children to save some money, invest wisely, pay the bills, spend a little on enjoyment, give something to charity, and never think about what they don't have. "When children are lucky, money is treated just as a medium to obtain what is necessary or what is pleasurable, and there is some sense of balance in what should be saved and what should be spent," says Dr. Mio Fredland, a New York child and adolescent psychiatrist. But that is an ideal too few parents can realize. <p>Financial dysfunctionality need not be terminal, however. Here are some examples of how professionals have used their parents' money outlook--dysfunctional or not--to their own advantage:<p>~~ Berger, who is a first vice president at PaineWebber, grew up in a wealthy Cleveland family. She bought into much of what she learned at home. "To a large extent, my parents drew up the yardsticks for me," she says. "Much of what I attach financial value to is the same as my parents." Although she now lives in Beverly Hills, she still applies her Cleveland mentality to her purchases. Before spending money, Berger asks herself whether something is "worth it." Flying first class, $100 dinners, and Ray-Ban sunglasses are not worth it. "I'd rather eat pizza," she says. <p>Berger has picked up some of her parents' peccadillos as well. "My dad always bought very, very good shoes," she says. "He always thought a well-dressed man was judged by his shoes." As a result, shoes are one thing Berger refuses to skimp on. <p>Like her parents, she hates to be in debt. So she makes extra mortgage payments periodically to bring her balance down, even though she could probably find better, more productive places to invest that money. <p>But Berger has modified, somewhat, the behavior she learned as a child. Because she is half of a two-income household and the mother of three sons, she's tossed out the aspects of her parents' frugality that involve time-consuming bargain hunts. To Berger, time is more precious than that. "My mother will go 30 miles out of her way to save one dollar on a pair of slippers," Berger says. For the daughter, that doesn't work. "I blend the messages I got as a young child with what works for me as an adult," she says. <p>~~ Dr. Danella Schiffer, an industrial psychologist who grew up in New York City, also adopted many of her family's money values. But then she tinkered with the formula to make her life a little more pleasurable. Her parents, for example, never bought anything on credit. Schiffer uses a credit card, but for convenience only. She has never paid interest on anything but a mortgage.<p>On the other hand, she refuses to adopt the same parsimony that dictated her parents' spending. "My parents always bought the bottom of the line on everything," Schiffer says. Although she won't buy until she has the cash, when she has it, she goes first class. Her car has plush leather seats. In 1975, she bought eight acres of land in Connecticut and built a home that has been featured in House Beautiful. She enjoys spending money on landscaping and is willing to hire artisans to copy museum pieces that she loves--as long as she can pay with cash.<p>~~ Violet P. Woodhouse rejected nearly everything she learned about money from her foster parents. She grew up on an Alaska farm, a hardscrabble life with little money for pleasure. "I always felt like I was an alien," she says. "I never belonged with those people." Woodhouse knew that farming--and scraping by--was not for her. "I understood somewhere early on that people did make money and that that wasn't how you did it," she says. Woodhouse became a financial planner and then, in her early 30s, decided to go to law school. Today she specializes in family law and financial planning for divorce.<p>Woodhouse says that her parents, like most, never discussed money with her. As a result, in her adult life she had to unlearn the habit of feeling squeamish about discussing money with people hired to work for her. "How many people ask their life insurance salesman how much commission he's making?" asks Woodhouse, who is the author of Divorce and Money (Nolo Press). Most of Woodhouses's clients will ask her: What is your hourly rate? What is your retainer? "But they just don't go beyond that," she says. "Most people don't understand that everything is negotiable. Lawyers need business, and there's a lot you can do to negotiate." <p>Woodhouse is now exceedingly up-front in money discussions. When she and her husband remodeled their house recently, they asked the contractor for a rundown on prices of all the materials as well as what he was making on the job. "He didn't like it," she says. "But that's the way I do business."<p>For many people the money problems inherited from parents are more deep-seated and difficult to change. Psychologist Schiffer, who evaluates top executives to determine their suitability for job openings and promotions, says she sees many clients who come from dysfunctional families. If the parents had problems with gambling, alcohol, or mental illness and there was little money for necessities, the children are often determined, to a fault, to move in the opposite direction. "They become very conservative, cautious people who are afraid to make a misstep lest they end up like their parents," she says. One of the problems for people who grow up in such households is that they become too risk averse, which can then impede their career development. It is also difficult for them to find pleasure in spending money on themselves.<p>Even more damaging are parents who use money as a means of control. They are willing to buy expensive things for their children, but only if the things reflect well on them. When the child chooses something for himself, they are unwilling to pay for it.<p>Another trick is to use money as a reward for good behavior or obedience. The effects of this behavior can be very long lasting. Says child psychologist Fredland: "This creates a child who is never able to completely grow up, because they feel forever that they need to receive money in order to feel that they're good."<p>Fredland sees a number of patients who have money-related problems. "It's never the only problem," she says. "But it can be destructive." For example, one woman grew up with a mother who bought her very expensive, conventional clothes for occasions that were important to the mother. "The mother was extremely interested in having her children perform well socially," Fredland says. But when the daughter wanted money for clothes of her own choosing, she got a quick turndown. "When the girl wanted something teenage and funky, the mother said no," Fredland says. <p>As an adult, the daughter got head over heels in debt. "She overloaded her credit cards and got into trouble," Fredland says. "When she bought clothes, she was giving herself a present and she was rebelling at the same time. She got into terrible trouble for it."<p>Many children who grow up with serious money struggles see money as good or bad; magic or evil. They reward or punish themselves by buying or not buying something. If they are good, they can buy a treat. If they are bad, they must do without. This is the kind of conflict that can require counseling. "One of the things I do when I meet clients is to have them stop and think about their ideas about money," says Cecily Maton, a financial planner in Chicago who specializes in the finances of people who divorce. "If people reward themselves with a spending spree, they need a psychologist, not a financial planner."<p>But most of us can work through these issues ourselves, come to a better understanding of why we react to money as we do, change the things we don't like, and keep from passing them on to our kids. In his 1979 book, Kids and Cash, now out of print, Ken Davis, a stockbroker, wrote: "Money must be recognized as a useful tool, not an object to be sought for its own sake. Recognition by a child that money has no value except in exchange for other things they want or need is important to getting the proper perspective on how money should fit into their lives."<p>Davis suggests that parents help their kids feel comfortable about money; that they avoid attributing magic or evil characteristics to it; that they help their children understand that money itself should not be a goal. "If you spend every dime before it is earned, it will be more difficult to teach your kids to save," he says. "If you save every dime except what is needed for the bare essentials, your kids may learn to save but might never learn how to enjoy what they accumulate." <p>As in other aspects of life, it's balance that we're after. Money is a necessary tool that we must learn to use dispassionately. Once we've accomplished that, we need to teach our kids the very same lesson.<p>Mary Rowland, a columnist for the New York Times, writes about personal finance from New York City. <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
