<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-A Worth Notes Guide to the Investment Classics</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-A Worth Notes Guide to the Investment Classics</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Four up on Wall Street:  Speed-reading the legends<p>By Curtis Hartman<p>Each fall brings its flood of new investment books. Each spring flushes most of them out again--as soon as investors figure out that they won't get so rich in the next depression that they can retire at age 35 to swim with the sharks and not get eaten.<p>Still there are a handful of books about investment and money management that have lasted. These are the vaunted tomes containing the wisdom, knowledge, and advice every investor needs.<p>They are also, for the most part, extremely boring. <p>You didn't read these books in college. They stared at you through business school, and you've been promising yourself you'll get to security analysis--just as soon as you finish the latest Tom Clancy doorstop.<p>That's where we come in. Like the folks at cliffs notes, whose yellow-and-black-covered summaries have spared generations of students from actually reading middlemarch, worth has boiled down to their essentials four of the most-cited investment classics. <p>We won't go so far as to suggest that you substitute our summaries for the real thing. But we hope that these crib sheets will at least prepare 
you for tomorrow's call to your broker. <p>
Thesis:
Buy low, sell high. The only way to consistently make money is to find stocks with value that the market has not recognized. Over the long term, the market will catch on, and the price of the stock will go up. This requires rigorous statistical analysis; anything less is mere speculation.<p><p>1. SECURITY ANALYSIS BY BENJAMIN GRAHAM AND DAVID DODD
Impact:
security analysis (mcgraw-hill) has been the training manual for professional investors for half a century, and it remains the bible for most practitioners today. Disciples include Sir John Templeton and Warren Buffett, both of whom studied under Benjamin Graham. In general, value stocks--that is, stocks that are priced by the market for less than they'd be worth if the company were liquidated--do worse in fat times and better in lean. From 1980 to '83, for example, value stocks returned 19.9 percent compared with 14.7 percent for growth stocks (that is, stocks that are valued by anticipating their future earnings) and 17 percent for the S&P 500. But between '89 and '91 growth stocks were stronger, returning 20.8 percent to the S&P's 18.5 percent and value stocks' 13.5 percent. In 1992 and the first half of 1993, value stocks have, once again, been in fashion, notching a 14.6 percent gain against the S&P's 8.4 percent and growth stocks' 4.9 percent.<p>Authors:
Graham has been described by investment counselor and writer John Train as "this century's (and perhaps history's) most important thinker on applied portfolio investment." Though he was scornful of speculation, he made his biggest score on a speculative stock play. Sober and magisterial on the page, Graham, a fund manager and a part-time professor at the Columbia School of Business Administration, was messier in his personal life. He was married three times and was once described as leaping "from blonde to blonde like an Alpine goat springing from peak to peak." The same year Security Analysis was published, he wrote Baby Pompadour, a Broadway play that closed after four performances.<p>Graham had been in the money business 13 years when, in 1928, he decided to teach a night class at Columbia to help him get his thoughts together. In 1934, Security Analysis was published, written with David Dodd, a Columbia colleague. Dodd remained true to the precepts of Security Analysis all his life, writing the foreword to the fifth edition shortly before his death in 1988, but Graham disavowed the method in his later years, complaining that it was too much work. He retired to Aix-la-Provence, where he lived with his son's former mistress until his death at 82.<p>Summary:
"Successful common stock investment extends over many years and usually involves many separate commitments," Graham and Dodd warn. To keep principal safe while earning a satisfactory return, the security analyst needs a discipline built on stringent standards and the most technically sophisticated statistical methods available.<p>Because the market is more irrational than it is efficient, the price of a stock only occasionally coincides with the stock's intrinsic value. The goal is to buy stocks when they are priced below intrinsic value and sell when they are priced above it. <p>To that end, the analyst seeks not to predict the future but to understand, and quantify, the financial present. This is not glamorous work. Security analysis focuses on determing the intrinsic value of a security, regardless of its price, by focusing on the company's past perfomance, not on projected earnings (impossible to predict, given the way outside factors can affect stock prices). Instead, analysts pore over financial statements--particularly balance sheets--to measure asset value, cash flow, and earnings. Value is what counts. Not price. Not the nature of a company's business.Just the numbers.<p>Advice:
So what does an analyst look for in determining intrinsic value? A low ratio of price to real earnings--measured as dividends paid plus increase in net assets per share--is often a strong indicator of value. But the true "margin of safety" comes when an analyst can identify the difference between a company's market capitalization and what it would be worth were it broken into parts and sold. Over the long run the market will at least be efficient enough to recognize the imbalance and push up prices. <p>Each new edition of Graham and Dodd has introduced ever more detailed techniques to address the realities of an increasingly complicated financial world. But the basic tenets of security analysis have stayed the same:  "To sustain the traditional Graham and Dodd respect for facts, to distinguish general accomplishments from hopes and expectations, and to reach sound principles of valuation," as Dodd wrote before his death.<p>Caveat:
Not only is the book slow going, but following all of Graham and Dodd's techniques could eat up an entire lifetime. Most of today's so-called value investors don't bother. While value investing has become a growth industry, with databases to spew out ratios and newsletters to offer picks, the sheer number of investors following this discipline has bid most of what Graham and Dodd would have called value out of the market. Today value investors usually look for stocks that are merely less overvalued than the rest of the market.<p><p>2. A RANDOM WALK DOWN WALL STREET BY BURTON G. MALKEIL<p>Thesis:
You can't beat the market with active trading over the long term. No one can--not a broker, not an analyst, not a fund manager--because no one can predict the future. In what has become an inspiration to a generation of business journalists, Malkiel theorized that "a blindfolded monkey throwing darts at a newspaper's financial pages could select a portfolio that would do just as well as one carefully selected by the experts." And a prudent individual could do better still by holding a diversified portfolio over the long term.<p>Impact:
random walk (W.W. Norton), which synthesizes a handful of academic theories about why the pros can't beat Wall Street, offers laymen a concise explanation of why they could do as well playing the market as the people they pay to manage their money. For obvious reasons, brokers hated this book when it came out in 1973. And they hate it today.<p>Author:
For 35 years malkiel has traveled through the money business, academia, and government, as an investment banker at Smith Barney, a director of the Vanguard Funds, a governor of the American StockExchange, chairman of the Princeton economics department, and dean of the Yale School of Organization and Management. From 1975 to 1977 he served on President Ford's Council of Economic Advisors. <p>Summary:
Most professional investors depend on one of two approaches to the market, Malkiel argues--one based on logic, one based on psychology.<p>The former, the "firm foundation" theory, holds that each stock has a firm anchor of intrinsic value, which can be determined through careful analysis of the company's current position and future prospects for earnings, growth, and income. <p>The latter, the "castle in the air" theory practiced today by the so-called technicians, or chartists, ignores intrinsic value. The chartists proceed under the assumption that what matters is the price people will pay for a stock, not what it is really worth. By studying past price and volume information, they attempt to measure and predict the future movement of the crowd.<p>Malkiel dismisses them both.<p>The fundamental problem with analysis, he says, is that "forecasting the future is inherently a very treacherous occupation." The raw information may be wrong or the analysis faulty. Or the market may disagree, paying a higher multiple for growth today and value tomorrow, depending on the temper of the crowd. "God Almighty doesn't know the proper price-to-earnings multiple for a common stock," he says.<p>If you think you see an undervalued stock, by Malkiel's definition, you are wrong: The market, he says, is an efficient pricing mechanism. The price of a stock perfectly reflects the crowd's attitudes toward that company. If people think a price will go to $40 tomorrow, it will go to $40 today.<p>Malkiel is even more scornful of the chartists. He compares them to the alchemists and diviners of a more innocent age, as they try to discover trends in their detailed, often arcane readings of the charts. Bunk, Malkiel insists. A chartist could find patterns in the toss of a coin 100 times, but he still couldn't predict what would happen on the 101st toss. Stock prices, like a coin toss, move in a random walk. He doesn't deny that the temper of the crowd influences prices, as do value and earnings--but not in ways that a professional can predict, or an individual can profit from, particularly after commissions and fees.<p>Advice:
The way to profit is to understand, and manage, the two kinds of risk--the risk that something will happen to an individual company and the risk that something will happen to the market as a whole. Investors can cut potential losses by putting together a basket of 20 or more stocks and holding them over the long term. The market as a whole will always go up and down, but investors can eliminate individual company risk by constructing a portfolio of stocks whose risks offset each other. A well-constructed portfolio will have a higher return per unit of risk than an investor would gain from simply investing in a single stock.<p>Caveat:
In a perfect world, all stocks would be perfectly priced. But there are always people who will see something or know something that others don't. There's an old joke about the professor of investing--a random walker--who spied a ten-dollar bill on the sidewalk. He didn't pick it up: According to efficient market theory, it couldn't be there.<p><p>3. REMINISCENCES OF A STOCK OPERATOR BY EDWIN LEFEVRE<p>Thesis:
There are two kinds of people in the mar-ket--the operator and the sucker. The smart can feast, if they watch the tape, but everyone else gets eaten.<p>Impact:
Although reminiscences, a fictionalized biography of Jesse Livermore, a celebrated jazz-age speculator, was first published some 60 years ago, its take on crowd psychology and market timing is as timely as last summer's frenzy on the foreign exchange markets. Livermore, whom Lefevre renames Larry Livingston, won and lost millions over the decades leading up to the crash of '29, speculating for the sheer joy of it: commodities or stocks, long or short, it didn't really matter. Usually he worked alone, but he'd play for a group, too, running up stock prices so that insiders could score.<p>In 1925, two years after the novel was published, Livermore pulled his greatest coup, making some $10 million trading grain futures in a few months. In 1929 he was widely blamed for causing the crash with his short selling and was forced to make a public denial and to hire a bodyguard for protection against angry crowds.<p>Margin requirements and SEC regulations may have changed how the game is played, but the nature of the players is the same--and always will be, according to "Livingston." His trading advice, based on the psychology of the bull and the bear, still rings true, while his explanation of the mechanics of insider trading and price manipulation is loaded with hands-on tips.<p>Author:
Trained as a mining engineer at lLehigh University, Edwin Lefevre became a journalist at 19, producing eight books during his 53-year writing career. Only Reminiscences, reviewed as nonfiction in the New York Times when it was published, remains in print. <p>Summary:
Larry Lvingston goes to work at 14, just out of grammar school, as a quotation boy in a stock brokerage office in Boston. He's always been good with arithmetic, and as he starts watching the board, he finds that he can predict which way the numbers will go. But he never actually makes a play himself until another office boy asks him to go in on a tip with him--they put $5 on Burlington in a bucket shop; his share of the profit is $3.12.<p>That is the start of his career at the bucket shops, where any chump with a dollar or two can play against the tape, like betting at the race track. Livingston does well enough to quit his job. When he shows his mother his first $1,000, her jaw drops--but by the time he turns 20, his stake is ten times that. They call him "the boy plunger" at the bucket shops. At 21 he moves to New York and learns how to speculate big-time. Wall Street opens his eyes. He thinks he is smart because he can predict the ticker's turns, but that isn't enough, and he goes bust. He goes to St. Louis and plays the bucket shops there until they run him out. His first big break comes with Union Pacific in 1906. Everyone is buying UP, so he decides to sell and shorts 3,000 shares in a rising market. When the stock goes up, he shorts another 2,000 shares. Then an earthquake hits San Francisco, where UP has its terminus--but the price still doesn't fall. So Livingston doubles up, then doubles up again. He clears $250,000 when the price breaks.<p>Livingston goes on to corner the cotton market. He has a $1 million day during the bull run just prior to World War I. He knows all the great Wall Street personalities and most of the suckers, too.Though he thinks tips are for chumps, he takes them occasionally, to be polite. What counts is understanding how things work.<p>Livingston is bullish in the bear markets and bearish with the bulls. He looks for the big swing. If one of his friends needs a price manipulated for a group of insiders, he takes care of it. You can always move a price up, he says, if you've got the line to run out. The key is to protect yourself by juggling shorts and longs, selling big on the way down. <p>Advice:
Only a sucker gambles on the market. a speculator bets on what he thinks and knows. It's a tough business; you have to be on the job all the time, or you won't have one. Livingston goes broke several times. But he comes back. Losing it all teaches you what not to do. <p>Caveat:
Jesse Lvermore, the real Larry Lvingston, went broke for the fourth and final time in 1934 and was never able to raise a stake again. He tried setting up as an investment advisor in New York and failed; then he tried writing a book explaining his system and failed again. In 1940 he shot himself in the men's room of New York's Sherry-Netherland Hotel.<p><p>4. EXTRORDINARY POPULAR DELUSIONS AND THE MADNESS OF CROWDS BY CHARLES MACKAY<p>Thesis:
"How easily the masses have been led astray," Charles Mackay laments. As individuals we are endowed with God-given reason. But in a crowd, judgment is swept away by unreasoning desire.<p>Impact:
First published in 1841, extraordinary Popular Delusions (Harmony Books) remains the most cited, and least followed, investment book in print, particularly sobering in light of the current bull market. Andrew Tobias, who wrote the foreword for the 1980 edition, called it the greatest money book ever written. Financier Bernard Baruch said in a foreword to the 1932 edition that the book had saved him millions.<p>Politics junkies will relish the section on the delusional scheme to get rid of the 18th century French national debt, while IPO aficionados can savor the tale of insider speculation in new issues in England in the 1720s. The shortest and most famous chapter, "The Tulipomania," about the bidding up of tulip-bulb prices in Amsterdam in the 1630s, has all but become a cliche, used to explain everything from the original Ponzi scheme to 1990's "midsummer madness" in bank stocks.<p>Author:
In syntax and point of view, mackay's as conservative as William Buckley, but he shares P.J. O'Rourke's eye for whimsical detail, delighting in oddities like the French hunchback who rented out his hump as a movable writing desk for speculators or the Dutch merchant sailor who, at the height of the tulipomania, mistook a tulip bulb for an onion and ate it for breakfast--only to wind up in jail, having consumed in two bites enough capital to build, equip, and man an entire merchant ship.<p>Summary:
It would take 50 volumes to chronicle all the instances of crowd madness and "moral contagion," Mackay says, but in 16 chapters he manages to detail everything from witch-hunting to alchemy, the Crusades, dueling, and the passion for slow poisons in Italy. Each chapter instructs, in its own didactic way, but only the first three are must-reads.<p>The first chapter introduces John Law, the wandering Scotsman whose "Mississippi scheme" beggared the French under Louis XIV. Law's plan--to harvest the riches of Louisiana while simultaneously wiping out the French national debt--never made any sense. But would-be buyers mobbed Law in the street and in his Paris home, pleading for shares, while stock jobbers ran a superheated aftermarket, sending prices soaring. The result was predictable: first the crash, then mass penury.<p>John Law at least believed in his scheme. The following year in London, when a group of well-connected British merchants duplicated Law's venture, they added price manipulation to the mix. Incorporating themselves as the South-Sea Company, they proposed to take over Britain's national debt with the proceeds from the fortune to be made trading with Spanish America. No one mentioned that the king of Spain had limited English trade there to one heavily taxed vessel a year. "The English commenced their career of extravagance somewhat later than the French," Mackay writes. "But as soon as the delirium seized them, they were determined not to be outdone." In early 1720, when Parliament voted to sell the country's national debt to the South-Sea company, share prices shot from 100 pounds to 130 and on up to 300. In April, with no revenues, nor even any legitimate prospects, the company offered another 1.5 million shares. They sold in an hour and a half and were trading at 550 by May. An entire market was born, and some 100 similar "bubble" ventures launched, one "for trading in hair," another "for carrying on an undertaking of great advantage, but nobody to know what it is." The frenzy lasted for eight months. In August, with shares up to 1,000, word leaked out that some of the directors were selling out. Prices dropped to 700. Then 400. Then 135.<p>Mackay is toughest on the Dutch, who in the 1630s became caught up in a speculative fever over tulip prices. By 1636, when 80 florins would buy a good suit, a single bulb could cost 2,500 florins or more. When two Semper Augustus bulbs, the rarest in the country, came on the market, one fetched 12 acres of land, the other 4,600 florins, a new carriage, two gray horses, and a set of leather harnesses.<p>"Everyone imagined that the passion for tulips would last forever," Mackay notes drily. But it didn't. As always, some of the rich saw the crash coming and got out early, but "many a representative of a noble line saw the fortunes of his house ruined beyond redemption." And the crowd, of course, got creamed.<p>In his 1932 foreword--written when the Dow was at 41, down from a precrash high of 381--BernardBaruch argued that there is only one way to avoid getting trapped in the grip of a popular delusion: When you see a market taking off, remind yourself that "two and two still make four."<p>Then again, for the cynical, disciplined investor, there's nothing quite so profitable as a good popular delusion.<p>
Worth Extra Credit:
Barbarians at the Gate
by Bryan Burrough  and John Helyar
This fast-paced novelistic account of the $28 million RJR leveraged buyout was a best-seller and the best business book of the '80s; its description of how ego and avarice drove the deal that came to symbolize the excesses of the decade alternately fascinates and appalls. If a fiction writer had created the characters, no one would have believed them. Meet F. Ross Johnson, the larger-than-life RJR CEO, who tried to make a fortune bribing his board to let him take the company private, cheap, and the folks who tried to help him, like Shearson head Peter Cohen, a loutish overachiever, and his boss James Robinson III, married to the putative PR whiz Linda Robinson. And Henry Kravis, the paranoid deal-maker who won the costly battle.<p>
The Money Game
by "Adam Smith"
During the '60s, the identity of the writer behind the pseudonym Adam Smith was a topic of speculation on Wall Street. Of course, now we know who Adam Smith is: George J.W. Goodman, former editor of Institutional Investor and the host of the PBS show Adam Smith's Money World. Smith/Goodman's take was that among the biggest players, making money was not the goal.Being in the game was what mattered. Money was just a way of keeping score. His central observation--"if you don't know who you are, the stock market is an expensive place to find out"--has become axiomatic.<p>
Where Are The Customers' Yachts?
by Fred Schwed Jr.
It's long been a cliche that WallStreet has a river at one end and a graveyard at the other. But Schwed points out that that omits "the kindergarten in the middle." The title of Schwed's 1940 book comes from the joke about the rube who visited the harbor. "There are the bankers' yachts," his guide told him. "And there are the brokers' yachts."<p>"But where," the rube asked, "are the customers' yachts?"<p>Writers such as Jane Bryant Quinn have acknowledged their debt to Schwed and his deadly take on the day-to-day workings of investors and brokers. Schwed particularly skewers the crowd at its most bullish and bearish extremes. "When the market is doing well and your friends and neighbors are buying stock," he advises, "sell and put your money in a bank. The market will go higher--maybe quite a bit higher. Ignore it.<p>"Eventually there will be a recession. When it gets so bad as to arouse the politicians to make speeches, take your money out of the bank and buy stock. The market will go lower--maybe quite a bit lower. Ignore it.<p>"This investment advice always works," he says, "but the procedure is so difficult that almost no one can do it."<p>
The Money Masters
by John Train
Voyeurs, as well as anyone interested in the flesh-and-blood people behind the classic strategies, will find these nine profiles compelling. Ben Graham is in here, as is T.Rowe Price, who made a fortune with growth stocks, and Stanley Kroll, titan of the commodities market. In a 1989 sequel, imaginatively titled The New Money Masters, Train gives the same treatment to eight '80s luminaries, among them Jim Rogers, Peter Lynch, Michael Steinhardt, and John Neff.<p>
An Investor's Anthology
Edited by Charles D. Ellis
This is the investment dilettante's dream, mining everything from textbooks and speeches to Playboy magazine and Berkshire Hathaway annual reports. Ellis has chosen 84 brief excerpts to illustrate "the most interesting ideas and concepts from the literature of investing." Keep it by your bedside for leisure time--slip into T. Rowe Price on "How to Pick a Growth Stock" on Friday night, argue with Maynard Keynes about "The State of Long Term Expectation" on Saturday, and spend Sunday with Sidney Homer learning "How (Not) to Explain the Bond Market to Your Wife." The longest piece, Graham and Dodd "On Intrinsic Value," is only 28 pages. The shortest, "The Market and Prices," by Adam Smith, is barely two pages long.<p>
Curtis Hartman is a senior editor at Worth.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Publishing Industry<p>

