	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Road Test: Jeep Grand Cherokee</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
A classy all-around car that happens to be a truck<p>By Stephan Wilkinson<p>Women love this car. Anna Quindlen begged for one in the New York Times. My wife, glaring over the roofs of lesser vehicles, became Parnelli Jones when she drove it, spiking its bluff prow high into the rearview mirror of every <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyota</b></a> that dared impede her. My teenage daughter's cutest friend lost control when I pulled up in front of the high school. "Oh. My. GOD," she said. "You've got a Jeep Grand Cherokee Laredo." (A good suburbanite-in-training, she even knew the model and trimline.)<p>In the mornings, the narrow two-lanes up here in the Hudson River Highlands turn into the Ardennes, as columns of mommies in fat-tired four-wheel-drive Cherokees rumble toward school bus stops like Patton's tanks probing for von Rundstedt. <p>You know what? They're on to something. I hate pickups, have no truck with sport-utility vehicles, and can't imagine why anyone would confuse a van with a good car__but the new Grand Cherokee is one superb piece. Luxury sedans weren't this sophisticated a decade ago. Certainly sport-utility vehicles never were, and the new Grand Cherokee makes Explorers, Blazers, Troopers, Monteros, Pathfinders, and 4Runners seem positively agricultural. If I could have but one all-purpose car for the rest of my life, the Grand Cherokee would be a contender. <p>Cruder Cherokees have long been a phenomenon, popular among Connecticut Marlboro Men__and women__but this is the first iteration of the model that truly deserves to be a hit. Somehow, <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a> has managed to make live axles feel like independent suspension all around, and the handling of this car/truck is taut, the ride luxuriously comfortable. (The steering is less praiseworthy; it's too light and there's a certain on-center numbness, so you find yourself gently tacking down the road, the imprecision leading to small not-enough/whoops-too-much steering inputs.) <p>Except for its Rubbermaid School of Design plastic lower-body cladding, the look of the new Grand Cherokee is rounded yet tough, subtly carlike yet still aggressive, utilitarian. The interior is superbly roomy and the seats almost furniture-caliber in uprightness and comfort. But the instrument panel is conventionally rectangular and fussy, with such odd touches as an oversized vehicle-information screen that constantly reads out the time and date__items that don't seem all that crucial, particularly since the radio also endlessly displays the time. <p>The new Grand Cherokee offers the first V8a torquey 5.2-liter, 220-hp Dodge truck engine__in the compact sport-utility category, but even the Chrysler people will tell you to skip it in favor of the 190-hp straight six unless you have a big boat or a house to tow; the V8's fuel burn ran between 15 and 16 miles per gallon during the typical errand-running, kid-fetching, mall-trolling use to which we put the car. <p>All this comes at a price, however. The cheapest six-cylinder Grand Cherokee goes for about $20,000, but a fully optioned V8 Grand Wagoneer version (leather seats and imitation woodgrain interior accents set it apart) will take you well past $30,000. Stick with the six, tick the options boxes carefully, and you'll end up with change from a $25,000 check. And if you ever run into Anna Quindlen, she'd like a ride. <p> <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
