	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Revival Time</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Wait__there may be life in those old leathers yet<p>By Carla Koehl<p>Right now, somewhere in the closet, a beloved but decaying leather briefcase is hanging on by a thread, long overdue for the thrift shop.<p>Before dumping it, or any other old or dowdy leather wallets, belts, or purses, consider sending it to Joy Liotta Horvath. From her home office in Norwalk, Connecticut, Horvath has been repairing, restitching, restoring, and hand-making leather luxury items for 16 years for customers as far flung as Australia, and as much-hyped as decorator Mark Hampton. <p>Alligator and crocodile skins are her specialties, but Horvath will work on any leather item except shoes as long as she deems it salvageable. Her inventory of 250-plus skins, mostly from her now-defunct leather factory ("Who could compete with Asia?"), gives her ample material for rebacking worn belts and straps, overhauling exhausted luggage, lengthening or shortening the handle on a handbag, and even cloning the occasional much-loved but clearly expired attach case. <p>Reincarnation comes at a price: from $50 an hour for most stitching and repairs to $2,500 to $4,000 for creation of a small, handmade alligator purse. Horvath quietly brags, though, that she restitches most wallets for just $30 and charges just $125 to fit Louis Vuitton luggage with lookalike replacement handles (LV quotes $200 to $250). Horvath requires four to six weeks for most jobs, though rush orders can be accommodated (203-847-9035).<p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Small Business Ownership

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
