<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Life Swapping</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Life Swapping</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
To vacation like a native, trade homes and learn about the kindness of strangers.<p>By Sandy MacDonald<p>As a career diplomat, Brian Carlson has seen and lived in his share of opulent embassies. But nothing prepared him for the Paris apartment he and his wife, Marcia, happened upon through a friendly trade.<p>"It wasn't anything palatial," he recalls, "but when we opened the shutters we were literally in the shadow of the Eiffel Tower." For Marcia, even more enjoyable than the view was "the sense of living how the French live." Their hosts had left detailed notes on nearby museums and a list of their favorite boulangeries and restaurants, so that when the Carlsons ventured forth, they weren't just another pair of bumbling tourists trying to eke an authentic experience out of a blur of supposed attractions. As Marcia says, "We knew exactly where around the corner to go."<p>It's this opportunity to play instant insider that inspires tens of thousands of otherwise reasonable Americans to hand over all their worldly goods__house, cars, pets, and occasionally children__to perfect strangers and to head off for parts unknown, there to step into the strangers' lives. Like a mail-order marriage, it's a for-better-or-for-worse proposition__usually, much, much better.<p>"You can live the way you're accustomed to, or would like to become accustomed to," says Vicki Locke, owner/manager of St. Croix's Chenay Bay Resort, who has parlayed her island home and a Florida condo into idyllic sojourns in Provence. This year she and her family of five plus another family of five snagged an English country house with indoor and outdoor pools and a stable of horses. "When you get a mansion, you can do multi-couples, or whatever you want," says Locke. "My friends have been green for years as I go off with my whole family for weeks at a time."<p>Long the province of professors and retirees, home-swapping is fast entering the mainstream. Most exchangers, like the Lockes, make use of a listing service such as Intervac, a 40-year-old organization whose roster has doubled in the past five years. "We could triple it if my partner and I had more time and money," says Lori Horne, who after seven years as a satisfied Intervac swapper bought into the business in 1987. "We've never even done any advertising."<p>For a $62 yearly fee, Intervac's 9,000-odd members get to list their properties__described in a hyper-condensed, Esperanto-like code__and desired dates and destinations in one of three seasonal directories. February's "big book," with a deadline of November 24, is the one that serious summer swappers pounce on, their self-introductory letters and color photos (and/or faxes and videos) at the ready. Typical listers will make 30 to 40 initial offers, in the hope of lining up a handful of viable trades.<p>"You've got to get on the phone and ask lots of questions," advises Horne. "If you feel the slightest discomfort or flakiness__like maybe they're not going to go through with it__move on, because if they drop you, you're in trouble." Having nonrefundable airline tickets is one of the scarier aspects of these site-unseen arrangements, but that hurdle can be cleared with contingency plans__which you have to insist on, Horne warns. Typically, the middle-class Europeans who sign up to swap have both city and country homes, so you can take your pick__or "bank" a later visit__if they're unable to vacate on cue. Usually, though, you end up with both homes. One deep-pocketed Spanish industrialist with whom Horne has traded her Marin County home several times has five houses to put in the pot__including one on Majorca that comes with a fully crewed yacht. He offered the Hornes his Barcelona pied--terre during the Olympics and, upon learning they'd already arranged another exchange, surprised them with tickets to the opening ceremony instead.<p>Such magnanimous gestures are apparently the norm among house exchangers. With no money down, just a commitment of blind faith, swappers go all out to dispense good will. It's customary, for example, to leave a day's provisions (so the exhausted newcomers won't have to rush out to shop) and a packet of information on local attractions and services. Most homeowners, however, embroider these bare minimums, leaving behind a fresh-baked cake, a bottle of fine wine, and a phalanx of relatives and neighbors to see to their guests' every need and show them the country as no average tourist will ever get to know it.<p>These onlookers are helpful not only for their friendly input but also as a crucial safeguard. Massachusetts writer John O'Brien's neighbors, for instance, suspected something was amiss when the family he'd traded with (through the second-largest international exchange organization, Vacation Exchange Club) engaged in what appeared to be a weeklong keg party. One set of friends went so far as to rescue the family dog, but no one wanted to call the O'Briens and ruin their vacation. It was ruined soon enough, though; the first sight to greet them upon their homecoming was their children's toys hanging from the telephone wires. Their house had been thoroughly trashed.<p>"I had an idealistic attitude toward travel, that it's the most valuable thing you can do in your life," says O'Brien, who'd had delightful prior exchange experiences in Paris and a medieval German town. He's still a believer and has encouraged several friends to try exchanging (with uniformly happy results), but as for putting his own house on the line, "No, never again."<p>Intervac's method for weeding out home-wreckers is simple and swift: If a complaint seems at all founded, boom, the listing's pulled and the offender is out of the club__for life. "We never get the same complaint twice," says Horne. "You have to remember, if it's risky for you, it's just as risky for the person coming over." Asking for references is de rigueur, as is a close look at your insurance policies; generally, coverage extends to nonpaying guests. In Intervac's long history, Horne claims, "We've never had anything serious or criminal; it's always little things, like a phone bill." Long-distance calls, in fact, are usually the only extras incurred. Exchangers customarily offer up all their perks, including country club memberships, live-in au pairs, and the family car(s), perhaps agreeing beforehand to a mutual cap on mileage. One visitor to Great Britain was so surprised to find a Bentley in the garage, he never dared set foot in it and took the Underground instead.<p>Because foreigners tend to be inordinately intrigued with all things American, even would-be exchangers in what Horne would call "a no-place place" (the coasts have the greatest cachet, with Colorado following close behind) have a shot at the big time__within reason. Michael McGinn, a political consultant who lords over County Cork's Mallow Castle, where Edmund Spenser penned "The Fairie Queene," happened to mention to a syndicated columnist that he might be amenable to a trade. "I was deluged with offers of timeshares in Orlando," he sighs. Unless you have something pretty special to pony up, you might have to be prepared to trade horizontally or even down. But that can work out just fine. One of Vicki Locke's favorite perches in Provence was "a small, sweet place" where the exchange partner's parents took Locke's family under their wing, and where every morning her boys would traipse down the hill to get pain au chocolat from the bakery.<p>"You get to be a part of the place," she recalls fondly. As a hotelier, she has an open-ended professional courtesy pass to resorts throughout the world. Yet she and her family prefer the quirky pleasures of other people's homes: "Even if it takes a couple of days to figure out how the washing machine works," she says, "I wouldn't do it any other way." <p>For an introductory kit, contact Intervac U.S., P.O. Box 590504; San Francisco, CA 94159, 415-435-3497. A thorough, if occasionally hokey, exegesis on the intricacies of home exchanging can be found in the book Trading Places, by Bill and Mary Barbour (Rutledge Hill Press; 513 Third Ave. S., Nashville, TN 37210; 615-244-2700; $9.95).<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
