<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Going With the Grain</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Going With the Grain</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Premium bourbons give a smooth answer to the single-malt challenge.<p>By John Mariani<p>Time was when a man who liked bourbon drank what his father and grandfather drank, learning to handle the kick and the bite on the back of the throat. But those days are gone. Domestic sales have dropped more than 50 percent since 1970, a downturn that has pushed tradition-bound Kentucky distillers of America's only indigenous spirit to copy the producers of single-malt scotch and French cognac and promote what are called premium single-barrel and small-batch bourbons, which are generally smoother and more expensive than their traditional predecessors.<p>The model came from Maker's Mark, a small, historic-landmark distillery in Loretto, Kentucky, owned by booze giant Hiram Walker. Selling for about $15 a bottle, Maker's Mark took on a cult status on the basis of the unorthodox notion that a mellower, more fully rounded bourbon could be produced using expensive winter wheat, rather than cheaper rye (all bourbon must by law contain at least 51 percent corn), and production methods deliberately promoted as old-fashioned. Maker's Mark's success inspired such giant distilleries as Jim Beam and Wild Turkey to make their own premium products, some costing $50 a bottle, some sold in crystal decanters, and others sold only at duty-free airport shops in the Orient.<p>Today there are at least a dozen premium bourbons, but it's not always easy to distinguish what makes one distinctive from another, or in fact, from the standard bourbons produced by the parent company. Jim Beam, for example, makes four small-batch bourbons, each made only in limited quantities. The press release for Beam's Baker's Bourbon says that it is made with a special strain of yeast "developed long ago and maintained for generations." Yet this is the same strain used in several other Jim Beam products. The claim for the same company's Knob Creek bourbon is that it is aged in white-oak barrels whose insides are charred to the maximum number "4" level (which adds flavor and tannins to the whiskey), but the press release neglects to say that all Jim Beam bourbons are made using the number "4" charring and that many other distilleries use this method, too.<p>In fact, most premium bourbons are not distilled separately from bulk bourbons but are only bottled blends of bourbons from various barrels selected by a master distiller for their particular fineness and flavor. Some may be aged longer than standard brands (up to 12 years in some cases). Others may be drawn straight from the barrel at "barrel proof" rather than being distilled at higher proof and then diluted with water. Others may or may not be filtered. And some are not blends at all, but are taken from a single barrel. All producers would lead you to believe their premium bourbons are based on age-old methods handed down over generations or saved only for special occasions, but the truth is that most of these small-batch whiskeys have come on the market only in the past two to five years. <p>However arch the claims for distinctiveness, there's no doubt that these premium bourbons are very different from the harsh, traditional whiskeys still produced in enormous bulk. To find out how distinctive these premium bourbons are, Worth did a tasting of 12 currently being sold nationally. We also threw in a few bulk bourbons and one Tennessee whiskey, none of which compared favorably with the rich character of the premiums. We tasted them straight, then cut with distilled water, discovering (as with cognacs, vintage champagne, and single-malt scotches) that one's own preference for the style of one producer's bourbon is more important than the rarity or price of the liquor. Cutting them with water diluted some of the tastes that made one different from another. These are bourbons better sipped in a snifter after dinner than served on the rocks with water as a pick-me-up before. They're listed by proof, from lowest to highest. <p>Rock Hill Farms__80 proof, $38. A deep amber color and a delicate bouquet full of caramel and vanilla. This is an enchanting lightweight bourbon with many layers of flavor that heavier alcohol might knock out. The bottle is a heavy squat beauty etched with an illustration of Kentucky horse country.<p>Basil Hayden__80 proof, $30. A Jim Beam product distilled separately from the firm's other bourbons. It contains higher percentages of rye, barley, and malt, which give it its richer flavor. Amber in color. Lighter than most bourbons because of the lower proof, and very smooth, with a gentle bite. Pleasant and easy to drink.<p>Hancock's Reserve__88.9 proof, $39. A nice middle-place finisher for a premium bourbon, extremely smooth, with a sweet toasted undertone. Gorgeous stoppered bottle and beautifully crafted cylindrical wooden gift box, which add to the cost. <p>Maker's Mark__90 proof, $15. The first premium to enter the market and still the benchmark. Deep color, medium nose but an interesting bouquet. Nice and warm in the mouth without any real bite. This is a delicious, mellow bourbon with terrific flavor, either before dinner with water or after in a snifter.<p>Evan Williams__90 proof, $10. Made by Heaven Hill. Aged a minimum of seven years. A powerful but nice, mellow aroma, with a slightly caramel undertone and a traditional bite at the end. Better cut with water as a before-dinner drink. <p>Blanton's__93 proof, $38. From Ancient Age. A single-barrel bourbon, unblended. Deep, rich color, light lovely nose, full of vanilla. A very good after-dinner drink, with body and flavors that start and finish elegantly on the palate. Beautifully packaged with horse-and-jockey stopper. <p>Elijah Craig__94 proof, $14. Named after the man who gave bourbon its distinctive taste by aging it in charred barrels. Aged 12 years. Very deep, rich color, a pretty, mellow bouquet, and a sweet undertone. The kind of bite you expect from a bourbon, but not at all a head-wagger.<p>Knob Creek__100 proof, $25. A Jim Beam product, aged for nine years. Medium color, high-alcohol nose. A balanced bourbon, with everything in synch, but nothing exceptional. <p>Wild Turkey 12__101 proof, $50. Very deep color and high alcohol in the nose and finish. Taken from selected barrels. A formidable whiskey, but it tastes harsh even after 12 years of aging, with a massive bite. It lacks the complexity in finish of other premiums.<p>Baker's__107 proof, $30 to $35. A Jim Beam product distilled at a lower proof than most whiskeys and sold in a wine bottle. Deep caramel color but a light, delicate aroma. This is a powerhouse, with an enormously long finish on the back of the palate. Some finesse, but the alcohol makes it one-dimensional.<p>Wild Turkey Rare Breed__About 110 proof, $30. A blend of six-, eight-, and 12-year-old stocks undiluted with water, so that barrel proof varies from bottle to bottle. Rich color but light nose full of wood and vanilla. This has too much bite and burn because of the high alcohol content.<p>Booker's__About 125 proof, $45. When it was introduced in 1987, this was a single-barrel bourbon, but now it is made as a blend, in small batches. With its barrel proof uncut, this unfiltered bourbon has a very big alcohol kick in the nose. Very woody, with lots of tannin and tobacco taste. Unique; the best choice for fans of a high-alcohol gargantuan style.<p> <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
