	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Always Carry Protection</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Always Carry Protection</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
The farther you wander, the more important it is to pack traveler's health insurance<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>It's a traveler's worst nightmare. He's out fishing for Nile perch, say, on the Ugandan side of Lake Victoria, when he feels a terrible pain in his chest. Who to call? The local doctor, who speaks no English, specializes in cattle. And the nearest hospital won't admit a foreigner without payment up front.<p>Few of the 500,000 Americans who will need immediate medical attention outside the United States this year will face such a drastic situation. But anyone who travels abroad, especially to remote or dangerous places, would do well to buy travel health insurance. Although most U.S. insurance policies are accepted abroad, only a good travel insurance plan will guarantee immediate payment on claims, a necessity since many hospitals overseas either require advance payment or hold a patient's passport until all the American paperwork clears. Other benefits typically include access to a hot line that will provide medical advice and help you locate the closest available English-speaking physician, evacuation to the closest appropriate hospital, and assistance in filling prescriptions. In serious cases, family members will be flown in to be with the injured. Most of these policies cost less than $100 per week, kick in as soon as the taxi leaves for the airport, and have a maximum payout of $100,000.<p>Travel policies are valid only outside the 48 contiguous states and will not cover trips to U.S. State Department-designated "danger zones," such as Bosnia and Iraq. Consumers with pre-existing health conditions, such as heart ailments or diabetes, will need to purchase riders to their policies. And these policies don't cover injuries you might receive while pursuing high-risk activities, such as parasailing or uncertified scuba diving. Routine doctor visits are also excluded.<p>Of the 20-odd companies that offer travel health insurance, these five offer the best comprehensive direct-payment policies: Access America, 800-284-8300; HealthCare Abroad, 800-237-6615; International SOS Assistance, 800-523-8930; Travel Assistance International, 800-821-2828; and The Travelers Companies, 800-243-3174. Evaluating a provider is as simple as presenting a company representative with the specifics of your upcoming trip and asking what's covered.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
