<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Q & A</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>Q & A</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Q & A</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Departments  
<p>
 Q & A 
<p>
Readers' questions answered  
<p>
 Q:  For several years I've been putting money in a 403(b) plan
at work. I have not been able to reach the maximum annual contribution
allowed, but I expect to do so sometime in the next year. I have
read that 403(b) plans have a "catch-up" provision that can be
exercised before retirement. How can I calculate the amount I
can put in, and when can I start?  
<p>
 A:  When you set up a 403(b), your employer automatically diverts
a portion of each paycheck into the plan. But you can also make
voluntary additional plan paymentsup to certain limits.  
<p>
Ordinarily, the annual voluntary contributions to a 403(b) cannot
exceed $9,500. If you are already making contributions to a SEP
or 401(k), this amount may be lower.   
<p>
 If you have been working for your current employer for at least
15 years, and your previous contributions averaged less than
$5,000 a  year, you can make annual contributions to bring your
contributions up to the $5,000-per-year figure. However, the
annual contribution cannot exceed $3,000, and your total contributions
cannot exceed $15,000. What's more, the sum of your total annual
contributions can't exceed 25 percent of your reduced salarythe
salary remaining after the contribution amount has been deducted
from itin any given year.   
<p>
 And finally, the law limits the total amount you can invest
in a 403(b), based on a variety of factors, including your employment
history and your use of other retirement plans. The calculations
are complex. Your best move is to check with your employee-benefits
administrator to see how each limitation may affect your 403(b)
plan participation.  
<p><p>
<p>
Q: I would like to start investing in stocks, but need to learn
the basics. What are the best sources of information?  
<p>
 When it comes to investing, information is an asset you can't
afford to do without. Fortunately, useful sources abound.   
<p>
 For starters, here are a few excellent, common-sense books that
every investor should have on the investment shelf. How to Buy
Stocks by Louis Engel and Brendan Boyd (Bantam) is the all-time
best seller on the stock market, an excellent primer. The Intelligent
Investor by Benjamin Graham (HarperCollins) is considered the
classic on value investing. It provides guidance for both the
defensive and the aggressive investor. By focusing on company
financial statements, Graham has taught two generations of investors
how to buy stocks that are currently worth more than their market
price. In One Up on Wall Street (Penguin) and Beating the Street
(Simon & Schuster), Peter Lynch, a Worth columnist and the most
successful mutual fund manager of all time, shows individual
investors how to identify promising industries and stocks by
using knowledge they already have from their daily lives.  
<p>
 Then there are the stock information services that are available
at most libraries. The Value Line Investment Survey provides
some of the best analysis in the business on the 1,700 stocks
it covers. The Standard & Poor's Stock Reports provide substantial
analysis of historical and current performances of thousands
of stocks. S&P also publishes a monthly Stock Guide, which tracks
the performance of more than 5,000 stocks. Moody's manuals also
provide substantial company data that investors can use to gauge
the health of a particular prospect.   
<p>
 There are also analysts' recommendations. Every full-service
brokerage firm produces numerous reports on particular companies,
industries, and even the economy in general.   
<p>
 And, of course, investors can request company annual reports.
An annual reportusually free for the askingis a company's summary
statement about its past and most recent financial status. In
it investors will find the company's financial statements, as
well as a healthy dose of company hype. And though annual reports
aren't the best source of information, they're a useful way to
familiarize yourself with a particular company.  
<p><p>
<p>
Q:  My broker has been touting stock in a company that's about
to go on the market. I realize that IPOs are high-risk, but I'm
curious. How can I research the company and the prospects for
the stock so that when it goes public, I can intelligently take
it or leave it?   
<p>
 A:  Investors generally have one of two reasons when they purchase
initial public offerings: speculating that interest in a new
company will drive up the price in the short term, or investing
on the company's anticipated performance over a longer time.<p>
<p>
 Timing is the most important criterion for short-term speculating.
Because IPOs usually involve a relatively small number of shares,
the ebb and flow of investor interest can send shares sky-rocketing
one day and plunging within a few months, weeks, or even days.<p>
<p>
  As a result, stock prices at any point may bear little relation
to the company's actual value. Regardless of a new company's
eventual success or failure, investors may reap short-term profits
from an IPO that stimulates a high level of investor curiosity.
But investors who aren't comfortable with the gut-wrenching feeling
that a roller coaster induces should steer clear of IPOs.  
<p>
 On the other hand, the long-term performance of many IPOs can
be excellent. After all, every stock was an IPO at one time.
But the number of stories about the fabulous successes far exceed
the number of investors who got in on the ground floor of truly
spectacular IPOs. There are several questions about a company's
financial health that can give investors a sense of the long-term
prospects:   
<p>
         Is the company an established organization with a proven
record of profitability, or is it just starting up?  
<p>
         Is the company operating in a growing industry?   
<p>
         Does it have a proprietary product or service?   
<p>
         Does it enjoy a significant market share?  
<p>
         Does the company plan to use the money it raises by
selling stock to improve the business, or merely to line the
pockets of the original investors?  
<p>
 A company's financial record is probably the most important
part of the prospectus. Declining earnings or a short history
of earning profits may be warnings of things to come. Investors
also should generally avoid companies with high debt levels.<p>
<p>
 The prospectus may contain valuable nonfinancial information
as well. For example, legal actions against a company may have
troubling implications. The prospectus should also reveal how
long the current management has been in place, as well as the
background and experience of key managers. And finally, look
at why the company is issuing stock. If a portion of the proceeds
go to corporate officers, they are, in effect, reducing their
own stake in the company. So much for their confidence in the
company's prospects.  
<p><p>
<p>
Q:  I am going back to school and my income will be very low
for the next few years. However, I have accumulated a significant
amount of money in an IRA. Will I be able to finance some of
my educational expenses with my IRA money?  
<p>
 A:  Unless you become disabled, just about the only way you
can make penalty-free IRA withdrawals before age 5912 is through
a life annuity, whereby you agree to pay out your account in
equal installments, based on your life expectancy. Of course,
if you don't have much in your account, or you're relatively
young (and therefore your life expectancy is many years), you
won't be able to take a lot out each year. Here's how to calculate
your allowable withdrawls:  
<p>
 Step 1: Determine your life expectancy from the life expectancy
tables contained in IRS Publication 590, "Individual Retirement
Arrangements (IRAs)."  
<p>
 Step 2: Project the amount your IRA will grow over your projected
life expectancy using a reasonable rate of interest, which is
contained in the "Internal Revenue Bulletin" published at the
beginning of each month.  
<p>
 Step 3: Set up an annual schedule for taking distributions out
of your account. When you do so, you must:  
<p>
 Establish absolutely equal payments; you can't take out one-third
of the balance one year and one-sixteenth the next  
<p>
 Make distributions at least once a year; you can make payments
more frequently, but not less frequently.  
<p>
 The payment schedule must be in effect for at least five years,
or until you reach age 59, whichever period is longer.   
<p>
 Warning: Failure to follow these rules will likely cost you
a retroactive penalty of 10 percent on everything you take out.<p>
<p>
 We will try to answer every question we receive, although we
cannot publish them all.  Readers should send questions to WORTH
Q&A, 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY  10022.  
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
