<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-White Water: Black Fear</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-White Water: Black Fear</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Rafting the Zambezi, the world's wildest day trip<p>By Pam Houston<p>I am passionate about white-water rivers for many reasons. First because I love seeing untamable country and because white-water rivers often cut wild country__gorges, mountains, and deep canyons__that there's no other way to see. I love the light and shadow on the canyon walls, the colors__browns, reds, oranges, and grays__that change with every bend of the river, every movement of the sun. I love the pace of life on the river, five or six miles an hour, accelerated to nine or ten miles an hour in the rapids; it is just the right speed to see scenery that huge.<p>What I love most of all, of course, is the acceleration; the moment when the current catches the flat underside of my big inflatable raft and pulls me toward what I can hear but sometimes cannot see: the roar of water washing over rocks, the smooth green slick of river that plummets toward a three- or six- or nine-foot wall of white water, the joyful drenching as my boat makes contact with the wave, the exhilaration when I come out, right side up and whole on the other side.<p>Or I don't.<p>Sometimes my boat flips and the big wave holds me under, tossing my arms and legs as if I were a cat in a washing machine, then spits me out to swim like mad for the boat.<p>Or it doesn't.<p>Maybe the wave holds me in there until I gulp down so much water I drown, or the wave picks me up and slams my body into the rock that has made it, and I die on impact. Because up to now this last scenario has not happened, and because I know there is no passion without risk of loss, I will continue to run white-water rivers until I've beaten the odds so many times I start to get nervous, and then I'll have to turn to some other, tamer passion: men with foreign accents, say, or books.<p>And though I wish it were not true, it is a fact that I can't get passionate about anything that doesn't risk my physical, emotional, or spiritual health (here I could list as evidence either the expeditions I have taken or the men I have dated). I can't get passionate about anything I think I can own.<p>Passion, for me, is born in the same place as desire; it depends upon the possibility of its not being fulfilled in order for it to exist in the first place. I am not passionate about rivers I'm sure I won't die on, any more than I'm passionate about a man I know I can have forever. I can like those other rivers, love them even, but passion for me is a love-plus-fear equation. Passion on the river happens in the long second when the nose of the boat dips downward and I hear the roar of the water in my ears, and the river says, "How could you have thought you were in charge here?"<p>For that moment, that gut-gripping, adrenaline-rushing, mind-focusing surge of excitement, there is no river I know of like the Zambezi on the Zimbabwe-Zaire border, as it flows away from Victoria Falls.<p>They call it the "world's wildest day trip"__six hours and fifteen rapids (numbered five through nineteen), five of which are larger than anything in the United States, all large enough to get seared indelibly on even the most experienced boatwoman's memory. And unlike most of the world's great white-water trips, on this one, for a day and $100, anyone can go.<p>The tiny town of Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe, is home to many of the world's best river guides. In season (March to December) about 35 guides from three river companies take as many as 300 people a day down the Zambezi. Some of the clients are seasoned river rats like me, but the vast majority of them are on a white-water river for the first time.<p>The day starts out with almost two hours of training in boating and safety procedures. Our guide, whose name is Jason, tells us he has flipped in rapid No. 18 every day for the last two weeks, so we had better pay attention: This is how to tighten our life jackets, this is what to do if we find ourselves in the water, this is what to do if we're in the boat and he's in the water.<p>"Yes," Jason says, "there are crocodiles between rapids, so if you do fall out, try not to stay in the water too long."<p>Then it is into the boat for some command training. Jason will man the oars, he says, but he needs our active cooperation if we are to get through waves this huge. When we enter a rapid, we are to wait for his command, and when he gives it, we are to hurl our full weight against whatever part of the boat is about to hit the big wave__"highsiding," it's called__and, if we are lucky, we'll punch the boat through.<p>Having rowed inflatable rafts through America's biggest rapids for six years, I am skeptical about the value of passenger participation. It's just a way to keep us all entertained, I think, wishing they'd give me my own boat to row. How big can these rapids be, I think, and then I see rapid No. 5.<p>Or hear it, to be more precise. I can't actually see rapid No. 5 until we are pointing nose down into it about 20 degrees off vertical, bracing for Jason's "NOW" command that will send us hurtling into the massive white wave. (Later Jason will tell me I went a little pale in the entry to five; he'll say that's where everyone goes a little pale.) Suddenly I'm glad I'm not the one rowing; suddenly I understand why he needs the weight of six people to punch through the wave.<p>"NOWWW!" Jason says, and we all hit that wave screaming. There is a surge of whiteness, a drenching, a momentary stoppage of time in which the thunder in our ears becomes the thunder in our ears, and we rise out of the wave and back to the surface as if from an incredible depth. We ride a few smaller standing waves and lose ourselves in cheers and hollers. Jason's tight features loosen, and he passes the bail buckets around.<p>The word comes back from the boats ahead of us: Three boats have turned over; everyone is back aboard safe. We are the last of 12 boats and we're designated "clean-up." It is our job to save any strays.<p>Rapid No. 6 is just as big as No. 5, and No. 7 is slightly smaller, wave-wise, but almost half a mile long. The Zambezi is known as a pool-and-drop river, which means the rapids are mostly huge amounts of water pouring over steep rock falls and ledges with lots of slow-water recovery time in between. This is actually a safer type of river than the much smaller-volumed but more technically challenging rivers of Idaho or Appalachia, where there is constant moving white water and where the rocks that bash your boat and your body are much closer to the surface.<p>On a pool-and-drop river, the guide has to do only two things right: position himself right in the middle of the V-slick (the green, V-shaped pour-off at the top of a rapid) and hit the wave with his boat perpendicular to it (pointing forward or backward); perfectly straight on.<p>Rapid No. 7, on the Zambezi, is the exception to the pool-and-drop rule. It is long, complicated, and full of rocks that are not safely buried beneath hundreds of feet of rushing water. But Jason proves to be as smart as he is strong, and we glide past the Crease, Indicator Rock, and Land of the Giants, unscathed.<p>All the rafts have to portage at rapid No. 9, which is a class-six rapid. A class six, according to the international river classifying system, is a rapid that's unrunnable, likely to cause severe injury or death.<p>Tell that to the Zambezi video kayakers, who precede the rafts down the river every day catching all the action on video (copies of which they will sell in great number that evening). These extremely passionate (or slightly insane) young men give the portaging tourists what most of them don't know is the kayaking demonstration of their lives, as they plunge off a 60-foot cliff into white-water chaos, which turns out, on our day, not to mean certain death.<p>Rapid No. 11 has the steepest drop of any of the 15, and when we hit the wave, it feels like concrete; it stops our boat dead and won't let us go for six or seven seconds, the water churning beneath us, rattling our hold on the safety line and each other.<p>Of course, what we've been waiting for all day, is rapid No. 18, home of the wave named Oblivion, the one rapid that at this river level flips 80 percent of the boats.<p>I've seen No. 18 on yesterday's video tape, and frankly, I'm not too worried. There's plenty of water and no rocks near the surface in the main channel, and on the video I watched, boat after boat of people turned over, only to wash right out and get rescued.<p>I'm not too worried, that is, until we hit a rock in rapid No. 17 that breaks both our oars, and I see Jason's face turn from responsible and serious to helpless and panicked as we float toward Oblivion with two little stubs coming out of the oar locks.<p>We are in a bad position. We can't stop or slow ourselves by rowing upstream, can't row to shore and wait to be rescued, can't maneuver the boat at all toward where we need to be in No. 18, and if we don't enter the rapid in the right place, who knows where we'll end up? We have one spare oar, which we cracked earlier in the day and will do us almost no good. We have no boats behind us, and the boat in front of us is about to enter No. 18.<p>Jason shouts ahead and, luckily, Pennant, who has rowed boats on the Zambezi for 11 years, is strong enough to row upstream and give us his spare oar. While my shaking hands hold the two pieces of the cracked oar together, Jason's shaking hands bind it with an old piece of inner tube. We secure the oars again and are ready to face Oblivion with 30 yards to spare.<p>Rapid No. 18 contains three big waves. The first two are big enough to flip a boat if you don't hit them straight on, and the third one__Oblivion__will flip you almost no matter what you do. Jason's plan is not to go "highside" on the first two waves; we want to have all our strength and timing to hit Oblivion together.<p>Will there be anyone to rescue us? I wonder, looking below the rapid and seeing only overturned boats and swimmers everywhere, but I say, "Didn't anyone make it through?"<p>"I doubt it," Jason says. "It's been getting worse every day. Hold on in here," he says, as the speed builds under the boat, "This pool's got crocs."<p>I have, in all the excitement, forgotten about the crocodiles.<p>We hit the first wave just fine, but the second wave turns us sideways. Our cracked oar breaks for good, and we head for Oblivion between sideways and backwards, as bad a position as we can be.<p>"NOWWW!" Jason says, and we hit the big rubber side tube as hard as we can and climb up on it with all our weight, and somewhere under all that watery chaos, the video camera finds our boat standing right up on end, the raft a thin divider between madly pounding wild water and seven dangling bodies.<p>Seconds later it is over. Jason jumps up and down and hugs each one of us and throws the broken oar up in the air. We are the only boat to make it through without flipping today, the only boat anyone can ever remember making it through sideways. We go to work pulling swimmers from the river.<p>That night, over dinner, I ask Jason how long he'll run the Zambezi, and he says, "Until it kills me or until my adrenaline runs out." What passion lacks in intelligence it makes up for in obstinacy.<p>And if love locates itself between head and heart, then passion must live between heart and guts: some tiny irrational space in the body that loves all things dark and mischievous, that celebrates excitement, chaos, and everything it cannot own.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

