	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-Where's the Beef?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-Where's the Beef?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By John Mariani<p>The catalogs may offer a well-made flannel shirt, durable gardening shears, or a good discount on a laser gunsight, but is there really any reason to order frozen beefsteaks through the mail? Readers of the ads in the back of magazines such as The New Yorker and Gourmet might think the best beef in the world is to be had only by sending away for it. The superlatives used in these ads__"world-famous," "prize-winning," "exquisite," "restaurant-quality" and so on__seem to promise that only the finest hand-picked beef is slaughtered, packed up, and sent to you for that "buttery, melt-in-your-mouth flavor."<p>Don't believe it. Worth tried four of the most readily available mail-order steaks, and only one was worth the cost or effort involved. Only Palm Pak (a branch of the famous national steakhouse chain), uses USDA prime meat, the highest grade available. The rest ship USDA choice__good, but never as good as prime, and in most cases no better than you'd find at your local supermarket. <p>Furthermore, only the Palm Pak steak had the requisite marbling and thin exterior fat that give great beef its unique, hearty flavor. The rest needed enhancement__butter, barnaise, anything to perk them up. <p>Although most shippers offer several other cuts of meat in their catalogs, the magazine ads offered only filet mignons, which we used for our tasting. The ads also offer deeply discounted prices at various times of the year, which can save you up to $30 on an order. We cooked the filets in a super-heated black iron skillet medium-rare, with a seared exterior and a juicy red interior. All were tasted on their own, then with a light sauce made with butter, shallots, and red wine.<p>America's Blue Ribbon Beef; 485 Crossroads Parkway, Bolingbrook IL 60440; 800-873-4538. Six 6-ounce filet mignons at a special offer of $29.95 (regularly $59.95) plus $6.95 shipping.
Nice beefy flavor, though not especially rich, and trimmed of all fat. The size and weight of these six-ounce filets makes them ideal for one person, and they sear nicely on the outside and stay rare within because of their thickness. Only USDA choice shipped.<p>Omaha Steaks international; 4400 South 96th Street, P.O. Box 3300, Omaha NE 68172; 800-228-9055. Six 5-ounce steaks at a special offer of $29.95 (regularly $51.95) plus $6.50 shipping.
Tender, but very little flavor, and that livery. At five ounces, they'd make decent tournedos, but they need sauce to make a meal. Omaha Steaks says it may ship "either choice or prime," but customers must request prime, which adds to the cost.<p>Classic Steaks by Skylark Meats, Inc.; 4430 South 110th Street, Omaha NE 68137-1217; 800-288-2783. One dozen 4-ounce filet mignons for a special offer of $57.25 (regularly $72.25) plus $6 shipping.
Very tender USDA choice, with some beefy flavor, but the flavor fades fast on the palate and the meat needs more marbling. The four-ounce size is skimpy and cooks quickly, making it hard to sear well enough to keep the inside rare.<p>The Palm Pak; 1010 16th Street NW, Washington, D.C. 20036; 202-775-7256. Six 12-ounce filet mignons at $100, shipping included.
By far the best tasted, in every respect. The USDA prime beef has rich flavor and terrific texture that is tender and buttery, and the veneer of fat and marbling makes you forget this is filet mignon, not sirloin. Weighing in at a big 12 ounces, this is quite a mouthful for one and may be easily sliced (after cooking) to serve two people because the fat content is so satisfying to the palate.
 <p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

