	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-Road Test: The Lexus GS 300</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-Road Test: The Lexus GS 300</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Stephan Wilkinson<p>The Lexus GS 300 sneaks up on you. Straight out of the box, there is nothing that particularly grabs you about this newest luxury sedan (other than its $42,500 equipped price, that is). No enormous torque, no asphalt-fracturing acceleration, no be-the-first-on-your-block styling, no phony race-car-body cladding.<p>The interior is luxurious, but nothing so over-the-top that it tempts you to black out the windows and get naked. The car's architecture is conventional: lots of front overhang, a long six-cylinder engine driving the rear wheels, a Jaguaresque variation on generic big-Toyota lines. All of this means plenty of front-seat room, only moderate rear-seat space and headroom, and a trunk high bustled to recapture some of the volume sacrificed to the back seats.<p>Take a short drive and you'll initially notice four things. A neon/electroluminescent instrument display that gives new meaning to the word vivid. An engine so quiet at idle that those  brightly glowing gauges are the only sign that it's running. A steering wheel that robotically motors up out of the way or back into place when you remove or insert the ignition key. And ride and handling that utterly insulate you from the harsh realities of the road. Perhaps cars are getting too good, too cool and emotionless, for the GS 300 is exciting in the way the latest mega-ram notebook computer is exciting: the soulless new machine.<p>But remember, this is a subtle machine. At first, you might think it little more than a highly refined rolling cocoon with a superb sound system (Nakamichi, seven speakers, a 12-CD changer in the trunk, $1,900 extra on the order form). The GS 300 has all the right luxury cues, such as please-touch-me polished walnut here and there, gathered leather (another $1,300), thick carpeting, and switches and controls that all show intense attention to tactile satisfaction.<p>After a few hundred miles, you'll find yourself increasingly intrigued by the car's incredible suppleness, its balance and comfort, as you sculpt back-road corners and bends. Bend on some more throttle and awaken a polite but distinct metallic wail from the three-liter, 24-valve, dual-overhead-cam six. Steering that first seemed too light and delicate will start to feel more linear and remarkably precise.<p>Some automobiles__German cars, particularly__transmit through steering wheel and seat cushion a sense of the road that encourages you to drive hard. The GS 300 is a bit different; you get the sense that somewhere under you, there's an enormous amount of work going on__suspension bits and driveline parts doing a Gregory Hines on the blacktop, an electronically controlled automatic transmission folding in seamless shifts__and that it accomplishes the major part of the driving job for you.<p>In a world that offers a number of excellent upmarket cars for $30,000 or less__Volvo 850, Mazda 929, Mitsubishi Diamante LS, Saab 9000 Turbo, the just-introduced <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a> New Yorker and LHS__the GS 300, at a base price of nearly $38,000, is good enough that it might make you reassess even the harshest value-versus-esthetics equation you've developed. <p> <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
