		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-Relief for the Beach-Bound</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Carla Koehl<p>If the idea of sitting still at the beach for more than ten or fifteen minutes at a time induces terminal nausea, be assured escape is possible. There are enough new sports gadgets and toys in this summer's lineup to exhaust even the most zealous weekend athlete__and not one of them involves Velcro Ping-Pong paddles.<p>Self-respecting runners with too much dignity to bounce, Tigger-like, along the shore on NordicTrack's new Exerlopers ($199.95 a pair; 800-445-2209) will want to opt for the best all-terrain running shoes on the market: Asics Gel Trail-Lytes ($85). The tongueless, wraparound design keeps out pebbles and errant seaweed, and the hard-rubber outsoles are responsive even in the deepest sand. Anyone who can stand the colors__gray specks splattered on the midsoles, with hot pink and purple for women; plum, "papaya," and blue for men__will find these lightweight (9-oz.) shoes are the best things that ever happened to their hamstrings (Asics 800-766-2742). Sport sandal lovers who are sick of scuffing boat decks and sailboards with their black-bottomed Tevas now have the option of white-bottomed ones, new this year from Deckers Corp. (800-433-2537). The Deck Contour sandals ($62 a pair) have new, non-skid neoprene and rubber treads that minimize slipping in any direction. Teva's standard nylon woven straps are adjustable in the heel and toe. <p>The smallest and newest in hi-tech sports gadgetry for 1993 should more than satisfy the speed-obsessed: The Skywatch windmeter ($64.95 from Windsurfing Express, 800-843-7873) fits in the harness pocket of any sailboard, and the Blade Trainer computerized speedometer ($44.95 from Inline USA, 800-685-6806) clips on the toe of any in-line skate. Express Line skating gloves ($29.95 at 800-521-0549) come complete with detachable rearview mirror, Velcro'd to the back of the left-hand glove, and hard plastic palm guards. Mid-collision, it's also worth clutching a pair of Ray-Bans with DiamondHard Scratch-Protection from Bausch & Lomb (800-828-1430). The new surface makes the sunglasses ten times more scratch-resistant than regular glass, and repels water to reduce spotting (available only on certain Ray-Bans, from $110 for Cats to $128 for Wayfarers).<p>Despite efforts to the contrary, there are still those who remain convinced the beach was meant for the prone. For them, there's the new Crazy Creek chair (about $50) in an extra-wide 17.5 inches, with a full half-inch of foam padding, and two extra inches of height for neck support, coming out in August from Crazy Creek (800-331-0304). And anyone who's been dragged, kicking and screaming, to the beach from the office can console himself with Bare's new fake cellular phone water bottle ($6) with antenna as nozzle, available at Sailboard Warehouse (800-992-SAIL). <p>Those still fiercely clinging to childhood should pick up a SlingKing Jr., the only hand-held Day-Glo water-balloon launcher that hurls wet ones up to 50 yards (adult size launches up to 75 yards). "Target use only" is the not-reassuring disclaimer printed on each launcher, but it's so tough to stretch back the rubber tubing that even Mom and Dad will have a hard time doing any damage with it ($24.95 for one, $21.95 for two, and $19.95 for three from SlingKing, 800-788-5553; 100 balloons included with each launcher).<p> <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
