	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Review: Package Tracking From Your Keyboard</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Review: Package Tracking From Your Keyboard</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ted C. Fishman<p>
Federal Express, every MBA student knows, owes its success to the realization that the parcel-post business is less about planes, trucks, and boxes than about the software that routes and tracks them. Now FedEx has put that capability in everyone's hands by fixing it on the Web (<a HREF="http://www.fedex.com">www.fedex.com</A>): Users can send packages by merely working a keyboard. Obtaining a FedEx account takes but a minute, and airwaybills can be printed on your own plain paper. The site can direct shippers to thousands of FedEx drop-off spots where supplies are available and where packages can be deposited for delivery or a courier summoned for pickup; the site will estimate when a driver will show up. Packages can be tracked easily and delivery confirmed. United Parcel Service (<a HREF="http://www.ups.com">www.ups.com</A>) has also parked on the Web. Its site won't print a label, but users can calculate costs, identify drop-off locations, summon a truck (for air shipments), and track packages. The U.S. Postal Service (<a HREF="http://www.usps.gov">www.usps.gov</A>) lets users track parcels sent via its premium Express Mail service. But the site's real virtue is its wealth of information, including tables that let users locate zip codes and calculate postage.<p>
KEYWORDS: 
Website, Internet, site of the month

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
