<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Review: Future Tense</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Review: Future Tense</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The Sovereign Individual
By James Dale Davidson and Lord William
Rees-Mogg (Simon & Schuster, $25)<p>
One World, Ready or Not
By William Greider (Simon & Schuster, $25)<p>
By Walter Russell Mead<p>
There is nothing more fashionable these days than talk about the rapid pace of economic and technological change, but the ability to imagine true change is still rare. Conventional futurists project existing trends out to infinity and predict more of the same: China will continue to get richer as industry keeps shifting from the West to the East; Medicare costs will rise as America gets older; computers will be faster and cheaper.<p>
This kind of forecasting has had a bad track record over the past 200 years. Betting on the status quo has been the surest way to lose money since the time of Louis XVI and George III. From the industrial revolution on, the world has experienced one upheaval after another. Each generation has had to live in a world radically different from anything known or expected by its parents. In 1915, virtually no one had heard of Vladimir Ilyich Lenin or Adolf Hitler; Communism and fascism hardly existed. A couple of decades ago, leaders like Jeane Kirkpatrick and Richard Nixon believed that Western democracies were fighting a defensive battle against the powerful and confident Communism of Leonid Brezhnev. Financial analysts assumed that inflation was here to stay, and many predicted that gold and oil prices would skyrocket through the 1980s. Today most people think that the triumph of Western democracy and market economics in the Cold War has set the stage for an indefinite period of American supremacy, democratic stability, and economic prosperity.<p>
On the other hand, unconventional futurists, the ones who won't draw a smooth, straight line into infinity, commonly descry a fall off the cliff. Writers like Ravi Batra offer advice on how to survive the coming great depression; goldbugs have built an industry on predicting an imminent collapse of the paper-money system. In short, to build a convincing future scenario that resembles neither a financial apocalypse nor a continuation of the present seems one of the most difficult things in the world to do.<p>
Yet two books from very different perspectives, one on the right and one on the left, successfully challenge both dooms-day scenarios and the comfortable views we are used to. Neither The Sovereign Individual, by James Dale Davidson and Lord William Rees-Mogg, nor One World, Ready or Not, by William Greider, is perfect, but both illuminate issues important to anyone investing over a time horizon beyond a couple of years.<p>
Start with the latest contribution from Davidson and Rees-Mogg, a former editor at the right-wing Times of London who can be as dotty as his name. Rees-Mogg and Davidson loathe patriotism, the United States, and democracy. They think all three are doomed and may turn ugly as they die. Their advice to Americans: Forget patriotism, get a second passport, move money out of the country before it's too late, and give up on the American experiment in democracy.<p>
U.S. readers will find this book peculiar. Some of the thinking in it is obviously flaky, particularly the acceptance of the extreme charges against the Clintons (Vince Foster was murdered; Bill Clinton knowingly consorted with major drug figures). Whatever their faults, the Clintons are almost certainly not as bad as Rees-Mogg and Davidson believe, and like so many Brits from the days of Lord North up to the present, the authors seriously underestimate the resiliency and inner strength of the American political system. Yet readers would be mistaken to throw the book across the room in disgust, because it has some fascinating things to say. The central insight is that the relationship between rich individuals and the state is changing in unpredictable ways and that the ideological and political ground is preparing for a radical shift. The authors argue that the nation-state was a creation of the old, industrial-based technology. The increasingly dominant information-based technology is eroding the foundation of the nation-state.<p>
From below, the rise of organized crime erodes the authority of government. From above, the globalization of the economy and the increased use of electronic commerce, which lets people conduct their affairs far from the prying eyes of tax collectors, shrink the capability of national governments to manage their economies and collect revenues. Add in the demographic squeeze (the obligations to fulfill generous pension and Social Security promises to an aging population), and you've got a death spiral of rising costs and shrinking revenues. Rees-Mogg and Davidson welcome this process: Existing levels of taxation on the rich are fundamentally unjust, the authors claim, and far exceed the value of any government services the rich receive in exchange.<p>
The future forecast here looks in some ways like the Middle Ages, when people did not think of themselves primarily as members of a national group or assume that the state would provide basic services to most of the population. Big nation-states will break into smaller privatized units. Just as how in the Middle Ages the poor and weak sought protection from powerful knights and lords, so in the future ordinary people will look to the rich and powerful for protection and justice, offering obedience and loyalty in return.<p>
The Sovereign Individual has little counsel for governments in places like the United States. Rather, it offers advice to individuals: Get out while you can. Populist rage will grow as our government fails to reduce the growing gap between economic winners and losers. Strapped for revenue, the government will raise taxes on the rich and increase its use of "exit taxes" to punish wealthy individuals who renounce their U.S. citizenship to avoid tax obligations.<p>
William Greider's vision of the future, as revealed in One World, Ready or Not, comes from a very different place on the political spectrum. Greider is a convinced democrat and an American patriot who thinks the nation-state should remain a strong feature of political life. Where Rees-Mogg and Davidson see the state as a morally neutral or even immoral political unit, Greider believes the concept of a national society bound by duties and moral obligations is an essential part of the world picture. Still, he identifies many of the same forces at work that Davidson and Rees-Mogg do, and he, too, predicts rough sledding ahead for the nation-state as we know it.<p>
What separates these two books is Greider's belief that the governmental redistribution of wealth from the rich to the poor is, economically speaking, a good thing. The great danger of rapid economic development, Greider argues, is that income tends to shift from the mass of the population to the most affluent parts of society, which have the skills to take advantage of new technologies and opportunities. Income redistribution not only assures political stability -- insuring the rich against social catastrophe and class war -- but also stimulates economic growth. If money is not moved to the middle class and other mass-market consumers, there will not be enough demand to buy the products industry turns out. This would result in slower growth and, under certain conditions, economic depression.<p>
Davidson and Rees-Mogg counter that redistribution transfers assets from wealthy individuals, who know how to invest them, to government bureaucrats, who don't. A classic example: Government-funded pension programs, such as Social Security, put money in government bonds rather than in stock markets, reducing the returns on invested capital for the system and cutting the availability of cheap capital for the entrepreneurs who could make the economy grow.<p>
Where Rees-Mogg and Davidson worry about Luddite populists destroying the economy in pursuit of short-term interests, Greider concentrates his fire on a runaway affluent class that neglects its social responsibilities -- a class also in hot pursuit of short-term goals.<p>
Both dangers are, I think, real -- and globalization aggravates them to a large degree. Redistribution has actual economic costs, and economic globalization puts redistributive jurisdictions, such as Germany and the United States, at a competitive disadvantage to open, low-tax countries like Switzerland and, especially, to offshore bank havens like the Cayman Islands. Yet Greider is also right to argue on behalf of the nation-state's still enormous moral authority; Americans feel that other U.S. citizens ought not to perish for lack of housing or health care. It may be irrational, but we believe we owe one another and our country more than we owe citizens of other countries. Also, such transfer payments result in higher consumer demand and stronger economic growth.<p>
Clearly, the future is going to be bumpier than most people think. These books can be seen as opening shots in a new class war between the rich, who want to exploit and extend their gains from globalization, and the rest of the population, who want to rein them in. Investors should study both books carefully; to read them is to get a sneak preview of the forces and passions likely to transform our investment and political horizons over the next generation.<p>
KEYWORDS:
book, Mead
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
