		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Feature: The Case Against Microsoft</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Feature: The Case Against Microsoft</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						THE CASE AGAINST MICROSOFT
Why a great company is no longer a good investment<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
It's almost hard to believe that a company so large (nearly $9 billion in annual revenue) and so well established (22 years old) can still be performing this well. True, Microsoft has made a habit of success. But even by its standards, 1996 was an extraordinary year.<p>
It was a year in which the company defied the skeptics and mobilized its resources to meet the competitive challenge posed by Netscape Communications. In which sales rose an estimated 40 percent while earnings grew even faster. And in which the price of Microsoft's stock doubled, propelling chairman Bill Gates's personal wealth even further into the ionosphere.<p>
Wall Street deeply believes in Microsoft. The market has priced the company's stock at 46 times annual earnings per share. Figures compiled by Zacks Investment Research show that 23 of the 30 analysts who follow Microsoft still recommend it as a buy even at its recent price. Collectively, these analysts expect the company's earnings to rise at least 23 percent annually for the next five years.<p>
Microsoft, in other words, has now achieved one more noteworthy feat: It has become a sure thing. <p>
Which is exactly why I think there's good reason to be concerned about the stock. By bidding the price up to 46 times earnings, investors have given themselves almost no leeway for bad news, let alone room for improvement. Most of the good news is already baked into the price of the stock, so how much more upside reward can there be? <p>
By my calculations, even if Microsoft's earnings growth keeps pace with analysts' estimates, from this price the stock should deliver no better than an 11 percent annual return in the next few years. Basically, Microsoft would match the long-term performance of the market as a whole. If growth slows even slightly, investors would make more money by buying a 30-year Treasury bond and clipping coupons.<p>
I probably wouldn't be such a skeptic if one other person hadn't also recently expressed concern about Microsoft's future: Bill Gates. At the annual shareholders' meeting this past November, he said: "We have a number of competitors that are working in concert...that pose a major challenge to us -- perhaps the largest challenge that's faced us in a long, long time."<p>
Microsoft is a great company -- the world's best-managed software outfit. But it still has its work cut out for it. It's not the sure bet Wall Street believes it is.<p>
A fair appraisal of Microsoft has to take into account that many of its products hold dominant positions in mature markets. This means there's little or no room left to grow at the expense of competitors or to increase overall sales at previous rates. Moreover, regardless of who wins the browser wars between Microsoft and Netscape, the Internet almost certainly is going to pose a continued serious threat to Microsoft's entire lineup of software products, including its most important offering: the operating system that runs 90 percent of the world's personal computers.<p>
By the end of this year, the familiar files-and-folders format of the Windows operating system will begin its slow trek into computer oblivion -- both Microsoft and Netscape will make their browsers the first thing a user sees when a computer gets turned on. Also headed for extinction, as consumers get accustomed to downloading whatever tools they need over the Internet: the $499 shrink-wrapped PC-software program. Say good-bye, too, to the market for the expensive biannual upgrade package. Upgrades will be easily accessible over the Net.<p>
Bill Gates is right: Microsoft is moving toward its biggest challenge since it first crawled out of the entrepreneurial ooze in 1981 -- the year the company purchased the DOS operating system from Seattle Computer for, according to legend, $75,000. <p>
I don't doubt that Microsoft will survive all of these challenges and remain a force to be reckoned with for years to come. The folks at Microsoft are too aware of what they did to IBM to let the same thing happen to them. <p>
But will Microsoft be able to preserve its near monopoly and juicy profit margins? Infatuated as it is with Microsoft at the moment, Wall Street certainly appears to think so. I'm less sanguine.<p>
Wall Street's current love affair with Microsoft stands in sharp contrast to the rocky relationship between the two as recently as 1995. Perhaps you remember: The development of Microsoft's new operating system, originally slated to launch in December 1994, was running horribly behind schedule. With the company's credibility at stake, Gates drew a line in the sand by naming the product Windows 95. The birth finally took place in August of that year with a multimillion-dollar marketing blitz and a mountain of publicity.<p>
While all of this was going on, though, a previously unknown (to Wall Street) company called Netscape stole the limelight. Netscape's innovation was a browser that enabled computer users to easily download the graphics-heavy information on the World Wide Web, the fastest-growing part of the Internet. On August 9, 1995, Netscape rocked the market with a red-hot initial public offering. That day, Netscape shares soared from $28 to a high of $75 before settling back to close at $58.<p>
Microsoft's stock, on the other hand, had stalled out. After rising from $31 a share in early February to $52 on July 14, its trading price drifted downward just as the arrival of the long-delayed Windows 95 product and the company's huge marketing and press campaigns should have been driving it higher. <p>
Analysts concluded that Microsoft had missed the boat. Although it had rushed its own Web browser to market, its Internet Explorer was clearly inferior to Netscape's product -- and the gap just seemed to get larger when Netscape launched its second-generation Navigator on September 18.<p>
By then, the word was out: Microsoft didn't have a credible Internet strategy. All anyone needed to do to confirm this suspicion was check out the Microsoft Network, a lame new online service that adopted the outdated membership structure of America Online -- a company itself challenged by the Web. On November 16, 1995, Goldman Sachs removed Microsoft's stock from its recommended list, citing the company's lack of an Internet strategy. Others on Wall Street quickly followed.<p>
The Street was right about one thing: The Internet poses a serious challenge to Microsoft and its monopolistic grip on the market for computer operating systems. Windows not only generates an estimated $35 in revenue for each program installed by a computer maker, but its ubiquity gives Microsoft enormous clout in its other software lines. Microsoft programmers working on a spreadsheet or word-processing product simply know more about the underlying operating system than do independent software producers. They also have the inside track on updates. (Microsoft shares all this information with independent companies. The speed and extent of its sharing is a matter of industry debate.) Finally, Microsoft leverages its relationships with computer makers to ensure that its spreadsheets, games, and word-processing software come already installed on new machines.<p>
Netscape's Internet browser seemed like it could end Microsoft's lock on the operating system and, in turn, weaken its hold on the software market. How come? Because Navigator, linked with the Java software language from Sun Microsystems, is platform neutral. That means it will run on a Windows machine, a Macintosh, or in Unix. Java enables programmers to write applications that can be understood by any platform. Operating systems cease to matter.<p>
But on December 7, the anniversary of Pearl Harbor, Gates launched a counterattack that, at least in the opinion of Wall Street analysts, would successfully blunt the Netscape challenge. At a news conference, the software magnate pointedly quoted Japanese admiral Isoroku Yamamoto's 1941 fears that Japan's sneak attack had awoken a sleeping giant. Gates then disclosed plans to send wave after wave of products and near-products out to battle Netscape. The assault, Gates said, would include the next generations of Windows and Microsoft Office, both of which would be linked to the Internet. Windows NT, a new operating system for corporate networks, would provide easy access to the Net as well. And he promised that a revamped Microsoft Network would make its proprietary content accessible to all users of the Net.<p>
Some of the products and initiatives Gates trumpeted on December 7 turned out to be vaporware -- a standard Microsoft tactic that sets out to freeze the opposition in place simply by announcing a product that doesn't yet exist. But an impressively high percentage of the new offerings Gates listed that day are already on the market. MSN was relaunched as a full-service Internet gateway last November. Office 97 added the ability to communicate and publish information on the Net to old standby programs such as Excel. Internet Explorer 3.0, meanwhile, closed the technology gap with Netscape's Navigator.<p>
Microsoft's performance was so impressive that Wall Street couldn't help but kick itself for losing faith. <p>
"I thought that Microsoft was about to get smoked. It looked to me like they simply didn't get it," recalls Roger McNamee, general partner at Integral Capital Partners, an investment partnership in Menlo Park, California. But somehow, he marvels, within nine months the company got its act together. "I'm amazed at the religious zeal they've applied to reinventing themselves."<p>
"Gates did a remarkable thing," adds Michael Murphy, editor of California Technology Stock Letter. "The clich about big oil tankers is that the captain decides to change course and 12 miles later the ship begins to turn. But Gates managed to turn a $9 billion company virtually on a dime."<p>
As far as Wall Street is concerned, December 1995 marked the high-water mark for Netscape and its threat to Microsoft: Netscape's stock peaked at a pre-split-adjusted $171 a share just days before Gates's speech. No one on Wall Street now wonders if Microsoft will survive. Now Netscape is seen as the company with the questionable future.<p>
The problem with this version of events -- the story as Wall Street now sees it -- is that it radically simplifies the challenge facing Microsoft (just as the Street's fears about the company may have been overblown in the first place). And it overestimates the kinds of returns an investor can expect from Microsoft.<p>
In some ways, the account doesn't give Bill Gates and his team enough credit. The task wasn't simply to galvanize a 20,000-employee company to squash an 1,500-employee upstart like Netscape. The true challenge cut much closer to the company's core.<p>
Microsoft is an incredibly complex enterprise, but it earns its money in a straightforward manner. It sells new software -- $499 (retail) for Office 97, for example. It also charges current users to upgrade to the newest version -- $209 (retail) to upgrade Office. Both parts of this revenue stream are showing disquieting signs of maturity.<p>
Since Microsoft already has about as large a share of the market for existing users as it's likely to get, growth in first-time sales of programs is pretty much limited to the increase in sales of new personal computers -- which was about 15.5 percent in 1996 and is expected to slow to 14.5 percent in 1997.<p>
The upgrade business, meanwhile, traditionally works on a two-year cycle. Every other year, Microsoft rolls out new versions of Windows and Office. Users plunk down $60 for Windows and $210 for Office. This revenue stream, however, depends heavily on the consumer's appetite for newer, faster, and more -- an appetite that is showing signs of satiety (partly because software upgrades force users to make costly hardware upgrades). The incremental improvements that Microsoft made in Windows 95, for instance, did not send every Windows 3.1 user racing to the store. Dataquest, a market-research firm in San Jose, California, estimates that when all the figures are in Microsoft will have sold 46 million copies of Windows 95 by the end of 1996, 27 percent fewer than Dataquest originally projected. <p>
Office 97, which is expected to account for more than $3 billion in annual sales, may be facing an even bigger upgrade problem. The very complexity of the package, which is about 20 percent larger than Office 95, gives many users a reason not to risk overtaxing their machines to gain marginal improvement. Only 25 percent of users made the jump to Office 95 when the program was last upgraded.<p>
The Internet offers Microsoft a way to keep users upgrading and a potential source of new growth. Microsoft is "Web-enabling" all its software to make it easier to move directly from a program to the Web then back to the program. Work is under way to seamlessly link the next generation of such programs as Excel with the Internet so that a user can download information from the Web into a spreadsheet. Adding the Internet to the next upgrade, Microsoft's marketers have decided, provides the kind of improvement that will help drive sales. "The thinking is," says McNamee, "that people aren't paying for the functionality we've been adding so we'll Web-enable everything and people will pay us for that."<p>
The Internet also offers Microsoft opportunity for growth. Most Internet users now pay about $20 a month for Internet access. MSN is Microsoft's attempt to capture some of those dollars. Computer users who want MSN to be their gateway to the Internet can put the entire $20 into Microsoft's pocket.<p>
Microsoft also wants to get paid for content it creates, the primary reason for its investment ($220 million up front and $70 million a year) in MSNBC, a combined cable-TV news channel and Web page. Other Microsoft content either already on the Internet or under development includes Mungo Park, an adventure travel show that transmits video of its explorers to the Net, and Slate, a magazine of politics and culture edited by Michael Kinsley, formerly of The New Republic. Microsoft has said it plans to spend $300 million to $400 million annually to develop such content for at least the next three years.<p>
Microsoft's current course, while probably the best one the company could have adopted, should be seen for what it is -- a risky transition strategy whose success rests on proper timing and an unproven Internet business model. Web-enabling the newest generation of Office and the one thereafter gives the company a chance to preserve its revenue stream from upgrades of that product. "If Microsoft can maintain the value of the Office franchise, then it will keep growing at 25 percent a year," says McNamee. He also notes, however, that upgrading to a Web-enabled Office 97 makes no sense for much of the market. McNamee rates the company's chances of convincing a bare majority of users to upgrade to Ofce 97 as no better than 60-40. <p>
But Web-enabling its software is also risky: Microsoft may succeed in fending off Netscape, but its strategy will also accelerate the growth of the Internet and the World Wide Web.<p>
That has far-reaching effects on Microsoft's business model. Java makes it possible to embed programs in information. As a result, computer users won't need to activate a program like Excel to read or interpret data downloaded from the Internet. Instead, the data will arrive with their own spreadsheet or word-processing application -- an applet, in Java-speak -- already attached. <p>
Such downloads won't be free, of course. Data providers and software companies aim to collect fees for these transactions. Microsoft wants to sit "at the center of this huge array of transactions and collect a few cents every time someone uses their software in an application," says Murphy.<p>
This strategy could potentially channel a lot of revenue in Microsoft's direction but almost certainly at lower margins than Microsoft now enjoys. This won't be catastrophic for the company, but it could have big consequences for investors. As the table on page 67 shows, Microsoft's huge market capitalization hinges on its immense profitability. The company's 24.8 percent net profit margin humbles even such earnings machines as Coca-Cola and Merck. Put those high margins together with the company's extraordinary growth rate, and it's clear why Wall Street believes Microsoft is worth three Boeings -- even though Boeing's annual sales exceed $21 billion.<p>
But now consider what even a slight drop in margins does to the growth rate in Microsoft's earnings. If margins stay steady, sales growth of 35 percent a year translates into earnings growth of 35 percent. But if margins drop from their current 25 percent to just 22 percent -- still above the levels at Coke and Merck -- profit growth falls to 18 percent. (Microsoft's margin was 22 percent in the mid- to late 1980s, a period when the company still faced significant competition in the software market; it makes sense to expect the company to earn similar margins in the competitive Internet environment of the future.)<p>
If Microsoft can do no better than increase its earnings at an 18 percent annual clip -- still an impressive performance by virtually any measure -- investors should count on earning about 5 percent a year on the stock through the year 2001. Take a look at the chart titled "What If...," to see the troubling details.<p>
That chart, in fact, clearly lays out the choices facing an investor. If you believe this analysis is wrong and Microsoft will increase earnings at 25 percent a year or better, you should buy the stock. If earnings grow at 30 percent for the next five years, an investor in Microsoft should earn about 27 percent a year. Earnings growth of 25 percent annually should produce a 19 percent yearly gain.<p>
It's hard for me to imagine Microsoft increasing sales and earnings -- while keeping margins intact -- at those rates for that long. Microsoft's mature businesses won't produce those rates of growth and revenues from the new Internet business, which, though it's growing quickly, is pegged by Microsoft at no more than $2 billion a year at the end of this period. That doesn't make it another Office.<p>
No, the other growth scenarios in this chart are much more likely, and they result in annual returns to investors of just 11 percent and 5 percent. That's certainly not good enough to make me want to buy Microsoft at current price levels. I can find other software and technology stocks that are earlier in their growth cycles or had their prices knocked down in 1996 and are likely to give me higher returns than I can earn with Microsoft.<p>
Would I sell the stock at its recent price if I owned it? Not yet. Wall Street typically overvalues a stock by assuming current growth will continue forever. Microsoft is headed for such a banner 1997 that the market could well give the stock a more excessive valuation than it has now. Knockout December and March quarters could put even more of the company's future performance into the stock price. Which would, of course, give an investor even less reason to hang on for the long term.<p>
KEYWORDS:investment, technology, browser, Internet, high-tech

					</font>
