<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Personal Adviser:  Go Once, Go Twice</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Personal Adviser:  Go Once, Go Twice</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Wine lovers can't get enough of the Napa Valley auction<p>
By Rudy Maxa<p>
Here's the first rule for wine auctions held in fabulous settings: Don't expect bargains. Not that celebrations of the grape staged in such bucolic locations as Sonoma Valley and Napa Valley aren't terrific fun. The dinner parties, the vineyard tours, and the entertainment are all top-drawer. But when it comes to actually bidding on wine, that's more about charity and showmanship than about snaring a case of the grape below retail. <p>
Would you pay $28,000 for a six-liter bottle of the second release of Colgin-Schrader cabernet sauvignon? Or $42,000 for three three-liter bottles of the 1991, 1992, and 1993 Araujo Estate cabernet sauvignon? Those were winning bids last summer at the granddaddy of all the oh-so-social wine events, the Napa Valley Wine Auction, a fund-raiser held in Saint Helena, California. <p>
"The charity auctions have built up such a momentum now, people go to them not even concerning themselves about cost or price -- they've become events," says Jack Daniels, co-owner of Wilson Daniels Ltd., a prestigious wine-importing firm in Napa Valley. "The charities are the purpose behind them all, and that's why people are there. They have a tremendous time and do tend to get caught up in it."<p>
Since its inception 16 years ago, the big Napa auction has raised more than $11 million for local health-care organizations. And this four-day event (involving about 1,600 guests, who pay around $1,250 per couple) is so much fun that getting a ticket has become difficult. Invitations for this year's auction, scheduled for June 5 to 8, will be mailed in February, so now is the time to call for one (800-982-1371 or 707-942-9783, extension 901).<p>
The first day of the Napa auction, Thursday, is devoted to tasting unbottled wine from barrels (you may bid on cases during the weekend's silent auction). That evening, attendees dine in small groups (averaging 25 guests) at about 50 participating wineries, many of which hire celebrity chefs. Last summer, for example, Paul Bertolli of Oliveto in Oakland drove the stove for Robert Mondavi and his guests, while the chef and pastry chef from Manhattan's Les Celebrites did the honors at Beringer Vineyards.<p>
On day two, Napa wineries and restaurants offer special luncheon menus for auction guests as a prelude to the weekend's largest social event, the vintners' dinner at the sprawling Meadowood resort in Saint Helena. Always themed, the dinner is a raucous affair held under an enormous tent, with dancing till midnight. And the Napa crowd is big on dancing.<p>
Saturday is auction day, and with as many as 300 lots up for bid, the event can last seven hours. Local restaurants provide outdoor booths that offer house specialties. Staff circulate through the auction tent, liberally pouring from bottles of Napa wine carried in wire baskets. <p>
Casual and social as the auction is, the bidding reaches serious heights. Last summer's top lot fetched $150,000 from one of Napa's own, Vine Cliff owner Chuck Sweeney. What did he get for his winning bid? Four dinner parties -- one for each season -- anywhere in the U.S., hosted by groups of Napa vintners, plus an astounding 90 magnums of wine, one from each member of the wine growers' association. <p>
The second-highest winning bid bought a re-creation for six people of the historic 1976 Paris Tasting, a two-night event: Julia Child and Thomas Keller (of the Napa restaurant the French Laundry) prepared the first dinner at Stag's Leap; Wolfgang Puck cooked the next night at Chateau Montelena. Throw in a couple of nine-liter bottles of 1993 wines, and you've got the package that fetched the $100,000 winning bid from Dan Lynch, who got seriously rich seven years ago when he sold his computer trade-show company to publishing giant Ziff-Davis.<p>
You don't have to be Mr. or Ms. Gotrocks to enjoy the lovely June weather in Napa Valley or the festivities that surround the auction. But along with your ticket, you'll probably need a rental car and lodging. Meadowood resort and Auberge du Soleil are the two most coveted addresses; Accommodations Referral (800-240-8466), a local agency, can help you with a range of options. <p>
If Napa sounds a bit over the top, Sonoma Valley hosts a much more informal auction weekend over Labor Day for about half the cost of the Napa package. And with visits to Sonoma vineyards, wine seminars, and an auction with buffet dinner and dancing, it's just as much fun -- you get to see winemaker and comedian Tom Smothers do tricks with his yo-yo (for details, call 707-935-0803). "If Napa is a Mercedes, Sonoma is a pickup truck with a half-breed dog in the back," says Anthony Dias Blue, chairman of the Sonoma Valley event and a regular at the Napa auction. "But everybody likes it that way."<p>
KEYWORDS:
wine, travel, vineyard

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
