				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Personal Adviser:  Do This Now: Is It a Dream?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						New ways to find out if that deal really is too good to be true<p>
By Tom Nawrocki<p>
Sure, just as the endless late-night infomercials promise, there are fortunes to be made in real estate and franchised businesses, but even more fortunes have been made pushing shady get-rich-quick schemes. That's why the Federal Trade Commission, in cooperation with the North American Securities Administrators Association, has published a new series of free booklets to help consumers detect scams. <p>
The series includes the brochures Wealth-Building Scams, Work-at-Home Schemes, Multilevel Marketing Plans, Franchise Business Opportunities, and Business Opportunities: Avoiding Vending Machine and Display Rack Scams. Each contains pertinent questions to ask of potential business partners, as well as resources for more information and places to register complaints. To order any of the above titles, or for "Best Sellers," the FTC's complete list of consumer and business publications, write to Public Reference, Room 130, Federal Trade Commission, Washington, D.C. 20580. For more information, call the FTC at 202-326-3650, or check out the FTC Web site at <a HREF="http://www.ftc.gov.">http://www.ftc.gov.</A>
KEYWORDS:
consumer, government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
