	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Planes, Trains, and Autos</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						As a whole, the U.S. economy can do no better than the sum of its parts. So here's an industry-by-industry look at the year ahead -- from inside and out.<p>
Worth Staff Report<p>
The climate for business in the year ahead appears to be shaping up as a subdued version of 1996. Revenue and earnings growth will slow, but only slightly. Consumer spending will increase, but again, only slightly. Consolidations will be lower in number and in profile. <p>
The real action will be closer to the ground, within individual industry sectors. The profiles that follow summarize the outlook for 22 separate areas of enterprise -- from the most basic (steel and trucking) to the most complex (biotech and aerospace). They include perspectives from within each industry and from Wall Street.<p>
AGRICULTURE
OUTLOOK: Fields of genes.
Biotechnology will have a big impact throughout the farm belt. The first large-scale plantings of genetically altered crop seeds occurred in 1996, with encouraging results. New insect- and herbicide-resistant seeds produced significantly higher yields. Farmers' costs declined as well, because of the reduced need for chemical spraying. In 1997, usage will expand sharply, both in the U.S. and abroad. Not surprisingly, there is also a lot of legal scuffling over the patents for hybrid-seed technology. Industry alliances are basically split into two camps: one led by <a name="NYSE:MTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11010"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Monsanto</b></a>, the other by <a name="NASD:MYCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14178"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mycogen</b></a>. <p>
The excitement over mutant seeds notwithstanding, global agricultural prices are expected to decline in 1997.<p>
What the industry says: "The market just got a taste of this technology -- limited quantities in cotton, corn, and soybeans. In 1997, there are going to be significant quantities available. The technology's going to have a very high profile in terms of the value it delivers to farmers." (Carl Eibl, president and chief operating officer, Mycogen) <p>
What the Street says: "We're looking at a quantum leap in what genetic engineering can bring to the farmer, to the grain processors, and to the end user. But the proprietary-technology base is in the hands of a small number of companies. This ultimately could lead to the formation of agricultural-industrial complexes." (Sano Shimoda, analyst, BioScience Securities)<p>
Stocks to watch: Monsanto (NYSE: MTC) has made a number of outright and partial equity purchases in key biotech areas. It's dominant in herbicide-resistant hybrids. Mycogen (Nasdaq: MYCO), a much smaller company, has the jump in insect-resistant hybrid technology. <a name="NYSE:PHB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14440"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pioneer Hi-Bred</b></a> (NYSE:  PHB), the world's largest corn-seed company, has the biggest pool of germ plasm, the genetic material used to make hybrids.<p>
AIRLINES
OUTLOOK: Less turbulent.
Fares are expected to stabilize nationwide, except in the northeastern United States as <a name="NYSE:LUV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11377"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Southwest Airlines</b></a> continues to infiltrate that market. The reinstatement of a 10 percent excise tax on tickets, scheduled to take place around midyear (perhaps May), will hurt industry profits. Fuel-price uncertainty is also a concern. <p>
What the industry says: "Fare wars on the East Coast are going to be the story of the next couple of years." (Harry Lehr, vice president of finance, <a name="NYSE:ALK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10046"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alaska Air Group</b></a>) <p>
What the Street says: "The year 1997 will be strong for profits but poor for profit growth." (Sam Buttrick, analyst, PaineWebber)<p>
Stocks to watch: Alaska Air Group (NYSE: ALK) has cut its costs faster and further than any other air carrier in the history of the industry. Its ticket sales have also improved. Southwest (NYSE: LUV) is already in Baltimore and Providence. This airline is considered the best in the business in terms of financial discipline and performance, but it may have trouble maintaining its historic growth rate. Analyst Buttrick believes Southwest's stock may even take a short-term hit before resuming an upward trend.<p>
AUTOMOTIVE
OUTLOOK: High idle.
Barring a sharp hike in interest rates, which would raise the cost of auto loans and leases, automobile makers should come close to repeating their 1996 sales performance. <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a> forecasts industry-wide sales of 15 million to 15.5 million new cars and trucks in the U.S. for 1997, while 1996 is expected to come in at around 15 million units. That's below the 1986 U.S. record of 16.3 million, but still a respectable performance. Price increases should at least keep pace with inflation.<p>
U.S. automakers continue to benefit from rising demand for trucks (including minivans and sport utility vehicles), which bring in more profit than cars do and which have accounted for much of the strength in the market. U.S. producers also hold an edge in this area over the Japanese. <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyota</b></a>, <a name="NASD:NSANY"></a><b>Nissan</b>, and <a name="NYSE:HMC"></a><b>Honda</b>, however, intend to change that.<p>
What the industry says: "We don't see the Fed raising rates much. The consumer mood is good. There's some concern about the level of consumer debt -- we've been looking at higher delinquencies -- but we have not seen a falloff in auto sales because of it. Right now, we're running at pretty close to 95 percent of straight-time capacity. <p>
"What's got me worried the most is the position of the yen, which has weakened more than we had anticipated. This allows the Japanese to take a lot of profits home to reinvest." (Gary Valade, executive vice president and chief financial officer, Chrysler)<p>
What the Street says: "I expect a slight rise in interest rates in 1997, leading to flat sales and somewhat lower earnings." (Ronald Glantz, analyst, Dean Witter)<p>
Stocks to Watch: <a name="NYSE:OEA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12200"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>OEA</b></a>OEA (NYSE: OEA) makes air bags. Its sales have been growing at a 13.6 percent annual rate over the past three years, and this growth is sustainable. <a name="NYSE:AIZ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10072"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Amcast</b></a> (NYSE: AIZ) has spent a fortune on aluminum-component factories, an investment that should begin to pay off as the industry continues to use more of this lightweight, durable material.<p>
BIOTECHNOLOGY
OUTLOOK: Elevated moods.
Biotech companies are once again finding it possible to raise capital for research and development, either by tapping the equity markets or by partnering with established drug companies. One reason for this: Many biotech companies now have drugs in late-stage clinical trials and should continue to benefit from recent initiatives by the Food and Drug Administration to speed up the approval process, especially for products targeted to combat diseases like cancer and AIDS. <p>
What the industry says: "To be successful in our industry, you must have a strong pipeline of drugs." (Dr. Francesco Bellini, chief executive officer, Quebec-based BioChem Pharma, whose recently approved 3TC has quickly become one of the top-selling AIDS medicines)<p>
What the Street says: "There's an explosion of new products coming to the market." (Tim Wilson, analyst, UBS Securities, who also notes that 30 to 50 percent of the nearly 300 drugs in stage-two or -three clinical trials could eventually reach the market) <p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NASD:BCHXF"></a><b>BioChem Pharma</b> (Nasdaq: BCHXF) manufactures Lamivudine, a version of 3TC that could --  pending regulatory approval -- be used for the treatment of hepatitis B. <a name="NASD:CHIR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12972"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chiron</b></a> (Nasdaq: CHIR) has recently become profitable and has a number of promising drugs in late-stage clinical trials. <a name="NASD:LGND"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13469"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ligand Pharmaceuticals</b></a> (Nasdaq: LGND) has partnerships with a half dozen large drugmakers; these should help its broad product line.<p>
CHEMICALS
OUTLOOK: Lull before the fall.
The cyclical chemical industry is about to head into one of its down phases as capacity additions outstrip demand. Prices, and therefore profits, are expected to decline for the next several years. Prices for styrene monomer and its derivatives have already suffered steep declines and are hovering slightly above the breakeven point. Prices throughout the polymer chain (ethylene, polyethylene, and polyesters) are expected to weaken later in the year. <p>
What the industry says: "The real story in the near and long term is Asia and Latin America. We look forward to very strong growth in each of those areas. World economies will be improving in the next year." (Walter Tusinski, vice president and chief financial officer, <a name="NYSE:RCM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10024"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ARCO Chemical</b></a>)<p>
What the Street says: "Assuming demands stay good and costs high, prices become the swing vote. Capacity is going to be booming in the next few years." (James Kelleher, analyst, Argus Research)<p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:DD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10487"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Du Pont de Nemours</b></a> (NYSE: DD) should benefit from improving demand in Europe and Asia. It may also sell its petrochemical company, Conoco; the sale would contribute about a dollar a share to its 1997 earnings. <a name="NYSE:APD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10042"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Air Products & Chemicals</b></a> (NYSE: APD) provides a service to plants and refineries that helps them comply with pollution and safety standards. With most of its equipment in place, and capital spending thus winding down, the company is positioned for substantial profit growth. <p>
COMPUTER HARDWARE
OUTLOOK: NCs battle PCs.
Corporations spend $13,000 a year for each personal computer linked to a local area network, yet only 21 percent of that goes for the actual computer hardware and software, according to the Gartner Group, an information-technology research company in Stamford, Connecticut. The other $10,000 goes to technical support, system administration, and lost productivity as employees futz with their machines.<p>
In 1997, though, corporate buyers will have another way to go: the network computer. These machines offer the same network connectivity as the PC, but at a lower cost. They aren't encumbered with hard-drive storage or floppy disks. Instead, software applications and data reside in the network server, not on the desktop.<p>
<a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a>' JavaStation (list price: $742, without monitor) is the only network computer actually to reach the corporate market, but many of the top software and hardware companies have announced plans to produce their own versions in 1997.<p>
Interest in the new machines could spark industry sales. But they aren't likely to seriously dent the PC market for a while -- if ever. Most analysts still expect PC sales to grow at healthy double-digit rates in 1997. More powerful PCs that use <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>'s Pentium Pro chip and <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>'s Windows NT operating system will become an increasingly popular alternative to some low-end workstations.<p>
The downward pressure on prices should continue. U.S. computer makers also face increased competition from Japanese manufacturers.<p>
What the industry says: "It's going to be an interesting year, because for the first time in a very long time you are going to have a choice. Part of the real attractiveness of the NC is its minimalist functional utility." (Scott McNealy, chief executive officer, Sun Microsystems)<p>
What the Street says: "Personally, I think it's absurd to think there will be a mass migration to that machine." (Edward Keely, portfolio manager, Founders Growth Fund)<p>
Stocks to watch: Direct selling enables <a name="NASD:DELL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13193"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dell Computer</b></a> (Nasdaq: DELL) to keep its inventories low, giving it a big cost advantage over most other PC makers. <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>'s (NYSE: IBM) mainframe business could be surprisingly strong. As for Sun Microsystems (Nasdaq: SUNW): Does NC stand for no chance?<p>
COMPUTER SOFTWARE
OUTLOOK: More freebies.
Microsoft has made several bold moves to maintain its dominance, including marshaling PC makers to support its concept of a network computer that uses a Microsoft operating system (in response to the stripped-down, non-Windows machines offered by <a name="NASD:ORCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14337"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oracle</b></a> and Sun Microsystems). But as the focus of the industry shifts to applications that work on multiple computer-operating-system platforms, Microsoft may lose its control over the rate of software innovation. <p>
What the industry says: "What is really changing is that there's a new software platform -- based on [Sun's] Java script -- that people are using to create applications across platforms. The platform is now a level above the operating system and makes you less dependent on any given vendor." (Jim Clark, founder and chairman, <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape Communications</b></a>)<p>
"There is no one solution, no panacea. The reality is that everyone runs non-homogeneous, multivendor environments." (Charles Wang, chief executive officer, <a name="NYSE:CA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10383"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Computer Associates</b></a>)<p>
What the Street says: "We'll see an increasing level of data, and then functionality, get off-loaded onto the Internet. Ultimately, all local processing and storage could move to the network." (Jonathan Cohen, analyst, Smith Barney) <p>
Stocks to watch: Computer Associates' (NYSE: CA) multiplatform systems-management software is going to become increasingly important as more and more corporations network. Microsoft's (Nasdaq: MSFT) Office 1997 software could be another blockbuster for the company; the software integrates Internet tools with Microsoft's existing word-processing, spreadsheet, and database programs. Oracle (Nasdaq: ORCL) CEO Larry Ellison has been one of the biggest proponents of network computers.<p>
DEFENSE AND AEROSPACE
OUTLOOK: Opportunity enters the industry's orbit.
Military contractors have been on a rice-cakes-and-water diet since the end of the Cold War. But some have learned to cope without the fat defense budgets of the past. <a name="NYSE:MD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10975"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonnell Douglas</b></a> achieved record earnings in 1995, though its total payroll is now half of what it was in 1989. One bright spot: the boom in demand for space satellites, coming primarily from communications companies. Defense contractors best positioned to benefit from Sputnik Round Two include Hughes Electronics, <a name="NYSE:LMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10903"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lockheed Martin</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:LOR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47548"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Loral</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:ORBI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13046"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Orbital Sciences</b></a>. Orbital, in particular, is known for quick development of smaller, cheaper satellites. Its sales are expected to grow at a rate of 25 percent a year for the next three years. <p>
Of the few new major program initiatives, the most watched is the Joint Strike Fighter -- a $100 billion prototype program for the air force, navy, and marines. Boeing and Lockheed Martin are vying for the final contract. The winner will get an estimated $750 billion contract that will keep assembly lines humming for a generation. McDonnell Douglas, which is the largest military-aircraft manufacturer in the United States, suffered a painful blow when it was eliminated from the Joint Strike Fighter competition in November.<p>
The continued division of power between the White House and Congress following the November elections should neutralize the impact of politics on the industry.<p>
What the industry says: "The industry has a strong core base. The key issue is which companies are going to take advantage of that base and expand their business." (John Montague, vice president of financial strategies, Lockheed Martin) <p>
What the Street says: "It's the first time since the 1950s that the aerospace industry has had such a high growth opportunity." (Wolfgang H. Demisch, analyst, BT Securities, referring to the increased demand for space satellites)<p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boeing</b></a> (NYSE:  BA) is positioned for rapid earnings growth. Its production of commercial aircraft has nearly doubled -- from 18.5 planes a month in January 1996 to the current rate of 36 a month. The purchase of Rockwell International's defense-and-space division should also give Boeing a boost. Philip M. Conduit, Boeing's new chief executive officer, is well respected throughout the industry and the company. A host of commercial-jet suppliers -- all feeding at the same trough -- will benefit from Boeing's exploding commercial-jet business, including <a name="NYSE:UTX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11559"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Technologies</b></a> (NYSE: UTX), an engine manufacturer; <a name="NYSE:ALD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10062"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Allied Signal</b></a> (NYSE: ALD), which produces instrument panels; and <a name="NYSE:FA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10180"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fairchild</b></a> (NYSE: FA), which manufactures fasteners.<p>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES
OUTLOOK: Many shocks to the system.
Deregulation is coming, though it's far from clear whether this industry is prepared for it. The jolt will be cushioned, however, if the California model becomes a template that other states follow. California has mandated a deregulated pooling system to take effect as of January 1, 1998. But utilities will be compensated for assets that become worthless as a result of the change. Meanwhile, expect the frenzied pace of mergers and acquisitions in this industry to continue. <p>
What the industry says: "Companies that circle the wagons and try to defend their retail monopolies are ultimately going to lose out." (Stephen Baum, president, <a name="NYSE:ENA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11316"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Enova</b></a>, the parent of San Diego Gas & Electric)<p>
What the Street says: "Utilities need to figure out what business they want to be in, whether it's distribution, transmission, generation, or marketing. Companies that want to stay in the generation business had better work out plans with regulators to recover their investments." (Steve Fleishman, analyst, Merrill Lynch)<p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:CIN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42531"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CINergy</b></a> (NYSE: CIN) is the result of the combination of Cincinnati Gas & Electric and PSI Resources. This is Indiana's largest electric utility and a solid low-cost producer in the Midwest. <a name="NYSE:PSR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11220"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Public Service Company of Colorado</b></a> (NYSE: PSR) is merging with Southwestern Public Service, a Texas gas company, to form New Centuries. The combination creates a stronger corporation.<p>
FOOD
OUTLOOK: A recipe for improved corporate earnings.
Falling commodity prices should cut costs and improve profit margins, but many food-industry stocks are already selling at relatively high prices. That's partly because investors see this industry as a defensive play; it is likely to fare better than other categories if economic growth slows. Price competition in the cereal category is expected to fade.<p>
What the industry says: "In 1995 and 1996, we were looking at flour prices that had reached 20-year highs and packaging costs that went up about 25 percent. Now ingredient and packaging costs are falling. We're looking forward to good things." (Carl Watts, president and chief executive officer, <a name="NYSE:TBC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12367"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tasty Baking</b></a>)<p>
What the Street says: "Packaged-food companies should benefit from lower commodity prices, which might give them an edge in an otherwise inflationary economy." (Leonard Teitelbaum, analyst, Merrill Lynch)<p>
Stocks to watch: Tasty Baking (NYSE: TBC) has an arrangement with the 7-Eleven convenience-store chain that will expand distribution of Tasty's products and lower its distribution costs.<p>
HEALTH SERVICES
PROGNOSIS: Slow recovery.
The pressure to reduce costs and lower prices will persist. Health-maintenance organizations, however, may see some relief after two especially tough years. Whether that will happen in 1997 or 1998 is difficult to foresee. Hospitals face a tougher road; they have too many beds that they can't fill. <p>
What the industry says: "There is going to be continued cost pressures, especially on single-product companies." (Robert L. Ryan, senior vice president, <a name="NYSE:MDT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10981"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Medtronic</b></a>)<p>
What the Street says: "The issue in 1997 will be a renewed focus on changes in Medicare. It's not going to be easy to adjust to that. The government has been pumping 10 percent more into this industry every year." (Clifford "Kip" Hewitt, analyst, Sanford C. Bernstein & Co.)<p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:AET"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10039"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Aetna</b></a> (NYSE: AET) is in the midst of a major shift toward managed care. Medtronic (NYSE:  MDT) is expanding the use of implantable cardiac defibrillators.<p>
HEAVY MACHINERY
OUTLOOK: Downshifting in the U.S.
This business is at the peak of its cycle in the U.S. Sales of construction equipment are running at record levels. In contrast to past cycles, however, domestic equipment makers are better positioned to compete overseas and therefore soften the blow as sales in the U.S. taper off. John Deere, for instance, doubled its net sales with 30 percent fewer employees in the past ten years. <p>
What the industry says: "Investors are generally unaware of the growth potential for our businesses in Asia and the Pacific Rim." (Francis Corby, executive vice president, <a name="NYSE:HPH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10708"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Harnischfeger Industries</b></a>) <p>
What the Street says: "Any domestic sluggishness could be offset by growth in Asia. If Europe starts to show improvement, that would help even more." (Tobias Levkovich, analyst, Smith Barney) <p>
Stocks to watch: Harnischfeger Industries (NYSE: HPH) should benefit from new products, additional acquisitions, and gains in market share. <a name="NYSE:CAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10304"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Caterpillar</b></a> (NYSE: CAT) does 50 percent of its business overseas, where sales should continue to rise.<p>
HOME BUILDING
OUTLOOK: Lots of for sale signs.
Demand for new homes hasn't kept pace with production, and the inventory of unsold homes has been rising. Builders have been offering incentives -- ranging from cash discounts to free Buicks to island vacations -- and that's helped prop up buying but has hurt margins. Expect at least a modest decline in housing starts for 1997 -- to about 1.38 million from an anticipated 1.46 million in 1996.<p>
What the industry says: "We characterize the U.S. market as a 'preference market' as opposed to the 'shelter market' it used to be. Demand for housing no longer exceeds supply. We've got to entice people with lifestyle enhancements -- designs that make our homes attractive as well as affordable. We're not projecting a huge jump in interest rates, but we're already seeing a slowdown in sales with rates at very reasonable levels." (Robert K. Burgess, president, <a name="NYSE:PHM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11137"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pulte</b></a>) <p>
What the Street says: "During the next 6 to 12 months, I expect this sector to drastically underperform the market." (Greg Nejmeh, analyst, Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette) <p>
"We're not recommending buying any home builders." (Steve Dobi, analyst, Goldman Sachs)<p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:LEN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10891"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lennar</b></a> (NYSE: LEN) and <a name="NYSE:CTX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10308"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Centex</b></a> (NYSE: CTX) are both experiencing slowing home sales, but they have other businesses that are healthy: title insurance, captive mortgages, and construction products (Centex is the majority shareholder in Centex Construction Products, for example). <a name="NYSE:TOL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11488"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toll Brothers</b></a> (NYSE: TOL) and <a name="NYSE:DHI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15714"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>D. R. Horton</b></a> (NYSE: DHI) do nothing but build homes. Yet both have record backlogs and strong order flow. <p>
MEDIA
Outlook: Less favorable than 1996.
Publishers, especially newspapers, should benefit from sharply declining paper prices. Radio, a major beneficiary of the Telecommunications Act of 1996, is now facing opposition to some of the perks that came with the legislation, including provisions that relax and even remove the limitations on radio-station ownership. Broadcasters are focused on an upcoming Federal Communications Commission ruling that may allow one company to own two radio stations in a single market. <p>
What the industry says: "Radio has always been a kind of mom-and-pop business. But with the improved services to advertisers and listeners, the radio business is now able to compete with other media far better than it could in the past." (John Gehron, cochief operating officer, <a name="NASD:AMRD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Radio Systems</b></a>)<p>
What the Street says: "A rapid decline in both imprint and white-paper prices could produce cost savings, particularly in the newspaper business." (John Reidy, analyst, Smith Barney)<p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:GCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10623"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gannett</b></a> (NYSE: GCI) has yet to win the Street's notice for multimedia acquisitions that have greatly diversified its base. American Radio Systems (Nasdaq: AMRD) has favorable intermediate growth prospects because of the number of "sticks," or start-ups, it has. These start-ups could soon contribute to the company's revenue in a meaningful way. Though still thought of as newspaper outfits, <a name="NYSE:TRB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11508"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tribune Company</b></a> (NYSE: TRB) now gets 45 percent of its revenue from broadcasting, while the <a name="NYSE:WPO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12444"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Washington Post Company</b></a> (NYSE: WPO) derives more than 50 percent of its revenue from broadcasting and cable. These companies should become more attractive as higher-growth hybrids. <p>
OIL AND GAS
OUTLOOK: Neutral to positive.
The return of Iraqi oil, or anticipation of its return, will cause prices to fall at some point during 1997. But in the longer term, the pricing trend is still upward: Worldwide demand for petroleum continues to increase at an annual rate of about 2.5 percent. Refiners and drillers will do better in 1997 than the exploration and production companies.<p>
What the industry says: "If everyone weren't convinced that we are in store for a long sustained demand for energy, the big international oil companies wouldn't be drilling in expensive waters like the deepwater Gulf of Mexico." (David Lesar, executive vice president, <a name="NYSE:HAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10697"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Halliburton</b></a>)<p>
What the Street says: Earnings of exploration and production companies "may suffer due to the negative impact on pricing from the return of Iraqi oil to the market. But oil stocks in general may still benefit in the long run." (Michael Mayer, analyst, Schroder Wertheim)<p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:MOB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11006"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mobil</b></a> (NYSE: MOB) has above-average earnings and dividend growth as well as above-average growth in oil-and-gas production. Yet it is trading at a discount on earnings and cash flow to its peer group. <a name="NYSE:PZL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11164"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pennzoil</b></a> (NYSE: PZL) could achieve a 50 percent increase in earnings, thanks in part to its joint venture with Conoco and an upgrade of its refinery in Shreveport, Louisiana. <p>
PHARMACEUTICALS
OUTLOOK: Companies will be surfing a demographic wave. 
Older people use more drugs, and the number of people over age 65 will grow 17 percent by the year 2000. <p>
The ongoing pressure to reduce health-care costs also points toward an increase in the use of drugs. Drug sales through managed-care firms are expected to grow anywhere from 53 percent to 90 percent by the end of the decade. <p>
Industry profit margins have also been improving -- the result of cost cutting by drugmakers, higher industry-wide prices, and rising volume. A regulatory environment that is more friendly to this industry hasn't hurt either. One concern to keep in mind: A number of important, high-volume drugs lose their patent protection in 1997 and face competition from generics. These big-name drugs include <a name="NYSE:GLX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41781"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Glaxo Wellcome</b></a>'s Zantac, an ulcer treatment with $3.5 billion in sales in 1995, and Zovirax, an antiviral drug with $1.3 billion in 1995 sales. Patents expire in 1999 for <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a>'s Mevacor, a cholesterol medicine with $1.2 billion in sales in 1995, and in 2000 for Vasotec, a high-blood-pressure medicine with $1.9 billion in 1995 sales.<p>
What the industry says: "The pendulum is swinging in managed care, as there is more agreement that many drugs provide cost-effective treatment of chronic disease as well as help prevent illness." (David Shedlarz, chief financial officer, <a name="NYSE:PFE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11175"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pfizer</b></a>) <p>
What the Street says: "In this economy there are a lot of reasons to invest in defensive growth companies. Many of the pharmaceutical companies offer consistent earnings growth at reasonable valuations to the market and on a historical basis." (Kenneth Nover, analyst, A. G. Edwards & Sons)<p>
Stocks to watch: Pfizer (NYSE:  PFE) is the industry darling. It will bring nine new drugs to market in the next few years, including Aricept, an Alzheimer's treatment, and Atorvastatin, a cholesterol treatment. It also recently won approval to broaden the use of Zoloft, an antidepressant that competes with <a name="NYSE:LLY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10509"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eli Lilly</b></a>'s (NYSE: LLY) Prozac. Zoloft is the number-two seller behind Prozac in the $4 billion antidepressant market, and Zoloft's earnings are expected to grow 20 percent in 1997 and 17 percent in 1998.<p>
<a name="NYSE:PNU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11570"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pharmacia & Upjohn</b></a> (NYSE: PNU) is the result of a 1995 merger of these two companies that paved the way for substantial cost savings. The quality of the company's future product offerings, however, remains uncertain. <p>
RAILROADS
OUTLOOK: On track.
Two competitive railroad systems emerged in the West when Burlington Northern merged with Sante Fe in 1995 to form <a name="NYSE:BNI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10250"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Burlington Northern Sante Fe</b></a> and when <a name="NYSE:UNP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11544"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Union Pacific</b></a> acquired Southern Pacific in 1996. A similiar scenario has unfolded in the East, where <a name="NYSE:CSX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10274"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CSX</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:NSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11084"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Northfolk Southern</b></a> have vied to buy Conrail. Efficiencies resulting from these mergers will help the industry become more competitive with trucking.<p>
What the industry says: "If we can avoid ice storms and auto strikes, 1997 will be a good year for the rail industry." (Howard Keen, chief economist, <a name="NYSE:CRR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10395"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Conrail</b></a>) <p>
What the Street says: "This industry continues to get more efficient. It is also leveraging its efficiency by improving service." (Anthony B. Hatch,  analyst, NatWest Securities)<p>
Stocks to watch: CSX (NYSE: CSX) and Norfolk Southern (NYSE: NSC) are in a battle to buy Conrail (NYSE: CRR). Whoever wins could emerge as the dominant railroad force in the East. <p>
RETAIL
OUTLOOK: <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a> founder Sam Walton spins in his grave.
When the final numbers are tallied, the Christmas selling period will turn out to have been a pretty good one for retailers -- not spectacular, but not nearly as bad as the pessimists feared. Sales in the spring, though, could be weak. They aren't likely to equal the strong first quarter of 1996. Such a scenario could leave retailers overstocked by April, forcing markdowns. Retailers that keep the reins on inventory should enter summer in the best shape. <p>
What the industry says: "People are buying more for need than when the urge hits them. This is leading to more-compressed selling seasons." (Robert G. Galvin, chief financial officer, <a name="NYSE:NIN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15956"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nine West</b></a>) <p>
What the Street says: "For every success story, there's another retailer in Chapter 11 that will never come back." (Saul Yaari, analyst, Piper Jaffray)<p>
Stocks to watch: Wal-Mart (NYSE: WMT), the world's largest retailer, has struggled in recent years after saturating its prime rural markets. Same-store sales rose only 4 percent in 1996, compared with 6 to 7 percent in 1994 and 1995. International expansion has yet to pay off. Price competition throughout the retail sector could cut further into Wal-Mart's profit.<p>
<a name="NYSE:TIF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11481"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tiffany</b></a> (NYSE: TIF) hasn't had to advertise a sale since 1985. Its same-store sales grew 12 percent in the first half of 1996. The recent opening of a flagship store in Tokyo was well received. Tiffany plans to increase retail space by 5 to 7 percent over the next few years. Earnings are expected to increase at a 20 percent annual rate for several more years.<p>
SEMICONDUCTORS
OUTLOOK: Back in the chips.
Demand has begun to turn around (sales fell an estimated 10 percent in 1996), helped by strong personal-computer shipments and an increased need for specialized chips used in consumer electronics. Industry experts expect semiconductors to emerge from their down cycle by the second half of 1997. One caveat: The semiconductor industry is global -- about two-thirds of its sales are now generated outside the U.S. -- and its turnaround depends on improvements in foreign economies as well. <p>
What the industry says: "My 35 years of [chip-making] experience leads me to believe that, by the second quarter of 1997, production and consumption will be in balance and prices will tend to stabilize." (Pasquale Pistorio, chief executive officer, <a name="NYSE:STM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42481"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SGS-Thomson Microelectronics</b></a>) <p>
What the Street says: "We're moving back to an era of diversified electronics driving demand." (Drew Peck, analyst, Cowen & Co.) <p>
Stocks to watch: Intel's (Nasdaq: INTC) Pentium Pro sales will feed its microprocessor monopoly, but analysts say Intel's stock may be volatile in 1997 because its fortunes are so dependent on PC sales. <a name="NYSE:MU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Micron Technology</b></a>'s (NYSE: MU) 16-megabit dynamic random-access-memory chip has sold well, and the company's costs are falling, but don't expect Micron Technology's share price to come anywhere close to its 1995 highs. Only a quarter of SGS-Thomson's (NYSE: STM) sales are PC-related, and its broad mix of differentiated chips are well positioned for the next up cycle.<p>
STEEL
OUTLOOK: Flat at best.
New mini-mills are starting up, existing mills are operating at peak capacity, and foreign producers continue to glut the U.S. market. Upshot: price wars and lower profits. The falling yen has played a major role in this equation, as has a lackluster European economy, by prompting producers to ship greater volumes to the U.S. Upcoming negotiations with the Big Three automakers could prove pivotal. <p>
What the industry says: "My crystal ball tells me 1997 will be a lot like 1996, with slow, steady growth." (John Correnti, president, Nucor) <p>
"If you ask me what I lie awake at night and think about, it's exchange rates. The Japanese yen, for example." (Paul J. Wilhelm, president, U.S. Steel Group of USX) <p>
What the Street says: "Automobile sales have been relatively flat but very strong. So steel producers in the United States will go into contract negotiations with an advantage. We would not be surprised to see trade suits -- in the form of dumping and subsidy actions against importers -- implemented much as they were in late 1992." (Robert J. Schenosky, analyst, Merrill Lynch) <p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:OS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12208"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oregon Steel Mills</b></a> (NYSE: OS) is a mini-mill that manufactures pipe and tubing used by the oil-and-gas industry. <a name="NYSE:AKS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17195"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AK Steel Holding</b></a> (NYSE: AKS), an integrated steel company, has the highest profitability in the business. <a name="NASD:WTHG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Worthington Industries</b></a> (Nasdaq: WTHG) processes steel sheet and is refocused on growth.<p>
TELECOMMUNICATIONS
OUTLOOK: Busy signals.
Telecommunications will continue to grow rapidly. Yet who will benefit and who won't remains unclear. The Telecommunications Act of 1996 was supposed to create the framework for the future. But several key issues -- such as whether to allow long-distance and regional Bell companies to compete on one another's turf -- will remain tied up in the courts until at least mid-1997.<p>
Meanwhile, the Baby Bells continue to seek growth through increased services, such as installing new types of phone lines that transmit data faster. The planned $21.8 billion merger of <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:BTY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41763"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>British Telecom</b></a> -- with the new company to be called Concert -- puts even more pressure on <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> and the Bells. The full impact of this transaction, however, won't be felt until after its completion, which is scheduled for the end of 1997.<p>
The much-anticipated shift in the United States from analog to digital technology will pave the way for an upgrade to digital phones and allow for increased transmission of data. Handset makers await the shift to higher-margin digital phones. Meanwhile, the wireless industry is bracing for the arrival of personal communications services, or PCSs. <p>
What the industry says: "The confusion in the marketplace right now is creating more opportunity and choices than ever before." (Irwin Mark Jacobs, chairman and chief executive officer, Qualcomm)<p>
What the Street says: "I'm not bullish on anything." (Bette Ann Massick Colombo, analyst, Bear Stearns, referring to the three long-distance carriers and the regional Bell telephone companies)<p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:BEL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10197"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bell Atlantic</b></a> (NYSE: BEL) could benefit from its pending acquisition of <a name="NYSE:NYN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11044"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>NYNEX</b></a>, as well as from a strengthening economy in the Northeast. <p>
Can AT&T (NYSE: T) bounce back the way IBM did? Or will it follow Western Union on the long, downhill slope into oblivion? The appointment of R. R. Donnelley & Sons' John R. Walter as AT&T's president has done little -- so far -- to resolve that question.<p>
TRUCKING
OUTLOOK: Computerizing.
Capacity has fallen back in line with demand in the past few years; this has helped to ease the pressures on pricing. But carriers are continuing to focus on cutting their costs and improving their margins rather than on expansion.<p>
What the industry says: "The industry is aggressively looking for ways to cut costs through the use of better technology. It can't raise prices." (Edward Arnold, chairman, Arnold Industries) <p>
What the Street says: "Investors need to be vigilant. Trucking stocks are undervalued right now, but only if the economy remains stable." (Jeffrey Kauffman, analyst, Merrill Lynch)<p>
Stocks to watch: <a name="NYSE:CNF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10393"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Consolidated Freightways</b></a> (NYSE: CNF) is spinning off its unionized CF MotorFreight unit but retaining its more nimble, non-union short-haul and airfreight businesses. <a name="NASD:SWFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15252"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Swift Transportation</b></a> (Nasdaq: SWFT) has a successful acquisition strategy, a clearly defined market niche, and the ability to grow regardless of economic conditions. <a name="NYSE:CBB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14596"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Caliber System</b></a> (NYSE: CBB) has disappointed investors consistently but remains the only trucking stock with a chance to double.<p>
Dave Califano, Paul Davies, John Fried, Deborah Jermanok, Ken Kurson, Jim Melloan, and Michael Peltz contributed to this story.<p>
KEYWORDS: analysis, prediction, pick

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
