	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Kicking the Tires</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Kicking the Tires</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Trucking stocks, long the market's laggards, look like bargains -- a few actually are<p>
By Amy Barrett<p>
Buying trucking stocks over the past three years has been the investing equivalent of purchasing an Edsel. Shackled by high operating costs and intense competition, even the better-managed trucking companies have been unable to find favor on the Street, and their stocks have been left in the dust.<p>
**Yellow Corp. -- which hasn't turned a profit since 1993 -- may make money next year.**<p>
A group that has languished during this market rally while virtually every industry has surged is enough to make any bargain hunter salivate. Especially when analysts start predicting that industry bellwether <a name="NASD:YELL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15192"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yellow Corp</b></a>. (which hasn't had a profitable year since 1993) may make money next year. Yellow is expected to turn its $1.07-a-share loss in 1995 into a 71-cent gain in 1997, according to earnings estimates collected by Zacks Investment Research. And Yellow is not alone -- Wall Street expects the trucking industry's earnings to jump 32 percent next year. "Certainly there is a value story to be told here," says Douglas Rockel, a trucking-industry analyst at New Yorkbased broker Furman Selz. <p>
An industry full of undervalued stocks just waiting to rally -- it sounds too good to be true. And it is. Not every trucking company is headed for a turnaround, says Rockel, and investors will have to pick carefully. As he says, "There are some good trucking companies out there.'' And some laggards that will remain stuck in low gear. <p>
**How to find a worthwhile trucking company.**<p>
To find the good companies, start by understanding how the trucking industry as a whole suffered such a wreck. As analysts tell it, the companies got sideswiped by wildly fluctuating demand. They ramped up their fleets in 1994, only to see freight traffic nosedive in the wake of the Mexican peso crisis in December 1994. Burdened with excess capacity, they lowered prices in hopes of filling all those empty trucks. Many lost money.<p>
That situation isn't going to turn around quickly. Competition can be brutal, because the barriers to entering this business are virtually nonexistent (it takes only one enterprising person to start a trucking company). That's why Jeffrey Kauffman at <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> thinks it could take the trucking industry many years to consolidate, pare costs, and become more efficient. So for now, analysts advise investors to choose among two segments of the industry with the greatest growth potential: the truckload carriers and the regional less-than-truckload companies. <p>
**These trucking companies are worth further investigation.**<p>
Truckload carriers travel directly from the shipper to the drop-off point, while LTLs concentrate on a single area of the country and bundle cargoes at their own shipping terminals. Companies worth considering are <a name="NASD:AIND"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12659"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Arnold Industries</b></a> and <a name="NASD:ODFL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10432"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Old Dominion Freight Line</b></a> among the regionals and <a name="NASD:SWFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15252"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Swift Transportation</b></a>, <a name="NASD:WERN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15136"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Werner Enterprises</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:LSTR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16155"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Landstar System</b></a> among the national truckload carriers. <p>
These companies should benefit from three important trends. First, many manufacturers are finding it more efficient to outsource their shipping operations than to maintain a private fleet, in part because of the increasing use of technology to provide better and faster service. Merrill's Kauffman expects some $15 billion in revenue to migrate from private fleets to LTLs and truckload carriers over the next five years. Second, the shift to just-in-time inventory means companies are using truckers more frequently for smaller, more time-sensitive shipments. And third, last year's deregulation of intrastate shipping (interstate trucking was deregulated in 1980) is beginning to separate the wheat from the chaff. Companies that have been able to cut costs are stealing business from competitors. <p>
**Arnold and Yellow illustrate the concerns in the trucking industry.**<p>
Consider the divergent fortunes of industry giant Yellow Corp. and a regional carrier such as Arnold Industries. Yellow has struggled to reorganize its overbuilt hub-and-spoke networks by offering more direct point-to-point service along the most heavily traveled routes. Yellow's stock -- recently trading at 19 times 1997's projected earnings (the stocks in the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index show an average multiple of 14 on 1997 estimated earnings) -- already discounts a turnaround.<p>
Arnold Industries, however, offers more direct service through truckload and LTL subsidiaries. And its stock trades at just 13 times 1997 earnings estimates. Also, Arnold, which plans to acquire a private company in Salt Lake City, has been steadily adding business. <p>
LTLs "are a good value versus the rest of the market now,'' says Renee Weaver, analyst at Wheat First Butcher Singer, a brokerage based in Richmond, Virginia. Wall Street projects an earnings rebound at Arnold: to $1.26 a share in 1997, up from an estimated $1.03 this year. Weaver thinks Arnold could reach $28 a share in the next 12 months from a recent price of $16. <p>
**Old Dominion may be a big bargain due to a dip in the stock price in the last 3 months.**<p>
Old Dominion, an LTL based in High Point, North Carolina, may be an even bigger bargain, says Weaver. The company's stock suffered a major slide in the past three months, at one point dipping below its book value of eight dollars a share. (Book value is the net value of all the company's assets divided by the number of shares outstanding.) That alone signals a good buy. What's more, Old Dominion could increase earnings per share by almost 50 percent next year, thanks partly to the company's expansion into Colorado, Nevada, and New Mexico, Weaver says. She thinks the stock could return to $13 a share in the next 12 months. <p>
Salomon Brothers' James Valentine has whittled down his dream fleet to Swift Transportation, Werner Enterprises, and Landstar System, all truckload carriers. They should benefit this year from stabilizing shipping rates, he believes. At Landstar, which has been helped by cost cutting and two acquisitions in 1995, Valentine sees 20 percent earnings growth next year. Werner's earnings could rise 15 percent in the second half of this year, says Valentine, who calls the company "one of the best-run truckload carriers." Valentine predicts earnings at Swift Transportation will jump 38 percent in 1997. <p>
Investors headed down this highway could still suffer a flat if costs kick up. Although the LTLs and truckload carriers use cheaper non-union labor, a recent shortage of drivers could force some companies to boost their pay. And if the economy starts to stall, revenues will sputter. But even with such caveats, these stocks look like relatively safe buys. Their low prices give investors a safety margin in a high-priced market.<p>
<img src="/imgs/p139cht(475X210).gif" width=475 height=210><p>
KEYWORDS:transportation, truck, stock, industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
