	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Genius, Gurus, & Grumpy Old Men</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Genius, Gurus, & Grumpy Old Men</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Welcome to the world of investing newsletters, where YOU HAVE TO SHOUT TO BE HEARD!<p>
By Mike Steere<p>
Asking Bill Bonner to talk about his life and work is probably a mistake. Bonner -- sworn enemy of the equivocal and the un-grandiose, a man who has done for investment-newsletter marketing what Richard Wagner did for grand opera -- ought to introduce himself via direct mail.<p>
**Newsletter editors like Bonner tend to use stylized text to make their points.**<p>
You DON'T know this man, but you should -- he's the KING of the long-copy, big-idea NEWSLETTER promo.<p>
Meet BILL BONNER and Learn how direct-mail VIRTUOSITY and a stable of way-off-center financial GURUS have brought one 48-year-old...<p>
      A chateau in France. 
      Maryland's premier goat-cheese-producing rural estate. 
      A booming international company with $75 million in annual     sales.<p>
Meet him TODAY and get FIVE BONUSES, absolutley FREE!<p>
ONE Boggle at what Bonner and his people do to call attention to their mailings.<p>
TWO Wonder if Bill has telepathic connections with the night terrors, hopes, and anger of cranky gray-hairs with a few hundred thousand in the market -- the core readership of investment letters.<p>
THREE Discover newsletters' ugly secret -- atrocious graphic design pays!<p>
FOUR See behind the hype into Bill's private world of intellect and high ideals.<p>
FIVE Puzzle over the contradictions between a quiet and gentle man -- idolized by staffers, liked and admired even by competitors -- and his frantic, ego-driven business.<p>
**Agora Publishing specializes in the "magalog."**<p>
Of course, Bonner and his company, Baltimore-based Agora Publishing, would do it in some much more artful and engaging way. They'd keep doing it, too, for many thousands of words. Then they'd send out a few hundred thousand pieces. A magalog (direct-mail talk for a magazine-like promo or catalog) can run 30 pages, the length of "Who Murdered Vince Foster?" a political-conspiracy pitch for James Dale Davidson's Strategic Investment letter. A bookalog can go well over 100 pages, as did "The Coming Mutual Fund Meltdown." This pseudo-paperback, with full-color mushroom cloud on the cover, was testimony for Dr. Gary North's apocalyptic biblical-financial Remnant Review.<p>
Coming from Agora, with the imprimatur and often the hands-on involvement of William Robert Bonner, every word in these things is a jab at humanity's animal core -- fear, greed, will to power. They're also wonderful, if sometimes twisted, entertainment.<p>
**Meet Bonner -- who seems to be the opposite of his direct-mail personality would lead you to believe.**<p>
In person, Bonner turns out to be quieter than his thunderclap copy. He speaks in resonant bass, in an accent both Northern and plantation South, like his native seaboard Maryland. You think of a prep-school English teacher who also coaches basketball. He's lean and angular in khakis, button-down shirt, and tie, his dress of choice for as long as anybody can remember. The face, under sparse raven hair, is all planar surfaces and bridge-girder jaw.<p>
Bonner folds his six feet, three inches into a booth at City Cafe, a yupscale spoon in Baltimore's Mount Vernon district, a few blocks from the restored Victorian-era mansions where Agora is headquartered. "We're succeeding," he says. The numbers say it more emphatically than he does. In the past two years, Agora's sales have grown from $55 million to $75 million. This growth is flat by Agora standards; the company has been digesting the book and newsletter publishers it bought in a 1994 binge. Agora owns newsletter-publishing companies in England, New Jersey, and Florida, as well as general-readership book publishers in the U.S. and England. It publishes 40 newsletters with a combined circulation of about 650,000.<p>
**The investing newsletters reach for people eager to be richer, happier, and more productive.**<p>
The most provocative of these are the investment letters that emanate from the home office in Baltimore, including six "guru" titles published in partnership with outside personalities/authorities (i.e., gurus). Agora does guru-less letters, too, and operates an investors' club with its own monthly letter. A new division of the company publishes newsletters from health gurus, including the celebrated diet rebel and medical contrarian Dr. Robert Atkins.<p>
The investment letters have paid for this diversifying empire, but not necessarily because they're making subscribers rich. Bonner, who characterizes his letters as bear market and hard money, even apocalyptic, says the early-1990s market run-up has been tough. Lately, Mr. and Ms. Buy-and-Hold have gotten fat returns in mutual funds without resorting to Swiss annuities, as Dr. North recommends, or the Bulgarian Brady bond, favorably mentioned in Strategic Investment.<p>
"Being contrary in the last couple years was not a good posture," Bonner says.<p>
Bonner speaks a refrain he uses to pump up his staff: "People don't wake up in the morning and say, 'Gee, I think I'll subscribe to a newsletter. Honey, we're out of newsletters!'"<p>
Nor do they want more information. They want what information can yield. "They want to be richer, happier, healthier, more productive," Bonner says. "We try to go directly to those emotional points.<p>
"Boredom is the great enemy," he says. "There is no glory in softness."<p>
**Mark Hulbert and his crew sort through financial newsletters to find the ones whose suggestions make the most sense.**<p>
Unlike the rest of us, who reflexively throw out envelopes bellowing BECOME A WALL STREET MILLIONAIRE THE NO-RISK WAY! Mark Hulbert and his staff date-stamp and file every single investment-letter pitch they get. By year's end, the collection overflows a deep drawer in the Alexandria, Virginia, headquarters of The Hulbert Financial Digest, an influential newsletter about newsletters.<p>
The Financial Digest pierces the fog of newsletter hype with rigorous statistical science. Since 1980, it has produced ratings and rankings of the real-market performances of investment letters' recommendations. Staffers mine the mail-package collection for periodic attacks on inflated performance claims.<p>
The 40-year-old Hulbert and his numbers have brought newsletters greater respect in the mainstream investing world, which traditionally has regarded them as dclass, if not frauds. The Financial Digest has validated letters by proving that letter gurus' investment advice is every bit as good as anybody else's. Four out of five newsletter editors fail to beat the market. But so do 80 percent of other investment pros. Hulbert says his work shows that the best newsletter gurus are world-class, "doing work that is the envy of the top finance researchers in the country."<p>
(Hulbert avoids personal opinions and lets his numbers do the talking. They speak loudest about The Chartist and The Value Line Investment Survey, both of which earned 15.8 percent annual returns over the past 15 years.)<p>
"I feel somewhat defensive of the industry as a whole, that people are going to throw out the baby with the bathwater," Hulbert says. Given his oblique and precise manner of speaking, this is powerful personal testimony.<p>
PART II<p>
Hulbert receives about 400 letters and rates 160 of them. His role, as Dr. Statistical Science, requires him to put the cold "what" of performance above the "how" and "why" and other distractions. "If they're looking at tea leaves, if they're looking at a comic strip [as a guru once did], I don't care what it is if they can beat the market in a statistically significant way," Hulbert says. "We take an absolutely, ruthlessly empirical approach."<p>
**The Hulbert Financial Digest used to be one of Bonner's letters -- until Hulbert bought him out.**<p>
This seems like a long way from Baltimore and Bonner, whose stock-in-trade is the screamingly anti-empirical side of the business. But The Hulbert Financial Digest is the firstborn financial newsletter of Bill Bonner, who was a founding partner of Hulbert's. After the then-infant Agora added other investment letters, Hulbert bought full ownership of his digest to avoid conflicts of interest.<p>
"I'd call him a friend, yeah," Hulbert says of Bonner. Friendship does not, however, get in the way of the mission. Hulbert's most recent ratings show that none of the five Agora letters he rates beat the market in either the first half of this year or multiyear periods.<p>
**Hulbert's drawer of newsletters inspires based on the sheer number of outlandish claims.**<p>
Digging through Hulbert's drawer of direct mail is a supreme adventure in shameless braggadocio and bad taste. Even Hulbert shows a gut reaction. "The stereotypic newsletter editor is a lunatic self-promoter," he says. "You look at some of these advertisements and see why that stereotype is perpetuated." But he also acknowledges the primacy of direct mail in the business: "Newsletters are a stepchild of the direct-mail industry," he once told the Baltimore Sun.<p>
If so, the mailings are the demon seed. The first hour of gaudy megalomania, saying "I'm right, and the rest of the world is wrong; I see the future, but your stupid broker doesn't have a clue," bolstered with insane performance claims -- gain 1,213 percent! -- brings on perceptual shock. If copy were audio, I'd be deaf. As it is, I'm suffering visual trauma caused by huge type in horrible colors, geeky photos of the letter- writing gurus, and page upon page of cramped text.<p>
**Tricks used by direct-mail publishers are attempts to extend survival time.**<p>
You can't blame the mailers for making a commotion. A direct-mail package lives or dies in something like four seconds. The tricks used by publishers to disguise pitch pieces -- as magazines, tabloids, books, personal letters -- are attempts to extend survival time. A magalog might be stacked with magazines, to be read later instead of thrown out, says Denny Hatch, editor of the industry letter Who's Mailing What! Then, when you pick it up, he says, "it just screams!"<p>
What it screams depends on the product. "Traditional investment letters appeal purely to greed," Hatch observes. This explains the headlining of gains. With less traditional, more ideological letters, the pitch may probe for a core of political antipathy or fear. Direct mail is a portrait not just of newsletters but also of their subscribers.<p>
Investment letters exist in a sort of statistical vacuum. The best estimate is that there are 1,000 to 1,100 of them. Since a 1985 U.S. Supreme Court decision freed their editors from mandatory Securities and Exchange Commission registration as investment advisers, nobody has kept an official count. No outside group audits circulations, so circulations are self-reported, if they're reported at all. George Wein, who brokers subscriptions to some 500 letters through his Select Information Exchange, says that less than 10 percent have 10,000 or more subscribers. The leading guru, in total subscribership, seems to be Louis Rukeyser, whose stock and mutual-fund letters report a combined circulation of about 350,000. Only a few letters are in the 100,000-subscriber range.<p>
**There is a definite target audience for the newsletters: Well-off males older than 50.**<p>
Estimates of the number of prime subscription prospects converge at about four million. The pros are absolutely in sync about who this core readership is.<p>
"You're male. You're in your 50s or older," says Walter Pearce, a publisher of investment letters for KCI Communications in McLean, Virginia. <p>
"Not super, super rich, but people who are definitely well off," Pearce goes on. "Basically, they're do-it-yourselfers. They've been burned by their brokers, or they've been dissatisfied with their financial advisers. They think they can do better jobs themselves."<p>
The profile in three words:<p>
Grumpy old men.<p>
**The letters yell the sorts of things grumpy old men yell at one another.**<p>
Once you know the target, the strange, peevish style of investment letters -- the way they're marketed, the letters themselves -- makes perfect sense. When they're not yelling about huge returns from brilliant stock picks, timing calls, and political-economic analyses, the letters yell the sorts of things that grumpy old men yell at one another.<p>
The common thread is us versus them, beginning with distrust of the financial establishment. "Newsletters are offering themselves as an alternative to Wall Street," Mark Hulbert says. "They're saying, 'Don't go with your personal broker....Wall Street is not the defender of the small guy.'" Beyond the antipathy toward Wall Street are politics that lean anti-government right, as part of a general phobia of institutions. The Ron Paul Survival Report asks, with a straight face, "Is Bill Clinton a Spy?" Anti-Clintonism, a staple of investment letters, redlines in a bogus top-secret government report from The Wall Street Underground letter, which lays 56 murders at the White House door.<p>
Low-circulation letters look exactly like what they are -- one-man, kitchen-table productions banged out fast and on the cheap. Large-circulation letters have the resources to be gorgeous but generally hew to the kitchen-table look. Ugliness is stagecraft; the spindly typewriter-style lettering is the pancake makeup. Long after the last Selectric has been scrapped, we'll be straining our eyes on pseudo-IBM typing generated by computers. Dick Wambach, who edits the industry letter Newsletter Design, says the ransom-note look appalls him. On the other hand, slick and pretty would probably lose readers. The information might seem less fresh, the voice of truth less lonely and embattled. "If success looks like garbage," Wambach says, "make your letter look like garbage."<p>
PART III<p>
It stands to reason that investment letters don't shout about their connections with big multi-letter publishing houses. Agora and its two counterparts, Phillips Publishing and KCI Communications, reveal themselves reluctantly in Hulbert's drawerful of direct mail. To see them at all, you've got to watch return addresses. Promos for Elaine Garzarelli's recent launch, The Garzarelli Outlook, and John Dessauer's Investor's World originate in Potomac, Maryland, home of Phillips. Subscription forms for Louis Rukeyser's Mutual Funds and Stephen Leeb's Personal Finance go back to KCI and its corporate siblings in McLean. From Baltimore comes the sound and fury of the Agora letters.<p>
**Phillips, Agora, and KCI are the big three in newsletter publishing.**<p>
These three publishers began in the 1970s in the manner of Silicon Valley start-ups, with very little to offer the world but the ideas, brains, and energy of their founders. They're clustered around Washington, D.C., because of the city's enormous traffic in specialized communications from trade, industrial, and political interest groups. Phillips is this sea's giant octopus, with annual sales of $227 million, versus $75 million for Agora and $45 million for KCI's parent company, National Information Corporation. Counting investment newsletters and nothing else, however, the companies are more closely matched.<p>
Investment-letter editors join publishers for the same reasons that feudal lords once threw in with kings. "It's tough out there," says Doug Fabian, a second-generation guru in Southern California, who just came under the Phillips umbrella with a pair of namesake letters. "A lot of the smaller  publishers are looking to the strong management of big companies." By "management," he means production, subscription fulfillment, and, above all, large-scale direct-mail assaults.<p>
**If an editor can hang on to readers year after year, publishers can go after a larger audience.**<p>
A publisher's critical function is to go out and get the readers. It's up to the editors to keep them, year to year, with winning investment advice, on-point analysis, and whatever written entertainment they can manage. The contrast between a mail piece and the letter it's fronting can be stunning. Picture a carnival barker outside Finance 301. You go from "Get Rich Now!" in huge and lurid type to cramped copy and technical-analytical graphs and portfolio listings.<p>
The difference applies, in an Agoran sort of way, to the solicitations and letters coming from Baltimore. The  big end-of-the-world-as-we-know-it themes carry into the letters, but much more quietly. Even Agora's Old Testament prophet, Gary North, waxes mild. The July 1996 Remnant Review walks his 10,000 readers through the Internet and E-mail then segues into a jeremiad against mainstream investment advice. Like the Bible, which provides its inspiration, Remnant Review is short on specifics and subject to interpretation. Less than one page out of eight is nuts-and-bolts investment information.<p>
**Distaste is often part of the criteria in sending out direct mail.**<p>
Editors generally seem nervous about the publishers' campaigns for their letters. They're worried about being embarrassed by promotional excesses. But distaste is also dependence. Editors know that they can't get new subscribers the way the mail wizards can. Says Agora's Strategic Investment editor James Dale Davidson, he of the "Who Murdered Vince Foster?" come-on, "If the direct mail doesn't alarm me, it probably isn't any good."<p>
Phillips and KCI play their direct mail and letters loud but pretty straight. The pitch pieces stick close to the gurus' investment triumphs, with emphasis on the numbers. Agora's franchise is the melodramatic and bizarre.<p>
One magalog for Strategic Investment is three-ring global apocalypse. It announces a coming plague ("like the Black Death"), a world-banking collapse, nuclear gangsterism in Russia, narco-lord ownership of U.S. politicians, a looming oil crisis, and a real-estate collapse. These aren't half the doom buttons that the piece pushes -- every one of which, somehow or another, equals a wonderful investment opportunity, just like those already uncovered by the letter's "Investors' CIA." Deep intelligence lets readers enjoy recent windfalls shorting the British pound and Swedish krona, the pitch claims.<p>
**The newsletters often provide a rather entertaining read -- combining the best from different genres.**<p>
It's a harrowing trip from the front-page banner, invest along with the world's richest gangsters, to page 28's sign-off, "With warmest regards, James Dale Davidson." It's also hilarious entertainment, combining James Bond, science fiction, the Book of Revelation, and Wall Street Week. "Read this briefing. It may be a matter of life and death importance," Bill Bonner writes in a tense note from the publisher. Non-investors might be tempted to send in the special one-year rate of $59 just to see what happens next.<p>
Flipping through Agora packages is like channel surfing. The sniffy BBC import is the mailing for Agora's The Oxford Club, a newsletter-cum-club with extras that include meetings, overseas junkets, and use of a club room in an Agora building in Baltimore. Off-white bond paper bears a stately notice of nomination by club chairman James Boxley Cooke and a lengthy briefing on "the most remarkable fellowship in the world." You go from there to the religious channel, with bear-market survivalist Bible thumping ("Let them which be in Judaea flee into the mountains") for Remnant Review. Then there's the History Channel infomercial for Taipan, which takes grand century-spanning looks, both forward and backward. <p>
You could forget about investments altogether and love the showbiz. If, as more than one marketing sage has observed, direct mail is theater, its greatest producer, playwright, director, promoter, and leading man is Bill Bonner. The main stage is Agora.<p>
**Agora's attractive offices have a dizzying effect on one who visits after reading drawerfuls of Agora materials.**<p>
Coming to Agora after looking at the company's mail pieces brings on a sort of vertigo. The experience is like going to a professional wrestling match, then beginning to suspect that the action is for real.
This sense of for real begins with Bonner's earnestness. The chosen media of expression -- direct mail and off-plumb newsletters -- have "sham" written all over them, but Bonner seems to be trying to send serious messages. "We live or die by our ideas," he says. "We believe that the way we see the world is essentially righter than the way most people see the world."<p>
Bonner's tenets reach back toward the age that begot the row-house mansions in which Agora's American operations are centered. The buildings are mid-19th-century museum pieces. The square they stand on is so beautifully preserved that a movie crew has been here shooting a film adaptation of a Henry James novel.<p>
The buildings connect the company not just to a time but also to a way of thinking: of Adam Smith's economics; of civil society as opposed to political society. "We believe in people acting independently, building wealth, maintaining health through individual responsibility and individual action," Bonner says. The purest expression of the Bonnerian worldview, according to staffers, is the guru-less letter Taipan, which manages to be both fantastically optimistic and pessimistic. It predicts an upcoming technological golden age in which the prosperous, including the letter's readership, will live like yesteryear's merchant princes. Meanwhile, misery and violence will rule the rest of the world. Hulbert doesn't rate Taipan, so there's no outside assessment of the readership's race to become royalty, but the publisher, J. Christoph Amberger, claimed returns of 35 percent for 1995.<p>
PART IV<p>
The Agora letters' emphasis on ideas -- as much as buy-this, sell-that recommendations -- derives from another big idea. Bonner says he's a  believer in the "efficient market" hypothesis, which, put very simply, says it's hard as hell to beat the averages.<p>
**Some of the newsletters manage to succeed in spite of poor investing returns.**<p>
The big idea, in this case, is also a good idea. Ruth Lyons, group publisher of Agora's guru investment letters, points out that a high-personality, high-concept letter -- Strategic Investment, in this case -- can bomb in portfolio performance but still prosper. (According to Hulbert, Strategic Investment's recommendations have lost an average of 7.3 percent annually for the past five years.) "People read it for the focus, rather than the investments," she says. "The renewal and conversion rates are pretty good." Lyons also explains why a political rant like "Who Murdered Vince Foster?" can make good marketing sense. Exposing somebody else's conspiracy fosters a sense of inclusion. "There's an undertone," she says. "'We've got a secret that can help you, if you're one of us.'" <p>
Lyons, an attractive and manifestly bright thirtysomething with degrees from the University of Maryland and Johns Hopkins University, represents the other dimension in which Agora is surprisingly for real. Whether or not the staff is serious about Bonner's core ideas, they're way serious about advancing their careers and the company.<p>
**Agora's young staff is energetic and low-key, lead by Bonner's powerfull pull.**<p>
Agora is charged up, highly educated, sleek. It's even sort of hip. One recent estimate put the average age of the 150-person headquarters staff at about 30. The company encourages employees to act their ages. Agorites break for weekly basketball games, eschew formal office dress -- unless they're in the mood -- and are spontaneously hospitable in a way that says they love what they're doing. Bonner's backward-leaning libertarianism translates into a very 21st-century no-chart, nonauthoritarian organization. Bonner exercises his leadership by low-key but powerful pull, rather than push.<p>
I see him doing it in a morning of franchise meetings for Agora's health letters. "Franchise," in the Agora lexicon, means something like mission statement. It is a letter's editorial and marketing essence. Groups of eight to ten Agorites sit at an enormous table in a room walled with buttery wooden paneling and murals. These teams include representatives from marketing, editorial, and customer service. (Much of the raw editorial content and direct-mail copywriting comes from outside the building -- the former from the letters' gurus, the latter from freelance specialists.) While Bonner stares, shifts, and drums his fingers, his teams review financial performance and hash out how they can hit present and future readers harder. A purple-inked brochure, welcoming new subscribers to a health letter, elicits the most dramatic response of the morning from Bonner. He shows his distaste more loudly than he speaks it.<p>
"It's soft. Its colors are soft. The message is soft. Everything about it is soft," Bonner tells the franchise team. "And I think that's a mistake."<p>
**Bonner and Davidson's relationship goes back to childhood.**<p>
Bonner found his vocation by a long and complicated series of accidents, which started on his family's farm near Annapolis. Bonner's father worked as a carpenter and farmed tobacco. Bill was best friends with his mother's best friend's boy, James Dale Davidson, who would later reveal Bonner's gift for direct-mail marketing and become the editor of Strategic Investment.<p>
Davidson, a trim redhead whose utterances are careful and hyper-literate, remembers Bonner, the boy and teenager, spinning out entrepreneurial ideas. But Bonner's higher education shows more of the 1960s search for self than business sense. He majored in liberal arts, graduating from the University of New Mexico after a junior year at the Sorbonne in Paris. Smitten with both writing and France, Bonner went back to Paris as correspondent for a countercultural magazine called Zygote, which flopped before he saw a paycheck. "I wrote some pieces and wondered why they didn't respond or send me money or anything," he recalls. "You can imagine dumbbell written over my face."<p>
Bonner looked more left leaning than he was ("During the Vietnam War, it was hard to distinguish civil libertarians from the lefties," he says), to the point that Parisian police once mistook him for a student protester and beat him up. But this was a son of Ayn Rand, not Chairman Mao.<p>
**Davidson's National Taxpayers Union introduced Bonner to direct marketing.**<p>
His friend Davidson turned new-right politics into a vocation, founding the Washington-based National Taxpayers Union. Bonner, meanwhile, made a feint at a conventional profession, finishing law school at Georgetown University. But he gave up on law even before his 1978 graduation. "I was thinking of a career building houses," he says. If it weren't midwinter, he would have started right away. Davidson, who says he couldn't stand to see his friend waste his time, asked him to help out at NTU. "He ended up doing most of the marketing, because he was very good at it," Davidson says.<p>
At NTU, Bonner had a pivotal "Aha!" which he described to the Baltimore Sun: "I discovered the world of direct-response advertising...that you could ask people for money in the mail and they'd send you some."<p>
Both Bonner and Davidson hankered for richer financial rewards and went commercial. Davidson would move into international finance. Bonner followed his predilection for the written word. The proto-Agora in Washington put out a political-satirical newspaper called The Public Spectacle, which died almost immediately, and a magazine called Frontiers in Science, which had a lengthy living death, sucking time and energy and cash. "I ran out of money over and over again, had these losing propositions," Bonner says. Publishing success arrived in 1979 with International Living.<p>
**Bonner and Davidson's first success, International Living, now has a circulation of 100,000.**<p>
The newsletter, which still has a circulation of 100,000, is a ratatouille of advice about low-cost travel and overseas living, with emphasis on affordable retirement havens. Bonner opines that the core subscribers are retired schoolteachers. "The nice thing about International Living is that it doesn't go to those grumpy old men," he says. He would have done more in the IL vein, but nobody was buying. Subsequent successes were investment letters.<p>
During the company's lean years, he met and married his wife, Elizabeth, a staffer who worked his kind of long hours and got an equity stake in the company because there wasn't enough money to pay her what she was worth. Bill and Elizabeth now have six children, four of their own and two from an earlier marriage of Bill's.<p>
In 1983, Bonner bought a building in slummy near-downtown Baltimore for one dollar. The move to the mansions took place in 1994, as did the international buying spree. And suddenly, little Agora was a $75 million company notable not only for the brazen wackiness of its main product but also for an appealing eclecticism and a kind of institutional lan.<p>
PART V<p>
Two of the company's purchases in 1994 were Pickering & Chatto, an English academic press that publishes quality-bound editions of such books as The Political Writings of Mary Wollstonecraft and The Works of Aphra Behn, and Santa Febased John Muir Publishing, which specializes in guidebooks, including the eco-kid number Extremely Weird Frogs. Pickering & Chatto's books are the foundations of Agora's big ideas, Bonner says. He had the notion of selling Pickering & Chatto tomes to investment-letter customers, who could then do in-depth studies. So far, it hasn't worked.<p>
Earlier this year, the Bonner family moved to Chateau d'Ouzilly in the South of France. This is, on an obvious level, an International Livingstyle retreat to gorgeous surroundings. But it also establishes a new European command for Agora. The company offers foreign-language editions of Taipan and hopes to do huge things in Europe with American-style direct mail and newsletters. The whole world -- the subject matter of Agora's big-idea letters, after all -- may someday be screamed at by Agora mailings.<p>
**A control to a copywriter is what a no-hitter is to a pitcher.**<p>
The word "control" has a special meaning in direct mail. It refers to the package that outperforms all others for the same product. A control is to a copywriter what a no-hitter is to a pitcher. High-volume mailers, like Agora, never send out a control alone. There's always at least one test package, the creators of which do everything in their power to knock off the control. If a test does win, it becomes the control, until it gets beaten. Publishers study returns and play with ink color and other near-molecular details to squeeze a few more respondents out of each mailing. They strive to beat themselves so that the market doesn't beat them.<p>
The day their publishers quit playing the control game, investment letters like Agora's start dying. They exist like mountaineers at 8,000 meters, in a death zone, where expensive and hard-won supplements -- oxygen for climbers, new subscribers for letters -- are the only sustainers of life. Direct mail is the only effective way to get new subscribers. But it's so expensive that the first year of a new subscription is a wash. A typical 300,000-piece mailing, which might cost $150,000, is a success if it breaks even. Such mailings, or even bigger ones, go out every six or eight weeks for every major newsletter. In most cases, break-even success means a response rate of 1 to 2 percent. But then only about a quarter of first-year subscribers opt for a second year -- and thus start to generate profits. Thereafter, about half drop their subscriptions every year.<p>
The numbers mean that newsletters are living or dying by the mailings going out now. Letters that succeed next year will do so because of people who haven't been moved to subscribe yet,  by mailings as yet unsent. "With ideas we haven't had yet! Connections we haven't made yet! People we haven't met yet!" Bonner goes on.<p>
**A good control can gain almost mythic proportions -- if it works.**<p>
About ten years ago, Bonner wrote a package -- the control of controls -- that is happily at home in the death zone. The control for International Living is a longevity legend. Agorites know it by heart. When one starts reciting, others join in, sounding eerily like a congregation at prayer. "You look out your window, past your gardener, who is busily pruning the lemon, cherry and fig trees...amidst the splendor of gardenias, hibiscus and hollyhocks." <p>
The writing seems at first pretty obvious -- clear blue sky, deep blue sea, nah nah nah. But about the time the maid brings in breakfast in bed, there's this horrible ache to have every single thing the words are about. The inner being is howling, "I want it! Tell me how to get it!"<p>
"For a moment, you think you have died and gone to heaven," the control says.<p>
**If readers aren't reaping the benefits promised in his control, Bonner certainly is.**<p>
Bonner, at least momentarily, must be getting the same heavenly sensation. When he wrote the IL control, paradise in a faraway land was mostly a copywriter's image. Now he's got a castle in France, huge and vastly more expensive than the retirement cottage in the promo package. Getting up and working, instead of having breakfast in bed, is purely a personal choice. He could loll indefinitely, while "a gentle breeze comes drifting in from the ocean, clean and refreshing." Bonner's immortal pitch piece and its kin -- and the newsletters they're pitching -- have done more for him than the most outrageous promises to subscribers.<p>
"When I tell people what I do, they are sort of generally amazed that you can earn a living doing the sorts of things I do," he says. "It's great." But then Bonner gets uncomfortable with the notion of success. "I'm afraid to look at it too hard," he admits. "I can't take it too seriously....I'm cautioning, warning against a feeling of satisfaction and accomplishment."<p>
Bonner is flat incapable of congratulating himself, and perhaps that's key. If he were better at making noise about himself, he might not be so good at making the written noise that has made him rich, that keeps him mightily entertained, along with his Agorites and their  readers. Hype, when Bonner is doing the hyping, has the power to bend reality -- his way. <p>
Bonner/Descartes: I think, therefore I hype, therefore I am.<p>

