<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Virtue Has Its Rewards</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Virtue Has Its Rewards</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Keep a clean house? Teach school? A discount is in order.<p>
By Morey Stettner<p>
In Idaho, you can save on homeowners insurance by cleaning your house. In Massachusetts, you can lower your premium by taking a six-hour class on home safety. In California, you can pay less to cover your car if you're a scientist, engineer, or teacher.<p>
Insurers are increasingly eager to reward their customers for taking steps to prevent claims -- from doing home maintenance to choosing public transportation over driving. If your odds of filing a claim are lower, some insurers figure, then you deserve a price break. You probably know about the typical discounts: Drivers who have anti-theft devices or passive restraints in their cars usually pay less; homeowners who install security systems or who have the same insurer cover their car and home may also cut their costs. But the savings don't stop there.<p>
"The industry trend is to encourage people to take steps to protect themselves and their homes," says Loretta Worters, public-relations director at the Insurance Information Institute, a trade group in New York City. "The industry is just starting to do things like offer discounts for homeowners who have fire-retardant shingles or who install roof clips to guard against hurricane damage in high-risk areas."<p>
Agents may not always tell you about every discount you qualify for, so it's important to know what sort of behavior can get you a cheaper rate. And you should always ask if any discounts are available, then compare prices among a range of companies for the same amounts of coverage after all discounts have been applied to your quote. "Don't lose sight of the bottom line," says Bob Hunter, director of insurance at the Consumer Federation of America in Washington, D.C. "Some of the companies with the most discounts start off charging the highest rates."<p>
You don't have to install expensive upgrades to earn a discount -- at least in Idaho. Idaho Mutual Insurance takes 5 to 10 percent off a homeowners-insurance bill for "outstanding housekeeping and maintenance," a new program that began last summer. "We look for a homeowner who keeps the place neat as a pin inside and out," says Brian Henman, Idaho Mutual's executive vice president. "That means no boxes piled up, no weeds covering the windows, no engine block being repaired in the driveway for a long time. Of course, we require photographs of the premises before we issue the credit."<p>
Classroom learning can also help you reduce your rates. <p>
Massachusetts offers a free six-hour course called HomeSafe on such topics as weatherization, home repair, and lead-paint hazards, which can earn homeowners a 10 percent discount with some insurers. And in many states, individuals who have completed a class in defensive driving can shave 5 to 15 percent off their auto premium.<p>
"These discounts involve trading behaviors," says Linda Ruthardt, Massachusetts insurance commissioner. "If the consumer promises to take steps to prevent claims or keep the claim from getting too big, the insurer will lower your premium."<p>
If you live in a community that enforces its building codes, you may also save money. Insurance Services Office, a nonprofit statistical-research group, has recently begun rating areas on how well they enforce their building codes. If your city earns a high score in promoting and overseeing the construction of safer buildings, some insurers will take 5 to 15 percent off the price of homeowners insurance. The ratings, now available in Florida, South Carolina, and North Carolina, will be expanded nationwide in the coming years. <p>
Even your personal life can help you save on insurance. In California, 20th Century Insurance gives auto-insurance price breaks to scientists, engineers, and educators. "We've found that people in these careers are safer, more careful drivers," says Ric Hill, a 20th Century vice president. Plymouth Rock Assurance, which operates in New England, offers to reduce auto rates by as much as 15 percent if the applicant works for certain employers or belongs to groups such as churches, unions, or social clubs. "We think members of nonprofit organizations may be a better class of risk," says Plymouth Rock vice president Alan Hines. "Do-gooders are a different class than price shoppers." 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
