<html>
	<head>
		<title>96/10-Profits From The New Money</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Profits From The New Money</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						The form of money is changing again -- and new middlemen will reap the profits.<p>
By Curtis Lang<p>
Point and click. the computer screen reads, "Welcome to CDworld." Point and click. Browse 100,000 CDs on-line. Point and click. Order a CD. Point and click. Now it's time to pay.<p>
But forget about cash or checks. This electronic merchant will accept digital cash -- money in the form of ones and zeros stored on a computer's hard drive -- but not any form of paper money.<p>
Since the Lydians of Asia Minor minted the first coin 2,600 years ago, money has been invented and re-invented countless times. During the past hundred years, gold-backed paper money has been replaced by promise-backed paper money, for example. And now, driven by the proliferation of electronic retailers and the increasing ease of electronic bill paying, the form of money is changing again.<p>
The transition will not be bloodless. Every form of money produces its own group of middlemen -- goldsmiths in the Middle Ages or credit-card issuers in the 20th century -- who become rich from helping it circulate. Every time a dollar changes hands, a few pennies stay behind in ATM fees or credit-card interest. The number of pennies is immense. The Nilson Report estimates that in 1990 transactions in the U.S. economy involved $1.2 trillion in checks, $1.6 trillion in cash, and $446 billion in credit-card debits.<p>
Electronic money will make up only a very small piece of that pie by 2000. Jupiter Communications in New York projects that on-line shopping (transactions that will be paid for largely in electronic money) for entertainment, clothing, software, airline tickets, and other goods will grow from $575.6 million in 1995 to $7.3 billion in 2000. But that $7.3 billion is just the opening wedge that the companies that make digital money or provide electronic bill payment hope will let them grab a share of the entire pie.<p>
For example, <a name="NASD:CYCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47308"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CyberCash</b></a>, founded in 1994, runs a service that lets merchants receive payments on the Internet -- a substitute for cash, checks, and plastic. Consumers use its software "wallets" to pay for and track on-line purchases. Merchants pay fees for each transaction. CyberCash went public on February 15, 1996, at $17 a share (see "<A href="/articles/Z9606C.html">Finding the Next Microsoft</A>," June 1996).<p>
Banks and their credit-card companies, such as Visa and MasterCard, don't oppose electronic money -- they just want to control it. Their major weapon? Smart credit cards that use simple computer chips to access checking accounts and credit lines.<p>
Smart cards aren't well suited for at-home electronic shopping: Like conventional credit cards, they need to be swiped through a piece of hardware to transfer money over computer networks or phone lines. "My belief is that the successful payment vehicle in the next five years is going to be credit cards," says David Weisman, director of money and technology strategies at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Massachusetts. "People are used to them. There's frequent-flier miles and other benefits." Digital cash, on the other hand, is "going to feel like foreign currency."<p>
Although the fight over electronic cash is just heating up, the battle to control the home desktop has reached a fever pitch. Rather than doing battle against banks and credit-card companies, players like <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> and <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a> are signing them up as partners; both see a chance to dominate a home-banking marketplace expected to grow from 750,000 home-computer bankers in 1995 to 13 million by 2000, according to Jupiter Communications. The banks suffer a distinct disadvantage -- with a few exceptions, they lack the technological savvy to build their own gateways.<p>
Microsoft is facing a stiff challenge from the much smaller Intuit. In February, Visa and Microsoft announced a partnership to provide home banking using Microsoft Money -- which has an installed base of more than two million users -- as the gateway. But for on-line banking, Microsoft Money is widely considered an interface inferior to Intuit's Quicken, which also has a larger installed base of more than nine million users. To counter Microsoft's partnership with Visa, Intuit has struck deals with America Online and Electronic Payment Services, which provides ATM networks for 2,000 banks.<p>
<a name="NASD:CKFR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43345"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CheckFree</b></a>, a third rival in this market, began as a company offering automatic-payment systems for health-and-fitness centers. The company, which went public in September 1995, now plans to offer its own brand of digital cash and is branching out into personal finance and home banking. CheckFree recently acquired Servantis, which makes electronic-commerce software for more than 70 financial institutions.<p>
But "CheckFree has been looking for a strategy for about a year," says new-media analyst Gary Arlen, president of Arlen Communications in Bethesda, Maryland. "They're an unknown quantity to a lot of banks who are very hard pressed to figure out where they fit."<p>
Companies building the pipelines to link the desktop with the merchant and then to the bank or credit-card company don't face competition from established financial middlemen. But large full-line computer makers are poised on the sidelines just waiting until the market gets big enough to justify their entry.<p>
For example, <a name="NASD:OMKT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43511"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Open Market</b></a> in Cambridge, Massachusetts, which makes software for transaction processing on the Internet, has carved out the high end of the Internet commerce-software market for itself, but <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, Microsoft, Visa, and <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> all plan to offer a wide array of high-value-added services soon. In a deal that should garner market visibility, Open Market recently licensed its software to high-end Internet service provider BBN Planet in Cambridge.<p>
<a name="NYSE:VFI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13718"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>VeriFone</b></a>, on the other hand, already has a big share of the mass market. The company all but created the automated-credit-card-authorization industry out of thin air 15 years ago and now has 65 percent of the worldwide installed base of credit-card swipe machines.<p>
Building on that base, the Redwood City, California, company, which owns 9 percent of CyberCash, plans to roll out electronic wallets for consumers and Internet gateway products for credit-card customers and issuers. VeriFone has inked alliances with database-software maker <a name="NASD:ORCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14337"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oracle,</b></a> <a name="NYSE:
WFC"></a><b>Wells Fargo Bank</b>, <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape</b></a>, and Microsoft. In addition, this year VeriFone acquired Enterprise Integration Technologies, the principal architect of the leading public key-encryption standard for secure transactions on the World Wide Web. That acquisition makes it all but impossible for another party to lock VeriFone out of the marketplace.<p>
Those deals push VeriFone into unproven markets -- but the risk will be worth it if the company can gain a big share of all those pennies.

					</font>
					<p>
					<font size=4>
					<blockquote>
					</blockquote>
					</font>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

