<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Paper Pushers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Paper Pushers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ted C. Fishman<p>Do you dream of elves sneaking in at night and cleaning up your desk or office? If so, then give some thought to scanners during the waking hours. <p>They haven't received the attention of the World Wide Web, but these amazing, now affordable computer add-ons will prove just as indispensable to homes and offices as an Internet connection. By turning real pages into digital bits, these "paper management systems," as one manufacturer calls them, will put the contents of our desks and drawers into our computers. Then they'll rid our lives of fax and copy machines, too.<p>Consider the PaperPort Vx or PaperPort ix, from <a name="NASD:VSNR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47703"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Visioneer</b></a>. The Vx is about a foot long and a few inches wide, and the ix is a computer keyboard with a trim scanning barrel at the back; each can devour a deskful of paper and reduce every sheet or stack of pages into thumbnail-sized images on a virtual desktop. To do this, the scanners employ the additional magic of Visioneer's software, which enables users to manipulate and sort documents as images on a computer screen. <p>Now that a single computer mouse can accomplish everything a typing and clerical pool can, the virtual desktop is far harder to clutter than a physical one. Optical-character-recognition software can convert documents into different formats -- that of a favorite word processor, for example -- almost instantly. With an attached modem, documents can be routed by E-mail or sent to a fax machine elsewhere. Scanners can also function as a simple copy machine, reproducing scanned materials through a printer.<p>The PaperPorts scan only in black and white, however, and can handle only one loose page at a time. This makes them less than ideal for those other great scanner uses: getting color pictures and bound material into a computer. Multimedia presentations and graphically interesting Web pages demand as much; also, computers are increasingly becoming the repositories of family photo albums, photographic household inventories, and miscellaneous gimcrack-like greeting cards and children's drawings.<p>Color flatbed scanners, such as <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a>'s ScanJet 4p, make this possible, swallowing just about any picture or document thrown at them and yielding computer-screen reproductions with the clarity of good slides. The 4p, like most flatbed scanners, is sold with useful software for scanning and manipulating images. (The good news is that Visioneer's PaperPort software comes with all of Hewlett-Packard's color flatbed scanners; the bad news is that it works only with Visioneer and Hewlett-Packard scanners.) Beware: The 4p can prove hard to install. It requires a special adapter card (included), which tends to conflict with many Sound Blaster brand sound cards. The best solution is to have the scanner installed where purchased or to attach it only to late-model machines with "plug and play" cards that automatically resolve most conflicts in a computer's hardware.<p>Plustek's OpticPro 4800P color flatbed scanner creates fewer installation headaches. It connects easily to the back of a computer -- no special adapter cards are required -- and can be used without disconnecting the printer. <p>The machine fits lengthwise on a standard desk (most flatbeds cannot) but letter-sized materials are the largest it can handle. Still, its ability to fit in a briefcase makes it ideal for lawyers or others who might need to take a scanner to the documents, rather than vice versa. It's fast, too, and produces higher-resolution scans than others in its price range. However, the OpticPro's software works less seamlessly with other applications than Visioneer's products do, though revisions are promised.<p>Those with more ambitious scanning needs, or who want to add scanning and document-management software to scanners they already own, should turn to Envisions (800-365-7226), a mail-order house devoted to scanners and scanning. Its excellent high-end scanners sell for prices considerably lower than those of comparable models from other makers. <p>Take the 4cx color flatbed scanner, for example, which permits sharper resolutions than the PaperPorts. Envisions bundles it with <wam-co>Adobe</wam-co> Photoshop (the most powerful imaging software available to consumers) and a full suite of optical-character-recognition, document-management, and presentation software for $849. That's $50 less than the suggested retail price of Photoshop alone. Envisions also mixes and matches packages to suit more specific needs.<p>Prices for scanners are proving just as volatile as those for personal computers, so shop carefully. Models and features change quickly, and vendors aren't shy about passing off older models as new ones; don't count on them to pass along a price drop, either. Be aware of scanning's hidden costs, too -- chief among them the increased need for memory of all kinds. Color-image scanning requires at least 16 megabytes of memory on a Windows 95 system; more is preferable. In addition, images of all kinds eat up disc storage space. A high-capacity external storage device, such as the Iomega Zip Drive, which saves information onto 100-megabyte discs, may be needed to spare hard drives the cluttered-desk fate the scanner was meant to cure. Still, it beats those low-tech piles of paper.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
