	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Half the Fax</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Half the Fax</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Laurence Hooper<p>A sleek black box only slightly bigger than a pack of cigarettes, FaxView ($499) is based on a nifty idea: Instead of getting printed faxes, users peer inside this device to see them displayed as glowing red images. This works better than you might imagine. Pages, which can be viewed at a couple of magnification levels, are relatively easy to read. So hook FaxView to a cell phone or a phone line and -- presto! -- a portable fax machine.<p>Well, sort of. The problem is that real fax machines also send documents. FaxView can only transmit short messages pecked out on an on-screen keyboard -- which gets mighty tedious. The device can't handle graphics or scan in existing documents, either (though it can store as many as 25 pages of received faxes and re-send  elsewhere).<p>My laptop computer, which also sends and receives faxes, is much better at creating documents. FaxView is much smaller and lighter -- it looks like it belongs on Mr. Spock's utility belt -- but I'm not going to stop carrying my laptop when I'm on the road. So even at less than eight ounces, FaxView is deadweight.<p>I guess there are folks who'd love FaxView. Workaholic lawyers come to mind: They could receive confidential documents in traffic jams. Reflection Technology, which makes FaxView, suggests that construction workers could use it while on a building site -- a rather desperate scenario, I think.<p>Basically, this gizmo is a solution in search of a problem. It's a pretty cool-looking solution, I'll admit, and it's a kick to walk around knowing there's a fax machine in your pocket. But that thrill, at the end of the day, is FaxView's main benefit.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
