	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Dilbert Was Here. So Was Faith Popcorn</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Dilbert Was Here. So Was Faith Popcorn</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ted C. Fishman<p>The media love media, so it's no surprise the book industry has embraced the Web. Publishers can tempt readers there with reviews, sample chapters, and even audio snippets from the authors themselves. When it comes to business and finance -- perhaps the most crowded niche in publishing -- HarperBusiness offers the best site: HarperBizNet (http://www.harpercollins.com/business/indextop.htm). At one point earlier this year, a third of the books on Business Week's hardcover best-seller list were featured on the site, as was The Dilbert Principle trivia game. A regular element is a schedule of speaking engagements for HarperBusiness authors, many of them celebrity gurus who usually speak only to paying crowds but who often turn out for free when peddling their books.<p>For other book-related resources, try BookWeb (http://ambook.org) from the American Booksellers Association. It provides current news on the book industry and includes links to information on authors. Or visit BookWire (http://www.bookwire.com), which sponsors, with Publishers Weekly, "Authors on the Highway," a comprehensive list of book tours searchable by author, title, or publisher.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Publishing Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
