	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-New Secrets to Buying Biotech</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-New Secrets to Buying Biotech</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
For new biotech companies, the goal isn't to become the next Merck anymore<p>By Pamela J. Black<p><a name="NASD:INCY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16850"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Incyte Pharmaceuticals</b></a> does not make a single drug -- nor does the Palo Alto, California, company aim to develop any drugs itself. The company's products are instead databases of human- and microbial-gene sequences that someday may lead to drugs that can wipe out diseases at their source. However, some other company will develop those drugs -- Incyte (Nasdaq: INCY) has sold nonexclusive rights to parts of its database to pharmaceutical giants such as <a name="NYSE:JNJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10824"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Johnson & Johnson</b></a>. Ten such deals will bring in more than $160 million over the next few years.<p>Welcome to the new financial model for building a successful biotech company. The founders of the previous generation of biotech companies -- <a name="NASD:AMGN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12623"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Amgen</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:GNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10628"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Genentech</b></a>, <a name="NASD:CNTO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12923"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Centocor</b></a>, and Genex, to name just a few -- set out to build the next <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a>. Companies in the new wave, however, aren't trying to do it all; they plan to grow in partnership with the big pharmaceutical companies, which will fund their research efforts in exchange for marketing rights on new drugs or licenses on any new discoveries. "One company doesn't have to go from a dead halt to <a name="NYSE:BMY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10232"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bristol-Myers Squibb</b></a> in ten years," says Cynthia Robbins-Roth, editor of BioVenture View, a newsletter in San Mateo, California.<p>Investors who want to figure out what to pay for a biotechnology stock have to change their thinking, too. In the old public-markets model, investors had to figure out how much more money -- after they purchased their shares -- the company would need to raise before it made a profit. In effect, they had to figure out how much smaller their current stake in the company would be by the time the company stopped raising money. For companies following the new model, investors must calculate how much of future sales the company has promised to its partners in exchange for current financing.<p>The reason for the new model is pretty simple: Biotech companies learned the hard way that public markets are an expensive place to raise the $300 million it takes to develop a new drug -- the cost of research, clinical trials, manufacturing, and marketing.<p>To get a sense of just how expensive, look at Amgen (Nasdaq: AMGN), which is arguably the only biotech to join the ranks of the drug giants. Founded in 1980, the Thousand Oaks, California, company first turned to the public markets in 1983, raising $40 million. Subsequently, Amgen raised $38 million in 1986 and almost $75 million in 1987. Because of all the shares issued in those offerings, an investor at the initial public offering saw his ownership of the company diluted by more than 50 percent by 1987 -- his shares had that much less of a claim on the company's earnings. "If you own a biotech from the start, each time the company sells stock, your holding gets diluted," says John McCamant, associate editor of Medical Technology Stock Letter in Berkeley, California. "You end up owning a smaller chunk of it."<p>Fortunately for those shareholders, Amgen turned a corner in 1989 when it got FDA approval for Epogen, a drug that stimulates the production of red blood cells, and by 1995 net profit had hit $538 million. Even though the company issued more than eight million shares in the public markets to finance its growth, by 1995 earnings came to $1.92 a share -- up from one cent a share in 1987. A share purchased for $18 in 1986 was worth $657 in July 1996.<p>But most old-model biotechnology companies didn't turn out nearly as well for investors. More typical is <a name="NASD:IMUL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12015"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ImmuLogic Pharmaceutical</b></a>(Nasdaq: IMUL), a 1987 start-up. The Waltham, Massachusetts, company went public in 1991 at $10 a share and sold more stock to the public in 1992, 1993, and 1995. Shares outstanding grew from 9.85 million in 1991 to 20.2 million in 1996, a 105 percent increase. Sales (since the company is still losing money, it has no earnings) have more than doubled from $3.2 million in 1991 to $7.8 million in 1995. But because of the dilution created by all those shares, sales per share have increased only 21 percent. Since the company lost $19 million in 1995, more dilution may lie ahead.<p>Contrast ImmuLogic to <a name="NASD:AGPH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12537"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Agouron Pharmaceuticals</b></a> (Nasdaq: AGPH), a company following the new financial model in its efforts to develop drugs. To fund its research on an HIV drug called Viracept, Agouron has turned to financing from Japan Tobacco: Agouron receives $30 million from Japan Tobacco for reaching strategic milestones. In exchange, Agouron has given Japan Tobacco exclusive rights to sell Viracept in Asia. Meanwhile, Swiss pharmaceutical giant Hoffmann-LaRoche is paying the San Diego biotech $55 million to fund development of a cancer drug, Thymitaq, in exchange for worldwide marketing rights and co-marketing rights in the U.S. The money from each partner is almost as much as Amgen raised in 1987 in its third public offering.<p>So what's a partnership-financed company such as Agouron worth? 
Fortunately, the deals themselves are good barometers of the value of a stock. Some of them are, from an investor's point of view, better than others.<p>For example, investors should probably take a pass on companies that have already sold most of their future to a partner. Genentech, for example, has limited appeal for investors since 68 percent 
of it is owned by Roche Holdings. Roche has the right to buy the rest of the company in the next five years for just over $60 a share. "There's not a lot of risk but no upside either," says John McCamant. "They come up with a blockbuster drug, and Roche will buy them out."<p>Partnerships can help an investor focus on the products that are most likely to actually reach the market. "The shareholder uses the partner as a due-diligence proxy," says John McCamant. In other words, since an established company that presumably knows the drug market has decided this potential product has a future, investors can try to figure out how big the future market will be rather than worry about the validity of the basic science practiced in a company's laboratories.<p>Biotech companies are usually valued at four to eight times anticipated revenues, says Jim McCamant, John's father and editor of Medical Technology Stock Letter. He expects Agouron's Viracept to be approved in the first half of 1997. Because it has shown fewer side effects in clinical trials than other HIV products, it could capture 20 percent of what Jim McCamant estimates will be a $2 billion market for HIV drugs at the end of 1997. Discounting that $400 million by 30 percent (since the drug is a year from market) and then, to be conservative, multiplying by the lowest multiple -- four -- McCamant figures that if Agouron produced Viracept alone its market value should be $1.12 billion.<p>Thymitaq is harder to evaluate because it's not known which cancers it will treat effectively. Jim McCamant estimates that sales of the drug will be about $200 million in two years. Since Agouron is splitting revenues with Roche, it will see only $100 million of that. Discounting those revenues by 60 percent (since revenues are two years in the future) and again applying the multiple four, McCamant arrives at a market cap of $160 million for a company selling only Thymitaq.<p>Add the two together, and Agouron is worth at least $1.28 billion -- without counting the value of other drugs in the pipeline. The company's stock traded at $42.50 in early July, giving Agouron a market cap of just $451 million -- a big discount to McCamant's estimate. With about 10.6 million shares outstanding, Agouron should sell at approximately $121 a share within two to three years. "It's a no-brainer that Agouron is undervalued," McCamant says.<p>Don't assume that a market value like this is guaranteed. A competitor could undercut prices. So investors should look for companies with drugs for diseases that are currently untreatable. These companies "have pricing flexibility, at least until competition comes along," says Cowen & Co. analyst David Stone.<p>Companies built on a broad enabling technology that can be applied to many different markets and drugs are also more likely to achieve a projected market cap. Technology that has earned a patent provides additional security. <a name="NASD:RZYM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51693"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ribozyme</b></a> (Nasdaq: RZYM), 
a Boulder, Colorado, start-up, licenses the patents to the discovery by Nobel winner Thomas Cech of a form of RNA that can destroy disease-causing proteins. "Anyone who wants to use them to treat a specific disease will have to deal with us," says David Morgenthaler, managing partner of Morgenthaler Ventures, an investor in the company.<p>And anyone who wants to buy the next wave in biotechs -- while they are still out of favor -- can use these methods to figure out how much to pay.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Biotechnology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
