<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Going Small</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Going Small</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						They offer the very best returns on Wall Street, and mutual funds can't buy them. You and I can. Welcome to the small time.<p>By Clint Willis<p>Shock waves as big as tsunamis have staggered even such seaworthy blue-chip stocks as <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a>. Surges of pessimism have hammered many smaller recent favorites, such as <a name="NASD:USRX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15388"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>U.S. Robotics</b></a> and <a name="NASD:IOMG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13832"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Iomega</b></a>. Why then would any investor want to put a dollar into microcaps -- the smallest stocks that trade on the public markets?<p>Simply because no other sector of the market so amply rewards the
individual investor willing to do the hard work of independently evaluating companies. "the few people who have the time and the talent to find these stocks can get a bigger reward for the risk they 
take than anywhere else in the financial markets," says Mark Boyer, a managing partner at ROI Partners in San Francisco.<p>That's not what most of the experts told me, however. According to them, microcaps -- stocks with a total market value of $25 million or less -- are poison for individual investors. "The smaller the company, the lower the quality of the business franchise and the management team," says Neal Bradsher, managing director of Campbell Advisors, a New York City money-management firm that specializes in microcaps. "When you have a market cap that small, there's probably something wrong with the company," says David Warnock, a partner with Cahill, Warnock in Baltimore.<p>What these professionals, most of whom make their living investing in these stocks, didn't feel compelled to stress is that this part of the stock market can be extraordinarily profitable. Thanks to Ibbotson Associates, the Chicago investment-research firm, everyone knows that small-company stocks have beaten the tar out of blue chips over the long haul: From 1926 through 1995, while large-company stocks returned 10.5 percent a year on average, small-company stocks returned 12.5 percent. But what most investors don't know is that much of that extra return results from the performance of the smallest of small stocks. "Almost all of the superior returns offered by small stocks come from micro-cap stocks with market capitalizations below $25 million. $10,000 invested in that group on December 31, 1951 soared to over $29 million in value [through 1994], achieving a compound growth rate of over 20 percent for the 43 years reviewed," reports James P. O'Shaughnessy in his 1996 book, What Works on Wall Street.<p>Returns like that come from investing in companies that are so small that the big institutions that dominate Wall Street avoid them: There aren't enough shares available to do high-volume deals. That means this part of the market is inefficient -- no analysts track earnings, and no computerized traders keep prices from getting out of line. Individuals can find the best of these tiny companies -- and invest in them -- before anyone on Wall Street even knows they exist.<p>That's what Jim Seward, a Kansas City, Missouri, money manager, did in 1985. Cook Data Systems, which was then launching a chain of video-rental stores, had a market capitalization of about $10 million -- a mere flyspeck by the standards of most investors. But Seward dropped by the company's first store and then met with the owners. "They had a lot of cash and a good business plan, so I bought it," he recalls. The company became Blockbuster Entertainment.<p>Finding companies like that -- and small fry that will make an investor a healthy profit without ever growing up to become a Blockbuster -- doesn't require sophisticated methodologies. "Microcap stocks are really one of the easiest arenas for small investors to work in," says Marc Robins, editor of The Red Chip Review in Portland, Oregon, which tracks tiny companies and their stocks. "The businesses are typically very simple, and their annual reports are easy to read. They don't have silly tax rates or overseas divisions or goofy pension plans to figure out." What it does take is hard work. Coming up with the list of eight recommended microcaps for this story took me about 240 hours -- or about 30 hours of work per stock. That may seem like a lot, but think of it this way: If you own a thousand shares of a single $4 stock that goes to $12, you will have earned more than $250 an hour from your investment of sweat on that one pick.<p>I began by building my own list of potentially interesting microcap stocks. No investment bank, no brokerage firm, no mutual fund keeps a list of the kind of microcap stocks you want to find. Institutional investors call any stock a microcap that has a market capitalization -- the value of all the company's issued shares multiplied by the current price per share -- of less than $100 million. For the really small stocks, an individual investor is truly on his own. (See "First, Find the Haystack," on page 78, for more on how to build a list.) My initial list contained 45 companies.<p>Getting lots and lots of information on each of these companies turned out to be extremely easy -- too easy, in fact. It's clear that institutional investors don't avoid the market for microcaps because they can't find out anything about these companies. I wound up buried in information. Companies gladly sent me annual reports, brochures, press clippings, and anything else that could tell me their story. It's just not worth a big investor's time to study a company this small -- holding even 10 percent of a microcap's total stock, which would come to $2.5 million, isn't enough to give much of a kick to a $1 billion portfolio. That, and not the lack of information, is what keeps this part of the market reserved for relatively few investors.<p>In some cases, the information made it easy to eliminate a company, and I got down to 25 companies in short order. Coin Bill Validator (market cap: $16.1 million), which makes paper-currency-validation systems for the gaming and vending industries, looked interesting, but press releases told me that costs were up and profits were way down.<p>Other companies seemed like quality stuff. Jim Hjelm's Private Collection (market cap: $3.2 million), a New York City firm that designs, makes, and sells bridal gowns and bridesmaids' dresses, sent me some pictures. The dresses were absolutely stunning. Profits are rising; debt is low.<p><a name="NASD:AILP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=45012"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alpnet</b></a> (a market cap of $24 million when I spotted it and $33 million at presstime), in Salt Lake City, is the largest publicly owned dedicated supplier of worldwide translation and "product-localization services," which involve modifying products to work in foreign markets. For example, when <a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq Computer</b></a> enters a foreign market, Alpnet translates the maintenance manuals and operating instructions. Revenues grew more than 30 percent in 1995. I was interested.<p><a name="NASD:REXL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14581"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rexhall Industries</b></a> (market cap: $17.9 million), a Lancaster, California, company that makes recreational vehicles, posted 21 percent sales growth in 1995, a slow year for the industry.<p>If these were blue-chip companies, I would have had to rely on market analysts and research reports to get the inside dope on each one. That's not true with microcaps. "The guys at these firms say, 'Look! A shareholder! Grab him!'" says Boyer. "The companies that I visit are so willing to talk about themselves, they'll tell you anything."<p>Investor relations? Hah! Ask to talk to a senior manager, preferably the CEO. "If they're not cooperative and communicative, cross them off the list," says Seward. A few of the companies out of the original 45 on my list didn't call back. Only one flat out refused to talk.<p>From all my reading, I had developed a list of several dozen questions to ask these companies -- covering everything from profit margins to legal issues. But after a few interviews, I threw out all but four or five. If the manager's answers didn't impress me, I moved on. "For these firms to become big-cap companies, their management teams will have to articulate their business plan to Wall Street," says Seward. "If they can't even describe it to you..."<p>Question No. 1: How will the company grow? The manager's vision should include a realistic plan for increasing sales and earnings during the next several years and beyond.<p>Alpnet, for example, has a share of the $1.7 billion translation and product-localization market second only to that of <a name="NYSE:BTZ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14371"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Berlitz</b></a>. Moreover, at least one research company estimates that the market will grow 30 percent annually for the next five years. CEO Tom Seal and chief financial officer Kerry Stubbs spent two hours telling me about their plan to take a bigger piece of that growing pie: First, open offices in more countries to get access to more customers; Alpnet is in 22 countries now, up from 9 in 1989. Second, offer one-stop shopping. Alpnet translates information into well over 100 languages, and most of its competitors have a much narrower range. Third, deliver quick results in a world where companies need to get new products to market right away.<p>The three-part strategy is designed to crowd out competitors. "<a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> used to have 50 companies translate for them, and now they have 3," said Seal. "We're one of them."<p>Joseph Murphy, president of Jim Hjelm's Private Collection, was equally persuasive about how he plans to make his company grow in a mature market. Hjelm's is the only publicly traded company in the highly fragmented bridal-gown industry, with a 1 percent market share. Murphy's strategy for growth made sense to me. The company has identified emerging fashion trends at the high end of the market and is launching new lines to fill those niches. One such line consists of bridesmaids' dresses that are suitable for other occasions. 
"I think that's a great idea," confirmed my wife, Jennifer, who keeps an $800 bridesmaid's dress in the attic. The firm's Occasions bridesmaids' line is the hottest in the country.<p>Finally, Murphy plans to acquire smaller bridal-gown competitors. "Many of the small, family-owned companies in this industry have older owners who are looking for an exit strategy," he said.<p>Hardest to evaluate, I found, are companies with new products. For example, <a name="NASD:LIFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=45891"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LifeCell</b></a> (market cap: $24.2 million), in the Woodlands, Texas, is building a market from scratch for its new product, AlloDerm, which is a patented tissue-grafting method used in periodontal, plastic, and reconstructive surgery. CEO Paul Frison figures that the combined U.S. market for all these uses could reach $300 million.<p>If he can get his product in front of prospective customers, that is. Frison has started by building a sales and marketing staff to sell the product directly to burn-treatment centers. New regional distribution networks will sell AlloDerm to plastic surgeons. The firm also recently signed a deal with a major dental-supply company and has licensed AlloDerm to Medtronic (market cap: $12 billion) for use in heart valves.<p>Some managers couldn't articulate their plans. I was impressed by a statistic in the marketing materials of Trans-Industries, which makes bus lighting, electronic highway signs, and things like that: The company's literature claimed that 9.7 out of 10 transit buses use its products. Forty minutes on the phone with the firm's CFO provided more good news -- the company's lineup of products is broader and deeper than that of its competitors. But I still hadn't heard a strategy for increasing sales or defending market share from potential competitors -- despite asking several times. I reluctantly dropped the company from my list.<p>Question No. 2: Does the possibility of competition from larger, better-financed companies scare you? Most small companies face significant competition or the threat of it. An investor doesn't expect to find companies without competition -- just savvy, hardworking executives who have strategies for thriving despite it.<p>Company executives who don't admit that fear sure frighten me. Bruce Wilson, CEO and CFO of <a name="AMEX:HPP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=45751"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Healthy Planet Products</b></a>, which produces greeting cards with environmentalist themes, confidently noted that "there isn't any significant competition in wildlife- and wilderness-photo greeting cards." Not yet, maybe -- but wait until Hallmark hears about the company's 20 percent annual earnings growth. I crossed Healthy Planet off my list, despite its gorgeous balance sheet and strong earnings record.<p>I liked <a name="NASD:ULTR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43286"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ultradata Systems</b></a> (market cap: $20.2 million) because, while confident, CEO Monte Ross seemed to have a healthy respect for the competition. The Saint Louis firm sells a line of handheld travel devices that serve as low-tech substitutes for a global-positioning system. For $29.95 a pop, the company's Road Whiz Plus gives drivers information about distances, gas stations, hotels, hospitals, restaurants, and the like along an interstate. Another unit provides details about more than 10,000 golf courses in the U.S.<p>Competition? No one makes similar devices, so the ten-year-old firm has a big head start -- and three patents protect its technology. Global-positioning systems could, in theory, pose a threat as they get cheaper and more portable. But Ross points out that right now a typical GPS costs upwards of $2,000. No threat from that direction for a while.<p>The company's sales have grown about 70 percent annually since 1993, and long-term debt is almost nonexistent. Its return on equity (a measure of profitability) is an eye-popping 32 percent. The capper: Road Whiz Plus is the third-best-selling item on QVC's <a name="NYSE:HSN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12024"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Shopping Network</b></a>, according to Ross. How can I pass this one up?<p>ThrustMaster (market cap: $17.7 million) seems almost paranoid about its competition -- a trait I find scary in friends but like in my investments. The company spends a fair amount of money fending off copycats who try to rip off its line of peripherals used to play games on personal computers. The Portland, Oregon, firm is the market leader in realistic "flight controllers" for games that involve simulated flying.<p>CFO Kent Koski pointed out that the market for PC entertainment software (as opposed to stand-alone game devices, such as Nintendo or Sega) grew 30 percent in 1995; that helped boost ThrustMaster's sales 43 percent. But competition is increasing, so the firm will have to continue churning out first-rate products.<p>Can they do it? I'm no great judge of computer-entertainment peripherals, but presumably George Lucas can afford to hire people who are -- and Lucas Arts is among the companies that buy this little firm's products to make their games more fun. And Koski notes that NASA has bought some joysticks to be used for training in the space-shuttle program, and a defense contractor wants a computer-simulated program for tank commanders. If this company's stuff is good enough for Lucas Arts and guys who drive tanks for a living, I'm certainly interested.<p>Actually, I did manage to find one company where competition isn't a problem. <a name="NASD:MODT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10378"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Modtech</b></a> (a market cap of $24 million when I called and $27 million at presstime), a 14-year-old maker of modular, relocatable classrooms in Perris, California, was hammered when the state's severe recession crimped education spending. In fact, Modtech was the only major manufacturer in its business to survive the five-year drought in orders. Now the company is sitting pretty indeed. The California economic recovery let the state increase its education budget; since the end of 1995 the company's backlog has grown 500 percent to $20 million. Clearly, the world of relocatable classrooms is Modtech's oyster.<p>Question No. 3: Are you really, really good at this? I discovered that it was hard to come right out and ask this one. But by the time I'd talked to most CEOs for 15 minutes, I felt close to an answer. And while it may not much matter who runs <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> (sorry, Lou Gerstner), a company with a market cap of $25 million or less needs a great team at the wheel. "With companies this size, you're betting as much on the quality of the management as you are on the product," says Byron Roth, president of Cruttenden Roth, an investment-banking and brokerage firm in Irvine, California.<p>I rejected any company whose head honcho wasn't smart and articulate. When a manager bowled me over with his enthusiasm, charm, and general smarts, I took that as a good sign. In a few cases, I insisted on it. Take <a name="NASD:REXL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14581"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rexhall</b></a> (market cap: $17.9 million), the motor-home manufacturer. I knew that the company had serious competition from the likes of <a name="NYSE:WGO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11643"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Winnebago</b></a> (market cap: $219 million) and <a name="NYSE:FLE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10586"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fleetwood</b></a> (market cap: $1.4 billion). Its only hope is to outsmart the big guys.<p>I think founder Bill Rex can do it. After 13 years with another RV company, Rex took the top spot at a struggling competitor; in 18 months he turned it around. In 1986, he and Charles Hall started Rexhall, and by 1990 sales were $39 million. Then the Gulf War devastated the California market, where the firm's sales were concentrated.<p>Since then, however, revenues have climbed 45 percent a year to $60.7 million in 1995. The firm has a 3 percent share of the $2.7 billion market for Class A motor homes -- the biggest and fanciest ones made -- and aims to boost that to 10 percent within two to three years. "Other guys have gotten that kind of market share," Rex said matter-of-factly. "They're not as good as we are, and they don't have our financial strength."<p>What's so great about Rexhall RVs? I could tell that Rex was glad I asked. "Most people use 70-ounce carpeting; we use 90-ounce. Our fiberglass siding is what you'd find in a $300,000 motor home, but ours sell for $60,000 to $160,000. The other guys take a cookie-cutter approach -- they're too big to do anything else...." Twenty minutes of this, and I was about ready to write a check -- for an RV. Failing that, I put the stock on my list.<p>By now, I had zeroed in on about ten companies I liked. But I still had doubts about some of them, and it seemed like a good idea to take another piece of advice from Byron Roth: "Call customers, and talk to suppliers," he urged me. "Get as much information as you can." Who better to judge a company's product versus the competition?<p>For example, I was worried about the ability of Minneapolis-based <a name="NASD:EVMD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=45523"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Everest Medical</b></a> (market cap: $23.2 million) to compete with companies like <a name="NYSE:USS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11558"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>U.S. Surgical</b></a>, so I called some of their doctor customers. Those conversations helped put me at ease. <p>Everest Medical is a leader in bipolar surgical instruments, which help doctors minimize tissue damage during surgical procedures that use electricity to take tissue samples. The market for bipolar instruments -- an advance over monopolar instruments, which require more complicated electrical connections -- is growing, but bigger companies have introduced competing instruments. Everest's strategy is to protect its technology with patents (43 so far) and target specific niches, such as the relatively tiny market for bipolar surgical scissors.<p>Everest's customers don't think the competition is much to worry about. Everest's products are superior to instruments that don't use this technology; moreover, bipolar technology is indeed catching on in the industry. The big guys will take notice, the customers figure, but they would be better off buying Everest than trying to get around those patents.<p>At some point in your investigation of a microcap, it's time to abandon the phone and go for a visit. Managers of small companies will likely be happy to have you drop by for a tour of headquarters or a chat with the CEO. That might be tough if you're investing in firms that are across the country from you -- one advantage to staying close to home. "I do a lot of investing in my own backyard," says Red Chip Review's Marc Robins. "It's easier to drive by and get a better understanding of the company."<p>Robins, Boyer, and other stock pickers treat such visits as 
a chance to notice signals that don't come across on the telephone. Check out everything from the furniture in the president's office to the men's room -- which could turn out to be important. "This sounds dopey, but if you visit a technology company, you want to see how clean their bathrooms are," adds Boyer. "It says something about how they run things."<p>Imponderables matter a lot. "It's like visiting someone at home," says Richard C. Perkins, a money manager at Perkins Capital Management in Minneapolis, who drops in on some 75 companies a year. "You can tell a lot about the person."<p>Site visits are an art, not a science. When I tagged along with Eric Miller, a portfolio manager at Heartland Funds in Milwaukee, on his visit to a small, publicly traded head-hunting and temporary-help firm (market cap: $10 million), I didn't immediately understand what Miller was after. A meeting with the CEO's son (senior executive, head of acquisitions) and the CFO yielded an hour of questions and answers about competition, profit margins, potential risks, and the like -- the kind of thing you could do on the phone.<p>So why did Miller bother to go in person? The real reason didn't dawn on me until after the visit was over: He wanted to make sure these people weren't clowns or free spenders or both. "I had a sense they were in for the long haul," he said approvingly -- and indeed, the CEO's son repeatedly said, "I'm an ambitious character. I'd like to have a big company."<p>Miller also noted that everyone was friendly and that the son of the CEO's office was very small. "I want to see they're not squandering resources," he said. (Unfortunately, this company didn't make my list for this story.)<p>I decided not to visit every one of the remaining ten companies on my list but to concentrate on the one company that raised the most doubt: Jim Hjelm's Private Collection. The company had a great plan, and if it worked it would be a great investment -- but could management execute? A quick trip to New York would give me a chance to visit the manufacturing facility and meet the people.<p>In New York City's garment district, Joseph Murphy greeted me at the firm's headquarters, a showroom with a row of desks for salespeople in the back. The desks are occupied by five employees who keep track of the company's different lines and work with designers to improve them. When I stopped to chat with one of these women, she noted that sales for her line were up 300 percent on the year.<p>One sales representative spent ten minutes explaining to me why the firm's dresses are so great; I came away hazy on details but convinced. "It's ethereal," she said of a blue wedding gown 
designed by Lazaro -- he's one of the firm's two big-name designers and the only one who goes by a single name. "It may not sell, but it will get people's attention."<p>At the manufacturing plant across the street, I met him. Lazaro was wearing a T-shirt and cutting small pieces out of a bolt of satin. Murphy introduced me.<p>"Hi," said Lazaro, looking pleasant but slightly confused. <p>I nodded distantly to hide my own confusion: I didn't know whether to address him as Lazaro or Mr. Lazaro.<p>The plant was busy and crowded, but no sweatshop. I met the pattern cutter and some quality inspectors. Murphy talked some more, but by now I knew enough: These people were smart; their dresses were beautiful. The sales rep claimed the dresses are comfortable, too. I can't confirm that: You have to draw the line somewhere when you're researching a stock.<p>In the end, I wound up with eight picks; they're listed in the table on page 82. Please remember that it takes only a little buying to send the prices of these thinly traded stocks soaring. Readers might want to wait for a correction to buy any stock that has moved up a lot.
But this specific list isn't the point of this story anyway. The process I used to find these stocks is one that any investor can duplicate. Investing in microcaps is hard work -- a lot harder than buying based on a broker's recommendation or a tip in a magazine -- but it's also potentially extremely rewarding. And how often does the market -- let alone life -- actually reward you for hard work?<p>Additional reporting by Sean Donahue and Carol Pickering.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Biotechnology Industry, Technology Industry

