	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-You'll Never Drive Alone</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-You'll Never Drive Alone</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Cadillac and Lincoln drivers get some help from above<p>By Jim Mateja<p>You're traveling a desolate road late at night. Suddenly your right front tire blows out. The car careers off the road, over a ditch, and into a clump of bushes so thick that no passing vehicle will ever be able to see you. It's your worst automotive nightmare.<p><a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> have both taken steps to relieve motorist anxiety via a global-positioning satellite tied into a series of sensors in some of their top-model cars. The car's cellular phone is linked with a service center that knows the location of your vehicle and can send help in the event of a mechanical breakdown or medical emergency. It doesn't matter if you don't know where you are; the satellite pinpoints your location for the tow truck, which in some cases may already have been summoned.<p>OnStar, the GM system, will be offered as an option for the first time in all 1997 model Cadillacs, except the new Catera. The Ford system, called RESCU (Remote Emergency Satellite Cellular Unit), became an option with the 1996 Lincoln Continental. Both automakers say the system will eventually spread to other vehicles in their lineups.<p>RESCU costs $1,995, while OnStar will cost under $1,000, though with a monthly access fee (expected to be about $20 or $25). RESCU includes a set of four Michelin "run-flat" tires, which can be driven up to 50 miles at up to 55 mph at zero pressure, so you can drive to a safe place to change a flat.<p>OnStar is linked to a service center in Michigan, RESCU to one near Dallas. The cell phone links the driver to the center; in addition, both systems have special buttons to summon emergency aid. With both systems, if you press an emergency button and fail to respond to the staff member who calls the in-car phone, the staffer will immediately send emergency help to your location. OnStar has perhaps the most important safety feature: Any time an air bag inflates, sensors automatically dial up the service center to summon medical help to the site. RESCU doesn't yet have this extra, but Ford is considering adding it.<p>OnStar also offers some novel features that go above and beyond safety. Say you stop for lunch, and after an enjoyable meal you realize that you locked the keys in your car. No trouble. Just call the service center, tell the staffer your tale of woe, and give him or her your personal code. By pushing a few buttons, the staffer can unlock your car door.<p>Say you are running late for a plane, quickly park the car in a lot, and rush on board the craft. At 30,000 feet over Boise, you realize you forgot to lock your car. Call the service center, and the staffer can lock it for you. Or, on your return, you forget where you parked the car in the lot. The service center can set your car horn honking and your lights flashing so that you can retrieve it from the maze of vehicles.<p>That last service can also be a vital safety feature. Remember the car with the flat tire that ran into a clump of bushes so thick a rescue truck might have difficulty finding it? The honking horn and blinking lights can serve as a signal for rescuers.<p>If your car is stolen, OnStar can help locate it. RESCU doesn't have that capability, though Ford is considering adding another anti-theft feature in the near future -- if the car is stolen, the service center would be able to turn the radio up full blast and set either the heater in the summer or the air conditioning in the winter to the highest setting to totally frustrate the thief. <p>OnStar also allows the motorist to call for directions, for example, to the nearest restaurant or hotel. RESCU will provide the addresses and phone numbers of the nearest police station and motor club, but not those of eateries or places to sleep.<p>Ford may eventually add many of the same features OnStar offers, but points out that, while OnStar has a more varied menu, the motorist will pay for those conveniences through the monthly access fee. As with all other automotive accessories, the bottom line is that you get the luxury you pay for.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
