<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Proper Channels</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Proper Channels</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
FCC to couch potatoes: We're with you -- and your dish<p>By John Fried<p>Have you been forced to paint your satellite dish forest green to camouflage it in the shrubbery, fearful of the wrath of your homeowners association? Fear no longer. When President Clinton signed the Telecommunications Act of 1996, he gave the Federal Communications Commission the power to overturn local and private restrictions against satellite dishes smaller than one meter in diameter__which can cost as little as $200. The FCC has since preempted existing local zoning restrictions, and similar rules regarding bans by homeowners associations and community boards should be enacted by summer's end. "Homeowners won't have to ask anyone's permission," says Satellite Broadcasting & Communications Association spokesman David Withrow.<p>Satellite subscribers now number more than 5 million, and the new legislation will help fulfill industry predictions of over 14 million users by the year 2000. "The FCC decision reflects a long legal struggle for Americans who are used to freedom of choice and who have had cable forced down their throats by their neighbors and local government," says James E. Scott, editor of Satellite TV Week.<p>Dishes larger than one meter in diameter, which allow viewers to receive hundreds of channels as well as live feeds of unedited news footage, are still considered an eyesore and therefore subject to local and private restrictions, but some regulators feel these rules may also be relaxed in the future. Stay tuned.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry, Government Legislation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
