<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Banking's Next Big Mistake?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Banking's Next Big Mistake?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Banks have issued millions of new credit cards -- all that plastic will take a big bite out of earnings.<p>By Greg Millman<p>We thought we understood the market," says a rueful Brian J. O'Hare, president of Norwest Card Services, the credit-card division of Norwest in Minneapolis. In 1993 and 1994, Norwest blanketed the country with direct-mail credit-card solicitations. In 1995, the bank had to take an $11 million charge against earnings -- a result of losses on credit-card loans.<p>Norwest has company. Its 1995 write-off was small compared with the $106 million in losses at Mellon Bank. At Comerica, whose credit-card business grew by 80 percent in 1995, write-offs rose from 1.45 percent of receivables in the fourth quarter of 1994 to 8.48 percent in the fourth quarter of 1995.<p>The write-offs banks have declared so far may be only the tip of the iceberg. Banks have applied the same excessive zeal to credit-card lending as they once did to loans to third-world countries and to developers of commercial real estate, two fads that proved dangerous to their bottom lines. Investors who reaped big gains in bank stocks last year need to protect their profits by dumping the stocks of banks likely to face big losses from bad credit-card debt.<p>It's easy to see how banks got into this position again. They sent out more than three billion card solicitations last year. That blizzard of plastic hit consumers already snowed under by debt. Debt service, the minimum amount cardholders owe each month, is rising faster than income, and personal-bankruptcy filings rose 27 percent -- faster than in the depths of the last recession -- in the first four months of this year. A March study by Veribanc, an independent bank-research firm in Wakefield, Massachusetts, showed that credit-card delinquencies -- charges that are at least 90 days overdue -- surged from $2.02 billion in mid-1994 to $3.53 billion by the end of 1995. "The stuff that banks put in the mail in 1994 and 1995 is coming back, and it will take until the latter part of the year to work through the system," says Moshe Orenbuch, an analyst with Sanford Bernstein. "Bank provisions for loan losses are low," says Frank DeSantis Jr., an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette, "so relative to past times, it doesn't take a lot of deterioration to affect earnings."<p>It's not easy to identify those banks most at risk -- and the stocks that pose the most danger to investors. For example, by itself a high delinquency rate (meaning many credit-card holders aren't paying their charges) may not spell problems, says Veribanc research director Warren Heller. Banks that specialize in high-risk credits charge higher prices (annual fees, interest rates) on their cards, so paying accounts cover bad credits.<p>The chickens are most likely to come home to roost at banks that combine these characteristics: They allowed their credit-card business to grow rapidly, they depend on consumer loans for a big slice of income, they face intense pricing pressure that prevents them from raising interest rates, and they have inadequate reserves to cover losses. Since there tends to be a lag of 6 to 18 months before consumer-credit time bombs explode on bank income statements (and because bad-risk cardholders can keep transferring balances from one card to another before finally defaulting), experts believe the worst is yet to come.<p>The example of Norwest shows how these factors can form a financially lethal cocktail. Despite its efforts to target good credit risks, many of Norwest's offers were accepted by people who later lost high-paying jobs, a risk that hadn't shown up on credit reports. And because of interest-rate competition, Norwest lost some of its best customers. Consumers with good credit chose lower-rate cards, while riskier borrowers couldn't afford to be picky. O'Hare noticed delinquencies rising at the end of 1994, more than a year after the bank began its campaign. The problem didn't hit the bottom line until the end of 1995.<p>So which banks are most at risk? Certainly, stocks of the so-called monoline credit-card companies, <a name="NASD:ADVNA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12489"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Advanta</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:FUS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15687"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First USA</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:COF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42309"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Capital One Financial</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:KRB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12449"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MBNA</b></a>, which deal only in credit cards, bear watching. Beginning with almost no market share in 1990, this group had captured 18 percent of the $347 billion credit-card business five years later. Much of that growth came from balance-transfer offers that lured customers from other cards with low initial teaser rates. (MBNA is the exception; it relied on joint-marketing cards through organizations such as the Sierra Club.) Credit-card losses have been rising fast at all the monolines. For example, from the first quarter of 1995 to the like period of 1996, losses at Capital One rose from 2.8 percent of receivables to 4.7 percent and at First USA from 4.1 percent to 5.3 percent.<p>Despite impressive earnings growth, given these risks, valuations of all four stocks aren't attractive, says A. G. Edwards analyst Jack Peirce. Investors pay 16 times 12-month trailing earnings for the group, compared with an industry average price-to-earnings ratio of 11.2.<p>Some regional banks pose an even bigger danger to investors. Collectively, their card losses, as a percent of receivables, rose from 3.2 in the fourth quarter of 1994 to 4.1 in the same period of 1995, and individual stories are even more troubling. Richmond, Virginia's $18 billion Crestar Financial, the nation's 37th-largest bank, has 14 percent of its loan portfolio in credit cards. When Crestar raised low teaser rates last quarter, creditworthy account holders took a hike. Card losses rose from 2.7 percent of receivables in the first quarter of 1995 to 4.5 percent in the first quarter of 1996. And yet, trading at 13 times trailing earnings, Crestar stock remains expensive compared with its peers.<p>At another regional, the <a name="NYSE:BK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10177"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bank of New York</b></a>, charge-offs of bad credit-card debt rose a whopping 19 percent in the first quarter of 1996, according to an April report from Oppenheimer & Co. The stock is trading at 11 times earnings.<p>Investors shouldn't assume that banks see the writing on the wall. The <a name="NYSE:BKB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10175"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bank of Boston</b></a>, for instance, recently launched a credit-card campaign designed to make it the largest issuer in New England by the end of 1997, says director Jeff Slawsky. He isn't worried about the woes at other banks. "We believe we have a good handle on who we target," he says. That sounds familiar.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
