<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Need News Fast?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Need News Fast?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Eric Tyson<p>QUOTE.COM -- http://www.quote.com
INTERNET NEWS ALERT -- http://www.newsalert.com
FARCAST -- http://www.farcast.com
ROSEBUD -- CompuServe:  GO ROSEBUD
STOCKTRACKER -- http://www.stockcenter.com/stocktra.html
POINTCAST NETWORK -- http://www.pointcast.com
EYEQ -- 800-642-2525
DOW JONES NEWS/RETRIEVAL -- 800-522-3567<p>It's hard to believe, but not much more than a generation ago, print publications were about the only way people like you and me could get security prices, news, and research. Today, lightning-fast products, from on-line computer services to pagers, allow investors to maintain up-to-the-minute tabs on their stocks. This isn't necessarily a good thing. Keeping such a close eye on prices can cause some investors to lose sight of a stock's long-term fundamentals. Instead, the focus becomes short-term fluctuations; this often leads to emotionally based trading decisions. And the use of triggers, which alert investors to a stock's rise above or fall below certain preset price levels, intensifies this short-term myopia.<p>But a lot of people don't want to hear that; they feel compelled to watch their investments closely, minutely, and a growing multitude of software programs and Internet sites have been developed to satisfy this urge. Just enter a bit of portfolio information and these products will update -- some of them every night, some in real time -- the value of your investments. There's plenty these tools should do but don't: They don't produce useful performance analyses -- such as calculating total return over time -- and they can't create tax reports. But the best of them handle their more-limited tasks well.<p>Other than providing the possible entertainment value that comes with tracking investments closely, these services are most useful for their power to strain out items of interest from the daily flood of information sloshing around us. Users can gather news and articles on mutual funds, industries, and specific companies -- valuable stuff for long-term investment decisions.<p>Just don't expect these services to be cheap (which is the attraction of much of the Internet, after all). For example, Quote.Com, whose base rates range from $9.95 to $42.95 per month, depending on the number of portfolios being tracked, requires an additional fee before providing access to information from wire services and Standard & Poor. (Also, although it offers access to a fair number of information sources, the search mechanism doesn't permit "and/or" searching, which is a good way to scan for articles on specific topics.) And Internet News Alert, which provides quotes and real-time wire-service news for an otherwise affordable $3.95 per month, charges $1.95 a pop for more than one article per source in a single day. (It runs "and/or" searches, but has a relatively limited number of sources.)<p>Farcast, on the other hand, is an Internet service that allows users to request stock quotes and news retrievals via E-mail. To save time, summaries are sent initially, but full articles from the major wire services can be requested for no additional cost. This service is $9.95 per month. <p>Rosebud, a $39.95 software program, searches for specific news and finance topics on CompuServe; it minimizes on-line time when the meter's running by conducting its searches while the user is off-line and then storing retrieved information on the user's hard drive, from which it can be read later.<p>A couple other services also require a commercial on-line service such as CompuServe to act as a gateway to their Internet servers. But I'd pass on both. StockTracker ($9.95 per month; free during after-market hours) is limited: It provides information only on the U.S. stock market. PointCast Network, although it is free and can put chosen stock prices onto a computer as a ticker-tape screen saver, is weak when it comes to company news searches.<p>Generally, the aforementioned Web sites are not very user-friendly and often fall short of their marketing hype. For the best news-clipping and information screening, check out software programs such as EyeQ and Dow Jones News/Retrieval. These services can cost more than their Internet competitors, but they also provide more -- access to hundreds of publications and sophisticated search capabilities that allow searches arranged by keywords. They provide current market quotes and let users track portfolios. EyeQ costs $39 per month, $12 per connect hour, and $3 per document retrieved; DJNR is $29.95 a month for eight hours of evening and weekend usage.<p>As for stock quotes, true market addicts with big bucks to spend -- who have to know prices right now! -- will want to consider pagers or even (if they're willing to burn thousands of dollars) Quotron and Bloomberg terminals. But folks following the market this closely are probably traders reacting to short-term events, a costly and bad example for the rest of us. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
