<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-What They're Recommending</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1996 
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>WHAT THEY'RE RECOMMENDING<p>This month Al Frank, editor of The Prudent Speculator, joins our panel of financial-newsletter writers. The price listed with each writer's stock pick is the maximum at which the author considers the recommended stock attractive. The newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages, and may have changed his opinion after the April 22 publishing deadline.<p>AL FRANK
THE PRUDENT SPECULATOR<p>Looks for undervalued stocks with the potential for long-term appreciation.<p>Read-Rite (Milpitas, California), a leading manufacturer of magnetic recording heads for computer disc drives, is a deal. The stock has fallen more than 60 percent since last September over concerns about a choppy product transition and the announced merger of Seagate Technology and Read-Rite customer Conner Peripherals. Given that Conner represents only 13 percent of Read-Rite's sales and that Seagate plans to continue doing business with the company, I believe the market has overreacted. Trading at less than seven times 12-month trailing earnings and four times cash flow, the stock looks extremely undervalued. My target is $48 a share within three to five years.<p>JIM McCAMANT
MEDICAL TECHNOLOGY STOCK LETTER<p>Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.<p>ImmunoGen (Cambridge, Massachusetts) is developing some promising cancer treatments and is a major beneficiary of the FDA's recent decision to accelerate approval of cancer drugs. ImmunoGen's most advanced product, a treatment for B-cell lymphoma called Oncolysin B, is in phase-three trials. The company also has a full pipeline of other cancer treatments in earlier stages of development. ImmunoGen has a collaborative relationship with Harvard's Dana-Farber Cancer Institute for cancer research and will probably enter into a new corporate partnership sometime in the next few months. This would move the stock a lot higher.<p>MICHAEL MURPHY
CALIFORNIA TECHNOLOGY STOCK LETTER<p>Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.<p>Semiconductor-equipment maker Genus (Sunnyvale, California) dominates two markets: It has a 70 percent market share in tungsten chemical-vapor deposition (which puts layers of metal on the silicon chip) and an 80 percent share in high-energy ion deposition (a process that insulates the circuit lines from the underlying wafer). This latter process is used widely for DRAM chips and increasingly for logic chips. The stock has fallen 60 percent from a September high of $15 a share on the fear that DRAM makers will cut back production. On the contrary, Genus should have a strong backlog of orders. Investors have a good shot at doubling their money this year.<p>LOUIS NAVELLIER
MPT REVIEW<p>Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, 
low-volatility stocks.<p>Iomega (Roy, Utah) is in a great niche. The company makes fancy little Zip drives, otherwise known as removable data-storage devices. The stock is a big turnaround play: Earnings turned positive in the third quarter of 1995, and sales grew 287 percent from the fourth quarter of 1994 to the fourth quarter of 1995. On top of that, profit margins are expanding rapidly. One of the technical indicators I use__institutional accumulation__shows that Wall Street is very keen on the stock. In fact, Hambrecht & Quist, the West Coast investment firm specializing in technology, recently started pushing the stock, and other big firms have since piled in. <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
