				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jonathan Butler<p>A DETOUR FOR AUTO INVESTORS
Skip <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GM</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a>. Investors in auto stocks should take an alternate route__auto-parts makers. The recent strike against GM highlighted the Big Three's resolve to buy more parts from outside providers. But don't pick just any route: The Detroit trio are consolidating the number of suppliers they use, says Value Line analyst Alex Silverman. This could mean long-term gains for the stocks of those parts makers with the lowest costs, greatest efficiency, and strongest balance sheets, says Deutsche Morgan Grenfell/C. J. Lawrence analyst Mark Spellman.<p><p>

