<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Finding the Next Microsoft</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Finding the Next Microsoft</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>The goal: nothing less than the call of a lifetime<p>By Clint Willis<p>Imagine for a moment that you bought $10,000 worth of stock in <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> at the company's initial public offering back in March 1986. Imagine you're still holding on to those shares, and they're worth $869,000.<p>Back to reality. You and I didn't do that -- but we could have. By 1986, most of us had heard quite a lot about the ten-year-old wunder-company and its wunderkind founder, Bill Gates. Microsoft's IPO was among the most well publicized in history. And while it was tough for retail investors to get shares at the initial offering price of $21, the stock traded as low as $26 later that first month.
Now, I'm not the sort to mope about these things for more than a decade or so. So I recently set out to find the next Microsoft. By that, I mean the stock that could make me more or less rich if I was willing to bet my kids' college savings -- or, perhaps better, a modest chunk of my Keogh.<p>My plan was cunning yet simple: Talk to investors who bet on Microsoft early and find out what they saw in it. Then ask them and other farsighted money-management types about public companies that share most of the essential qualities that made Microsoft a huge success.<p>Over the course of two months, I made hundreds of telephone calls. Occasionally, I met with opposition. "When people ask me where to find the next Microsoft, I have a tendency to hang up," growled a fund manager who had bought shares at the IPO. For one thing, he noted, Microsoft circa 1986 was far from a sure thing.<p>Poobash, I figured. Why not ask the only venture capitalist in on the deal -- David Marquardt of Technology Venture Investors?
Well, for one thing, he wouldn't return my phone calls.<p>That's okay. If I'd been the only early-stage outside investor in Microsoft, I wouldn't return my calls, either. Anyway, a friend of Marquardt's told me that even Marquardt hadn't been convinced that Gates had a winner. "Marquardt called me and said he wished he could trade his piece of Microsoft for one of my deals," said the friend, also a venture capitalist. "It was an extremely high-risk situation with a very young, hardheaded guy in charge."<p>Undaunted, I tracked down Ruthann Quindlen, who had been 
a software analyst for Alex. Brown & Sons when that company underwrote the Microsoft deal. She's now a partner in the Palo Alto, California, venture-capital firm Institutional Venture Partners. "Microsoft back then was a very different company," she said. "When we took them public, it wasn't clear that their products or market position were going to make them a success."<p>Yet Quindlen and the rest of them must have seen something. I pressed on. A few dozen conversations later and I had a list of three qualities that defined the Microsoft opportunity. Those qualities would guide my search.<p>I didn't expect to find companies that perfectly met my criteria -- but in the end, I think I came surprisingly close in four cases. Along the way I got a half dozen or so highly speculative but extremely interesting stock picks. What's more, I learned about the Bower-Christensen hypothesis, which has something to do with...I forget. Anyway, here are the criteria.<p>The company must be part of an emerging paradigm shift. For those of you who haven't lately read Thomas S. Kuhn's The Structure of Scientific Revolutions, a paradigm shift occurs when people begin to see the world in fundamentally different terms and behave accordingly. Here I use the phrase the way stock pickers use it: to describe a big change that creates markets with opportunities for investors to make lots of money.<p>It's not enough for a market to be big; it must also be new or changing rapidly. "I look for disruptive technologies," said research analyst Brian Fernandez. "They disrupt the old order and create the kind of wide-open anarchy that produces big winners."<p>The <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>-led emergence of the personal computer, which Microsoft rode to success, was that kind of event. A few weeks into my research, I was convinced that similar events were occurring in no fewer than three fields: the Internet, telecommunications, and biotechnology. Ergo, I decided that the next Microsoft would emerge in one of those industries.<p>The company must have at least a quasi-monopoly on an enabling technology. An enabling technology is, very simply, one that allows people to make practical use of new products or systems. Microsoft's enabling technology was the MS-DOS operating system for PCs, which it bought on the cheap from another small Seattle firm in 1980 and then developed at the behest of IBM.<p>That relationship provided Microsoft with a continuing stream of royalties from Big Blue. It also allowed Gates to sell his operating system to other manufacturers, which had quickly come out with clones of IBM's machine. Soon Microsoft had the enviable position it maintains to this day: a de facto monopoly.<p>Take note, however: IBM didn't have to give Gates such a great deal. "He outsmarted them," said Phil Lamoreaux, general partner of the hedge fund Lamoreaux Partners in Sausalito, California. "IBM should have kept control of the operating system, but they still believed the big money was in mainframes."<p>Several people I called argued that something like this could not happen again: No company as powerful as IBM circa 1981 will make such a dumb mistake. But why ever not?<p>The company must capitalize on its monopoly to create new applications for the technology. "Microsoft didn't make its wealth off the operating system," said Roger McNamee, who bought Microsoft shares in 1987 and is now a general partner of Integral Capital Partners in Menlo Park, California. "It used its market position to develop a leadership position in software applications."<p>Gates used his firm's early profits to provide the clunky MS-DOS with a user interface with superior graphics, which he called Windows. Windows required a new generation of software applications -- and Microsoft seized the chance to introduce a raft of new programs that would eventually blow away then market leaders Lotus and Ashton-Tate.<p>A couple other matters are worth mentioning. First, none of 
this would have happened if Gates weren't a brilliant manager. Many people I called argued that the next Microsoft will be run by a genius like him -- one who understands marketing as well as technology and has a gift for lining up the right partners to provide market access and financial support. "Lots of people can catch a wave," Fernandez pointed out, "but most of them get wiped out."<p>Second, size is not a criterion. "Don't confuse small size with risk," Lamoreaux cautioned. "A small company that is in at the early stages of a market is safer than the third- or fourth-best company in a big, mature market."<p>So I was developing an idea of what the next Microsoft would look like. But how much should I pay for it? That's a tough one. Microsoft would have been cheap at almost any price in 1986. The same probably goes for its true heirs among today's small firms. In the end, I decided to give some thought to valuation but not to let 
a high stock price put me off a company that had a shot at a Microsoft-like position in the right market. That's no way to run 
a portfolio of stocks -- Warren Buffett wouldn't approve -- but I'm not running a portfolio. Anyway, Buffett missed Microsoft.<p>Here's the story of my hunt.<p>FIRST STOP, CYBER-SPACE
Not everyone agreed that the Internet would produce the next Microsoft, but many conceded the possibility. "The Internet is the closest thing we have to the PC market in the early '80s, because of the embryonic stage of any commerce done on it," said Lamoreaux. "It will clearly change rapidly in the balance of this century, and there are lots of opportunities for developers and users of technology. The Internet is a global phenomenon, though, not just domestic. Most of Microsoft's business is in the U.S., while the Internet permits global status instantly."<p>But Lamoreaux and others are still debating whether one company can play the role of a Microsoft. Competition is fierce, with banks (Citibank, <a name="NYSE:WFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11619"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wells Fargo</b></a>), telecommunications companies (<a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>), entertainment firms (<a name="NYSE:TWX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11482"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Time Warner</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a>), and Microsoft itself investing millions of dollars in products and services they hope will give them choke holds on various markets.<p>The most visible battle is the effort to establish a widely accepted platform that consumers will use to interface with the World Wide Web. <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape</b></a> has distributed more than 20 million free copies of its Internet browser in an effort to grab market share. The company has a stunning $4.2 billion in market capitalization. Still, no one knows how Netscape is going to earn its first dollar. I don't think that was ever true of Microsoft.<p>Meanwhile, everyone says the Net is going to make big money for merchants that sell everything from books to bedroom sets to bank accounts. But I won't find the next Microsoft among those sellers, either; the market is too fragmented. Instead, I must look at the middlemen who get paid to make all of those transactions possible.<p>The prime example, ironically, may be a company that Bill Gates tried to buy last year: software manufacturer <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a>. At the moment, the firm is best known for its market-dominant personal-finance and tax software, including Quicken. But some of Intuit's biggest fans are more excited about its early lead in the emerging colossus that is the home-banking market.<p>Intuit chairman Scott Cook is widely considered a visionary almost on the order of Gates -- and like Gates, he's known for building relationships with strong allies. As of early 1996, Cook had forged agreements with 37 financial institutions to offer on-line banking services to Quicken customers. That's the largest customer base (more than ten million accounts) with access to such services, and this gives the firm a head start over competitors like Microsoft and <a name="NASD:CKFR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43345"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CheckFree</b></a>.<p>The firm's highly profitable software business (Intuit is expected to sell $100 million worth of Quicken alone this year) generates plenty of money to build the infrastructure needed to handle millions of financial transactions. Meanwhile, Intuit is increasing its consumer base by offering free software that lets customers establish home banking with participating banks. "They look benign now giving away this banking system," said Roger McNamee. "But once they get everyone on it and it becomes the de facto standard, they're going to make serious money."<p>Most of that money will come from financial institutions, which might pay Intuit as much as $100 for each customer who signs on. And when the network is established, the company can start charging for home banking as well as on-line investing, insurance sales, and the like. <p>I could go on. The analysts I talked to did. But Intuit has a market capitalization of $2 billion and is a company we all know; it almost felt like cheating to stop there. What about smaller outfits?<p>Many of the companies scrambling for a piece of the Net are tiny. It's generally hard to find among them one with a clear shot at a dominant position in a fat niche. Still, a few people mentioned <a name="NASD:CYCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47308"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CyberCash</b></a>. The firm is building a system by which companies and customers make fast, secure credit-card and checklike or cashlike purchases on the Net. "The potential market is absolutely enormous," said Steven Birer, senior analyst at Hambrecht & Quist in San Francisco.<p>A report by Killen & Associates, a research firm in Palo Alto, California, claims that the market for electronic commerce and financial services will grow from $369 billion in 1995 to $774 billion by 2000 and $1.6 trillion by 2005. "There doesn't need to be a lot of payment systems on the Internet," said Birer. "One or two will be enough, and CyberCash's could be in that number."<p>A few more phone calls and I found myself agreeing that it's possible. The firm just might end up in a position to charge fees on huge numbers of credit-card and other transactions over the Net.<p>Right now, CyberCash has the best technology. Its products include the first real-time Web-based credit-card payment system, launched about a year ago; this year, the firm will introduce a service that lets consumers keep money in a CyberCash "wallet" and draw from it to pay for purchases over the Net. CyberCash will also roll out what it calls a coin service, which will let consumers make small on-the-spot payments for information and games.<p>What's more, CyberCash has established relationships with banks that process 85 percent of U.S. credit-card transactions. It has forged alliances with dozens of firms (including <a name="NASD:CSRV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43062"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CompuServe</b></a>, CheckFree, <a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a>, and Toshiba), making CyberCash software available to more potential users. Consumers can also download free CyberCash software from the firm's Web site (http://www.cybercash.com).<p>CyberCash co-founder and CEO Bill Melton made his name and fortune as the founder of VeriFone, which developed the technology behind those credit-card terminals you run your card through at the grocery store. "Melton's been bringing technology to the financial industry for the past three decades," enthused CyberCash's other founder, marketing vice president Magdalena Yesil. "He understands the dynamics between banks, merchants, and technology."<p>Unlike Intuit -- or Microsoft in its infancy -- CyberCash has yet to earn a profit. The firm raised $40 million by going public this February and now has a market cap of about $325 million. Revenues will grow from $1 million this year to $25 million in 1997, according to Steve Birer's estimate. He figures the firm will earn its first profit in 1998.<p>But how big can CyberCash get? Let's say it earns a fee of 0.01 percent on 20 percent of the $1.6 trillion in projected Internet transactions by 2005. That's revenue of $320 million compared with Microsoft's $5.9 billion this year.<p>INFORMATION, PLEASE
During the past decade or so, companies such as <a name="NASD:COMS"></a><b>3Com</b> and <a name="NYSE:BAY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15419"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bay Networks</b></a> have made fortunes creating computer networks for businesses. Others such as AT&T and <a name="NASD:ERICY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41776"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ericsson</b></a> have expanded their empires to embrace new technologies such as cellular communication.<p>What's left? Plenty, I gather. Venture capitalists and techno types talk of the "wide-area network" -- the sprawling web of communication devices and technologies emerging around the world. The development of that network includes a shift from analog to high-speed digital networks, from regulated monopolies to free global markets, and from wires and cables to wireless delivery of information. "There is a tsunami of change in the telecommunications market," said Gary Morgenthaler of the venture-capital firm Morgenthaler Ventures in Palo Alto and Cleveland. "If you cleverly design a product, you can lead this market."<p>All right, which product? The cable and phone companies will be spending billions of dollars laying the wires, fiber-optic lines, and coaxial cables to get higher-speed lines into homes and businesses. Forget them, I was told; look for the firms that will supply gear that makes those networks work. Makers of high-speed ethernet switches, for example. These switches allow users on a local-area network to exploit the network's full data-transfer capability, or bandwidth. Without the switches, the networks slow down.<p>Switching companies such as <a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cisco Systems</b></a> and <a name="NASD:ASND"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41997"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ascend Communications</b></a>, with market caps of $26 billion and $6 
billion, respectively, are already well known to investors. But Lamoreaux mentioned a small firm ($300 million market cap) founded by Shlomo Margalit and Zeev Rav-Noy. This eight-year-old company, <a name="NASD:MRVC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17187"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MRV Communications</b></a>, makes ethernet switches that run at 100 megabits per second versus the old standard of 10 megabits per second.<p>Aharon Orlansky at Preferred Technology, a New York City brokerage firm, is by all accounts the man to talk to about MRV. Trouble is, he opened our conversation as follows: "First of all, to say that they are the next Microsoft is not true."<p>I hate when that happens. Orlansky indicated that MRV isn't out to dominate data networking in the way that Microsoft dominates software. But before I could hang up, he added that MRV does manufacture the best 100-megabit switches on the market. And it got to that market quickly enough to beat out much bigger competitors like 3Com and Bay Networks. What's more, MRV is a low-cost producer.<p>Great technology and low costs aren't enough to dominate a market these days, but MRV has also taken a page out of the Microsoft manual by cutting a deal to supply switches to industry giant <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>. Now the rest of the industry might think about changing to MRV.<p>There's also MRV's fiber-optic technology, which helps convert electrical power into light for transmission over high-speed fiber-optic cable. Together, the fiber-optic and ethernet switching markets will account for some $6 billion in sales in 1996. Unfortunately, MRV's share of those markets is less than 2 percent. And while that share will probably grow, I concluded that Orlansky was right: MRV is not the next Microsoft.<p>That said, MRV might be a pretty good investment. The company has no debt and $9.1 million in cash. Orlansky figured sales would grow 60 to 100 percent annually over the next three years and hit at least $400 million by 2000. He thought the company could earn $3.50 a share, justifying a stock price of $125.<p>That's a potential return of 290 percent in four years. No Microsoft, but it's better than a poke in the eye with a sharp stick.<p>Two or three dozen phone calls later, I was excited again. I had become a believer in something called consumer computing devices, or CCDs.<p>Got a minute? The shift to wireless communication and digital technology allows more information to be delivered at higher speeds to an increasingly mobile population -- including a lot of people armed with CCDs, which might range from so-called smart phones (phones that handle both voice and data transmissions -- the latter via screens that display faxes, E-mail, that sort of thing) to handheld organizers. "By the end of the decade, half of all cellular phones will be smart phones," said Todd Bakar, an analyst at Hambrecht & Quist in San Francisco.<p>The market for smart phones and organizers will belong to global telecom and hardware companies, just as <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple</b></a>, IBM, and IBM-clone manufacturers dominated the emerging PC market. But like IBM a decade ago, companies like Ericsson and <a name="NYSE:NOK.A"></a><b>Nokia</b> are looking to outside sources for the low-cost, flexible operating systems that will drive their new machines.<p>Enter Geoworks, with its $400 million market cap and <a name="NASD:GSCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51257"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GEOS</b></a> operating system. The 13-year-old company paid its dues during the 1980s and early 1990s, making a low-cost, efficient operating system that didn't use much memory; it was ideal for primitive computers, such as the old Commodore 64. Microsoft ate Geoworks' lunch along with everyone else's.<p>Geoworks founder Brian Dougherty may have the last laugh. He used the company's seemingly outmoded technology as the basis for a new GEOS operating system, which is cheap and flexible enough to allow CCD manufacturers to design their products around it.<p>This time, Geoworks has a serious jump on the competition, which includes Microsoft as well as Apple and General Magic. Analyst Jeffrey Schlesinger of UBS Securities went further, saying that Geoworks' operating system is a de facto standard.<p>That's what I wanted to hear. <p>Geoworks' list of partners includes Ericsson, Nokia, <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a>, Toshiba, Sharp, and other big names. The by-all-accounts-fabulous Hewlett-Packard OmniGo 100 organizer already uses the GEOS operating system, as does the new Nokia 9000 Communicator smart phone.<p>There's more. Microsoft used its operating system as a base to launch a generation of software applications ranging from Microsoft Word to Excel. Likewise, Geoworks is teaming up with its partners to develop applications that will work on the GEOS operating system. "The real story is going to be the applications and add-on products it develops with the equipment makers," said Schlesinger. "It's very similar to the Microsoft model." <p>Moreover, unlike Microsoft in its early days, Geoworks can look to overseas markets. Digital cellular networks already exist in Europe, Asia, and Australia. "Our biggest markets for now are Europe, Japan, and the U.S. -- in that order," said Geoworks CEO Gordon Mayer.<p>I was briefly disappointed to learn that the company was losing money: Schlesinger estimated it would lose $9.2 million in the fiscal year ended March 1996. But the firm has $50 million in the bank, most of it from its public offerings in June 1994 and November 1995 and from equipment manufacturers who are using the product. Gary Morgenthaler figured there would be 100 million wireless-phone subscribers in the U.S. and Canada alone by 2000 (there are now a fourth that many). And it can't be long before the third world goes wireless. "This is the same kind of paradigm shift that Microsoft rode to success," Morgenthaler concluded.<p>I figured I was getting warm again: Someone had said "paradigm."<p>I TAKE THE CURE
"The next Microsoft will almost certainly be a biotechnology company," according to Michael Murphy, editor of California Technology Stock Letter. Murphy warmed to the topic quickly; he said that buying the right biotech stocks now is like investing in <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> in 1907. He pointed out that the entire biotech industry has a market capitalization of perhaps $65 billion, not much bigger than Microsoft's alone.<p>Trouble is, most biotech companies don't make any money. Exceptions, such as Amgen, whose 1996 revenues Value Line estimates will be $2.2 billion, are no longer cutting edge. The fortunes of the profitless rest are riding on the quirks of human body chemistry and the FDA approval process.<p>That hardly sounds like the Microsoft model. Still, there was a time -- a very brief time -- when Microsoft was unprofitable. And in the past several years, there has been progress toward new types of treatments such as gene therapy, which has enormous potential to attack ailments ranging from cancer to AIDS.<p>Forget the Internet. If they can cure everything, I'm happy to go back to a world of bike couriers and typewriters. But can they? "During the next 5 to 25 years, you're going to see a whole remaking of medicine," insisted Morgenthaler. "This will be a paradigm shift in the way drugs are discovered and applied to diagnosis and treatment."<p>Then I learned that Bill Gates himself is a major investor in biotech. 
"If I had his money, I'd be investing in biotech, too," added my source. "I mean, the Internet won't save him if he needs an organ transplant."<p>Gates is the largest single shareholder in a little gem called <a name="NASD:ICOS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12419"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ICOS</b></a>, which is developing drugs to treat inflammatory conditions like asthma and cardiovascular disease. ICOS founder George Rathmann, who in another life gave Amgen its start, has Gates-like credibility. "People in biotech are always looking for the next <a name="NASD:AMGN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12623"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Amgen</b></a>," said Jacqueline Siegel, an analyst with Gerard Klauer Mattison in New York City. "Well, the guy who founded it runs ICOS."<p>ICOS has a broad lineup of potential blockbusters that are currently in clinical trials or in preclinical research. But the company lacks the kind of single unifying technology or product that will force the world to come to it -- nothing ICOS has looks comparable to Microsoft's original operating system. ICOS could become a very big company some day, but it didn't quite fit my model. Reluctantly, I moved on.<p>Another 30 or 40 telephone calls (but who's counting?) and I found what I was looking for: At least a couple of biotech companies are developing strategic positions that will allow them to siphon off large portions of the money that will be made in the biotech industry's biggest markets.<p>Like Microsoft in its early days, San Diego's <a name="NASD:VICL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16150"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vical</b></a> is working on a technology that industry giants will need to create their next generation of products. The giants are huge drug manufacturers, and the products are synthetic genetic materials used to fight disease -- "DNA as drugs" is how Vical's CEO, Alain Schreiber, described them. "Genes in a vial." <p>During the past several years, companies such as Human Genome Sciences in Rockville, Maryland, have been working to decode the human body's gene sequence. So far, HGS has isolated and sequenced more than 850,000 individual genes; it has used that information to develop more than 120 therapeutic protein candidates and 60 novel protein targets for small-molecule-drug discovery.<p>I don't know what that means, do you? They tell me that, for starters, this information can be used to create anti-inflammatory, anti-viral, anti-osteoporosis, and anti-cancer agents. But the biggest winners may turn out to be companies that control the enabling technology that delivers those applications to the human cell.<p>That's where Vical comes in. Murphy and everyone else I asked pointed out that Vical was the leader in two technologies -- naked DNA therapy and cytofectins -- that allow gene therapy without the use of viral delivery systems. "It's not the only approach, but it has the right combination of ecacy, safety, and low cost," said David Stone, an analyst with Cowan & Co. in Boston. "That makes Vical the first gene-therapy company ready for prime time."<p>Companies such as <a name="NASD:SOMA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13635"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Somatix Therapy</b></a> and <a name="NASD:TGEN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42013"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Targeted Genetics</b></a> are working on ways to deliver gene-based therapy. But most of them rely on viruses to transport the genes. "You can't control viruses," said Murphy. "In one study, 10 percent of the virus ended up in the poor mice's testicles. You just can't go into human trials with that kind of unpredictability."<p>I'll say. Anyway, like Gates before him, Alain Schreiber has parlayed his firm's technology into licensing agreements with big companies -- most notably <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a> and Pasteur Mrieux-Connaught. Those firms make payments to Vical every time a vaccine that uses Vical's technique passes into a new phase of FDA approval. Better yet, Vical will eventually share in the profits from resulting approved vaccines. Like Microsoft, Vical will make money from the delivery system now and profit from specific applications later.<p>Stone figured Vical probably wouldn't earn its first profit until around 1999; that's okay for now because the company has $50 million in cash, and its cash "burn rate" is an exceptionally low $10 million a year.  Schreiber can always do another public stock offering or tap corporate partners for cash -- barring a series of disasters in trials for the firm's therapies.<p>"It's too early to say they've won the race," Stone told me. "But Vical is in the pole position." He figures Vical could go from its current market cap of $212 million to $4 billion or $5 billion in five years and keep growing from there.<p>Then again, it could go out of business without ever earning a nickel.<p>The same goes for <a name="NASD:ISIP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14081"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Isis Pharmaceuticals</b></a>, a Carlsbad, California, company that has emerged as the leader in antisense technology. Like gene therapy, antisense may be useful in attacking a huge range of problems, from inflammatory diseases to cancer; thus, the potential market is almost boundless.<p>"We believe we are building a strong proprietary position in antisense technology, and we believe that that will be an asset of extraordinary value," said Isis chairman and CEO Stanley T. Crooke. At last count, the firm had applied for over 200 patents, with 19 allowed (the last step on the road to issuance) and 19 issued.<p>Better, Isis isn't content to license its technology to other companies. It has agreements with two major partners -- 
a royalty deal with Ciba-Geigy and a 50-50 split of profits with Boehringer Ingelheim. Isis has also struck a deal with Human Genome Sciences; the companies will work together to develop antisense compounds for pharmaceutical companies. <p>By the end of 1996, Isis will have four or five antisense compounds in clinical trials with human subjects. "Isis is clearly going to be the leader in antisense therapy," said Jim McCamant, editor of Medical Technology Stock Letter.<p>Analyst Paul Boni of Mehta and Isaly in New York City figured that Isis will turn its first profit in 2000. Meanwhile, it's running through some $20 million each year; that money comes out of its cash hoard, currently $75 million. It's still 
a small company, with a market cap of about $275 million.<p>Analyst David Stone acknowledged that Isis, like Vical, has a shot at a market cap of $4 billion to $5 billion in the next five years or so. He didn't want to go further and put a market cap on either firm for a decade or two from now, but he did draw an analogy that I liked.<p>"There's another order of magnitude where the big drug companies with market caps of $50 billion or more are today," Stone said. "Companies like Vical and Isis might 
get there."<p>The next Merck? I'll take it.<p>HOME AT LAST
I like every company I've investigated. You could make me happy by giving me stock in any of them. But I started this job with the goal of picking one best bet, so which of these companies has the best shot at delivering Microsoft-like gains over the next decade?<p>Here goes. Intuit is building a strong position in the potentially huge market for home-banking and related services, and has proved that it can make money creating applications to exploit that position further. But we're a bit late on Intuit. CyberCash is a leader in its field now, but I'm not convinced that it can build 
a monopoly; a bigger company may yet swat it aside.<p>Next, telecommunications. MRV's potential market is too small, but Geoworks...I like Geoworks. It feels like Microsoft. The firm's operating system is clearly an emerging standard. Geoworks is working hard to create applications that will work with its operating system, just as Bill Gates did with Microsoft. And smart phones are probably going to be big.<p>But not as big as biotech. That's why in the end I have to vote for Vical or Isis. Both are still small in terms of market cap; both have a strong lead in developing enabling technologies with potentially huge markets.<p>It's a tough choice between the two, but I have the sense that Isis may be better focused on protecting its lead (people at the company talked a lot about patents), and Isis also works harder on developing products whose profits it will largely keep. Then there's the intangible factor: The people at Isis are tremendously excited about what they're doing; they seem to have a vision. "Maybe they're just more excited about making lots of money," suggested a colleague of mine.<p>Well, fine. Isis it is.<p>
Additional reporting contributed by Sean Donahue and Carol Pickering.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry, Biotechnology Industry, Stock Investing Strategies<p>

