	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Return of Biotech</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-The Return of Biotech</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> THE RETURN OF BIOTECH <p>Jim McCamant thinks the current rally in emerging drug stocks has a long way to run  <p> By Jonathan Butler   <p> Since the first biotechnology company went public in 1980, Jim McCamant has been widely regarded as a leading authority on emerging drug companies. Although the biotechnology "crash" of 1992 has made positive returns hard to come by in recent years, the stocks recommended by McCamants's Medical Technology Stock Letter rose108 percent during 1995. He also contributes each issue to Worth's"What They're Recommending" column.   <p> Worth: Why do you focus on biotechnology? <p>McCamant: It's probably the most inefficient part of the stockmarket. The frustrating thing is that the inefficiencies tend to last years. The cycle's fairly long, and there are few good analysts --  partly because price-to-earnings ratios don't have anything to do with the value of these companies. What matters is the quality of the science and the people.  <p> Biotech stocks last peaked in January 1992. Where are we now in the cycle?  <p>The last cycle, which began in the second quarter of 1987, was four and a half years. What creates bottoms and tops are excesses, and there aren't many excesses now, so I don't think there will be a downturn until 1997.  <p> Has anything changed since the last biotech downturn? <p>There are now more products in the clinical process and late stages of development. In 1992, at the top of the cycle, there were 25 products in trials; now there are around 150.   <p> If price-to-earnings ratios are not useful, how do you value biotech companies?  <p>One clue is, which biotechs are receiving high premiums from their big-company partners? When Isis did a deal with Germany's Boehrin-ger-Ingelheim, it sold stock privately at $15 a share even though Isis stock was trading publicly at less than $6 ashare. The big drug companies have realized that they're not getting much value for their research dollars and that it's more attractive to buy products or marketing rights from a biotech company that already has a technology.  <p> How do you identify good stocks? <p>I look for companies that can produce many applications from a technology. This decreases short-term risk and increases the potential long-term gain. If investors hold on in the bad times,they should be able to make ten to one on the upside over five years.  <p> Any recommendations? <p><a name="NASD:CHIR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12972"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chiron</b></a> is the best managed of the large biotechs. It's reasonably priced and has the broadest product pipeline. I also like three second-tier companies. <a name="NASD:ISIP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14081"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Isis</b></a>is the leader in antisense technology, which turns off the production of disease-causing proteins in the cell. <a name="NASD:LGND"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13469"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ligand</b></a> is developing hormone products. And Agouron Pharmaceuticals is testing an AIDS drug and an anticancer product. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Biotechnology Industry, Stock Investing 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
