<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-The Dowry in Utility Marriages</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Dowry in Utility Marriages</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-The Dowry in Utility Marriages</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> THE DOWRY IN UTILITY MARRIAGES <p>Low-cost producers will profit as takeovers transform once staid electrics  <p> By Anne Field  <p> Mergers aren't just for such glamour industries as media and high-technology anymore. Dull ol' electric utilities are merging at a steady pace five deals were pending in 1995, up from three in 1994, and analysts predict a dozen major marriages over the next 12 to 18 months. Investors won't reap the premiums that came with such high-pro file deals as <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM's</b></a> acquisition of Lotus Development or <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Walt Disney's</b></a> union with ABC/Cap Cities, but investors who pick the right utility can look forward to a 10 to 15 percent rise in the value of their stocks and possibly to a post-acquisition increase in dividends.   <p> The merger of WPL Holdings with two smaller utilities is typical of the current wave of deals. The Madison, Wisconsin, electric company recently acquired two colleagues in Iowa, IES Industries and Interstate Power. When the deal is complete, investors in the two Iowa electrics are likely to get 11 percent and 15 percent premiums for their shares, respectively. More over, the new company, Interstate Energy, may be able to boost dividends as it finds efficiencies of scale. Management expects such savings to total $700 million over ten years.  <p> A combination of slowing demand for electricity and deregulation is driving utilities into one another's arms. Energy-conservation efforts over the past two decades have substantially cut the need for power driving rate increases to a new low in 1994 and created surplus capacity in some regions. At the same time, the laws governing the sale of bulk power have changed to make interregional sales easier. Until 1992, utilities basically had been limited to selling power to wholesalers in their immediate geographic areas. That year, a new law let utilities and independents sell power to any wholesaler anywhere.  <p> More recently, states have begun considering a practice called retail wheeling, which would allow utilities in neighboring states to compete for direct access to big commercial and industrial customers and, perhaps someday, to all consumers. In other words, customers will be able to shop for the cheapest service, rather than have to buy from the local utility. "The business is going through a profound change. In ten years, it will be totally different," says Edward Tirello, an analyst at NatWest Securities.  <p> In this newly competitive environment, low-cost producers of electricity will prosper and grow while high-cost producers will stagger under excessive generating costs. As a result, utilities have been slashing jobs and overhead for the past decade. Now, with much of the easy cost cutting done, they're seeking further reductions through mergers. "By combining with a nearby lower-cost utility, companies can produce operating ef ficiencies through workforce reduction, smarter use of generation and transmission assets, and increased purchasing power for fuel," says Nancy Messer, an analyst with A. G. Edwards & Sons.  <p> Utility investors need to weed out high-cost producers from their portfolios. These tend to be companies that have hefty investments in nuclear power or other expensive new generating plants, or that operate in high-tax states. Both problems plague Long Island Lighting Company in New York, for example, which charges a whopping 15.3 cents per kilowatt hour to generate power. Interstate Energy's regional competitors, such as Commonwealth Edison in Chicago and Centerior in Cleveland, face similar problems; expensive stakes in nuclear power keep these utilities' rates at about 8 cents per kilowatt hour, slightly above the national average of 7.2 cents but about 40 percent higher than Interstate Energy's rate of 5 cents per kilowatt hour.  <p> Investors should hunt for low-cost producers that will be valuable acquisitions either for companies hoping to expand their low-costoperations or for high-cost electric utilities looking to lower the price of generating power. Three promising candidates are <a name="NYSE:ALS"></a><b>Allegheny Power System</b>, headquartered in New York City, <a name="NYSE:OGE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11115"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oklahoma Gas & Electric</b></a> (OG&E) in Oklahoma City, and <a name="NYSE:WPS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11646"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>WPS Resources</b></a> in Green Bay, Wisconsin. All three offered yields close to the industry median of 5.9 percent in mid-December.  <p> Allegheny is a strong, medium-sized player with a market cap of $3.4 billion and 1.3 million customers in Pennsylvania, Maryland, Ohio, Virginia, and West Virginia. The utility has low rates 5.4 cents per kilowatt hour and 12-month trailing earnings of $1.98 a share as of last December. Earnings are projected to increase to $2 a share for the four quarters of 1995 and to $2.03 in 1996. <p> OG&E provides electricity to about 670,000 customers in Oklahoma and western Arkansas. A $1.7 billion company with a low rate of 5.8 cents per kilowatt hour, OG&E earns a 13.3 percent return on equity above the industry norm of 11.5 percent. Like Allegheny, OE&G gets most of its power from older, coal-based facilities and has no investment in nuclear plants. OE&G's trailing 12-month earnings of $3.05 a share should grow thanks to recent cost-cutting measures. A possible merger would also drive up the value of shares. A likely suitor is Western Resources in Kansas, a $2 billion utility that also has low rates and may be looking to expand.  <p> WPS Resources is the holding company that owns Wisconsin Public Service, which supplies electricity to parts of Wisconsin and Michigan. WPL Holdings almost went after WPS, but agreed to acquire the Iowa companies instead. It therefore may be some time before another company starts courting WPS, but in the long term, the utility is a likely merger candidate. With one of the strongest balance sheets of any utility, WPS increased earnings from $2.21 a share in 1994 to $2.30 in 1995, despite recent rate reductions. Earnings are projected to rise to $2.39 a share in 1996. Most important, the company's power costs are just  five cents per kilowatt hour.   <p> Other low-cost producers that would make attractive merger partners are Idaho Power, one of the cheapest providers in the U.S. (just 3.8 cents per kilowatt hour), and Montana Power (4.7 cents). Both would be especially attractive to a high-cost California utility, such as Southern California Edison (10.4 cents per kilowatt hour), or to a utility looking to sell to the California market. Pennsylvania Power & Light, with a 7.2-cents-per-kilowatt-hour rate, poses a threat to overpriced utilities in the high-tax New York area.  <p> Investors who are counting on stock gains from takeovers have to be patient. State regulators must approve each merger, a process that usually takes 18 months. Regulators can also nix the deal, so analysts recommend diversifying with a utility mutual fund such as one of Franklin's utility funds or <a name="FUND:FSUTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSUTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Select Utilities Growth</b></a> or a basket of about 15 medium-sized companies. Nevertheless, investors can rest assured that the new current of mergers will keep sparks flying in electric utilities for some time to come: NatWest's Tirello expects the number of investor-owned utilities to decline to 40 from 120 during the next  five years.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
