	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Net-Surfing Upstream</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Net-Surfing Upstream</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Net-Surfing Upstream</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> NET-SURFING UPSTREAM <p>There's more certain profit in the companies that make the nuts and bolts of the internet  <p> By Jonathan Butler  <p> In 1995 every stock touched by the Internet turned to gold.<a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape Communications</b></a>, which makes a browser to navigate the Net, was  first offered to the public in August at $28 a share; it closed at $161.25 on December 6. A competitor, <a name="NASD:SPYG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42484"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Spyglass</b></a>, recently traded at $110 a share, up from an offering price of $17. The stock prices of Performance Systems International (PSI) and <a name="NASD:UUNT"></a><b>UuNetTechnologies</b> companies that hook individuals up to the Net doubled and tripled, respectively, during the year.  <p> The Internet itself is no fad. The number of users worldwide grew to 38 million at the end of 1994, and is expected to reach 200 million by 1999, according to International Data Corporation. That's a 50 percent annual compound growth rate over the next four years.  <p> But not every company so fervently embraced by investors will grow at that pace. Some, such as Netscape and Spyglass, or UuNet and PSI, are competitors, and they all face challenges from much bigger outfits such as <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>. "It's hard to see what would stop a phone company from offering the same service," says Nick Moore, an analyst at Franklin Funds in San Mateo, California.  <p> Investors who want to pro fit from the Internet phenomenon, but who shudder at paying 538 times projected 1996 earnings the recent price for Netscape for untested companies facing intense competition, should try a time-honored strategy called upstreaming. The term is most commonly applied to vertical industries suchas oil, where refiners the downstream companies that sell to consumers rely on upstream exploration and production companies for their raw materials. With the Internet, upstreaming means concentrating on the more established companies that providethe raw materials the modems, the routers, and the switches of the information superhighway, as opposed to the untested  firms that sell software and access services to consumers. "You don't know whether or not Netscape is going to win, but either way, the equipment companies that are building the actual physical network are going to do well," says John Segrich, an analyst at Gabelli & Co. in Rye, New York.  <p> Modems and modem-like products connect computers to the Internet, and include anything from small, $100-to-$200 modems that sit beside desktop PCs to T1 carriers high-capacity modem-like boxes that cost thousands of dollars a piece.  <p> Two companies currently dominate this business: <a name="NASD:ASND"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41997"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ascend Communications</b></a>and U.S. Robotics. Ascend, based in Alameda, California, thrives on speed. Its Pipeline product uses a form of digital transmission, called ISDN, that is roughly ten times faster than a traditional modem. Pipeline accounts for 25 percent of Ascend's sales, which are growing at a rate of 40 percent a quarter. Ascend also makes a switch used by 28 of the country's top 30 companies that connect users to the Internet such as <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b> and UuNet.   <p> Analysts expect Ascend's earnings to rise about 75 percent in1996. So it's not surprising that its stock traded at 92 times trailing 12-month earnings as of December and roughly 75 times the median 1996 earnings estimate.  <p> The modems produced by U.S. Robotics, located in Skokie, Illinois, aren't as speedy as Ascend's Pipeline, but U.S. Robotics is closing the gap. It acquired ISDN Systems last August for about $40 million in stock. Earnings at the company are growing at more than 50 percent a year. The stock recently traded at 68 times trailing 12-month earnings and about 35 times the median 1996 earnings estimate.  <p> Once connected to the Internet, users can choose to download (retrieve) or upload (send) information, or exchange electronic-mail messages with other users. All those transactions pass through a server, which oversees connections and the log-ins that identify different users. Diversified computer-makers such as <a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a>,<a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:SGI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11735"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Silicon Graphics</b></a> dominate the server business. <p> Investors can find purer plays in companies that make routers and switches. Routers act as intelligent traffic directors, selecting the best path for information to travel. <a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cisco Systems</b></a>,based in San Jose, California, is by far the biggest producer of routers, which account for 90 percent of its sales. Becauseit makes servers and switches as well, Cisco can offer its clients one-stop shopping, says Tyler Smith, manager of the $1.4 billion <a name="FUND:AGBBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/AGBBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alliance Growth B</b></a> fund. As of December, investors could buy Cisco stock for 46 times trailing 12-month earnings and roughly 29 times the median 1996 earnings estimate.  <p> <a name="NYSE:BAY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15419"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bay Networks</b></a> of Santa Clara, California, is a distant but competitive number two in the router market. The company is the result of a 1994 merger between Wellfleet Communications, a maker of routers,and SynOptics Communications, a producer of intelligent hubs, which connect networks. The stock recently traded at 50 times12-month trailing earnings.   <p> One of the ways to increase the capacity and performance of a router-based network is to add a switch. Similar to those used by telephone companies to process the thousands of calls they receive each minute, switches act as liaisons between the modem-type equipment offered by Ascend and U.S. Robotics and the routers provided by Cisco. The nascent Internet switch market, $25 million in sales in 1995, is expected to double in 1996.  <p> <a name="NASD:CSCC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42090"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cascade Communications</b></a>, located in Westford, Massachusetts,is the nation's largest maker of Internet switches, and supplies three out of the four largest service providers. But San Josebased <a name="NASD:STRM"></a><b>StrataCom</b> is biting at its heels. StrataCom's stock trades at 60 times 12-month trailing earnings, and its recent deal to provide CompuServe with $30 million of equipment could signal an important competitive breakthrough, says Tom Pincince at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Massachusetts. In an investment area as rich and volatile as the Internet, excitement can be found even far upstream. <p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategies<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
