	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Mergers, Mergers Everywhere</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Mergers, Mergers Everywhere</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Mergers, Mergers Everywhere</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> MERGERS, MERGERS EVERYWHERE <p>It doesn't take much looking to find more industries ripe for mergers and takeovers  <p> By Anne Field  <p> Investors looking to profit from the current wave of mergers have no shortage of industries to study. Here are some examples:  <p> CARDIOVASCULAR MEDICAL DEVICES  <p><a name="NYSE:JNJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10824"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Johnson & Johnson's</b></a> bid for Cordis is just part of a wave of acquisitions rolling through the ranks of companies that make medical devices as hospitals and HMOs increasingly demand one-stop shopping. The hottest candidates are companies that make products used to fight heart disease, such as <a name="NASD:TGET"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14840"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Target Therapeutics</b></a>, which sells brain and heart catheters. Over the past four years, Target's annual sales have grown by about 36 percent and its annual earnings by almost 46 percent. Analysts project that earnings for the fiscal year ending March 1996 will hit $1.42 a share, up from $1.02 for  fiscal 1995. <a name="NASD:VNTX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14920"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ventritex</b></a>, a maker of implantable defibrillators, may be another target. It broke into the black in  fiscal 1994 and then saw earnings stall in  fiscal 1995. Analysts are projecting a loss of $1.15 a share for the  fiscal year ending in June 1996. But they also expect a return to profitability in  fiscal 1997 thanks to a next-generation product that could capture as much as 25 percent of the market.  <p>  <p>LIFE INSURANCE  <p>Slowing population growth and increasing competition for consumers' savings are driving mergers in this mature industry. To bolster balance sheets, larger companies are buying small fry that have excess capital. In 1994 and 1995, there were 156 mergers in the industry, valued at more than $24 billion. Some mergers have boosted the stocks of insurance acquirers more than those of takeover targets (a turnabout from the norm). <a name="NYSE:RLR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14912"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ReliaStar Financial</b></a> may be an ongoing example of this. In early 1995, when it bought USLICO, ReliaStar's stock jumped to $40 from $28. ReliaStar has bene fited from USLICO's distribution system and access to the military market, and earnings are projected to hit $4.34 a share for 1995, up from $3.30 a year earlier. Penn Treaty American may be a hot takeover target because it is one of the few pure plays in long-term nursing-care insurance, which, in turn, isone of the fastest-growing segments of the industry. Thanks to its state-of-the-art policy, Penn Treaty has shown 28 percent annual growth in new premium sales for  five years.  <p>  <p>PAPER  <p>This highly cyclical industry has been in an upturn, giving companies strong earnings and abundant cash flow for increasing capacity either by building new plants or buying other companies. Acquisition is cheaper, and as a result, merger activity should remain strong in 1996. <a name="NYSE:CDP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13084"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Consolidated Papers</b></a> is a pure play in coated paper for magazines and brochures, a highly profitable area coveted by bigger players. Earnings per share are estimated at $5.19 for 1995 and $6.97 for 1996. Since <a name="NYSE:MEA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10978"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mead</b></a> sold its Lexis-Nexis business, it has become an attractive target; about 75 percent of its business is in popular coated paper and another product that's in demand coated unbleached craft board used for beverage carriers. Its 1995 earnings should hit $6.18 a share, up from $1.52 in 1994.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Biotechnology Industry, Insurance Industry, Stock Market Trends, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
