	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Scouting the Web</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Scouting the Web</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Scouting the Web</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> SCOUTING THE WEB <p>Cyberspace holds more financial and business data than you could ever use.  Here's a guide.   <p> By Ted C. Fishman  <p> Six months ago the hydra-headed cyber-thing called the WorldWide Web was best known as a playground for connoisseurs of certain Danish photographs. No more. The Web has rapidly evolved into the most prolific and democratic provider of investment and personal-finance information ever. About 2,000 Web sites offer advice, data, and financial services, and the number grows daily.   <p> Companies of every stripe but particularly high-tech firms  are everywhere, describing their enterprises and their progress,and listing contact persons to boot. The initial public offering of <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape Communications</b></a> (http://www. netscape. com), the most oversubscribed IPO in history, was built on the enthusiasm of Web surfers who discovered its products online.   <p> The Web is a part of the Internet, the global "network of networks." It is less a thing than a mode of communication employing a common technical format. No one owns it, and it's shaped by whoever invents the best tools for navigating its complexities and "authoring" documents on it. Perhaps half a million groups, companies, and individuals today create Web sites (something like text and image slide shows), which increasingly incorporate sounds and special effects as well. RealAudio's site (hhtp://www. realaudio. com),for example, lets you hear the day's business stories from ABC and National Public Radio through your computer.   <p> For investors, there are two primary benefits to this technology: virtually unlimited access to financial data, and a research medium that weaves together disparate sources of information through "hot links" words or phrases highlighted in the text of a site that transport you to other sites with the click of a mouse.   <p> Take a <a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boeing</b></a> investor. When, in December, the news hit CNN'sFinancial Network Web site (http:// www.cnnfn.com) that Boeing had resolved its strike, hot links in the story connected audio recordings of statements by union and company officials, background material from CNN and other news services, and Boeing's own Website (http:// www.boeing. com), which includes annual and quarterly reports.   <p> For those concerned with managing the money they already have, there are free government publications, magazines, news services, and information from brokerage and mutual fund companies. For example, the <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a> site (http:// www. schwab.com) lets investors read about the 300 mutual funds in its Mutual Fund One Source, and National Discount Brokers' (http://pawws.secapl. com/Ndb_phtml/top.shtml) offers online stock trading.   <p> Finally, because one never knows just what lies beyond the next hot link, the Web is terrific for generating investing ideas through sheer serendipity. The problem is that it can be bewildering to navigate, so it helps to have a reliable guide, at least until you get your sea legs. So we scouted out some sites that will save you time, and maybe money. Good hunting!  <p> ON-RAMPS FOR THE CYBER-SAVVY  <p> CNNfn, The Financial Network http://cnnfn.com  Dow Jones Business Information Services http://dowvision. wais. net  Reuters NewMediahttp://beta.yahoo.com/headlines/ current/business/summary.html <p> These are the best of the business news sites, and all are free. Reuters and CNNfn usually have more breaking news, while Dow Jones puts sections of The Wall Street Journal online. The paper is free, and stories about the companies covered in the news are linked to background information in Dow Jones's databases. CNNfn is allied with Nexis-Lexis, the leading electronic archive of newpapers and magazines, which allows users to search for previous stories on current topics. The Nexis-Lexis databaseis also available separately; it's exhaustive and expensive.  <p> American Stock Exchange http://www.amex.com  Chicago Mercantile Exchange http://www.cme.com  MarketPlex of the Chicago Board of Trade http://www. cbot.com/mplex.htm  <p> Most of the world's major financial exchanges have a presence on the Web (excluding the New York Stock Exchange). These three set the standard, providing information ranging from statistics, to basic educational materials on stocks, futures, and other derivatives, to quotes on their contracts, some of which are delayed. The Board of Trade and the Merc sites supply agricultural statistics on grains and livestock, as well as links to the government and news agencies that collect them.  <p> GNN Personal Finance Center http://gnn.com/gnn/GNNhome.html PR Newswire http://www.prnewswire. com/cnoc/prnewswire.html <p> GNN, the Internet-only off shoot of giant <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b>, has one of the best-laid-out sites, and its personal finance areas are among the liveliest on the Web. Recent articles include "The Bag Lady Syndrome," on the fear of poverty felt by many financially secure women. GNN also tracks 30 or so of the new finance-related sites that spring up every week. PR Newswire has long been the world's primary outlet for corporate public relations, posting press releases in quantity, from companies large and small. Thisis public relations, mind you, not journalism, but it's still a good place to see what's on the front burner at the companies and industries you watch.   <p> Briefing by Charter Media, Inc. http://www.briefing.com  University of Michigan Gopher Site gopher://una.hh. lib. umich.edu:70/00/ebb/indicators/ei.txt <p> Data heaven. Both sites offer summaries of virtually every economic indicator under the sun, and then some. Briefing charges for some of its stuff. The University of Michigan site, though not technically a Web site, is accessible from the Web and free. <p> Quicken Financial Network http:/ www. intuit.com/quicken  <p> <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a>'s latest release of its Quicken personal-finance software is designed specifically to take advantage of the Quicken Financial Network and comes bundled with a customized version of Netscape's Web-navigating software that will take you right to the siteand let you browse it for free. For $9.95 a month, users get seven free hours of Internet access, one of the cheapest Webon-ramp deals. The Quicken site, like the software, includes tools to help you balance your books and keep your tax records up-to-date. It also supports online banking, with links to major banks. The Network is linked to a sister service for mutual fund investors, which mantains detailed ratings, price histories, and analyses of more than 5,000 funds, plus free access to the databases of Morningstar Mutual Funds, the premier ratings service. <p> Insurance News Network http://www. insure. com  Quotesmith Corporation http://www.insure.com/Quotesmith  <p> Insurance News Network offers reliable news, ratings, consumer information, and statistics on the insurance industry. Recent postings summarized crash tests on popular cars. INN also provides Standard & Poor's Insurance Ratings and Insurer Reports, a good resource to determine if your insurer can and will pay out when you need it. Quotesmith offers free and confidential price-comparison charts for term life insurance.  <p> Securities and Exchange Commission http://www.sec.gov  <p> Find out if that cold call came from a broker with the wrong kind of record. The SEC site lists every enforcement action the agency takes. It also holds the largest online repository of corporate information, the EDGAR Database. EDGAR includes the statements companies must file with the SEC whenever they take actions that could affect their stocks.  <p> Internal Revenue Service http://www.ustreas.gov/treasury/ bureaus/irs/irs.html <p> An assortment of resources is available for the beleaguered taxpayer, including copies of every form and instructions on filing (electronically if you like) and getting help. If browsing here is too much fun, try checking the tax tables.  <p> Debt Counselors of America http://shops.net/ shops/ GET_OUT_OF_DEBT TRW Information Services http:// www.trw.com/iss/isdiv.html <p> Debt Counselors of America is a not-for-profit organization for those with credit and money-management problems. Its site offers software to help people sort out their affairs, details on credit and money scams, and advice on debt consolidation. TRW, the nation's largest credit-reporting service, gives a straight forward account of how it compiles its reports, as well as instructions for reviewing credit records and correcting them if necessary. <p> PAWWS Financial Network http://pawws.secapl.com  Quote.Comhttp://www.quote.com  MIT StockMaster http:// www.ai.mit.edu/stocks.html <p> PAWWS and QuoteCom provide current price quotes on stocks and other instruments for less than it costs to subscribe to dedicated quote vendors. Both services offer delayed quotes for free. Prices vary, depending on the services ordered, but $50 buys a package of information that exceeds most individual investor's needs, including a large variety of reports and stock ratings. PAWWS will also keep track of your portfolio free if you use its specified discount brokers. MIT's site is a store house of historical stock and mutual fund charts detailed enough to please the most hard-coretechnical trader. Its data files can be incorporated into your own charts and spread sheets.   <p> THE GNN/KOBLAS CURRENCY CONVERTER http://bin.gnn. com/  cgi-bin/gnn/currency OLSEN & ASSOCIATES http:// www. olsen. ch/foreign/websvcs.html <p> For investors who trade foreign currencies or own investments denominated in them, this site provides weekly updates on 56 different currencies and can convert any of them into any other. Olsen &Associates is a Swiss firm that advises currency traders. Its site (free for now) provides market analysis, historical data on currencies, and models for long-term trading.  <p> WWW Virtual Library: Finance and Investments http://www.cob.ohio-state.edu/dept/fin/cernh.htm Financial Data Finder http://www.cob.ohio-state.edu/dept/fin/osudata.htm  Wall Street Directory http://www.wsdinc.com  <p> Enter here for the deluge. Together, the first two "hot lists," compiled at Ohio State University's Department of Finance, bring together more than 1,000 sites related to economics and finance, all sorted by category. The still broader Wall Street Directory contains more than 2,500 entries, with an emphasis on commercial sites. Go here to shop for brokers, fund groups, financial software, and premium news and quote services.  <p> SETTING UP  <p> The first thing you need is a modem, your computer's phone connection. Go for speed, a modem no slower than 28,800 baud  per second (28.8 bps). Good ones begin at $100. Most computer stores stock several browsers, the Web-navigating software. The granddaddy of them all is Mosaic, but the overwhelming choice at the moment is Netscape. A good alternative, especially for beginners, is to join a commercial online service, such as America Online, CompuServe, or Prodigy, all of which include Web access and browsers with membership. GNN (800-819-6112), a division of America Online, offers a suite of Internet applications, including an excellent Web browser and a very stable phone link, for $14.95 a month. <p> Another option is the all-in-one Internet software suite. WorldWide Web Kit from Ventana (with Netscape) and Quarterdeck's Internet Suite (with Mosaic and additional applications, including electronic mail) are both relatively bug-free and cost about $40. For Windows 95 users, Delrina's CommSuite 95, at $180, integrates a set of Internet programs and a modem fax program. <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> bundlesits Internet Explorer browser for Windows 95 with Plus Pack for Windows 95. Explorer can also be downloaded for free off Microsoft's electronic bulletin board or off its Web site (http// www. microsoft.com). Microsoft's new online service, Microsoft Network, will also connect you to the web.  <p> Once you're online, your browser will show a box near its top for typing in Web page addresses, called Universal Resource Locators. The address line is unforgiving, so enter URLs exactly. A good place to start is Netscape's site (http://home. netscape. com).The Netscape home (or opening) page gives you several ways to search by topics and key words across the Web.   <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Taxation, Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

