	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-The New Landscape in Telecom</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The New Landscape in Telecom</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-The New Landscape in Telecom</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> THE NEW LANDSCAPE IN TELECOM <p>Deregulation will redivide the industry, creating secure investments as well as short-term growth plays  <p> By Jonathan Butler  <p> In 1984, the justice department forced American Telephone & Telegraph to relinquish its decades-old reign as Ma Bell, our regulated telephone monopoly. <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> kept its long-distance business but spun off  local service into seven regional Baby Bells. New long-distance providers sprang up, and a blizzard of novel services (from call waiting to high-speed phone lines for data) appeared. The so-called communications revolution was underway, creating a $400 billion global telecom market--which analysts say could grow to $1 trillion in the next ten years.   <p> Now the revolution is about to enter a new phase as Congress designs a Telecommunications Reform bill that will further deregulate the industry. While many of the particulars remain unsettled, the bill's main thrust is in place: to open up local phone service--a market that generates $60 billion in revenue annually and was here to fore the sole preserve of the Baby Bells--to competition. The bill will virtually erase the lines between providers of long-distance telephone, local telephone, cable-TV, and cellular-phone services.  <p> For investors, this means a new playing field. Here's a look at how the major combatants stack up:  <p> AT&T, MCI, AND SPRINT  <p> The big three long-distance firms--AT&T, <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:FON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11560"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SPRINT</b></a>--now control some 85 percent of the $65 billion long-distance business, a strength they can leverage as they try to enter into local phone markets.   <p> AT&T undoubtedly will profit from its recent decision to split into three parts. It will spin off a laggard computer business, which lost over $500 million this year, and divest its equipment-making arm, which will remove any conflict of interest AT&T has in selling products to rivals. AT&T also became the nation's largest cellular provider by acquiring McCaw Cellular and LIN Broadcasting. Its cellular revenues, which are growing at 30 percent, are expected to hit $3 billion this year. AT&T is the "classic stock that investors ought to be focusing on at this point," says Stuart Conrad of C. J. Lawrence.  <p> MCI has chosen a different route. In September, it paid $190 million for Nationwide Cellular, which buys time on cellular networks at a discount and resells it to consumers. This "lets MCI participate in wireless without making the investment in building a big network," says Bill Deatherage, an analyst at <a name="NYSE:BSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10191"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bear Stearns</b></a>. MCI used the money it saved on a network to buy a computer database integrator, SHL System house, for $1 billion.This could give MCI an edge by enabling it to design software-based communications systems tailored to client specifications.  <p> The long-distance market share of third-place Sprint has been stuck at 10 percent since 1989. Sprint  has teamed up with three cable companies, Tele-Communications Inc., Comcast, and Cox Cable, to buy $2.1 billion in licenses for personal communications services (wireless phone systems that are very similar to cellular) in 29 U.S. markets. Sprint's plan is to offer a package of local and long-distance calling, cable, and wireless to 10 million homes by 1997.   <p> Will Sprint get bought by a Baby Bell? Perhaps so. The resulting company would be a formidable rival. If this happens, "AT&T and MCI would have to focus on keeping market share in long distance and would have less money to compete for local markets," says Oscar Castro, who manages the <a name="FUND:MNGCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MNGCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Montgomery Global Telecommunications Fund</b></a>.  <p> Sprint stock is relatively cheap, trading at a price-to-earnings ratio of 14, compared with MCI at 18 and AT&T at 20. Since the last two should maintain annual earnings growth in the mid-teens for the next five to ten years, analysts say these stocks are not too expensive.  <p> <a name="NYSE:BLS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10200"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BELLSOUTH</b></a>, US WEST, AND <a name="NYSE:SBC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11379"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SBC</b></a>    <p> Deregulation will be a shock to the Baby Bells. They'll lose their exclusive rights to two major sources of revenue: the access charges long-distance companies pay for local hook-ups, and the fees customers pay for calls outside a 12-mile local area but within a Bell's region. These two sources provide about 45 percent of the Bells' revenues.  <p> Three Bells that have already diversified beyond local service are US West, BellSouth, and SBC Communications (formerly Southwestern Bell). BellSouth made early cellular investments in Australia, Latin America, and Germany (where it owns 20 percent of the national license). Its markets include over 50 million potential foreign customers. In addition, BellSouth, benefiting from the housing boom in the Southeast, is expanding its domestic network 50 percent faster than any other Bell.   <p> BellSouth shares are attractive in the low $70s, says Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette analyst Timothy Weller. He thinks the stock could rise to $82 a share in the near term. He also expects earnings to grow 10 percent annually in the next five years.   <p> Colorado-based US West is also remaking itself, with cellular ventures in Russia and Malaysia and a 50 percent stake in Mercury One-2-One, a British wireless company. At home, US West owns 25 percent of cable giant <a name="NYSE:TWX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11482"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Time Warner Entertainment</b></a> and recently began a Midwest test of a system that will allow viewers to selectany video at any time.   <p> Texas-based SBC now derives 35 percent of its profits from nontraditional sources. It owns a 10 percent stake in Telfonos de Mxico and offers directory services in Australia. It also owns two cable stations in Washington, D.C., and one in New York, as well as cable operations in Great Britain.  <p> Experience in the deregulated British telecom market has prepared US West and SBC for a deregulated U.S. market. "They've already been doing there what they will be facing in the U.S.," says Castro.  <p> <a name="NYSE:NYN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11044"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>NYNEX</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:BEL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10197"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BELL ATLANTIC</b></a>, PACTEL, AND <a name="NYSE:AIT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10094"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AMERITECH</b></a>  <p> The most vulnerable Bells may be NYNEX (New York), Bell Atlantic (Washington, D.C., and Philadelphia), PacTel (Los Angeles and San Francisco), and Ameritech (Chicago). All four rely heavily on revenues from large cities--just the markets the long-distance giants are expected to target. PacTel, in particular, will have trouble sustaining a 7.1 percent dividend yield (versus 4.6 percent for all Bells) in the face of state deregulation in 1996. Any company can then buy PacTel's calling time wholesale and resell it to PacTel customers. Ameritech has an added liability: It has stayed overly focused on its local business instead of diversifying like other Bells.  <p> <a name="NASD:WCOM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15160"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>WORLDCOM</b></a> AND <a name="NYSE:FRO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11281"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>FRONTIER</b></a>  <p> The beneficiaries of deregulation may include smaller long-distance companies such as WorldCom and Frontier, both of which have outpaced their larger rivals by exploiting the $20 billion small-business market, a segment that is growing at an annual rate of 15 percent. <p> WorldCom, based in Jackson, Mississippi, is the fourth-largest long-distance provider. Its price-to-earnings ratio is 50 percent higher than the average for AT&T, MCI, and Sprint, but its earnings are also growing roughly twice as fast as the majors'. WorldCom "derives less than 5 percent of revenues from the hotly contested residential markets," says Weller. And analysts think the Bells will be more likely to buy bulk long-distance time from WorldCom than from the Big Three, their direct competitors.    <p> Frontier, formerly Rochester Telephone, is now equal parts long-distance and local-service provider. The company is now threatened by the clout of AT&T, which invaded its home turf in January 1995. Frontier lost only 2 percentage points of market share, but pressure from AT&T could drive it into an alliance with a Baby Bell, says Michael Mahoney, manager of <a name="FUND:GTTBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GTTBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GT Global Telecommunications Fund</b></a> in San Francisco.  <p> <a name="NYSE:ATI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16964"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AIRTOUCH</b></a> AND <a name="NASD:VCELA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15058"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>VANGUARD</b></a><p> Only 10 percent of the U.S. population currently subscribes to cellular phone service--leaving plenty of room for the 40 percent annual growth that analysts project over the next decade. Smaller cellular firms can still compete effectively in this environment, or they could be acquired by cash-rich Bells.  <p> AirTouch, recently spun off from PacTel, competes in the California market, but it has the second-largest share of the German wireless business and owns a piece of Japan's exploding cellular market. In all, its licenses cover 80 million potential users globally, including 35 million in the U.S.   <p> AirTouch is an unlikely takeover target, given its $14 billion size and complex overseas alliances. But its share price should rise as investors realize its international potential, says Mahoney: "I don't think its value is understood by the market."    <p> Vanguard Cellular, by contrast, may be taken over by Bell Atlantic or NYNEX. The company, operating under the brand name CellularOne, serves some 7.5 million people in 35 metropolitan markets on the East Coast. Its markets are secure for now because they are not densely populated enough to be invaded by PCS companies.   <p> <a name="NYSE:NOK.A"></a><b>NOKIA</b>, <a name="NASD:ERICY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41776"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ERICSSON</b></a>, AND <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MOTOROLA</b></a>  <p> Manufacturers serving the big telecom companies will flourish. Developing countries are clamoring for phone and video networks, especially cellular, which is easier and cheaper to install than wired systems.  <p> The biggest cellular equipment makers are Ericsson, Nokia, and Motorola. Of the three, Nokia is "by far the most attractive when you compare valuation to growth," says GT Global's Mahoney. With 20 percent of the worldwide equipment market (versus Ericsson's 40 percent and Motorola's 20), Nokia has been growing at an average of 25 percent a year for the past five years. Yet it is selling at only 15 times his estimated 1996 earnings, says Mahoney, versus 22 for Ericsson and 18 for Motorola. Then of course there is AT&T's equipment division, which is slated to go on its own next year. With global sales of $16 billion and the top spot in the U.S.market, its future is bright. By 2002, its total revenues could surpass those of the original Ma Bell monopoly back in 1983. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
