				<font size=5><b>Fund Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Fund Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> FUND BRIEFS  <p> Do This Now  <p> Investors who made big mutual fund profits outside of IRAs, 401Ks, and other tax-deferred accounts in 1995 should call their funds now for estimates of their capital-gains distributions. This year's market rally will make distributions larger than usual. The $3.8 billion <a name="FUND:BRWIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BRWIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Brandywine Fund</b></a> expects to distribute a sizable 12 percent of its share price. Jim Hillman, a tax consultant with Coopers & Lybrand, says investors can reduce their liability on these gains by selling their losing funds. Muni shares boughtjust before the 1994 bond crash are good candidates to balance out 1995 gains. Investors can repurchase similar funds after the new year.  <p>  <p>Wellington Stable  <p> When Vincent Bajakian died in a small-plane crash on September 24, Vanguard/Wellington balanced fund, the nation's 13th largest, lost its manager of 23 years. In the two weeks following, the fund's share price dipped but assets grew slightly, to $11.7 billion. Wellington's interim manager, Ernst von Metzsch will probably become permanent, says Dan Wiener, editor of The Independent Adviser for Vanguard Investors. Von Metzsch, 55, had assisted on the fund before taking over the $532 million <a name="FUND:VGENX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VGENX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard Specialized Energy</b></a>, where he earned an average annual 12.2 percent a year over the past ten years. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Taxation, Retirement
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
