	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Building Blocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-The Building Blocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special Issue <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> THE BUILDING BLOCKS <p>Here's the outlook, sector by sector, for the industries that propel the economy  <p> By John Koten   <p> The U.S. economy will do better in the coming year than most economic prognosticators expect. According to Blue Chip Economic Indicators, a newsletter out of Sedona, Arizona, the consensus prediction among economists is that the gross domestic product will grow 2.5 percent in 1996--a forecast that, coincidentally or not, is the same as the White House's. Wall Street likewise believes that 2.5 percent is the Federal Reserve Board's target. While the experts may be paying homage to the Fed's prowess under Alan Greenspan, they may also be underestimating what he has in mind. After surveying the major U.S. industries reviewed below--and second-guessing the Fed ourselves--Worth believes that the domestic economy will achieve at least 3 percent growth in this election year. Only 3 of the Blue Chip's 52 economists are more optimistic. In this case, though, we don't mind being so near the top.  <p> HEAVY MACHINERY <p>Frank Manfredi, editor of the industry newsletter Machinery Outlook, forecasts a 7 percent decline in unit sales for construction-equipment makers in 1996. Still, Steven Colbert of Prudential Securities in San Francisco predicts that <a name="NYSE:CAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10304"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Caterpillar</b></a>'s earnings will rise to $5.65 a share in 1996 from an estimated $5.40 a share in 1995. The silver lining in the sector is agricultural and farm equipment. Crop prices in countries like China, Taiwan, and Japan have risen in 1995, benefiting farmers who are in turn buying new machines. <a name="NYSE:CSE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42141"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Case</b></a>, spun off in June 1994 from <a name="NYSE:TEN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11455"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tenneco</b></a>, is a particular favorite among analysts. Its stock price shot up 80 percent in the first ten months of 1995.   <p> DEFENSE <p>The revenue outlook for the defense sector is the same as 1995--flat, or even down moderately, according to Morgan Stanley analyst Pierre Chao. Oppenheimer & Co. analyst Lior Bregman believes that "revenues will stabilize in 1996 after years of decline."That may be good for the bottom line. "After 45 years of gluttony, defense businesses have become cost-driven and have to answer to the same market pressures as everyone else," says Chao. "They've been doing that through unparalleled consolidations." Indeed, despite large cuts in overall U.S. spending every year since1990, the sector has improved its profitability by 470 percent in five years. This includes gains by companies formerly guilty of commercial diversification that have since hewed to the straight and narrow, such as <a name="NYSE:LMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10903"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lockheed</b></a> (profits up 216 percent in five years) and <a name="NYSE:GD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10633"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Dynamics</b></a> (up 540 percent). Since General Dynamics shed its electronics group and Cessna aircraft, it has been averitable cash-generating dynamo. Improved efficiency at <a name="NYSE:MD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10975"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonnell Douglas</b></a> undoubtedly made it a more attractive potential merger candidate for <a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boeing</b></a>.  <p> Although some still see commercialization as a potential positive for the industry, Chao hotly disputes that. "I vehemently disagree with the idea that diversification is good for the companies in this industry," he says. "To quote Norm Augustine [the president of Lockheed Martin],  Defense companies have a record unblemished by success outside the industry.'"  <p> FINANCIAL SERVICES <p>As a group, banks, thrifts, insurance providers, mutual fund companies, and stock brokerages are as healthy as they've ever been, thanks to declining interest rates, a rising stock market, increased merger and acquisition activity, and a strong market for initial public offerings. In the first three quarters of1995 alone, bank-industry earnings reached an estimated $36.3 billion--a record. Jim Coons, chief economist of Huntington National Bank in Columbus, Ohio, predicts another record year in 1996. <p> Restructuring and consolidation will remain a major theme. According to the American Bankers Association, there were 329 bank consolidations in the first half of 1995--involving 18 of the 50 largest banks--compared with 550 for all of 1994. Analysts expect this  activity to spill over to the insurance and mutual fund businesses as well. Henry Dickson, an analyst at Smith Barney, suggests that investors steer toward banks that are buying back stock and have good dividend yields and sustainable earnings growth.  <p> PHARMACEUTICALS <p>Joseph Riccardo, an analyst at <a name="NYSE:BSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10191"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bear Stearns</b></a>, believes the revenues of this sector will grow at a rate of between 9 percent and 10 percent in 1996 and that the trend toward mergers and other forms of consolidation will continue. A shortening of the period required for federal approval of new products has also helped stir this industry, though pricing pressures remain. "The case for the drug industry's improving earnings growth relative to the S&P 500 has been solidified," writes <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> analyst Margo Vignola. "We estimate a 9 percent gain in 1995, a 12 percent gain in 1996, [and] a 13 percent gain in 1997."   <p> By the last week of September, most major stocks in the sector had reached 12-month highs and were trading above their historic price-to-earnings valuations. But Riccardo believes pharmaceutical stocks remain underowned and  undervalued, making them a reasonably safe place for  defensive investors in 1996.   <p> RETAILING <p>"Right now, retail doesn't look good, particularly in apparel," says Karen Sack, an analyst at Standard & Poor's. "Nineteen ninety-six doesn't look too promising either." The problem is pretty straight forward: too many stores chasing too few customers. Expect retail Darwinism to be the theme of 1996 and beyond. "We expect mass consolidation," says Richard Baum, vice president of investment research at Goldman,Sachs. "Investors should be playing the powerful companies that will absorb the weaker ones." Baum advises avoiding companies with high levels of debt.   <p> One surprising bright spot is <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears, Roebuck</b></a>, which has been posting increases in same-store sales of late. Steven Schuster at First Manhattan notes that Sears's stock is selling at only12 times next year's projected earnings. "You'll make money if you buy Sears," he says. "It's guaranteed." William Julian at Lehman Brothers says, "People are spending less, and when they do spend, it's on items for the home or products that have a specific use." His favorite pick: <a name="NASD:BBBY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14933"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bed Bath & Beyond</b></a>, which sells better housewares and home furnishings at a discount.   <p> AGRICULTURE <p>Responding to higher prices and crop shortfalls in 1995, both domestically and abroad, farmers will increase their planting in 1996--good news for companies that supply farmers with seed, chemicals, and equipment.  <p> "Farmers are in a buying mood," says Richard Elam, an investment analyst at Everen Securities, who predicts that 81 million acres of corn will be planted in 1996, up from 71.3 million in 1995." A big corn year is coming," he says, "and corn benefits fertilizer companies even more than soy." Bigger yields will benefit suffering agricultural processors such as <a name="NYSE:CAG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10388"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ConAgra</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:ADM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10124"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Archer Daniels Midland</b></a>, too, though Elam believes they're not likely to see relief from high commodity prices until mid summer.  <p> BIOTECH <p>The biotech sector, which rises and falls with the success of new product launches, has been boosted by streamlined  approval procedures at the U.S. Food and Drug Administration and by reduced concerns over the enforceability of biotech patents. The revenue outlook is positive as the sector continues a climb out of the doldrums that began in 1994, when a dozen different product launches failed outright or failed to meet lofty expectations.   <p> J. Kevin Buchi, vice president of finance at Cephalon, a West Chester, Pennsylvania-based maker of therapeutic products for the treatment of neurodegenerative disease, thinks the biggest challenge facing the sector is financing the seven-to-nine-year period required to launch a new product. He predicts that mature companies with broad lines will have few problems obtaining adequate backing but that newer companies may face a shortage of funds. He doubts health care reform will have much of an impact on the sector--still a tiny fraction of the overall health care industry. <p> R. Brandon Fradd, an analyst at Montgomery Securities, recommends that potential biotech investors "wait until the last two weeks of December, to avoid profit taking and benefit from the January effect." Biotech stocks remain prone to big price swings: According to the biotech analyst report from Montgomery, the volatility of the average biotech stock is eight times greater than that of the S&P 100.  <p> HEALTH SERVICES <p>Health care spending is now growing 10 percent annually--a rate that may very well decline if congressional Republicans succeed in reforming Medicare and Medicaid. Clifford Hewitt, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein & Co., says a growth rate of 7 percent to 8 percent would be "enough to sustain most of the companies in the sector." But he adds that many weaker companies would be in trouble if the 6 percent rate the Republicans seek is reached. "There's no end in sight to pressures on cost containment," says Cliff Hotte, chief executive of Health Management Inc., a Long Island sub-acute care provider. "I think we're moving inexorably along a continuum of care, from acute to sub-acute to the community setting."  <p> HMOs, however, should continue to do well regardless of what happens in Congress. "We're witnessing a total conversion from fee-for-service to one in which providers are rewarded for holding down costs," says Hewitt. His favorite HMOs are <a name="NASD:OXHP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15344"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oxford Health Plans</b></a> and <a name="NASD:PHSYA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14364"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PacifiCare Health Systems</b></a>. Kurt von Emster, the manager of the <a name="FUND:FKGHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FKGHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Franklin Global Health Care fund</b></a>, believes the best-run HMOs will build on 1995's 30 percent revenue growth and that earnings could rise at an even higher rate in 1996.  <p> Hospital stocks have remained in a kind of suspended animation, as investors await the outcome of health care reform. Says Hewitt: "People over react to news of legislation because the effects are so difficult to quantify."  <p> HOME BUILDING <p>Home-building stocks kept pace with the broad market in 1995--meaning a better than average year for the industry. This is a cyclical business that typically does well during the early part of an economic expansion, not late in the cycle. Still, says Sam Stovall, editor of Standard & Poor's Industry Reports, home-building stocks could be a good buy for the next few months because they are still trading below their historic price-to-earnings ratio average of 19.5.  <p> Low mortgage rates have helped to boost home sales and pare down high inventories. Stanley Duobinis, economist with the National Association of Home Builders, says this has paved the way for a 3.7 percent growth in the new housing market for 1996. The nation's largest single-family-home builder is Dallas-based <a name="NYSE:CTX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10308"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Centex Corp.</b></a>, with $3.27 billion in fiscal 1995 revenues. In the third quarter, its orders were up 21 percent from the year-earlier period. Pulte, the country's second largest home builder, saw its third-quarter orders shoot up 48 percent.   <p> TELECOMMUNICATIONS  <p>Watch for a scramble in the major telecommunications segments--local, long-distance, wireless, and cable--following the passage of the federal telecom legislation. The bill will allow the local companies to compete in long distance and long-distance companies in local.  <p>The long-distance giants have the advantage of existing nationwide networks and powerful name brands. The big question for them, though, is whether they can make any money in the local markets. They can buy bulk local access from the Baby Bells and resell it to customers, but the margins in the few places where this has already happened are very slim. The long-distance guys can also bypass the Baby Bells in the big cities, where competitive access providers like <a name="NASD:MFST"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16208"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MFS Communications</b></a> and <a name="AMEX:ICG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15924"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intelcom Group</b></a> have set up networks in high-density business areas. Or the long-distance players can build their own networks, which is hugely expensive. Meanwhile, a Baby Bell that wants to get into the long-distance market can expect the four major long-distance carriers to bid for its business. Perhaps the Baby Bells' biggest obstacle is that they aren't used to operating in a competitive environment. Still, it's not a zero-sum game: With the pie getting bigger, there doesn't necessarily have to be a lot of losers.   <p> A third telecommunications group is wireless, which includes cellular and personal-communications providers. These companies' revenues are increasing at more than 35 percent a year. With only 10 percent of the U.S. population currently subscribing, there's plenty of room to keep growing. Cable companies also are attempting to secure a chunk of the market. These outfits have the advantage of already having routes into the home, but their wires are one-way, so they'll have to spend a lot of time and money upgrading.   <p> FOOD <p>The fierce competitiveness of a mature industry with little room for domestic growth has made it difficult for food companies to offset the high costs of raw materials (including paper forpackaging) by raising prices. As a result of these and other factors, many companies have restructured in the past 18 months. This positions the industry well for 1996, according to John M. O'Neil, an analyst at Oppenheimer. Lower commodity costs would, of course, amplify this benefit.  <p> Some industry analysts expect food stocks to benefit from sector rotation if the economy remains sluggish or slows in 1996. Says O'Neil: "They're stable-demand stocks: the economy may weaken, but the purchasing of food continues." O'Neil's favorite stock is <a name="NYSE:CPC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10268"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CPC International</b></a>, whose brands include Skippy, Mazola, and Knorr, and which derives 60 percent of its earnings from outside the U.S. "In Europe, Knorr is a bigger brand than Kellogg's or Kraft," says O'Neil.  <p> OIL <p>The leading petroleum companies today can be as profitable with oil at $17 a barrell as they were a few years ago when the price was $20 a barrell. <a name="NYSE:MOB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11006"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mobile</b></a>, for instance, has reduced annual expenses by approximately $2.5 billion in the past year. Oil industry shareholders should benefit from this trend even though analysts forsee significant increases in the price of crude anytime soon. Value Line does expect a tiny hop in industry profitability, forecasting that total industry net income will reach $28 billion in 1996, up from an estimated $27.5 billion in 1995. As much as some OPEC countries would like to raise prices, the organization can't do it without losing business to non-OPEC producers like the U.K., Norway, and Columbia.  <p> STEEL <p>Demand for steel began to improve late in 1995, helping to trim inventory levels that rose to excessive levels due to early in the year. (Predictions of steel shortages ended up causing a glut.) The prospects for 1996 look better--with domestic industry production expected to rise to 112 million tons from 109 million in 1995, according to Peter Marcus, at Paine Webber. Over the longer term, however, planned capacity expansions may outstrip demand, hurting prices and industry profits.  <p> AUTOS <p>The Big Three automakers may sell more cars in 1996 than most analysts and economists expect--bolstered by an economy that also may be somewhat better than expected. Value Line projects total industry sales of $360 billion in the coming year, up 4.7 percent from an estimated $344 billion in 1995.  <p> Few analysts expect Japanese auto makers to increase their market pentration in the U.S. this year, though the German car companies may very well gain further ground in a market that continues to favor higher-priced vehicles. With the outlook for Europe anything but rosy, neither <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GM</b></a> nor <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> are expected to get a major boost from overseas sales.  <p> General Motors has the most potential for improved unit profitability, because it still has more room to cut costs than either Ford or <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a>. But the Number Two and Three auto makers are leveraged to earn hefty returns on even a modest increase in sales. David Bradley, an auto analyst at J.P. Morgan Securities, forecasts that GM's earnings will rise to $7.90 a share from an estimated $6.92 a share in 1995; Ford's will jump to $3.70 a share from $3.10, and Chrysler's to $8.00 a share from $4.85.   <p> MEDIA  <p>Cable companies, previously stalled by rate inquiries, will be able to offer new and different programming services in 1996, up the prices they charge, and improve cash flow into their core business. This trend was already underway in the latter half of 1995. The telecommunications bill probably will allow broadcasters to own more stations and expand their reach. Of course, buying stations is costly, and competition for these outlets could intensify. Two big plusses loom: the elections and the Olympics. By consuming lots of advertising space, both events will push up the prices for what's left. "This is quite good for broadcasting," says Tim Wallace, an analyst at S.G.Warburg.  <p> Print publishers face higher paper prices and advertisers who are unreceptive to off setting the cost difference. Newspapers and magazines will "try to increase ad rates, but I'm skeptical,"says Brian C. Oakes, a J.P. Morgan analyst.  Ad growth may only reach five percent.   <p> Several analysts recommend such stocks as <a name="NYSE:DJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dow Jones</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:GCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10623"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gannett</b></a> because they have expanded beyond newspaper publishing. <p>"Broad-based publishers are better off than newspapers because probably more of them are viewing electronic stuff as an opportunity. Plus, each has something particular to offer. For example, Thomas Nelson has the inspirational market, Scholastic has the children's, KIII has strong business-to-business publishing.  Finally, the demand for their product is better than the advertising climate."   <p> COMPUTER SOFTWARE <p>For computer-software companies, 1996 will be the year they can no longer avoid the Internet. Jamie Kiggen, a technology analyst at Prudential Securities, suggests that investors should scrutinize their software investments to be prepared. "A company without an Internet strategy is a cause for concern," Kiggen says. "The Internet will change the way companies sell products and interact with consumers," he says. For those who doubt the growing importance of tailoring products for the net, look no further than <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape Communications</b></a>, which sells software for cruising the Internet's World Wide Web. Netscape had the hottest initial public offering of 1995, going public at $28 and climbing to $75 on the first day. The stock later reached $105.50 before settling into a range of $95 to $102. Another company to monitor is database-software concern <a name="NASD:ORCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14337"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oracle</b></a>. Analysts note that Oracle recently moved into providing software for Internet server computers.   <p> Internet or no Internet, though, analysts expect <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> to continue its dominance of the software industry in 1996. This will be the year that sales for Windows 95 operating software kicks into high gear, driving both the software and hardware markets. The company sold 3 million retail copied of Windows 95 in its first two months on the market, but Rick Sherlund, software analyst at Goldman, Sachs, points out that there's more to the company than just Windows 95. "Microsoft's growth will be sustained by its diversity of products," Sherlund says. He's excited about Microsoft's Blackbird, a set of tools for programming on -- you guessed it -- the Internet, and its Gibralter Internet server application.   <p> Analysts are also looking for merger and acquisition action in the software industry for 1996 on the heels of <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>'s $3.5 billion purchase of Lotus Development and Computer Associates' $1.5 billion take over of software maker Legent. "While the leaders in the software industry are cash-rich, I expect them to continue to purchase smaller companies that make strategic and financial sense," says Kiggen.  <p> COMPUTER HARDWARE <p>There's no escaping the Internet on the hardware side of the computer industry, either. Analysts expect that the continuing clamor to get wired will fuel demand for personal computers and related hardware.   <p> Another driving factor will be Microsoft's sales of Windows 95, says William Gurley, an analyst who tracks computer companies at CS First Boston. "Hardware may lag slightly behind software sales, but there is a direct connection between these two markets," he says. Windows 95 doesn't work as well on older personal computers, so companies and individual users who want to take full advantage of the software can be expected to purchase new PCs. That benefits all of the top personal-computer companies -- except for <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple</b></a>, whose Macintosh computers use their own operating system instead of Windows. Among PC companies, Gurley likes mail-order giants like <a name="NASD:GATE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16706"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gateway 2000</b></a> and <a name="NASD:DELL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13193"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dell Computer</b></a>. He thinks they'll benefit from customers purchasing their second PC; those customers are more likely to feel comfortable ordering their computer over the phone.   <p> One factor that could actually hamper the business of top PC makers is the decision by <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a> to begin manufacturing computer motherboards. Intel, already atop the semiconductor industry because of demand for its Pentium microprocessors, will begin taking its chips and installing them on circuit boards for resale to computer manufacturers. The ability to buy motherboards from Intel could well allow smaller PC companies to save on research and development costs and compete more effectively with the big players. For 1996, analysts expect Intel to earn around $5.10 a share, according to the consensus estimate from First Call.  <p> Though computing trends continue to favor computer workstations and personal computers over mainframes, Ed Monterio, a portfolio manager at CIC Asset Management, thinks International Business Machines will enjoy another good year in 1996. IBM staged a sharp recovery in 1995, climbing to $114 after a low of $74 in January. But Monterio thinks there's further room in the stock, and he looks for IBM to reach $140 to $160 in 1996. "It's very cheap compared to earnings, and it has good dividend potential," he says.   <p> AIRLINES <p>It's conceivable that airline investors one day will feel they are treated as well financially by the industry as discount travelers. But it remains to be seen whether 1996 will be that year. The industry does appear closer to achieving its long-sought oligopolistic structure. Airlines have been raising fares, eliminating shorter (and less profitable) routes, negotiating tougher wage deals with employees, and playing hardball with travel agents. <a name="NYSE:CAI.A"></a><b>Continental Airlines</b> completely scrapped in CALite service, and <a name="NYSE:UAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11520"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UAL</b></a>'s United Airlines revamped its Shuttle offerings. <a name="NYSE:DAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10448"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Delta Air Lines</b></a> mandated a new commission structure with travel agents that should save the industry approximately $400 million in1996.   <p> Airlines have also been trying to stop adding new planes faster than they are adding new customers. Analysts expected that the industry would fill 64 percent of its available seats in 1995, up from 62.2 percent in 1994 -- a trend that could continue in1996. One threat to profits is a fuel-tax hike currently being considered in Congress. The higher levy (which would take the form of the industry losing a special exemption it has had for years) could cost the industry about half a billion dollars annually. <p> The Street's consensus on airline stocks is that the industry should perform better in 1996 than it did in 1995. Of the major carriers, <a name="NYSE:LUV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11377"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Southwest Airlines</b></a> remains a favorite because of its strong balance sheet. It is also the only major carrier that hasn't lost money in the past five years.   <p> CHEMICALS <p>Midway through 1995, prices for commodity chemicals began to weaken. It's not a sure thing that these prices -- which reflect the industry's health -- will rebound in 1996, but some analysts believe they will.   <p> Sales, meanwhile, are rising. <a name="NYSE:DOW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10471"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dow Chemical</b></a>, for instance, reported a 16 percent increase in 1995 third-quarter sales. Monsanto has been benefiting from management changes and higher prices for its agricultural and industrial products. <a name="NYSE:DD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10487"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Du Pont</b></a> is expected to overcome litigation for its breast-implant products and report record gains next year, according to analysts.   <p> Paul Raman, an industry expert at S.G. Warburg, predicts the major chemical companies will all do well in 1996 because they will get higher prices for their products. He's forecasting a 20 percent improvement in fourth-quarter 1995 earnings and a similar jump in 1996. He's especially optimistic about stronger sales in China.   <p> Paul Leming of C.J. Lawrence, however, is far less sanguine. He expects prices to soften further because of excess inventory and sees a "huge downward momentum" in earnings over the next four quarters.   <p> CONSUMER ELECTRONICS <p>Several analysts believe sales of the two leading electronics retailers, <a name="NYSE:CC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10343"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Circuit City</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:TAN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11441"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tandy</b></a>, could increase by as much as 20 percent in 1996, though declining prices and increasing competition could restrict improvement in their bottom line results. What's hot? Computers and big-screen televisions.   <p> Otis Bradley, an analyst at Gilford Securities, believes Tandy's stock price could gain as much as 50 percent in 1996, thanks to the ongoing profitability of its 6,800 Radio Shack stores and the apparent recent success of its Incredible Universe and The Edge stores. Scot Ciccarelli of Gerard Klauer Mattison in New York estimates that Tandy will have $320 million in net cash by the end of 1996 to spend growth projects and to reduce debt. <p> Circuit City plans to add 70 new stores next year to its 300 current locations. Analysts expect the company's stock to earn about $2.25 a share in 1996, up from an estimated $1.75 a share in 1995.   <p> Reported by Jonathan Butler, Monica Corcoran, Maxwell G. Dale, Manjeet Kripalani, Ken Kurson, Deborah Pont, and Dean Robinson. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends, Stock Inveting Strategies

