		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>All That Glitters in Gold Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-All That Glitters in Gold Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>ALL THAT GLITTERS IN GOLD STOCKS
Mining shares offer both growth and value.<p>By Kenneth Gerbino<p>Stock market investors are often confronted with this quandary: Should they buy the shares of a company with strong growth prospects? Or should they opt for a stock that represents a good, intrinsic value for the price? Rarely do these scenarios exist simultaneously. At the moment, the shares of gold-mining companies may fit that picture.<p>Traditionally, investors have used gold as a hedge against economic uncertainty or as a way to protect capital against the scourge of inflation. But the stocks of gold-mining companies offer other attractions as well. For one, their economic prospects aren't entirely dependent on the price of gold. Most of these companies are adept at hedging the price of future production just as wheat and soybean farmers do -- so a small decline in gold prices doesn't necessarily spell poor profits for gold miners.<p>Most mining companies also typically sport decent margins because it costs far less to mine an ounce of gold than it does to buy the stuff on the world market. On average, the top 20 producers in North America spend roughly $220 in cash costs for each $395 ounce of gold mined. Thus, the spot market -- where commodities are sold for cash and delivered immediately -- would have to decline precipitously for these companies to get hammered.<p>These high margins also mean that gold companies offer attractive leverage. Suppose the world market price is $395 an ounce but a mining company can dig gold out of the ground at a total cost (cash costs plus production expenses and depreciation) of $295 per ounce. Now assume gold prices increase at a conservative 6 percent annually, to $419 an ounce, with half the rise due to a 3 percent increase in inflation and the other 3 percent from a boost in Asian demand. Because the industry has been getting more efficient, mining costs aren't likely to rise. So that $24 increase gets added right to a company's bottom line. The $100 profit becomes $124, a 24 percent net increase on just a 6 percent jump in the price of gold.<p>Surging demand for gold also has allowed companies to boost their revenues and profits by starting up more new mines. According to Gold Fields Minerals Services, an industry publication, today the total world appetite for gold stands at 3,257 metric tons per year, which surpasses the current mine output of 2,281 total tons. Moreover, gold held in reserves by central banks rarely gets dumped on the market, so there doesn't appear to be much danger of a gold glut. <p>Mining companies also are growing by upgrading their existing mines. This not only boosts capacity but also tends to lower production costs. A case in point is <a name="NYSE:FCX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10606"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Freeport-McMoRan Copper & Gold</b></a>, based in New Orleans. It has steadily upgraded its Ertsberg/Grasberg mine in Indonesia since 1990. Since then, the company has lowered its costs and raised annual production from 284,000 ounces to 800,000 ounces. Meanwhile, its stock rose from a split-adjusted $5 per share to a recent $23.25. <p>On the value side of the ledger, gold-mining shares can be hidden asset plays because vast amounts of precious metal reserves are usually not officially stated in a mining company's annual reports. Highly valuable properties that have been drilled and tested can't be officially considered viable until they pass standard metallurgical and engineering tests. That often results in off-balance-sheet surprises. The recent bidding war over Toronto-based Lac Minerals is an example of this. Last July, 11 days after <a name="AMEX:RYO"></a><b>Royal Oak Inc.</b> made a $1.3 billion offer for the company, Lac's board announced it had an additional 5 million ounces in reserves worth $2 billion. Upon hearing that news, American Barrick in Toronto bid $1.7 billion, an offer the company finally accepted on September 7.<p>Another reason to be bullish on gold: As world populations increase and whole countries move from agricultural to industrialized societies, the demand for gold should continue to rise. In the last three years, the demand for gold jewelry has outstripped Western Hemisphere mine output by 655 metric tons per year. That amounts to 23 million ounces annually, or almost 10 percent of the U.S. Treasury's gold reserves, the world's largest. Asian demand could also easily kick in more than a 3 percent annual increase over the next three years. Asian gold demand steadily rose from 200 metric tons per year in 1983 to 1,000 tons in 1993, a 400 percent increase. The main reason is China. The Chinese, like most other Asians, are firm believers in the value of gold. Throughout the 1920s and '30s, Shanghai was the third-largest gold market in the world, after London and New York. After a debilitating bout of inflation during the late 1940s, China learned a tough lesson on the merits of owning gold. <p>So, if you're looking for growth and value, check the list of six gold mining companies below. These investments now shine bright.<p><p>BEST BETS IN GOLD STOCKS
---------------<p><a name="NASD:MAENF"></a><b>MIRAMAR</b>. Recent share price: $6.25. 52-week high: $7.87. 52-week low: $4.87. Outlook: Con Mine in Canada has large untapped reserves. Recent $146 million renovation of this mine should lower costs.<p>FREEPORT COPPER. Recent share price: $23.25. 52-week high: $27.50. 52-week low: $20.63. Outlook: World's largest single-mine gold reserves; low-cost copper producer. Strong exploration possibilities.<p><a name="NYSE:PDG"></a><b>COEUR D'ALENE</b>. Recent share price: $21.00 52-week high: $25.50. 52-week low: $16.50. Outlook: Two major quality projects in the pipeline, and silver production adds more potential leverage.<p>AMERICAN BARRICK. Recent share price: $24.63. 52-week high: $31.00. 52-week low: $21.38. Outlook: Huge untapped reserves in Carlin Trend, Nevada; Lac merger will create strong leader in the field.<p><a name="NYSE:PDG"></a><b>PLACER DOME</b>. Recent share price: $23.63. 52-week high: $28.25. 52-week low: $19.13. Outlook: Company is flush with roughly $700 million in cash. Dozens of global mining projects in the works.<p><a name="NASD:TKOCF"></a><b>TASEKO MINES</b>. Recent share price: $12.13. 52-week high: $15.87. 52-week low: $9.50. Outlook: Fish Lake Deposit in Canada for sale, world's fifth-largest gold/copper deposit. Buyout projected at $26-$30 a share.<p>Data as of 9/12/94. Miramar trades on the Toronto exchange, and share price shown is in Canadian dollars; Taseko Mines trades over the counter; others trade on New York Stock Exchange.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
