<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Why It's Dangerous to Dis Dollar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Why It's Dangerous to Dis Dollar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Bill Clinton might not believe it, but our economy is likely to follow our currency into the tank. Ditto his presidency.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>President Clinton, the chief engineer of our economy, is steaming ahead, full throttle, with a cheap-dollar policy. So what if the greenback is in a virtual free fall against the Japanese yen and the German mark? Clinton has made it clear to investors both here and abroad that the U.S. needn't fret about a weak currency.<p>Nobody knows where the dollar's fall will end. It won't go straight down; there will be periodic blips upward. But temporary action matters little, for the damage has been done. As Clinton seems willing to let the dollar fall further, even more damage can be expected. What kinds of damage? Higher inflation and interest rates, reduced purchasing power, and declining markets. American investors are about to find out how ugly things get when policy makers trash their currency. <p>Clinton's decimation of the dollar -- though egregious -- is only the latest in a series of devaluations, intended or otherwise, that have brought our currency to its knees. In less than ten years, the dollar has gone from 3.46 deutsche marks to 1.55; from 263 yen to 98. In just the past 12 months, the buck has fallen 4 percent against the J.P. Morgan index of 19 currencies. Since 1950, the dollar's purchasing power, measured by consumer prices, has fallen 83 percent. <p>These declines have very serious consequences for our economy's future as well as for our own personal wealth creation. Don't be fooled into believing that a falling dollar is good for our economy. The benefits -- greater sales of our goods overseas, which creates higher employment at home -- are short-term in nature. The effects of a weak dollar are exceedingly deleterious and last a long time.<p>As far as the dollar is concerned, Americans have lived a blissfully ignorant life until now. Unless you were planning a trip abroad, you weren't likely to think about the value of the dollar versus other currencies. Because our country and its economy are so vast, we haven't been forced to learn how a strong or weak dollar will affect our lives tomorrow or next year. We could maintain an isolationist's attitude. <p>Few countries can afford this complacency. More common is the attitude taken by Europeans and Latin Americans. There, economies are more dependent on neighboring countries and their currencies. As a result, every consumer is an expert in foreign exchange. The French know the exchange rate of the Germans, and vice versa. Such knowledge can pay off. If the franc is stronger than the mark, that makes it cheaper to cross the border and buy German goods with francs.<p>Isolationism on currencies is no longer an option for American investors, however. This is because we depend on foreigners to fund our government's deficits, a fine scenario for everyone when the dollar was strong and interest rates relatively high. But now that the buck is plunging against world currencies, foreign investors are decidedly less interested in buying dollar-denominated investments because of the losses they must take in currency translations. <p>This is especially important for investors to understand now, because in coming weeks, stock and bond markets may have vehement reactions to the dollar's decline. Bonds dropped 0.5 percent in early July when the dollar crisis began but bounced back. Stocks seem to have shrugged off currency concerns altogether. The S&P 500 is up 1.75 percent since the dollar started to crater; the Dow Jones Industrial Average is up 2.8 percent.<p>The last time the dollar dropped and the stock market inexplicably stayed high was in the spring of 1987, a few months before the market crash. On October 18, the stock market and the dollar suddenly got back in sync. Investors, though, were dazed.<p>Now foreigners holding U.S. securities are dazed. If a Japanese investor, say, bought some Treasurys in mid-January before the Federal Reserve started raising interest rates, he'd now be facing a loss of 24.3 percent; principal losses would have been 15 percent and currency losses 9.3 percent. And folks wonder why foreign investors are fleeing?<p>This flight is an enormous problem for President Clinton and for all of us. From 1985 through 1990, foreign investors bought almost $200 billion worth of Treasury bonds and notes. Now that the administration is letting the dollar slide, our government debt looks uglier and uglier to both foreign and domestic investors.<p>So who's going to buy our huge issuance of bonds? Because investors are scarce, rates will have to go higher for our securities to appeal to anyone. And unless Clinton gets religion on cutting government spending, changes the tax rules to encourage Americans to save money, and defends the dollar by behaving like a leader rather than a pleaser, interest rates may go very high indeed.<p>So far, Clinton has been lucky with interest rates, markets, and the economy. His bumbling on the dollar will end that.<p>It's instructive to consider the public approval ratings of Jimmy Carter and Bill Clinton on their handling of the economy. Both began their terms with similar ratings -- around 60 percent -- which dropped fairly quickly. In their respective second years in office, Carter's ratings began an irreversible plunge while Clinton's have stayed in a more respectable range. Not great, though: The most recent figures available show that Clinton's handling of the economy received a 44 percent approval and 45 percent disapproval rating. <p>From here on, Clinton's ratings are probably going to look a lot more like Carter's. Americans soured on Carter when the oil shock hit and interest rates rose. Clinton's numbers will almost certainly worsen as interest rates increase, foreign investors flee our markets, and the economy slows.<p>To see what distressed currencies can do to a country's economic health, look at the recent foreign-exchange crises in Latin America. The latest panic began in the early 1980s, when capital inflows dried up following the revelation that Mexican debt held by foreign investors could not be paid off. Ensuing currency devaluations in Chile, Argentina, and Uruguay -- between 100 percent and 200 percent in three months -- increased annual inflation rates from 10 percent to 20 percent to as much as 60 percent overnight. Hyperinflation continued through the 1980s in Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, and Peru, according to Claudio Sapelli, a Chilean economist at the World Bank, largely because of big government deficits and lax monetary policy.<p>Only recently did the situation in Latin America settle down. Now, for example, Argentina's inflation rates are as low as the United States', thanks to big cuts in government spending and successful privatization of ossified state-owned enterprises, the opposite of what is happening in this country. The U.S. is facing the kinds of challenges Latin America has faced. As long as its fiscal-policy stance is weaker than the stances of its trading partners, the dollar will devalue.<p>But perhaps the trickiest reason why the dollar will continue to be dangerously weak is the paucity of leadership coming out of the White House on the economy and on world affairs. The credibility of the financial markets is tough to earn; once lost, it is virtually impossible to win back. Despite his driving need to please, Clinton has lost the respect of investors everywhere. At home and abroad he is perceived as dithering, weak, and an entitlement giver.<p>David Fand is a former economic advisor to the comptroller of the currency and a research associate at George Mason University. He conducted a study, going back to 1967, that shows a strong correlation between the trade-weighted value of the dollar and defense spending as a percent of gross domestic product. When defense spending falls or rises, the dollar follows suit.<p>From 1968 to 1973, for instance, military spending declined from 9.7 percent of GDP to 6 percent. The dollar dropped 19 percent during the period. When defense spending picked up, from 1981 to 1986, the dollar rose 8.5 percent. This doesn't mean that we should start a war somewhere, but simply that defending the nation is a good way to defend the dollar.<p>There are other ways. Clinton must slash entitlement spending and alter income-tax structures to encourage Americans to save. Our savings rate is abysmally low; as a percentage of disposable income, it has declined from 8 percent in 1980 to 4.7 percent. The household savings rate in Japan is about 20 percent.<p>Americans are also borrowing more. In 1980, consumers' indebtedness was 23.5 percent of total household assets. Now it's 26.5 percent. Uncle Sam can't expect us to fund his debt if we're already heavily leveraged.<p>One reason Americans don't save is triple taxation. An investor's gross income is taxed, interest on savings is taxed, and when he dies, his estate is taxed. Says Fand: "The message is, you're an idiot if you save."<p>Of course, every cloud has a silver lining. Clinton's current indifference to the dollar places the country in grave danger. It puts his presidency in the same spot. 
---------------
Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Economy, International Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
