<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Highflier Caught in Cash Crunch</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Highflier Caught in Cash Crunch</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Cott Corp. is positioned to capitalize on a consumer trend: The perfect story stock, in Wall Street parlance. As usual, there's a story behind the story.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p><a name="NASD:COTTF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42846"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cott Corp.</b></a>, a Toronto-based maker of private-label soft drinks and beer, is the quintessential '90s highflier. Its stock, which trades on Nasdaq (COTTF), has rocketed from a split-adjusted low of around 30 cents a share in 1991 to a recent $23.75 (both U.S.). Last fall, it traded here as high as $38. The shares also trade on the Toronto Stock Exchange.<p>One reason Cott is such a winner: In Wall Street parlance, it's the perfect "story" stock. Here's the short version: As a low-cost producer of beverages and foods, Cott is well positioned to capitalize on the consumer trend toward high-quality, private-label goods. Supermarket and drug chains like its products because they carry fatter margins than major brands like <a name="NYSE:PEP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11166"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pepsi</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coke</b></a>. Consumers go for Cott because they pay lower prices, too. <p>Does this story have a happy ending? Investors apparently think so: They've bid up Cott shares to 54 times last year's reported earnings of 60 cents per share. (All numbers are Canadian unless noted.) As a comparison, Coca-Cola's price-to-earnings ratio is 23. Cott's present market capitalization is $2 billion, equal to 3.1 times the company's $665 million in sales. Most bottling companies trade at a fraction of sales.<p>Cott shares are favored by growth- stock-fund managers and touted at brokerages <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a> and Oppenheimer. In the U.S., Cott supplies goods to <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a> as Sam's American Choice. Canadian clients include Loblaw and Oshawa Foods.<p>Cott's operations are run by Gerald Pencer, 49, son of the late Harry Pencer, who founded the company in 1952. Says Pencer of his business: "Retailers are ringing our phones off the hook. Not only is our product helping retailers differentiate themselves, but it enables them to make more money." <p>Such is the story behind the stock. Now, the story behind the story.<p>This one isn't pretty. Upon closer inspection, disturbing facts about Cott's business, finances, executives, and stock come into focus. Cott's quarter-to-quarter sales are declining, but its earnings and assets would be far lower if the company did not use the aggressive accounting practices that it does. Top managers have been dumping shares, snagging sweetheart deals and big bonuses. <p>Cott's go-go accounting looks curiously familiar to people who knew Pencer before he got into the soft-drink business. Sad indeed is the history of Financial Trustco Capital, a financial-services conglomerate Pencer ran in the 1980s. In 1988, after years of impressive earnings and asset growth, Pencer gave up his management duties. His was a graceful and, as it happened, timely exit; just a few months later, Financial Trustco imploded. Shareholders' equity, which was $144 million, was written down to a negative $76 million. The stock plunged to around 2 cents a share after trading as high as $19 in the mid-1980s. <p>What went wrong? The 1987 stock market crash, according to Pencer. Others take the slightly different view that Financial Trustco's aggressive accounting practices finally caught up with it. "The company was overstating income and assets, and their auditor was accepting it," says Chris Robinson, an associate professor of finance at Toronto's York University who examined Financial Trustco's books and ultimately wrote a case study of the debacle. The particulars included overstatement of the market value of securities held by the company and failure to record a massive loss on the effective disposal of a subsidiary.<p>Six years later, though, Pencer is back and bigger than ever. He's running a different company, but his financial style doesn't appear to have changed. The accounting firm he's using to audit Cott's books is the one Financial Trustco employed: Coopers & Lybrand. There's a key difference between then and now: U.S. investors are big owners of Cott. They weren't of Financial Trustco.<p>These shareholders seem willing to overlook a lot about Cott. Fans call it a growth stock, but sales actually fell 12 percent and 6 percent in each of the past two quarters, ending October and January. Of the drop, Pencer says, "This is a seasonal business. "He insists that the numbers for the first quarter, which finishes in late April, will come roaring back. They had better; Wall Street isn't forgiving of "growth" stocks that show declining sales. <p>The rate at which insiders are selling the stock is also a concern. Last year, Pencer sold more than 1.5 million shares of Cott stock -- roughly one quarter of his holding -- at prices between $11 and $35 (U.S.). Ten other executives or directors dumped another 1.4 million shares in 1993. Note this: Cott president Heather Reisman unloaded 69,000 shares less than a month before Cott issued 3 million shares to the public at $31 (U.S.) per in a secondary offering. Had investors known that Reisman was selling, they might have been more hesitant to snap up Cott shares in August. But news of Reisman's sales didn't reach the Ontario Securities Commission until November, well after the offering. <p>Heavy insider selling, however, is nothing compared to the ingenious methods Cott uses to account for itself. Unfortunately, many U.S. shareholders may not know that Canada's generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) are more liberal than U.S. practices. For example, the standards are sufficiently flexible to allow Cott to count as assets what in the U.S. would be considered expenses. This reduces the costs Cott runs through its income statement and bolsters the assets on its balance sheet. Net result: Magically higher earnings. <p>During the year ended January 29, for instance, the company's balance sheet shows $30 million in "other assets." Included here are prepaid contract costs -- essentially what Cott pays to buy shelf space for its products from retailers. At a stretch, a U.S. company could consider contract costs an asset, but even Coca-Cola Beverages in Canada doesn't. Also listed as assets: "Deferred development costs," incurred designing packages for private-label clients. This would be regarded as an expense in the U.S., not an asset. <p>Another interesting technique found on Cott's balance sheet involves $37.6 million of goodwill. At best an intangible and illiquid asset, goodwill usually includes a company's brand name or good customer relations. Cott's goodwill is "principally the excess of the costs of acquisitions over the fair values of the net tangible asset acquired," as stated in SEC filings.<p>One such acquisition was the purchase of a minority interest in Cott Beverages USA for $16 million in Cott shares in fiscal 1993. Curiously, Cott bought this interest from several of its own employees, paying $7.1 million to chief operating officer Fraser Latta and $700,000 to vice president of finance Paul Henderson. Latta had gotten his minority interest, gratis, less than a year earlier, as part of an "amended" employment agreement that took effect a few months after he joined Cott.<p>What does this maneuver achieve? Pencer says the payments are just deserts for associates who increased Cott's business in the U.S. "The best way to motivate [people] is to allow them to participate in the growth of the company," he says. "It's the culture of our company." <p>Here's another way of looking at it: The deal takes what appears to be executive compensation, normally another of a company's costs, and whisks it off the income statement and onto the asset side of the balance sheet. A clever move, particularly in light of how a $7.1 million compensation cost would have cut into Cott's 1993 reported earnings of $12 million.<p>What else is going on in Cott's books? How is the company really doing financially?<p>Those questions are exactly what Lawrence Rosen, Canada's foremost accounting authority and head of the forensic accounting firm of Rosen & Vettese in Toronto, wanted to answer. Rosen took Cott's financials and applied a more conservative accounting method called cash-flow analysis. "Pencer's management style is to enhance the bottom line, and you can do it under [Canadian] GAAP," says Rosen. "It is all an illusion. A cash analysis shows that this company is in deep trouble."<p>Rosen's calculations showed Cott's net earnings at $19 million in fiscal 1994 -- roughly half the $35 million Cott said it earned. This would mean the company earned 30 cents a share, not 60 cents as it reported for the year. <p>Based on Rosen's figures, Cott's stock trades at 108 times earnings, not 54 as reported earnings indicate. "GAAP is always showing you this nice rosy picture," he says. "In truth, you're looking down an elevator shaft." <p>Rosen also believes that Cott will run out of cash soon unless the company alters its management style. This is because Cott is paying big bucks to retailers to stock its merchandise and because it is carrying unusually high amounts of customer inventories on its books. <p>Here's what Cott spent on assets during fiscal 1994, in millions of dollars: $21 went to receivables -- money owed to Cott by suppliers or clients; $38 to inventories; $6 in payables; $2 each in bank loans and income taxes; $16 to "other assets"; $11 in goodwill. Subtract $1 million in prepaid expenses, and you have a $95 million cash outflow. <p>Yet Cott generated only $43 million in cash during the year, Rosen reckons, producing a shortfall of $52 million. This may be one reason the company visited the capital markets twice last year, raising $171 million.<p>Cott's shortfall would be of less concern if its investments were in tangibles like plant and equipment. But they were in inventories -- soft drinks and other products -- that may not get sold, receivables that may not be collected from customers, and goodwill that isn't sellable.<p>Joshua Livnat, chairman of the accounting department at New York University's Stern School of Business, echoes Rosen's views on Cott's cash flows. "You cannot really fudge the numbers when it comes to cash flows," he says. "They are investing substantially more than they are generating."<p>Cott's accounting may seem odd to outsiders, but to insiders it means a bigger paycheck. In March '92, Cott adopted a profit- participation plan under which certain executives receive a cash bonus equal to 10 percent of the company's pretax net income. The executives earn their bonuses if Cott earns at least 15 percent return on shareholders' equity during the year.<p>Not a bad incentive to push the company's pretax earnings and bolster assets in shareholders' equity. Indeed, in fiscal 1993, five honchos earned a total of $1.4 million under the profit plan. That's in addition to salaries totaling $1.2 million given to those five folks.<p>Between profit plans, salaries, and big insider stock sales, Pencer has gotten mighty rich off Cott's success. So have many shareholders who have ridden this rocket. But as accounting expert Rosen points out," Every day that Cott operates, it consumes much more cash than it generates from sales." Eventually, Rosen says, companies with such problems go under. <p>Pencer vigorously denies his accounting is aggressive. "We've gotten all the advice we need, including our auditor's," he says. "We just want to make sure we're doing things right." If Cott expensed costs and took an earnings hit, he says, average investors wouldn't understand. <p>Indeed, plenty of investors love Cott's stock. Major holders at year end were Florida's Sunbank Capital Management, mutual fund giant Twentieth Century in Kansas City, and Jundt Associates, a Minneapolis growth-stock firm. <p>Some investors may be relying on Wall Street analysts to alert them to problems at Cott. One analyst, Jennifer Solomon at Mabon Securities, recently put a sell recommendation on the stock largely because she's worried about increased competition for Cott. But Morgan Stanley and Oppenheimer continue to recommend Cott shares aggressively. The two underwrote $171 million in Cott shares last year, earning big fees for their work.<p>Investors can't be expected to know how to plumb Cott's books; they're confusing at best. Remember: Accounting standards vary among countries and firms. Don't assume that all are equally clear and fair for shareholders.
---------------
Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies
