	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Fashionably Late</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Fashionably Late</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Barneys, America's merchant of cool, is boorishly behind on its bills. Is this just part of the attitude, or is the store in trouble? <p>By Alan G. Millstein<p>When all of new York City's glitterati turned out to view Barneys' bold new uptown fashion emporium last September 7, nobody had any idea of the financial fissures just below the store's glamorous surface. As tuxedoed waiters passed champagne and caviar, attendees oohed and aahed over the understatedly elegant store, designed in blond wood and sleek glass by star architect Peter Marino. <p>There wasn't a hotter ticket in town. Invitations to Barneys' Madison Avenue gala were harder to get than opening-night seats at the Metropolitan Opera. It looked like the Pressman clan--owner of the 17-store Barneys New York chain and the last of America's great retailing families--had a hit on its hands. All eight Pressmans involved in running the store basked in the limelight.<p>Little more than three months later, the Pressmans found themselves under the glare of a much harsher spotlight. The New York Times, one of the newspapers that had fawningly recounted the details of Barneys' opening-night triumph, reported that the store wasn't paying its bills to vendors and suppliers. In an article in the paper's style pages, Amy Spindler, a columnist and fashion reporter, revealed that several design firms had not been paid by Barneys for merchandise shipped in August for the new store's opening. The Times reported that some of the unpaid invoices were as much as three months past due. <p>Stung by its first taste of bad publicity, Barneys went on the attack. Behind the scenes, Charles W. Bunstine II, the company's chief operating officer, telephoned Spindler and threatened to get her fired. Bunstine doesn't deny threatening the reporter. He says he filed a complaint with an assistant managing editor at the paper, Warren Hoge, charging Spindler with errors owing to her "financial illiteracy." The Times printed an editor's note clarifying some details in the story. Spindler's reporting on the late payments, however, has since proved correct.<p>Publicly, the company showed a more benign face. Barneys released a public apology to its suppliers on December 16, blaming the payment problems on poor communications. Management claimed that distractions associated with the Madison Avenue opening created the slowdown in payments. "We are diligently working to remedy this communications issue," the company said, adding that its business was "incredibly healthy." The story died down.<p>But the damage to Barneys' well-sculpted facade had been done. While store management was claiming the check was in the mail, New York's fashion industry was beginning to wonder just how healthy Barneys was. <p>And the question still stands. As of February, lawsuits for nonpayment or late payment of bills continued to come in. Even more worrisome, a number of powerful credit agencies began advising clients to do business with Barneys on a cash-only basis, if at all. It was beginning to look like the store was in trouble.<p>As it happens, chiseling suppliers, manufacturers, and contractors has become a modus operandi for Eugene Pressman, 42, Barneys copresident and prime mover. (He shares his title with brother Robert, three years younger.) At work and at home, Pressman has become a particularly troubling kind of customer: very wealthy, very prestigious, and very tough to collect from.<p>Listen to Michael Ratner, president of Richter & Ratner, an 82-year-old construction firm that has done specialty cabinetry work for a number of Barneys stores. "The Pressman brothers [Eugene and Robert] make you feel that it is a privilege to do work for them," says Ratner, recalling several jobs his firm did as far back as 1991 in Chicago and Troy, Michigan. "I saw Gene by chance and told him I couldn't get his chief financial officer to return my calls about an open invoice for about $105,000. Gene just walked away without acknowledging that I existed."<p>Ratner's troubles with Barneys began last August, when he was owed almost $900,000 for cabinet work and construction-management services done on the Chicago store. In February, Ratner's company sued Barneys for $146,000 still owed for the work. "We worked for the Pressmans for more than eight years, and this was a very painful decision to sue them," says Ratner. "But they just failed to return over 90 phone calls about our unpaid invoices."<p>The tale of Barneys' troubles is worth telling for several reasons. The Pressmans are the last in a venerable American tradition--the close-knit but very big-league retailing family. Although the founder of the store, Eugene and Robert's grandfather Barney Pressman, was an immigrant discount-clothing merchant, the store that bears his name is now an upscale and innovative giant. If it is humbled, an era in merchandising will come to an end. Furthermore, Barneys is the gold standard in selling fashions to the affluent and successful set. Yet the manner in which the store conducts its business is anything but a textbook for success. <p>On a larger scale, the Barneys story appears to be a familiar one of overreaching by a third-generation son who had every privilege in his youth. Gene Pressman's days of getting whatever he wants, for himself or his business, may be over.<p>With the exception of Gene, who for years has maintained a high profile in New York business and society, the Pressman family is quite private. Because Barneys is a nonpublic operation, its accounting practices have been kept off the record for most of the seven decades the company has been in business. Almost all of the store's top management are Pressmans: Fred, the patriarch at age 71, is the chairman, though he's not active in the store. Copresidents Gene and Bob are his sons. Fred's wife, Phyllis, buys for the gift salons. Additional store responsibilities are assigned to Bob's wife, Holly; Gene's wife, Bonnie; and Fred's married daughters, Nancy Pressman Dressler and Liz Pressman Neubardt.<p>Gene Pressman would not make himself available for interviews for this story despite repeated requests. But interviews with more than two dozen people close to the Pressmans both personally and professionally show a pattern of hubris on his part that is remarkable even by the fashion industry's egomaniacal standards. <p>The brothers who control Barneys are not cut from the same cloth. Gene, boyishly handsome, trim and physically fit (he is said to run seven miles a day), was a man about town before he married Bonnie, a former runway model. Early on, he thought of going to Hollywood to become a film director. He is Barneys' tastemaker and style arbiter and is found front row and center at major fashion shows. His home is a waterfront estate in Westchester County, north of New York City.<p>Robert, bespectacled and heavier set, is the quieter of the two. He earned an M.B.A. from Pace University in New York City. He and his wife maintain an apartment in New York City and a house in Connecticut. He is Barneys' moneyman.<p>In 1990, Gene and Robert announced an expansion plan that called for 25 to 30 Barneys branch stores to be up and running across the nation by the end of 1994. Thus far, 12 branches have been opened in cities such as Seattle, Dallas, Houston, and Chicago. These stores range from 6,500 to 125,000 square feet and sell women's sportswear, accessories, and private-label and European designer menswear.<p>Now, Barneys' expansion plans have been drastically scaled back. The company is concentrating instead on enlarging existing stores and finding a number of downmarket outlet-mall locations. <p>Notwithstanding the store's Christmastime promises to make good on its bills, suppliers continued to file lawsuits against Barneys in early February. Three clothing manufacturers went to the courts seeking payments that totaled more than $100,000. A few weeks later, Charles Bunstine was still blaming the ongoing problems on computers, paperwork glitches, and even on himself.<p>Such talk is small consolation for the folks waiting to be paid. And those who know about the personal financial history of Barneys New York's leader might feel less consolation still. In the late 1980s, Gene was dogged by complaints from contractors and craftspeople hired to restore his sprawling Westchester home. Though he's certainly wealthy, Pressman was sued and threatened with suit a number of times for not paying his personal bills.<p>Pressman's home is a 100-year-old Tudor-style estate in Mamaroneck, on Long Island Sound. In the 1930s and 1940s, the home belonged to gangster Bugsy Siegel. <p>"When Gene took possession of the house and its grounds, it was in terrible shape," says Peter Marino, the architect responsible for the designs of most Barneys retail properties and several of the Pressman family's homes. "The Mamaroneck house was built in 1895, and it included a secret passageway from the waterfront docks to the basement. It was probably the way they moved the bootleg whiskey from ships waiting off Long Island Sound to Bugsy's house."<p>Marino prepared the architectural plans for the total renovation of the Mamaroneck estate. For him, the work was another Pressman success. <p>For the contractors who did the work, however, the renovation ended badly. On September 26, 1989, a mechanic's lien in the amount of $25,871.13 was placed on the Mamaroneck home by Walter Concrete Construction Corp. of Elmsford, New York. "This was the first time in 17 years in business that I had to sue someone to collect a bill," says Walter Lenz, president of the firm. "We were hired by the general contractor, Anmat of Rye, New York, to do extensive work on the pool area and surrounding foundations. What I remember most was the incredible arrogance of Gene Pressman, who was constantly making changes in the architect's site plans."<p>The original contract with Walter Concrete was for $88,215, and there was more than $17,000 in change orders. "When I tried to collect the balance due for our work, Pressman tried to chisel me down on the price, and that's when I decided to sue him," Lenz says. Suing didn't do much good. After three years, Lenz settled with Pressman for 40 cents on the dollar.<p>Another subcontractor on the Pressman job was Fairfield Dock, a 50-year-old Connecticut marine contractor engaged by Anmat to rebuild the property's dock area. "There were a number of change orders in the architect's plans, and when we billed the general contractor, we had to resort to threatening to sue Anmat to collect," says James Bradley, president of Fairfield Dock. <p>The saddest story of all about the renovations at the Pressman home involves Anmat, the general contractor. According to Fred Sciliano, former president of the company, Anmat worked inside and out on the home to the tune of nearly $800,000. "I spent one year of my life working on Gene Pressman's home, and the resulting problems and financial disputes over constant changes in the architect's plan left me with little or no profit at the end of the job," he says. <p>The troubles on the Pressman project, combined with the downturn in the economy in the late 1980s, ultimately caused Sciliano financial distress. "Working for them was a learning experience, that's for sure," says Sciliano. "So I decided to close my contracting business shortly after finishing the Pressman estate." Sciliano now works for a New York City construction company.<p>Sciliano's tale may have a familiar ring to Barneys' contractors and vendors back in Manhattan. David R. Corbin, president of New York--based Corbin Ltd., one of the nation's leading family-owned manufacturers of dress trousers, is one of the suppliers who filed suit against Barneys in February, for $68,614. "We had filed suit for payment from Barneys after waiting for more than five months for payment for our fall 1993 shipments," he says. Like Gene and Bob Pressman, Corbin is from his family's third generation in the business. "I have canceled spring shipments to the store, and I will not do business with them in the future even though my unpaid invoices were finally cleaned up in early February," he says.<p>Corbin is a small fish; he's not going to do any harm to Barneys, and he knows it. But if the cancellation of shipments should mushroom, if other manufacturers should follow Corbin's lead, the effect could be serious. Typically, when suppliers, manufacturers, or credit agencies (known in the business as "factors") get wind of a store's payment problems, shipments of merchandise slow or stop altogether. The store's offerings begin to look meager. Shoppers go elsewhere.<p>In the late 1980s, gene pressman hatched a grandiose retailing plan; but he needed someone to fund it. Isetan, a fourth-generation family-run retailer out of Japan, has taken on much of this burden. In 1990, according to an Isetan spokesman, the company put up between $125 million and $200 million in exchange for 75 percent of Barneys' stores in Japan, 25 percent of Barneys' U.S. stores, and 50 percent of the real estate under Barneys on East Oak Street in Chicago, on Wilshire Boulevard in Beverly Hills, and on Madison Avenue in New York City. The agreement runs for 499 years.<p>Also shouldering part of the burden of Pressman's grand plan: Manufacturers, craftspeople, and suppliers who ship goods to Barneys, then bite their nails until they get paid. Some seem to feel they have no choice. The president of one outerwear manufacturer says he shipped to Barneys despite the recommendation of his factor not to do so. "I had not been paid for my fall outerwear shipments, but I desperately needed the exposure Barneys Madison Avenue offered to me in September," he says. <p>In February, Barneys finally paid the manufacturer $10,000 for merchandise shipped the previous August. The factor reversed its position, and the manufacturer planned to ship another $25,000 in goods for spring 1994.<p>The Pressman operation has long been known for playing tough with suppliers, according to Martin Greenfield, president of an eponymous men's tailored-clothing manufacturer that counts President Clinton among its customers. Greenfield worked with Barney and Fred Pressman during the 1950s and '60s. "If I needed a cutting ticket to keep my factory in Brooklyn going during the off-season," Greenfield says, "I would call Fred and make a deal for a couple thousand suits." Greenfield says Fred was notorious for squeezing suppliers for inside prices. "He left me with little or no profit, but he saved my business when I needed the work," says Greenfield. <p>Barney Pressman, according to Greenfield, lived and breathed retailing. "I knew Barney for more than 40 years," he says, "and all he liked to do was talk business--even when we vacationed in Florida." This dedication to hard work helped the store defy, for six full decades, the age-old retailing maxim that success depends on location, location, location. On 17th Street and Seventh Avenue in a nondescript downtown neighborhood known as Chelsea, Barneys made its name as New York's leading retailer of high-quality men's clothing; it had no competition when it came to breadth of selection for men of all sizes and shapes. Radio ads built the store's traffic in the 1930s, saying, "Calling all men to Barneys from 34 extra short to 56 extra tall, we fit them all."<p>In the 1970s, young Gene Pressman was beginning to fancy himself the Leonardo da Vinci of retailing. And make no mistake about it: He has brought dramatic changes in the family business. First he went upmarket, aggressively pursuing Italian menswear designers like Giorgio Armani and Brioni in the '70s. He also developed a thriving women's business from scratch. Later, he conceived of his audacious design for the new flagship on Madison Avenue and shops across the U.S.<p>Barneys' foray into women's wear came as a direct result of threats made by Gene to his father and grandfather that he would leave the needles and pins of Seventh Avenue for Hollywood if they didn't go along with his plans. Barney himself persuaded the rest of the family to gamble on Gene's dream.<p>The women's store downtown grew from 6,000 square feet in 1981 to 70,000 square feet in 1986. But Gene may have been frustrated. It was becoming clear that his effort to lure the beautiful people to shop on lower Seventh Avenue was more difficult than he had thought. The ladies who lunch and then shop till they drop remained uptown, habitues of Bergdorf's, Saks, and Bloomingdale's. Gene decided in the 1980s that if the chic and sleek female shoppers wouldn't travel downtown, then Barneys would go uptown.<p>It was a plan audacious enough to fit Gene Pressman's grandiose vision of retailing in the '90s. He would bring a venerable downtown institution uptown--to the toniest shopping corridor in New York City. The move was about nothing if not competition: The site was within walking distance of the three B's of retail fashion: Bloomingdale's, Bergdorf's and Bendel's.<p>In November of 1990, the Pressmans and Isetan purchased the ground floor and eight additional stories of retail condominium space from Metropolitan Life at Madison Avenue and 61st Street. Then, in another bold move to capitalize on the weak real estate market, the store announced in December 1992 that it was purchasing floors 10 through 24 in an all-cash deal. Three of the additional floors would be used by Barneys as executive offices, and the rest of the space would be leased to outside tenants.<p>And so it was that Gene Pressman's uptown obsession took its final shape. The 230,000-square-foot store would be the first new department store built in midtown Manhattan since the early 1920s, when Edwin Goodman moved his family's fur salon and custom tailor shop, Bergdorf Goodman, to Fifth Avenue at 57th Street. <p>But all was not well for Isetan back in Japan. It had opened Barneys stores in Tokyo and Yokohama, but for several years the company had experienced profit declines. The country's grinding recession had created a drop in consumer spending on luxury goods. Shuwa Corp., a real estate conglomerate that was the Tokyo-based retailer's largest shareholder, bailed out of almost all its 29 percent stake in Isetan. In May 1993, Isetan's president, Kuniyasu Kosuge, a member of the store's founding family, abruptly resigned.<p>Fast on the heels of Isetan's troubles came the first talk of cost overruns at Madison Avenue. The store, budgeted at $80 to $90 million, came in at a final cost of $140 million, 65 percent over plan."You could work with Fred, but it's Gene that calls the shots on the retail stores and their design," says Michael Ratner of Richter & Ratner. "I was told Gene's constant changes in design plans and the overtime costs were running over $1 million a week during the months prior to the store's opening. It's hard to believe, but Gene just doesn't care what things cost." <p>Owen Steel Co. of Columbia, South Carolina, which supplied the new store with structural steel, was among the first to file liens on the store. It put a mechanic's lien on the company last August for $106,372 in unpaid invoices. Several designers of accessories and apparel went on the record with stories of slow payments. WWD, the newspaper to the fashion trade, reported that Abba Accessories filed suit to recover almost $30,000 in unpaid invoices. John Bartlett, winner of the 1993 Council of Fashion Designers' Perry Ellis Award as outstanding young menswear designer, says that payment of his invoices was between 90 days and five months late. "For the small designer, it's difficult," he says, "because to be in Barneys is a huge privilege."<p>At the height of the Christmas selling season, a month after stories started trickling out about Barneys' slow payments, WWD ran a page-one article on the subject. The paper's top financial reporter, Sidney Rutberg, tried to sort out the company's financial condition and identified a group of manufacturers who said that the company's failure to pay its bills in a timely fashion was made more aggravating by its habit of not returning phone calls to vendors who complained.<p>Adding insult to injury for the small vendors, the WWD story said that some high-profile firms who sold to Barneys were "getting paid without undue delay." A spokeswoman for high-profile designer Donna Karan says, "We have no problem with Barneys." Architect Marino says he receives a check every Friday from the store for the work he has billed. <p>The WWD story reported numbers for the quarter ending October 1, 1993, which included the preopening expenses of the Madison Avenue store. The store group had net sales of $79.3 million versus $43.7 million in the same quarter of the previous year. Cash on hand was $22 million, with accounts payable of $42 million and inventory of $68 million. Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization--an important measure of financial health--were $6.7 million, up from $3.8 million for the 1992 quarter. Same-store sales were up 14 percent. <p>Chief operating officer Bunstine confirms these numbers. He further estimates that 1993--1994 storewide sales will meet the company's projections of $400 million. He says that all of Barneys' stores, in New York and out, are profitable: "The Madison Avenue store will do about $150 million in sales during its first year in operation, and 17th Street will be in excess of $50 million." Interestingly, this last figure is down considerably from Bunstine's earlier projections of "slightly under $100 million" in sales downtown; the uptown store may be cannibalizing 17th Street's business. <p>Christmas was just fair for Barneys nationwide because, as Bunstine puts it, "We have never been a destination store for holiday gift items." Nonetheless, for the second quarter, ending January 31, 1994, the flagship store was ahead of plan, Bunstine says. <p>The fact that Gene Pressman lives in Bugsy Siegel's old home is an irony, given Barneys' recent bill-paying imbroglio. Benjamin "Bugsy" Siegel, bootlegger and bookmaker, is often credited with the idea of turning a dusty desert gulch into a glitzy gold mine called Las Vegas. Siegel used charm, good looks, and guile to develop the Flamingo Hotel, Las Vegas' first world-class hotel and casino.<p>Siegel was obsessed with the minutiae of architectural design and interior decoration, and his desert resort came to fruition at twice its estimated construction costs. The overruns eventually led to Siegel's financial ruin and ultimately cost him his life. The modern-day Moses of slots and craps brought about one of the great business ideas of the century, the legalized temple of chance. But he never saw the promised land.<p>Will gene pressman's obsession with upscale, uptown retailing, New York style, be his Achilles' heel as Las Vegas glitz was Bugsy Siegel's? It's too soon to call. The jury is still out on the unusual layout and design of the Madison Avenue store, in which the men's and women's departments are essentially different stores. Some say the success of Gap stores demonstrates that couples like to shop together, not apart, on weekends; others marvel at the atmosphere Gene has created. (See "How Does the Madison Avenue Store Measure Up?")<p>The jury also remains out on Barneys' financial future. Is the Madison Avenue store a financial success? If cost overruns on the store haven't placed Barneys on shakier financial footing, why have payments to vendors been so slow--is it a matter of attitude or of ability to pay? Will the store get future shipments in a timely fashion? <p>Unlike retailers that have gotten into financial trouble because of heavy debt loads--Macy's and Federated are recent examples--Barneys has traditionally avoided leverage. That may be changing. In mid-February the company was said to be securing a loan for an undisclosed amount from a consortium of insurance companies and Chemical Bank.<p>Even with this capital, Barneys may not be out of the woods. The store is still behind on its payments to some smaller fashion resources--the very folks that make Barneys unique. If they were to stop shipping, the store would lose much of its high-fashion edge.<p>In fact, that kind of behavior might prompt the credit agencies to continue to advise against shipping to Barneys. Three of the largest credit-checking advisory agencies in New York--Bernard Sands, Credit Exchange, and Solo--have expressed strong negative opinions about the store's past and present credit history.<p>"Barneys is a sick chicken with fundamental cash-flow problems, and we recommend that our clients ship to them on a cash-only basis," says Richard Posner of Credit Exchange. But Posner, who has worked in the credit-checking business for 47 years, believes manufacturers will ship Barneys the goods they need for spring 1994. "When Saks went through its problems with the financial factors several years ago, every manufacturer shipped them out the back door," he says. Posner speculates that part of Barneys' current problems came about as a result of cost overruns associated with the Madison Avenue store. <p>A spokesman for Bernard Sands Credit Agency also confirms that his company is suggesting that its clients not ship orders to Barneys for the time being. "We would like to see the year-end statement before making a definitive recommendation on future credit for the store," says one of Sands' top executives.<p>Unlike in the old days, Barneys' greatest asset today is its location. The decision by Gene Pressman to develop a significant women's fashion business and to take on the heavyweights of midtown retailing is fraught with risk. But in pushing through his big idea, Gene Pressman is following in the footsteps of other retail giants of this century who had a commitment to their dreams. These include Stanley Marcus of Neiman-Marcus, Adam Gimbel of Saks, Bendel's Geraldine Stutz, Bergdorf's Ira Neimark, and designer-retailer Ralph Lauren. <p>Gene Pressman is New York's last great retail showman, and like his grandfather before him, he's a man who loves the rag game. But the difference between downtown retailing and the uptown carriage trade is that the great uptown showmen always wore velvet gloves. Unlike Pressman, they never had to, or thought to, bare their knuckles.<p><p>Sidebar: How Does the Madison Avenue Store Measure Up?<p>We asked three of New York's most incisive and intuitive fashion and retailing authorities for their opinions of Barneys' uptown emporium. One hit, one miss, one mixed review.<p>Ruth Ann Britten, a New York--based retail consultant and former owner of a major fashion buying office: "Barneys' point of view is too narrow in women's wear. There are not enough clothes for women over 50 years old who can afford Barneys prices. The Chelsea Passage  [the in-store gift shop] looks like an updated Pottery Barn. Their buyers seem to reach for the most esoteric items in major designer lines--the Armani collection looked like a sea of maid's uniforms. The store didn't take markdowns fast enough to compete with Bergdorf's or Bloomingdale's on winter clothes. The footwear department had too many combat boots. Most of the handbags were bizarre, and the jewelry looked like it belonged in a craft show in Greenwich Village. Why so many black dresses?"<p>Vicki Ross, owner of Vicki Ross Associates, a major New York--based buying office for fine women's apparel and accessories: "Why are men's and women's apparel floors separated? Only savvy shoppers know that you get from the men's store to the women's store on even-numbered floors using a back door. Downtown's Chelsea Passage is much more inventive than uptown's. The clothes have an antiestablishment look to them and the absence of color was a real mistake. The sales help are very knowledgeable; the doormen are adorable and will park your car for you if you give them a tip."<p>Marjorie Deane, publisher of The Tobe Report, a weekly merchandising magazine for retailers: "Barneys has a particular customer in mind, and they are providing a wonderful shopping experience by the exquisite use of neutral-colored wood and glass to create a calm and comfortable retail environment. It's nice to see so many couples with baby strollers in the store on weekends. There's an abundance of black clothes, but that's what's selling at retail. The gift department is wonderful. I've been shopping for myself after office hours because they're open until eight in the evening. The Mad61 restaurant is a great place to people watch; it seems that every woman who eats there owns a fur coat."
--A.G.M<p><p>

